<SLUG> BC-GLF-USOPEN-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT QUITE DALY WAY AT OLYM PIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Olympic Club has taken away John Daly's
driver this week, but it can't touch his daily drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is pretty cool, and they spelled it right,'' said Daly, who
has driven down John Daly Boulevard every day as he enters the U.S.
Open.
</P>
<P>
   Not only John Daly Boulevard, but Daly City, which is about two
of Daly's big drives down the freeway from here. The ``other'' John
Daly was a dairy farmer who once owned most of the property in this
area.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the name game is a good thing for Daly, who is 3 shots
off Payne Stewart's lead after a surprising 1-under 69. It
certainly is a big turnaround from last year, when Daly stormed out
of the U.S. Open at Congressional Country Club near Washington
D.C., after playing only nine holes of the second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have the shakes this year like I did then. I'm not
craving alcohol,'' said Daly, whose bouts with the bottle are
well-chronicled. ``When you putt at a major (championship), your
nerves are already there, and then top it off with the shakes _ if
you've never been there, you wouldn't understand _ it was a
difficult time for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The only thing Daly doesn't like is not being able to hit his
big drives off the tee this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sucks. I hate it,'' Daly said of hitting 3-woods and
2-irons instead of the driver. ``The bonus from Callaway (for
winning the driving title) is huge, but I'd rather be in the
fairway.'' &QL;  &QL; 
Arizona connection &QL;  &QL; 
Of Arizona's eight entries in the Open, three are among the
leaders. Tom Lehman shot 68, Andrew Magee was at 70 and Phil
Mickelson came in with a 71.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked my butt off,'' said Magee, who was 3 over after three
holes before he capped his rally with a 6-foot birdie at the 18th
hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. Open is not fair, but you know that coming in. I
guess I'm not just a big fan of the (sponsoring U.S. Golf
Association).''
</P>
<P>
   Other Arizona players were probably thinking the same. Like Kirk
Triplett, who was among the leaders after a 33 on the front nine,
only to end up at 73. Mark Calcavecchia and Don Pooley also were 2
under early before falling back to 74.
</P>
<P>
   It got worse, as Brandel Chamblee (76) and Howard Twitty (79)
struggled in. &QL;  &QL; 
Open tragedy &QL;  &QL; 
Rick McGuire, the vice chairman of the U.S. Open who has strong
ties to Phoenix, died of a heart attack Thursday morning, just a
few hours before the tournament began. McGuire, whose son, Mike, is
an assistant pro at Phoenix Country Club, was 51.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rick had gotten tickets for about 30 of us from Phoenix,''
said Ralph Bernhisel, the director of golf at Phoenix Country Club.
``We were all having such a good time, and for this to happen is
such a tragedy. I especially feel bad for Mike.''
</P>
<P>
   Magee, who is using McGuire's locker this week, also was hit
hard by the news as he walked off the 18th green.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had played with Rick in the Santa Claus Classic,'' Magee
said of the annual pro-am at the TPC of Scottsdale. ``He was truly
a great guy.'' &QL;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 0006EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
