</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-HOFFARTH-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
( ADDS NOTES )  
NBC   DOESN'T OVERCOVER MARTIN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ From noon to 2 p.m. Thursday, NBC interrupted
``Another World'' and ``Days Of Our Lives'' for the first round of
the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   It could easily have been called ``As Casey Martin's World
Turns.''
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, TV decided not to wring more unnecessary suds from
this soap opera.
</P>
<P>
   By the time The Handicapped Golfer climbed into his E-Z-Go cart
after a 3:30 p.m. tee time and nearly run over a USGA official who
cut in front of him, ESPN had assumed coverage (in a somewhat
surreal setting, using NBC broadcasters Dick Enberg and Johnny
Miller). Enberg mentioned that Martin deserved ``high-grade
bravados.'' Miller called Martin ``a brave guy.'' USGA boss David
Fay, in the booth, discussed both sides of the controversy that led
to Martin's court-sought permission to use a cart for the
circulatory ailment in his right leg known as
Klippel-Trenaunay-Weber Syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, Martin's wild ride through the Olympic course
Thursday was thankfully less than full throttle.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's round didn't really deserve much attention (he wasn't
even finished when coverage ended). ESPN cameras didn't even show
his cart rides between holes, showing instead more shots from other
players.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe a reserved treatment is surprising from NBC just coming
off the Michael Jordan Experience. It will have much more of a
chance to cover him live today with his second-round tee-time of 10
a.m. But if anything, extended coverage by NBC and ESPN Thursday
tended to rein in the hype and make the scores the thing to focus
on rather than the potential sideshow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing we do (at NBC) is address the issues that are
hot and interesting, but we are fair to who gets covered,'' Miller
said before the tournament. ``It's more the scores than who it is.
We do try to cover who's the best. And there are a lot of good
stories in the game today, in addition to Casey Martin.''
</P>
<P>
   Meaning that even with non-Masters'-like TV time _ NBC does 16
hours over the four days, and ESPN takes the first two rounds to
near completion _ there won't be anything more on the Martin story
unless something materializes.
</P>
<P>
   It's also ironic that the usually vocal Miller measures his
words when talking about Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an issue I'm trying not to make a lot of comments
about,'' said Miller. ``I see both sides. I pull for him, but I
understand the PGA Tour's position. On one hand it's que sera, but
on the other hand, how disabled do you have to be to have the rule
apply? Would it apply to someone like me who has had six
operations? He's in a gray area. I'm very open to his plight, but
from a public view, anything negative sounds very cold.
</P>
<P>
   ``He probably wishes he didn't have to walk. I credit him for
staying so much dead-center on the course that he has the right
stuff to handle the media scrutiny. It's the first time he's here
with the big boys. It'd be quite a thing for him to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Added course reporter Roger Maltbie, who followed Miller in the
18th-hole tower seat Thursday afternoon: ``I certainly feel this is
a special occasion _ a first _ and it's newsworthy. We want the
public to see it first-hand and feel the emotion of his playing. By
the time the first two rounds are complete, you'll see a lot of
him, I believe. But if Casey is 6-over, his coverage is over.''
</P>
<P>
   CASEY AT THE BAT
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who has received nothing but praise by media types for
his accommodating demeanor, writes in the current issue of WE, a
magazine for people with disabilities:
</P>
<P>
   ``Every tournament I'm on the front page or the top of the
sports page, and I'm not totally comfortable there. I want
attention for playing well.''
</P>
<P>
   He goes on to say that some reporters bother him and ``don't
listen to my answers because they have their own agenda. Sometimes,
they have an angle and will come after me relentlessly until they
get their quote.... They hang around until they can take your words
to suit the kind of story they want to have been assigned to write.
That's when it's a distortion, a pain for me.''
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-TRANSACTION WIRE
</P>
<P>
   With the network's NBA coverage complete for the year and
probably no Michael Jordan to baby-sit anymore, Dick Ebersol has
abdicated his title of NBC Sports president to Ken Schanzer.
Ebersol, who had the nameplate since 1989, is going to be known as
the chairman of NBC's Olympics division....
</P>
<P>
   A seven-year contract extension between KCAL-Channel 9 and the
Lakers translates into about a $140 million revenue-sharing deal.
It also guarantees the station all Lakers playoff games that aren't
tied into the national NBC package....
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' new three-year deal KRLA-AM (1110) doesn't mean
they'll be butting heads with the Ducks, whose games were on the
station last season. The Ducks' contract with KRLA ended, and
reportedly they're talking to XTRA-AM (690), which is the station
that the Kings left because of the signal's lack of penetration in
the San Fernando Valley and because the station presented many more
conflicts with other teams' broadcasts....
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie Bernstein was allowed out of her contract as a reporter
with ESPN a year early so she could hook up with CBS' ``NFL Today''
show this fall....
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's football game at Miami on Sept. 26 will be on CBS'
schedule with a 9 a.m. kickoff time locally, and Terry Donahue will
be the analyst.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT SMOKES
</P>
<P>
   -- The case of the mistaken celebrity hunk. Go back to that May
25 issue of Sports Illustrated with Mike Piazza on the cover that
proclaimed: ``Trade of the Century.'' The riveting account of
Piazza's final hours as a Dodger as documented by writer Michael
Bamberger takes a strange turn when Piazza takes a phone call from
Fabio. Bamberger assumes it's the male fashion model, who wouldn't
know baseball from boccie ball. So Bamberger writes that. Anyone
who has heard Jim Rome's sports-talk radio show is clued into the
fact that ``Fabio'' is the nickname Piazza gave Eric Karros. We saw
it and laughed it off. But Daily News reader Mark Neuman asked SI
about it. He received e-mail back last week: ``We checked with
Michael Bamberger regarding the `Fabio' that Piazza was on the
telephone with and our writer, who was present at the time,
repeated that it was the model Fabio, not Karros. Go figure! Best
wishes, SI Letters.'' Just a flippant ``Go figure?'' How about go
figure out who does fact-checking. The official scorer just changed
that from a wild pitch to E-SI.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT CHOKES
</P>
<P>
   -- Sports Illustrated has struck a deal with Norwegian Cruise
Lines to create ``SI Afloat,'' which will charge people to take
cruises and mingle with real-life sports celebrities... like Fabio!
</P>
<P>
   -- ESPN's Sunday morning round table ``The Sports Reporters''
has changed its name to ``ESPN Magazine's The Sports Reporters.''
</P>
<P>
   -- The latest New York media scandal. Famed WCBS sportscaster
Warner Wolf, the video-mad East Coast version of Fred Roggin, lost
his dentures during a live sound bite last Friday night. The New
York Post headline: ``Let's Go to the Poli-Grip,'' along with a
three-picture sequence of Wolf catching his fangs before they bit
the dust. C'mon, is that news? Imagine if Carlos Del Valle was on
the air and became tongue-tied during a KNBC sportscast. No one
would anyone think differently of him.
</P>
<P>
   -- Maybe it's best that USC's new football play-by-play man
doesn't use his real name. With analyst Paul McDonald next to him
and Paul Hackett on the field, it would get pretty confusing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
