<HEADLINE>
FIXES DURANT'S SCORE TO 68 
 
STEWART CLOSES FAST FOR OPEN LEAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Birdies on the closing holes yesterday at the
Olympic Club proved tougher to collect than Beanie Babies during
the Christmas shopping season.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there was Payne Stewart, basket full and face awash in an
impish grin, trying to calculate the odds against repeating the
birdie-birdie-birdie finish that propelled him into the first-round
lead at the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doing it again, I don't know,'' said Stewart, who was one of
only five players to birdie the par-4 17th hole, which played to a
scoring average of 4.65. ``I can see doing 16 and 18. But when you
get a birdie at 17, you can almost soar to the 18th tee. In my
mind, that's an eagle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there would be long odds against it. But whoever made
the odds just lost, because it just got done.''
</P>
<P>
   By closing with three consecutive birdies, Stewart finished with
a 4-under-par 66 and took a one-stroke lead over Mark Carnevale on
a day with the par-70 layout played to an average score of 75.
</P>
<P>
   Well-tucked pins, firm fairways, tiny greens and thick rough
tinged with a heavy morning dew helped make scoring conditions
difficult for the 156 starters. Stewart was among nine players who
finished yesterday with under-par scores.
</P>
<P>
   Others included Tom Lehman, Bob Tway, Joe Durant and Jose Maria
Olazabal, all at 68. John Daly, Jesper Parnevik and Jeff Maggert, a
Houston resident and Texas A&AMP;M graduate, are at 69.
</P>
<P>
   Several notables struggled, however. Past major-championship
winners Ben Crenshaw (82), Hale Irwin (80), Davis Love III (78),
Nick Faldo (77), Curtis Strange (77) and Corey Pavin (76) all find
themselves at least 10 strokes in back of Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Defending champ Ernie Els, fighting a back ailment, labored to a
75. So did Fort Worth resident Mark Brooks, who still finished five
strokes ahead of fellow Fort Worth resident Sam Randolph (80).
</P>
<P>
   All in all, a less than stellar showing by the game's top
players. But they had plenty of help from U.S. Golf Association
officials, who set pins in positions that were ``scary,'' in the
estimation of Colin Montgomerie, who shot even-par 70.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised they had the pins so difficult on the first
day,'' said Tiger Woods, who shot a 74 that included a four-putt at
the ninth green. ``Usually, there's a blend of difficult pins and
easy ones. Today, everything was shaded toward the difficult
ones.''
</P>
<P>
   But the well-hidden pins could not stop Stewart, who collected
five birdies and one bogey. He also drained two par putts from
beyond 12 feet in matching his best career start at the Open. In
1991, when Stewart won the title, he opened with a 67.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took advantage of some breaks out there today,'' said
Stewart, who bagged two birdies and collected two pars on holes
where he drove the ball into the rough. ``When you get them, you
have to take advantage of them, especially at a U.S. Open. Because
you don't get that many.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's biggest break came at No. 17, where he hit a driver
into the first cut on the right-hand side. Figuring he could not
reach the green, Stewart opted to play a 2-iron out of the tall
grass and caught it flush. The ball rolled. And rolled. And rolled.
</P>
<P>
   All the way to the front edge of the green, where Stewart
drained the 45-footer for birdie and began an impromptu funky
chicken dance in celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was huge,'' Stewart said. ``That hole is a par-5, no
matter what the scorecard says. To get away with a three ... let's
just say it was a brisk walk down to the 18th tee. I was ready to
hit another shot.''
</P>
<P>
   He followed with his worst swing of the day, a misdirected
2-iron into the right rough. From there, Stewart dug out an 8-iron
that skirted the edge of the green before reaching pin-high and
turning toward the hole. It eventually stopped 12 feet above the
hole, and Stewart canned the ticklish putt for his final birdie of
the day.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's closest pursuer is Carnevale, a career journeyman who
has bounced between the PGA Tour and Nike Tour in recent seasons.
But the 38-year-old emerged as the only front-runner to finish 18
holes without a bogey in the opening round.
</P>
<P>
   Carnevale, 38, hit 10 of 14 fairways and found 12 of 18 greens
in regulation. He one-putted nine greens, including three for
birdies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Granted, this is only Thursday. But this is where all the
attention of the golf world is this week,'' said Carnevale, whose
lone PGA Tour triumph came at the 1992 Chattanooga Classic. ``This
is what you have struggled all your life to get to. You finally
realize, `Hey, I'm here.' I'm excited. It was a lot of fun out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   And when was the last time Carnevale played 18 holes without a
bogey?
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe at Putt-Putt,'' Carnevale said. ``I'm not sure. But it's
been a while.''  &LR; tagtop:Jimmy Burch, (817) 390-7760
 &LR; tagbottom:jburch\Nstar-telegram.com
</P>
</TEXT>
