</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-LEHMAN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Lehman recovers after double bogey
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JAYNE CUSTRED &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SAN FRANCISCO _ When Tom Lehman walked off the 10th green Thursday
at The Olympic Club, it looked like his three-year run of
contending at the U.S. Open was in danger of coming to an end.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman had just three-putted from four feet for a double-bogey
6, putting himself at 2-over for the day. But Lehman said that more
than anything, the hole strengthened his resolve to play better on
the remaining eight holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, being 2 over par at that point makes me feel like I
better not mess up anymore from here on in,'' Lehman said. ``I was
in a tough situation. But making a birdie on the 11th hole and then
a really good save on 12, which was like making a birdie, helped a
lot more. So from that point forward, I played really well.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehman ended up making birdies on three of the final four holes
and finished only two strokes off the lead at 2-under-par 68. That,
of course, sets him up nicely for another run at yet another Open
title. In the last three years, Lehman has finished third, tied for
second, and third at the U.S. Open. But Lehman insisted Thursday
that this is a tougher course for him than the last three.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last four years in the Opens where I have played
well, I think this may be the most difficult course for me in terms
of it not quite setting up as well as the other ones did,'' Lehman
said. ``For me, it is quite difficult. I am not saying that I can't
play well, obviously. But it means that it requires my best golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehman showed on the back side of the first round just how good
his best can be. He sank a 15-footer for birdie on No. 11 and then
drained a long 30-foot birdie putt on No. 15. Lehman added a
12-footer on No. 16 and closed with a six-foot birdie on No. 18.
</P>
<P>
   But Lehman said that perhaps his best effort was his par save on
No. 12, where he hit way right off the tee, had to pitch back out
into the fairway and then hit a sand wedge to within 10 feet and
made the putt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the kinds of things in the U.S. Open that I think
you have to do once in a while because you aren't always going to
drive it in the fairway,'' Lehman said. ``No matter who you are,
you need every so often to get up and down for par. That was one of
those situations like making a birdie.''
</P>
<P>
   It also helped ease the pain of the double bogey on No. 10, when
Lehman hit his 7-iron second shot just left of the green, made a
great chip to four feet and then three-putted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there was a huge spike mark that was right in my line
on the first putt,'' Lehman said. ``It hit the spike mark and
bounced off line. There's not much you can do about that. Missing
the second putt, that was just a bad putt. The 10th hole wasn't my
best effort, but I managed to survive and shot a good score.''
</P>
<P>
   And set himself up for yet another chance to win the national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman said coming into the tournament that he thought he should
have a good week. He finished third at last week's Buick Classic,
closing with a spectacular 65. So after his early troubles
Thursday, Lehman was more than pleased with the way his day ended
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think anybody will tell you that you can't win the
tournament in the first round, but you can certainly lose it,''
Lehman said. ``So as long as you don't lose it in the first round,
you need to be happy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
