<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAYTON HOLDS KEY TO SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Gary Payton had done it again. No surprise. It was
expected under the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics trailed the Los Angeles Lakers at halftime in Game 4
of the Western Conference semifinals. Even more frustrating, they
were getting walloped in the series on their way to playoff
elimination.
</P>
<P>
   So Payton exploded _ in the locker room and in the face of
former coach George Karl, who barked back. The scene reflected the
type of confrontations (usually over game-plan disagreements) that
Karl and Payton engaged in several times last season, seemingly
many times during their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics went on to lose that game 112-100. Payton followed
the tirade with an explosion on the court _ 31 points, 13 assists
and eight rebounds in 41 minutes _ yet his monster game did not
translate into a victory. One loss later, Karl was finished as
Sonics coach.
</P>
<P>
   Point of the story?
</P>
<P>
   If Paul Westphal did not know already, he has a clue now.
Westphal, who was named the Sonics' new coach Wednesday, must get
more out of Payton _ in subtle ways _ than his predecessor did.
</P>
<P>
   Karl struggled with his point guard from start to finish.
Veteran Sonic players complained privately that Karl established
rules _ such as players must practice to play _ then let Payton
bend them with impunity. They also complained that Payton sometimes
strayed from Karl's game plans or would sometimes distance himself
from his teammates in critical moments of games when his leadership
was needed.
</P>
<P>
   After the Sonics were dropped from the postseason, Karl met with
president Wally Walker to discuss the team's future. One of Karl's
suggestions was that the Sonics should be open to the possibility
of trading Payton for several players if the team experienced more
second-round jolts. It was the second time in four years that Karl
made such a plea.
</P>
<P>
   Walker told Karl then what he told the Post-Intelligencer
recently: ``I'm still a Gary Payton fan.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry Ackerley loves Payton. The team owner invested seven years
and $87 million into the All-Star point guard. Seattle fans idolize
Payton, and the NBA markets his ability.
</P>
<P>
   Karl admired Payton's skills. To most observers, Payton is the
best point guard in the game. Karl also knows that Payton turned
him into a $3.5 million coach. Karl helped Payton become a $12
million player.
</P>
<P>
   Their relationship, while respectful, was airtight only for
public consumption. Karl continuously insisted on more from Payton.
He wanted a type of leadership Payton isn't ready to give. In
Payton's view, playing hard and producing every night is enough;
Karl also wanted a second coming of Nate McMillan, a vocal leader
in the locker room as well as on the court.
</P>
<P>
   Payton, though, is a superstar. And with superstars come
baggage. Now, it is Westphal's turn to carry the load.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line in the NBA is what happens out there when the
game begins. Are you playing hard? Are you playing for the team?
Are you giving everything you have?'' Westphal said. ``There are a
lot of personality quirks that everybody has. Me included. And
after having coached Charles Barkley (in Phoenix) I don't think
there's anything that I'll see that I haven't already seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Westphal knows the makeup of his best player. Payton often does
not practice. He is volatile and emotional. Payton is so
competitive that when he doesn't win, he transforms into someone
whose raging persona rivals the Incredible Hulk. Karl never got a
grip on that part of Payton.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Westphal will. He is cut from the same cloth. Although
Westphal is considered laid-back now, he was a terror growing up.
Westphal told a childhood story about getting kicked out of a
sixth-grade game. He thought the officiating was terrible and
committed a flagrant foul.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the only correct call (the referee) made all game,''
Westphal said.
</P>
<P>
   But after the game, Westphal remembers the official's advice:
Get emotions under control, or flame out. Westphal had grown up a
``monster on the court,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So his meeting with Payton in Oakland earlier this week wasn't
about changing the eight-year Sonic. Westphal merely opened the
lines of communication as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are very fortunate if you have a superstar who is willing
to be coached,'' Westphal said. ``If your superstar is not willing
to admit he's wrong sometimes, or admit that the coach has to have
the final say on things, then you're doomed. I don't care who you
are.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much of it comes down to the integrity of the player to
agree to have a coach tell him what the final say is. There have
been instances exhibited in the NBA recently where a player can get
a coach fired. Hopefully, the player can be reasonable, and I think
that's the case here.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite being short-tempered, Payton is gentle, respectful and
open-minded. All superstars must exercise those qualities at some
level.
</P>
<P>
   For as little as Chicago's Phil Jackson is given credit for the
Bulls' success, the glory is his. Sure, Michael Jordan makes all
the game-winning baskets, but he is canning them Jackson's way.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan hated the triangle offense when Jackson was named coach.
He still believes ``it is not a professional offense.'' However, it
wasn't until Jordan accepted Jackson's idea of leading that the
Bulls thrived. Remember that Jordan was in the league seven years
before Chicago won its first title.
</P>
<P>
   Payton will give Westphal a chance. He wants to reach the next
level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody can't be the perfect person in practice, slapping
the floor and being rah-rah,'' said Eric Goodwin, who manages
Payton with Aaron Goodwin, his brother. ``Most of the big stars in
the game have their own quirks. These guys are being tugged in
millions of ways. There has to be an outlet. Sometimes he (Payton)
doesn't want to practice. But that's not what leadership is about.
Leadership is finding ways to win games.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton's reluctance about practice is due in part to his
chronically sore back, for which he gets regular treatment. It's
not in the club's best interest that he risks aggravating the
problem in practice.
</P>
<P>
   Payton, though, has missed just two regular-season games his
entire career. He is regarded as the Sonics' toughest player. Think
Westphal will ride him about practice?
</P>
<P>
   Westphal won an NBA championship alongside John Havlicek on the
1973-74 Boston Celtics. Havlicek almost never practiced, Westphal
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd come (in the gym), sit and watch practice, but played 48
minutes every game. Nobody played harder than him, and he never
touched a ball in the summer,'' said Westphal, who continued his
point by describing how Celtic legend Larry Bird came to practice
early and left late. ``Everybody says be like Larry Bird. Nobody
says be like John Havlicek _ never practice, never touch a ball (in
the summer).
</P>
<P>
   ``... A coach has to be flexible and understand the need of his
players, that players are not all the same. And that the players
have to understand that you are treating them fairly but not
equally. Then you have no problem.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a theory Payton already believes in. Westphal's problem
will be getting the 11 other Sonics to buy into it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
