<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-USOPEN-MARTIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTIN FINDS SUPPORT BETTER THAN SCORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ By 3:30 Thursday afternoon, when Casey Martin
finally teed off his dream, the fog and chill and mist all were
rolling in from the Pacific Ocean. Martin's tale had been warm, but
now it would be played out in the chill of reality and competition.
</P>
<P>
   The grandstand behind the first tee was packed. Melinda and King
Martin, Casey's parents, searched high and low for seats, and when
they finally were able to sit down, husband gripped the hand of
wife, father the hand of mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so thrilled,'' said Melinda Martin, who acknowledged
that tears were flowing down her cheeks when her son took his first
swing in his first US Open. ``The people cheering for him ... it
was very supportive. You could feel it in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   King Martin was experiencing nerves that would chew at him for
the entire round. Bill Wisnall, the lawyer from Eugene, Ore., who
had won the civil suit against the PGA Tour that enabled Martin to
ride a cart in PGA-sanctioned events and the US Open because of a
circulatory problem that makes walking difficult, put it bluntly:
``King's getting an ulcer today.''
</P>
<P>
   Casey Martin himself heard the roar, ``and on that first tee, I
was trying not to think too much, to keep my thoughts simple. But
when they announced my name and the people roared like they did, I
admit I had to hit the ball quick before I first fell down.''
</P>
<P>
   After that first tee shot, King Martin removed himself from his
wife and family and friends and walked alone for much of the way at
The Olympic Club, needing the solitude to steel himself so he could
watch his son swing through a dream.
</P>
<P>
   But at that moment of that first Open swing for Martin, father
and mother were together watching son, ``and it was like the
fulfillment of a dream,'' said Melinda. ``I was overwhelmed. I was
thinking of what it was like 10 months ago when none of this seemed
possible ... and now he was able to fulfill the dream.''
</P>
<P>
   After the tee shot, Martin climbed into his EZGO golf cart, the
cart the PGA and the US Golf Association had not wanted him to
ride, as was the case with many in the golf establishment. Jack
Nicklaus and Arnold Palmer were two of the legends of golf who gave
videotaped testimony against him at the trial in mid-February where
Martin's opponents contended that allowing a player to ride in a
cart would soil the integrity of high-level competitive golf. For
his part, Wisnall could not help but think ``of the irony of
ironies.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because, said the lawyer, ``the last piece of evidence we
introduced before we rested our case was a commerical from EZGO.
The commercial had two golfers talking about how wonderful a cart
was, the EZGO cart. And the two golfers in the commerical? Jack
Nicklaus and Arnold Palmer ... and now Casey was riding an EZGO in
the Open even though they didn't want him to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin wished that he did not have to ride in a cart as he
stepped into it on that first hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never wanted to ride a cart to play golf,'' he said. ``It
hurts a little (psychologically) to get into a cart, but I need it
... and I'm grateful I'm able to use it.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin parred the first hole and bogeyed the second when his
approach shot spun off the green and he could not get up and down.
The media contingent was sizable and the gallery also was large as
he finally settled down on the sixth hole for his first birdie.
Another birdie two holes later, on the par-3 eighth, brought him
back to level par, and the tale was growing warmer and warmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember back to a meeting Casey and I had back in my office
two weeks before the trial,'' said Wisnall. Wisnall said he had
told Martin he had only one condition for bringing the suit to
trial under the Americans with Disabilities Act.
</P>
<P>
   Which was?
</P>
<P>
   ``That if Casey ever got to a United States Open,'' said the
lawyer, ``he would have to come through with tickets for me so I
could be right at the ropes and see every swing of his. I was
thinking years down the road ... and here it was four months after
the suit and Casey was in the Open.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was a no-brainer that Wisnall put his law business on hold
Wednesday afternoon, rushed down from Eugene to San Francisco, and
was at the ropes for every swing.
</P>
<P>
   Which were not too pretty on the second nine.
</P>
<P>
   On the ninth green, Martin had peeked at the leaderboard and
seen his name in bold, black letters at even par, but then the fog
rolled in some more, the air was chillier, ``and it felt really
cold,'' said Martin. And the cold affected his swing.
</P>
<P>
   But Martin kept rescuing hellacious par after hellacious par
until finally, the cold, the darkness, and the nerves all gathered
to thwart him on the final holes. He bogeyed the final two for a 39
on the back and a 4-over-par 74, eight shots off the lead, for the
day. But, said Martin, fizzling end or no fizzling end, ``I was
overwhelmed by the support I got.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
