<HEADLINE>
EDITORS: 
  
</HEADLINE>
  
 Friday, June 19, 1998
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Saturday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WATER-FILTERS (San Francisco) _ Home water filters intended to
remove chemicals and other impurities may be leaching lead into
glasses of water. A sampling of 16 under-the-sink filters found
that nine contained brass parts that leached lead at levels above
those considered safe under California's tough anti-toxics law. By
JANE KAY.
</P>
<P>
   BATTERED-GAYS (San Francisco) _ San Francisco would be the first
city in the nation to fund shelter beds for gay men who are
battered by their partners, if Supervisor Mark Leno gets his way.
Although the city has helped three women's shelters in town, there
has never been a safe place for gay men fleeing domestic violence.
By CAROL NESS.
</P>
<P>
   CHEVRON-POLLUTE (San Francisco) _ Chevron's refinery in
Richmond, Calif., tops the nation's list of polluters with more
than 944 million pounds of toxic waste produced in 1996, according
to the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency. By JANE KAY.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-2000 (Washington) _ A crush of Republican heavyweights
helped Texas Gov. George W. Bush raise about $1 million here for
his re-election bid. The big turnout fueled speculation he will run
for president in 2000, but he says he still has not made up his
mind. By GARY MARTIN
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-MERGERS (San Francisco) _ Merger mania and business
unions are starting to sweep the Internet, as big corporations
pounce on smaller on-line firms that offer gateways to a new medium
and millions of consumers. By EDWARD IWATA.
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN (Undated) _ Some employees question the accuracy
of services that check references of job candidates. By PAMELA YIP.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ Pentium II notebook computers are
hot, literally. We takes a look at a couple of power machines that
will singe your lap if you're not careful. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-HELPLINE (Undated) _ How to partion your hard drive to
recover wasted space and turn on your USB ports. By DWIGHT
SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-CRITIC (San Francisco) _ Close observation and the
occasional use of stiletto prose characterize media critic Ken
Auletta's ``The Highwaymen,'' a collection of his New Yorker
pieces. The book profiles media moguls such as Rupert Murdoch,
TCI's John Malone, Time Warner's Ted Turner, Microsoft's Bill Gates
and Viacom's Sumner Redstone. By DAVID ARMSTRONG.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BEST-FILMS (Undated) _ When it comes to the American Film
Institute's ``Top 100'' domestic films of the last century,
quibbling is just too easy. The list has been the source of much
discussion and consternation. What made it is moot. It's what
didn't that irks us most. By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-MULAN (Undated) _ How far Disney has come from ``The
Little Mermaid,'' an innocent, joyously childish tale about a
mermaid who yearns for legs. And how un-childlike are the deepest
pleasures of ``Mulan,'' an elegant film about a young woman in
ancient China who goes to war. By AMY BIANCOLLI
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GLF-OPEN-FANS (San Francisco) _ Golfers aren't the only ones
scoring at the U.S. Open championship. So are the fans. Kirk
Dowdell uses a ``Pope Scope'' _ a $10 must-have,
cardboard-and-glass gizmo invented for the pope's 1987 visit _ to
see over the view-obstructing heads of people standing in front of
him. By RACHEL GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ For 4 1/2 hours on Thursday I was
a citizen of Tiger Nation, the most rapidly growing nation in the
world. If I had a dollar for every time I heard the word ``Tiger''
at the U.S. Open, I'd have made more money in one day than Tiger
Woods ever has. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ One of the darkest fears I hear
expressed by the 50 or so people who call me every day is that the
poor are ripping them off. I can understand resentment against
able-bodied adults who are on the dole. Especially when those
able-bodied adults happen to be collecting aid while they're behind
bars. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
