<HEADER>
A6949 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEST-FILMS-HNS &LR;      06-19 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEST-FILMS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE `TOP 100' ARE IN THE EYE OF THE BEHOLDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   No ``Notorious''? ``White Heat'' blacked out? ``Roman Holiday''
left in ruins?
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to the American Film Institute's ``Top 100''
domestic films of the last century, quibbling is just too easy.
Movie buffs could bicker for hours on end (and some have) over the
ranking, which was announced Tuesday night in a worshipful
three-hour CBS television special.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the list has been the source of much discussion and
consternation. What made it is moot. It's what didn't that irks us
most.
</P>
<P>
   ``Funny Girl'' didn't. ``Ship of Fools'' didn't (it wasn't even
on the ballot). ``She Done Him Wrong'' didn't, despite some of Mae
West's randiest come-ons (including ``Whyncha come up sometime, 'n'
see me?''). ``Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf?'' didn't, despite
Richard Burton and Elizabeth Taylor in their greatest, most
vitriolic and elemental roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Producers'' didn't. ``The Awful Truth'' didn't. ``Safety
Last'' didn't, proving that even Harold Lloyd couldn't overcome an
innate industry prejudice against comedy (silent, at that).
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Chaplin made it (with three: ``City Lights,'' ``Modern
Times'' and ``The Gold Rush''), although he's been caught slumming
in the bottom third of the list. His masterpiece in sound film, an
insane anti-fascist satire called ``The Great Dictator,'' wasn't on
the ballot. The Marx Brothers are duly represented by ``Duck
Soup,'' but where the heck is ``Animal Crackers,'' or ``Horse
Feathers''? (Answer: not on the ballot.)
</P>
<P>
   What about Fred Astaire in ``Top Hat?'' And the griping never
ends.
</P>
<P>
   That's the problem with a list like this: Everyone who's ever
gone to the movies has a really loud opinion. The AFI determined
its winners from a tally of 1,500 voters (including filmmakers,
critics, historians and assorted bigwigs), who chose their top 100
choices from a ballot of 400 domestic feature films.
</P>
<P>
   In determining the ``best,'' voters were asked to consider a
film's historical significance, critical reception, popularity and
box office. It's important to remember that a movie's artistic
value or dramatic impact was not the sole criterion. It's important
to remember, too, that the AFI's voters were not asked to rate
their choices from one to 100; a movie's ranking merely reflects
the number of people who included it in their final lump of 100.
</P>
<P>
   ``Citizen Kane'' made No. 1 because more people included it in
their final list than any other film. Anyone could have predicted
it would win, teetering over such celluloid titans as ``The
Godfather'' (No. 3), ``The Wizard of Oz'' (No. 6) and ``The Bridge
on the River Kwai'' (No. 13).
</P>
<P>
   Orson Welles' masterwork is a movie everyone can agree on. It's
groundbreaking cinema, artful, poetic and thrillingly smart. No one
participating in the AFI vote would have dared leave it off their
list; it's too important, already too widely regarded as the
greatest movie ever made.
</P>
<P>
   Try leaving ``Hamlet'' off of a list of Top 100 English Plays,
and you get the idea.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Citizen Kane'' is a cerebral winner, a film more studied
and admired than cherished and enjoyed. No one rents it because
they're in the mood for a good laugh, or a long cry, or a sweet,
extended swoon over dreamy kisses; for that, there's
``Casablanca,'' the AFI's runner-up.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Citizen Kane'' is an egghead No. 1, ``Casablanca'' is a No.
2 built for Kleenex. There are better Humphrey Bogart films
(``Treasure of the Sierra Madre,'' No. 30), and better Ingrid
Bergman films (``Notorious,'' which didn't make it), and better
Michael Curtiz films (``Angels with Dirty Faces,'' ditto), but
``Casablanca'' yanks hard at our emotions. It's the sentimental
favorite, the romance all of us secretly wished were ours.
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, the ballyhooed ``Top 100'' has nothing to do with the
best American movies. It has everything to do with our favorites
movies we've seen 10, or 15, or 25 times, movies we grew up or grew
old with, movies that resonate in our now-departing 20th-century
culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a Wonderful Life'' is No. 8 because we have it memorized;
``The Wizard of Oz'' is No. 6 because of ``Toto, too''; ``Gone with
the Wind'' is No. 4 because we hum Max Steiner's score in the
shower. They can't be regarded, any longer, with anything
approaching critical detachment; it's like watching your kids in a
high-school play. Even their errors are proof of greatness.
</P>
<P>
   So along with the critical darlings (``Raging Bull,'' 24) and
hoary historical milestones (``Birth of a Nation,'' 44), the list
highlights films that have no business being in a best-of anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Fair Lady'' (91) is a charming slice of misogyny, but not
much more. ``Yankee Doodle Dandy'' (100) is fun, but so is ``On the
Town,'' which wasn't nominated. ``Forrest Gump'' sneaked onto the
list at 71, a reflection not of the movie's inherent worth but of
the mass hypnosis that turned it into a cult.
</P>
<P>
   For even less discernible reasons, ``Dances with Wolves''
slipped in at 75, just one shy of ``The Gold Rush.'' But why be a
crab about it? We all have our most-loved movies our childhood
crushes, favorite scenes, and pet likes and dislikes that make no
sense to others.
</P>
<P>
   Naming the best 100 movies is a pointless task, because a good
film spurs intense emotional response. It inspires passion, anger,
terror, anxiety, laughter, grief or delight. Despite all the talk
of lighting and camera angles and well-crafted scripts, the act of
moviegoing is a profoundly subjective experience. Movies are our
secret worlds; when we enter, we give ourselves up to fantasy. The
films that hold us firmly are those that win our hearts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 1130EDT &QL; 
