<HEADER>
A6950 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-MULAN-HNS     06-19 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-MULAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MULAN,' POETRY IN MOTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   How far Disney has come from ``The Little Mermaid,'' an
innocent, joyously childish tale about a mermaid who yearns for
legs. And how un-childlike are the deepest pleasures of ``Mulan,''
an elegant film about a young woman who goes to war.
</P>
<P>
   The setting alone isn't exactly kids' stuff: ancient China, at
the time of the Hun invasions. The story, a timeworn legend that
involves Mulan's cross-dressing, army training and daring military
exploits, is deadly serious business. And the artwork _ epic Asian
imagery, shimmering pastel backgrounds and vivid-yet-graceful
characterizations _ is as sophisticated, and as ravishing, as
anything the studio's animators have produced. Despite its family
pedigree, ``Mulan'' is a grown-up film.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Disney sticks to its standard formula, diluting a sober plot
with comic relief (the voices of Eddie Murphy, Harvey Fierstein)
and hip-hip-hooray hymns and ballads that sound sweet but have the
nutritive value of a marshmallow. The songs are by pop craftsman
Matthew Wilder (who wrote a bit for ``The Air Up There'') and
lyricist David Zippel (``Hercules''), and they have a familiar,
labored earnestness think ``Pocahontas,'' revamped for the Northern
Wei Dynasty. No one will be humming these tunes when the lights go
down.
</P>
<P>
   What the film lacks in musical verve it makes up for in
grandeur. ``Mulan'' opens on an exquisite image of the Great Wall
at night, just as a mountainously muscled Hun leader named Shan-Yu
(Miguel Ferrer, doing a cool Clint Eastwood) is mounting his
invasion of China. Shan-Yu, a rock-like fellow with gleaming yellow
eyes and a hawk to match, is a villain in the grand comic-book
tradition of hulking bad guys the nastier the malefactor, the
thicker the neck.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the flame-haired Hades of ``Hercules,'' Shan-Yu is
little more than a plot device, a relatively minor character with
limited screen time and no apparent superpowers (beyond the ability
to survive an avalanche). He sings no songs; he sports no wiseacre
anthropomorphic sidekicks.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good thing, too, because it allows the film to focus on a
terrific main character. Animated with great elasticity and fire,
and voiced with a neat sardonic edge by Ming-Na Wen (but sung by
Lea Salonga, Kim in Broadway's ``Miss Saigon''), Mulan is the
stubbornest in a long line of triumphantly obstinate Disney
heroines.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, she's a klutz. She hates makeup, speaks out of
turn, blows her first meeting with a husky matchmaker (she sets her
rump on fire) and is prone to wildly funny slapstick pratfalls.
</P>
<P>
   ``When will my reflection show who I am inside?'' she sings,
then rests in a garden scattered with blushing pink blossoms. A few
moments later she learns of the Hun invasion from an imperial
messenger, who demands the conscription of one man from each
family.
</P>
<P>
   Mulan's family has one man: her proud, aged father, voiced by
Pat Morita with infinitely craggy wisdom. ``It is my honor to
protect my country. . .. I know my place. It is time you learned
yours!'' he rebukes Mulan. Mulan knows her place, but she doesn't
want to stay in it. While her parents sleep, she cuts her hair,
dons her father's armor, assumes the identity of a young man and
rides off to war. Imagine ``Yentl,'' dressed for combat.
</P>
<P>
   Mulan's quest awakes her slumbering ancestors, who grumble about
the kid's rebelliousness (``I knew it, I knew it! Mulan was a
troublemaker from the start!'') but resolve to help. They appoint a
runt dragon named Mushu (voiced by Murphy with gut-popping puffery)
to rouse a powerful stone statue, but Mushu accidentally shatters
the old guy and scoots off to aid Mulan on his own (``travel size,
for your convenience!'' he boasts, explaining his size).
</P>
<P>
   Once in boot camp, Mushu instructs her in the fine art of
manliness (``punch him'') and assists her training, led by the
studly Captain Shang (voiced by B.D. Wong, sung by Donny Osmond).
</P>
<P>
   Mulan, renamed Ping, pals around with army buddies Yao (Harvey
Fierstein) and Ling (Gedde Watanabe) and helps pursue the advancing
Huns. Along the way there are glorious vistas (inspired by David
Lean) and breathtaking windows into ancient Chinese culture: a
scene in which Hun soldiers ring the lip of a snowy crest is
arresting and unforgettable.
</P>
<P>
   The marvel of ``Mulan'' is its juxtaposition of visually poetic
images with the roughness of battle; it's a watercolor portrait of
war. There's no gore to speak of _ despite the combat sequences,
one scene in a burnt village and a bit of hand-to-hand violence in
the climax. The 4-year-old accompanying this reviewer was adamantly
unfazed (although she had a better time at ``Barney's Great
Adventure'').
</P>
<P>
   Yet it's a weird gumbo, this mix of adult subject matter,
radiant artistry, saccharine tunes and a buoyant, child-friendly
jokiness. It doesn't quite gel _ as though Disney yearned to be a
grown-up film _ but couldn't bear to abandon its family-movie
formula or the Happy Meal revenues it promises.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mulan'' may be art, but it's art that yields to commerce.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 1131EDT &QL; 
