<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Global grilling
 &HT;    By Jan Norris
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Americans aren't the only ones who get fired up about grilling.
Here's a look at barbecuing in different countries.
</P>
<P>
   Morocco and Greece: Skewered meats, typically lamb, cooked over
direct heat. Mediterranean spices, such as garlic, lemon and
oregano used in basting sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Southeast Asia, Japan: Whole fish cooked over small hibachi-type
grills, with dipping sauces that include soy, ginger, honey and
often, hot chiles.
</P>
<P>
   Caribbean: Pork and chicken cooked over open-pit barbecues or
roadside steel drums. Sweet-hot spicy rubs (jerk seasoning) are
applied to the meat.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal, Spain and France: Rotisserie-cooked roasts, primarily
beef and lamb, with basting sauces flavored with wine, garlic and
fresh herbs.
</P>
<P>
   Scandinavia, Pacific Northwest: Smoked foods, particularly fish.
Fish is salted before smoking; flavoring comes from the wood used.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
