A6957 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DONATE-SHOES20-COX     06-19 0395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DONATE-SHOES20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Good soles?
 &HT;    By Tim Pallesen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH _ Residents of one of the city's poorest
neighborhoods were blessed with thousands of sports and outdoor
shoes recently after looters raided a tractor-trailer filled with 5
tons of name brands parked a block off Tamarind Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Chip Woods said he concluded that it would be ``stupid''
to ask anyone to return the stolen shoes. ``For some of those kids
there, this was probably their first pair of new shoes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Herbert Gross, a 37-year-old trucker from Tallahassee, told
police he exited Interstate 95 around 2 p.m. Wednesday (June 18) on
his Miami-to-Mississippi run because he was looking for sex and
marijuana. ``He flagged down a young lady riding a bike and asked
if she wanted to party,'' Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   An anonymous caller later told police that drug dealers broke
into the 18-wheeler first, followed by others who wanted new men's
shoes by Rockport, Nike, Tommy Hilfiger, Timberland and Nautica.
</P>
<P>
   Two cars collided on 13th Street trying to reach the scene,
Woods said. About 40 people were inside the trailer when police
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a free-for-all. Everyone came from everywhere,'' said
Edward Robinson, who lives on 13th Street between Tamarind and
Douglas avenues where Gross parked before police said he
disappeared into a nearby rooming house with an unidentified
25-year-old woman.
</P>
<P>
   Police retrieved about one-third of the shoes _ nearly 1,700
pairs _ which were strewn on the street or still in the trailer
when they arrived. Some of the looters had left old shoes where
they'd sat down to try on their new shoes, Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   John Fayard, the wayward trucker's boss in Gulfport, Miss.,
declined comment Thursday, except to say his insurance will pay for
the shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was looked upon by this neighborhood as an opportunity _
not a crime,'' said resident Edward Fitzgerald. ``Was it a crime
for Michael Milken to make all that money on junk bonds?''
</P>
<P>
   Only Edward Robinson, the loss prevention director at the
Mississippi salvage yard where the shoes were to be delivered for
reshipment, called the police giveaway an outrage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe anybody should keep things they steal,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
