<DOCNO> NYT19980619.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 11:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6999 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-19 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELCOME TO TIGER NATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Filed in the commentary, ``k,'' and sports, ``s''
categories)  
 Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For 4 1/2 hours Thursday I was a citizen of
Tiger Nation, the most rapidly growing nation in the world. If I
had a dollar for every time I heard the word ``Tiger'' at the
Olympic Club, I'd have made more money in one day than Tiger Woods
ever has.
</P>
<P>
   Forget about the thwank of titanium on Titleist. Here's what the
U.S. Open sounds like: ``Tiger, Tiger, Tiger ...''
</P>
<P>
   You hear it on the shuttle bus going in, along all the fairways,
at all the concession stands and on the bus going out. The
pulsating sound of ``Tiger'' blots out the caws of crows, the beat
of camera helicopters and the drone of golf jargon on the
sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we cut across here, we can catch Tiger.'' ``Tiger hit a
bullet with that one.'' ``Did you see Tiger bogey on that hole?''
``Did you see? Tiger threw his putter.''
</P>
<P>
   Need I say Woods? Need I say the most famous sports hero in the
world, even for those who don't quite consider golf a sport?
</P>
<P>
   The only break you get from hearing his name is when the
marshals hush the crowd before a shot, and thank God for that bit
of etiquette.
</P>
<P>
   Etiquette crumbles somewhat when the Tiger stampede starts. When
it's coming at you, you know how Custer felt when he saw the Sioux
nation coming.
</P>
<P>
   Except this nation comes in all races, ages and color of polo
shirts, and you don't die, except maybe of boredom. This is golf,
after all.
</P>
<P>
   It starts with the tiny figure of Tiger Woods swinging a club
far in the distance. Before the ball finishes rolling 290 yards
toward you, the horde of uncountable thousands is coming your way
along the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, one Tiger chaser would slip down an embankment,
taking two or three others with him, but they keep coming after a
brief ``Are you OK?'' and ``Excuse me.'' Golf is still a polite
sport, and this is a polite stampede.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Nation isn't quite what you'd think it is. Most Tiger
stalkers were like most golfers _ older white guys who'd look right
in a Lexus. Tiger is a golf phenom, not an ethnic phenom.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there were a lot of young people. At 6:30 a.m. high school
students Nancy Luu and Jason Cunningham already had staked out
seats in the top row of the bleachers at the 18th hole.
</P>
<P>
   After the crowds arrived, 11-year-old Anthony Sigg of
Sacramento, Calif., was sitting on his dad's shoulders watching
Tiger. ``He's got a better view than I do,'' said his dad, Clay
Sigg.
</P>
<P>
   The youngster said, ``I'm here to see Tiger and Davis Love.''
Anthony already plays golf and knows that there are a lot more
golfers than Tiger.
</P>
<P>
   The complexion of the crowd at the U.S. Open had changed quite a
bit since the last time it was at the Olympic Club in 1987. There
were hundreds of African Americans, Asian Americans and Asians.
Shinichi and Chikako Saito came all the way from Osaka, Japan, to
watch the tournament in their new Stanford University sweat shirts,
and yes, watch Stanford's most famous alumnus.
</P>
<P>
   Guys who usually play public courses, like Frank Brown and
Richard Lomax of Sacramento, ogled the Olympic Club. ``These
fairways look like our greens at home,'' Lomax said.
</P>
<P>
   Why were they there? ``Tiger, I have to say Tiger,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   I saw a teen-ager in a Tupac Shakur T-shirt and baggy pants,
which led to the most interesting clothing clash on the course all
day.
</P>
<P>
   Two girls his age walked by, looked at his Tupac shirt and
giggled. They were wearing Bermudas and blouses in Muffy-Buffy
plaids. Hey, who's wearing the funny clothes here?
</P>
<P>
   Tiger unites all, though. As he approached the 14th hole, the
kid in the Tupac shirt began chatting with an older man in a blue
blazer and Panama hat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, Tiger's in trouble,'' the Tupac kid said. ``That ball
really rolled backward,'' the blazer man said. ``Like a rolling
stone,'' the kid said. ``Come on, Tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tiger, Tiger, Tiger. But there were other names, and even the
most star-struck Tiger groupie knew them.
</P>
<P>
   John Daly, what a guy. He looks like John Candy's younger,
meaner brother. He hits long, lives large and is my kind of
athletic role model. A Kaiser roll model.
</P>
<P>
   I was waiting along the first fairway for Tiger when Daly's ball
landed nearby. He leaned on his club and lit up a ciggy. When it
was time to hit, he crushed it on the fairway. His caddy picked up
the butt.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the kinds of details you see watching golf in person
that you'll never see on television.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Watson played in the same group with Tiger and got bigger
cheers on occasion. Golf is the only sport where you'll hear a
woman in the crowd say to her husband, ``Tom is looking awfully
well, isn't he?''
</P>
<P>
   They don't say anything about guys' butts, as in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Another comment I heard on the sidelines was, ``He's got his
glove off. That's interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the power of this sport. The player in question put his
glove back on, leading to follow-up glove analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Some advice if you're going on safari with Tiger this weekend.
Just do it briefly. It's great to see him up close, but you only
see parts of him between heads, under visors and around carefully
bobbed hair.
</P>
<P>
   There has to be more to watching golf than that. Don't ask me. I
only saw Tiger once close up, and never did see him sink a putt. I
assume he did.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger and Tiger and Tiger, oh my.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 1155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980619.0086 </DOCNO>
