<HEADER>
A7009 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RESEND-YOUNG-COLUMN20     06-19 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESEND-YOUNG-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   RESEND: Fix on spelling in the 6th graph.
</P>
<P>
   Commentary: Let's all get bald
</P>
<P>
   By John Young
</P>
<P>
   C.1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ I just realized I should stop pretending I was
somebody else and start being like Mike, which is bald.
</P>
<P>
   I tell myself I'm not bald every day when, looking in the
mirror, I lean my head just so. Then from far-off points I comb the
morning strands in a left-to-right swipe. It is their commute to
work.
</P>
<P>
   I realized the futility of this exercise the morning after
Michael Jordan won his sixth NBA title, his teammates hugging his
neck like superfluous follicles.
</P>
<P>
   I thought to myself: Here is this man the world adores, the
epitome of grace, style and merchandizing, and he's got nothing on
his head but Air.
</P>
<P>
   And look at heads around the league, and look at the leagues
below, the colleges, the high schools, the junior high leagues.
There's more skin there than Sports Illustrated's swimsuit edition,
which has less and less suit every year.
</P>
<P>
   And we're not just talking about black guys. During the playoffs
the Indiana Pacers, in an apparent team initiative to make coach
Larry Bird look prettier than John Tesh, all shaved their heads.
Now, head-shaved, seven-footer Rick Smits is no Yul Brynner.
Indeed, if Brynner had a backyard hound, the sight of Smits would
have caused it to lose its skin. But if that guy can parade lobar
nudity with pride, so can the rest of us. The fact is, we know we
can because Mike does.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, this is about Michael Jordan. Just ask NBC. He's next to
God and bigger than the Beatles.
</P>
<P>
   One might protest, pointing out that the Beatles changed hair
styles around the world, and not just in smelly gyms. But the fact
is that bald consciousness is conquering the world. The other night
I saw Ringo Starr on the ``Tonight'' show. What was the legendary
mop-top wearing on his head? Just this side of nothing. Ringo has a
Rick Smits cut.
</P>
<P>
   Let's all get bald. Gov. George Bush? Let's get bald. Sen. Kay
Bailey Hutchison? Let's get bald.
</P>
<P>
   As hairlessness sweeps the land, we must wonder about economic
hardships, all those hair cuts, and who's making a mint off the
little man. In Waco, this trend could vault the local barber into
the income bracket occupied only by the local allergist.
</P>
<P>
   That's why I'm the one next to make a mint. I've applied for a
patent on a new hair-loss drug _ no, not to restore hair, to lose
it. Pending FDA approval, I think the trademark I've secured,
Nogaine, is a winner.
</P>
<P>
   The baldness-causing agent? That's secret, of course. Generally,
I can tell you it's synthesized to mimic pheromones found in the
blood of veterans of President Clinton's damage-control team. Now
you can have the luxurious shimmer of James Carville without his
blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   In salve or pill, Nogaine can give you MJ's shine, if not his
jump shot. Hey, you take what you can get.
</P>
<P>
   We're coming to understand that this hair stuff is an impediment
to excellence, all those wasteful spins on the salon chair, all
those creams and combs. With Nogaine, fuss no more.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Bulls' championship was a symbolic victory by the
forces of baldness over those of baldness remedies. Utah's Karl
Malone has been a TV spokesman for Rogaine. Loser.
</P>
<P>
   No I'm thinking that getting rid of unneeded hair may only be
the first big-money pharmaceutical opportunity brought on my modern
social developments.
</P>
<P>
   That's why, with women already starting to recoil from
scientific advances in the name of Viagra, my lab teams are busy
working on a pill to restore male impotence.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 1200EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980619.0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 12:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7012 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-CRITIC-HNS &LR;      06-19 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-CRITIC-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEW MEDIA MOGULS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ ``Murdoch's hair is turning white,'' writes New
Yorker media columnist Ken Auletta of plutocrat Rupert Murdoch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is 64, and his shoulders stoop slightly. His voice is soft,
and his manner is unfailingly courteous as he sits with one leg
tucked under the other. Only the hard brown eyes suggest that he is
a predator.''
</P>
<P>
   Close observation and the occasional use of stiletto prose
characterize Auletta's ``The Highwaymen,'' a collection of his New
Yorker pieces just published in an updated paperback edition by
Harcourt Brace.
</P>
<P>
   The book, first issued last year in hardcover, is built around
profiles of media moguls such as Murdoch, TCI's John Malone, Time
Warner's Ted Turner, Microsoft's Bill Gates and Viacom's Sumner
Redstone _ the toll-takers, construction bosses and salvage-truck
operators on the information superhighway.
</P>
<P>
   Auletta came through San Francisco recently to promote ``The
Highwaymen,'' which features a new introduction and a wholly new
chapter on Microsoft _ changes necessitated, he says, by the
pedal-to-the-metal speed at which the highwaymen move. Indeed, they
are going so fast, it unnerves even them, Auletta says.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you got inside Bill Gates' or Andy Grove's mind, you'd find
they're scared,'' Auletta says. ``Scared of (unpredictable)
technology, scared of government, scared of the press, scared of
consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   A desire to glimpse the human side of media tycoons and
understand how the emotional melds with the commercial is what
drives Auletta to craft his celebrated, fly-on-the-wall profiles.
``Essentially, you're visiting other planets and trying to
understand the natives,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to demonize these guys but they're people. They make
mistakes. They're driven by panic or by their desire for their
little place in history. These are not people waking up every day
thinking, `How many people can I kill today?'''
</P>
<P>
   Auletta, a trim, snappily dressed, 56-year-old, is a widely
published magazine writer and former New York Daily News and
Village Voice columnist. His previous book, ``Three Blind Mice,''
was a dissection of ABC, NBC and CBS, an insider's tale of how the
Big Three broadcast television networks failed to understand
changing technology and the changing media marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought of themselves as a single channel and not as a
newsstand,'' Auletta says of the networks' slowness (NBC partially
excepted) to diversify into cable TV and cyberspace. ``In
retrospect, that was quite dumb.''
</P>
<P>
   Auletta has been writing ``Annals of Communications'' for the
New Yorker since 1992. With its long lead times and acres of space,
the New Yorker allows Auletta to dig deeply and develop his
reporting on complex issues and complex people _ a rarity in the
age of sound-bite journalism.
</P>
<P>
   Auletta's M.O. is to spend time in board rooms and corporate
jets with members of the billionaire boys' club, seeing them
up-close and personal and, he hopes, unrehearsed. In the process,
he tries to glean insights into how they do deals and where they're
likely to go next on the Infobahn.
</P>
<P>
   For an unflattering piece on Murdoch titled ``The Pirate,''
Auletta spent eight days with the News Corp. chief over a
five-month period, taping 15 hours of interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Auletta says he tells his subjects at the outset that
```Everything is on the record unless you tell me it's not, and
there's no ex post facto off the record.'''
</P>
<P>
   ```I will be unobtrusive,''' Auletta says, continuing his
recitation of the ground rules. ```I won't talk (at business
meetings). I won't sit in a central seat. Look, I'm trying to
understand you. If I pick up stuff _ say, about a pending deal _
I'm not going to leak it to a daily reporter.'''
</P>
<P>
   When, as a fly-on-the-wall reporter, ``you get real close,
you're not just reporting press conferences. You're getting behind
the mask _ you think. They're always performing.''
</P>
<P>
   Auletta says he realizes that top CEOs might give him access to
their meetings, meals and tete-a-tetes because they think they can
co-opt him for their own self-promoting purposes, but he thinks
it's worth taking the risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get to be a CEO without a tremendous amount of
self-confidence, and you think you can persuade reporters to write
your version. But,'' Auletta says of his way of working, ``if
you're nice, quiet and subtle, they feel comfortable with you.
Ultimately, they're going to say things that they don't mean to
say.''
</P>
<P>
   Often an executive not ordinarily given to self-examination will
inadvertently reveal character.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Murdoch, the son of a relatively small-time
Australian newspaper proprietor, was snubbed at his exclusive
English boarding schools and made to feel the unworthy outsider as
a boy. Thus, while he is politically conservative, Murdoch sees
himself as anti-establishment and has a me-against-the-world
attitude. He is, in Auletta's opinion, driven as much by personal
animus as by political agendas.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Auletta rakes Murdoch for taking the BBC World Service
off his Star TV satellite network in China because the Beijing
government thought the BBC was too critical of China. He also takes
Murdoch to task for publishing a flattering biography _
hagiography, actually _ of Beijing's late paramount leader, Deng
Xiaoping, written by Deng's daughter for Murdoch's HarperCollins.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTINAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Auletta says he has no political agenda of his own. ``I'm not
there to prosecute a predetermined point,'' he says. Thus,
Auletta's pieces are characterized not so much by a unifying
political sensibility as by a storyteller's fascination with how
big personalities animate big issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Auletta's favorite piece in ``The Highwaymen'' is a chapter
titled ``What Won't You Do?'' Catching the commercial commissars of
culture off-guard by asking them where they draw the line on what
they will produce or distribute, he sends record company
executives, filmmakers and studio heads backpedaling furiously as
they defend violent, misogynist gangsta-rap and the salacious
offerings of tabloid TV as First Amendment treasures. At one point,
a huffy Oliver Stone, so very fond of bending historical facts to
his own liking in his movies, demands that Auletta quote him
accurately.
</P>
<P>
   Its very unpredictability, Auletta says, is what makes writing
about the modern media business interesting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have one of the great beats,'' he says.
``Intellectually, it's a great time to be covering
communications.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
