<HEADER>
A7019 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN     06-19 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSERVATIVE STANCE ON SUBMITTING GENERATES BACKLASH BY MODERATE
TEXANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Not All Baptists Have a 19th Century Mindset,'' declares a
statement sent out by moderate-led Texas Baptists.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are millions of Southern Baptists who do not believe
women are second-class citizens ...'' states the declaration. It is
part of the backlash to the Southern Baptist Convention's recent
adoption of a statement that wives are ``to graciously submit to
the servant leadership of their husbands.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A statement demeaning to women as that which passed the
Southern Baptist Convention in Salt Lake City would never pass in
the Baptist General Convention of Texas,'' declares the statement
issued by Texas Baptists Committed.
</P>
<P>
   It continues: ``We know that in God's eyes, men and women are
equal and that marriage is a partnership relationship between
equals and calls on both parties to seek to please and affirm each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Baptists Committed is a Baptist moderates support group
that during the last decade has fended off efforts of conservatives
to take over the Texas convention in the way they've done at the
national level.
</P>
<P>
   But while conservatives are in full control of the
Nashville-based Southern Baptist Convention, moderates, led by
Baylor University's moderates, control the independently governed
Baptist General Convention of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Baptists, whose state convention is larger than many
national denominations, have rebelled against what they call a
``fundamentalist'' mindset of the national Southern Baptist
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   While continuing to support Southern Baptist missionaries and
many other efforts of the national denomination, Texas Baptists now
send a smaller percentage of state money to the national
denomination and are backing moderate-led seminaries and university
theological training as an alternative to conservative graduate
theological training.
</P>
<P>
   David Currie, of San Angelo, coordinator of Texas Baptists
Committed, says Texas Baptists are the ``real'' Baptists and that
the conservatives in charge of the national denomination have
wandered off into the direction of the Rev. Jerry Falwell and other
more fundamentalist Baptists.
</P>
<P>
   The Southern Baptist Convention's statement about wives
submitting was approved earlier this month in Salt Lake City as
part of a larger document on ``The Family,'' which also rejects
homosexual ``marriages'' and asks children to be obedient to their
parents.
</P>
<P>
   Along with statements about women being ``helpers'' to their
husbands, Bible verses are quoted, including the Genesis account of
Adam and Eve and how a woman will be a helpmate to a man.
</P>
<P>
   The statement was added to the Baptist Faith and Message
Statement, a general statement of beliefs that must be signed by
all professors at the six seminaries supported by the national
denomination.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Southern Baptist leaders, including the outgoing
convention president, the Rev. Tom Elliff, of Del City, Okla.,
defended the statement on ``The Family'' and said the pronouncement
wasn't interpreted well by the news media.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you hear about from the media is submitting,'' Elliff
said. ``But the statement was about a lot more than submission. It
nullifies any thought of homosexual unions and the big call is for
husbands to love their wives as Christ loves the church.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliff said the biblical teaching doesn't mean wives have to
knuckle under to husbands who mistreat them and their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be hard to submit to a cruel husband, but what we are
talking about is the ideal situation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Currie, head of Texas Baptists Committed, said moderate Baptists
will take out ads in state Baptist newspapers _ and perhaps in
secular publications _ to let the public know that not all Southern
Baptists agree with ``fundamentalists'' on the submitting
statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Southern Baptist Convention is becoming an embarrassment
to traditional Baptists,'' Currie said.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
