<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7040 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-US-HNS &LR;      06-19 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-US-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN'S ASSURANCES MEET WITH SKEPTICISM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDs: FILED in ``i'' and ``f'' categories)   News Analysis  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ On at least two counts, past experience does not
encourage optimism that America's intervention to prop up the
wilting Japanese yen will prove effective for long.
</P>
<P>
   First, intervention in money markets has not generally worked,
and second, Japan in the past has repeatedly failed to live up to
its promises to straighten out its economic problems.
</P>
<P>
   Previous moves to halt the decline of a major currency by buying
up large amounts of it in world markets have had only temporary
impact unless matched by quick fiscal and economic policies by the
government under fire. As one Paris banker said Friday,
``Intervention is a tactic for buying time, but the time passes
swiftly unless other measures are taken.''
</P>
<P>
   Japan's Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto has pledged such steps,
declaring he will act speedily to stimulate his country's economy
and swiftly revamp the crippled banking system, with its pile of
bad loans, that has been a major factor in the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   But Hashimoto has made similar promises before and failed to
follow through. As the London Financial Times pointed out: ``There
remains widespread skepticism about whether Mr. Hashimoto's
announcement contains anything new and, even if it does, about the
strength of the Japanese commitment to carry out the reforms.''
</P>
<P>
   The British daily said the forces within Japan that have been
blocking genuine reforms are so powerful that Hashimoto might have
to resign if he tried to do what he has promised. The entrenched
bureaucracy that has long run Japan still appears reluctant to
change the methods that brought unprecedented post-World War II
prosperity but have now badly failed.
</P>
<P>
   The paper warned that Hashimoto might falter unless Washington
``cajoles an inward-looking Japanese leadership toward doing what
needs to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   More currency intervention would not be enough, it said, adding
that Congressional opposition to further monetary injections could
be expected since many lawmakers ``believe public money should
never be used to help countries in distress.''
</P>
<P>
   French economist and former Finance Ministry official Francois
Ringet said the United States ``will have to keep a relentless eye
on the Japanese to ensure that they fulfill their commitment. As
events have now shown, only the Americans possess the financial and
political power to keep the Japanese from delaying and finding ways
of not living up to their promises.''
</P>
<P>
   The French analyst questioned Washington's ``attention span,''
however. ``The Americans tend to get diverted because of their
worldwide responsibilities,'' he contended. ``Japanese officials
are aware of this from previous experience. They have patience and
know how to wait out those who seek to compel them to adopt
policies they have no desire to carry out.''
</P>
<P>
   Japanese officials have been guilty of trying to cover up
aspects of the crisis, Ringet noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Finance Ministry concedes that bad bank loans are three
times higher than previously disclosed, nearly $600 billion,'' he
said. ``The Finance Ministry tried to hide the extent of the losses
because it hasn't wanted to force more bank closures. This is not
how a modern government should be run and is hardly a way to
instill confidence in how the Japanese will do things from now
on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 1229EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
