A7120 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLBROOKE-ANALYSIS-BO     06-19 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLBROOKE-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLBROOKE: AIDES SEE STRONGER US VOICE AT UN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton nominated Richard Holbrooke as
ambassador to the United Nations Thursday, to energize the US
foreign policy team as crises loom in Asia, the Balkans and the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   The current UN ambassador, Bill Richardson, has not provided the
punch Clinton wants, according to some administration officials.
``Richardson has not been dynamic or forceful, he's been solid and
competent,'' said one who, like others who have worked with
Richardson and Holbrooke, asked not to be named.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton chose Holbrooke, a hard-charging diplomat and investment
banker, because the United States is struggling to reform the
United Nations while prodding allies to take tougher approaches
against pariah countries such as Iraq. At the same time, the
administration wanted a forceful advocate to urge Congress to pay
back dues of more than $1 billion to the UN.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke's experience in business will help ``shape a UN that
is leaner, more efficient, better equipped'' and prepared for the
21st century,'' Clinton said as he announced the nomination in a
Rose Garden ceremony Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. More to the point, ``Foreign policy is going to get a
lot more interesting with (Holbrooke) in the mix,'' said James
Gibney, managing editor of Foreign Policy, a publication that
Holbrooke once edited.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke has openly campaigned for a high-level job foreign
policy job in the administration for two years. Officials who
followed the decision-making said the traits that initially hurt
him _ including an oversized ego and a reputation for stirring
things up _ worked to his advantage this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton and Gore want Holbrooke's energy and they'd like a new
approach on problems such as Kosovo and dealing with the UN
Security Council,'' one official said.
</P>
<P>
   The ascension of Holbrooke, a friend of both Clinton and Vice
President Al Gore, comes as the administration tries to recover
from several foreign policy setbacks. The Middle East process is
stalled, and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright's top advisers
fear a resurgence of terrorism against Israelis. Nuclear tests by
India in May caught the United States by surprise, despite what had
been regarded as a close relationship with the government in New
Delhi.
</P>
<P>
   At the UN, the administration is frustrated by European
governments' reluctance to impose harsh sanctions on Iraq. And many
of Clinton's advisers agree with Holbrooke's assertion that ethnic
fighting in the Kosovo province of Serbia will spill out to
neighboring countries unless the West quells the violence soon.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton Thursday called his foreign policy team
``cohesive,'' Albright, Secretary of Defense William Cohen and
National Security Adviser Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger have at times
disagreed over such issues as how to contain Saddam Hussein and how
long to keep 8,000 US troops in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking with reporters Thursday, Richardson expressed
frustration at his failure to persuade Congress to pay the UN dues
owed by America. ``I thought I could make a difference,'' he said.
``I regret I couldn't be ambassador a little bit longer. The
president asked me about this (Energy Department) job. I'm
interested in domestic policy.... I'm not a professional foreign
policy person. I'm basically a politician and proud to be. I'd like
to run for office again.''
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting with India's new government this spring, Richardson
reportedly spent little time talking about the prospect of nuclear
tests and said the United States wanted to broaden its
relationship. Just a few weeks later, India conducted five atomic
blasts.
</P>
<P>
   US officials disagreed about exactly what Richardson had said
during his private meetings in New Delhi, and several said the
State Department had unfairly blamed him for failing to send clear
signals to India.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said that in 1996, Albright resisted suggestions
that Holbrooke serve at the UN because of his reputation for
working on his own and bucking his superiors. But after a year and
a half as Secretary of State, Albright apparently feels comfortable
enough to share the limelight.
</P>
<P>
   Since John F. Kennedy appointed Adlai Stevenson ambassador to
the UN in 1961, most political appointees in the post have been
made members of the Cabinet. Although in theory they report to the
secretary of state, they sit at Cabinet meetings and give their own
recommendations on policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's chatter today that Madeleine must be upset because she
might find herself challnged more often by Dick, but that's
nonsense,'' said James F. Hoge, editor of Foreign Affairs. ``There
is a strengthening of the foreign policy team, not a change in
direction. Dick brings quite a body of experience.''
</P>
<P>
   As a diplomat, Holbrooke has been involved in major events from
the Paris Peace Talks that ended the Vietnam war to the Dayton
talks that brought a fragile peace to Bosnia. Currently the vice
president of Credit Suisse First Boston, he served as a young
diplomat under then Secretary of State Henry Kissinger, worked as a
Peace Corps country director in Morocco, assistant secretary of
State for Asia and ambassador to Germany.
</P>
<P>
   A devout believer in the UN, NATO and other organizations,
Holbrooke likes to quote one of the architects of European unity,
Jean Monnet, who said, ``Nothing is possible without men, but
nothing is lasting without institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and Republicans agree that without Holbrooke's
constant prodding, the Bosnian peace accord would not have been
signed in 1995. But not everyone is a fan of Holbrooke or the
peacekeeping mission he engineered.
</P>
<P>
   ``His crown jewel is a failure,'' James M. Inhofe, a Republican
from Oklahoma who chairs the Senate Armed Forces Readiness
Committee, said in an interview Thursday. Holbrooke, he said,
``wants to leave the troops in Bosnia until the policy works or
until everyone is worn out.''
</P>
<P>
   James Henderson, who monitors European policy at the cnservative
Heritage Foundation, cautioned against reading too much into the
nomination. ``This says as much as domestic policy as anything
else,'' he said. ``Holbrooke is positioning himself as Secretary of
State for the Gore administration, if that comes to pass.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The Globe's UN correspondent, Colum Lynch, contributed to this
report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
