<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7127 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENNOCHI-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-19 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENNOCHI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIRTUAL UNREALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN VENNOCHI  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Hide the Big Dig? Put the Boston Garden demolition
under wraps?
</P>
<P>
   Instead, why not build a ``Truman Show'' kind of set when the
Democratic National Committee comes to town next week?
</P>
<P>
   Create a virtual Boston. That will make it even easier to
promote the ideal city that doesn't exist _ instead of the
charmingly imperfect one that does.
</P>
<P>
   Putting the city's best foot forward is a noble goal in the
effort to convince the DNC to pick Boston for its year 2000
convention. Conventions are big business and spinoff from a
national political convention is estimated at $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   But how much of our collective soul should we sell to grab it?
And if we really want to shield DNC honchos from the city's
negative points, why stop the cover-up at the Big Dig or the
Garden's sad and dusty remains?
</P>
<P>
   Throw a tarp on lower Washington Street, where what's left of
the Combat Zone spills into an unsightly hodgepodge between the
Lafayette Hotel and Kneeland Street. And while we're at it, drape
another tarp over graceless Kenmore Square.
</P>
<P>
   The Public Garden is delightful. But the Boston Common,
especially bordering Tremont Street, is a bit ragged. Surely, we
need to spruce it up. If we can't find temporary homes for the
homeless who camp out there, maybe we can outfit them in camouflage
suits _ the better to blend in with the greenery.
</P>
<P>
   There's good food and atmosphere, not to mention Paul Revere's
house, in the North End. But there are also truckloads of trash.
Better keep the DNC off the Freedom Trail and out of that Boston
neighborhood _ as well as most others, if you fear reality.
</P>
<P>
   Have you ever walked through Haymarket after the pushcart
vendors are done for the day? If so, you have heard the sound of
scampering feet and seen the small shadows _ cast not by children,
but by rats. That's another eyesore we wouldn't want to foist upon
the DNC.
</P>
<P>
   And rats aren't the only living creatures worthy of disguise. We
can fill up our perfect virtual city with perfect virtual people.
For instance: how about a mayor who speaks poetry instead of _ how
shall we put it _ prose?
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, that's ridiculous. Our plain-speaking mayor, is, in
fact, the driving force behind Boston's bid. It takes
nuts-and-bolts planning and old-fashioned strategizing, not flights
of fanciful speech or thinking, to sell a city, thank goodness.
</P>
<P>
   It's just as ridiculous for the city to try to ignore the
elephant in the living room that is known as the Big Dig. Anyone
who sets car or foot in the city knows it's impossible to avoid,
let alone ignore. And the 50 or so DNC represenatives who will
begin arriving Monday, will quickly find that out, too.
</P>
<P>
   So, perhaps this is the appropriate moment to suggest that
whatever the cost and aggravation of this massive public works
project, the planning behind it seems to be paying off.
</P>
<P>
   Cranes dot the skyline. Gaping holes loom behind safety
barriers. At times it seems the city has been taken over by
construction workers and their plodding equipment. Even so, Boston
is not gridlocked. At least not every moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to hide it,'' insists Kelley Quinn, one of
the city officials heading the effort to woo the DNC. ``The reality
is, I agree that psychologically it could be a barrier, but
physically it's not.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Guzzi, president of the Greater Boston Chamber of Commerce,
says the convention bid has allowed the business and political
communities to rally in a very positive way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're going to get it,'' says Guzzi. But if
Boston doesn't win this bid, he and others believe politics with a
capital ``P,'' not logistics will be the more likely reason.
</P>
<P>
   Six other cities besides Boston are in the mix for the DNC
convention: Denver, Los Angeles, Miami, Minneapolis, New Orleans,
and Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The other cities will, doubtless, be doing what Boston is doing,
too. As Patrick Moscaritolo, who heads the Greater Boston
Convention and Visitors Bureau, points out, ``In any marketing
campaign, you always show your top assets. The `wows.'''
</P>
<P>
   The bigger trick is to turn an ``ow'' into a ``wow.'' Perhaps a
Big Dig theme park?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Joan Vennochi is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
