<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7135 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CHINA-BOS &LR;      06-19 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CHINA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US TO PRESS CHINA QUIETLY ON DISSIDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and w coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a significant tactical shift, President Clinton
will press his demands for the release of over a dozen Chinese
dissidents at next week's summit in China in closed meetings, not
in the media.
</P>
<P>
   After years of wrangling publically with China over human
rights, the administration has decided to take a different approach
for the nine-day summit, which starts June 26. This stance is based
in part on the fact that China no longer holds dissidents who are
well-known outside of the country.
</P>
<P>
   The change is also an admission that the old US policy did not
work. As celebrated dissidents were freed from prison, others were
put behind bars. Clinton and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
will stress that Washington wants basic legal reforms in China, not
simply a trickle of prisoner releases in coming months.
</P>
<P>
   Once they settled in the United States, many of the former
dissidents lost their effectiveness as protesters. They spent more
of their time in school or making money or squabbling among
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``If China continues to release people on the condition that
they go into exile, even the administration realizes they can't
point to that as a real sign of success,'' said Mike Jendrzejczyk,
Washington director of Human Rights Watch.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the administration has worked with non-governmental
groups in compiling a high-priority list of dissidents to be freed.
But their names have not been released. This is in sharp contrast
to last fall's Sino-American summit in Washington, when the White
House made no secret of its desire to see the release of Wei
Jingsheng and Wang Dan, prominent democracy activists.
</P>
<P>
   Both Wei and Wang were exiled to the United States after the
summit, supposedly because of their deteriorating health. Last
year, under pressure from the United States, China revised its laws
so that ``counter-revolutionary'' activities are no long illegal.
In other words, many of the demonstrators jailed after the 1989
protest at Tiananmen Square did not commit crimes after all _ but
the revision is not retroactive.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating matters, the Chinese government made it illegal to
``endanger state security.''
</P>
<P>
   Chinese prison cells are filled with other political prisoners.
By the government's count, some 2,200 remain locked up. The Clinton
administration has put special emphasis on several of them because
of the severity of their sentences or the unjust circumstances
surrounding their arrests. They include:
</P>
<P>
   _Liu Nianchun, a labor activist who was arrested in 1995 after
petitioning the National People's Congress to ``rectify'' human
rights abuses. Even though Liu's three-year sentence should have
ended last month, he is being detained in a ``re-education through
labor camp'' outside of Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   _Chen Longde, a human rights worker who was arrested in 1996 for
writing to the People's Congress about corruption and lack of
democracy. After suffering torture by electric shocks and beatings,
Chen jumped from a two-story platform at a labor camp. Barely
mobile because of two broken hips and a damaged kidney, he is still
forced to do labor, according to Human Rights Watch.
</P>
<P>
   _Gau Yu, a journalist who was arrested in 1993 for writing in
Hong Kong publications about disputes among senior Chinese
officials. She was sentenced to six years for revealing ``state
secrets,'' and friends say she is in poor health.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese government thinks that journalism is propaganda,
and so all real journalists are dissidents and criminals,'' said
Wang Juntao, a friend and former colleague of Gau Yu. They were in
the same prison before Wang was exiled in 1994. This summer, he is
living in Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   There are also people like Ngawang Choephel _ hardly a household
name here. Choephel, who who spent the 1992-93 academic year
studying and teaching ethnomusicology at Middlebury College in
Vermont on a Fulbright scholarship, was unfairly imprisoned by
China two years ago, according to US officials.
</P>
<P>
   During a 1995 trip to Tibet, his homeland, he worked on a
documentary about music and dance. Chinese authorities arrested him
and charged him with spying. He was sentenced in 1996 to 18 years
in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Friends in Vermont worry about Choephel (pronounced Chope-pell).
They describe him as an artist who did not dwell on politics. ``The
charges are completely made up, fake, false, and baseless,'' said
Jon Barlow, who took a music workshop with Choephel while at
Middlebury.
</P>
<P>
   Eager to make an example of Tibetian political prisoners, China
rarely, if ever, releases them before their sentences end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since we heard about his arrest, we've been trying in
every conceivable way to try to convince the Chinese they made a
grave mistake,'' said Tim Rieser, an aide to Patrick Leahy of
Vermont, the top-ranking Democrat on the Senate Foreign Operations
Committee. Leahy mentioned the case in a 1996 meeting in Beijing
with top Chinese officials.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups are divided about whether the US government
should concentrate on behind-the-scenes pleas for the release of
dissidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to use quiet diplomacy in the months leading up
to the summit, but the administration has used quiet diplomacy for
years in Choephel's case and it hasn't worked,'' said John Ackerly,
president of the Internatioinal Campaign for Tibet.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese officials have assured foreign diplomats that fewer
political dissidents are being imprisoned than in previous years,
according to US officials. While that might well be true, the
Chinese appear to be sending more dissidents to the
``re-education'' camps. The Clinton administration says 200,000
Chinese are in such places. Aides say Clinton and Albright will
complain to President Jiang Zemin and other officials about the
widespread use of the camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``The really nasty thing about the Chinese system is that as
they pass amendments for criminal procedure law, they rely
increasingly on administrative justice, which doesn't have due
process,'' said an official familiar with China.
</P>
<P>
   The Jiang government maintains that the camps are useful for
turning misfits into productive citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Tong Yi served as a secretary and researcher to Wei Jingshen,
the dissident. While Wei was imprisoned, she was dispatched to a
camp for more than two years. She never had a chance to dispute the
charges against her or to appeal her conviction.
</P>
<P>
   At the camp, Yi says she was beaten for refusing to work more
than eight hours a day. She was forced to do she calls ``useless
busy work'' yanking the threads from old clothes. But she considers
herself lucky. She says that friends worked in grimy factories,
making clothes and batteries for export.
</P>
<P>
   The only re-education occurred when visitors toured the sites
and the guards pretended to teach lessons in Communism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The re-education is really a joke,'' says Yi, 30, who was
released two years ago and went into exile in New York. ``The irony
is that even though it's called re-education, the police used all
the labor to make more profits.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
