<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7139 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-19 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN'S SINKING ECONOMY, AND ITS DRAG ON THE US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Japan's damaged economy suffers from the banking equivalent of a
hole in the boat.
</P>
<P>
   The once mighty financial houses that bankrolled Asia's
decade-long growth spurt have a deep dark secret: bad loans. Debts
that are unlikely to be repaid have rotted out the underpinning.
With the Japanese yen spiralling down against the dollar, the
United States this week was frightened into a dramatic policy
shift.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury began buying yen with dollars _ propping up the
currency of the world's second-largest economy. Uncle Sam's timely
rescue snapped a stock market plunge, triggering a nifty rally on
the world exchanges. We still don't know all that the Clinton
administration extracted from Japan's sclerotic government in terms
of agreements to reform the Japanese economy. But you can only
throw so many dollars into a hole in the boat. The recurring
problem is still Japan's inability to clean up its banking system.
Like the savings and loan collapse that the US endured a decade
back, corruption and overconfidence in a key banking sector can sow
tremendous damage throughout what had been a thriving economy.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's political system is a precariously balanced house of
cards. Decades-long customs of bribery, payoff, winking at
regulations, and overly cozy relationships between bureaucrats on
one hand and businessmen or gangsters on the other have minimized
the cleansing and purgative effects of market forces.
</P>
<P>
   The Hashimoto government is wildly unpopular. Right now there is
insufficient political cohesion. No leader or party can effectively
take charge. The interests that profit off construction projects
have engineered a massive government public works splurge. But that
does nothing for banking reform.
</P>
<P>
   Until Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin convinced President
Clinton to approve the dollar-for-yen emergency bailout, the US
emphasis had been on trying to knuckle Tokyo into initiating a big
tax cut to spur domestic consumption.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Japanese consumer is different from the American
consumer,'' explained a Japanese government official Wednesday. For
reasons of culture, history, and social custom, the Japanese save
more money than do Americans. The United States argued that
increased demand would kick-start the economy, increase job
creation and domestic bank lending, as well as reduce the export to
the US of distress-sale manufactured goods, whose low prices
undercut US products.
</P>
<P>
   But the Japanese don't think US-style tax cuts would cut loose a
lot of wild-and-crazy domestic consumption. ``The Japanese consumer
would take his tax cut money and save it,'' said a Japanese
official. The spending habits of Asians have more influence here
than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   Companies and consumers in Asia were buying a lot of stuff that
Americans manufacture. But the downward spiral caused those
customers to stop buying. That slump in turn has clipped profits of
US firms, and fears of that sort of downward spiral chopped almost
600 points off the Dow Jones from the May 13 highpoint of 9211,
before Wednesday's recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Take the case of 3M Co., one of America's largest manufacturing
firms, amplified in Tuesday's Wall Street Journal. One sixth of
3M's revenue, and nearly one-quarter of its earnings last year came
from Asia. But weakness in Asian sales, aggravated by currency
shifts, forced 3M to warn three times in the last six months that
sales and profits were being hurt by the Asian turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   With the yen sinking, Asian customers had to pay higher and
higher prices for the same product. ``The situation in Asia is
deeper and longer than we had anticipated,'' 3M chairman L.D.
De-Simone told the Journal. ``And we had anticipated a poor
situation.'' 3M estimates its earnings will drop 10 percent as a
result, which may lead to layoffs here among the 75,000 employees.
And the stock got walloped, dropping nearly 7 percent one day this
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we had seen the bottom and that it wasn't going
anywhere lower,'' DeSimone said. ``That is not the case now.'' He
doubts things can turn around before year's end. The Asian turmoil
has already affected some New England companies. Many of the
region's high tech firms will be unable to replace Asian customers
who cancel orders. That means less business for the chip suppliers,
board fabricators, the parcel guy who trucks cartons to the
airport, the baggage handler at Logan. Yet there may be some
upside.
</P>
<P>
   Outfits like Fidelity are expanding their operations in Japan,
thanks to pressure exerted by the Clinton administration. And many
Japanese will presumably decide to shove their money into American
stocks and mutual funds, preferring to ride out the typhoon in the
safer harbor of US investments.
</P>
<P>
   So if you're selling mutual funds in Tokyo, you may find
customers. But if you're selling plywood or computers or swordfish,
you're not selling there what you sold last year. If you're the 3M
guy, or one of his about-to-be-laid-off workers, you're thinking
all this is going to get worse before it gets better.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
