r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCMANUS-EVIDENCE-GOD-     06-19 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCMANUS-EVIDENCE-GOD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEAR-DEATH RESEARCH AND THE EXISTENCE OF GOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Mike McManus is a syndicated columnist whose ``Ethics &AMP;
Religion'' appears in almost 100 newspapers)
</P>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or
fax her at (816) 822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By MIKE McMANUS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   This morning I woke up in a hospital bed. Through the window
next to my bed and I could see tiny wisps of clouds in a delicate
pattern that again reminded me of God's marvelous handiwork. I felt
blessed to be alive.
</P>
<P>
   Three months ago, I was in the same hospital (on the same floor,
with the same gentle nurses) to have an orange-sized tumor removed
from my colon. The surgery went well and in five days I was home.
The cancer had passed through the wall of the colon, but had not
entered my lymph system. Doctors debated about whether I should
take chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   Some said that since I had a 70 percent chance of recovery, I
was taking a needless risk of infection by taking a treatment that
would weaken my resistance to disease, and which at best could push
my survival odds only to 75 percent. Others said I was healthy
enough to take the risk, so I did.
</P>
<P>
   But last week I had to have emergency surgery because my body
had been invaded by a rare bacteria, a disease called necrotizing
fasciitis, that actually eats one's flesh and can be fatal.
Surgeons had to cut out two pockets of dead flesh. The care of
these wounds was very painful at first, but is now tolerable. And
antibiotics seem to have halted the bacteria's spread.
</P>
<P>
   At a time like this one is tempted to feel utterly helpless. My
life is in the hands of others. But I had complete confidence in
the medical team, and in God, who I felt was not yet ready to
``take me home.'' I feel absolutely at peace.
</P>
<P>
   However, Romans 8:28 kept running through my head: ``..in all
things God works for the good of those who love him, who have been
called according to his purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   But what has been God's purpose in these illnesses?
</P>
<P>
   A friend who visited said, ``Sometimes God allows terrible
things like this to happen to get your attention. In 1955 Eli
Wiesel was hit by a taxi. In his long recovery, he also recovered
his faith that was lost at Auschwitz. I think God is calling you to
a new level of holiness. The Lord wants you to develop a closer
walk with Him.''
</P>
<P>
   So I've been reading more Scripture. My son, Adam, asked me to
read Psalm 18:32-33:
</P>
<P>
   ``It is God who arms me with strength and makes my way perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``He makes my feet like the feet of a deer; he enables me to
stand on the heights.''
</P>
<P>
   That has certainly been my experience. But how does one convince
the skeptical of such matters? During these weeks I've been reading
a wonderful book with answers called ``God: The Evidence'' by
Patrick Glynn.
</P>
<P>
   He lost his faith in high school, went to Harvard and emerged a
convinced agnostic, which later hardened into convinced atheism.
``Reason, I thought, was the only path to truth. No God in the
personal sense, no afterlife, no soul, no inherent justice in the
universe. We were on our own.''
</P>
<P>
   But then he read a book called ``Life After Death'' by a
psychiatrist named Ray Moody recounting ``near-death experiences,''
deathbed visions of people who ``died and made a comeback.''
Victims of heart attacks, crashes, etc. described what they called
a realm beyond death. Most said they felt a sudden sense of peace
and detachment, an absence of pain. Some said they felt they were
floating over an operating table, then moved down a tunnel to a
heavenly landscape and encountered a ``Being of Light'' that some
described as Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   Some even felt they underwent a detailed review of their lives,
a replay of every thought and action -- and its consequences for
good or ill on others.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael Sabon, a cardiologist, was critical of Moody's
methodolgy. So he decided to ask his own patients who claimed
``near-death experiences'' detailed questions that would not be
known to laymen. Some said they had observed surgeries on their own
heart and described details they could not possibly have observed
while unconscious on the operating table.
</P>
<P>
   A significant number also described ``hellish'' near-death
experiences that prompted some to change their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Those who felt they encountered Christ were struck by an
overwhelming sense of unconditional love and compassion along with
His firm sense of right and wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Glynn's conclusion: ``Near-death research offered the first
systematic body of evidence suggestive of the existence of a
soul.''
</P>
<P>
   He cites similar persuasive evidence for the existence of God in
physics, astronomy and medicine, which I will examine in next
week's column.
</P>
<P>
   I did not need Patrick Glynn's research to have faith in God.
But others do.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   c. Michael J. McManus
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
