<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7145 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JEWS-SOUTH-BOS &LR;      06-19 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEWS-SOUTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROJECT TRACES THE HISTORY OF JEWS IN DIXIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CURTIS WILKIE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSON, Miss. _ Under a canopy of stately oaks, a Jewish
cemetery occupies a half-acre of land in the little south
Mississippi town of Summit, its century-old headstones representing
the last traces of a vanished society.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish peddlers helped settle Summit in the early 1800s and
established its first stores. ``Louis Alcus and Isaac Scherck,''
wrote a local historian, ``were second to none in contributing to
the building up of the town.'' Nineteen Jewish men went off from
Summit to fight for the Confederate cause in the Civil War and came
home to organize Congregation Ohaveh Shalom (Lovers of Peace) in
1870.
</P>
<P>
   But over the years, their descendants drifted away, moving to
nearby New Orleans. A tornado destroyed the synagogue building in
1924, and today no Jews are left in Summit.
</P>
<P>
   Although Jews have disappeared from dozens of villages in the
Baptist-dominated ``Bible Belt,'' Jewish communities are thriving
in cities such as Atlanta, Charlotte, N.C., Charleston, S.C., and
New Orleans, while Memphis is home to the largest Orthodox
congregation in the country.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to preserve their legacy in the deep South, the
Museum of the Southern Jewish Experience has just opened a
summer-long exhibition in Jackson that follows the 19th century
immigration of thousands of Jews from their homes in the Alsace, a
disputed region that provoked clashes between France and Germany,
to a corridor along the Mississippi River between New Orleans and
Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alsace to America: Discovering a Southern Jewish Heritage''
demonstrates in displays and oral histories how the European Jews
found comfort in the French culture of New Orleans, then spanned
across Dixie in search of opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Because they did not eat pork, a staple of the region, the Jews
were called ``egg-eaters'' and considered curious newcomers. Still,
they put down stakes in the tough frontier country.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, their names, emblazoned on their general stores,
became the names of the towns: Marks, Miss.; Kaplan, La.
Eventually, many became cotton brokers, landowners, leaders of the
mercantile class, and burghers of their communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came to this country with nothing more than their
education,'' says Louise Glickman, director of development for the
museum. ``They learned to adapt to the land and to talk with the
people. They were so determined to become part of the community
that a disproportionate number of Jews fought on the Confederate
side despite their abhorrence of slavery.''
</P>
<P>
   Eli Evans, president of the Charles H. Revson Foundation in New
York, wrote of his Southern roots in ``The Provincials.'' Jews and
Southerners were both ``stepchildren of anguished history,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's this braided identity of being Southern and Jewish,''
Evans says. Despite differences in religion and social views from
the Protestant conservatives, ``Jews were not aliens, but blood and
bones part of Southern history.''
</P>
<P>
   Early Southern Jews were keenly aware that their families were
the only ones in the community not to worship on Sunday, and in
their zeal to become bona fide Americans they grew more secular.
The reform movement, a more liberal strain of Judaism, was founded
in the South and more than 100 reform congregations still exist in
the deep South.
</P>
<P>
   But the same demographics that changed the face of the South in
the years after World War II devastated the commercial
underpinnings of Jewish communities in small towns.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was not killed by the boll weevil was killed by
Wal-Mart,'' says Glickman.
</P>
<P>
   In Clarksdale, a Mississippi Delta city, Temple Beth Israel had
a full-time rabbi and 100 families attending services in the 1960s.
``Today, there are probably 25 members,'' says John Levingston, who
owns a furniture store there. ``During the school year, we contract
for a student rabbi and have services every two weeks. The younger
generation moved away to pursue economic opportunity. Many members
of my family left. They've not been replaced. With our aging,
shifting population, the congregation will probably not exist in a
few years.''
</P>
<P>
   Macy B. Hart, executive director of Museum of the Southern
Jewish Experience, says he started the institution in 1989 to
provide a home for Torah scrolls and other religious artifacts left
behind as synagogues were abandoned. ``There has been a dwindling
Jewish presence,'' he says, as Jews moved to cities or married
non-Jews and were assimilated into Christian Southern society.
</P>
<P>
   According to Mark Greenberg, the museum historian, the Jewish
population in Mississippi has declined from 4,600 in 1937 to 1,400
recorded in the 1996 American Jewish Yearbook. In Arkansas, there
are only 1,700 Jews compared to 6,500 sixty years ago. The numbers
in Tennessee have fallen from 25,000 to 18,000 over the same
period.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Jewish population of Atlanta has expanded
dramatically. From the time Sam Massell, a prominent Jewish
businessman was elected mayor in 1969, the number of Jews in the
city has tripled, from 24,000 to 77,000.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the number of Jews in the South has increased from
200,000 in 1937 to 1 million today, but Florida has accounted for
most of that increase. The state's Jewish population is estimated
at 650,000 _ up from 21,000 in 1937 _ and most are concentrated on
the east coast of Florida, an areawhich is as distinct from
Southern culture as the Lower East Side of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The Jackson show focuses on the Mississippi River states of
Mississippi, Louisiana, Arkansas, and Tennessee. ``The story of
Southern Jews is the story of rural America,'' Hart says. ``We have
a rich legacy, like all small-town folks, and it's important to
protect our history.''
</P>
<P>
   The current exhibition, which celebrates Jewish life in small
Southern towns, was timed to coincide with the ``Splendors of
Versailles,'' another summer attraction in downtown Jackson that is
drawing thousands of visitors. Many of the tourists are crossing
the street to attend ``Alsace to America,'' too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The exhibition is about memory,'' says Glickman. ``We want to
show that we're more alike than different.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 1349EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
