u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-19 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE INNOVATIONS, FEWER VIEWERS FOLLOWED THE PUCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ESPN and Fox took substantial hits in their NHL playoff
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN aired 32 games and averaged a rating of 1.2, down 29
percent from last year's 1.7. Its Stanley Cup finals coverage
suffered a bigger hit. The cable outlet's three games earned a 2.6
rating, down 37 percent from last year's finals.
</P>
<P>
   Fox did a little better. Its coverage of Game 1 between the
Washington Capitals and Detroit Red Wings earned a 3.3, down 17
percent from last year's opener.
</P>
<P>
   The disappointing numbers overshadow considerable effort to
improve hockey's image on television.Both Fox and ESPN have
attempted to bring the game closer to viewers.
</P>
<P>
   The much-discussed FoxTrax is a case in point. Designed to give
viewers a better way to keep track of the puck, FoxTrax has been
derided by hockey connoisseurs and applauded by new fans. NHL
commissioner Gary Bettman told reporters recently that he wasn't a
fan, but if the blue streak that followed the path of the puck
helped attract viewers, so be it.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN producer Larry Kristiansen applauds Fox's attempts and
points out that his network also has employed several new toys.
Instead of using only two cameras to cover the action, ESPN uses
all sorts of robotics and goalcams, allowing viewers to watch the
proceedings as if they were goalies. The goalcam also allows
viewers to watch power plays unfold.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN also added a camera to give viewers a feel for the speed of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Kristiansen says the process is still evolving and he for one
would like to see cameras installed along tracks to enable viewers
to get a better sense of the speed as well as the action.
</P>
<P>
   That innovation will be some time in coming _ as, apparently,
will higher television ratings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Record numbers
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Game 6 of the NBA Finals earned a 22.3 rating and 38 share,
making it the highest-rated game in NBA history, according to
Nielsen Media Research. That number overtakes 1988's Game 7 between
the Pistons and Lakers, which drew a 21.2 rating and 37 share on
CBS. NBC estimates that 72 million viewers watched all or part of
the Bulls' win over the Jazz Sunday. NBC averaged a national rating
of 18.7 throughout the series, also a record ... Longtime network
executive Ken Schanzer was appointed president of NBC Sports
Thursday, succeeding Dick Ebersol, who becomes chairman of the
sports division and new Olympics division ... ABC pulled a 4.7
rating for its World Cup soccer broadcast of Germany's 2-0 win over
the United States Monday. That number is significantly lower than
those earned during the first round of the 1994 World Cup when
US-Romania achieved a 7.8 rating and US-Switzerland pulled a 5.9
... Pity Warner Wolf. Last week the 38-year veteran of television
sports had his worst day ever. During a broadcast on New York's
WCBS, his new dentures popped out. His sportscast started well
enough. But when he went to his trademark, ``Let's go to the
videotape,'' he began to mumble. The embarrassment ended when he
wrestled the plate into place. Of course, the New York Post was
watching. Its headline: ``Let's go to the Poli-grip.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
White a movie mogul?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of all people to own a movie production company, it's Reggie
White. The last time we heard from the minister, he was making a
complete fool of himself in front of the Wisconsin State Assembly.
To this day, he stands by his gibberish on race and ethnicity. But
the Lord moves in strange ways. He blessed this fool with a deal
that will allow him to build Reggie White Studios in Denver. White
and his partners, Colorado Rockies vice chairman Richard Monfort
and Denver businessman Rodney Linafelter, are trying to raise $100
million to produce major motion pictures, made-for-television
movies, and original cable television programming ... ESPN's
Classic Sports airs nonstop Wimbledon moments Sunday from 2-10
p.m., starting with Arthur Ashe's historic 1975 victory over Jimmy
Connors ... CNN/SI's Nick Charles teams with veteran analyst Gil
Clancy for TBS's quarterfinal coverage of the Goodwill Games boxing
tournament. The telecasts from New York's Madison Square Garden are
July 27-28 at 8:05 p.m. ... Red Auerbach appears on CNN/SI Saturday
at 11 a.m. with Charles to discuss NBA dynasties.
</P>
</TEXT>
