<SLUG> BC-CYCLE-RACES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAER A CLASSIC FIGURE BEHIND LOUDON CLASSIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; LOUDON, N.H. _ Before it became known as the Loudon Classic
and before it was held at New Hampshire International Speedway,
where the 75th anniversary of America's oldest motorcycle race will
be staged this weekend, motorcycle enthusiasts from all over New
England and points beyond knew it, quite simply, as the ``Laconia
Races.''
</P>
<P>
   But to those who knew him, it might as well have been called
``Fritzie's Races,'' because the late Fritzie Baer was generally
regarded as the man responsible for fathering the first American
Motorcycle Association event in New England.
</P>
<P>
   NHIS owners Bob and Sandy Bahre and their son Gary, the
speedway's president, may very well be the closest thing to the
First Family of auto racing in New England. And the Baers _
Fritzie; his wife, Louise; and their five children _ rank as New
England's First Family of motorcycling.
</P>
<P>
   A factory dealer for the Indian Motorcycle Co. in Springfield,
Mass., Baer organized a motorcycle club in 1933 called ``Fritzie's
Roamers'' that was recognized a year later by the AMA as the most
active and successful in the nation. Through his contacts with the
AMA and as president of the New England Motorcycle Dealers
Association, Baer helped bring motorcycle racing to the Laconia
Region at Belknap Recreation Area, now Gunstock Ski Resort.
</P>
<P>
   After resigning from the Indian Motorcycle Co. in 1950, Baer
signed on as managing director of the Belknap Recreation Area,
where he staged his motorcycle events and became affectionately
known as ``The Man in the Red Hat.''
</P>
<P>
   It was easy to spot Baer at the Belknap races. He was a large,
gregarious sort who loved to smoke cigars. And he always wore a red
hat, hence the nickname.
</P>
<P>
   When a new race venue had to be found in the early '60s, Baer
was instrumental in persuading Keith Bryar to build a facility that
could stage the Loudon Classic. In so many words, Baer persuaded
Bryar that if he built a new track _ Bryar Motorsports Park _ the
motorcyclists would come. And they did _ in droves.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad, in addition to being a motorcycle dealer, was also a
promoter and he did the announcing for all the races, so he was
very active in motorcycles,'' said Butch Baer, 71, the third of
Baer's four sons, who lives in Monson. ``His whole life revolved
around motorcycles, really. It didn't matter, really, whether it
was Indian or Harley or whatever, he was very strong at promoting
whatever he could to help the motorcycle industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Motorcycles _ particularly those made by the Indian Motorcycle
Co. _ were intertwined with the Baer family history.
</P>
<P>
   Three years after starting work at the Indian factory, Baer, a
native of Clinton, Mass., earned enough money to buy a new 1923
Indian Chief with a Princess sidecar. One day, while tooling
Worcester with a friend, the 21-year-old Baer spied two pretty
women standing at a street corner. One was a 16-year-old who became
his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``They courted for about a year when they decided they were
going to get married,'' said Butch. ``She put on her riding clothes
and they got on the cycle sidecar and they headed for Albany, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``They stopped at a gas station that was across the street from
the Town Hall in Albany, and she got out and changed clothes in the
gas station. Then they went into the Town Hall and got married.
They went back to the gas station, changed back into their riding
clothes, and went off on their honeymoon.''
</P>
<P>
   The newlyweds hit the open highway on a blissful motorcycle tour
that took them through the Finger Lakes region of upstate New York.
``In five years' time, my mother had four children,'' Butch said.
``Each time, she was brought to the hospital in the sidecar and the
baby was brought home in the sidecar. That's why we're motorcycle
people.''
</P>
<P>
   When Baer died in 1984 at age 83, his ashes were spread at
Gunstock. ``We did it somewhat surreptitiously,'' said Tom Baer,
73, of Goffstown, N.H., the second oldest of Baer's four surviving
offspring. ``But his ashes are spread on the Red Hat ski trail,
which was named after him.''
</P>
<P>
   When the race gained a bad reputation for the unseemly behavior
that took place once it became a gathering spot for hell-on-wheels
riders who came to Laconia every June to trample upon it, ``it
really saddened my dad,'' Butch said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was `Animal Land' up behind Bryar's track. It was
unbelievable. `Animal Land,' that's what they called it. People
just went up there to get spaced out, drunk, start bonfires,
destroy some automobiles _ oh God, it was horrible. I was ashamed
to be a motorcyclist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a barrel of apples; it only takes a couple of bad
ones ...'' Butch added. ``But that's all gone now. It's become much
more family-oriented. You see more people going up for a vacation
and to have fun. The race is only a small part of the whole
event.''
</P>
<P>
   Could Fritzie Baer ever have imagined that it would last this
long? That what began as the Laconia Races would become the
nation's oldest motorcycle event?
</P>
<P>
   ``Dad? Oh sure, Dad would,'' Butch said. ``As far as Dad was
concerned, it was going to last hundreds of years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 1351EDT &QL; 
