<SLUG> BC-RAC-SWEEPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ROCK IS OK BY OK BY ME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALEM, N.H. _ When Ok By Me captured the New Hampshire
Sweepstakes Handicap at Rockingham Park last year, he had ``future
star'' written all over him. Ok By Me stormed past a good horse
named Influent, the 6-5 favorite, to win with authority, and it
seemed likely he would go on to upstate New York and become the
scourge of Saratoga.
</P>
<P>
   But something happened at The Spa. First Ok By Me finished fifth
at 9-5 in the Fourstardave Stakes. Then he finished sixth in the
Bernard Baruch Handicap at 2-1. It turned out that ``something''
was an injured ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he was up at Saratoga, he had a little chip removed from
his left front ankle,'' said trainer H. James Bond, who laid up Ok
By Me from August until March. ``But he's doing pretty good now.
He's run against some pretty tough horses. Hopefully, he'll show
what he's made of at Rockingham.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Ok By Me, a 5-year-old chestnut son of Canadian champion
With Approval, will be back at Rock Saturday to defend his
championship in the $200,000 Sweeps, run at 1 1/8 miles over the
turf. Without a win since, he has an excellent chance to get back
on track over a surface he relishes. ``He just seems to really like
the New Hampshire course,'' said Bond. ``We've been pointing for
this race.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if Ok By Me has run poorly since having the chip
removed. In his three starts this year, he has a second and two
thirds against top company. He gained the place in the Bouginvilea
Handicap at Hialeah March 29 in his return, then earned the show in
both the Royal Palm Handicap at Hialeah May 3 and the Connaught Cup
at Woodbine May 30. All three of his post-surgery starts have come
in Grade III events, like the Sweeps.
</P>
<P>
   ``His best race this year was his first one back at Hialeah,''
said Bond. ``He made a strong move and just got beat (by a
half-length). I admit his second Hialeah start, when he lost the
lead, wasn't as good. But by then, maybe he didn't want to run in
the heat. His race in Canada was pretty good. He went up there a
little sluggish, but I think he could have won it with a little bit
better racing luck.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Bravo, who was aboard Ok By Me when he took the Sweeps last
year, will be back up Saturday after Frank Lovato rode him at
Woodbine. The Rock turf course was firm for the Sweeps in 1997, but
its condition for Saturday is uncertain and it could be soft. The
Rock meeting opened June 7, but there have been only four races run
over the turf course so far during a meet which has seen three
cards canceled because of torrential rains. Two races were taken
off the turf Thursday and none were carded for the early portion of
last night's program, so no one knows what the turf course will be
like Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   However, Bond is unconcerned about the footing. ``He's got a big
old flat foot on him,'' the trainer said. ``There'll be no problem
with the course. He seems to run on anything. If it's soft or
whatever, he'll get used to it. He likes to run at a horse, and
there looks like there's some speed in the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a lot of racehorse in him. We can't hold him in the
barn right now. When he's right, he usually fires a big shot. We'll
see what happens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
