<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A POPULARITY, AND EGO, FIT FOR THE WORLD STAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The BBC has produced and aired an astonishing hourlong
documentary about Boston Philharmonic Orchestra conductor Benjamin
Zander. Called ``Living on One Buttock,'' an allusion to
Zander's &UR;  &LR; habit of half rising from the bench in his emphatic piano
playing, the show revels in the many activities Zander pursues
outside our ken. When not blasting Mahler symphonies out the BPO's
Cambridge office window, Zander keeps up a busy international
concert schedule, is a peripatetic teacher of gifted musical
students, and has carved out a lucrative and unusual sideline as a
motivational speaker.
</P>
<P>
   The documentary, recently sold to the Bravo channel, is a
veritable goulash of Zander testimonials. Sources as diverse as
Mahler's granddaughter and Zander's neighbor Alan Dershowitz praise
his abilities. And a US Army colonel from the Fort Leavenworth war
college extols Zander's speech before several hundred officers,
whom the conductor persuaded to sing ``Ode to Joy,''
enthusiastically if not harmoniously. Zander is also shown revving
up execs from Textron and British Telecom. (My favorite moment in
the show is Zander explaining to his Youth Philharmonic charges the
proper response to corrective criticism from an elder: ``How
fascinating.'')
</P>
<P>
   Zander's motivational lectures _ he calls them
``transformational'' talks _ will soon be gathered in a book,
``Pathways to Possibility,'' co-authored with his partner and
former wife, the psychotherapist Rosamund Zander. The two are
separated, but remain pals and collaborators. ``We're like England
and France, living on Appleton and Brattle streets,'' he explains.
``We're close, but we're separated by a channel.''
</P>
<P>
   Zander is indeed big box office in England; so why isn't he a
bigger deal in the land of Seiji and Keith? The musicians I spoke
with praised his inspirational abilities and his musicianship, but
faulted his considerable ego. The knock: Does not play well with
others. ``People either love him or they hate him,'' one fellow
explained. ``There's no middle ground. He has a lot to offer
musically, and it's a shame he hasn't done more around here.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
How fascinating
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The silly cryonicists, who loathe me for poking fun at them in a
recent column (``Immortality and the Chosen, Frozen Few,'' June 3),
have been dying for me to correct two factual errors in that piece.
The male-female ratio of withered, defrosted corpses in AD 2100
will not be 25 to 1, as I wrote, but closer to 22 to 4. Also,
Berkeley academic Robin Hanson thinks he has a 5 percent chance of
being revived after the deep freeze, not a 0.5 percent chance, as I
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Does not compute
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the Boston Computer Society folded in September 1996, the
staff closed up shop in six weeks. After they finished selling off
furniture and the like, they summed up the BCS's financial position
for the board of directors: The society had about $10,000 in debts,
$10,000 in receivables, and a cash surplus of $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   The $50K was entrusted to BCS lawyer and board member Harris
Luscomb, with the understanding that it would find its way to the
Computer Museum. That's the law; when a nonprofit goes under and
has assets left, they must be donated to another nonprofit. The
Computer Museum has earmarked the money to upgrade its best
Software for Kids exhibit, but, explains director emeritus Oliver
Strimpel, ``we haven't received the money yet.''
</P>
<P>
   What's taking so long? Luscomb is famous for not returning phone
calls, and he didn't return mine. Real estate magnate Arthur
Nelson, the last chairman of the BCS, says, ``The money is in the
bank, and it cannot be released until the attorney general approves
the final audit.'' Neither the audit nor the dissolution papers
have been submitted to the AG, explains Office of Charities
attorney Deirdre Rosenberg. Some members of the BCS suspect
skulduggery, although there is no evidence of such yet. Rosenberg
says these dissolutions can take 10 years or more. Nonetheless, she
adds: ``There are a lot of unhappy people out there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
