<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7154 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-HIGH-ART-BOS &LR;      06-19 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-HIGH-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHEEDY SHINES IN HIGHLY ORIGINAL `HIGH ART' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
HIGH ART 
Directed and written by: Lisa Cholodenko 
Starring: Ally Sheedy, Radha Mitchell, Patricia Clarkson, Bill
Sage 
Running time: 102 minutes 
Rated: R (strong sexuality, pervasive drug use, language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lisa Cholodenko's ``High Art'' is an impressively original take
on a far from unexamined scene _ young careerists interacting with
derailed druggies in SoHo. It's raised from semi-documentary
funkiness to something haunting, thanks mostly to what goes on in
the eyes of Ally Sheedy, making the career re-entry of the year as
a sensitive and complictaed photographer caught between the
competing needs of her former and current lovers. The film pivots
on Sheedy's astonishing Lucy Berliner, a talented photographer
fleeing the wear and tear and exploitation that go with fame by
plunging into drugs with a coterie she has gathered in a
fashionably seedy salon financed by a trust fund.
</P>
<P>
   When a downstairs neighbor, Radhi Mitchell's Syd, knocks on her
door to complain about a leak, Lucy finds herself invigorated _ or
as invigorated as her fragile, disillusioned nature can allow her
to be _ by the young ambitious assistant editor, who wants to
launch her own career by reviving Lucy's after the latter's 10-year
layoff. Never so zoned out that she can't quickly calculate the
quid pro quo in an emotional transaction, Lucy decides to let Syd
use her because she's attracted to Syd. It's more of a risk to
Lucy. There are reasons for Lucy's withdrawal, one being her
world-weary girlfriend, Greta, an ex-Fassbinder trouper played with
a sub-Dietrich growl in enervated but sympathetic fashion by
Patricia Clarkson.
</P>
<P>
   Syd, meanwhile, drops her boyfriend and begins a subtle mating
dance with Lucy, whose ability to get to us rests largely on her
open-eyed view of exactly what's going down as the two women decide
how much of themselves to expose and parcel out to one another. Not
that it's all a series of power transactions. By never having the
characters say too much, and entiocing us to read a wide range of
feelings from their faces, Cholodenko convinces us as well of the
physical urgency of their relationship, just as Sheedy convinces us
that part of Lucy's calculation involves figuring out just how
close to dance to the flame of a physical attraction.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Lucy's flight from expectations, Cholodenko makes clear
in a brilliant scene, involves her Holocaust-survivor mother,
played with real iron by Tammy Grimes, who maintains a lifelong
drop on Lucy by praising her as gifted, then deprecating her as
passive. Whatever else is going on in Lucy's eyes, however, Sheedy
convinces us she's a character who knows her own worth, even if she
has difficulty mustering the will to achieve. The physicality and
storminess of the emotions boiling up from beneath the
sensation-muffling drug haze are startlingly yet seductively
urgent.
</P>
<P>
   Without ever makng it apparent, Cholodenko and Sheedy yank what
could have been downtown cliche into something fresh and raw and
slightly subversive, which tells us we're in the presence of
something vital and unafraid of embracing contradictions. Mitchell
impressively reminds us as well that there needn't necessarily be
any incompatibility between wholesomeness and ruthlessness. In all,
``High Art'' is an invigorating look at the cost of emotional
demands _ and the cost of feeding one's appetites. I can't believe
there'll be a handful of performances all year that will approach
Sheedy's. She's unforgettable as a woman not thick-skinned enough
for her environment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
