 (jt)  
 For Saturday AMs 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Saturday, June 20:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-COCA HERBICIDE (Bogota) _ The Colombian government,
bowing to demands from anti-narcotics officials in Washington, has
agreed to test a granular herbicide on coca crops, despite warnings
from the chemical's American manufacturer against its use in
Colombia. By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   SWISS-GOLD-HOLOCAUST (Washington) _ The three largest commercial
banks in Switzerland say they will offer a maximum of $600 million
to settle claims by Holocaust victims. Jewish groups are irate,
saying the banks hold billions of dollars in dormant wartime
accounts. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-U.S. (Washington) _ Prime Minister Lionel Jospin of
France comes to Washington to preach better ties with America and
talks about Kosovo, Iran and European unity. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KASHMIR-WEDDING-DEAD (New Delhi) _ Separatist guerrillas kill 25
members of a Hindu wedding party in Kashmir. By John F. Burns.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-DISSIDENTS (Beijing) _ Chinese dissidents appeal to
Clinton to push for greater freedoms during his visit to China next
week. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-AUSTRIA (Salzburg, Austria) _ Pope John Paul VI, on a visit
to Austria, appeals to Austrians not to allow the sex scandal
involving the former archbishop to Vienna to turn them away from
the church. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ Developments in Kenneth Starr's
investigation of President Clinton. By Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   MANZANAR-NATIONAL-SITE (Los Angeles) _ After years of halting
steps, the National Park Service is developing as a national
historic site the abandoned remains of Manzanar, a Japanese
internment camp that housed 10,000 Japanese-Americans, most of them
United States citizens, who were taken there in the mass hysteria
that followed Pearl Harbor. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI-CORRUPT (Miami) _ Bribery. Kickbacks. Voter fraud.
Cover-up. Even as law enforcement officials promise more arrests,
the city of Miami is now engulfed in a series of high-profile
investigations that have uncovered a wave of public corruption. By
Mireya Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   PRESBY-GUNS (Undated) _ The Presbyterians pass a resolution
calling on members to work toward getting handguns and assault
weapons out of their homes. While Presbyterians have supported gun
control legislation in the past, this resolution is the first that
asks members to get rid of guns that aren't used for hunting. By
Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   SMITH-GLOBE-PROFILE (Undated) _ A profile of Patricia Smith, the
Boston Globe columnist who admitted fabrications. Who is she and
how is Boston reacting? By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   IMMIG-DEPORT (Undated) - Advocates for refugees and immigration
lawyers charge federal immigration laws are unevenly applied
throughout the country. Important decisions, they say, like whether
to parole asylum seekers or detain them for months, seem to hinge
on mundane, unrelated circumstances like the number of beds
available in a detention center, not on the dictates of a cohesive
national policy. By Mirta Ojita.
</P>
<P>
   NY-DEAF-MEXICANS (Undated) _ The last of the 18 defendants who
pleaded guilty to smuggling and enslaving deaf Mexicans in New York
will be sentenced Friday in Brooklyn federal court. But the status
of the deaf Mexicans who were witnesses for the prosecution is
still in limbo. By Mirta Ojito.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (Coded f)
</P>
<P>
   WORLDCOM-MCI (Frankfurt) _ European regulators consider
Worldcom's plan to acquire MCI. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   KOCH-TRIAL-VERDICT (Topeka, Kan.) _ A verdict is due Friday in
the trial that pitted the Koch brothers, four of the wealthiest men
in America, against one another. One side is being called greedy,
and the other is accused of cheating. And as much as $2 billion
hangs in the balance. By Leslie Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   ASTRA-MERCK (Undated) _ Astra will buy Merck's half of their
sales venture in the United States in a transaction with a value of
at least $4.4 billion. By David J. Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ECON (Tokyo) _ Speculation grows that Long-Term Credit
Bank of Japan and Nippon Credit Bank will merge. By Sheryl WuDunn .
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Today is a triple-witching day. The Dow
Jones Industrial Average was down 64 points at midday. By David
Barboza.
</P>
