<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-INSOMNIAC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREDICTABILITY LEAVES SWEET `DREAM' EMPTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
DREAM FOR AN INSOMNIAC 
Written and directed by: Tiffanie DeBartolo 
Starring: Ione Skye, Jennifer Aniston, MacKEnzie Astin, Michael
Landes, Seymour Cassel 
Running time: 88 minutes 
Rated: R (language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Dream for an Insomniac'' is a slight, sweet, promising debut
film in which acting outdistances structure. As an ensemble piece
it's disarming, with charm and freshness carrying it past an almost
sitcom predictability as it canters through its boy-meets-girl
stuff. You keep wishing newcomer Tiffanie DeBartolo would venture
more frequently outside the coffee shop where much of the action
takes place. This would increase the film's fluidity and San
Francisco charm and make it seem less like a film of a one-set
play.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps DeBartolo's best move was to sign MacKenzie Astin, Ione
Skye, and Jennifer Aniston as the leads. Astin, whose career seems
to be growing in soft leaps and bounds, in direct proportion to his
range, keeps things light as a blocked writer who wanders into the
coffee shop owned by Frankie's (Skye's) uncle. He arrives just in
time, it seems, to fill the romantic gap in her life, or at least
read her to the sleep she never gets enough of as an insomniac,
which she has been since her parents died years ago in a car crash.
</P>
<P>
   The exchanges between them are marked by tenderness, and played
against the tart repartee allotted to Aniston's sidekick, waiting
for Frankie to get it together so both can go to LA to pursue
acting careers. There's a subplot of sorts involving Frankie's gay
cousin, Rob, who convinces us he really hates the idea of hurting
his Sinatra-worshipping father's feelings by declaring his sexual
preference, especially in view of the old man's increasingly
heavy-handed hints about how much he'd like to see some
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   The film spins its wheels with an altogether unconvincing faked
romance, between Rob and Aniston's resolutely heterosexual Allison,
designed to throw the old man off the track. While it can't be said
that the main love story is exactly surprising or urgent, it at
least convinces you that Skye's character, and Astin's, have their
thoughtful sides. Personality is what carries ``Dream for an
Insomniac,'' not content. DeBartolo seems more at ease in
moment-to-moment work with actors than developing or sustaining a
tonal overview, but the perhaps inevitable awkwardness of her airy
first feature is offset by the bright, sunny energies that come off
the screen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
