<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GABELLI AT ODDS WITH INVESTING'S MICHELANGELO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Famed money manager Mario Gabelli calls Boston's Richard A.
Smith a Michelangelo among investors.
</P>
<P>
   Gabelli says he has been investing in Smith's companies for 30
years and has made ``a ton of money'' along the way. Gabelli
currently has stakes in all three companies Smith heads: publisher
Harcourt General Inc.; Neiman Marcus Group, the fancy retailer; and
GC Cos., a movie-theater operator.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, at the age of 73, Dick Smith remains ``the
intellectual giant'' behind the companies, says Gabelli.
</P>
<P>
   But the two extraordinarily successful investors part company on
Smith's decision to plow nearly $100 million in cash from the
theater unit into a series of venture capital investments that have
ranged from a drive-through coffee chain to a Russian telephone
service provider.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that is a mistake, and I am dead-set against it,''
says Gabelli, whose 13 percent stake in CG Cos. makes him the
second-largest holder behind the Smith family, which owns 29
percent of the company.
</P>
<P>
   If Smith wants to play venture capitalist, Gabelli says, he
should do it privately. ``Venture capital should not be
accomplished using a public vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than pouring money into start-ups, Gabelli would like to
see the company follow through on its pledge, announced in December
1996, to buy back up to 1 million shares of GC stock. A new company
filing this week showed GC had repurchased only about 119,000
shares at a cost of $4.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, though extemely private, is something of an icon in the
world of investing. He built a fortune -- estimated by Forbes
magazine last year at $515 million -- by skillfully shuffling from
beverage bottling to movie theaters, and then into high-end
retailing and publishing. He is among the most respected executives
in the Boston business community, serving on the boards of Liberty
Mutual, Harvard Management Co., a host of charities, and, until
recently, BankBoston Corp.
</P>
<P>
   With his record, criticism of Smith is rare. And Gabelli tempers
his own remarks, saying there is only ``a degree of difference''
with Smith. ``The stock (of GC) is incredibly cheap,'' Gabelli
says.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, as always, won't comment. ``Mr. Smith does not talk to
reporters,'' his assistant told us Thursday. In the company's
second-quarter report last month, Smith said ``we are very pleased
with the results of our investment group activity,'' citing the
initial public offering of one of the company's holding.
</P>
<P>
   That IPO marked the biggest score since Smith started using GC's
General Cinema theaters as a cash cow to fund the venture
operation. Global TeleSystems Group Inc., whose biggest owner is
hedge fund manager George Soros and his affiliates, turned out to
be a hot deal, and GC's $25.2 million investment is now worth about
$75 million. The company is selling telephone service in Russia and
Europe; its stock has risen to 42 1/8 from its opening price of 20
in February.
</P>
<P>
   GC's venture picks seem to be improving after some early
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   The first of those was a investment, along with others, in a
chain of drive-through coffee stands being rolled out by George
Naddaff, the man who helped make Boston Chicken a national chain.
General Cinema has since written off its entire $2.9 million
investment. Another goof was a $5 million investment in a chain of
children's clothing stores in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, GC has had gains on the sales of a chain of radio
stations and of an eyeglass retailer. Last year, GC made its
biggest bet yet, investing $30 million in American Capital Access
Holdings, a New York company that insures debt that is either not
rated or of borderline investment-grade quality.
</P>
<P>
   GC's chief financial officer, Gail Edwards, would not comment on
the overall rate of return in the venture business. That business
is run by Smith along with John G. Berlyson, his son-in-law who
once worked at Advent International, the big Boston venture firm.
Smith's son, Robert, is president and chief operating officer of
GC, which runs both the theaters and the venture unit.
</P>
<P>
   While Harcourt General and Neiman Marcus are doing well, the
theater business is struggling. Earnings have fallen for four
quarters in a row compared with the same periods a year earlier.
Last quarter the company lost $4.1 million compared with a profit
of $1.6 million the previous year. Revenue fell to $89 million from
$108 million.
</P>
<P>
   The company blames the results on the dearth of strong movies
and stiff competition in some of its markets. Analysts say General
Cinema has not been putting enough money back into the theaters to
keep up with the competition. Only one analyst currently rates the
stock a buy; three rate it a ``hold,'' the equivalent of sell in
Wall Street jargon.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the stock closed a 48, down 3/4, on volume that was
more than 25 times the average trading. There was no news to
explain the heavy trading.
</P>
<P>
   Gabelli would like to see GC sell its 1,150 domestic screens,
considering the fat premiums consolidators are now paying, and look
for another business. He likes Smith's push into the theater
business abroad. As for the venture investments, he says: ``It's
coffee here, children's clothes there. There's no rhyme or reason
to it.'
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
