<HEADLINE>
EVEN CHECKER GETS BAD REFERENCES 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
1998c. Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Running your own business can be rough, but it's doubly hard
when your clients are a group of unhappy people.
</P>
<P>
   Documented Reference Check is in the business of checking
references. If you're having trouble finding a new job, for
example, and you worry your old boss may be saying something nasty
about you, interviewers from the Diamond Bar, Calif., company will
call your old boss, mumble something about checking your references
and ask what kind of employee you were.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewers, as might be expected, stumble onto incredible
tales. One manager said the former employee was great but he was
just getting too old. Another employer claimed his former employee
had stolen merchandise and was a drug addict.
</P>
<P>
   A number of clients, such as the former employee who learned his
age was the reason for the termination, are able to use the
information as proof of discrimination and file lawsuits against
their former employers. Other clients threaten their former
employers with a character defamation lawsuit if they continue to
spread untrue stories to potential employers.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, I wrote a column about how brilliant the service
was after checking with former clients. Since then, several readers
have complained about Documented Reference Check's service.
</P>
<P>
   One engineer read that column two years ago and thought
Documented Reference Check might be able to tell him why he was
having such a hard time finding a job. The engineer, who asked not
to be identified, said an employee at a personnel firm said she
couldn't recommend him for a job opening because of what a previous
boss had said.
</P>
<P>
   The engineer paid Documented Reference Check $616.65 in October
to check seven references going back several years. The engineer
said he waited three months and then began calling and writing
letters. He said he never received a reference report or a refund.
</P>
<P>
   Report came too late
</P>
<P>
   Another client in Hempstead paid $157.90 to have her references
checked and was upset because the process took so long that she no
longer needed the information. She had initiated legal action
against her former employer and needed the reference report fairly
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Phone calls took a week or more to return, she said, asking not
to be identified. Finally, she said, she was told by a
representative that the report already had been mailed, but she
never received it. Several months later, the former regional sales
director for a medical care provider said, a report arrived but she
returned it unopened, hoping for a refund she never got.
</P>
<P>
   The Better Business Bureau in Colton, Calif., rates the company
as ``having an unsatisfactory business performance record'' and has
received 51 consumer complaints since 1995. The company responded
to 37, 11 are unresolved and three weren't answered.
</P>
<P>
   According to the bureau, customer complaints allege failure to
provide reports, inability to contact customer service
representatives regarding delays and dissatisfaction with
incomplete reports.
</P>
<P>
   Company defends record
</P>
<P>
   Michael Rankin, chief service officer of Documented Reference
Check, said he isn't surprised by those complaints and argues that
51 complaints in seven years in business isn't a bad record.
</P>
<P>
   Clients who use his company's services typically are upset to
begin with and they're often looking to Documented Reference Check
to provide some bad references so they can initiate a lawsuit or
support one ongoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't make up the references,'' he said, adding that the
interviewers just report what they are told by former employers. He
suspects that clients open up the report, don't like what they see
and then claim they never got it.
</P>
<P>
   Some reports are positive _ they'd hire the former employee back
in a second. Sometimes clients provide the wrong phone number or
name so the reference report comes up empty.
</P>
<P>
   The company does about 1,300 reference checks a month and at
least one report comes back undeliverable, he said. Rankin said he
assumes others get lost and is happy to fax a copy.
</P>
<P>
   He said the company's initial order line clearly states no
messages are retrieved and instructs clients to call the customer
service department for individual help. Some people don't pay
attention and every day several people still leave a message, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He provided a copy of the engineer's seven references, which
show that they were performed in early November. And like other
reports that Documented Reference Check has done, they clearly
spell out what the former bosses thought of the engineer.
</P>
<P>
   Send comments by e-mail to lm.sixelchron.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
