<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MCLACHLAN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCLACHLAN HOPES LILITH FAIR'S SECOND YEAR WILL RAISE EVEN MORE FOR
CHARITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GENE STOUT  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sarah McLachlan is the kind of person who usually trusts her
instincts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it feels right, I just do it,'' she says. ``And then I let
the chips fall where they may.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, McLachlan launched an all-woman summer concert tour
dubbed Lilith Fair. Despite a summer overcrowded with packaged
tours, Lilith Fair was a critical and commercial success.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started off as such a simple idea,'' the singer-songwriter
said by phone from her home in Vancouver, B.C. ``I thought,
wouldn't it be fun to get a bunch of women together and play a
bunch of shows? And from there, it just blossomed.''
</P>
<P>
   McLachlan, who is bright, thoughtful and quick to make fun of
herself, wasn't out to prove anything. But the success of Lilith
Fair erased any doubts about the commercial viability of a
large-scale all-women tour. Lilith Fair grossed nearly $17 million
in a summer when other packaged tours were hurting for ticket
buyers.
</P>
<P>
   McLachlan celebrated by giving away tons of money to some of her
favorite charities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an amazing feeling that comes from giving a local
women's shelter $25,000 and having them tell you that this is going
to help keep their shelter open for six months,'' McLachlan said.
</P>
<P>
   Success has given McLachlan the clout to launch a bigger 50-date
tour this year. The trek, featuring a rotating lineup, includes two
concerts this weekend at The Gorge Amphitheatre in Goerge, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's show features headliners McLachlan, Natalie Merchant,
Indigo Girls, Erykah Badu and Me'Shell N'degeocello. Sunday's
concert is the same, except that Sinead O'Connor substitutes for
N'degeocello.
</P>
<P>
   The Second Stage lineup includes K's Choice, Billie Myers and
Lhasa both days. At the Village Stage, it's Tara MacLean, Sinead
Lohan and Felicia Loud tomorrow, and MacLean, Lohan and J.R.
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Other dates will feature such artists as Missy Elliott, Paula
Cole, Shawn Colvin, Bonnie Raitt, Liz Phair, Lisa Loeb, Martina
McBride, Mary Lou Lord, Joan Osborne, Queen Latifah, Angelique
Kidjo, Victoria Williams, Neko Case and Luscious Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a challenge putting together this lineup because
everyone has very busy summer schedules,'' McLachlan said. ``But
you put the word out there and you phone everyone up, and then you
try to juggle their schedules.''
</P>
<P>
   Hip-hop star Missy Elliott is representative of this year's
diverse lineup. McLachlan saw Elliott perform last year in Miami.
``She just blew the roof off the place,'' McLachlan said. ``I'd
never felt such energy in a live show.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I invited her to join this year's Lilith tour, she was
totally into it. She said she didn't want to confine herself to the
hip-hop world. She wanted to be universal, to break out and cross
over.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with Entertainment Weekly, McLachlan, Merchant,
Phair, Elliott and Cole were startled when asked if there was any
truth to the rumor that Ginger Spice had quit the Spice Girls to
join Lilith Fair.
</P>
<P>
   Reminded of EW's question, McLachlan laughed out loud. ``I am
Ginger Spice,'' she said. ``It's true. I had to quit because Lilith
was starting.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Lilith Fair raised more than $700,000 for charities.
McLachlan hopes to double that amount this year with the help of
additional corporate sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have a responsibility to give whatever we can. ...
(Lilith) is a big money-making thing. And I think a lot of
companies and businesses have a responsibility to give something
back. (Lilith) is a really great vehicle for doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's corporate sponsors include Biore, Excite, Royal
Neighbors of America, Starbucks Coffee, Tower Records, VH1, Levi's
and Volkswagen of America.
</P>
<P>
   Levi's sponsored the Lilith Fair Acoustic Talent Search, but
McLachlan is miffed at the company for its portrayal of her and
several tourmates in an eight-page ad section in the current issue
of Vogue.
</P>
<P>
   McLachlan, who is shown with her hand down her jeans, explained
she was trying to adjust her underwear when the photographer
snapped her picture. Naturally, that was the photo Levi's chose to
use in the ad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went away from that shoot feeling pretty bad about it,''
McLachlan said. ``I was thinking, this is exactly what I don't
want. We're supposed to be strong, independent individuals. And
there we were, looking like tramps in a brothel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
