<SLUG> BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOUSEBOARD EASES USER STRAIN 
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By LONNIE BROWN    
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger    
 c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two products in today's column offer a new way of doing things.
One of them is a different approach to the keyboard. The other
takes the mouse off the desktop and puts it on your leg.
</P>
<P>
   First, the desktop-to-leg mouse move:
</P>
<P>
   There are some times during a computer session that the keyboard
is rarely used. The mouse is the only input device used. Playing
solitaire is one example. Navigating the Internet is another. Some
games rely on mouse movements and clicks.
</P>
<P>
   MouseBoard allows users to move the mouse from the desktop to
their leg or lap. The MouseBoard is about the size of a desktop
mouse pad and made of stiffer material. The board is mounted on a
thick piece of foam that's concave on its bottom so that it fits
the contour of the leg.
</P>
<P>
   Alan K. Lovejoy, founder of Medias &AMP; Co., a Colorado company
that makes the MouseBoard, said the product is particularly
appealing to ``designers and engineers on Abode or Quark who were
getting very sore arms after a busy day. Lately, we've started
getting calls from retired folks who love to surf the Internet, but
are troubled by arthritis or an arm injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Lovejoy said he came up with the idea when a friend of his,
Charlee King, was using the mouse to play Hearts on the computer.
``She said her arm was getting sore,'' said Lovejoy, adding that
when she placed a book on her leg and moved the mouse to it, the
shift in position provided some relief. Keeping the book in place
was the problem. MouseBoard's saddle-like shape solved that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It works well with a mouse with a cord on it,'' said Lovejoy,
``but if you have a cordless mouse that gives you a lot of freedom,
it really works well. That lets you lean back and get
comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   MouseBoard is most useful in situations where control is totally
with the mouse. ``If you're going to be switching back and forth
between the mouse and the keyboard, it's more convenient to leave
the mouse next to the keyboard,'' said Lovejoy. ``But for those
times when you're using just the mouse, MouseBoard lets you relax
instead of leaning toward the computer all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   I use a trackball instead of a mouse, but the MouseBoard works
equally well with either. It's main function is to reposition the
device being used, so it really doesn't matter if a mouse or
trackball is being moved to a more comfortable location.
</P>
<P>
   The MouseBoard weighs about four ounces, has a 7{-by-10-inch
surface available in blue, black, red or purple, and costs $19.95
plus shipping and handling. It is available on the Internet
(www.mouseboards.com) or by telephone at (303) 814-1973.
</P>
<P>
   NATURAL, YET ODD LOOKING
</P>
<P>
   The Microsoft Natural Keyboard still looks strange, even after
being around since 1994. Microsoft grouped the keyboard into two
parts, splitting it between the 5-6, t-y, g-h and b-n keys. Then it
bent those two sections at a slight angle so the wrists sit
straighter when typing.
</P>
<P>
   The design is supposed to give a more relaxed typing position.
More than 3 million of the keyboards have been sold.
</P>
<P>
   The Microsoft Natural Keyboard Elite is the successor to that
keyboard. It was introduced at the first of the year, and retains
the odd look of its predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   It is, however, following the computer trend of smaller and
cheaper, with new features.
</P>
<P>
   The Elite takes up slightly less desk space than the original.
It connects to the computer only through a PS/2 connection _ the
end of the connector is round and about the thickness of a pencil.
If you have one of the standard keyboard connectors about as thick
as the end of a thumb, the Elite doesn't use it. It does, however,
come with a Universal Serial Bus adapter to turn the PS/2
connection into a USB connection.
</P>
<P>
   The keyboard has three more keys than found on standard 101-key
keyboards. There are two keys that work with Windows operating
systems, allowing users to bring up the ``start'' menu and to use
Windows' shortcuts. A third key functions as a right-mouse button
without having to leave the keyboard to use the mouse.
</P>
<P>
   The estimated street price of the keyboard is about $55-$65.
</P>
<P>
   (Lonnie Brown is associate editor of The Ledger in Lakeland,
Fla. He can be reached by e-mail at LonnieB001(AT)aol.com. An
archive of his recent computer columns is on the Internet at
http://www.theledger.com/data.htm.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
