<P>
   COMPUTER-BOOKS (Undated) _ Clerking at a book shop one afternoon
15 years ago, a novelist named Kitty Florey watched two customers
approach the display racks. ``I get tired of these after a while,''
one said, indicating a stack of best sellers, ``but I don't know
what else to read.'' Ms. Florey proposed a few titles by Anne Tyler
and Barbara Kingsolver. Her manager suggested Ms. Florey's own
latest book. On a recent morning, the same Kitty Florey typed into
a computer the catalogue information and plot summary of ``The Man
in the Box,'' Thomas Moran's novel about an Austrian family that
shelters a Jewish doctor from the Nazis. Then she listed the book
under such categories as ``caring and caretaking,'' ``fugitives''
and ``Holocaust survivors.'' All the material became part of Muze's
data base, which some 300 bookstores offer to customers. Ms.
Florey's evolution parallels American society's: from an
old-fashioned, personal brand of taste-making to a high-tech
variety made possible by the advent of what is known as agent
software. By Samuel G. Freedman.
</P>
<P>
   W/Sidebar:
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-BOOKS-EVALUATE (Undated) _ Three authors rate the
computer book recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   WANING-CRITICS (Undated) _ These should be the best of times for
critics. The arts in America are exploding, culture has been
democratized and just about anything can be called ``art.'' Who
else but the professional critic has the expertise and the
perspicacity to go through it all, to determine what is art and
what is a masquerade, and to explain why? Yet in today's highly
commercialized society, celebrities often hold as much sway as
critics _ at least in determining popular success. Are critics
losing their influence? By Judith H. Dobrzynski.
</P>
<P>
   FATHER-ADVICE (Undated) _ Advice to mothers is as plentiful as
air. There are hundreds of books and thousands of old wives' tales.
What about advice to fathers? Tucked into books for mothers about
what they should expect from their babies and children are usually
a few pages telling them what they should expect from fathers
(usually very little). There is also a growing shelf of books of
advice for fathers: books encouraging them to take a greater part
in the children's lives, books ordering them to take back their
traditional roles and books jokingly telling them how to handle
their unpredictably moody wives and children. By Sarah Boxer.
</P>
<P>
   TV-CNN-NEWSSTAND (Undated) _ ``CNN Newsstand,'' the new
prime-time cable series, opened on a controversial note last week
with allegations that the United States used nerve gas against
American defectors during the Vietnam War. ``CNN Newsstand'' is the
overall title for three hourlong weekly collaborations between the
cable network and magazines in the Time-Warner empire. On Sundays,
Time magazine, which carried the nerve-gas charges, is the partner
from print; on Wednesdays, it's Fortune magazine and the beat is
business; on Thursday, it's Entertainment Weekly, and the beat is
show business. Critic's Notebook by Walter Goodman.
</P>
