<SLUG> BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-COLUMN-WINDOWS98-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINDOWS 98 OFFERS LITTLE FOR HOME USER  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By LONNIE BROWN    
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger    
 c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's all the fuss about Windows 98? Unless you're an attorney
with the U.S. Justice Department, should you, a home user, care?
The big rollout will come June 25. Should you be in front of your
favorite computer store with a lawn chair to get in line for the
early copy?
</P>
<P>
   I won't be. Not because I already have a reviewer's beta copy,
but because I'm less enthusiastic about Windows 98's arrival than I
was about Windows 3.0 or Windows 95.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the giant leap from Windows 3.1 to Windows 95, the move
to Windows 98 is only a small step _ at least for today's home
user.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Windows 98 does boot up faster. (Macintosh users love to
say, ``That's a great feature? You can re-boot quicker after a
crash?'') It does a little more than Windows 95. Some things are
easier to do.
</P>
<P>
   Some applications pop up quicker _ in some cases 50 percent
faster _ under Windows 98 than Windows 95. But is it all that
important to my computing session to have America Online start up
in 15 seconds instead of 30?
</P>
<P>
   Does Windows 98 run on my everyday workhorse computer? Not yet.
</P>
<P>
   It probably will in the future, perhaps even this year. But not
just yet.
</P>
<P>
   Windows 98 can run two or more monitors from a single computer.
It's a nice feature _ one that is more enticing to business users
who might be doing spreadsheets and databases at the same time _
than it is a home user. It has a more efficient file-management
system to save hard drive space. But with hard drives holding
gigabytes now instead of megabytes, home users may not find the
space need as pressing these days.
</P>
<P>
   Windows 98 still wants to have a good-size chunk of real estate
on the hard drive. A typical installation takes about 195
megabytes.
</P>
<P>
   Windows 98 also supports USB _ the universal serial bus. The USB
is wonderful: Got a new scanner? Plug it into the USB, and Windows
98 automatically knows the brand, model and what communications
ports are available for it. More stuff to add on? Simply plug it
in.
</P>
<P>
   There are some peripherals that are USB compatible, but right
now, there are more that aren't than are. In that respect, Windows
98, to steal a boast from Panasonic, is just slightly ahead of its
time.
</P>
<P>
   Windows 98 has many advantages over Windows 95. If I were a
systems manager, I'd be looking at its possibilities by the end of
the month. But unlike Windows 95, which had immediate advantages
for both home and business users, Windows 98 seems to pave new
roadway for business while filling in potholes in the road of home
computing.
</P>
<P>
   (Lonnie Brown is associate editor of The Ledger in Lakeland,
Fla. He can be reached by e-mail at LonnieB001(AT)aol.com. An
archive of his recent computer columns is on the Internet at
http://www.theledger.com/data.htm.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
