<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV22-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE CELLULOID CLASSROOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Mon., June 22)  
 (JT)  
 By DAVID GRIMES    
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Godzilla'' wasn't much of a movie but the big, ugly monster is
winning better reviews as a parenting tool.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Randall E. Osborne, an associate professor of psychology at
Indiana University-East, writes in ``The Official Godzilla
Compendium'' about how he taught his 2-year-old lessons in life
with the help of old Godzilla movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many examples in Godzilla movies of characters
helping each other,'' Osborne writes. ``Anguirus comes to
Godzilla's aid in battling Gigan and Ghidrah. I explain to my son
that it is important to know that people have different ideas and
preferences than we do, but that we must also be able to put those
differences aside ... for more important goals. He can then watch
examples of this when Rodan and Godzilla work together to defeat
Ghidrah in `Ghidrah, the Three-Headed Monster.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Osborne's son learned family values in ``Son of Godzilla'' when
``we see a poignant portrait as Godzilla tries to protect his son
from the freezing weather.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmental consciousness? ``My son understood what pollution
was by the time he was 2 years old,'' Osborne writes. ``His
understanding, of course, came from watching the film `Godzilla vs.
Hedorah' '' in which Godzilla saves Tokyo from a giant amoeba that
evolved from industrial sludge.
</P>
<P>
   I have always been of the opinion that children will eventually
learn all of life's important lessons if you force them to watch
enough movies and TV.
</P>
<P>
   For example, from watching ``Baywatch,'' my 12-year-old learned
two valuable lessons:
</P>
<P>
   1) Always take binoculars when you go to the beach.
</P>
<P>
   2) Your binoculars could be as powerful as the Hubble Space
Telescope and you still wouldn't see any women who looked remotely
like Pamela Lee.
</P>
<P>
   When he was younger, he picked up two valuable life-lessons from
the TV show ``Mighty Morphin Power Rangers:''
</P>
<P>
   1) If you karate kick a playmate, there is a very real chance
that he or she will try to karate kick you back.
</P>
<P>
   2) Girls can kick a lot harder than you'd think.
</P>
<P>
   From watching ``Jeopardy!'' he learned:
</P>
<P>
   1) Celebrities are, as a group, astonishingly stupid.
</P>
<P>
   2) Questions about opera or ballet? Ask mom.
</P>
<P>
   From watching the horror movie, ``Halloween,'' he learned:
</P>
<P>
   1) If you think there is a deranged, psychopathic killer loose
in your house, the first thing you should do is turn off all the
lights.
</P>
<P>
   2) If, after turning off all the lights, you are still having
trouble locating the deranged, psychopathic killer, go down in the
basement (by yourself, of course) or try backing slowly into a
room.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Road Runner'' cartoons he learned:
</P>
<P>
   1) Do not jump with springs on your feet while standing under a
rock overhang.
</P>
<P>
   2) Be suspicious of any merchandise mail-ordered from Acme as it
is prone to blowing up in your face, rocketing you head-first into
a rock wall, catapulting you off a mile-high cliff or otherwise
causing you grievous bodily harm.
</P>
<P>
   From the movie ``Jaws'' he learned:
</P>
<P>
   1) It is not a good idea to go skinny-dipping in the ocean at
night when there are reports of a 40-foot, man-eating, great white
shark in the area.
</P>
<P>
   2) If you are swimming and suddenly hear cello music, get out of
the pool fast.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Sarasota (Fla.)
Herald-Tribune.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The HERALD TRIBUNE, SARASOTA, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-19-98 1050EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
