<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-HISTBOX-COX- </SLUG>
   -$ADV21 
 &HT;     CLINTON STARTING A PATH TO CHINA OTHER PRESIDENTS HAVE TROD
 &HT;     With CHINA-AWAITS-$ADV21.
 &HT;     For Use Sunday, June 21 And Thereafter.
 &HT;     By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Here is a chronology of previous presidential visits
to China and how they came about:
</P>
<P>
   April 1971 _ China used ``Ping-Pong diplomacy'' to signal
China's readiness for a thaw with Washington after two decades of
animosity following the Korean War. Premier Zhou Enlai invited 15
American table tennis players and three reporters to Beijing for
what Zhou called ``a new page'' in U.S.-Chinese relations.
</P>
<P>
   July 9, 1971 _ President Richard Nixon's national security
adviser, Henry Kissinger, vanishing on a trip to Pakistan, secretly
flew to Beijing. Kissinger and Premier Zhou Enlai tentatively
agreed that their countries should cease being enemies. At
Kissinger's insistence, the Chinese agreed to refrain from dealings
with Nixon's political rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 21, 1972 _ Nixon electrified the world by stepping off Air
Force One in Beijing and shaking hands with Premier Zhou Enlai,
thus symbolizing America's de facto recognition of the Chinese
Communist revolution of 1949.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 28, 1972 _ Nixon and Zhou Enlai issued a ``joint
communique'' in Shanghai committing the United States to
``normalization'' of relations between the U.S. and mainland China.
In it the United States accepted that ``there is but one China and
Taiwan is a part of China.''
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 15, 1978 _ President Jimmy Carter announced
``normalization'' of relations in Washington, carrying out Nixon's
pledge. Carter promised the withdrawal of the last 750 U.S. troops
from Taiwan. Congress responded a few months later with the Taiwan
Relations Act, which obligates the United States to defend Taiwan
in case of aggression from mainland China.
</P>
<P>
   April 30, 1984 _ President Ronald Reagan ended a seemingly
symbolic six-day trip to China that turned out to be a turning
point. In the next five years, trade and security cooperation
blossomed.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 25-26, 1989 _ President George Bush was glowingly received
in Beijing by Chinese Premier Li Peng. But Chinese police stopped
dissident astrophysicist Fang Lizhi from reaching a presidential
dinner to which he had been invited at the U.S. embassy. Bush
publicly expressed ``regret'' to Chinese leaders over the incident.
</P>
<P>
   June 4, 1989 _ Chinese troops killed 500 to 1,000 people in
Beijing while quelling a pro-democracy uprising centered on
Tiananmen Square. Appalled at the violence, Congress and the Bush
Administration imposed sanctions on trade and military cooperation
with China, some of which still remains in effect.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For clients of the New York Times News Service &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
