<SLUG> BC-WORKPLACE-COLUMN-SMITH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS EMPLOYEE LOYALTY DROPS, BOSSES NEED TO MEND FENCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bosses have long suspected their workers are getting less loyal.
</P>
<P>
   Now there is evidence.
</P>
<P>
   According to a study released this week, American workers are
less committed to their employers and more likely to switch jobs
for small increases in pay, a trend that is making it increasingly
difficult for companies to hang on to their best employees in a
tight labor market.
</P>
<P>
   It would take a raise of 10 percent or less to make nearly a
quarter (22 percent) of employees switch their jobs. And more than
half (58 percent) would switch for a 20 percent raise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employee loyalty as we have known it is a thing of the past,''
said Dr. David Stum, co-founder of Aon Consulting Inc., a national
human resources firm that has studied worker commitment for the
past several years. ``Today's workers are more educated,
entrepreneurial and independent than ever, and are more discerning
in choosing where to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Stum's group surveyed more than 1,800 workers to see how their
loyalty index had changed since last year.
</P>
<P>
   The index is based on six loyalty components that include, among
other things, whether workers would recommend their organizations'
products and services, whether they would recommend their
organizations as one of the best places to work in their
communities, whether they intend to stay with their companies for
several years, and what it would take for them to switch jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The results showed a decline of 2.2 points in the index compared
with last year's benchmark baseline of 100.
</P>
<P>
   That should be a significant concern for companies, even if they
don't think they're having problems with turnover.
</P>
<P>
   ``Retention doesn't equal commitment,'' Stum said. ``Companies
want to do things `better, faster, cheaper,' but that doesn't come
from people who just show up.''
</P>
<P>
   The best ideas and results come from people who want to work for
an organization, are dedicated to its values, and who bring more
than a time-clock attitude to the table. That's real loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   But there are a number of factors contributing to an overall
decline in worker commitment, Stum said.
</P>
<P>
   The first is job-related stress.
</P>
<P>
   The percentage of employees reporting job-related burnout
increased from 39 percent in 1995 to 53 percent in 1998. Days lost
to stress increased from 1.1 days to 1.5 days a year during the
same time frame, a 36 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   In a related finding, conflict between work and family
responsibilities also has increased. The number of days lost to
care for sick children, elderly relatives, or because child care
had fallen through increased from 3.6 days a year to 4.6 days a
year between 1995 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Work stress and family conflicts erode people's ability to give
their best to their jobs, Stum said.
</P>
<P>
   The study was done to help companies figure out ways to improve
employee commitment and win loyalty back by better addressing
employee needs.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the study found the No. 1 way for companies to
build loyalty was by recognizing the importance of personal and
family time, Stum said.
</P>
<P>
   Companies need to insist that managers respect the family
responsibilities of employees, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so much that they want the company to fix the
problem, just to recognize it's tough,'' he said. ``Interpersonal
indifference is causing people to turn away from companies.''
</P>
<P>
   A second way managers can work to improve commitment is by
making sure employees understand the mission and culture of the
organization. Tying employee rewards to the success of the
organization also helps build loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   Opportunities for personal growth, including training and skills
development, also help improve loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el1l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``The first loyalty of employees today is to `Me Inc.,''' Stum
said. Employees stay when they feel a company is investing in them.
</P>
<P>
   Providing ways for employees to give feedback about their jobs
and the direction of the organization also builds commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Employees want two-way dialogues _ and information.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we found is there is a real hunger for the truth,'' Stum
said. Workers want to know where the company stands and where it's
going.
</P>
<P>
   It's ironic that companies spend more time and energy trying to
gain customer loyalty than the loyalty of their employees, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a fundamental truth about commitment: It takes some
to get some.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Smith is a reporter and columnist for the P-I. Her e-mail
address is carolsmith(at)seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
