<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH BUILDS BRIDGES, BUT SHIES FROM PRESIDENTIAL TALK IN
WASHINGTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A crush of Republican heavyweights helped Texas
Gov. George W. Bush raise about $1 million for his re-election
campaign in a single day, fueling more speculation that he will run
for president in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't made up my mind whether I'm going to seek the
presidency,'' Bush told reporters Thursday as he met powerbrokers
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican governor insists that he is taking seriously his
campaign against Democratic opponent Garry Mauro. But a poll out
this week showed that Bush holds a 53 percentage-point lead over
Mauro, the state's Land Commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will leave no stone unturned,'' Bush said while conceding
that the presidential speculation will continue ``because I haven't
said no.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing everything I can to dampen the speculation,'' he
said, ``but I sense that as long as I leave the door open, there
will be speculation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like what I tell my fellow Texans: `You have to calculate
this ... when you head into the booth in November, and make it part
of the equation.'''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, more than 600 people attended a reception at the
Willard Hotel, two blocks from the White House. Many on the guest
list _ including C. Bowden Gray, a former presidential adviser, and
Carla Hills, the former trade representative _ served in the
administration of his father, President George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   A $5,000-per-plate dinner was held after the reception for about
100 people. Bush aides said the fund-raisers were expected to add
``over a million'' to his $15 million war chest for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro, by contrast, has raised $2.2 million and is far leagues
behind the governor in opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent Texas Poll shows Bush backed by 70 percent of
the 691 potential voters surveyed. Seventeen percent favored Mauro.
</P>
<P>
   And of those surveyed, 67 percent said a possible Bush run for
the presidency would have no impact on their vote in the
gubernatorial race this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``People appreciate the job I'm doing,'' Bush said of the survey
results.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was ``amazed'' and ``mystified'' by national polls
that pick him as the top contender for the Republican presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, said Bush is seen by Republicans in
Congress as the ``best prospect, the front-runner and the one most
likely to be elected'' in a presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   It is that popularity at home and nationally that sent lobbyists
scurrying to the fund-raising events for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington special-interest groups are trying to build bridges
now in case he does run for president,'' said Paul Hendrie, a
spokesman for the Center for Responsive Politics, which advocates
campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   Lobbyists and special-interest groups also are signing up for a
June 23 Washington reception and dinner for Mauro, who has enlisted
the help of his friends of 25 years, President Clinton and first
lady Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore will headline a reception for Mauro in El
Paso, Texas, on June 25. The events for Mauro are expected to raise
$500,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both candidates are seen as players on the national stage,''
Hendrie said, adding that the Texas gubernatorial race this fall is
being seen as a ``dress rehearsal for the presidential campaigns.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Opponents will be looking for weaknesses, to uncover some
issues that will play out in a national election,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 1504EDT &QL; 
