<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELCOME TO OUYR HYPHENATED COMMUNITY 
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES    
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune    
 c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I am reluctant to comment on Money magazine's recent
best-places-to-live survey since I have been accused, by a reader,
of writing too many negative columns about Florida, which as we all
know is the closest thing you can find to paradise except during
hurricane season or love bug season or during those periods when it
is too hot, too cold, too changeable or all of the above.
</P>
<P>
   So I will make every effort to be positive in this piece, though
it won't be easy given the fact that Money magazine basically rated
the Sarasota-Bradenton area somewhere between Love Canal and that
place in Ohio with the vulture problem.
</P>
<P>
   That's a slight exaggeration, of course. Money actually ranked
Sarasota-Bradenton between Fort Myers-Cape Coral and
Charleston-North Charleston, S.C., which strikes me as good news
for Fort Myers and bad news for Charleston.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, the ranking would be nothing to get worked up about
were it not for the fact that our fair hyphenated community
finished dead last of all the mid-sized Florida cities that made it
on the (BEGIN QUOTE)Best of the South(END QUOTE) list.
</P>
<P>
   That means we were beaten out by Pensacola, Tallahassee, Daytona
Beach, Melbourne-Titusville-Palm Bay, Lakeland-Winter Haven, West
Palm Beach-Boca Raton, Fort Pierce-Port St. Lucie and the
aforementioned Fort Myers-Cape Coral.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear to me, if not to the editors of Money magazine, that
Sarasota-Bradenton (I'm resisting the urge to call us Saraton since
that sounds too much like an asthma inhaler) is a far superior
place to any of those other Florida cities, especially Pensacola
which is basically in Alabama and should therefore be disqualified.
</P>
<P>
   Two out of three medflies choose Sarasota-Bradenton over West
Palm Beach-Boca Raton, and well they should. Sarasota-Bradenton is
conveniently located near the Gulf of Mexico, which is something
that cannot be said about Daytona Beach or Lakeland-Winter Haven.
The Gulf beaches are nice to walk on when the red tide not too bad
and the sunsets are fabulous, thanks to the air pollution that
blows our way from St. Petersburg and Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   Sarasota-Bradenton also has a sophisticated system of bridges
and highways, several of which may be open on any given day. There
are no major theme parks in Sarasota-Bradenton, true, but who needs
roller coasters and flume rides when you can take a spin down U.S.
41 during rush hour?
</P>
<P>
   If its quiet and solitude you seek, than the Sarasota-Bradenton
airport is the place for you. You can gaze into the fish tanks or
wander the deserted corridors and never have to worry that the
sound of an arriving or departing jet will shatter your reverie.
</P>
<P>
   Sarasota is also known as the ``arts capital'' of Florida. While
some cynics might argue that that title is a dubious distinction in
a state that treats professional wrestling as a cultural event,
Sarasotans take great pride in their artistic sensibility to the
point that you can hardly build a self-serve car wash here without
running afoul of the Taste and Aesthetics Police. The ongoing
screaming match between the developers and the Taste Police makes
for great theater. Oh, and the stuff that gets put on stage isn't
too bad, either.
</P>
<P>
   I haven't even gotten into Sarasota-Bradenton's booming economy,
its magnificent weather, its outstanding schools and hospitals or
the high percentage of local politicians and business leaders who
have managed thus far to avoid indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Suffice it to say that Fort Pierce-Port St. Lucie (wherever the
heck that is) can't begin to compare to the Greater Metropolitan
Area that we call home.
</P>
<P>
   After all, 100 million sterile medflies can't be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
