A7305 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-HIGHART-TEX     06-19 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-HIGHART-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODERN `ART' FULL OF SECONDHAND POSES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seeing Ally Sheedy in ``High Art'' _ and seeing the way she's
used _ is a shock. It's not like watching Judd Nelson unfurl his
nostrils in ``Suddenly Susan,'' where he's the best thing in the
show and he still isn't any good.
</P>
<P>
   Sheedy has often had an exposed quality, and when she works, her
nervous vulnerability can pull you in. As Lucy Berliner, the
withdrawn photographer, our awareness of her comes into play. She's
been burned by the public, and isn't eager to expose herself to
direct sunlight; her wrinkled pallor is frayed around the edges.
</P>
<P>
   Under director Lisa Cholodenko, ``High Art'' brandishes a kind
of downtown chic, as if its cast spent too much time watching
documentaries on Weimar Republic Berlin, or high school drama class
versions of ``Cabaret.'' There are more gaunt cheekbones in this
movie than in a season of Calvin Klein ads, and the same level of
generic irony serves as the film's guiding sensibility.
</P>
<P>
   Syd (Radha Mitchell) is a sleek and ambitious young charmer who
lives below Lucy; how's that for subtlety. Lucy's leaky tub is the
device that sets Syd into action. Curled up in her cave with her
girlfriend, Greta, a ruthlessly inert German actress played with
world-weariness by Patricia Clarkson, Lucy is lured out into the
open with Syd. Syd is determined to get Lucy back into the world,
or at least into the pages of ain't-it-cool ``Frame'' magazine,
where she works and where the eager editors would love to put Lucy
back in harness.
</P>
<P>
   ``High Art'' should be called ``High Arch.'' With its
college-girl pretensions and a notion of sophistication based on a
surface approximation of ennui, it's about as believable as LeAnn
Rimes' rendition of ``Purple Rain.'' Nearly everything feels
secondhand.
</P>
<P>
   If anything works, it's Sheedy's desperate wariness. She plays
Lucy with the fervor of a recovering alcoholic fighting to stay
away from a shot of single-malt scotch.
</P>
<P>
   Director Cholodenko shows a skill for exploitation; in a way,
this is the kind of movie that Syd would direct. When the two women
engage in a circle flirt, Lucy is sweaty and wounded, but can't
resist. The only things that keep Lucy protected are her drug habit
and a pack of equally burned-out friends _ a truly funny touch that
plays like a parody of a support group.
</P>
<P>
   It helps that Sheedy has burned herself down to bone and sinew;
there's no flesh left to give her strength. It's a powerful if
one-note performance, an opportunity for a breakthrough that Sheedy
seizes greedily, and her neediness is the jolt that gives ``High
Art'' any spark.
</P>
<P>
   ``High Art'' is rated R for adult sexuality, adult language and
drug addiction.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``High Art''
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Ally Sheedy, Radha Mitchell, Patricia Clarkson
</P>
<P>
   Director: Lisa Cholodenko
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 96 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is a film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
