<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-FANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREEN RULES AT U.S. OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: Philadelphia, San Antonio)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RACHEL GORDON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Golfers aren't the only ones scoring at the U.S.
Open championship. So are the purveyors of souvenirs, food and
drink.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at this,'' said an elated Kirk Dowdell, opening a bag of
souvenirs he brought at the tournament, being held at the Olympic
Club.
</P>
<P>
   He pulled out a ``Pope Scope'' _ a $10 must-have,
cardboard-and-glass gizmo invented for the pope's visit to San
Francisco in 1987. The contraption works something like a
periscope, allowing users to see over the view-obstructing heads of
the people standing in front of them.
</P>
<P>
   And it's perfect for watching the golf match, particularly when
the crowd favorites are on the course, drawing fans six and seven
deep on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I already used it and it works. I was able to see Tiger Woods
play,'' said Dowdell, a Sacramento banker who spent Wednesday at
the Open with Lynn, his schoolteacher wife.
</P>
<P>
   And hey, for $10, the Pope Scope is practically a steal. Hardly
anything can be had for so little money at the U.S. Open
merchandise tent.
</P>
<P>
   There are the $114 wind-breakers, the $18-a-piece fuzzy club
covers and the $178 framed photos of the Olympic Club. The biggest
sellers, however, are logo U.S. Open caps _ in the $25 range _ and
golf shirts, many of them running $45 to $60. There's even a U.S.
Open tie-dye T-shirt for $28 that would look right at home on a
Dead Head.
</P>
<P>
   When the cost of souvenirs is added to the cost of tickets,
which run $60 or so a day, and food and drink, attending the U.S.
Open gets pricey. A beer runs $4 at the concession stand, a burger
$4.50. Bringing in food from outside the exclusive compound is
frowned upon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We bought lemonade and pretzels. That was $13,'' said Dowdell,
the owner of the Pope Scope. ``It's not cheap.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, said Bob Kelly, a Philadelphia attorney,
``When you come to an event like this, you spend money.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly forked over $400 for U.S. Open goodies _ before the
edibles and tickets. Luckily, he has family in the San Francisco
area so he doesn't have to worry about lodging.
</P>
<P>
   The rush for merchandise has been amazing, with the line to get
into the tent store nearly a block long at busy times. Inside,
hundreds of people jam the aisles, elbow-to-elbow. The bank of 40
cash registers never slowed.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg and Theresa Mickus, of San Antonio, spent $700 for
souvenirs on one visit and came back to buy more.
</P>
<P>
   Cost? No problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've already bought lots of shirts, caps, towels, tumblers.
You name it, we bought it,'' Theresa Mickus said. ``Now we're
looking for a vest.''
</P>
<P>
   Her brother, Mike Brisky, is in the elite group of U.S. Open
players, and she was getting in some last-minute shopping before
watching him tee off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
