<HEADER>
A7330 &Cx1f; taf-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOW-TICKLING-AFFECTS-     06-19 0411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOW-TICKLING-AFFECTS-BRAIN-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
I'M TICKLED 
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By ALISON MOTLUK  
 Copyright 1998 New Scientist  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's no fun to tickle yourself because one part of the brain
tells another what's about to happen, brain scans reveal.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah-Jayne Blakemore and her colleagues at the Institute of
Neurology in London used functional magnetic resonance imaging, or
fMRI, to look at how tickling affected the brains of three
volunteers. First, the subjects tickled themselves on the palm of
the hand with a specially designed tickling device. In another
test, a researcher operated the tickler.
</P>
<P>
   All the subjects rated the self-administered strokes as less
ticklish than the externally administered ones, and the fMRI scans
backed this up.
</P>
<P>
   When someone else was doing the tickling, there was much more
activity in the somatosensory cortex, the part of the brain that
processes tactile sensations. And the part of the anterior
cingulate that has been linked to pleasure lit up only when others
did the tickling.
</P>
<P>
   ``That explains why it feels better,'' Blakemore says.
</P>
<P>
   The scans also showed that only the self-tickle test activated
the cerebellum, part of the brain involved in planning. Blakemore's
team suspected that when people try to tickle themselves, the
cerebellum ruins the fun by sending urgent messages to the
somatosensory cortex warning it that a sensation is on its way.
</P>
<P>
   So Blakemore tricked the cerebellums of the subjects by retiming
the tickling machine so that self-administered tickles came later
than they expected. When delayed by 200 milliseconds, she says, the
self-tickle was just as good as an external one. ``The ticklishness
increased as the delays increased,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Blakemore now hopes to test volunteers with schizophrenia. Her
colleague Chris Frith suspects that schizophrenics will be able to
tickle themselves even without the delay, as there is evidence that
their cerebellums do not predict sensory consequences in the same
way as normal brains. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science
and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 1528EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
