<HEADER>
A7357 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV21-     06-19 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRUNING IN SHORTS AND T-SHIRT WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 21)  
(lb) 
 By ROBERT KOURIK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Grandpa never lied. When he said, ``Pruning trees in the summer
is bad, especially with fruit trees, because they might bleed to
death,'' he was just repeating an heirloom fallacy.
</P>
<P>
   While the conventional wisdom is that late winter and early
spring are the best times for pruning, in fact, most trees, shrubs
and perennials are helped by some pruning from late winter all the
way through late fall. And there are special benefits to pruning in
the summer:
</P>
<P>
   _ You can wear shorts and a T-shirt instead of the long johns
and sweaters that cold-weather pruning requires.
</P>
<P>
   _ Delaying some pruning till summer frees up time for the more
urgent gardening tasks of spring.
</P>
<P>
   _ The foliage is visible in summer, so dead, damaged or diseased
sections are easier to spot, and the effects of pruning on patterns
of light and shadow are more apparent.
</P>
<P>
   _ Flowers will be abundant on spring-blooming plants, since the
plants aren't pruned before the buds open.
</P>
<P>
   _ The calluses that will eventually seal the wound are quicker
to form when the plant is growing and photosynthesis is active.
</P>
<P>
   There are some shortcomings. Pruning deciduous trees in leaf
makes it harder to see the branching pattern, for example, and
previously shaded young limbs may be damaged by the sun, because
they haven't developed tough bark. (Cut with discretion in areas
with hot summers, leaving enough foliage to protect the upper
branches and the main trunk.)
</P>
<P>
   Where winters are cold, pruning too late in summer will leave
any new growth vulnerable to freeze damage. And you might knock
some fruit off trees before harvesting.
</P>
<P>
   Any pruning cut _ whether it's made in winter or summer _ can
admit diseases. That's another reason not to prune too late in
summer, so there's plenty of time for a callus to start forming.
Your Cooperative Extension Service or an arborist can advise you
about diseases specific to your area. And it's always a good idea
to disinfect the clipper blades with a 10 percent solution of
chlorine bleach between cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Pruning cuts should never be made flush with the trunk. Before
any cut, you should identify two parts: the branch collar and the
branch bark ridge. The collar is the slightly swollen area that
nearly encircles the shoot, branch or limb where it is attached to
the trunk. (The collar is usually especially prominent on
conifers.) Prune as close as you can to the outside of the collar
while leaving it intact.
</P>
<P>
   On some plants, the collar doesn't show clearly. In those cases,
use the branch bark ridge to figure out the approximate angle of
the cut. This ridge is the slightly raised or puckered area of
crusty bark extending partway around the sides of the trunk from a
point just above the branch.
</P>
<P>
   Draw an imaginary line from the top of the branch bark ridge
straight down the side of the trunk. Then notice the angle that
this line makes with the branch bark ridge. Your pruning cut should
angle out about as much as the branch bark ridge angles in.
</P>
<P>
   When you cut, don't leave a stub sticking out, because diseases
and fungi may colonize it and eventually enter the heart of the
branch or trunk. And don't worry about painting over the cut _
horticulturists now say that this doesn't help the healing process.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy summer pruning isn't for every plant. Hacking back a bush
or tree that flowers in mid- to late summer, for example, will ruin
its display of blooms, since the newly forming buds are chopped
off. Prune these plants while they are dormant, in late winter or
early spring. And remember that if you don't prune them, they're
likely to get leggy.
</P>
<P>
   Dormant pruning is used primarily to encourage new shoots, to
reinvigorate a plant that doesn't put out much new growth and to
stimulate multiple shoots to work with during the summer, when
unwanted or poorly placed shoots are best removed.
</P>
<P>
   But spring bloomers should be pruned immediately after they
bloom _ late spring for some plants, as late as midsummer for
others. These plants start forming their buds later in the summer,
so when they go dormant in late fall, they're ready for the big
display the following spring.
</P>
<P>
   Most summer pruning involves so-called thinning cuts _ taking
off branches all the way back to the branch collar. Winter, or
dormant, pruning mostly involves heading cuts, or the partial
removal of branches to stimulate and control the branching pattern.
</P>
<P>
   When you prune a plant in summer after it has bloomed, don't
spare the shears if the crown's foliage was too rangy or leggy the
previous summer. The farther back you prune the crown, the denser
it will be the next summer. As a general guideline, you can promote
more ornamental beauty _ or, in fruit trees, more bounty _ by
pruning so that shoots and branches angle up from the horizontal at
45 to 60 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   The best part of the summer for pruning is when heat and lack of
water cause a slowing of new growth. In the most arid spots, this
tapering off can occur as early as mid-July. In areas with warm,
rainy summers, active growth can continue until fall. For guidance
on when to start pruning, consult experienced gardeners, the
Cooperative Extension Service or a good pruning book.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
