<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-MERGERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERGER MANIA SHIFTS TO CYBERSPACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDWARTA IWATA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Merger mania and business unions are starting to
sweep the Internet, as big corporations pounce on smaller on-line
companies that offer gateways to a new medium and millions of
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is talking to everybody else,'' said Ryan Jacob,
portfolio manager of The Internet Fund, an investment fund based in
New York. ``The Internet is growing so rapidly that media companies
realize they can't wait much longer, or they'll be left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   The headlines and broadcasts are filled with new deals and
partnerships: Walt Disney Co. executives said Thursday they agreed
to buy 43 percent of Infoseek Corp., the hot Santa Clara, Calif.,
on-line search service.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, General Electric's NBC network bought 60 percent of
the popular Snap on-line search directory for $38 million from CNET
Inc. of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T Corp. reportedly is in talks to buy America Online Inc.,
the world's leading on-line service provider.
</P>
<P>
   After uch skepticism, behemoth media companies finally are
making large investments in on-line commerce, hoping to shove more
of their content on line as the Internet keeps growing.
</P>
<P>
   The small Internet companies also benefit from the deals.
Infoseek, for instance, will gain Disney's world-class marketing
might and mass entertainment offerings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a mutual necessity here,'' Jacob said. ``A lot of
Internet companies are finding it too expensive to (expand) their
business, and they really need deep pockets to finance them. They
can't keep selling their stock every six months to finance their
expansion.''
</P>
<P>
   Internet search companies must evolve into media companies and
broaden their brand name and products or face death, said Alan
Braverman, an analyst at CS First Boston in New York.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, traditional media and telecommunications
companies realize the Internet is a strong medium that soon may
compete with television and radio.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Internet is readily available to the masses via
telephone, cable or satellite, analysts project that 50 percent to
80 percent of American households will be on line over the next few
years.
</P>
<P>
   The big companies want to snap up the Internet companies while
they are still bargains, thus avoiding costlier acquisitions later
or building from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this stage of the game, these large media companies realize
it's cheaper to buy rather than try to build,'' Jacob said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
