<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7393 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEAMER-GIVEAWAY-COX     06-19 0324
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAMER-GIVEAWAY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Key to keeping employees is a BMW
 &HT;    (ATTN: Financial, technology editors)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the sweepstakes to attract and keep employees, a metro
Atlanta computer software firm might have found the key: actually,
a set of keys to a brand new BMW Z3 or BMW 318i.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue Systems Inc. has leased a fleet of BMWs for its 40
full-time workers, from receptionists to computer programmers. The
cars, in the employees' choice of color and options, will be
available in September and are valued at about $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've hit the lottery,'' said John Challenger, executive
vice president of the national outplacement firm of Challenger,
Gray &AMP; Christmas Inc. in Chicago. ``That's the best I've heard
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   In a metro area where 20,000 information technology jobs are
unfilled, the BMW is a recruitment tool.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a combination of rewarding our people and it's for
establishing an environment in which our people are happy to be
where they are,'' said chief financial officer Charles Crumley, who
is one of the three owners. ``We have very few (turnovers), but
it's a very competitive market and I'm sure some of our people have
other offers from time to time.''
</P>
<P>
   The company writes and sells software to state and local
governments and plans to hire 30 people in the next year. Chief
Executive Bill Glover, who drives a BMW Z3, came up with the idea
about a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Details are still being worked out, but Crumley said the company
will most likely pay most of the insurance on the cars. By law,
leased company cars are considered taxable income.
</P>
<P>
   Finding workers has reached the proportion of television games
shows, with companies giving out free cruises, massage therapy at
the office, even in-house dry-cleaning, with cubicle-to-cubicle
delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
