<P>
   CHINA-RELIGION-NYT (Nanjing, China) _ Open displays of worship,
unusual when the communists were reshaping China, are becoming more
widespread. Yet even as Bibles and church services become more
common, scores of Christian leaders live in labor camps or jails
for refusing to bow to government control. While the confirmed
number of imprisoned Christians appears to be lower than is often
asserted abroad, their travails are a telling sign that religion
here is not truly free. WITH GRAPHIC. Moved 6-16. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHERN-BAPTISTS-BOS (Undated) _ In each of the past three
years, the Southern Baptists' annual convention has been marked by
a defining declaration of the march rightward of the nation's
largest Protestant denomination. These developments reflect the
takeover of the denomination by those who believe the Bible must be
taken literally as the inerrant word of God. Starting nearly 20
years ago, they have pushed moderates out of the denomination's six
seminaries and its administrative bodies. By Diego Ribadeneira.
Moved 6-15.
</P>
<P>
   BAPTIST-COX (Undated) _ Controversy provoked by the Southern
Baptist Convention's call for women to ``graciously submit'' to
their husbands was unexpected and unfounded, said the Rev. Frank
Cox, the leader of the Georgia chapter told his Lawrenceville
congregation Sunday. But any man who thinks the convention's action
``gave him the right to be a dictator in the home does not
understand the word of God,'' said Cox. By Jennifer Brett. Moved
6-14.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-BISHOP-NYT (Chanal, Mexico) _ Chiapas Bishop Samuel Ruiz,
73, preaches a passionately egalitarian message, calling on Indians
to reject the virtual caste system under which they are routinely
abused or ignored. But many government supporters and followers of
other faiths reject Ruiz's message. When Ruiz comes to this town,
he wears a metal helmet as protection against bullets, and he walks
surrounded by burly bodyguards. By Julia Preston. Moved 6-15.
</P>
<P>
   CELIBACY-DEBATE-COX (West Palm Beach, Fla.) _ The two sides of
celibacy: is it liberating, or limiting? Some supporters say it
enables a clergyman to be of service to a larger family than a
biological one. Some critics say it encouraes pedophilia. By Steve
Gushee. Moved 6-15.
</P>
<P>
   BAPTISTS-MORMONS-NYT (Salt Lake City) _ Over the last week,
members of two of the most determinedly missionary faiths in the
United States, the Southern Baptist Convention and the Church of
Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, have been coming face to face in
what has been a courteous if somewhat wary encounter. That it has
been happening here, on ground that the 19th-century Mormon leader
Brigham Young declared a modern-day Zion, is the work of the
Southern Baptists. By Gustav Niebuhr. Moved 6-13.
</P>
<P>
   BAPTISTS-REVIEW-NYT _ The conspiracy theorists have it all
wrong. The U.S. government is not run by Freemasons. Or by the pope
or Jewish bankers. The American people are entitled to the truth:
the government is run by Southern Baptists, who were recently in
the news for boycotting Disney, proselytizing Jews and, just last
week, declaring that wives should submit to their husbands. By
Laurie Goodstein. Moved 6-13.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CHRISTIANS-COX (Ft. Worth, Texas) _ Texas Gov. George W.
Bush has strong support among Republicans, but so far, the
Christian Coalition has given him at best a lukewarm reception. By
Ken Herman. Moved 6-15.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS (Undated) _ Tom Beaudoin, 29, is a
self-described Generation Xer, that amorphous population cohort
born in the mid-1960s to the late 1970s. Beaudoin wants to be their
theologian. He believes that Generation X _ contrary to popular
perception _ is deeply spiritual, if not necessarily devout. By
Diego Ribadeneira. Moved 6-17.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT (Undated) _ Criticism was quick in coming
after the Southern Baptist Convention, at its annual meeting in
Salt Lake City this week, added to the denomination's basic
statement of beliefs a declaration that ``a wife is to submit
herself graciously to the servant leadership of her husband.'' By
Peter Steinfels. Moved 6-12.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX (Salt Lake City) _ Paige Patterson,
who became president of the Southern Baptist Convention last week,
began his climb to power in 1979 in a meeting with Houston Judge
Pauk Pressler in a skybox in the Houston Astrodome. At the time,
moderates dominated the giant denomination, and they were basking
in the glow of fresh national attention brought on by the election
of President Jimmy Carter, a born-again Southern Baptist. But
working in the background were conservatives such as Patterson and
Pressler, who thought Baptists were on a liberal path to
destruction. By Jim Jones. Moved 6-16.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-MUSIC-COX (Undated) _ The veteran Christian band 4HIM
takes care of details in their new record, `Obvious.' By John
Blake. Moved 6-12.
</P>
