<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CHINA (Hong Kong) _ When President Clinton steps onto
Chinese soil this week, he will be like a famed actor with a vast
supporting cast mounting a stage with a huge audience in
attendance, but no real script. Whether in his travels he will be
able to create a credible script that will lead to significant new
agreements or understandings will show the measure of his acumen as
a leader known for being able to think on his feet. By ORVILLE
SCHELL.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-CAMPAIGN (La Dorado, Colombia) _ Although Horacio Serpa
is desperate for votes in Sunday's tight presidential run-off, he
has been operating a shoestring campaign. That's because both Serpa
and his opponent, Andres Pastrana, are haunted by the specter of
the campaign finance scandal that nearly toppled the government of
President Ernesto Samper. By JOHN OTIS.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-PRESIDENTS (Bogota, Colombia) _ When they leave the
White House, former U.S. presidents often disappear on the golf
course, make a few speeches, write memoirs. In Colombia, however,
ex-presidents often remain major powerbrokers. They have swayed
voters in this year's presidential elections by publicly endorsing
candidates and offering back-room advice. By JOHN OTIS.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FOREST-FIGHT (Eurkea, Calif.) _ In the silence of the primeval
Headwaters Forest, it's easy to believe the end of the clamorous
battle over this largest unprotected grove of ancient redwoods is
finally in sight. But if the Headwaters fight is drawing to a
close, it's ending in much the same way it has played out since
1986, when it became one of the most acrimonious environmental
issues of recent times. By BILL DAWSON.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ A good example of mendacity and
hypocrisy is the tobacco industry's $40 million propaganda campaign
to make it appear that the defeated anti-tobacco bill was just
another manifestation of lawmakers' greed for more money to
increase the size of government. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON. (Filed
Thursday)
</P>
</TEXT>
