<HEADLINE>
FOR CORPORATE REBELS, SHORT-SLEEVED SHIRTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 21)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
(lb) 
 By DAVID COLMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The short-sleeved dress shirt conjures an image of
pale crew-cut men, circa 1965, feeding punch cards into a mainframe
computer the size of a studio apartment. But these days, when the
high school computer nerd has probably become one of the richest
men in the United States, the look has a quirky appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Once declasse, the short-sleeved dress shirt has achieved the
status of anti-fashion icon _ just look at Dilbert, Drew Carey and
the alternative rock group the Presidents of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Never to be left out of a trend, designers like Paul Smith and
Dolce &AMP; Gabbana are offering the short-sleeved dress shirt in finer
fabrics and flattering cuts. But even with a designer label, the
shirt is still the reigning symbol of mainframe chic, conveying the
aloofness from corporate dress standards that made the tattoo such
a popular decoration. Of course, the shirt carries a subtler
message.
</P>
<P>
   To emulate a moneyed nerd, only the best short-sleeved shirt
will do. The checked shirts at Paul Smith, 108 Fifth Ave., $155 to
$195, are neatly tailored and come in cheerful colors, perfect for
either Silicon Valley or SoHo. The classic short-sleeve in white is
available in a stylish version at Emporio Armani for $95. At Dolce
&AMP; Gabbana, 825 Madison Ave., an ultra-fitted white cotton shirt
with a pair of chest pockets is $165.
</P>
<P>
   Barneys New York carries several models, including a white
textured cotton shirt by Dries Van Noten that is now on sale for
$170. For the sexier computer jock, a sheer short-sleeved shirt is
$305 at Costume National, 108 Wooster St. in SoHo.
</P>
<P>
   The cheapest places to find short-sleeved dress shirts are at
thrift shops. Metropolis, on Avenue B at Seventh Street, has an
especially good selection. But beware: A common problem with many
models dug up from clothes graveyards is an uncomfortably high
polyester count.
</P>
<P>
   And for the complete style download: cerebral-looking
eyeglasses, available at Paul Smith, $210 to $350, and at Dolce &AMP;
Gabbana, $240; simple, plain-front khakis at Banana Republic, $48,
and New Balance running shoes from Foot Locker, $59 to $125. A
shirt-pocket protector is optional.
</P>
<P>
   One last note: The top button should never, ever be closed. Geek
chic is one thing; Forrest Gump is another.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
