A7428 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STONE-WALLS-$ADV21-AR     06-19 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STONE-WALLS-$ADV21-ART-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMETHING THERE IS THAT LOVES A WALL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)   (For release Sunday, June 21)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
(lb) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When James Huniford and Stephen Sills decided to
accessorize their weekend house in Bedford, N.Y., with the latest
suburban status symbol, they didn't fool around.
</P>
<P>
   Snaking around their 22-acre property is a massive stone wall
built by Spanish masons. It took two years to piece together the
rustic fieldstones without mortar. Such extravagance does not come
cheap. Huniford won't confirm the cost, but masons estimate the
price at more than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``People love it,'' Huniford said. ``They stop all the time.
We've had tons of people talk about it. We've had people drive up
off the street.''
</P>
<P>
   That paradox _ that a large, imposing stone wall meant to keep
people out attracts attention and the occasional unknown caller _
is not lost on Huniford and Sills, who own the design firm Sills
Huniford in New York, with clients like Anna Wintour and Nan Swid.
They understand that their stone wall is not only functional (good
fences make good neighbors, as Robert Frost reported), but it is
also an emblem.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the stone wall _ imposing, massive, redolent of
Old World charm and New World money _ has become one of the most
important status symbols for the high-end home in woodsy northern
suburbs, right up there with Range Rovers and $12,000 custom-built
AGA stoves.
</P>
<P>
   Bedford and Mount Kisco lead the masonry market in New York; in
Connecticut, Greenwich has gone wall-crazy, along with New Canaan,
Darien and Westport.
</P>
<P>
   Randi Heine, a Bedford resident who has worked with a mason on
her stone walls and other landscaping projects for two years, says
Greenwich is so wall-obsessed that she calls it ``the walled
city.'' Stonemasons in Westchester County, N.Y., and Fairfield
County, Conn., report waiting lists _ some as long as a year _ and
stone suppliers have come to expect seasonal shortages.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stock market went crazy, and people went crazy and started
building,'' said Carmine Luppino, a mason in Mount Kisco, whose
clients will wait a year for his services. ``It's a status symbol.
The bigger the wall you got, the bigger the piece of property you
got, the more money you got.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Tomlinson, an owner of Bedford Stone and Masonry Supply,
said: ``We've seen a major increase in the demand for stone in the
last five years. It's a status symbol, and it raises the value of
the house. Everybody is so busy right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Huniford wanted to build a wall because it provided privacy, and
it helped to mute noise from Route 172, the busy two-lane road on
which his house sits. Tommy Hilfiger in Greenwich, Ralph Lauren,
Michael Crichton and George Soros in Bedford _ all of whom recently
built stone walls on their properties _ no doubt craved a similar
privacy. But less famous residents also say that a stone wall
provides security and a je-ne-sais-quoi sense of exclusivity.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Greenwich, every house has a wall,'' Mrs. Heine said. ``And
then next to that, you have a house with a wall and an eagle. Next
to that, you have a house with a wall, an eagle and a flag. The
idea of success is to have a wall.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, aesthetically, they're just beautiful,'' Huniford
said. ``And I think people like the feeling of comfort it gives
them.''
</P>
<P>
   But the cost of the typical stone wall is enough to keep the
chain-link-fence industry alive. Luppino charges from $100,000 to
more than $1 million for a painstakingly jointed, hand-stacked
fieldstone wall, and he has charged one client $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for most masons begin at $20 a cubic foot and can climb
to $100 a cubic foot, depending on the mason's skill, the quality
of the material and the manner in which the wall is assembled.
(Dry-wall construction, in which stones are chiseled, then stacked
without mortar or cement, costs more.)
</P>
<P>
   Multiply that by hundreds or thousands of feet, and the
million-dollar tab doesn't sound so distant. Vincent Camuto, the
chief executive of the Nine West shoe-store chain, spent a little
less than $600,000 building walls on his property in Greenwich _
though his house is in a gated, walled community (the sign at the
front says ``propriete privee'') to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all luxury and lavishness and increasing the value of
your property,'' said Joe Coppola, a Stamford, Conn., mason who
built Camuto's and 500 other stone walls in Greenwich.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Tales of stone-wall hysteria abound. Bill Stanton, a private
investigator hired to get the goods on a Bedford billionaire told
this story:
</P>
<P>
   The billionaire asked a mason to build walls on his property,
instructing the household staff to observe the masons at work. A
day later, he fired the masons and had the servants take over the
job.
</P>
<P>
   When Huniford and Sills wanted to build their wall, they had to
spend six months lobbying Bedford's zoning board because they
wanted to build higher than most.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Megna, the Bedford town building inspector, said that
the reason the town instituted a law on fence height was that the
high stone walls were creating a boxed-in effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Huniford Sills wouldn't have gone through any rigmarole if
they had stuck with the height laws,'' he said, adding that the
size of the wall had become the talk of the town.
</P>
<P>
   Masons have their own analysis of the psychology of
wall-building.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's because when you make money, you like to be in your
own little world,'' Coppola said. ``And these people like to
compete with one another _ who has the nicer curbing or better
coping stones or who has a nicer stone wall.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that's been going on at a feverish pace for the
last four or five years,'' said Dan Ginnel, a Bedford real estate
agent. ``And when someone spends that kind of money, it doesn't
necessarily make a million-dollar differential, but generally they
do add to the overall value. Some walls add far more value.''
</P>
<P>
   Stone-wall fever is spreading. The pop singer Tina Turner took
one look at the Huniford and Sills wall and had to have one of her
own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to Bedford and saw that wall, and I didn't expect it to
be quite that awesome,'' Ms. Turner said. ``I thought, now that's
the wall I want to have!'' Huniford and Sills offered guidance on
the construction of a wall that now surrounds her house in France,
near Nice.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you know, their wall looked so old,'' Ms. Turner said.
``They just don't make things like that anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The decorators must not have told Ms. Turner the insiders'
secret of instantly creating a look of antiquity _ spray the stones
with buttermilk so moss will grow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
