<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7430 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CHINA-2TAKES-     06-19 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CHINA-2TAKES-$ADV21-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 21)  
 CLINTON CHINA TRIP HAS LIGHTS, CAMERA, ACTION. WHERE'S THE SCRIPT?
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ORVILLE SCHELL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner +
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ When President Clinton steps onto Chinese soil this
week, he will be like a famed actor with a vast supporting cast
mounting a stage with a huge audience in attendance, but no real
script.
</P>
<P>
   Whether in his travels he will be able to create a credible
script that will lead to significant new agreements or
understandings will show the measure of his acumen as a leader
known for being able to think on his feet.
</P>
<P>
   While his curious slow-motion travels will help Clinton learn
something about this important and complex country, and while it
will certainly win favor in Beijing, it will also raise
expectations at home that something of consequence should result.
</P>
<P>
   But ticking through the list of issues that divide the two
nations _ Taiwan's status, Tibetan autonomy, Hong Kong's
democratization, human rights, intellectual property rights,
China's admission to the World Trade Organization, the
proliferation of missile and nuclear technology and the targeting
of nuclear warheads _ it is hard to discern where major agreements
could come.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, given the uniquely ritualized way in which Chinese
leaders have embargoed sensitive issues from serious discussion
with outsiders _ lest they appear to be caving in to foreign
pressure _ it is not likely that the president will be able to get
a glove on much of substance.
</P>
<P>
   The most promising areas of concord for the United States are in
the missile technology and nuclear proliferation field _ although
past agreements and understandings have not proven particularly
durable.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, the Chinese do have a script, and it involves
acting out a drama in which the president of the United States
journeys all the way to China, much as ``tribute missions'' from
abroad used to visit the Forbidden City to make offerings to the
emperor.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will appear beside President Jiang Zemin in Tiananmen
Square, site of the 1989 crackdown against student protests, as a
sanctifying force for the Chinese Communist Party's post-Deng
Xiaoping leadership, as if to acknowledge China as a great nation
and to say, ``All is forgiven.''
</P>
<P>
   For China, the photo-op and the appearance of uncritical
acceptance are enough. Words hardly need be spoken, and agreements
will be bothersome details that might cause the appearance of
unalloyed mutual respect and unity to be tarnished.
</P>
<P>
   One of Clinton's problems is that Congress is in a state of
virtual warfare with Beijing over everything from satellite deals
and campaign contributions to religious persecution and other human
rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Further, because of its still-unrepudiated Maoist past, many
Americans still feel an uneasiness about the prospect of a powerful
China acting out on the world stage. Many also appear to feel a
certain ambivalence at the prospect of their president sanctifying
a regime that is so stubbornly resistant to reassessing its
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   China's real problems are shaping up as ones with which the
United States is ill-equipped to help or hinder. Most important is
the deepening Asian economic meltdown and how it might catalyze
dangerous social and political tensions within China itself.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, China has managed to remain almost miraculously
aloof from the Asian meltdown. But as Japan's crisis has deepened
and as troops backed by tanks and armored personnel carriers
entered Djakarta, Indonesia, last month, the world was left
wondering how China can continue to dodge the bullet.
</P>
<P>
   After all, China shares many of the same characteristics that
have led Indonesia to the brink: a poorly regulated but dynamic
economy, an autocracy that daily violates its people's rights; a
press controlled by the state; an economic system that is opaque,
nepotistic and steeped in cronyism and corruption; a poor
underclass menaced by rising unemployment; and a banking system and
financial markets that are poorly developed, inadequately regulated
and subject to wanton manipulation by elites.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important, the political legitimacy for both the
Chinese and Indonesian governments has been derived not from an
electorate or a credible political system, but almost exclusively
from their abilities to maintain high rates of economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   On this front, Asia is now delivering some ominous news. Japan
is officially in recession. The plunging yen has even caused the
governor of the People's Bank of China, Dai Xianglong, to worry out
loud that its depreciation will have ``a very unfavorable effect on
China's exports and ability to attract foreign investment.''
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong is suddenly showing negative growth rates, its stock
market keeps breaking new lows, and increased pressure on the ``the
peg,'' which backs its currency at a fixed U.S. dollar rate and
provides one of the few firm points of reference in the whole Asian
imbroglio, is making everyone nervous.
</P>
<P>
   In reaction to all this bad news, rumors have abounded that
China may have to devalue its currency, and equity markets
throughout Asia have gone into a further nosedive. ``It's a
bloodbath out there,'' declared Patrick Crammond, director of
equity capital markets for Credit Suisse First Boston.
</P>
<P>
   So far, China has eluded this maelstrom because of its
relatively strong economic position vis-a-vis the rest of the world
and because enough of its old Maoist autarky has remained intact to
keep it somewhat insulated from the unpredictable and dangerous
flows of global capital that have led to collapse elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   It has prudently kept its foreign debt low, roughly equivalent
with its foreign exchange reserves. Instead of being seduced like
other Asian nations into borrowing large amounts of short-term
capital from overseas banks, it has sought its foreign capital in
direct long-term investments.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As a result, it is not now subject to the repayment crunches
facing so many of its neighbors. And because its financial markets
are still relatively small, panicked foreign investors fleeing
other Asian markets have not had the same destabilizing effect on
China.
</P>
<P>
   The non-convertibility of Chinese currency has also proven a
blessing, because international currency speculators have not been
able to attack it as they have in Malaysia, Thailand and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, China's top leadership, now relatively stable, will
gather added sovereignty in the eyes of its own people as a result
of Clinton's visit _ even if he does engage in some plain talk on
human rights, which will certainly be censored in local reports.
</P>
<P>
   But China is nonetheless in jeopardy. Wariness about Asia's
economic future has already begun to squeeze the economy. Whereas
in 1993 its growth rate was 14 percent, before slipping to a more
reasonable 8.8 percent by 1997, it now hovers around 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   With the yen falling against the dollar and other Asian
currencies in sharp decline, it will become increasingly difficult
for Chinese products to compete in overseas markets. Indeed,
exports _ an important engine of China's technological development
and economic growth _ fell in May for the first time in two years.
</P>
<P>
   Should growth rates continue to decelerate, the nation will have
more difficulty providing jobs for the 6.5 percent of its workforce
that the government now acknowledges as unemployed _ the highest
official rate since 1949.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does that rate account for the 12 million to 15 million who
enter the job market each year; the millions of state workers who
have already been ``sidelined'' at a fraction of their normal
salaries, or the massive ``floating population'' of more than 100
million who have left their villages to seek manual labor in the
cities.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the troubling fact that numerous outbursts of
protest involving disgruntled workers and peasants have already
erupted.
</P>
<P>
   ``If such demonstrations were to assume a political character,''
warned the World Bank's East Asian and Pacific region senior
adviser, Pieter Bottelier, ``they could become dangerous to
stability beyond the immediate area where they occur.''
</P>
<P>
   Still to come are the tens of millions of older workers slated
to lose their jobs as money-losing state-owned enterprises (SOEs)
are closed as part of Premier Zhu Rongji's ambitious program of
reform. The only thing still keeping SOEs alive are state banks,
which are used like giant cash registers to keep these unproductive
industries solvent so that angry workers don't take to the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Lardy, a Brookings Institution economist, believes that
these banks present ``the most serious threat to macroeconomic
stability in China.''
</P>
<P>
   The recent focus of the Chinese people on economics has left
them notably indifferent to politics, but it may not take long for
economic problems to begin manifesting themselves as political
disaffection.
</P>
<P>
   Recent events in Indonesia remind us that as long as the economy
is moving onward and upward, ordinary people can accept many
indignities. When economic growth begins to falter, however, things
can turn political very rapidly. Unless there are other sources of
political legitimization, leaderships can fall with astonishing
suddenness.
</P>
<P>
   China is paradoxically both more fortified and more vulnerable
to the highly contagious economic flu now deepening in Asia. But in
the last few weeks, its privileged isolation has begun to look
increasingly precarious.
</P>
<P>
   It is into this very complex situation that President Clinton is
now heading.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the West has unrealistically viewed China in
extreme terms, as either ``the sick man of Asia or the ``economic
miracle'' maker. Clinton has done well not to repeat this error and
to stay ``engaged,'' even as the relationship became bedeviled with
some very prickly issues.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of his historic trip, Americans would do well to
remember how Deng Xiaoping surprised almost everyone by navigating
his country away from the apocalypse of Tiananmen Square and how
economic czar Zhu Rongji astutely steered it past other treacherous
shoals to revive its economy.
</P>
<P>
   But China's leaders now confront a challenge in which external
and internal problems may combine to end this period of high growth
and optimism. If the protective bulwark that has shielded the
country from economic turmoil is in fact now in jeopardy, one can
understand why the Beijing leadership is seeking whatever outside
legitimization it can find.
</P>
<P>
   But, of course, Clinton is not the pope, whose job it is to go
around the world sanctifying branches of the Catholic Church. His
job is to represent American interests. One of those interests is
to help promote stability in the world _ not by supporting every
status-quo regime, but rather by bolstering those governments whose
legitimacy comes from more than just their ability to promote
bursts of economic growth. As we are beginning to see in Asia,
while government is eternal, boom years tend to be cyclical.
</P>
<P>
   As recent events in Indonesia suggest, autocracies become
vulnerable when economic push comes to shove. It would be a pity if
Clinton's 1998 grand tour of China were to be remembered more as a
photo op than as a time when he spoke the truth about the
interrelation between free markets, the democratic process and
stability.
</P>
<P>
   There is an expression in Chinese _ tongchuang yimeng, or
``sleeping in the same bed but dreaming different dreams.'' It is
an apt description of the way the Sino-U.S. summit seems to be
shaping up.
</P>
<P>
   (Orville Schell, the dean of the Graduate School of Journalism
at UC-Berkeley, is the author of numerous books on China, including
``Mandate of Heaven'' and the forthcoming ``Virtual Tibet.'')
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
