s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARS-SOMMELIER-$ADV2     06-19 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARS-SOMMELIER-$ADV21-ART-685(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINE THERAPIST TO THE STARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 21)  
(lb) 
 By MELINA GEROSA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Christian Navarro has a talent that money can buy. When the
emptied, upended wine bottles rattled around in the ice bucket at
Table 90 at a charity gala in New York last month, the millionaires
seated in a circle turned to Navarro, their guest, to replenish the
supply. The pressure was on.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in a black Gucci suit with his jet-black hair waxed to
porcupine perfection, Navarro slid his finger down the wine list
with more cool than Jon Bon Jovi was managing onstage. Moments
later, a Mondavi 1994 cabernet sauvignon and a 1996 chardonnay
arrived. Not exotic choices, but given the limits of the New York
Hilton and Tower's cellar, even Piero Selvaggio _ whose Los Angeles
restaurant Valentino won a James Beard award for best wine service
in 1994 _ nodded approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christian's one of the most knowledgeable people about wine
I've ever met,'' said Emiel Petrone, executive vice president of
Philips Entertainment Group and Table 90's host at the gala, a
benefit for the T.J. Martell Foundation. ``He has knowledge beyond
his years.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Eagles want to party, when President Clinton is coming
to dinner or when Tom Cruise craves his favorite burgundy (1985
Domaine de la Romanee Conti), Navarro, 31, a partner in Wally's
Wine Shop in Los Angeles, is the man who often gets called. He is a
high-school dropout, who rose from sales clerk to self-taught
enophile to sommelier to the stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christian has built the most significant Hollywood base for
wine and spirits in the industry,'' said James Orr, a screenwriter
(``Three Men and a Baby''). ``He's a wine therapist. He listens to
what you want, and then he makes gentle recommendations. He has a
way of handling people so that they don't even know that they are
being handled.''
</P>
<P>
   Orr, who spends $75,000 a year to replenish his 4,000-bottle
cellar, has been a client of Navarro for eight years. He has
referred budding enophile friends, like Courtney Cox, Farrah
Fawcett and the producer Jack Rapke, to Navarro for just as long.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's my guru,'' said Rapke, who first called Navarro five
years ago, when he was co-chairman of Creative Artists Agency. ``I
used him to send gifts to a lot of very visible and not-so-visible
people. Then I asked him to help me start my own cellar, and we've
been working together ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Creative Artist agents, like Michael Ovitz, the former
chairman, followed Rapke's lead. ``It got to a point where Mike
Ovitz would say, `I need to send something to Tom and Nicole.' And
I would say, `I know exactly what they like,''' Navarro said with
the cocksureness of a Tom Cruise character. ``And then Tom would
call Mike and say, `How did you know we love this wine?'''
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz didn't know. But Navarro did, having developed a
meticulous list of preferences of 2,000 wine and spirits drinkers,
from Jack Nicholson to Jackie Chan. He does his homework.
</P>
<P>
   ``You call their assistants,'' he said. ``You call the people
who have worked with them. Anyone's secretary can send a bottle of
Dom, but when you send someone their exact, favorite wine, they
think you really thought about it. They don't know that I'm in the
middle, the guy behind the scenes,'' he said, flashing a gleaming,
gaptoothed grin.
</P>
<P>
   Navarro is careful to make his clients look good by including
personalized histories with the wines he sells them. ``This one
agent will have all these stars at his dinner, and he'll stand up
and say, `This particular wine, which I pulled out from my cellar,
was founded in the 1800s,''' Navarro said. ``He'll tell a whole
story about it, reading off of my little cheat sheet.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the celebrities started coming in themselves.
Michael Keaton drops into Wally's to chat about red Provencales and
pick up a few bottles of Mas de Gourgonnier for his home in
Montana. Out-of-town deliveries are no problem. Navarro shipped
Robert De Niro's favorite tequila, Petron, to him on faraway sets.
``Let's say he's shooting a picture in Paris,'' Navarro said. ``I
get it there. When Emilio Estevez finished a movie in Spain, I sent
him wine to give as gifts.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But Hollywood is only part of it. Navarro is also a consultant
to captains of finance. ``I started meeting the Wall Street guys,''
he said. ``Like the Hollywood guys, one would lead to another and
another.''
</P>
<P>
   Eli Broad, chairman of Sun America, the financial-services
company, seeks Navarro's advice for the Democratic Party
fund-raisers he holds at his palatial home in Brentwood, Calif.
``I'm not a great connoisseur, but I'm a client because I trust his
taste,'' said Broad, whose latest event raised $1.2 million for
House Democrats last month. The guests included Clinton, Michael
Douglas, Oliver Stone and Quincy Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was $10,000 a couple, so I couldn't serve cheap wine, but
on the other hand, I didn't want to spend a lot of money,'' Broad
said. Navarro chose a 1995 Patz &AMP; Hall chardonnay at $30 a bottle.
Did the president comment on the selection? ``Not extensively,''
Broad said. ``He doesn't drink a lot of wine. But he likes white,
and he said it was good, or something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The most money, Navarro said, is spent on private parties for
rock stars and law firms. For the 1995 wedding of Don Henley of the
Eagles, 140 bottles of Krug Clos du Mesnil champagne, at $200 each,
and 120 bottles of Zonchera Barolo, an Italian red wine, at $40
each, were ordered for the four-day festivities. ``The sky was the
limit,'' Navarro noted.
</P>
<P>
   Although Navarro is quick to drop the names and expenditures of
his famous clients, he is more reticent when it comes to his own
financial data. His income, which includes a salary as well as an
ownership interest in Wally's, adds up to ``a fair amount,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   A typical day for him consists of a restaurant lunch, a couple
of house calls to clients assembling wine cellars, and fielding 40
or 50 phone calls. Sometimes he is called to the cellars of
divorcing clients _ a duty he dreads. ``When the wine appreciates,
sometimes you're talking a couple million dollars,'' he said, ``and
to have both parties arguing over each bottle, with me trying to
give the pros and cons of each one, that's ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   Long before he learned the art of cellar mediation, Navarro's
talent was apparent. ``As a little kid, I used to smell everything
on the table, from the fork to the foods to the napkins,'' he said.
``My mother was always saying, `Put that down!'''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Mexico City and brought up in Palm Springs, Calif.,
Navarro spent his youth tagging along with his mother, a restaurant
and hotel consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``She would basically turn me loose in the kitchens,'' he said.
His first sip of wine came at the age of 10. ``I thought it was
grape juice, so I was shocked at the acids and mutated fruit
qualities,'' he said. His taste buds may have revolted, but his
nose found a favorite new forum. ``The cellar masters would ask me
to smell the different wines and I would say, `It smells like
smoke,' or roast beef, or whatever,'' he recalled. ``It became a
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Navarro dropped out of high school in 10th grade to travel in
Europe. He returned after a year and a half, settling in Los
Angeles, where he worked stocking shelves at the Wine House, a
retail shop.
</P>
<P>
   He read books on wine, peppered his colleagues with questions
and, after five years, took a growing list of his own clients to
Wally's Wine Shop on Westwood Boulevard. That same year, 1992,
fittingly for a Hollywood tale, he got a big break. When his boss,
Steve Wallace, became sick and couldn't make it to a tasting of
rare 19th-century wines by 40 distinguished enophiles, Navarro went
in his place. ``I was now on the fast track,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, the majority owner of Wally's, said of Navarro, ``He's
our Michael Jordan.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of his nose?
</P>
<P>
   Wallace laughed. ``It has more to do with smelling out
customers,'' he said. ``He knows wine, but it's really about the
service. He carries a pager and a phone, and no matter where he is
in the world, he's obtainable. We'll be out of the country on a
buying trip, and he'll constantly be on the phone to the States,
calling back Eli Broad or Michael Douglas or whoever. He's always
following up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
