</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-DROUGHT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FARMS, RANCHES LOSE MORE THAN $500 MILLION AFTER MONTHS WITHOUT
ENOUGH RAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WORTH WREN JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The intense dry spell that has gripped most
of Texas for two months has created a corn, grain sorghum and
cotton disaster in parts of the state, agriculture officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Agricultural Extension Service estimates that
weather-related losses statewide already have cut farm and ranch
income by more than $500 million this year, and the losses will
likely mount. Typically, agricultural income in Texas ranges from
$13 billion to $15 billion annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``The corn already is pretty well lost,'' said Bob Beakley, a
29-year farming veteran who has watched his 2,000 acres of corn
near Ennis wilt under the sun and hot winds since April.
</P>
<P>
   Beakley and his son, Steven, also raise cotton, wheat and
soybeans in southern Ellis County. He says they've lost more than
70 percent of their corn crop. And they say their 2,200 acres of
cotton and 800 acres of soybeans are ``on the cusp'' of disaster,
although their 800 acres of wheat produced above-average yields in
the recent harvest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cotton still has a little way to go,'' Bob Beakley said,
adding that a soaking rain within a couple of weeks during the
current crucial growth stage ``might revive the cotton to nearly
100 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   The extension service says farmers in Central and South Texas
stand to lose $150 million on corn and grain sorghum.
</P>
<P>
   Although spotty rains have offered relief in some areas, the big
losses are hitting most farmers without irrigation from the
southern fringes of the Metroplex to Mexico, and southeast and west
across most of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have stalks that don't have ears and ears that don't have
kernels,'' said Gary Stanford, the Ellis County agricultural
extension agent. He estimated an 80 percent loss of corn production
potential on more than 40,000 acres countywide, but he still
offered hope for a good cotton yield.
</P>
<P>
   ``The window has not closed on a cotton crop, yet,'' Stanford
said. But projected cotton losses across Central and South Texas
are already topping $150 million, the extension service reported.
</P>
<P>
   In Northwest Texas, where more than half the state's cotton is
planted, cotton and grain crops remain in earlier growth stages,
and losses have not been estimated.
</P>
<P>
   Tarrant County farmers and ranchers have had more rain and are
faring better than their counterparts in many other areas, but they
also urgently need more rain, said John South, the county's
agricultural agent.
</P>
<P>
   Beakley said the rainfall has been unusual this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had El Nino all winter, giving us roughly twice the average
rainfall we normally get in December, January and February,''
Beakley said. ``March was probably about normal. April, he shut
off, and we didn't show a measurable drop of rainfall in May.''
</P>
<P>
   June hasn't been any better in most areas.
</P>
<P>
   Even the grasshoppers are getting picky about the parched corn,
which now stands 5 to 7 feet high when it should be about 10 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The corn got dry like Post Toasties, and the grasshoppers
left,'' Stanford said.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, many North Texans are reporting waves of grasshoppers
chomping flowers and devouring leaves on shrubs, vegetables, trees
and even some cotton and grain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been here 26 years, and I've never seen 'em this bad
before,'' said Bill Buxkemper, the Hill County agricultural
extension agent whose Hillsboro phone has been swamped with calls
about grasshoppers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ironically,'' Buxkemper said, echoing a regional view, ``we're
coming off the best wheat crop we've ever made.''
</P>
<P>
   But the region's hay harvest cuttings are now also dwindling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ain't raising much of anything this year,'' said Sammy
Hutcheson, a Grandview-area farmer. He said the heat and the
grasshoppers have swiped more than half of his normal hay,
cantaloupe, tomato, black-eyed pea, onion and other vegetable
crops.
</P>
<P>
   Cattle ranchers in some areas are beginning to cull or consider
culling a greater-than-normal portion of their cattle as pasture
grasses weaken and hay prices rise.
</P>
<P>
   Dairy farmers, already in a price squeeze that has idled about
30 percent of the milk-producing farms in Texas since Jan. 1, 1995,
are seeing their forage costs rising.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're now feeding as much hay as we expect to do in the
winter,'' said Peggy Van Zandt, who farms with her husband, Ray Van
Zandt, between Grandview and Cleburne in Johnson County. The farm
is buying more hay at higher prices _ spending twice as much as it
did last year.
</P>
<P>
   Van Zandt Dairy normally grows enough pasture grasses to cover
the cows' forage needs at this time of year, and it normally raises
50 percent of the cows' winter hay needs, Peggy Van Zandt said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a lack of moisture, she said, the farm is failing to
deliver on both those forage fronts.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
