<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Friday, June 19. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Hank Warnken (212-556-1927).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-COCA-HERBICIDE (Bogota, Colombia) _ The Colombian
gGovernment, bowing to demands from anti-narcotics officials in
Washington, has agreed to test a granular herbicide to kill coca
crops, despite public warnings from the chemical's American
manufacturer against its use in Colombia. In the United States, the
herbicide, tebuthiuron, is used mostly to control weeds in areas
like railroad beds and under high-voltage lines far away from food
crops and people. The Environmental Protection Agency requires a
warning label on the chemical that says it could cause groundwater
contamination something Colombian environmental officials fear
could prevent peasants from growing food where coca once grew. By
Diana Jean Schemo. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KASHMIR-WEDDING-DEAD (New Delhi) _ In one of the worst attacks
on Hindu civilians in nine years of war in Kashmir, 25 men taking
part in wedding parties were killed today by gunmen armed with
automatic weapons. By John F. Burns.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-CAMPAIGN (Washington) _ In a significant test of
strength, the coalition supporting bipartisan legislation to
overhaul the campaign finance law won a series of House votes today
and drew an unexpectedly large number of Republicans to its side.
On one key test, 65 Republicans voted to preserve the legislation
sponsored by Reps. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., and Martin Meehan,
D-Mass. The bill is one of a dozen proposals up for consideration
in a free-for-all over the campaign finance laws. By Alison
Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI-CORRUPT (Miami) _ Bribery. Kickbacks. Voter fraud.
Cover-up. Even as law enforcement officials promise more arrests,
the city of Miami is now engulfed in a series of high-profile
investigations that have uncovered a wave of such pervasive public
corruption it is now often mentioned in the same breath as New York
during the so-called city scandals and Chicago during the heyday of
the Democratic machine. By Mireya Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   VIAGRA-INSURANCE (Undated) _ Kaiser Permanente, the nation's
largest health maintenance organization, will not cover patients'
costs for impotence drug Viagra because it would be too expensive.
By Milt Freudenheim.
</P>
<P>
   PRESBY-GUNS (Undated) Striking an unsually personal note in the
national debate on gun control, the top policy-making body of the
Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.) has passed a resolution calling on the
denomination's 2.6 million members to ``work toward removing
handguns and assault weapons'' from their homes and communities.
Presbyterian officials and other church leaders said the assembly's
resolution takes a new tack in asking directly for individual
action by church members, rather than seeking governmental
legislation. By Gustav Niebuhr. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SWISS-GOLD-HOLOCAUST (Washington) _ Switzerland's three biggest
commercial banks today made a public offer of $600 million to
settle claims from Holocaust victims who have charged that their
family assetts were stolen. Jewish leaders immediately rejected the
offer as ``humiliating,'' and said negotations had broken down. By
David E. Sanger.
</P>
</TEXT>
