<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BATTERED-GAYS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO CONSIDERS SHELTER FOR BATTERED GAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL NESS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A city supervisor wants to provide shelter for
gay men who are battered by their partners, and if the ordinance is
approved, it would make San Francisco the first city in the nation
to offer such services.
</P>
<P>
   Although the city has long assisted three women's shelters,
there has never been a safe place for homosexual men fleeing
domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Mark Leno proposed Thursday giving $37,000 to
Community United Against Violence to expand its counseling, legal
and shelter programs for same-sex victims of abuse in the home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today San Francisco will make history by committing itself to
having the only domestic violence shelter for gay men,'' Leno said.
He said the proposal has support from the Board of Supervisors,
which currently is divvying up the 1998-99 city budget.
</P>
<P>
   The plan doesn't envision a new shelter. Instead, it would pay
for four beds in an existing shelter for homeless men.
</P>
<P>
   The $37,000 also would allow Community United Against Violence
to add a part-time advocate to help both gay men and lesbians
escaping from violent homes to get legal protection and make the
transition to a more stable life.
</P>
<P>
   And it would fund one-time grants so domestic violence victims
to set up a new household.
</P>
<P>
   The need is undeniable, according to Leno and San Francisco
District Attorney Terence Hallinan, who last year stepped up his
office's response to domestic violence and made a special effort to
reach out to gays and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   Studies suggest that homosexual couples experience domestic
violence at the same rate as straight couples, but only recently
has the gay community started to bring the problem to light.
</P>
<P>
   Community United's crisis hot line gets calls from 400 people a
year _ two-thirds of them gay men _ seeking help with abusive
partners. On average, 50 need emergency shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Lesbians who are victims of abuse from partners can move into
the women's shelters, if there is room, but ``right now the men
have no place to go,'' said Jeff Sheehy, an advocate for same-sex
victims in Hallinan's office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 1642EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980619.0204 </DOCNO>
