<DOCNO> NYT19980619.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7505 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BC-MICROSOFT-CULTURE-     06-19 1590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-MICROSOFT-CULTURE-COX-$ADV2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GATES' ELITE CREW ENTERS THE SPOTLIGHT: MICROSOFTIES OR
MICROSERFS?
 &HT;    1170&AMP;add; moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories
for release Sunday, June 21.
 &HT;    Photos for this story are available from the New York Times News
Service.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ Perched on a high stool, Steve Ballmer, the
hard-charging super-salesman who serves as Bill Gates's right-hand
man, pounds one fist into his palm when he is asked to describe the
forces that shape Microsoft's corporate culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to tell your people to play to win,'' Ballmer
replies. ``You can't satisfy customers if you don't have any.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft critics say it's that kind of take-no-prisoners
competitive drive that last month entangled the software giant in
federal and state antitrust suits. But for the executive vice
president and his co-workers, spread out among 36 highly secure
sites here on the Microsoft campus, the case brought by the Justice
Department fails to compute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, this is a time of great distractions,'' Ballmer
concedes. ``But we're putting our heads down and we're doing our
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, that thing is Thursday's rollout of the Windows
98 upgraded operating system for personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   In a landmark case set for trial in early September, the federal
trust-busters charge that Microsoft Corp. has gone too far in
blending its Internet browser with Windows 98, allegedly seeking to
leverage its near-monopoly in the digital code that runs personal
computers into another monopoly in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our biggest threat does not come from the government,''
Ballmer says, dismissing the suit with a wave of his hand. ``The
real danger we face is falling out of touch with our customers. And
our customers want products that work together. They see all that
(integration) stuff in a beneficial way. It means that Microsoft is
doing what otherwise customers would have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But the bundling practices of which Ballmer boasts are widely
seen as predatory by Microsoft critics and industry rivals. The
company makes no apology for using Windows to attain commanding
positions in new markets, such as interactive TV and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Rivals say Microsoft's true aim is not to create new products
but rather to co-opt ideas and products developed by other firms,
such as the Netscape Navigator browser, and cobble all of them into
Windows. If Microsoft stays on this path, such features as speech
recognition, database searching and language translation are likely
to appear in future Windows releases.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, trustbusters have had limited success in curbing such
tactics. One notable exception: In 1995, Microsoft was obliged to
abandon its $2 billion acquisition of Intuit, maker of the leading
financial software Quicken, after the Justice Department threatened
to file suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cyberspace may indeed offer the potential of untold consumer
choice _ if nobody gains a stranglehold,'' said Robert Kuttner, a
co-editor of American Prospect. ``But what Gates is attempting is
as old as the efforts to monopolize the steel, rail, oil, and
telephone industries in the robber baron era.''
</P>
<P>
   Such viewpoints are hotly contested here. ``Intellectual
property is not a scarce natural resource as is oil,'' said
Microsoft spokesman Greg Shaw. ``The barriers to entry in the
software industry are quite low.''
</P>
<P>
   In hiring and retaining the developers who wrote, tested and
debugged some 4 million lines of code that went into the design of
Windows 98, the company has cultivated a distinctly elitist image.
</P>
<P>
   A recruiting pitch that Gates helped draft reads: ``Microsoft
people are part brainiacs, part free-spirited individualists, and
100 percent passionate about technology. Here you're encouraged not
only to speak what's on your mind, but also to do it. You'll find a
place where anything can happen and most often does.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, there is a a defensive tone in the recruiting
message that appears on the Microsoft Web site:
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, you've heard the rumors. You have to give up your life.
We've grown so big that you could never make a difference. It rains
here. Okay, that's no rumor. But have you heard about the kind of
passion you can feel simply walking down any hallway? Or the
freedom to jump from one hot technology and one opportunity to
another, backed by the kind of resources unheard of anywhere else?
Or all the breakthrough products that could only have come from the
creative chemistry of brilliant minds?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsofties,'' as company employees invariably refer to
themselves, have some of the lowest turnover rates in the industry.
Corporate rivals in California's Silicon Valley _ where job hopping
is common _ scornfully refer to Gates's crew as ``microserfs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft at its core highly values intelligence,'' says Scott
Langmack, who joined up 30 months ago to head Microsoft's extensive
technical support effort, leaving a higher-paid and more
prestigious marketing position at Pepsi-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a tremendous positive input all the time from Bill
(Gates) on down, Langmack adds. ``There's some magic about working
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft moved from downtown Seattle to the Redmond campus in
1986, the same year its stock went public. Since then, new
construction at the 296-acre site has virtually never ceased.
Computerized ID cards are needed to enter every building. Access to
the most sensitive units, where the leading-edge development work
goes forward, is highly restricted even for longtime Microsoft
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Gates and Ballmer, both 42, rank among the most elderly members
of Microsoft's 17,000-member domestic employee pool. Nearly a third
of the firm's workers are 29 or younger, and more than half of them
are between 30 and 39, with the average age 34.4 years.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever their ages, the dress code on campus is uniformly
casual, a custom that harkens back to the company's founding in
1975, when Gates would at times fall asleep on the floor after an
intense all-night bout of code-writing on the relatively primitive
computers of that era.
</P>
<P>
   The Microsoft crew often punctuates code-writing and
brainstorming sessions with pickup games of basketball, volleyball
or soccer on a dozen playing fields scattered among the highly
functional campus buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever it rains, as it often does here, workers on breaks
repair to state-of-the art video game machines that stand near the
row upon row of modestly-sized cubicles where nearly everyone _
including the peripatetic Gates _ puts in long, if flexibly
structured, workdays.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our products that define our culture,'' said Jeff Raikes,
Microsoft's vice president for sales and marketing, who was reared
on a farm in Nebraska and who ``started working with Bill,'' as he
puts it, 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a cool business,'' Raikes added. ``I'm spending more
time on public relations work with people like you because of the
antitrust suit. But we're doing what our customers say they want us
to do. And we'll be spending $2.6 billion on research and
development this year to make sure we're not left behind after
we've pushed Windows 98 out the door.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   For the debut of Windows 98, Ballmer's marketers have crafted a
metaphor: If high technology travels down an open road of
innovation, then Windows 98 will be that major thoroughfare. The
updated operating system will be advertised with ``Route 98''
signs.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Dataquest, a leading independent analyst of software
trends for personal computers, estimated that Windows 98 upgrade
shipments will total 5.5 million units this year. By 1999,
Dataquest projects, Microsoft will enjoy a 95 percent share in
operating system shipments for all computers throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to reflect on how Microsoft has changed since he accepted
Gates's offer in 1980 to join the company, Ballmer said: ``We're
still into software for microprocessors, if that's what you mean.
Everything else has changed. But, you know, the culture hasn't
really changed in those 18 years. In fact, I'm struck by how
similar the place is to the time when I got here and we had only 27
employees.''
</P>
<P>
   From a financial standpoint, Microsoft's growth in the
intervening years has been good to Ballmer. Last year, averaging
65-hour work weeks, often on the road, he earned $587,000 in salary
and bonuses. At current market values, Ballmer's Microsoft stock is
worth around $11 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In the Microsoft wealth sweepstakes, that places him second only
to Gates, a former Harvard chum who has become the world's richest
man, and Microsoft co-founder Paul Allen, 45, who left the company
in 1982 and whose remaining stock holdings in the software firm are
now worth about $17 billion.
</P>
<P>
   These high valuations have had an impact on how Microsoft is
viewed inside the company, within the industry and in the world at
large.
</P>
<P>
   More than 120 sites on the World Wide Web are devoted to bashing
Gates, often using the technology Microsoft sells and, in the case
of the Internet Explorer browser, gives away. Among them is a
``Bill Gates Personal Wealth Clock,'' which changes with the price
of Microsoft stock and which currently stands at about $52 billion.
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
