s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOT-ITEMS-$ADV21-NYT &LR;      06-19 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOT-ITEMS-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOT ITEMS: FLESH-COLORED SWIMWEAR, MAIL-ORDER COSMETICS, SEWING
CIRCLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 21)  
 (bl)  
 By CHRISTINE MUHLKE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Swimming in the Bluff
</P>
<P>
   At last it is possible to explore your nudist fantasies without
alarming fellow bathers. Rachel Crespin has created a flesh-toned
line of swimwear that makes beach bums look, well, naked. The suits
come in skin-matching shades for every ethnic group and in styles
ranging from string bikinis to this summer's popular one-shoulder
look.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Crespin, a former fashion editor at Harper's Bazaar and
Vogue, got the idea a couple of years ago when she was visiting
friends upstate. ``I went to meet my boyfriend at the pool in
Woodstock, and everyone looked so golden and glowing,'' she said.
``As I got closer, I realized they were naked. I was so impressed!
I thought, wouldn't it be funny if . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Funny and sexy enough for Sports Illustrated to put the
almost-birthday suits in its swimsuit issue.
</P>
<P>
   Available by phone at (212) 355-7577 until Aug. 1 and at Saks
Fifth Avenue after that.
</P>
<P>
   Bigelow Goes Postal
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Frustrated because your drugstore doesn't stock
garlic shampoo or J. Pickles hard-skin ointment? No worries. C.O.
Bigelow, the New York apothecary famous for its international
health and beauty products, is introducing a mail-order catalogue,
(800) 793-5433.
</P>
<P>
   After 160 years, the pharmacy at 414 Avenue of the Americas
(Ninth Street), where Mark Twain once filled prescriptions, is
offering by mail its ``apothecariana'': Portuguese soaps, T.
LeClerc powder, Boiron Camilia teething remedy. The catalogue was
created by popular demand when magazines, from Crain's New York
Business to Allure, cited Bigelow as a resource.
</P>
<P>
   ``People started calling, and we didn't know what to do with
them,'' Ian Ginsberg, an owner, said. ``We live in the best city in
the world, and we take it for granted that we can get sage-leaf
toothpaste. This catalogue helps us get it to the rest of
America.''
</P>
<P>
   Sewing Circles
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tailored to a generation that can barely open a hotel
emergency sewing kit, Sew Fast Sew Easy at 147 W. 57th St. is a
school for needle dummies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to give back the techniques I learned from experts in
the fashion industry to these creative women who are rent-broke
with Prada taste,'' said Elissa Meyrich, a former sportswear
designer who opened the school in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Dancers, artists, lawyers _ mostly women, ranging in age from 14
to 35 _ enroll to learn about making clothes to custom-fit their
style, budgets and bodies. A single three-hour class teaches how to
stitch up a chic nylon tote or crochet an evening bag (three nights
for a bikini). After four classes, even beginners can make a simple
skirt.
</P>
<P>
   Alison Raffaele, a makeup artist, has graduated to the second of
the school's four levels and is hooked. ``I watch stylists fit
clothes all day with pins and clips, so I see that when clothes
really fit, they look a thousand times better,'' she said. ``The
skirt I made fits like a glove and looks expensive. I feel like a
Holly Hobby for the '90s.''
</P>
<P>
   A Shady Deal on Guccis
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Downtowners who wouldn't be caught dead toting Louis
Vuitton knockoffs are embracing the newest Canal Street tourist
fodder: fake Gucci sunglasses. For $10 a pair (up to $170 less than
the real Gucci glasses), thrifty logo-maniacs are grabbing up
flashy pairs of brightly hued shades with gold interlocking G's a
la Lil' Kim, and the more authentic-looking Audrey Hepburn styles,
in black or tortoise.
</P>
<P>
   How to spot the phonies? Gucci won't comment for legal reasons.
But Robert Holmes, a fashion detective who sleuths for companies
with trademarks, explained how to identify them. ``A lot of the
counterfeit glasses have a gold G glued to them, which can be
popped off, and lettering that can be scratched off,'' he said.
``Gucci would never do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Uptown table vendors will try to pawn the glasses off as real,
Holmes said, while in Chinatown they assume buyers don't care if
they're fakes. Tom Sachs, an artist, keeps a pair for female
passengers on his Vespa. ``The great thing about buying them for
$10 is that when they go out of fashion, the sting isn't as hard,''
he said. ``The bad thing is you have to buy them four times because
they break.''
</P>
<P>
   Moody Hues
</P>
<P>
   Madonna and Naomi Campbell are women who are letting their
fingers do the talking with the first temperature-sensitive nail
polish, Polish Mood Shades. Its maker, Respect, says that each
two-tone polish switches colors as the wearer changes moods.
Bloated Blue becomes Pouty Pink, Gotta Have Chocolate turns to
Estrogen Emerald.
</P>
<P>
   Miranda Darling, a model and a satisfied customer, reported that
the lacquer ``changes color when you talk about boys.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone likes this '90s rendition of the mood ring. A
Dayton Hudson store in Minneapolis recently pulled the polish off
its shelves because employees thought it was demeaning. But Jenai
Lane, Respect's president, said that PMS is meant to take ``the
negative names that women are often called and give them new,
positive meanings.'' ($12, available at 9 &AMP; Co., or from
415-512-8995.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
