<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7521 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FATHERS-DRINKS-$ADV21     06-19 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FATHERS-DRINKS-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIKE FATHER, LIKE SON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 21)  
(lb) 
 By BOB MORRIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   My father never laid a hand on anyone in our home. The abuse he
committed was, instead, of the culinary variety. Growing up, I
would sit across from him at the table, offended to an almost
Oedipal level at his inability to leave my mother's cooking alone.
</P>
<P>
   He'd pour salad dressing on her lovingly prepared lemon chicken
or meatloaf. Then at dessert time, he'd rise from the table to
retrieve a trusty bottle of diet raspberry syrup to pour over
everything else, from Jell-O molds to cobblers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gross,'' I'd mutter.
</P>
<P>
   It never stopped him. If, as the British proverb says, the first
service a child does his father is to make him feel foolish, my
services clearly were not wanted. ``Your father will eat
anything,'' my mother would say. ``Step on his foot, and he opens
his mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   And it wasn't enough for him to enjoy his concoctions alone,
either. Others had to, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was gastronomic assault,'' one cousin recently recalled of
the ginger ale with apricot schnapps that Dad foisted on him. But
that was nothing. In my lifetime, I have seen everything from
coffee with milk and lemon (``very delicate flavor,'' Dad says) to
orange juice on cereal (``low-cholesterol breakfast'').
</P>
<P>
   Like a plumber with his box of tools, Dad travels with packets
in his wallet to improve upon whatever he is served. If my brother,
a formidable wine snob, pours him a serious cabernet or merlot, he
waits till nobody's looking, then sweetens it to taste. When he
isn't creating his delicacies at the table, he's inventing things
late at night, leaving them soaking in empty margarine tubs on the
kitchen counter, like so many science-fair projects.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, he's into soaking strawberries and raisins in
Nutrasweet-ened water. It's a topping of sorts. ``Just taste it,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   I know it won't kill me. I know people eat far stranger things,
like each other, but somehow I can't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not?'' Dad asks. Not long ago, it would have been easy to
tell him why not.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in a world of peach wine coolers and raspberry microbrews,
it's harder. And of course, now that we have orange-flavored
Snapple and orange-flavored Stolichnaya, his habit of pouring
orange juice into tea seems as hip as the half-and-half (half iced
tea and half lemonade) now requested by Hollywood power lunchers.
</P>
<P>
   Is it possible that my father isn't a madman but a futurist in
beverages?
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere between the age of Cool Whip and the age of Olestra,
it seems that the road has risen up to meet him. Like Aldous
Huxley, who accurately foresaw in ``Brave New World'' a society on
anti-depressants, Dad has anticipated a world of Cosmopolitans,
ice-blended mochas and pineapple salsa.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, I even find myself at expense-account lunches ordering
cognac with orange juice or at self-service markets mixing flavored
coffees to taste. The other day, when I didn't have tomato sauce, I
doctored some pasta with vinaigrette dressing and ketchup. My guest
loved it. I felt wickedly invigorated.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a boy of 14,'' Mark Twain wrote, ``my father was so
ignorant I could hardly stand to have the old man around. But when
I got to be 21, I was astonished at how much he had learned in
seven years.''
</P>
<P>
   Same goes for me, I guess. So Dad, now that I'm finally old
enough to know a thing or two, I not only forgive you your culinary
trespasses, I applaud them _ as long as I don't have to taste them.
</P>
<P>
   Happy Father's Day. Here's mud in your eye. And some Nutrasweet,
too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
