<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-CHINA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SAYS NORMAL TRADE WITH CHINA YIELDS JOBS FOR AMERICANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton defended his decision to continue
normal trade ties with China, saying Friday that expanded U.S.
trade with the hard-charging nation of 1.2 billion means jobs for
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, noting a potentially vast market for U.S. products in
China, said the Chinese economy is ``growing _ and the American
people ought to be able to get the benefit of selling to the
Chinese.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke shortly after White House Press Secretary Mike
McCurry took a verbal swipe at congressional critics, including
Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., for opposing Clinton's June 3 request
for a year-long extension of the so-called ``most favored nation''
trading status that has been approved without interruption by four
American presidents since 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton leaves next Wednesday for a 10-day, five-city visit to
China _ the first by an American president since Chinese communist
authorities cracked down on pro-democracy demonstrators in
Tiananmen Square in 1989, leaving between 400 to 800 dead and
hundreds more imprisoned.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that the United States has far deeper disputes with
other nations with which the United States maintains normal trade
ties, known as ``most favored nation'' trading status.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that there is ``no principled, grounded
distinction'' between U.S. trade with China and U.S. trade with a
variety of unnamed nations with which the United States has
``serious disagreements.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton added: ``Keep in mind, we're not asking for anything
special for China here.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, he said ``most people don't respond very well to threats
and to isolation.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton conceded that economic sanctions yielded results in
forcing white-governed South Africa to turn over power to black
South Africans as well in forcing Iraqi compliance with
U.N.-mandated weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
   But China is ``a case where I think we've got far more to gain
with a constructive engagement,'' Clinton said, adding: ``It's a
very great country with enormous potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's spokesman challenged congressional critics, saying
that the Republican Congress has been putting up ``isolationist
blinders'' that potentially imperil American jobs.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said ``a number of members of Congress'' are insisting
``that we should suspend normal trade relations with China _ which
is the thermonuclear device of economic diplomacy.''
</P>
<P>
   To threaten suspension of normal trading ties ``and to use it as
a penalty or to compel certain types of behavior is a very risky
thing to do,'' McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry added that critics who urge an end to normal trade
relations with China ``are exactly those who are favoring
isolationism versus engagement.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi, a San Francisco Democrat, is a leading congressional
critic of administration policies toward China.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Pelosi's contention that China must earn normal
trading status with the United States by honoring human rights,
McCurry replied: ``That is purely and simply an isolationist view.
That is exactly how you isolate China in seeking that.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry added: ``She would isolate China economically by way of
trying to compel different types of behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Pelosi issued a statement saying that when Clinton and
``his people resort to characterizing those who oppose his failed
China policy as isolationist, they couldn't be further from
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi said the U.S. trade deficit with China during the Clinton
presidency will exceed $250 billion by the end of the year. Pelosi
said China continues to sell technology for weapons of mass
destruction to other nations as well as repress human rights in
China and Tibet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has no real progress to show for his failed
China policy,'' Pelosi said.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials say about 120,000 American jobs are
dependent on U.S. trade with China, a nation of 1.2 billion with
one of the fastest growing economies in the world.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will seek to ``create more interest in Congress'' in
expanding economic and political ties with China during the foray
to China, McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress sometimes puts these isolationist blinders up and
they don't see these global problems as being connected to the
livelihoods of American families and the problems they're facing
when they sit around the kitchen table and worry about their
futures,'' McCurry said. ``We have to drive that point home.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry noted America's deepening trade deficit with Asia due to
the inability of faltering Asian economies to import U.S. products
and the ever-cheaper prices of Asian goods in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is all the more reason why we've got to act in a very
disciplined way to address the needs of these economies,'' McCurry
said. ``It really is our livelihoods that are at stake _ not just
theirs. The president will be making that case during his trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress has 90 days to vote to disapprove Clinton's extension
of normal trading status. The House is expected to take the initial
congressional action on Clinton's request after it returns from the
July 4 recess.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department reported on Thursday that the U.S. trade
deficit soared to $14.5 billion in April _ a new record for the
month.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, concerned about the plight of Asian economies, ordered
the purchase of Japanese yen earlier this week in an effort to stem
the declining value of the Japanese currency, a situation that
threatened to escalate the 10-month old Asian crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
