r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-     06-19 1280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAZDA'S REMADE MIATA IMPROVES ORIGINAL ROADSTER
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: Accompanied by CARS-GLANCE) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The old adage ``If it ain't broke, don't fix it'' often applies
to the world of automotive design, which is why Mazda took a real
chance when it remade the popular Miata roadster for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But I have to agree with the gushing publicity material that
Mazda included with the test vehicle I drove last week. By golly,
they did improve the car, and they didn't mess anything up.
</P>
<P>
   This new model still looks like a Miata, but one that apparently
has been working out at the gym in its spare time. Its muscles are
bulging all over, giving it a more masculine appearance.
</P>
<P>
   The hood and fenders have bulges and curves the older model
didn't have, and the sides are more sculpted. Gone are the cute
hideaway headlights, replaced by oval lights on each side of a
larger grille.
</P>
<P>
   The aggressive appearance is designed to bring more male buyers
into the Miata fold. The previous version, which debuted in 1989,
appealed more to women. The new model is less cute and more brute,
which apparently is what men want, Mazda research showed.
</P>
<P>
   I believe the new style is more an answer to the competition
from the equally muscular BMW Z3 than just an attempt to shift to
more male customers. The base Z3 costs just a few thousand dollars
more than a loaded Miata and has more snob appeal.
</P>
<P>
   But thank goodness Mazda didn't jack up the price of the Miata
after restyling it. It's still the only affordable roadster on the
market, with its base price of $19,770.
</P>
<P>
   The engine is slighty more powerful in the new model: 140
horsepower vs. last year's 132. That's due in part to a new
cylinder head for the 1.8-liter four-cylinder engine. It has
larger, straighter intake and exhaust ports for improved air flow.
</P>
<P>
   The extra power really isn't all that noticeable, though. There
is adequate but not impressive acceleration, but power isn't what
the Miata is all about. It's a driver's car, not a racer's, and its
best attributes are its tight, nimble roadhandling and the freedom
that the occupants feel with the top lowered and their hair
whipping in the breeze.
</P>
<P>
   Miata takes curves like it was glued to them, thanks to the
four-wheel, double-wishbone independent suspension. The new
shorter-throw five-speed manual transmission adds fun to the
driving experience. And the Miata maintains its rear-wheel drive, a
necessity for a true roadster.
</P>
<P>
   For those of you who just have to have an automatic, there is a
four-speed, electronically controlled gearbox available. But the
automatics are rare and hard to find because most people don't want
them. You'll appreciate the automatic the most if you have a long
daily commute in stop-and-go traffic. Except for that, the manual
is the best way to go.
</P>
<P>
   Mazda has strengthened the Miata's body without adding weight,
giving the car a more solid feel on bumps and bounces. There's just
not as much give in the body as before.
</P>
<P>
   And even though the Miata has dual front air bags, there is an
ignition-key-operated, cut-off switch for the passenger air bag on
the lower center of the dash. I found that convenient for taking my
6-month-old granddaughter for her first ride in a Miata. You risk
an infant's life if you put her on the front passenger side without
disabling the airbag _ even with a rear-facing safety seat.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few major convenience features that were lacking on
the predecessor. The rear window is glass (with a defroster built
in), and unlike the older model, the window doesn't have to be
unzipped to lower the manual top. Just flip the catches on top of
the windshield and push back with one hand, and the top goes down
easily. It's also easily raised with one hand even while sitting in
the driver's seat.
</P>
<P>
   Trunk space has increased 44 percent to 5/1 cubic feet, finally
making it large enough to hold at least one set of golf clubs.
Forget big suitcases, though. There is a package shelf behind the
seats for extra stowage, however.
</P>
<P>
   Miatas are offered with five options packages, beginning with a
simple one that adds just speed-sensitive power steering and wheel
trim rings. Our test car came with the touring package ($1,100),
which included the power steering as well as power windows and
mirrors, 14-inch alloy wheels and a three-spoke leather-wrapped
steering wheel.
</P>
<P>
   The popular-equipment package adds all of the above as well as a
Torsen limited-slip differential (manual transmission only), cruise
control, power antenna, wide-range speakers, power door locks and a
special windbreaker behind the seats. The windblocker limits the
flow of air into the passenger compartment, allowing the car to be
driven comfortably with the top down in cooler weather.
</P>
<P>
   The most luxurious model has the leather package, which includes
most of the above as well as 15-inch alloy wheels, tan leather
seats and interior trim, a tan vinyl top and a great Bose
AM/FM/cassette/compact-disc audio system with dual 200-watt
amplifiers.
</P>
<P>
   Base models come with an in-dash AM/FM/compact-disc unit with
clock, cloth sport bucket seats, remote fuel and trunk releases,
dual body color mirrors, styled steel wheels, rack-and-pinion
steering, four-wheel power disc brakes and a center console with
lockable storage compartment.
</P>
<P>
   Air-conditioning is a $900 option that was included on our test
car. The only other extra was carpeted floor mats ($80). Total
sticker was $22,300, including $450 transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Other available options include a removable hard top and a
cassette player. Antilock brakes are optional, but they are
available only with the manual transmission, popular equipment
package and Bose audio system.
</P>
<P>
   EPA fuel-economy ratings are 25 miles per gallon in the city and
29 on the highway, which is pretty frugal for such a fun little
car. The tank holds 12.7 gallons of fuel.
</P>
<P>
   A Cadillac roadster? General Motors plans to roll out a two-seat
Cadillac roadster built on a modified Corvette chassis and carrying
the Northstar V-8 engine, the trade weekly Automotive News reported
last week.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine said the vehicle could debut at this summer's Paris
Auto Show, but might not be ready until the North American
International Auto Show in Detroit in January.
</P>
<P>
   It would share a chassis with the fifth-generation Corvette, but
would have a different body and drivetrain. The Caddy, which would
be the GM division's first two-seater since the Italian-designed
Allante was discontinued in 1993, would be 11 inches shorter than
the 'Vette, but with a five-inch-longer wheelbase, the magazine
said.
</P>
<P>
   NEW GRAND CHEROKEE: Chrysler Corp. says it will unveil its new
Jeep Grand Cherokee on Wednesday (June 16) at Detroit's Cobo Hall,
the site of the North American International Auto Show.
</P>
<P>
   Some of you might remember that Cobo Hall is where the original
Grand Cherokee made its debut by dramatically ramming through a
plate glass window.
</P>
<P>
   Photos of the Grand Cherokee, meanwhile, have been posted on the
Internet for several weeks now, much to Chrysler's chagrin.
</P>
<P>
   (G. Chambers Williams III writes on transportation issues for
the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. His mailing address is
Star-Telegram/Northeast, 3201 Airport Freeway, Suite 108, Bedford,
Texas 76021; his E-mail address is chambers(at)star-telegram.com.
Fax: (817) 685-3883. Check out his Wheelin' new-car review column
weekly on the Internet at
ww.netarrant.net/today/news/opinions/necol.htm. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
