<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, June 20, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(ja) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pesky low pressure will swirl over northern New England,
producing yet another day of ample clouds and patchy showers across
the interior. Near the coast, morning fog will yield to a mix of
sun and puffy clouds with isolated thundershowers.
</P>
<P>
   Warm, muggy air will cover the rest of the Northeast and Middle
Atlantic states. Pockets of fog and low clouds will give way to
hazy sunshine and growing cumulus clouds by mid-morning. Some
clouds will mature into thundershowers over the northern
Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   Record warmth will occur in the Southeast Saturday, as the
mercury could surpass 100 degrees east of the Appalachians. Across
Florida, it will not be quite as hot, as clouds and isolated
thundershowers develop, while brush fires produce smoky conditions
in the north. Meanwhile, a few thunderstorms will blossom from the
Deep South to the lower Mississippi valley as a disturbance lifts
the sultry air mass.
</P>
<P>
   Strong to severe thunderstorms with hail and high winds will
erupt from near the western Ohio valley to the upper Middle West.
The greatest risk for tornado-producing thunderstorms will near the
western Great Lakes, where the combination of a surge of dry air
near 10,000 feet and jet stream disturbance ignites a volatile
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, searing heat will engulf much of the southwestern
Plains and western Texas as blazing sunshine and hot winds from the
southwest prevail. In contrast, moist winds from the north will
sponsor another cool, showery day in parts of the northern Rockies.
The West Coast will be mostly tranquil.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: WETTEST MONTH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although less than two-thirds of the month has passed, June has
become the wettest summer month on record in Salt Lake City. A
unseasonable midweek tempest that dropped up to two feet of snow in
the Wasatch mountains east of the city caused over 1.5 inches of
rain in the city. The rain brought the monthly total to 3.71 inches
eclipsing the rain record for any summer month which was set in
August 1968. Excessive summer rain is very uncommon in Salt Lake
City. The surrounding mountains act as an effective barrier to
moist air masses. Average rainfall in each month from June to
September is less than an inch.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
