<HEADLINE>
CHEVRON'S BAY-AREA PLANT CITED AS MAJOR POLLUTER IN EPA LIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE KAY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Chevron's Richmond refinery tops the nation's
list of polluters with more than 944 million pounds of toxic waste
produced in 1996, according to the U.S. Environmental Protection
Agency's latest Toxic Release Inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron, the only California manufacturing plant to make the Top
50 national list released Thursday, has manufactured gasoline, oil
and other products on the San Francisco Bay since the turn of the
century.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's time that Chevron sat down with community members
and talked about source reduction,'' said Karen Susag, community
organizer at Communities for a Better Environment, an environmental
group.
</P>
<P>
   The Richmond refinery's environmental manager, Marty Gilles,
said she believed the waste production figure was misleading.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only amount that is emitted to the environment is roughly
1.5 million pounds,'' Gilles said.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA ranks the refinery fifth highest in California for its
chemical releases of about 1 million pounds to the air and 500,000
pounds to the Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 943 million pounds are treated on site in ponds where
microorganisms digest and degrade the chemicals, Gilles said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that's a good thing,'' Gilles said, ``that we have a
waste system that does that removal.''
</P>
<P>
   But Susag isn't impressed, saying that Chevron should be obeying
the Pollution Prevention Act of 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was to reduce waste at the source, which does not
mean producing 944 million pounds,'' Susag said. ``Producing that
amount of waste is unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilles said Chevron is planning to significantly reduce the
pollutant methanol by adding scrubbers to its
hydrogen-manufacturing plant.
</P>
<P>
   The Emergency Planning and Community Right-to-Know Act of 1986
created the Toxic Release Inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that manufacture or process 25,000 pounds a year of
one of 650 toxic chemicals must report the production, discharge to
air, water, land or groundwater or offsite transfer to the EPA.
Companies that handle or store 10,000 pounds a year also have to
report.
</P>
<P>
   California ranked 18th in the nation for industrial releases of
toxic chemicals in 1996. Nearly 1,400 facilities reported a total
of 50 million pounds of releases, the majority to the air.
</P>
<P>
   Following the Richmond refinery on the California Top 10 of
waste producers are Mobil Corp. in Torrance, Exxon Co. USA in
Benicia and Shell Oil Co. in Martinez.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
