<HEADER>
A7647 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOGULS-SONS-$ADV21-AR     06-19 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOGULS-SONS-$ADV21-ART-770(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRINGING A SON UP RIGHT _ RIGHT UP TO THE TOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 21)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
(lb) 
 By MONIQUE P. YAZIGI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At the Fifth Avenue offices of Earl G. Graves Ltd.,
employees step with almost military precision. Secretaries in crisp
yellow suits make sure appointments are kept to the minute, while a
receptionist announces visitors within seconds of their arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the hunter-green office of the man whose name is on the
door, however, the atmosphere is considerably homier, almost a
suburban den: Children's crayon notes and athletic awards cover the
walls. This is fitting, since Earl Graves, the multimillionaire
publisher of Black Enterprise Magazine and the chief executive of
the United States' largest minority-controlled Pepsi-Cola
franchise, is in business with all three of his adult sons.
</P>
<P>
   Seated across from a picture of his two elder sons, Earl Jr. and
John, facing off in a Yale-Brown basketball game, Graves swept his
arm to take in the photograph as well as the opulent surroundings
and said, ``Someday, this will all be theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   In this classically sentimental expression of family succession
_ the punch line of so many New Yorker cartoons _ Graves spoke
earnestly for millions of fathers who, in every age, have groomed
sons to follow in their footsteps.
</P>
<P>
   A bulwark of American life since the days of small farms hacked
from the wilderness, the tradition of sons succeeding fathers in
the work place may be less routine now, in an era of working women,
large public corporations and economic prosperity that gives
offspring the freedom to strike out alone.
</P>
<P>
   But father-to-son succession is alive and well in a surprising
number of big New York enterprises, in fields as diverse as real
estate, public relations and sports ownership. The mogul-owners who
run them are often at the core of the city's power structure. After
completing the task of all good fathers _ hectoring sons to finish
homework, mow the lawn and respect Mom _ they have taken on the
added job of shaping ambitious, field-hardened minimoguls.
</P>
<P>
   Many of their sons, in their 20s, 30s and early 40s, are being
groomed as the next generation of New York's power elite. They
schmooze one another both inside and outside office hours, forming
alliances that mirror those that their fathers enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to see so many of my friends' sons now friends with
my own sons,'' said Howard J. Rubenstein, the public relations
czar, who is a power broker in political and business circles.
</P>
<P>
   ``SOBs'' is how his son Steven Rubenstein, 28, characterizes the
18-member breakfast club he started with Jeff Wilpon, 36, a son of
Fred Wilpon, an owner of the New York Mets baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   That's Sons of Bosses.
</P>
<P>
   Guests at the breakfast meetings have included Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani and Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all friends,'' Jeff Wilpon said of his fellow baby
moguls around town, who include William Rudin, 43, a member of a
prominent real-estate family, and Jonathan Tisch, 44, an owner of
the Regency Hotel and a son of Robert Tisch of Loews Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do business,'' Wilpon said. ``We socialize. I help them.
They help me. It all runs together.''
</P>
<P>
   Father's Day is a reminder that a major attraction of fathers'
and sons' working together is that it provides an opportunity to
maintain intimate ties into the adult years of the younger
generation _ rare in a highly mobile society.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to have a son with you,'' said Fred Wilpon, whose
midtown office is on the same floor as Jeff's. ``It continues the
dialogue for the rest of your life.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there are eager and ambitious daughters being
groomed by fathers to take over businesses (and daughters and sons
being groomed by mothers), but even in this modern world, the old,
traditional way is still the path most commonly followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is surprising, but in 1998 the most predictable and most
common person to take over the helm of a family business is the
oldest son,'' said John Davis, a senior lecturer at the Harvard
Business School and an author of ``Generation to Generation''
(Harvard University Press, 1997), a study of family succession.
</P>
<P>
   Although the pride and satisfaction of grooming a son, and of
being groomed by a father, are abundant, there are also manifest
perils, according to Davis and other family business experts (not
to say psychotherapists).
</P>
<P>
   Fathers, Davis has written, often complain that sons are in too
big a hurry to take over, or that sons too readily risk the company
that was built from scratch by years of toil. For their part, sons
say that fathers use business situations to instruct how to live
one's life, making sons feel as if they are still little boys.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Here are portraits of four New York families in the process of
handing major businesses from fathers to sons:
</P>
<P>
   The Wilpons
</P>
<P>
   A Son in a Hurry to Run the Mets
</P>
<P>
   From the time he was 10, Jeff Wilpon has been eager _ maybe too
eager _ to follow his father. At that age he carried a homemade
business card identifying himself as director of construction. His
father, Fred Wilpon, was an owner of Sterling Equities, a
real-estate conglomerate he founded with his brother-in-law Saul
Katz.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, when Jeff was a high school senior in Roslyn, his
father and uncle bought the Mets. Jeff was so gung-ho to join the
front office that he gave up every boy's dream _ a potential career
as a professional athlete. He had been drafted by the Montreal
Expos out of college and believes he could have started at catcher
in the major leagues, he said, but he quit after one
spring-training session to join the family business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always knew I wanted to do what my dad did,'' he said,
sitting, like his father, with legs crossed in Fred Wilpon's office
in Sterling Plaza, on Fifth Avenue. From time to time, his father
glanced dotingly at him.
</P>
<P>
   Robert W. Lear, a former chief executive of F&AMP;M Schaefer who is
now executive in residence at the Columbia Business School, said
that when being the owner's son is the main qualification for the
top job of a big company, a business can find itself on shaky
footing. Many young men being groomed to take over by fathers would
not make it as chief executives in publicly owned companies, where
family ties are irrelevant. ``They're not tough enough,'' Lear
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of this, Fred Wilpon insisted that before his son join
the family company, he should work for another builder, starting at
the bottom, sweeping floors on job sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted him to wear boots and be in the field,'' said Fred
Wilpon, adding that he sought to toughen his son by having him work
for bosses who would not show favoritism.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when Jeff joined Sterling Equities, he rose to his
present position as chief officer of development and construction,
overseeing planning for the new stadium that the Mets want built.
</P>
<P>
   In Jeff's office there is a picture of his 2-year-old son in a
Mets hat. Does Jeff expect his toddler to be the third generation
to join the company?
</P>
<P>
   ``One hundred percent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rubensteins
</P>
<P>
   Keeping Sons From Competing
</P>
<P>
   Howard J. Rubenstein used to throw the daily newspapers onto the
kitchen table and have his two sons, Richard and Steven, read the
articles and recite the answers to the classic journalism
questions: who, what, when, where, why and how.
</P>
<P>
   Rubenstein's own father was a reporter for The New York Herald
Tribune, who took him as a boy to fires and murder scenes. In turn,
he said, ``I wanted to teach my boys what I did.'' So he took them
on the rounds of his trade as a publicity agent _ to hundreds of
parties, dinners and political fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   Rubenstein started both his sons in the mail room of the
160-employee family company, which represents clients like the
duchess of York and George Steinbrenner.
</P>
<P>
   After getting advice from other fathers with more than one child
in a family business, he assigned them to separate divisions to
keep the peace. ``They are very different people, and I didn't want
them competing with each other,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard has a flair for entertainment,'' he added. ``Steven is
more civic-minded.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Richard, 32, heads two spinoff companies, one with
entertainment and small-business clients, the other representing
publicly owned companies. Steven, 28, represents real-estate
companies and political causes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted each one of them to have their own areas of
responsibility,'' their father said. ``In the beginning, when they
came in, they did not report to me. They were trained by other
people. It gave them a far greater sense of independence and a way
to prove their own merit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm their father. It's different if they came in reporting to
me. Each one was helped by senior people.''
</P>
<P>
   When the day comes for Howard Rubenstein to step aside, the
biggest question might be which son will inherit his palatial
30th-floor office on Avenue of the Americas at 55th Street, which
overlooks Central Park and New Jersey and whose windowsills are
lined with 100-odd hard hats from the buildings of real-estate and
construction clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be divided in half,'' Rubenstein said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's get out the tape measure,'' Richard said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Graveses
</P>
<P>
   Sons as Polished as Their Dads
</P>
<P>
   Earl Graves maintains that the family that skis together stays
together. Not to mention the family that spends summer vacations
together and sends its shoes out to be shined together.
</P>
<P>
   Graves, his wife, his three sons, their wives and their children
all take family ski trips to Vermont and Colorado, and they spend
summer vacations at two facing houses in Sag Harbor, Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Every Tuesday, the father and sons take their shoes to the
office to be sent out for shining. ``You must be presentable _ you
must look good,'' Graves instructs his sons, who all favor, as he
does, power business suits with suspenders.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the appearance of having raised a matched set, Graves
said he never forced his sons to follow in his footsteps; instead,
as they grew up in Scarsdale, he tried to make the business world
alluring by inviting corporate titans like Sanford Weill of
Travelers Group to the family dinner table.
</P>
<P>
   Another paterfamilias who believed his sons should not taste
success too easily, Graves refused to give them cars at college. He
would lend them a vehicle, but if their grades fell, he would take
it back. He also had his sons cut grass and work in the company
mail room during school vacations. Some summers, Michael, the
youngest, drove a Pepsi truck. Today, at 31, he runs the family
soft-drink distributorship, Pepsi-Cola of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   John, 35, a lawyer, is general counsel to the family business.
Earl Jr., 36, who is known as Butch, is president of Black
Enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   When they all first worked together, it wasn't always smooth.
``Butch and Johnny, I would say, were very vocal in their
disagreements,'' the senior Graves said. Former Ivy League
basketball rivals, they would sometimes take disputes into the
hallways.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would bring them into my office,'' Graves said, ``and say:
`This is not a basketball court. We are executives. We must act
like owners of the company.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Sterns
</P>
<P>
   A Daughter Wants a Shot, Too
</P>
<P>
   In the family of Leonard Stern, one gets the impression, there
is very little sentimentality about father-son matters. His sons,
Emanuel, 35, and Edward, 33, call him Leonard, not Dad.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I didn't think they could make it, I would pull them out,''
said the senior Stern, chairman of Hartz Mountain Industries, the
pet-food conglomerate that also owns more than 175 buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If not, it would destroy their lives,'' he said. ``The peer
group for owners' children is very tough. You really have to prove
yourself. I've seen too many kids whose grandparents started a
company with ruined lives.''
</P>
<P>
   His children, who also include a daughter, Andrea, grew up
knowing that the opportunity to join the business was always there,
although they pursued highly individual paths at first. Emanuel
helped open homeless shelters in the Bronx. Edward worked as a
reporter for Spy magazine. Andrea was a photographer.
</P>
<P>
   At a certain point, Leonard Stern recalled in his Manhattan
office, which is furnished like a Park Avenue living room, he told
the children: ``The business is here if you want it. If not, I'm
selling it off.'' He has a crisp manner and eyes that could pierce
a statue. About the same time he divorced his children's mother and
married Allison Stern, a former model, and the two became regulars
in Manhattan's society circles. ``It was my time to play,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   How soon after that did his children join the company?
</P>
<P>
   ``Instantly,'' he said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   He did not start his offspring at the bottom. ``This mail-room
business is really a farce,'' he said. ``Creating an artificial
sweatshop when your father is the chairman is ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, when it came to grooming them to inherit power, he was
careful to give limited responsibilities at first, so that failure
would not mean disaster. Emanuel began in retail real estate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was only 3 percent of the company, so if I messed up, it
wouldn't have hit too hard financially,'' Emanuel said. ``Leonard
is not stupid.'' Today Emanuel runs much of Hartz Mountain's real
estate, including the SoHo Grand Hotel and buildings in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   His brother graduated from Spy to the pet-food division of the
company, which he now runs, overseeing 2,400 employees.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Andrea founded The Long Island Village Voice, an
offshoot of The Village Voice in New York, which the family owns.
She has a staff of 23.
</P>
<P>
   On the face of it, Leonard Stern would seem to favor his sons as
business heirs over his daughter, who is, at 31, the youngest.
</P>
<P>
   That would be typical of most men at the top of family empires,
who groom sons to take over, whereas daughters are often given a
lavish wedding, a nice trust fund and a job that may be glamorous,
but not too important, for as long as they like. Raising a family,
it is understood, is their first priority.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Stern denied that he had favored his sons over his
daughter in the grooming department, but he noted that Andrea, who
married last year, is struggling with the issue of whether to drop
out and begin a family. She agreed that this was so.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's her lifestyle problem to sort out,'' Leonard Stern
said. ``I'm not favoring one over the other, but if my sons wanted
to stay home with kids, they just wouldn't be president of the
division.''
</P>
<P>
   Lear, the Columbia executive in residence, said that very few
women with families make it to the top of big private companies.
``They are competing with men who are putting in 18 hours a day
seven days a week,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Andrea currently has far fewer responsibilities than
her brothers, she said she has just as much desire to make it to
the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't count me out yet,'' she said. ``I'm just as driven and
ambitious as my brothers are. My time clock is just different.
We'll just see who takes over someday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
