u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTER-BOOKS-EVALUA     06-19 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-BOOKS-EVALUATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT AUTHORS THINK OF COMPUTER'S RECOMMENDATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (See COMPUTER-BOOKS) 
 (ja) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times asked Melissa Fay Greene, Stanley Crouch and
Elmore Leonard to rate the computer-generated book recommendations
offered by Amazon.com's Bookmatcher. The authors took the
Bookmatcher quiz. which first asked how frequently they read
different literary genres, like popular fiction, classics, romance
and science fiction. Then they were asked to rate 20 different
books, from ``Bad!'' to ``Loved It!'' ``Don't Know'' and ``Not for
Me'' were also possible answers.
</P>
<P>
   Although they were asked to rate more John Grisham than
Shakespeare, all three authors found Jane Austen and
``Underworld,'' by Don DeLillo on the lists. Ms. Greene punched in
the answers herself, while Crouch and Leonard answered the
questions over the telephone.
</P>
<P>
   MELISSA FAY GREENE, author of ``The Temple Bombing'' and
``Praying for Sheetrock.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Answering the questions is tricky. When asked, ``How do you
rate Macbeth?'' is it really possible to respond, `Don't know,' or,
worse, `Not for me'? Of course you say, `loved it!' even if you're
not in the mood to read it again in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Several times, I felt I was on the verge of being tricked by
my computer interlocutor; the novels ``Don Quixote,'' ``Ulysses''
and ``Les Miserables'' were proposed to me in quick succession. `Ah
ha!' I thought. `The software is trying to get me to say I love
really, really long books.'' Just to cramp its style, I replied
that I ``loved'' one of those and ``liked'' two. A better question
from the software might have been, `Have you ever honestly finished
any of the following books?'
</P>
<P>
   ``My recommendations: ``Underworld,'' by Don DeLillo (a terrific
recommendation _ even though it was probably triggered by my `long'
book responses; I'm reading the book right now and loving it);
`Northanger Abbey,' by Jane Austen (read it years ago, can't
remember if I `loved' it or only `liked' it); `The Reivers,' by
William Faulkner (ditto), `The Best of Roald Dahl,' by Roald Dahl
(where on earth did that recommendation come from?) and `Like Water
for Chocolate,' by Laura Esquivel.
</P>
<P>
   ``My reaction: overall, I'm flattered (which is truly the point
of these absurd exercises, a slightly upscale version of teen-age
magazine surveys like, `Which boyfriend type is truly for you?'). I
find that the recommendations generated by Amazon.com in response
to purchases I've made on line are more accurate than these
generated by questionnaire responses, however. And I have to ask:
Where's nonfiction? Where's poetry? For those are the two genres I
read more often than fiction. I bet there are plenty of titles in
those genres to which I could truly respond, `loved it!'''
</P>
<P>
   STANLEY CROUCH, author ``Always in Pursuit,'' cultural critic
and columnist for The (New York) Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   Out of the seven recommendations, three were books by Jane
Austien: ``The Jane Austen Collection: Emma, Mansfield Park,
Northanger Abbey,'' ``The Oxford Illustrated Jane Austen:
Northanger Abbey and Persuasion'' and ``Pride and Prejudice.''
Crouch is a fan of Austen and thought that was a good choice. As
for the other selections, ``A Shround for a Nightingale,'' by P.D.
James, ``Underworld,'' by Don Don DeLillo, ``Longing,'' by Maria
Espinosa and ``Finding Moon,'' by Tony Hillerman came up. Crouch
said he owned ``Underworld'' though hadn't yet read it and heard
that Ms. James was talented, but had not heard of the other two
authors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they understand my taste. You see, the problem
is that the range of things that you may like or may not like is
much wider. Even though I said I loved a book like `The Great
Gatsby' or `Animal Farm,' the fact that to them, that added up to a
whole heap of Jane Austen suggests to me that there is some
fundamental flaw in the way they do what they do.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have writers like our poet laureate Robert Pinsky, who did
this astounding translation of the `Inferno.' If they can't figure
out how to get someone like Pinsky or a guy like Derek Walcott, or
Philip Roth __ he's written so many exceptional works _ there's
something wrong. So I find this fundamentally worthless.''
</P>
<P>
   ELMORE LEONARD, author, whose latest novel, ``Be Cool,'' will be
published early next year by Delacorte Press.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard, who said he frequently reads popular fiction and rarely
reads classics, found ``The Jane Austen Collection'' included in
his list along with ``The Sufferings of Young Werther'' and
``Elective Affinities,'' by Johann Wolfgang von Goethe. He was
pleased to see ``Underworld,'' saying that he already has it
``ready to read.'' He also thought Robertson Davies' ``Rebel
Angels'' was a good choice. As for the other selections, ``Mutant
Message Down Under,'' by Marlo Morgan, and ``Where Echoes Live''
and ``A Wild and Lonely Place,'' by Marcia Muller, ``I've never
heard of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard said he didn't read fiction while he was writing, so he
had been saving ``Underworld,'' along with ``Cloudsplitter,'' by
Russell Banks and ``Cities of the Plain,'' by Cormac McCarthy to
read since he just finished his book. He would read nonfiction, but
the system doesn't recommend it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand the way computers think at all. I pick
books mostly from reviews or if I recognize the author, of course.
That was the reason I immediately chose `Underworld.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't have a feeling for computers to begin with. They
certainly don't have much popular fiction to recommend for me.
They've got all that Clancy and Grisham. I'd choose word of mouth
any time.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
