<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7658 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DUNLAP-BEHAVIOR20-COX     06-19 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUNLAP-BEHAVIOR20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dunlap's behavior at June 9 meeting encouraged firing
 &HT;    By Julie Waresh
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Al Dunlap's job wasn't on the line when
Sunbeam Corp's. board of directors gathered in New York early last
week. Rather, the seven directors, including Dunlap, met June 9 to
discuss how to answer a national magazine's allegations against the
company.
</P>
<P>
   But Dunlap's behavior at the meeting set in motion a series of
events that led to his firing just four days later.
</P>
<P>
   As the discussion unwound, Dunlap, Sunbeam's chairman and chief
executive until last Saturday, complained that he had been slighted
by the company's largest stockholder. He offered repeatedly to
resign, according to two directors who were at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``That caused us to wonder about what was happening within the
company,'' said Director Howard Kristol, a lawyer who hosted the
June 9 board meeting at his office. Sunbeam's five other directors,
including Dunlap, didn't return calls or couldn't be reached.
</P>
<P>
   Kristol described Dunlap's offer to quit as ``out of the blue.''
</P>
<P>
   The exchange, coupled with indications that Sunbeam's
second-quarter earnings would fall short of Dunlap's prediction,
spurred Sunbeam's five outside directors _ those who don't work for
the company _ to spend much of last week scrutinizing the Delray
Beach-based company's operations. Directors _ including Dunlap
appointee Kristol _ talked to employees and examined Dunlap's sales
and earnings forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we found was very disquieting,'' Kristol said.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry raised so much doubt that the board sacked Dunlap on
Saturday and, as part of the early Monday announcement of his
departure, said Sunbeam would fail to meet his numbers for the
second quarter and all of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Sunbeam's new CEO, Jerry Levin, has made no financial
projections for the appliance maker, whose stock has fallen 75
percent from its 12-month high in early March.
</P>
<P>
   The stock (NYSE: SOC) closed Thursday at $13.06, down 38 cents _
and nearing the $12.25 a share it was selling for when Dunlap, the
self-proclaimed turnaround artist extraordinaire, was hired in July
1996.
</P>
<P>
   The first board meeting last week, on June 9, was called to
discuss how the company should respond to a report in the June 8
issue of Barron's financial weekly that said Sunbeam's 1997
earnings were largely manufactured with accounting tricks, a charge
directors deny.
</P>
<P>
   Six of the seven directors attended the meeting in person, with
the seventh, William Rutter of First Union National Bank of
Florida, listening in by phone. Also there were Sunbeam's chief
legal officer, David Fannin; a representative of Sunbeam's outside
auditor, Arthur Andersen; another Sunbeam executive; and an outside
lawyer for the company.
</P>
<P>
   The board decided to prepare a private rebuttal to the Barron's
article, then assess what to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   Following that discussion, everyone left except the directors,
including Dunlap and Chief Financial Officer Russell Kersh.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Dunlap said he and Kersh, his sidekick in the
restructuring of several companies, were prepared to take severance
packages if the board did not support them, Kristol said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll settle up now,'' Dunlap said.
</P>
<P>
   He felt he had been slighted by Michael Price, whose Franklin
Mutual Series Fund Inc. is Sunbeam's largest shareholder, Kristol
said.
</P>
<P>
   Price, who was instrumental in Dunlap's hiring, had been quoted
in the June 8 issue of Fortune magazine as saying, ``We're not
going to sit around and let Al wreck the company. We're paying a
lot of attention.'' The thrust of the article was that Sunbeam was
looking to replace Dunlap.
</P>
<P>
   In response to that article, Price, whose fund owns 17 percent
of Sunbeam, had issued a statement saying his views were
``mischaracterized'' and he was ``completely supportive'' of
Dunlap.
</P>
<P>
   At the board meeting, Peter Langerman, who represents Price on
the Sunbeam board, assured Dunlap that he had the full support of
Price and the board, Kristol said.
</P>
<P>
   After Dunlap and Kersh left, and Rutter was no longer on the
phone line, the four remaining directors stayed around ``for
hours'' discussing what had happened, Kristol said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Kristol and Langerman, Directors Faith Whittlesey
and Charles Elson, a professor at the Stetson University law school
in St. Petersburgcq, participated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all of us independently, though we didn't say so at
the meeting, were dismayed by Mr. Dunlap's repeated offer to leave
the company with a suitable severance arrangement,'' Kristol said.
``No one at the meeting had suggested that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly raised some questions about the forecast and Mr.
Dunlap's commitment to realize the plan,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The four directors exchanged home phone numbers and agreed to
get more information on the company's financial condition, with
Langerman taking the lead, Kristol said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few days, it became clear that even Dunlap's most
recent earnings forecasts of 5 to 10 cents a share for the second
quarter and $1 for the year _ down from his earlier predictions _
were unrealistic.
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap made those projections at a May 11 meeting with analysts
in New York, where he presented his plan for Sunbeam to absorb
three companies _ outdoor equipment maker Coleman Co., smoke alarm
maker First Alert and Mr. Coffee maker Signature Brands USA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We reached the conclusion that we no longer had confidence in
Dunlap's ability to deliver in accordance with that plan,'' Kristol
said.
</P>
<P>
   The board called another meeting for last Saturday in New York,
asking Dunlap and Kersh to be available by phone. During the brief
conference call, Elson made the motion to fire Dunlap.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a good friend of mine, and it was a very difficult
decision,'' said Elson, a shareholders' advocate whom Dunlap
appointed to the board in September 1996. ``But you have to
separate your personal relationships from your role as a
director.''
</P>
<P>
   Kristol said the board does not intend to voluntarily negotiate
a severance package for Dunlap. The matter has been referred to the
company's lawyers, who may contend that Dunlap effectively resigned
when he offered to leave.
</P>
<P>
   The board fired Kersh, Dunlap's top lieutenant, on Tuesday.
Christopher Sues, a New York lawyer representing the two, did not
return phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the board met with representatives of MacAndrews &AMP;
Forbes Holdings, the corporate arm of financier Ronald Perelman.
</P>
<P>
   Perelman, a part-time resident of Palm Beach, became Sunbeam's
second largest shareholder _ with 13 percent _ when he sold his
Coleman stake to the company in March.
</P>
<P>
   At Sunday's meeting, the board tapped Levin to replace Dunlap as
CEO. Levin has turned around several of Perelman's companies,
including Coleman and Revlon Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Langerman, Price's representative, is serving as chairman.
</P>
<P>
   While Perelman's man is now in the driver's seat at Sunbeam,
Kristol said the billionaire investor _ who will name two directors
to Sunbeam's board _ wasn't behind Dunlap's firing.
</P>
<P>
   Said Elson: ``We acted proactively by putting the company and
our shareholders first.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
