<HEADER>
A7668 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-CNN-NEWSSTAND-NYT &LR;      06-19 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CNN-NEWSSTAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CNN NEWSSTAND': MOSTLY MORE OF THE SAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``CNN Newsstand,'' the new prime-time cable series, opened on a
controversial note last week with allegations that the United
States used nerve gas against American defectors during the Vietnam
War. The network's chief military analyst, retired Maj. Gen. Perry
Smith, resigned in protest (``sleazy journalism'' he called it) but
the report prompted Defense Secretary William Cohen to order a
fresh inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``CNN Newsstand'' is the overall title for three hourlong weekly
collaborations between the cable network and magazines in the
Time-Warner empire. On Sundays, Time magazine, which carried the
nerve-gas charges, is the partner from print; on Wednesdays, it's
Fortune magazine and the beat is business; on Thursdays, it's
Entertainment Weekly, and the beat is show business.
</P>
<P>
   Time-Warner executives hope that this pooling of resources will
lift CNN's ratings in slow periods when wars or the deaths of
celebrities are not available. At least, it is hoped, the new
entries will give CNN a leg up in the increasingly crowded
news-magazine field. Whether you call it synergy or merger muscle,
the new series is the best the company has come up with to hold
onto some of the many viewers who flip channels after catching
``Larry King Live.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the new business and entertainment programs _ plainly
inspired by the popularity of other such shows _ are efficiently
produced, with a mildly irreverent attitude toward the
personalities they perforce celebrate, they do not promise to be
the engines of success the network seeks. On first viewing, it is
hard to see what they offer that is not already either in abundant
supply elsewhere or not particularly worth supplying.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, much of the content seemed to be determinedly
inconsequential. Among the stories played up on the first business
hour was one about a man who predicts success from the shape of
your eyebrows and nostrils; a profile of a hot-shot computer maker,
and a peek inside corporate jets. The first show-business hour
delivered a report on how public-relations geniuses maneuver to
redeem clients' soiled reputations; the tough life of actresses
over 40, and an interview with Sean Lennon, son of John. All were
mildly diverting but not likely to revolutionize viewing habits.
</P>
<P>
   CNN's hope for making a mark among news fans resides in the
Sunday night program. With two of the network's best-known
personalities _ Bernard Shaw and Jeff Greenfield _ as anchors, it
aspires to more weight and import than its companion entries.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the main story about nerve gas, the premiere carried
a segment on teen-age sex, a news magazine perennial. Particular
attention for some reason was devoted to a Mormon community. There
was nothing especially wrong with the report unless you were hoping
for something surprising.
</P>
<P>
   More provocative was a short final feature called ``The Looking
Glass,'' under the auspices of Greenfield, who has been occupying a
prominent place as a commentator since moving to CNN some months
ago. In this appearance, he chided his audience for hypocrisy for
telling poll takers that they are sick of scandal and violence even
as they tune into Jerry Springer and anything about the president's
sex life instead of brooding over the tribulations of the Asian
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Greenfield is a leading proponent of one television school of
how to treat Clintoniana. While others (see ``Hardball'' on CNBC)
keep booking assertive loudmouths to rattle their cages, the
Greenfield school takes an introspective, above-the-commotion
attitude. He draws rueful attention to being in a line of work that
requires wheel-spinning, day after day, about who did or is doing
what to whom in the latest celebrity melodrama, be it about O.J.
Simpson, Diana, Princess of Wales, or Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   His good judgment or taste, as he would be quick to grant, can
have no effect at all on coverage of such tempting tales, certainly
not by his current employer. Yet there is something touching about
the abashed concession by one of television's news stars that his
tribe finds itself consigned to a journalistic netherworld, like
tenors fated to sing ``Pagliacci'' on tour forever and ever.
</P>
<P>
   The second edition of ``Newsstand: CNN and Time'' on Sunday led
off with a report on the propensity of some NBA athletes,
millionaires all, for fathering illegitimate children and then
failing to support them either financially or emotionally. From
another report, we learned that the new drug of choice among
youngsters is methamphetamine, street name ``crank,'' which can
produce symptoms of paranoia. And there was a brief epilogue of
conflicting testimony on the nerve-gas story. With its combination
of proven ingredients (money, sex, children, drugs) and its
hard-edge &UR;  &LR; reporting and soft-focus production, the program made a
professional, if not spectacularly fresh, package.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Asian economy went unmentioned, a few minutes was
given to the opinion, delivered by Walter Isaacson, managing editor
of Time, that the recent nuclear tests by India and Pakistan were
unsettling. His contribution seemed like an inexpensive gesture on
behalf of Greenfield's campaign to acknowledge the existence of
significant stories that are not natural news magazine audience
grabbers.
</P>
<P>
   In the same spirit, Shaw promised that ``CNN Newsstand'' would
devote less time than the competition to the Clinton-Starr-Lewinsky
operetta, a pledge that did not apply to his network. The next day
and night found CNN on the case as usual; among the journalists
assembled by ``Larry King Live,'' that major merchandiser of
celebrity chat, was CNN's senior analyst, Jeff Greenfield.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 1738EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
