<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Yankees-Braves: Godzilla, without the happy ending.
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're allergic to overkill, it's time to take cover with the
wife and kids. The schedule shows Yankees-Braves. Twice. We're
talking about a two-game series in New York next week (week of June
22 - 28) followed by another in Atlanta, and we're talking about
all of those words and videos involving an interleague matchup that
isn't happening in October.
</P>
<P>
   This ugly outbreak of Yankees-Braves games is among the worst
things that could happen to those among us who wish for hype not to
conquer reality when it comes to interleague play.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this season, many lost their minds around Chicago when
the White Sox and Cubs played before stuffed houses at Wrigley
Field. The same hysteria occurred in Boston's Fenway Park, where
the Mets visited the Red Sox for the first time since the 1986
World Series. And the Indians' trip to Cincinnati produced the
biggest home crowds for the Reds during a three-game series since
about the time the Ohio River was invented.
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, for each of these interleague series featuring the
Cubs and the White Sox, there are several others featuring the
Brewers and the Royals. As for the latter, the masses definitely
are not amused.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the baseball owners just don't understand that the, ahem,
success of interleague play is simply a mirage. In fact, the worst
thing that could happen here is for the players to agree this
summer to allow the owners to turn this two-year experiment into a
permanent monster.
</P>
<P>
   And you know what monsters do? They destroy. Approving
interleague play for the ages would be baseball's version of
constructing its own Godzilla _ you know, without the happy ending.
</P>
<P>
   Interleague play is a gimmick, and like all gimmicks, it worked
in the beginning. Last year, for instance, attendance rose 38
percent during that first round of interleague games. And what the
owners like to mention is that the first round this season also
showed a dandy increase. Oh, but this is what they don't tell you:
America is starting to say, ``Been there, done that,'' for anything
shy of Yankees-Braves, and after next week, America will say the
same even for a matchup such as that.
</P>
<P>
   Just look at the sliding numbers. After this year's first round
of interleague games, the increase in attendance was 12 percent
less than the increase after last year's first round. Not only
that, you'll see even more of a dropoff in that percentage of
increase after Part II of this year's interleague play next week.
But it won't matter.
</P>
<P>
   Since interleague play hasn't fully run its course, the owners
will look only at its short-term success and ask the players to
feed this monster that will bring long-term problems.
</P>
<P>
   There is the All-Star Game, for instance. And don't forget about
the World Series. Once, they featured the only meetings between the
American and National leagues during a season. No more. And here's
the point: Even before interleague play, television ratings were
dwindling for both.
</P>
<P>
   So what would a permanent dose of interleague play do? It would
create this scary movie called, ``Baseball's Godzilla swallows
what's left of the All-Star Game and the World Series _ and thus
the game itself.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: tlmajc(at)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
