A7679 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PENDERS-WASHINGTON!20     06-19 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PENDERS-WASHINGTON!20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New GW coach Penders says he'll get support he didn't at Texas
 &HT;    By Randy Riggs
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Among the virtues Tom Penders extolled about his new
job at George Washington University is the support of his athletic
director, something Penders said he believed was lacking last
season in his final year as men's basketball coach at the
University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Penders, the winningest men's coach in UT history who resigned
under pressure this spring, was introduced in Washington, D.C. as
coach of the Colonials of the Atlantic-10 Conference. He replaces
Mike Jarvis.
</P>
<P>
   Penders, 53, is a childhood friend of George Washington Athletic
Director Jack Kvancz.
</P>
<P>
   While never mentioning UT Athletic Director DeLoss Dodds by
name, Penders indicated he felt he lost Dodds' support this year.
He referred specifically to the fact that Dodds waited several days
to tell Penders about a meeting four players had at Dodds' home the
day after the season ended to express concerns about the direction
of the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``This past year I just felt quite simply that my athletic
director was undermining me,'' Penders said. ``... I just felt it
was clear to me that I could not work for my athletic director.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm working with an athletic director (Kvancz) that I totally
trust. I've lost a lot of weight this year ... and I feel like I
lost another 50 pounds when I took the steel plate out of my back
when I left Texas,'' added Penders, making a knife-in-the-back
reference. ``I don't have to worry about that here. I have people
that are going to work with me to bring GW the very, very best.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodds declined to respond to Penders' remarks, saying, ``We
appreciate the good things he did for the university, and we wish
him well in his new challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Penders resigned April 2 with four years left on a contract that
had an annual base salary of $550,000. Penders received a payment
of $643,000 when he left UT.
</P>
<P>
   Penders accepted a multiyear deal with the Colonials. His base
pay is expected to range between $450,000 and $500,000, plus
incentives. After leaving UT, Penders signed with Host
Communications to do broadcasting work, but said he had a clause
allowing him to pursue other coaching jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a coach who wants to coach,'' he said. ``This is what I
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Penders said he had one assistant on his Texas staff ``I would
love to bring with me,'' but declined to name him. His top
assistant, Eddie Oran, accepted reponsibility for faxing the
academic progress report of freshman guard Luke Axtell to KVET-AM
radio.
</P>
<P>
   Penders stressed that his problems at Texas were solely with
Dodds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved the University of Texas. I have many friends from the
chancellor on down to people on the board of regents, but it was
time to part ways,'' he said. ``The saddest part is I left great
players like Kris Clack and Chico Vazquez behind, who I love
dearly. They're my seniors, my captains. But you cannot succeed
without the support of your athletic director.''
</P>
<P>
   UT President Larry Faulkner wished the best for Penders, who in
10 seasons with the Longhorns had a 208-110 record with eight trips
to the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Tom Penders had a long run as a successful coach at
the University of Texas, and I think we still have very positive
feelings about the contributions he made to our program,'' Faulkner
said. ``I wish him well in the future, however he decides to try
and develop that future.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
