<P>
   CLINTON _ WASHINGTON _ Days before leving for an extended visit
to China, President Clinton discusses the trip in a 4:30 p.m. EDT
interview at the White House. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   JOB-GAP _ WASHINGTON _ A ``job gap'' exists between the number
of low-skilled persons entering the work force and the number of
suitable jobs awaiting them, the U.S. Conference of Mayors reports
Friday. Separate leads will be filed for Austin and Atlanta, as
well as a national story based on the mayors' 74-county report.
(Abulhassan, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-WASTE _ WASHINGTON _ In a maneuver dubbed ``Operation
Dino Mite,'' a military helicopter hovered over a deep ravine,
lowered a sling and pulled up fossils of a 6-foot-tall
Thescelasaurus dinosaur for transport to Montana State University's
museum. In Arizona, Oregon and towns throughout Missouri, troops
have built athletic fields for schools and communities. And in
``Operation Reefex,''(cq) they have dumped 85 old combat vehicles
and tanks off the New Jersey shore to serve as a reef. Welcome to
the post-Cold War military and its ``innovative readiness''
training program. Launched in 1992 under the leadership of
then-Senate Armed Forces Committee Chairman Sam Nunn, D-Ga., it was
born out of concern that the troops might have too much time on
their hands without a Soviet threat to confront. Since then, the
U.S. armed forces have been downsized dramatically and stretched
thin as they have been dispatched to trouble spots around the
globe. But the civil-military programs have continued, despite
questions about how carefully they have been monitored. (Malone,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: 1st lede moved Wednesday for release Saturday, June 20.
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   FIRES _ Following developments in Florida fires. At least 107
fires have erupted in 28 of Florida's 67 counties since May 25,
scorching more than 46,000 acres. The lack of rain and
record-setting temperatures have left many parts of the state
dangerously dry. (Williams, Atlanta Journal-Constitutin). (As
merits)
</P>
<P>
   FIRE-FLORIDA _ Waldo, Fla. _ Some gas stations and restaurants
in this small town between Gainesville and Jacksonville were
reopened Friday as firefighters worked to control fires in several
other north Florida counties. The fires have burned roughly 7,000
acres in forests west of Waldo, but some residents have stayed,
despite recommendations from officials that they stay away.
(McCabe, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   w/CRACKER _ West Palm Beach, Fla. _ Palm Beach County is a
tinderbox of dry grass and trees and fireworks go on sale Saturday
_ the start of the special 15-day fireworks selling season. There
have been 52 brush fires in the last two weeks. (Pickel, Palm Beach
Post)
</P>
<P>
   GM _ Dayton, Ohio _ Another 1,200 GM workers are laid off as a
result of the UAW strikes in Michigan. Nationwide, more than 90
percent of GM's production has been shutdown or curtailed.
Meanwhile, officials report no progress in bargaining talks.
(Wagner/Drummond, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
