<SLUG> BC-SUPREME-COURT-$ADV21-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT EXPECTED TO DECIDE SEX HARASSMENT CASES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 21)   (For use by the New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Beginning Monday, the Supreme Court is expected to
decide, in little more than a week, cases involving sexual
harassment on the job, attorney-client privilege after the client
dies, the president's line-item veto and the treatment of HIV
patients.
</P>
<P>
   By its tentatively scheduled June 29 adjournment, the court will
have produced 90 formal opinions, the highest number since it
disposed of 107 cases in its 1992-1993 term. It decided 80 cases
last year and 75 the year before. It now has 14 cases left to
decide.
</P>
<P>
   Already this term, it ruled unanimously that Title VII of the
1964 Civil Rights Act forbids men to harass other men as well as
women. By a 6-3 vote, it said the Constitution does not compel
publicly-owned TV stations to open political debates to all
candidates on the ballot, and in a 5-4 decision it said credit
unions should not have been allowed to enroll as members workers in
jobs or firms outside those that the credit unions were originally
set up to serve.
</P>
<P>
   In the pending sexual harassment cases, the justices are
considering whether employers should be held financially
responsible for a supervisor's sexual misconduct when the victim
complained to another supervisor and whether a school district is
liable for a teacher's harassment of a student.
</P>
<P>
   In another case, the question is whether a company is
responsible if one of its supervisors harassed a woman and
threatened to make her job difficult unless she succumbed to his
advances but never carried out the threat. She alleged that even
though she received a promotion, she felt compelled to resign
because of a hostile work environment.
</P>
<P>
   The court's decisions in the cases could have a tremendous
impact on workplaces around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``These cases should lay the groundwork for when employers must
pay for the actions of their employees, and that could be felt in
every office,'' says Joan Williams, a constitutional law professor
at American University here who specializes in women's issues.
</P>
<P>
   Several women's groups have filed briefs arguing that holding
employers financially responsible for their workers' behavior would
help deter abuse on the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``If employers know that they'll have to pay when someone is
harassed, you can bet they'll do a better job at making sure their
employees know that it's wrong and will not be tolerated,'' says
Kim Gandy, executive vice president of the National Organization
for Women.
</P>
<P>
   But many employers have contended that they cannot constantly
police the workplace for sexual abuse, and they worry that they
will be punished for actions that are beyond their control.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could open businesses up to a huge wave of sexual
harassment lawsuits,'' says Stephen Bokat, senior vice president
and general counsel of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce. ``Employers
shouldn't be held liable unless they knew or should have known that
there was a problem,'' Bokat adds.
</P>
<P>
   The question of whether a lawyer can be forced to disclose
confidences of a client after the client dies arises from
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's probe of President and Mrs.
Clinton. Starr wants the confidential notes of a conversation that
the late deputy White House counsel, Vincent Foster Jr., had with
his lawyer, James Hamilton, nine days before Foster committed
suicide in July 1993.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the conversation, Foster was embroiled in a
controversy surrounding the May 1993 firing of seven employees at
the White House travel office. Starr says the notes could be
important to his investigation into allegations that White House
aides or Hillary Rodham Clinton lied about the her role in the
firings.
</P>
<P>
   The line item veto case involves the constitutionality of the
1996 law in which Congress voluntarily surrendered to the president
the authority to shape spending and tax legislation, permitting him
to cancel individual items within five days of signing a bill into
law.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the justices heard a challenge to the act brought by
six members of Congress, but it dismissed their suit, saying they
had not suffered any actual injury because of the veto, which at
that point Clinton had not exercised.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the president has canceled 82 items in 11 laws. One
was a Medicaid tax benefit to New York City. The city, which claims
it was injured by the veto, is challenging the law.
</P>
<P>
   In the HIV case, the justices will rule on whether the 1990
Americans with Disabilities Act, which prohibits discrimination
against disabled people in employment, housing, and public
accommodations and services, applies to a person who has the human
immunodeficiency virus, which causes AIDS, but who has not
developed any of the AIDS symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Sidney Abbott of Bangor, Maine, sued a dentist who refused to
treat her in his office after she informed him that she had HIV. He
offered to treat her at a hospital, but she claimed that would have
unfairly forced her to pay an extra $150.
</P>
<P>
   The court also will rule on whether the government, in
considering applications for financial grants by artists, has the
authority to judge whether their work meets certain standards of
decency.
</P>
<P>
   The case was brought by Karen Finley of New York City and three
other performance artists whose request for grants from the
National Endowment for the Arts was denied in 1990. Then-NEA
Chairman John Frohmeyer rejected the artists' bids because he said
their works didn't reflect the ``general standards of decency''
clause written into the law by Congress earlier that year.
</P>
<P>
   Congress passed the decency clause shortly after a public
outrage erupted over the discovery that government money had funded
such art exhibits as Robert Mapplethorpe's photographs of
homosexual acts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
