<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7772 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDER-SHOOTING-HNS &LR;      06-19 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDER-SHOOTING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSMAN EXPRESSES CONCERN ABOUT MARINE HANDLING OF BORDER
SHOOTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The head of a House immigration panel said Friday
he was dissatisfied with a Marine Corps investigation that cleared
an anti-drug patrol in the shooting death of a young man along the
Rio Grande last year.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lamar Smith, chairman of the House Judiciary subcommittee
on immigration, said the report that found no criminal wrongdoing
by the four-man Marine patrol raised questions about training and
supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Results of the year-long Marine Corps investigation were made
public after the Navy released documents on the shooting to Smith,
whose subcommittee is investigating the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, R-Texas, said the Marine investigation ``just makes me
want to ask more questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Esequiel Hernandez Jr., 18, was herding is family's goats near
the Rio Grande in the Big Bend region of Texas when he was shot to
death on May 20, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   State and federal grand juries returned no indictments against
Cpl. Clemente Banuelos, who said he shot Hernandez after the young
Texan fired two rounds at the Marines. There were three other
Marines in Banuelos' patrol.
</P>
<P>
   A Justice Department investigation into the shooting also found
no criminal wrongdoing on the part of the soldiers, who were part
of the Joint Task Force 6 surveillance unit providing
anti-narcotics smuggling information to federal law enforcement
agencies. They were operating under the civilian authority of the
U.S. Border Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will never know what was in Esequiel Hernandez's mind,''
said Capt. Craig Quigley, a spokesman for Navy Secretary John
Dalton.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that young Marine clearly thought the lives of his
teammates were in danger, and he acted accordingly,'' Quigley said.
</P>
<P>
   The Marine Corps' admission that support for border missions was
at times less than acceptable has attracted Smith's attention, and
he wants to know the chain of events that led to the order to fire
on the young goat herder.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Marine Corps statement about the investigation,
``Officers in the chain of command who had direct responsibility
for supervision and support have been officially counseled in
writing.''
</P>
<P>
   Congressional aides are examining 20 boxes of documents received
from the Marines Corps, which is part of the Navy Department.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is calling for a full public accounting of the shooting
death. Because of the amount of information being examined, he
said, a hearing, if one is warranted, would not likely occur until
after Congress' August recess.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Weinacht, a lawyer representing the Hernandez family, could
not be reached for comment Friday.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Marine Corps investigation, the four-member
patrol was watching activity along the Rio Grande near Redford,
Texas, at dusk when they spotted Hernandez carrying a rifle. Marine
investigators said Hernandez fired two shots at the patrol, ``then
moved in a manner adjacent to the Marines, which caused the team to
believe he was trying to outflank them.''
</P>
<P>
   The patrol then ``moved for 20 minutes in a manner to ensure
visual contact while awaiting the arrival of the Border Patrol, and
in order to maintain their self-defensive posture.''
</P>
<P>
   The Marines determined the patrol acted within the scope of its
duties and complied with the ``rules of engagement, which include
the inherent right of self-defense.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the final analysis,'' Marine investigators said, the patrol
``believed their lives were threatened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Acting in self-defense, they used the basic tactical training
skills they learned at the School of Infantry and in subsequent
unit training,'' it concluded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 1815EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
