<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7856 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DILLARD'S-MINORITIES-     06-19 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DILLARD'S-MINORITIES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMUNITY LEADERS ANNOUNCE AGREEMENT WITH DILLARD'S INC. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1997 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A group of community leaders on Thursday
announced an agreement with Dillard's Inc. that included an apology
from the retailer for any past mistakes in dealing with minorities
and measures to correct any problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dillard's is to be applauded for their movement,'' Kansas City
Mayor Emanuel Cleaver said. ``I'm pleased to say that.'' Cleaver
appointed the committee in December after a black shopper won a
million-dollar award because of her treatment at a Dillard's in
Overland Park, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement completes seven months of often-tough
negotiations. Dillard's, which has eight stores in the Kansas City
area and Topeka, said it was pleased the talks with the Community
Redress Committee were successfully concluded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are firm and sincere in our belief that the progress we
have made by working together thus far is only an indication of the
progress which can still be made when persons of good will and open
mind meet to resolve conflict and misunderstanding,'' the retailer
said in a three-page letter to Cleaver that outlined the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement included the formation of a committee of community
representatives and Dillard's executives who will meet frequently
to chart the retailer's progress and suggest any improvements.
</P>
<P>
   One paragraph of the letter appeared to particularly gratify
committee members, who gathered Thursday afternoon at Metropolitan
Missionary Baptist Church to announce the agreement. That paragraph
was about racism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dillard's agrees with you that the issue of race is a serious
problem in our society and that no element of society is immune
from this problem,'' the letter stated. ``There is absolutely no
place for discrimination anywhere. Where we have erred and made
mistakes in the past we sincerely apologize.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Michael Zedek, a committee member, said this language was
one of the breakthroughs that made the agreement possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should not be minimized,'' Zedek said. ``We are pleased
to see this context and that they see themselves as part of this
context.''
</P>
<P>
   Other provisions of the agreement:
</P>
<P>
   Dillard's will post notices at its stores giving the phone
number of the store manager to register any complaints about
customer service and a pledge to respond to the complaint. The
notice will also contain the telephone number of Paul Schroeder,
Dillard's vice president and general counsel, whom the customer can
call if still unsatisfied.
</P>
<P>
   Dillard's reaffirms its commitment to being an equal opportunity
employer, including maintaining a way to address complaints about
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Dillard's will develop a program to train its security and sales
personnel about how minority shoppers might feel when they visit
retail stores.
</P>
<P>
   Dillard's will seriously consider philanthropic support of
organizations that support diversity and racial understanding in
the community.
</P>
<P>
   Dillard's will try to increase the number of its minority
vendors.
</P>
<P>
   The Community Redress Committee, composed of area clergy and
community and civic leaders, was formed specifically to address
concerns about the treatment of minorities at Dillard's stores in
the Kansas City area. But the Dillard's letter said it expects
provisions such as the effort to increase minority vendors to be
carried out nationally. The retailer has 272 stores.
</P>
<P>
   The committee was formed after Paula Hampton of Overland Park
was awarded $1.1 million in a lawsuit against Dillard's. Dillard's
asked the federal judge who presided over the trial to reduce the
award or set aside the verdict. That motion is pending.
</P>
<P>
   The jury found that Hampton was denied a free gift at Dillard's
Oak Park Mall store because she is black. Hampton and a niece had
been detained at the store when a security guard suspected the
niece of shoplifting. No evidence of theft was found.
</P>
<P>
   Committee members said they were often frustrated in the talks
with Dillard's but credited the sincerity of Schroeder with keeping
the negotiations going.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Wallace Hartsfield said there was still work to be done
in carrying out the agreement's provisions. But in remarks
addressed to Cleaver at the news conference, he noted the
committee's accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have reached a preliminary agreement with Dillard's that
meets the challenge set by you,'' Hartsfield said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
