<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7863 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSICAL-OKLAHOMA-KAN &LR;      06-19 1295
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSICAL-OKLAHOMA-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY'S HISTORY IS A PART OF A FAMOUS MUSICAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BRIAN McTAVISH  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ There's a bright golden haze on the memory.
</P>
<P>
   It surfaces each time 86-year-old Howard McNeill recalls Lynn
Riggs, the second cousin who was ``more intellectual'' than anyone
else he knew in their native Oklahoma. For one thing, he wrote a
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Green Grow the Lilacs'' it was called. First produced in 1931
by the Theatre Guild, it included characters based on McNeill's
grandmother, mother and aunt. It ran for 64 performances in New
York and was nominated for a Pulitzer Prize.
</P>
<P>
   The play, a turn-of-the-century love story of a cowboy and a
farm girl set against the rivalry between ranchers and farmers,
effectively launched Riggs' successful writing career. He became an
active member of cafe society on both coasts, kept a home in trendy
Santa Fe, hobnobbed with Hollywood stars like Bette Davis and Joan
Crawford and still found time to write more than 30 plays
influenced by his humble beginnings.
</P>
<P>
   But Riggs' theatrical legacy, as well as McNeill's personal
recollection of him, may have ended there if not for the keen
interest of Richard Rodgers and Oscar Hammerstein. In 1943 the
legendary Broadway team embraced the romantic plot and earthy
characters of ``Green Grow the Lilacs.'' The result was their
now-classic musical ``Oklahoma!''
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers and Hammerstein's first and most famous collaboration
set new ground rules for American musicals with its innovative use
of singing and dancing designed not only to viscerally entertain
audiences but also to advance story and characterization.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the timeless artistic triumph of ``Oklahoma!'' is less
interesting to McNeill than the musical's unique role in keeping
his family history alive. Now a medical supplies consultant who
lives in Chanute, Kan., McNeill, like Riggs, was reared in
Claremore, Okla.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oklahoma!'' which became a movie in 1955 _ the year after
Riggs' death at age 54 _ continues to have more than 600 licensed
productions a year in the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're proud, just like you would be if your dad was president
of the United States or something,'' McNeill said of Riggs' impact
on him and his remaining Oklahoma relatives. ``You just have a real
kindred, glowing feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   The glow increases exponentially when considering that the three
main female roles transplanted from ``Green Grow the Lilacs'' to
``Oklahoma!'' were inspired by family members who influenced Riggs'
and McNeill's young lives long before the stage versions became
part of theater history.
</P>
<P>
   Riggs and McNeill were born more than 10 years apart. But when
their mothers died, they were raised at different times by Riggs'
aunt and McNeill's grandmother, Mary Thompson. It was Thompson's
strong-willed yet loving personality that imbued the Aunt Eller
character in ``Oklahoma!'' That's her churning butter as ``Oh, What
a Beautiful Mornin' '' opens the musical.
</P>
<P>
   Other kin who achieved ``Oklahoma!'' immortality include
McNeill's mother, Laura Thompson, who became Laurie, the fetching
female lead in ``Oklahoma.'' McNeill's aunt (and Riggs' sister)
Willie Thompson, became the musical's man-crazy Ado Annie, who
sings ``I Cain't Say No.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was pretty authentic,'' McNeill said the other day.
``Willie had been married three or four times. She'd get rid of one
guy and look at another one. My grandmother raised her two
daughters, to tell you the truth. She was working in Kansas City.
She was a hasher, a waitress _ we used to call them hashers. She
was a good-looking gal, and guys were all the time trying to make
her. She was all the time looking for a man.''
</P>
<P>
   Other ``Oklahoma!'' characters culled from the lives of real
Oklahomans included Laurie's handsome cowboy beau Curly, inspired
by a hired hand who used to work for Riggs' Aunt Mary. McNeill
vividly remembers seeing _ if not really knowing for social reasons
_ the creep who became Curly's archenemy Jud in ``Oklahoma!''
</P>
<P>
   ``His name was Jeeter Davis, and I remember him just like it was
yesterday,'' McNeill said. ``He was a farmhand, but one of these
guys that would get drunk on Saturday and thought he was a whiz
with the women and ... he was just a dirty old boy. He'd come to
town and sit there. Back then a lot of people would come to town on
Saturday in wagons. And old Jeeter, why, he'd get on his wagon and
strum his guitar and sing and make oodle eyes at the girls. The
character in the play, he was that type of guy.''
</P>
<P>
   McNeill doesn't often share these stories with people. He
considers it boasting, the kind of carrying-on that led to one of
his most embarrassing moments. It happened when he was stationed in
Covington, Ky., during World War II, and the national tour of
``Oklahoma!'' visited nearby Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ``Old me, I was bragging to some other GIs about how one of my
relatives wrote the original play,'' McNeill said. ``And I said,
`Well, I'll just take some of you guys with me. We'll go down and
see it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So we go down to this theater, and I told the gal I wanted to
get some tickets. She said, `You can't get any tickets. They're all
sold out.' And these guys are starting to rawhide me. So I said,
`Now, lady, just a minute. You mean, I can't get any tickets?' She
said, `You can't get any.' I said, `Let me use your telephone.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So I go in the booth and I called up Lynn _ I had his phone
number in New York. I said, `This is Howard. I'm down here in
Cincinnati, and I want to go see your play, and I've got four guys
with me.' I said, `Here, you tell this girl to sell us some
tickets.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And he said, `Howard, I don't have anything to do with that
ticket-selling or anything else. I already sold my rights to the
play.' I'll tell you, when I walked out of that booth, I felt
pretty low with those guys going, `Yeah? Yeah?' But then they did
finally kind of believe me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless something comes up about the family,'' McNeill said,
``I don't go around talking about it anymore _ unless maybe I've
had a highball or something.''
</P>
<P>
   McNeill's daughter, Melinda McNeill, who works at Hallmark Cards
in Kansas City, is more open to broaching the subject with people
because ``Oklahoma!'' is her way of proudly connecting to a past
that she can only imagine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did it to a guy in the line at Best Buy,'' she said. ``He
was buying the musical on CD. I just thought, `I've got to say
something to him. I've just got to. He'll never see me again. He
doesn't know me. He'll never know me. He may think I'm a bit insane
...'
</P>
<P>
   ``I just said, `Thanks for buying that CD. That means a lot to
me.' He said, `Really?' And I said, `Well, that musical was
inspired by my family.' I enjoyed saying that.''
</P>
<P>
   She and her father plan to enjoy one of next week's performances
of ``Oklahoma!'' at Starlight. Her brother, who lives in St. Louis,
also was planning to catch a performance of the touring show there
this week.
</P>
<P>
   But Melinda McNeill says she will be the only one among her
immediate family _ her mother died several years ago _ who will ask
theater officials about going backstage to meet the actors playing
her relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly her father acts as if he won't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who are you going to say hello to?'' he asked her during a
recent get-together in Kansas City. ``What are you going back there
for?''
</P>
<P>
   ``To feel the love,'' she replied with a silly smile, although
she really wasn't kidding. ``I love hearing people who've been in
the musical. I have a lot of people who played my
great-grandmother, grandmother and great-aunt _ 650 times a year
this thing is performed. That means a lot to me. It's a warm
feeling.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 1843EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980619.0259 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7864 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RICH-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-19 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICH-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE FIRE NEXT TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By FRANK RICH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   New Yorkers can't stop howling about Rudolph Giuliani's proposed
$15 million bulletproof bunker, but let's give the mayor a break.
Perhaps he is afraid of Pat Robertson, who this month warned that
terrorist bombs, earthquakes, tornadoes and ``possibly a meteor''
could strike Orlando, Fla., in biblical vengeance for ``Gay Days''
at Disney World. There are more gay people in New York than in
Orlando, and Giuliani has recently endorsed domestic-partnership
rights for them. Who knows what havoc Reverend Pat might cook up in
response? In 1985, when he prayed on TV for Hurricane Gloria to
spare his headquarters in Virginia Beach, Va., the storm diverted
to New York's Fire Island, where, as writer Christopher Buckley
astutely noted, it wiped out Calvin Klein's summer house instead.
</P>
<P>
   It's as easy to laugh at Robertson's lunacies as it is at
Giuliani's, but the men differ in one unfunny respect: Robertson's
ugly views about gay people, as sinners deserving of treatment or
punishment, are triumphing over Giuliani's benign ones within the
Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Since mid-May there has been an ever bolder escalation of
gay-baiting by GOP politicians. Congressmen publicly endorsed a
Family Research Council luncheon in Washington honoring Reggie
White, the Green Bay Packers star who decries homosexuality; Sen.
James Inhofe of Oklahoma likened philanthropist James Hormel, a gay
nominee to be ambassador to Luxembourg, to David Duke; and Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott took to TV this week to brand gay people
as sinners comparable to thieves. He was seconded by his House
counterpart, Dick Armey, the man who once called Barney Frank
``Barney Fag.''
</P>
<P>
   Where is this drumbeat leading? Washington cynicism dismisses
such incidents as typical election-year red meat tossed by a party
to its base _ in this case religious conservatives. But this is the
kind of pandering that can incite hate crimes as well as votes _ as
witness the warning signs in Texas just last week.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion was the state Republican Convention in Fort Worth.
The Texas GOP had refused to let the gay Log Cabin Republicans have
an information booth in the hall _ despite the fact that more than
50 openly gay Log Cabin members had actually been elected as
delegates and alternates to the convention itself. The party's
spokesman justified the booth ban by likening Log Cabin to the Ku
Klux Klan and child molesters. Log Cabin organized a small,
peaceful civil rights rally nearby in protest _ which in turn
attracted Bible-waving counterdemonstrators bearing such signs as
``There's no such thing as a Christian fag.''
</P>
<P>
   One gay Texan Republican at the rally, sufficiently shaken up
that he asked not to be named, described it as ``a 1961 Mississippi
situation'' with ``shouting and screaming'' bigots raging out of
control; a video taken by a Dallas gay church, the Cathedral of
Hope, confirms his view.
</P>
<P>
   Much to his credit, Texas Gov. George W. Bush implored
Republicans to stop their ``name-calling'' well before the rally.
But national GOP potentates not only fail to repudiate homophobia
but contribute to the name-calling and, taking a cue from Pat
Robertson and Gary Bauer, hide piously behind the Bible as they do
so. Any elected leader who implicitly fuels the fears that feed
bigotry _ or who remains silent while others do so _ is not serving
God but only his own selfish, short-term political interests.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the Bible could also be used as a rationale to bring
back slavery and the subjugation of women. In the Jim Crow South,
it was even used to rationalize lynching, as historian Leon Litwack
documents in his new book, ``Trouble in Mind.''
</P>
<P>
   The national head of the Log Cabin Republicans, Richard Tafel,
also knows Scripture; he's an American Baptist minister. At the
Fort Worth rally, he preached to the crowd that ``we are all God's
children, worthy of his love.'' But his voice could hardly be heard
over the protesters, one of whom brazenly boasted on camera
afterward, ``I didn't get me enough gay-bashing of queers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have to have someone hurt and beat up and dragged from
a truck to stop this?'' asked the gay Texas Republican who was
terrified by what he experienced outside his own party's convention
last Saturday. Someone should ask Lott, who went on TV just two
days later to further fan the flames.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 1843EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
