<DOCNO> NYT19980619.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7866 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOB-GAP-COX &UR;  &UR; MANYLOW- STUDYSAY   06-19 0412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOB-GAP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BY SAMAR ABULHASSAN
</HEADLINE>
     MANY LOW-SKILL WORKERS WON'T FIND JOBS, STUDY
SAYS
 &HT;     Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories. &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Urban employers are not creating enough jobs for
workers with low skills, the Clinton administration reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   By 2003, the number of welfare recipients seeking jobs in 74
metropolitan counties will exceed the available low-skill jobs by
about 350,000, according to a U.S. Conference of Mayors survey.
</P>
<P>
   The survey was included in a ``State of the Cities'' report
compiled by the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development
(HUD) and released at a Mayors Conference meeting in Reno, Nev.
</P>
<P>
   Even in Atlanta, one of the nation's hottest economies, the
survey projected that 19,200 current welfare recipients would be
seeking work over the next five years, but only 7,160 low-skill
jobs would be available. That means 2.7 people would compete for
each low-skill job, a category that includes machine operators,
unskilled laborers, and jobs in the food and service industries.
</P>
<P>
   As federal welfare reform efforts try to move all able-bodied
recipients into the workplace, ``the challenge is for the nation to
produce jobs on the scale needed to accommodate all of the
households making the transition,'' said J. Thomas Cochran,
executive director of the Conference of Mayors.
</P>
<P>
   According to the HUD report, the national economy has produced
more than 16 million new jobs in the past five years, with
unemployment at a 28-year low. But the report found that cities are
still suffering from concentrations of poverty, shrinking
populations and inadequate housing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not talking about something insurmountable,'' William
Apgar, a senior HUD official, said in a conference call with
reporters on Friday. ``These problems are well within our reach.''
</P>
<P>
   To combat this problem, the administration wants Congress to
expand or create a number of programs in fiscal 1999, which starts
Oct. 1, including a new $400 million fund to create and retain an
estimated 280,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's ``urban agenda is helping cities continue to
recover from years of decline and making them better places to live
and work,'' HUD Secretary Andrew Cuomo said in a statement. ``This
is a midterm report card with an A grade for cities, but there is
still work to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
