<HEADLINE>
JAZZ EVENTS AIM TO PUT KANSAS CITY BACK ON THE MAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 CALVIN WILSON  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The festivals
</P>
<P>
   - The Kansas City International Jazz Festival is June 26 and 27
at Crown Center. Performers include Take 6, Dee Dee Bridgewater,
Joe Lovano, Pete Fountain, Brad Mehldau, the Brian Blade Fellowship
and the Andrienne Wilson Quartet. For information, call
1-888-337-8111.
</P>
<P>
   - The Kansas City Blues &AMP; Jazz Festival is July 17-19 in Penn
Valley Park. Performers include the Pat Metheny Group, David
Sanborn, Kevin Mahogany, John Scofield, Benny Waters, Charlie
Hunter &AMP; Pound for Pound and Claude ``Fiddler'' Williams. For
information, call (800) 530-5266.
</P>
<P>
   Legend has it that Kansas City is a jazz town, a swinging town,
a place where the music reaches down to the bottom of your soul and
dares you not to dance.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the myths surrounding the city's musical heritage or
its actual exalted place in jazz history (as reflected in the
national attention focused on the new Jazz Museum), Kansas City has
lagged behind three other famous jazz meccas _ Chicago, New Orleans
and New York _ in international reputation and tourism. Fans of
Charlie Parker and Count Basie aren't necessarily inclined to visit
their old stomping grounds.
</P>
<P>
   But that may be about to change. Because this summer Kansas City
can claim two of the more ambitious jazz festivals in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Neither is new. The Kansas City International Jazz Festival,
Friday and Saturday, is in its third year; the Kansas City Blues &AMP;
Jazz Festival, July 17-19, is in its eighth. Between the two of
them, they'll be presenting some of the biggest and most-respected
names in jazz.
</P>
<P>
   The pop-inflected atmospherics of Pat Metheny and the
blues-soaked fusion of David Sanborn await Blues &AMP; Jazz
festivalgoers next month. The lineup also will include Kansas City
singer Kevin Mahogany, who has made waves from coast to coast, and
guitarist John Scofield; both of them combine artistry with
accessibility.
</P>
<P>
   Fans at next weekend's International Jazz Festival may be swayed
by the straight-ahead vocalizing of Dee Dee Bridgewater or the
close-to-the-bone bop of sax man Joe Lovano. Also on the schedule
are pianist Brad Mehldau and drummer Brian Blade, two of the
most-talked-about young performers in jazz.
</P>
<P>
   The imaginative programming bodes well for both events, said
Frank Malfitano, founder and executive producer of the 17-year-old
Syracuse (N.Y.) Jazz Fest.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're both outstanding festivals,'' he said. ``Both have
great lineups, a programming stamp and an identity. But they're
trying to accomplish some very different things.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blues &AMP; Jazz festival, Malfitano said, ``obviously has more
crossover potential and the potential to draw larger audiences in
and become more of an economic development tool for tourism.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he said, the International Jazz Festival
``has some of the brightest, up-and-coming names in jazz. I think
that's a unique festival in its own right, very well thought-out,
and shows great promise.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only this summer will they offer more than most jazz fans
could wish for, but the festivals also reflect a commitment to
present a global jazz perspective while emphasizing Kansas City's
role in that continuum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure that Kansas City jazz is something that
is, not something that was,'' said John Jessup, an organizer of the
Kansas City International Jazz Festival.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, the event, which added a second day last year and
drew about 6,000 people, has made several changes that organizers
hope will raise its profile:
</P>
<P>
   - Held in September in previous years, the event is now closer
to the beginning of the festival season, when more acts are
available and attendance is likely to be higher.
</P>
<P>
   - Ticket prices, formerly as high as $50, have been lowered to
$10 in advance, $12 at the gate.
</P>
<P>
   - The International Jazz festival now makes its home at Crown
Center, instead of the larger (and harder to fill) Starlight
Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still fighting for recognition on the street,'' said
organizer Steve Irwin. ``But even though there weren't a lot of
people at the first festival, and even last year we were
disappointed, we got so much good feedback from the people who were
there that we were encouraged. It was perceived as a quality
event.''
</P>
<P>
   With its emphasis on traditional jazz values, the Kansas City
International Jazz Festival provides an intriguing counterpoint to
the more populist Blues &AMP; Jazz event.
</P>
<P>
   Jo Boehr, the International's executive director, said its
mission is to present straight-ahead jazz with a few detours into
more cutting-edge territory. But that territory must lie within the
acoustic jazz tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't want acid-jazz or fusion,'' Boehr said.
``That's just not what we've chosen to do. There's nothing wrong
with doing it. We're just trying to go in a different direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Down in the valley
</P>
<P>
   The Blues &AMP; Jazz festival, meanwhile, has long been recognized
as a major Kansas City summer event. A principal goal now is to
heighten its national profile, said Greg Patterson, who has been
executive director of the Blues &AMP; Jazz Festival since January.
</P>
<P>
   The festival aspires to grow, Patterson said, to ``a nationally
recognized level much similar to the Chicago Blues Festival, the
New Orleans Jazz and Heritage Festival.''
</P>
<P>
   And the way to get there, he added, is to do all the things the
festival has been doing right _ only even better.
</P>
<P>
   As in past years, the event in Penn Valley Park, which attracts
about 100,000 people over a typical weekend, will feature musicians
from across the jazz as well as the blues spectrums.
</P>
<P>
   But this year festival organizers did three things that have
significantly improved the all-around quality of the lineup:
</P>
<P>
   - They created a talent committee to get the job done, including
some members of the festival's board. In the past that task was
handled more informally and with less board involvement.
</P>
<P>
   - They aggressively solicited suggestions from area jazz and
blues fans and from disc jockeys about which performers to pursue.
</P>
<P>
   - And they went after those performers sooner than in past
years, increasing the festival's chances to land choice acts before
they could be booked elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the changes are intended to preserve the festival's
mass appeal while enhancing its musical integrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to have the bigger names,'' Patterson said, ``but
also a consistency in bringing back the real strong roots names _
the names that people recognize as being the start, the actual
heritage of the music itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Among this year's performers, nonagenarian violinist Claude
``Fiddler'' Williams and saxophonist Benny Waters would qualify as
just such legendary jazz figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're people who can actually tell the story the way the
story needs to be told, and make it interesting enough to where
your 15-year-olds, your 19-year-olds, your 25-year-olds, are going
to come and take a listen and learn something _ as opposed to just
attending another concert.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blues &AMP; Jazz Festival is becoming more expansive in its
musical views. Over the years the festival's audience has become
more jazz-savvy, said Rich Carr, a member of the festival's board
and its former president.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're much more up on what's going on,'' Carr said.
``Before, I think, it was just something to do on a Saturday or
Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's a much different crowd: Much more knowledgeable about
the music, much more opinionated on what they want to hear and
see.''
</P>
<P>
   Local heroes
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City jazz musicians, long known for their ability to tell
musical stories, will be well-represented at both festivals. No
doubt some of the people out to hear Sanborn or Lovano will also
sample homegrown sounds on the festival grounds.
</P>
<P>
   And in a city where the jazz focus has sometimes been on the
past to the exclusion of the present, that can only be a good
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a time to start counting our jazz blessings,''
said trumpeter Mike Metheny, whose quintet will open for his
brother's Pat Metheny Group at the Blues &AMP; Jazz festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those two festivals, in addition to the other things that are
going on here this summer, can't help but increase the prestige of
Kansas City as a jazz town,'' Metheny said. ``And both of them
feature outstanding local talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahmad Alaadeen, a saxophonist whose Group 21 makes its local
festival debut at the International Jazz event, said he was
``honored to have the opportunity to let Kansas City hear us in a
first-class venue.''
</P>
<P>
   So far as the festival's John Jessup is concerned, that's only
as it should be.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best jazz music is played by people who get paid to play
it,'' he said. ``And we want to be among those who are paying jazz
musicians what they deserve, to play great music.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately the quality of the music and the commercial prospects
for the festivals go hand-in-hand. And considering the current
line-ups, the future looks more than promising.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before you can really teach people about this music and bring
them to this music,'' Malfitano said, ``you've got to get them. So
it's really important to have those artists who instantly and
automatically reach people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you've got them there, the rest is easy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
