<HEADLINE>
`LILLIAN': FINDING POETRY IN THE BANAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes at end of review.)  
(lb) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The title character in ``Lillian'' fits no one's
ideas of a woman of mystery. Her English accent is unmistakably
middle-class; her gestures are small and rather prim; her lips are
often pursed into the expression of someone savoring the vestiges
of that morning's mouthwash.
</P>
<P>
   There is certainly no air of concealment in the way she talks
about her life. And though you don't know what she's wearing, you
can be sure it's not a Garbo-style cloche and sunglasses.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as drawn by the British performance artist David Cale,
Lillian is a luminous embodiment of the ineffable in life, a
reminder that even the most mundane existence is shaped by currents
beyond comprehension.
</P>
<P>
   She likes the fact, she says cozily, that there is so much
inside her that she herself doesn't understand. The idea of
psychoanalysis absolutely appalls her. And though she has worked in
a bookstore and surrounds herself with books at home, she never
reads them. She prefers what they represent closed.
</P>
<P>
   Cale, who first came to attention for his dreamlike monologues
about sexuality and who has recently appeared as an actor in the
New York productions of ``Curtains'' and ``Present Laughter,''
emerges here as a potent foe of those who would break personality
down into quantifiable elements and influences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lillian,'' his one-person show at the New Theater Wing of
Playwrights Horizons, is a wondering and accepting look at the
clear, intricate patterns that develop over time from the ordinary
muddle of daily life.
</P>
<P>
   The evening may skirt the sticky edges of New Age mysticism and
the sentimentality of late-blooming-romance novels. But as directed
with gentle precision by Joe Mantello, ``Lillian'' is mostly an
immensely appealing work that finds an ordering poetry in the
seemingly banal.
</P>
<P>
   Both Cale's performance and his words give off a quality of
being rooted in common soil, like the chrysanthemums Lillian so
loves. The lyricism of the piece is less a matter of individual
phrases and images, which are often deliberately pedestrian, than
the ways in which they accumulate and echo.
</P>
<P>
   Cale, a lanky, long-faced man with Clark Gable ears, doesn't
look at all feminine, and there has been no attempt to use costumes
or makeup to make him more so. First seen onstage as a silhouette,
he wears simple men's street clothes that make no particular
impression.
</P>
<P>
   It's the smile with which he greets the audience that you first
notice: polite, welcoming and just slightly strained, it's the
smile of a hostess who is a tad nervous about receiving her guests,
but also amused by her own nervousness.
</P>
<P>
   That quality of benign detachment permeates the first-person
story that Cale proceeds to tell. It begins with Lillian recalling
the day when, as a married woman in her mid-30s, she went to bed
with Jimmy, then a store clerk and 15 years her junior. The sex is
described in terms both graphic and genteel, adjectives that apply
to Lillian's voice in general, and is given equal weight with
recollections of the pet lizards Jimmy keeps in aquariums.
</P>
<P>
   The encounter, though it will change Lillian's life in ways she
can't begin to anticipate, is not the stuff of fireworks. She finds
it not unlike a visit to the dentist and admits that her husband,
Keith, is a better lover, along the lines of ``a really good waiter
in a pretty good restaurant.'' And her attitude is more maternal
than erotic as she describes a postcoital bath in which Jimmy draws
animals on her shoulders in soap and asks her to guess what they
are.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of patterns felt but not seen recurs in ``Lillian,''
which spans close to a decade. So do images that crack open doors
onto breathtakingly unknown territory: a small ant-shaped tattoo on
a man's ankle; a strip of photo-booth pictures that give
illuminating form to previously unidentified feelings; a feral
white dog running among a field of flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Cale nor his alter ego pushes the significance of these
images, but they never trivialize them either. Lillian watches her
own life with admiring curiosity, as if contemplating the slow
emergence of a photo negative into focused detail.
</P>
<P>
   Cale matches the lapidary nature of his narrative with clean,
understated gestures _ encircling a wrist with a hand, smoothing
out the folds of a shirt sleeve _ that somehow come to paint a
complete physical portrait. Robert Brill's set and Beverly Emmons'
color-drenched lighting give off the same effect of pregnant
simplicity.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There are moments when Lillian directly brings to mind the
life-affirming, middle-aged heroines of Willy Russell's comedies,
``Shirley Valentine'' and ``Educating Rita,'' with a soupcon of the
eccentric monologists of Alan Bennett's ``Talking Heads.''
</P>
<P>
   But she is less adorably plucky (thank heavens) than Russell's
characters and far less tart and forlorn than Bennett's. Actually,
if she ever went against personal policy to crack a book, she might
find she has more in common with James Joyce's Molly Bloom, a woman
who instinctively says ``yes'' to life again and again without
considering reasons or consequences.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `LILLIAN'
</P>
<P>
   Written and performed by David Cale; directed by Joe Mantello;
set by Robert Brill; lighting by Beverly Emmons; production
manager, Christopher Boll; production stage manager, Peter B.
Waxdal. Presented by Playwrights Horizons, Tim Sanford, artistic
director; Leslie Marcus, managing director; Lynn Landis, general
manager. At New Theater Wing, 416 West 42nd St., New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 1844EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
