<HEADLINE>
NOVELTY CONTACT LENS DESIGNS NOW AVAILABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATHERINE L. DYKSTRA  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ That wild-eyed look
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few of the from one company, Wesley Jessen:
</P>
<P>
   - Hypnotica _ Black with white spiral.
</P>
<P>
   - White Out _ Pure white.
</P>
<P>
   - Wild Fire _ Red with yellow star burst.
</P>
<P>
   - Pool Shark _ Black, with an eightball in the corner.
</P>
<P>
   - Zoomin _ A flower.
</P>
<P>
   - Starry Eyed _ A star with a crescent moon.
</P>
<P>
   You're on your lunch break, about to pay the cashier at a
fast-food restaurant. You glance up and suddenly notice _ gasp! _
his eyes are hypnotic whirlpools of black-and-white swirls.
</P>
<P>
   A scene from a new horror movie? Hardly. It's the latest in
contact-lens fashion. And it's hit Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lenses open a whole new avenue for people to express
themselves,'' said Darin Nitschke, a Bonner Springs optometrist who
said he has sold a few pairs so far. ``These allow people to make
any statement they'd like.''
</P>
<P>
   The novelty lenses are available from several companies. One,
Wesley Jessen, based in Des Plaines, Ill., supplies more than 40
Kansas City area optometrists with six designs, everything from an
eightball to a crescent moon (see accompanying box).
</P>
<P>
   Remember when rocker Michael Jackson had cat's eyes in his
``Thriller'' video or Tom Cruise glared through eerie bloodstained
eyes in the movie ``Interview With the Vampire''? Both achieved the
effect with novelty contacts.
</P>
<P>
   The lenses are most popular among young men ages 16 to 24, said
Janet Day, senior franchise manager for Wesley Jessen.
</P>
<P>
   Travis Warburton, 18, and his sister, Tiffany, 17, of Bonner
Springs, were eager to try on the lenses after hearing about them
from friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would probably wear them to work or to a club,'' Travis
said.
</P>
<P>
   Travis works at an alternative clothing store, where he thought
the contacts would draw attention and increase his sales.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is as impressed. ``It's not my cup of tea, but it's
fun for the kids,'' said Phyllis Browning, Nitschke's receptionist.
</P>
<P>
   Jessen introduced the novelty contact lenses about five months
ago. The styles are offered in conventional, soft contacts only.
</P>
<P>
   The eye-catching lenses cost about $140 a pair. That's more than
contacts that change eye color (about $110) as well as normal
lenses (about $90), according to Nitschke. Most patients also must
buy a normal pair of lenses if they don't plan on wearing the
novelty lenses every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly wouldn't wear them every day,'' Nitschke said.
</P>
<P>
   The lenses also are offered in nonprescription for those with
20-20 vision.
</P>
<P>
   Although the wearer ideally should be able to tell no difference
from a normal lens, Travis and Tiffany complained that some of the
styles altered their vision slightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a black ring around everything,'' Travis said as he
gazed through the Hypnotica spiral-design lenses. ``It's like
tunnel vision.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the lens is covered in design; a 5-millimeter circle is
left clear over the pupil.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average pupil is 3 millimeters,'' Day said. ``Some people
with larger than average pupils might get a halo effect. Then it's
just a matter of getting used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Slonim, spokesman for the American Academy of
Ophthalmology, said that a novelty-lens wearer might experience
minimal visual problems, including reduced peripheral vision or a
slight glare while driving at night.
</P>
<P>
   And some doctors are concerned that teen-agers might be sharing
the contact lenses. ``It is possible to transmit conjunctivitis,
corneal ulcers and a number of diseases from one person to another
if they are shared,'' said Ronald Cedrone, chairman of the American
Optometric Association's contact-lens section.
</P>
<P>
   He said he hopes consumers don't forget that the contacts are a
medical device. ``I think the fitting process may be trivialized so
that the `wild eyes' might be looked at as a consumer product,'' he
said. ``Even if there is no prescription, it is still a
prescriptive device,'' according to the Food and Drug
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   As always, this trend is taking off most strongly in Los Angeles
and New York, but Kansas City is in the top 20 percent of sales in
the country, said Brad Macleod, product manager at Wesley Jessen.
</P>
<P>
   So you may just spy a red-and-yellow-eyed boy or a starry-eyed
girl on your next lunch hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that's nice about the novelty lenses is that it's
crazy and it's fun and it's trendy, but when the kids go home they
can take these off,'' Day said. ``It's a temporary, fun thing; it's
not like a tattoo.''
</P>
</TEXT>
