<HEADLINE>
SPRINT PCS TO SPEND $700 MILLION TO EXPAND ITS WIRELESS PHONE
NETWORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HAYES  
 c. 1997 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTWOOD, Kan. _ Within a couple of years, skiers at Vail,
Breckenridge and other areas of Colorado should be able to call
home without leaving the slopes. Gamblers in Las Vegas and Atlantic
City, N.J., should be able to call without leaving the slots.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint PCS said Thursday it had signed a contract to spend an
additional $700 million to expand its wireless phone network. Among
new areas where wireless service will be added are Vail and
Colorado Springs in Colorado, Las Vegas and Atlantic City.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint PCS, the wireless unit of Westwood-based Sprint Corp.,
now provides phone service in 156 U.S. cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to aggressively build and expand the network on a
massive scale,'' said Andrew Sukawaty, chief executive officer of
Sprint PCS.
</P>
<P>
   Combined with other construction projects already under way and
contracts with smaller companies to provide wireless service under
the Sprint name, ``the promise of a seamless, nationwide PCS
network under one brand is now reality,'' Sukawaty said.
</P>
<P>
   In the deal announced Thursday, Sprint PCS will spend $700
million with Lucent Technologies Inc. to supply equipment for the
expansion. As part of a three-year deal, Lucent will supply
hardware, software and consulting services to Sprint PCS.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Paglusch, vice president of technical services and network
operations for Sprint PCS, said the agreement would add service in
new areas and improve existing service.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we said from day one was that not only are we going to
come in and build out the network, we're going to continue to
expand the footprint, keep up with capacity as it increases and add
sites to provide better service,'' Paglusch said.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent, based in Murray Hill, N.J., already had a $1.8 billion
contract with Sprint PCS to help build initial phases of the
wireless network.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint PCS, which expects to have more than 8,000 employees by
the end of the year, currently has more than 1.2 million customers
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   With the latest Lucent contract, the company has agreed to spend
about $4.5 billion to build the infrastructure for the network.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 1846EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
