<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7878 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      06-19 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HYPOCRITICAL TOBACCO BILL DESERVED TO BE STAMPED OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1997 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: The Senate's scuttling of its tobacco bill offers
hopeful evidence that representative democracy is still a
functional concept.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was a hypocrisy paraded across the political stage as a
means to protect youthful Americans from the ravages of smoking. In
reality, it was a government-sanctioned attempt to raise taxes and
loot a legal business enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   Its most significant results would have been a huge tax increase
for Americans least able to afford it and a substantial expansion
of government power.
</P>
<P>
   Based on experience, there is no reason to believe it would have
reduced tobacco consumption by youngsters. There is reason,
however, to believe it would have led to the growth of a cigarette
black market and more unwarranted federal intrusion into private
life.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the much ballyhooed initiative may have been becoming
irrelevant to most average Americans. A recent poll showed drugs,
gang activity, alcohol abuse, reckless driving and sexual
misconduct well ahead of teen tobacco use as major concerns of
Americans. Nearly 40 percent of the respondents said drug abuse was
their main concern, while only 2 percent listed teen tobacco
consumption.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Kluger, author of ``Ashes to Ashes,'' a history of
America's battle over smoking, questions claims about the
legislation's ability to curb youth smoking. He recently called the
focus on children ``great politics'' but said it was ``nonsense in
terms of anything you can put numbers next to.''
</P>
<P>
   From another perspective, said economist Stephen J. Entin,
executive director of the Institute for Research on the Economics
of Taxation, ``there is no economic justification for the (proposed
tax increase). Some people simply like to smoke. Policy-makers
should accept that and mind their own business.''
</P>
<P>
   Why aren't they minding their own business when it comes to
smoking? In a word, money. This is why the Senate tied itself in
knots trying to pass a bill that would have robbed smokers and
tobacco companies of hundreds of billions of dollars. It was about
money for Uncle Sam and the congressional incumbents whose war
chests would have been fattened by contributions from the bill's
beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   It's worth noting that Sen. John Ashcroft of Missouri was a
steadfast opponent of the effort and thus distinguished himself for
refusing to embrace the hypocrisy. In this regard, Ashcroft's
instincts proved sound. It's probably no coincidence that the
legislation died shortly after the Senate couldn't summon the
courage to cap legal fees generated by tobacco litigation. After
this happened, the political upside of the proposal was diminished
considerably.
</P>
<P>
   If Congress and the media were seriously interested in
discouraging teen smoking rather than engineering a huge bonanza
for undeserving special interests, they should take a closer look
at a House bill pushed by Rep. Sanford Bishop, a Georgia Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop's to-the-point proposal is notable for its focus on teen
smoking rather than enhancing revenue and government power. His
bill would require tobacco retailers to get licenses that would be
revocable for selling tobacco to minors; would fine and possibly
revoke the driving licenses of minors caught buying and using
tobacco; and would restrict cigarette vending machines to areas
banning minors, such as bars.
</P>
<P>
   It's an approach that deserves a serious look from anyone really
worried about teen tobacco use.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 1848EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
