<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7882 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-ECON-NYT &LR;      06-19 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN DENIES REPORT OF MERGING MAJOR BANKS
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By SHERYL WuDUNN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ As a high-level U.S. delegation pressed Japanese leaders
Friday to strengthen the economy and tackle bad loan problems, news
reports surfaced that the government might rescue two major banks
by merging them.
</P>
<P>
   A report by Kyodo News Service, citing unidentified government
officials, said that authorities were considering a merger of the
Long-Term Credit Bank and Nippon Credit Bank, two of the nation's
largest _ and weakest _ financial institutions. The Tokyo Stock
Exchange suspended trading in shares of the banks as it tried to
confirm the reports.
</P>
<P>
   Both banks denied the reports by late Friday afternoon and the
government said it would refrain from supporting feeble banks.
</P>
<P>
   The government ``intends to let bad banks collapse, and it does
not have any intention of bailing them out,'' said Kanezo Muraoka,
the government's chief Cabinet secretary, as quoted by Kyodo News.
</P>
<P>
   In meetings Friday with Lawrence Summers, the U.S. deputy
Treasury secretary, Japanese leaders stressed Japan's efforts to
clear away the bad debt and invigorate the economy, while Summers
called on Japan to continue fiscal stimulus, including tax cuts.
Koichi Kato, secretary general of the Liberal Democratic Party,
told Summers that the Liberal Democrats would decide before
elections in July on whether to create a new ``bridge bank'' that
would help absorb the business of failed institutions. Such a bank
would be a major step toward solving the bad debt problem, Kyodo
News quoted Kato as saying.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the financial markets seemed to welcome the reports
of a possible merger between Long-Term Credit and Nippon Credit as
a sign that mergers may be in the works to accelerate the disposal
of bad loans and nudge along greater consolidation in the banking
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Investors have been worried for the last few weeks that
Long-Term Credit could be facing difficulty in paying some routine
debts.
</P>
<P>
   Early Friday morning, the stock price of Long-Term Credit fell
to an all-time low, plunging to 95 yen, down 31 yen from Thursday's
close. After the reports, the stock bounced back to 120 yen before
trading was suspended. Shares of Nippon Credit rose 10 yen to 135
yen.
</P>
<P>
   The share prices of both banks have taken a beating over the
last couple of weeks, and investors have not forgotten the
financial turmoil last November, when four financial institutions
collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Reports of a potential merger between Long-Term Credit and
Nippon Credit have been circulating in the market over the last
couple of weeks. Long-Term Credit seems not to have been as active
a borrower as it usually is in the money market, according to a
banker at a large Japanese bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not participating in the market,'' said the banker,
who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``But we cannot say why.''
Long-Term Credit said through a spokesman that the bank's
day-to-day money operations had been normal.
</P>
<P>
   Nippon Credit is also under scrutiny amid its efforts to
restructure 200 billion yen worth of debt. More than a year ago,
the government rescued the bank with an injection of new capital
and issuance of new debt.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few weeks, leaders in Japan's governing Liberal
Democratic Party have mentioned the possibility that another large
bank could fail. A week ago, Taku Yamasaki, the party's top
policy-maker, tried to assure the markets that there would not be a
failure any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's banks are burdened by more than $600 billion in bad
debts, and Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto has said that cleaning
them up is a top government priority.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
