<HEADER>
A7898 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRESBY-GUNS-600&AMP;ADD-N     06-19 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESBY-GUNS-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESBYTERIANS ASK MEMBERS TO REMOVE HANDGUNS FROM HOMES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Kan., Ohio, Va., Calif.)   (mk) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a strong statement about personal responsibility and guns,
the top policy-making body of the Presbyterian Church (USA) has
passed a resolution calling on the denomination's 2.6 million
members to move toward removing handguns and assault weapons from
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution, passed by a 4-1 margin at the church's annual
General Assembly late Thursday afternoon, follows on a three-decade
stream of declarations by several major Protestant, Roman Catholic
and Jewish organizations favoring restrictions on handguns and
assault weapons.
</P>
<P>
   But Presbyterian officials and other church leaders said the
assembly's resolution takes a different tack in asking for
individual action by church members, rather than seeking a purely
legislative remedy.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution, which comes after a recent series of schoolyard
shootings around the country, says the General Assembly should
``call upon all Presbyterians to intentionally work toward removing
handguns and assault weapons from our homes and communities,''
adding that church members should ``develop community strategies
and create sanctuaries of safety for our children.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Its new ground is in speaking directly to Presbyterians to do
something,'' said the Rev. Kathy Lancaster, a Presbyterian official
who specializes in criminal justice issues for the church.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Joan Brown Campbell, general secretary of the National
Council of Churches, said, ``It's taking this very serious issue
and bringing it home, and saying church people have guns in their
homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that some of the boys accused in the recent shootings had
been involved in local churches, Campbell said, ``Maybe we're not
doing all we could as church people to teach people a lifestyle of
living nonviolently.''
</P>
<P>
   The Presbyterians' resolution is strictly advisory, rather than
binding. But it nonetheless sparked about 40 minutes of debate in
the General Assembly, an annual eight-day gathering that is winding
down at the Charlotte, N.C., Convention Center. The vote in favor
was 393 commissioners, as Presbyterian delegates are called, to
120.
</P>
<P>
   An amendment that would have modified the resolution's language
by removing the reference to handguns was defeated by 361-144. Bill
Ward, a commissioner from Wichita, Kan., who spoke in favor of that
amendment, said in an interview afterwards that ``our church is
treading on something that's legal and trying to say to all of us
who use shooting as a sport'' that that sport was wrong. The
resolution does not mention rifles, shotguns or hunting. In 1990,
the assembly adopted a resolution calling for handgun control but
said the statement was not intended to ``disparage the legitimate
ownership and use of firearms'' for hunting, collecting and
recreational sports. Others at the assembly who opposed the
amendment described it as a ``feel-good'' measure that would have
little practical effect.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Harley, an attorney from Springfield, Ohio, said, ``If
you look into history, you'll see the first thing totalitarian
dictatorships have done is disarm its citizenry.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ann Holt, a retired teacher from Raleigh, N.C, who voted for
it, said it was ``the church's responsibility to make a response''
to gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner who made the motion proposing the resolution
could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Asked for her response to the resolution, Tanya Metaksa, chief
lobbyist for the National Rifle Association, said that organization
was sorry that the Presbyterian assembly ``would suggest to their
parishioners that self-defense is no longer an option.'' She said
that 2.5 million times a year, a firearm is used for self-defense,
``and 95 percent of those times, no shot is ever fired, but
people's lives are saved.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I think they never heard the whole story,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Although critics have accused the church's leadership of being
liberal-leaning, Presbyterians are an ideologically diverse group
who lately waged a fierce internal fight over whether to allow
ordination of homosexuals as ministers, elders and deacons. In
1997, the church amended its constitution to bar such ordinations
by declaring that those who are ordained must be either monogamous
within marriage or celibate as unmarried people. An attempt to
soften the amendment's language failed earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess is, we're a slice of middle America,'' said the Rev.
Douglas Oldenburg, a seminary president elected last Saturday as
the denomination's moderator, one of its top officials. ``I have no
idea what percentage of us have handguns _ probably more than I'd
wish.''
</P>
<P>
   The church has long been among those religious organizations in
favor of restricting access to handguns and, most recently, assault
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these declarations date to 1968, the year in which the
Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. and Sen. Robert Kennedy were
assassinated. But some were issued in 1975, the year of
assassination attempts against President Ford. Others have come
more recently, after the rise in urban violence and drug abuse in
the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   A committee of the Roman Catholic bishops in the United States,
for example, released a statement in 1975 calling for ``effective
and courageous action to control handguns, leading to their
eventual elimination from our society.'' The bishops as a body
reaffirmed that statement in 1992 in a pastoral message on
substance abuse.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, the Union of American Hebrew Congregations, which
represents about 800 Reform synagogues, called for eliminating the
manufacture, sale and possession of handguns, except for use by
police, the military and licensed gun clubs. In 1995, the United
Church of Christ's General Synod asked for legislation requiring
safety devices on guns.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the United Methodist Church, building on earlier
statements, recommended that the denomination's churches be
designated as ``no gun zones,'' where all firearms were prohibited.
The 1990 Presbyterian statement, which focused on handguns and
assault weapons, criticized the entertainment industry for the
``glorification of violence.''
</P>
<P>
   In interviews Friday, Presbyterians at the assembly expressed
differing opinions about the resolution. The Rev. Thomas Nance Jr.,
a Richmond, Va., minister who described himself as being ``on the
right-wing of things,'' said he voted for the resolution. ``There's
just too much violence and we have to do some things to ensure the
safety of people in this country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Arlynn Barner, a Los Angeles real estate salesman who voted
against the resolution, said, ``I would feel uncomfortable without
a handgun in my home for protection.''
</P>
<P>
   Oldenburg, the moderator, said he voted for it. ``Will it make a
difference? Who knows?'' he said. ``Now it's up to individual
Presbyterian families to follow the counsel, the advice, of this
assembly or not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
