<HEADER>
A7899 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-OZZIE-BOS &LR;      06-19 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-OZZIE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO FILMS CONTRAST '50S TV IMAGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN KOCH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
OZZIE AND HARRIET: THE ADVENTURES OF AMERICA`S FAVORITE FAMILY 
Produced by: Peter Jones and Selina Lin  
On: The Arts &AMP; Entertainment channel  
Date: Sunday at 8 p.m. 
 
 
ERNIE KOVACS: PLEASE STAND BY  
On: The Arts &AMP; Entertainment channel  
Date: Tuesday at 8 p.m.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's instructive comparing two upcoming, and generally engaging,
A&AMP;E biographies _ one devoted to Ozzie and Harriet Nelson and their
television family, the other to comic innovator Ernie Kovacs. The
documentaries are airing as part the cable channel's weeklong
Biography series dedicated to the 1950s. The first revisits the
mother and father of all family shows, Ozzie and Harriet Nelson,
and their real children David and Ricky, who also played their
children on radio, then more famously still on television. The
other Biography is devoted to the wacky Ernie Kovacs, whose
inspirational comedy depended as much on his appreciation of TV
technology as on his ageless lunacy. (``Ozzie and Harriet: The
Adventures of America's Favorite Family'' runs Sunday from 8-10
p.m., ``Ernie Kovacs: Please Stand By,'' on Tuesday from 8-9 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   As naturally as we think of Kovacs as an innovator, we associate
the nuclear Nelsons with whitebread family values that have come,
correctly or not, to epitomize '50s conformity and stasis.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing these two documentaries, however, reveals a striking
irony. And I'm not referring to the troubles afflicting the
off-screen Nelsons that contrasted darkly with their wholesome TV
image. The most public of their difficulties involved Rick after
the family show shrewdly helped his chart-topping pop-singing
career. Drugs and family chaos took their toll long before his 1985
death in a plane crash devastated the extended and genuinely
close-knit Nelson clan.
</P>
<P>
   All of this and more is well represented, and treated
unsensationally, in the two-hour program. But there's nothing
really surprising about the family's hardships. They were, the
documentary points out, an enterprising and highly ambitious
show-business family subject to enormous pressure and stress.
</P>
<P>
   On screen, Ozzie was a fuzzy patriarch with an unidentifiable
job and a silly fetish for Tutti-Fruity ice cream. But this
easygoing, slightly daffy image was a radical disconnect from his
real-life drive and even unconventionality. Ozzie especially, but
Harriet, too, were scarcely the middle-class models they portrayed
in 435 episodes of their popular ABC show. Both came from itinerant
show business families and, while not bohemian, their adult lives
on the road, on bandstands, and in theaters had little in common
with their suburban screen stereotypes. Harriet Hilliard Nelson,
born Peggy Louise Snyder, went from vaudeville to fronting Ozzie's
successful big band as a slinky crooner _ and, according to the
documentary, was the first ``girl singer'' hired by an established
big band.
</P>
<P>
   The program reveals in colorfully sympathetic detail who the
off-screen the Nelsons really were, and for this effort alone, and
its emphasis on their show-biz savvy, it's worth watching. But it
misses an extraordinary opportunity, I think, to explore more
thoroughly the abyss between the hard-driving show-business Nelsons
and the soft fantasy family they projected on TV. The documentary
does show how as he aged, Rick Nelson was painfully imprisoned by
his popular teen image, but it doesn't begin to explain adequately
how the comforting, conformist TV family _ which bred others like
``The Donna Reed Show'' and ``Father Knows Best'' _ evolved and how
it so shrewdly served advertisers and the appetites of '50s
viewers.
</P>
<P>
   It's a shame the producers of this otherwise solid film didn't
include some probing cultural commentators in their list of
generally friendly if often fascinatating interviewees consisting
mostly of family members and former show staff. And while the
documentary reveals the off-screen Ozzie Nelson as a fiercely
independent business man protective of his creative properties, it
seems timid in assessing the impact of his domineering impact on
the family.
</P>
<P>
   Still, we're left the wiser: It required entrepreneurial if not
artistic daring and true grit to create and sustain ``Ozzie and
Harriet's'' marathon TV run from 1952 to 1966.
</P>
<P>
   Kovacs, on the other hand, was a truly creative noncomformist
who made a lasting impact on the medium. ``The Late Show With David
Letterman'' and ``Saturday Night Live,'' for only two examples,
wouldn't exist in their current form without the experimental, and
often extemporaneous, on-air hijinks pioneered by the New
Jersey-born entertainer. The biographical details in ``Please Stand
By'' hang together meaningfully. The many agonizing struggles of
Kovacs _ with tuberculosis, with the ex-wife who kidnapped their
two daughters from him, with typically craven network executives _
testify to the force of his irrepressible inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   But the most memorable and pleasure-giving aspects of the
hour-long film are the clips of his zany, ebullient work, from such
shows as ``Ernie in Kovacsland'' (1951) and ``The Ernie Kovacs
Show'' (1953). He possessed a Woody Allen-ish sense of the absurd,
but above all valued surreal visual humor that cleverly exploited
the new electronic medium he so obviously loved. Because they are
really inseparable from the camera tricks and other technological
effects they depend on, Kovacs's most inventive and exhilarating
gags are quite indescribable. But, then, some of them are in
``Please Stand By,'' over 40 years old but remarkably standing the
test of time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
