<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEAMSTERS-ELECTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPLIT WEAKENS CHALLENGE TO HOFFA TEAMSTER CANDIDACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A bid by union reformers to win the Teamsters presidential
election has stalled because of an internal split over a candidate
to challenge James P. Hoffa for the 1.4 million-member union's top
seat.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa, son of labor leader James R. Hoffa, is expected to garner
a significant number of votes this summer because of his father's
legacy, but union reformers had hoped to launch a viable campaign
against the 57-year-old Detroit lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   However, hopes for a consensus started to unravel when George
Cashman, president of Local 25 in Charlestown, Mass., and two other
international vice presidents from the eastern region declined to
back reform candidate Thomas Leedham of Oregon. The decision could
catapult Hoffa into the union presidency. In all, 475,000 members
are in the eastern region.
</P>
<P>
   Leedham was endorsed by Teamsters for a Democratic Union, the
union's 10,000-member reform group, after top candidate Ken Hall
dropped out of the race because of a health issue. Hall, who led
the Teamsters to victory during last year's strike against United
Parcel Service of America, had enjoyed widespread support.
</P>
<P>
   But over the past few weeks, divisions within the union, as well
as some defections to the Hoffa camp, have focused attention on the
group's ongoing struggle to unify its ranks since the
disqualification of Teamsters president Ron Carey. In November,
Carey was barred from a federally ordered rerun election because of
a campaign finance scandal involving the illegal use of union
funds. He later took a leave of absence.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, some local union leaders in the south and west have
switched allegiances from Carey to Hoffa.
</P>
<P>
   This week, nomination papers were mailed to delegates of the
Teamsters convention. The delegates must choose candidates to run
for general president and general secretary-treasurer, as well as
for at-large and regional positions.
</P>
<P>
   Cashman, who once considered entering the race himself, said he
and two others in the eastern region had backed Hall, but balked at
the notion that they should rally around a replacement simply
because he has received an endorsement from reformers.
</P>
<P>
   A labor source said some eastern leaders consider Leedham
arrogant and feel he is too much of a reformer to seek out their
views. The eastern leaders have been characterized by union
observers as moderates.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are now 1.4 million members in the Teamsters union, but
for one group to say they will pick a candidate that everyone
should surround, well, it just isn't possible,'' Cashman said this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Leedham, meanwhile, has said the most important factor in the
election should be the issues, not the personalities of the people
running. An international vice president, he is in charge of the
warehouse division, which represents 400,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unity among officials does not necessarily mean the membership
is supportive,'' said Sandy Pope, an aide to Leedham. &UR;  &LR; ``That's why
we will be taking our campaign directly to the members.''
</P>
<P>
   But the split appears to be widening. In Philadelphia, for
example, John Morris, one of four eastern international vice
presidents, is backing a slate headed by John Metz, director of the
Teamsters' public employee's trade division. Metz is based in St.
Louis. ``We think we have a good viable slate and we think it's
going to win,'' Jim Smith, an aide to Morris, said.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, meanwhile, Carroll Haynes, president of Local 237,
this week announced his support of Hoffa in a mail ballot election
slated for August. Haynes had backed Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for healing, and time to come together to protect
and ensure the survival or our great union,'' said Haynes. ``We
need to put aside our differences so we can go about the business
of protecting members' rights and benefits in the workplace.''
</P>
<P>
   At Hoffa Now!, Hoffa's election offices in Washington, D.C.,
campaign manager Thomas Pazzi said he was confident Hoffa will win.
``Part of the problem Leedham and Metz will have is name
recognition,'' Pazzi said in a telephone interview. ``Who knows who
they are?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
