<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
100 BEST FILMS? ARE THEY SURE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO -- Atrick trivia question for film fans: What is
the last line of ``The Maltese Falcon''? No, it's not a
Shakespearean line about the stuff of dreams from Humphrey Bogart
as Sam Spade.
</P>
<P>
   Ward Bond, as Detective Sergeant Tom Polhaus, stares at the
black bird and says ``Huh?'' _ which expresses the view of many
movie buffs miffed at the stiffing of their favorites among the 100
best American movies cataloged by the American Film Institute.
</P>
<P>
   A gruff, dimwitted stalwart of director John Ford's troupe, Bond
played cops and cowboys, appearing in seven of the 100, more than
anyone else (one more than the talented Robert Duvall), thus
proving that randomness and quirkiness infest such a list.
</P>
<P>
   Some 40,000 feature films were winnowed to 400. The final
criteria included ``critical recognition,'' ``major awards,''
``popularity over time,'' ``historical significance,'' and
``cultural impact.'' The Film Institute, celebrating its 30th
anniversary, has, under the leadership of Jean Picker Firstenberg,
preserved the art and the fun of the movies. Now, a little
marketing coup will sell 100-best videos and maybe even revive
wide-screen showings of the winners.
</P>
<P>
   I confess to having seen all 100, many more than once, when I
could have been working on a suntan. Moreover, if all but five of
them were on a nearby big screen, I'd ignore ``Godzilla,'' buy a
ticket, and order extra cholesterol on the popcorn. Choice is what
the list is about _ that, along with myth and memory and arguments,
which have begun grandly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Calcified critical orthodoxy,'' writes Mick LaSalle of the San
Francisco Chronicle, and the headline is even better: ``Top 100
films: a roundup of usual suspects.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who chose this list of the top 100?'' asks Bob Thomas of the
Associated Press, who knows Hollywood as well as anyone.
``Apparently it was done by 1,500 film people, critics, and
moviegoers. The only voters identified were President Clinton and
Vice President Al Gore. Whoever the voters were, they seem
deficient in film history.'' Thomas decries the presence of only
four silent movies and suggests that whim and whimsy treat the last
two decades better the 1930s or 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The omissions on the AFI list, and they are numerous, are,
frankly, a scandal,'' writes KennethTuran in the Los Angeles Times.
A roster without directors like Ernst Lubitsch and Preston Sturges,
he says, ``is like making a list of 100 best American novels and
forgetting about Ernest Hemingway and F. Scott Fitzgerald.''
</P>
<P>
   Words count as well as pictures, as a CBS spe
</P>
<P>
   cial reminded viewers _ Colin Clive and `It's alive!''
</P>
<P>
   in ``Frankenstein''; Marlon Brando, who ``coulda been a
contendah,'' in ``On the Waterfront''; E.T., who wants to ``phone
home.'' This idiosyncratic lineup may prompt some moviegoers to
emulate Robert De Niro's Travis Bickle: ``You talkin' to me?''
</P>
<P>
   Turan protests the absence of ``Buster Keaton, easily the equal
of Charlie Chaplin,'' represented by three films. The Marx Brothers
have only one, ``Duck Soup,'' which Bob Thomas correctly says is a
lesser film than ``A Night at the Opera.'' W.C. Fields once called
Chaplin ``a goddamned ballet dancer,'' perhaps realizing that
critics would fail to recognize that his ``My Little Chickadee'' is
funnier than ``The Gold Rush'' and that ``The Bank Dick'' is better
than ``City Lights.''
</P>
<P>
   Fields is mysteriously MIA on the 100, but he's in good company.
Fred Astaire, Ginger Rogers, Bing Crosby, and Bob Hope, are all six
places behind Ward Bond and one behind Kevin Costner.
</P>
<P>
   In 1967, Bosley Crowther, film critic for The New York Times,
published ``The Great Films,'' his choice of the 50 best films,
only 14 of which survive AFI scrutiny 30 years later later. No
Harold Lloyds need apply, and Nanook me no Norths. ``Naturally, my
choices are arbitrary,'' Crowther wrote. Maybe that's the meaning
of this ``Rosebud'' list.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
