<HEADER>
A7912 &Cx1f; gen-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-ARLEN-NAT     06-19 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-ARLEN-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     
 &HT;    
 &HT;      WHILE SPECTER RECOUPS, LLOYD GOES FOR DOLLARS
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Paul Kane  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, June 19 -- As Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., has been
recuperating from heart surgery and pneumonia the past three weeks,
Democrat Bill Lloyd has trying to kick-start the fundraising drive
of his campaign to unseat the veteran Republican.
</P>
<P>
   But even with Specter on the sidelines, Lloyd continues to fall
further behind in the money game, according to both campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going slow,'' said Peter Wiley, spokesman for Rep. Lloyd,
D-Somerset. ``Nobody at this point is willing to come across with a
lot of money for Bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd won the Democratic nomination last month largely on the
basis of his endorsement from the state Democratic party. He ran no
television ads, and had raised only $17,600 as of the end of March.
</P>
<P>
   But the campaign was always designed around the concept of
winning the nomination based on the Democratic machine -- or what's
left of it -- and then hitting the fundraising trail.
</P>
<P>
   One month after that primary victory, Lloyd has raised just
$60,000, Wiley said. In the first week of July, Lloyd said he plans
to hold a fundraiser in Somerset County to rally support in his
home base, which he hopes will pay some of the campaign bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are starting at ground zero,'' Lloyd said. ``There's no
question he's going to have a lot more money.''
</P>
<P>
   While filing forms are not due until the end of this month,
Specter is expected to have at least $5 million in cash. Through
March, he had raised that much and had $3.6 million remaining in
his account.
</P>
<P>
   Yet his absence could at least give Lloyd the chance to make
more appearances and get his message out while Specter recovers.
</P>
<P>
   Specter, 68, went into Thomas Jefferson Hospital in Philadelphia
May 30 complaining of chest pains. A day later he underwent a
double bypass surgery, and within a week he was suffering from
aspiration pneumonia. He left the hospital June 15, and will return
to work ``as soon as his doctors give him the go ahead,'' said
Specter spokesman John Ullyot.
</P>
<P>
   That go-ahead won't come until at least June 30, and possibly
not until mid-July, Ullyot said.
</P>
<P>
   That would be six weeks off the job -- and off the campaign
trail.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd is careful to say that he will not make Specter's health
and age an issue in the campaign, but that it could become one.
``That's really a question the public has to decide,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (the voters) make it an issue, it'll be an issue,'' Wiley
added.
</P>
<P>
   One issue Specter has missed out on was last week's Senate
debate on the $516 billion tobacco bill, which won 57-42 but failed
to get the 60 votes needed to kill off a filibuster. President
Clinton claimed there were two more Democratic votes he could have
secured, meaning Specter's vote may have been decisive.
</P>
<P>
   But he isn't saying how he would have voted because most of the
debate and amendments to the bill occurred while he was in the
hospital. ``In its final form, it was far different from the
original bill,'' Ullyot said.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd, however, endorsed the bill as a ``good opportunity to get
a pool of funds to address public health problems.'' It would
increase cigarette taxes by $1.10 a pack while settling all states'
lawsuits against tobacco firms. But conservatives criticized the
bill as a ``money grab'' for Democrats to fund White House
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd sees reducing smoking as part of his broader message of
making health care affordable; if smoking can be reduced, lung
cancer will decline, reducing health costs across the board.
</P>
<P>
   But getting that message out will be hard to without a major
increase in campaign funds. The goal is to have raised between $1.5
million and $2 million by November: about $15,000 a day from now
until election day.
</P>
<P>
   Even while he's been sick, Specter's campaign has held
fundraisers, including a June 8 event in Philadelphia while Specter
was in the hospital. It was attended by 12 U.S. Senators, including
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott and other GOP leaders, according
to Kent Gates, Specter's campaign manager.
</P>
<P>
   That one night almost certainly raised more than the $60,000
that the Lloyd campaign has raised since entering the race earlier
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd said he can't figure out why Specter is still raising so
much money. ``My guess is that his polls are telling him what my
instincts are telling me: that this race is far from over,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 1859EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
