<DOCNO> NYT19980619.0279 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7913 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-19 1394
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULLS LEARNED TO PLAY WITH HEART AGAINST DETROIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was after midnight, and the Los Angeles Lakers' team bus sat
idling on the second floor of Boston Garden, waiting for
stragglers, before it could head down the ramp to Logan Airport for
the long flight home. About an hour before, the Celtics had beaten
the Lakers, 111-102, in the steamy Garden to become the 1984 NBA
champions.
</P>
<P>
   On his way out of the building, Red Auerbach walked past the bus
with a couple of friends when a voice shouted his name. Auerbach
turned. Pat Riley, then the young coach of the Lakers, was stepping
down from the bus and walking across the floor, his right hand
extended.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congratulations,'' said Riley. ``You guys deserved to win. You
are just tougher than us. We're not tough enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Auerbach, against his nature, was almost demure. ``It could have
been different if you had (Bob) McAdoo,'' said the Celtics
president. ``He could have made a difference in such a close
game.''
</P>
<P>
   But Riley would have none of it. ``No,'' he said. ``He wouldn't
have made the difference. We're just not as tough as your club.''
</P>
<P>
   A year later, the Celtics and Lakers met again in the NBA
Finals. The Celtics embarrassed Los Angeles in the Garden in the
opener, 148-114. Kareem Abdul-Jabbar was particularly pathetic. The
media jumped on the theme that Jabbar was done, that the Lakers
simply could not beat Boston. Never had. Never would.
</P>
<P>
   In the second game, the Celtics led early in the first period.
Larry Bird was coming down the right wing for a fairly open
15-footer when Abdul-Jabbar challenged the shot and leveled Bird. I
mean leveled him. Bird went skidding on the seat of his pants past
the Celtics bench and out of bounds. It was a very loud, hard foul.
No one on the Celtics reacted. Abdul-Jabbar was not challenged. The
Lakers found some muscle. They beat the Celtics that night and kept
on going to win the series in six games, taking the clincher in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, Riley would call that episode, and that series, the
most important in Laker history. It was when they discovered it
took more than great players to win it all. It also took heart.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Bulls learned this lesson from Detroit. For years,
before Michael became Michael, Jordan and his teammates couldn't
get past Detroit. The Pistons were bullies and the Bulls wouldn't
muscle up to them in the playoffs. Detroit won back-to-back titles
in 1989 and '90 with grab-and-maul basketball. ``Detroit changed
the rules of the game,'' says our basketball guru, Bob Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   But then the Bulls found some heart and have been beating up the
NBA ever since. They can now clutch and grab with the best of them
and proved it once again this year by mauling Utah every time the
game was on the line.
</P>
<P>
   There is no greater player in any sport than Michael Jordan, but
at the same time, there is no player ever who bent the rules more
and was allowed to do so. He is a master when it comes to working
the officials. He is on them constantly, telling them how to call
the game. He never gets a technical. And he always gets an
audience. In the end, he gets his way.
</P>
<P>
   The seventh game of the Indiana series this year was a great
showcase of his clout with the officials. With the Bulls in danger
of being eliminated by the Pacers, Jordan simply took the ball at
the end of the game, and because he wasn't shooting well, he drove
into the pile and jumped into the nearest opposing Pacer he could
find. The result: two foul shots for Jordan and a bailout for
Chicago. But give Jordan credit for doing what has to be done to
win. This is all part of toughness.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the glorious summer of 1967, when a young Red Sox team
was on the way to restoring the love of baseball in New England,
there was a turning point early that season in Yankee Stadium. Jim
Lonborg was pitching in a night game against Thad Tillotson, a
journeyman righthander for the Bronx Bombers, who were three years
past their heyday but still a bit arrogant.
</P>
<P>
   Lonborg, who would lead the American League in hitting batters
that year, had drilled Tillotson when he was at the plate.
Tillotson didn't like it and was yapping at Lonborg when he went to
first base. First baseman George Scott didn't like what Tillotson
had to say, and in seconds, the two teams went at it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The night before, Joe Foy hit a grand slam for us,'' recalls
Lonborg. ``Then in the first inning of that game, Joe hit a
three-run homer. The next time up, Tillotson missed him twice and
then hit him in the head with the third pitch. He came up the next
time and I simply had to drill him. There was no thinking about it.
If you want to compete, you must let everyone know that you are
going to set a certain attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox kicked the Yankees' butts in the fight, and more than
anything else early that season, that incident pulled a group of
young players together as a formidable team that would go on to win
the pennant.
</P>
<P>
   Nine years later, at the same place, the reverse happened. The
Sox, fresh from winning the 1975 pennant and going to the seventh
game of the World Series before losing to Cincinnati, went into
Yankee Stadium early in the season. Bill Lee was pitching for
Boston. There was a play at the plate, and Carlton Fisk got into it
with the sliding Yankee runner. In the ensuing melee, third baseman
Graig Nettles sucker-punched Lee, and moments later, center fielder
Mickey Rivers cheap-shotted Lee, who suffered a separated shoulder
and was out of action for weeks. None of Lee's teammates answered
for him. They stood around like a bunch of wimps and let it happen.
From then on, the Yankees of that era had the Sox' number and beat
them in the big games, including the 1978 AL East playoff in which
Bucky Dent hit his infamous homer.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring of 1979, the Bruins were in the semifinals of the
Stanley Cup playoffs against the Montreal Canadiens. The first game
was at the Forum, and when Montreal had the game in hand late in
the third period, Canadiens coach Scotty Bowman inserted their goon
of the year, Gilles Lupien, into the lineup. Lupien and defenseman
Butch Bouchard triggered a brawl and mopped up on a bunch of
smaller Bruins on the ice at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, the Bruins were due to practice right after the
Canadiens on the Forum ice. The Bruins' colorful coach, Don Cherry,
got to the rink while Montreal was still working out and sent one
of the trainers into the Boston dressing room to fetch tough guys
Stan Jonathan and John Wensink. Cherry had not dressed Wensink for
the first game and was upest that he hadn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scotty,'' Cherry bellowed across the ice, bringing the
Canadiens' practice to a halt. ``You got us last night. I was
stupid not to dress this guy'' _ he pointed to Wensink _ ``but
he'll play every game the rest of the way and we're going to be
looking for those two guys.'' Cherry pointed to Lupien and
Bouchard.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadiens won Game 2, but when the series returned to
Boston, Cherry set Jonathan and Wensink loose in the third game,
and they pummeled Lupien and Bouchard into submission. It was the
critical point in the series. The Bruins had to put up, and they
did. The Bruins were back in the series and should have won. They
had the seventh and deciding game apparently in hand in Montreal
when the game officials came to the rescue, calling two phantom
penalties in the final 10 minutes to help the Canadiens get two
power-play goals. Then came the notorious too-many-men-on-the-ice
call vs. Boston in the closing minutes, setting up Montreal's tying
goal and forcing overtime, in which the Canadiens scored. They went
on to win another Cup.
</P>
<P>
   When discussing dynasties, even though the Canadiens were great,
never put them up with the Celtics, Yankees, or even the
present-day Bulls. Montreal controlled the NHL. It was not only the
site of league headquarters, but all the referees were Canadian.
And when Montreal was in trouble, the officials came to the rescue.
That was a given.
</P>
<P>
   This Bulls team is terrific but not an all-timer. The Celtics,
Lakers, and 76ers of the Wilt Chamberlain era were much better at
center and deeper on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
