<SLUG> BC-GM-STRIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM CHAIRMAN CALLS FOR STRIKE RESOLUTION
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By NICHOLE M. CHRISTIAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. _ The chairman of the General Motors Corp. called
Friday for a speedy resolution of the two-week strike that has shut
down virtually all of the carmaker's North American assembly plants
and idled nearly 100,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are committed to reaching a settlement as quickly as
possible,'' John F. Smith, GM's chairman and chief executive, said
here during commencement ceremonies at Kettering University, the
former General Motors Institute. The school is the alma mater of
one-fourth of GM's 72 corporate officers. ``Right now, nothing is
more important.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith's comments came as President Clinton also urged GM and the
United Auto Workers to work out their differences. But while these
high-level calls for labor peace were being made, another 5,000 GM
workers were sent home, this time from the Lordstown, Ohio, car
plant and the company also closed a plant in Silao, Mexico, which
had 2,455 workers. That brings to 23 the number of GM assembly
factories shut since the strikes began on June 5.
</P>
<P>
   All told, the company has laid off 105,500 workers, not
including the 9,200 walking the picket line outside two parts
factories here. Only seven GM factories remain open, mainly
nonessential small-car assembly plants, which make cars that are
significantly less profitable for GM than its trucks and and sport
utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the automaker was under pressure to become a more
efficient global player. ``We must have an agreement that allows us
to meet the demands of this changing marketplace,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's layoffs heightened concern among industry analysts and
observers that GM and the United Auto Workers will not be able to
broker a settlement and restart production before the automaker's
annual two-week summer shutdown, which is to begin June 29. Also,
the UAW's top strategists, and even some Flint union leaders, are
in Las Vegas for a convention that began on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if they came to a resolution over the weekend,'' said
Mike Robinet, managing director of CSM Forecasting in Farmington
Hills, Mich., ``it would take three to five days to vote on it,
ratify it and refill the pipeline of parts. GM isn't going to bring
people back for one or two days then send them home for a
vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   A GM spokesman said, however, that given a quick settlement, the
company could cancel its vacation and restart production, at least
at the Flint factories.
</P>
<P>
   No matter when a resolution is achieved, some analysts say it
will be difficult for GM to recoup lost production capacity, which
Robinet calculated at 114,000 cars and trucks as of Friday. Wall
Street analysts estimate that the strike is costing GM $60 million
a day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
