<HEADER>
A7917 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPORTS-MEDIA-TEX     06-19 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-MEDIA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LESS SCORING, NO STARS PLAGUE WORLD CUP, NHL TV RATINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the surface, hockey and soccer don't seem to have much in
common, one game being played on ice, the other on turf. When it
comes to TV, though, the two sports share a problem _ attracting
viewer interest.
</P>
<P>
   Each has a devoted live following; NHL arenas in North America
and soccer stadiums around the globe are packed for big games. But,
as the NHL playoffs on Fox and ESPN proved again and as the initial
games of World Cup coverage showed, neither sport has been able to
attract much more than a hard-core following in the living room.
</P>
<P>
   Hockey ratings stunk all season, and the Stanley Cup playoffs
didn't help matters.
</P>
<P>
   As for the first TV appearance by the American squad in this
year's World Cup soccer tournament, it didn't measure up to the
ratings for Team USA's matches in the 1994 World Cup and couldn't
even outpoint the soap it pre-empted, ``General Hospital''.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe tomorrow's Team USA match against Iran will provide a
ratings windfall, if only for jingoistic reasons.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe the NHL will surge in popularity next season.
</P>
<P>
   But don't bet on it.
</P>
<P>
   Discussions of why hockey fails to attract a wider TV audience
usually focus on these issues: The puck's too small to follow, the
sport's not indigenous to enough of the American population and
there aren't any individual stars to lure viewers.
</P>
<P>
   All real problems.
</P>
<P>
   Soccer has a whole other set of woes in this country, the main
one being that most of us don't care about the game past the youth
level.
</P>
<P>
   Both sports, however, die on TV for other reasons, problems that
aren't easily fixed by technology or rule changes.
</P>
<P>
   Hockey and soccer are generally low-scoring games played on
large surfaces by hard-to-identify players. And both sports have an
ebb-and-flow rhythm fully appreciated only by true students of the
games.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing is more exciting than a legitimate scoring chance in
hockey or in soccer, whether a goal results or not. But the casual
fan is not likely to stay tuned waiting for those occasional
moments to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   That each game is spread out over a large area, which TV can't
readily capture in a single shot, makes it all the harder to follow
the action and to see the offensive and defensive strategies that
lead to those scoring opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   More popular TV sports like football and basketball don't have
such problems. Football resets the action after every play,
allowing for slow-motion replays and analysis. Basketball is played
in a more confined space, and key plays usually amount to
one-on-one confrontations that are both intimate and easy to
televise.
</P>
<P>
   There are other reasons Game 7 of this year's NBA Finals drew a
22.3 TV rating while the U.S.-vs.-Germany soccer match pulled only
a 4.4 Monday, and Game 1 of the Stanley Cup Finals rated just a
3.3.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan, for one.
</P>
<P>
   There are some possible solutions, too. The NHL, for instance,
is trying to promote increased scoring by reigning in
obstructionist defensive schemes, and TV has offered innovations
like the glowing puck.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest roadblocks to attracting a larger TV audience for
either hockey or soccer may be endemic to the games themselves,
however, and no amount of technology or effort by the networks or
leagues may be able to overcome that. &QL; 
BAD MAGIC &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After Terry Bradshaw was sacked as host of his own TV show
earlier this year, you'd think the Ex-Jock Society would've sent
out a memo urging all would-be Lettermans to stick to sports.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe they did, and poor Earvin Johnson didn't get his.
</P>
<P>
   How else to explain ``The Magic Hour'', a waste of 60 minutes of
air time if ever there was one.
</P>
<P>
   Magic, by all accounts, is one nice guy. He's lauded for
launching business ventures in America's inner cities and for
preaching safe sex to all. He's also been a great champion and has
a smile with more juice than a nuke plant.
</P>
<P>
   But that's a pretty flimsy reason to give him an hourlong TV
show every night. It's embarrassing to watch Johnson fumble about
on stage, lacking the wit and timing of a professional comedian or
the sophistication and backgrounding of a good interviewer.
</P>
<P>
   One or the other, or both, are essential to successfully be host
of a late night talk show.
</P>
<P>
   In one program last week, viewers got to see Magic share a camel
ride with percussionist bandleader Sheila E. and a stroke session
with the Chicago Bulls' Ron Harper.
</P>
<P>
   Harper stole the show.
</P>
<P>
   Now that's something that never would have happened on the
court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 1901EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
