<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7918 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLAYER-MUSIC-REVIEW-N     06-19 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLAYER-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLAYER: THE RHYTHM AND RHYME OF VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BEN RATLIFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's hard not to resort to metaphor in describing a
Slayer concert, because what you're confronted with is both
kinetically massive and uniform, blank, detailless.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986 the band recorded ``Reign in Blood,'' an album that's
still the primary sacrament of death-metal; the short, powerful
record mixed the rhythms of hardcore punk with a single-minded
focus on ritual violence.
</P>
<P>
   As a lot of defunct death-metal bands have since found out,
carnage and devilry are a tricky songwriting trope: Unless you make
a living as a torturer, you can only imagine it in so many ways
before you get tangled up in cliches and the clunky Victorianisms
that go so well with decadent themes.
</P>
<P>
   But metal, for some reason, continues to need words, and where
they were prolific in the '80s, now the band's songwriters squeeze
out a batch of malevolent scenarios every three years or so.
``Imagine humanity's decline,'' sings Tom Araya in one of the
band's songs on its new album, ``Diabolus in Musica'' (Columbia ).
``Step inside my stain of mind/infesting superiority/infectious
immorality, oh yea.''
</P>
<P>
   Let the metaphors begin, oh yea: Watching Slayer's show at
Irving Plaza on Wednesday night was no more or less interesting
than watching an enormous furnace for 90 minutes. It was also like
being crushed by an archetype.
</P>
<P>
   Slayer constructed the language of death-metal, and in concert
they set about deploying it purely, with as little variation as
possible. This enforces the in-crowd aspect of the music. If you
have to ask at this point, you'll never know.
</P>
<P>
   The drummer Paul Bostaph began the show with a few triplet
rhythms that gave way to single slablike beats, spaced apart; it
was a teasing ritual. Then the speed-metal of ``Hell Awaits''
began. Typically, the songs flickered between thrashing two-beat
rhythms and a starchily funky four, with a flowing, histrionic
high-note guitar solo nailed somewhere in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Slayer's pleasures are purely physical; some of the show's best
moments were the pockets of winded silence after the band had ended
a 400 beats-per-minute song and before the fans could physically
raise a cheer.
</P>
<P>
   Eight of the 11 songs on ``Diabolus in Musica,'' a few of which
were played at the show, are in the same gray key, a detuned E
minor. Other major metal bands _ Pantera, Metallica, Megadeth _ at
this point, more than a decade into their careers, are hot-colored
and diverse by comparison. In a career-retrospective show like the
one at Irving Plaza, you can feel it's all one barreling song.
</P>
<P>
   Slayer's impact is bigger than even a large club like Irving
Plaza ought to withstand; the band's massive sound-board, to the
rear of the room, displaced about 100 people. But previous shows at
larger halls have proved that Slayer fans and furniture of any kind
_ even chairs bolted to the floor _ do not mix.
</P>
<P>
   At Irving Plaza, a whole new crop of young fans filled the
floor, becoming an eruption of arms, legs and hair. They knew the
coordinates, yelling every refrain; for ``Angel of Death,'' the
final song, the air in front of the stage rained with stage-divers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 1901EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980619.0284 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7920 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMATEUR-ROCKET-BOS &LR;      06-19 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMATEUR-ROCKET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMATEUR ROCKET SET FOR SPACE LAUNCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's an unlikely combination: A helium balloon carrying aloft a
10-foot-tall rocket, built entirely by amateur space enthusiasts
and fueled by asphalt and laughing gas.
</P>
<P>
   But if all goes as planned, the balloon will rise from a
NASA-supplied barge in the Gulf of Mexico Saturday morning and,
after reaching an altitude of about 20 miles, will fire the rocket
out into space _ and into the history books.
</P>
<P>
   If it works, it will be the first rocket built by amateurs ever
to reach space _ defined by the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration as an altitude of 50 nautical miles, or 57.5 statute
miles. It will also be the first trip into space by a rocket of its
type _ a ``hybrid rocket'' using a solid fuel (ordinary asphalt)
and a liquid oxidizer (nitrous oxide, or laughing gas, stored under
pressure in liquid form).
</P>
<P>
   The novel balloon-launch method has been tried once before by
the group, the Huntsville Alabama L5 Society (HAL5), a chapter of
the National Space Society, which promotes the exploration and
eventual human colonization of space. That earlier launch, on May
11, 1997, was not tracked accurately enough to determine its
highest altitude, but is believed to have reached about 30 miles _
well short of today's goal of reaching the fringes of space. Still,
it qualified as the world's first balloon launch of a hybrid
rocket.
</P>
<P>
   If the weather doesn't cooperate for the launch, the group plans
to try again Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Launching a rocket from a balloon _ the combination is called a
``rockoon'' _ is not just a stunt. The group hopes it could pave
the way for practical, low-cost rockets that could be used to carry
experiments briefly into space, for a few minutes at a time, to
conduct experiments for students and scientists.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the ``rockoon'' concept was pioneered back in the 1950s
by space scientist James Van Allen, discoverer of the Earth's
radiation belt. He used several such rockets to conduct some of the
nation's earliest scientific experiments in space.
</P>
<P>
   The advantage of the method is that the balloon can carry the
rocket above 99 percent of the atmosphere, reducing greatly the
amount of atmospheric drag it has to punch through. Thus, even a
relatively small rocket can reach heights many times greater than
it could if launched from the ground.
</P>
<P>
   As for the unusual fuel combination, it is a new version of a
kind of ``hybrid'' technology that was tried unsuccessfully a few
years ago by a private venture called American Rocket Co. The idea
is to combine the simplicity of a solid-fuel rocket _ similar to
the space shuttle's Solid Rocket Boosters, which require no
complicated fuel pumps and nozzles _ with the greater safety of a
liquid-fueled rocket, which cannot be accidentally set off by a
stray spark as solid-fueled rockets can.
</P>
<P>
   The unusual design of the home-built rocket is a product of the
inventiveness and enthusiasm of its builders, a band of inveterate
tinkerers dedicated to a vision of humanity's future in space. Tim
Pickens, a member of the group who is in charge of the rocket
system, wrote after last year's launch that ``I love a
challenge.... I can't go to the hardware store or even to the
grocery store with my wife without trying to transform something on
the shelf into usable rocket hardware.''
</P>
<P>
   NASA, which is interested in pursuing low-cost alternatives for
scientific research flights that are typically carried by
multimillion-dollar sounding rockets, is helping out by providing
some money and equipment, including the barge that will be used as
a launch platform in the Gulf 60 miles out from New Orleans, and
helium for the 120-foot-high balloon.
</P>
<P>
   But the rocket itself, the balloon that will carry it, and its
camera and radio equipment _ which, the group hopes, will transmit
live pictures of the launch, both from the balloon and from the
rocket itself _ were all built entirely by members of the amateur
group. They call the project HALO, for High-Altitude Lift-Off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our hope that Project HALO will demonstrate that extreme
altitudes are reachable by amateurs,'' wrote project manager
Gregory Allison. ``We hope to help lay the groundwork of
organization, technology, and imagination that will make cheap
access to space a reality for all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 1902EDT &QL; 
