<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV21-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BEAR TRAP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 21 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whether last week's surprise intervention in the currency
markets works or not to prevent the Asian crisis from becoming a
global nightmare, you've got to admire the Clinton administration's
verve &UR;  &LR; in trying.
</P>
<P>
   Never in its nearly six years has the administration more
sharply wielded the enormous power of the government to affect
events _ nor has the meager power of the press to deflect their
onrush been more conspicuously displayed.
</P>
<P>
   While the chattering classes went on about the self-deflating
exhibitionism of Monica Lewinsky and Kenneth Starr in ``Vanity
Fair'' and ``Brill's Content,'' the Treasury Department contrived
one last powerful attempt to persuade the Japanese to act to
reignite their economy. Moreover, while independent counsel Starr
vainly fulminated against his critics (having abandoned momentarily
at least his attempts to build bridges to sympathetic reporters),
Treasury officials put on a textbook display of good press
relations.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning, shortly after currency markets participants
discovered that the US government was buying yen in sufficient
volume to guarantee a short-term rise in its value, Treasury
Secretary Robert Rubin confirmed that the Japanese and American
governments were seeking to stem the currency's fall. Clinton
himself talked to reporters briefly in the Rose Garden as the
Federal Reserve Bank of New York shocked currency traders by buying
$2 billion worth of yen with dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin's ploy was a classic ``bear trap,'' a maneuver designed to
squeeze short-sellers, traders who had made large bets that the
value of the yen would continue to fall. The treasury secretary had
been a legendary currency trader himself while cochairman of
Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co., the big Wall Street firm.
</P>
<P>
   He set the trap the week before by feigning elaborate unconcern
_ then sprung it after a series of top secret negotiations Tuesday
night with his counterparts in Tokyo that were designed to
galvanize the Japanese to act. Fortunes were lost by traders who
had shorted the yen. Well-informed stories on the campaign
blossomed overnight in The New York Times, The Washington Post, The
Wall Street Journal, and The Financial Times.
</P>
<P>
   The joint US-Japanese action came as China appeared to totter on
the brink of pursuing a policy of competitive devaluation of its
currency, the yuan _ a move that, while aimed at self-preservation,
could tumble the world economy into a disastrous recession at the
worst possible time.
</P>
<P>
   China's currency (and that of Hong Kong) is tied to the US
dollar by its central bank's policies. Thus Chinese export prices
have been soaring relative to its Asian neighbors, especially the
Indonesians and South Koreans. Export sales are falling; job growth
has slowed.
</P>
<P>
   The official Chinese position has been that a devaluation would
serve no useful purpose; so weak is the Asian market that lower
prices would benefit Chinese firms little if at all, while
increasing levels of indebtedness throughout Asia and sending
tremors through markets as far away as Russia and the Middle East.
Privately, the Chinese with increasing urgency have been pleading
with the United States and Japan to act together to halt the fall
of the yen.
</P>
<P>
   Three times in the past 15 years, governments of the industrial
nations have acted in concert to impose a particular order on the
vast flows of funds that are the world currency markets, always
with the understanding that free-spending treasuries could have
only temporary effects if underlying policies were not changed.
</P>
<P>
   Three times they were successful: in 1985, when the Plaza Accord
sought to stem the rise of the dollar against the yen that had been
precipitated by America's bourgeoning federal budget deficit; in
1988, when the Louvre Accord brought an end to the yen's
appreciation; and in 1995, when the Clinton administration
intervened to boost the falling dollar. Never, however, has quite
so much depended on the outcome of their acts.
</P>
<P>
   The basic problem for Japan is much like the one that threatened
the United States during the late 1980s and early 1990s in the
savings and loan crisis _ a binge of ill-judged lending stimulated
by easy money and lax supervision _ only three times larger in an
economy only half as big.
</P>
<P>
   Mustering the political will to write off bank loans as
unrecoverable and to close companies as a result is no easier for
the Japanese than it was for the Americans. So far, the government
has refused to abandon its ``convoy system,'' whereby strong
companies act to keep week companies afloat.
</P>
<P>
   It took the United States 10 years to decisively narrow its
budget deficit. The period of Japan's embarrassment is going on
only seven years. There is a significant difference, however: The
American economy continued to grow robustly, serving as an engine
of sorts for the world economy, while the Japanese economy has
stagnated to the deteriment of its trading partners.
</P>
<P>
   After springing his trap on Wednesday, Rubin dispatched an
urgent mission led by Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers
and New York Federal Reserve Bank chief William McDonough to press
the Japanese for further financial reforms. Top treasury and bank
aides from the other leading industrial nations _ the Group of
Seven _ were scheduled to join them on the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   There is no particular reason to expect the intervention to work
_ except that the damage to the world economy will be so enormous
if it fails.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
