<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLD-NIGERIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIGERIA VICTORIOUS OVER BULGARIA, 1-0 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Nigeria's Super Eagles represent the hopes of millions
of West Africans. And after a 1-0 victory over Bulgaria Friday,
combined with the failures of the other African teams in the World
Cup finals, their constituency is about to increase.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria became the first African team to qualify for the second
round of this tournament as African player of the year Victor
Ikpeba concluded a lightning series of passes in the 26th minute.
The Nigerians then protected the advantage _ barely, though _ as
Emil Kostadinov cracked a close-in shot off the bar with five
minutes remaining in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bora Milutinovic defied convention by adding three
attackers as substitutes rather than drawing Nigeria into a
defensive shell _ a strategy that proved unsuccessful when the
Eagles were eliminated by Italy at Foxboro Stadium during the '94
World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best defense is to attack,'' Milutinovic said. ``Not just
for Nigeria, but for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Milutinovic's philosophy was the opposite when he coached the
US, but ``the best defense is a good offense'' reflects the
character of this Nigeria team _ confidence bordering on arrogance,
plus creative, uninhibited offensive instincts. When Nigeria won
the 1996 Olympic tournament, it rallied from a two-goal deficit to
eliminate Brazil and twice came from behind to defeat Argentina in
the final.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nigeria is a place where everyone thinks we have the materials
and if we don't win, it is not the players' fault but the fault of
the coach,'' said midfielder Finidi, who dropped his last name to
emulate the Brazilian tradition. ``I can't say how we will do in
the next round, but we are looking forward to it. Every player's
dream is to win the World Cup, but that is not an easy thing to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Cameroon, Morocco, South Africa, and Tunisia are winless,
the Nigerians could be the only team from the continent to advance.
This mixture of spectacular failure and success mirrors the
potential and the tragedy of a continent considered to be a
sleeping giant.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria has about 100 million citizens, representing one-fifth
of the population of the continent. The country has great natural
resources, especially in oil, and a capable, diverse populace. But
through corruption, mismanagement, and the failure to expand its
economy, Nigeria has dropped from having one of the world's highest
gross domestic products in the 1970s and '80s to being rated among
the 20 poorest nations.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the decline in prestige of their country, the Super
Eagles have attained their greatest successes recently. In 1994,
they won the African Nations Cup and came within an 89th-minute
Roberto Baggio goal of qualifying for the World Cup quarterfinals.
In '96, they won the Olympic title.
</P>
<P>
   They are on the verge of validating what some have expected for
many years.
</P>
<P>
   When African teams were allowed into the World Cup finals in the
1970s, they were dismissed as disorganized and inexperienced at
best. Sir Stanley Rous, then president of the Federation
Internationale de Football Association, encountered almost
universal skepticism when he predicted that the Africans would win
the World Cup before the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
   Africans lacked the resources to succeed as the colonial era
ended. There was a lack of professionalism since few played in
European leagues. The best African players, such as Eusebio and
Mario Coluna of Mozambique and Portugal, represented colonial
powers in international competitions. Africans had to contend with
misconceptions and stereotypes, and _ most crucially _ only one
team from the continent was allowed into the World Cup finals.
Sub-Saharan nations advanced to the finals only once before the
1980s, and Zaire was humiliated during the 1974 tournament in
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Brazilian Joao Havelange deposed Rous for the FIFA presidency in
1974 by promising the Africans an increased role in the world game.
Havelange was a Machiavellian ruler but also a visionary who
overruled the preponderance of doubters in awarding the '94 World
Cup to the United States. Havelange, whose term as president ends
July 12, made certain Africa was supplied with resources, mostly
training for coaches and referees; the passion and talent already
existed in potential players.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, Algeria upset Germany, 2-1, and Cameroon was eliminated
after the first round despite going undefeated. The Cameroonians,
who have qualified for four of the last five finals, shocked
Argentina in the opening match of 1990 but failed to win at USA '94
and so far at France '98.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria has taken up where Cameroon left off. Yet, like the
other African teams which have had success in the World Cup,
Nigeria is relying on a foreign coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe in ourselves and we believe in our coach,'' said
Austin Okocha, who along with Daniel Amokachi set up the goal
against Bulgaria. ``We employed him because we know he has gone far
in the World Cup before. The first time you meet him, you know he
is a good person, someone you can talk to, even about your personal
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have more maturity than in 1994. We are different people
with a different mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria tried one native coach since Dutchman Clemence Westerhof
departed in 1994 but won the Olympics with Dutchman Jo Bonfrere,
qualified for the World Cup under Frenchman Phillipe Troussier,
then threatened to fire Milutinovic if he lost to Spain in the
World Cup opener. But the Super Eagles _ they were merely
``Eagles'' before winning the Olympic title _ rallied for a 3-2
victory over Spain on Sunday Oliseh's dramatic late volley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have so much talent, that is our problem,'' Milutinovic
said. ``They didn't always work so much, but now they understand
they have to work hard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
