<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-LOUDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPERBIKE TOUR LEADER DUHAMEL FRACTURES ARM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ Honda rider Miguel Duhamel arrived at New
Hamsphire International Speedway as the new leader of the American
Motorcycle Association Pro Series Superbike Tour point standings.
But Duhamel's ride at the top came to an abrupt halt when the
31-year-old native of LaSalle, Quebec, departed NHIS in an
ambulance, his left femur and his hopes for a championship
shattered.
</P>
<P>
   Duhamel suffered a season-ending double compound fracture 7 1/2
minutes into Friday's qualifying session for the 75th Loudon
Classic. He went into Turn 1 at 76 miles per hour, skidded past the
entrance in slippery track conditions, and slammed into the wall.
According to a witness, Duhamel locked up his brakes, went straight
for the wall, and slammed into it. He wound up getting pinched
between his bike and the wall and popped up in the air before
landing on the asphalt face-first.
</P>
<P>
   Duhamel, who won four consecutive Superbike events to surge to a
7-point lead over Kawasaki rider Doug Chandler (236-229), was
evaluated at the track's hospital and transported to Concord
Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's awake and he's talking,'' said Gary Mathers, manager of
motorcycle sports for American Honda. ``And he's disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   Mathers said Duhamel was expected to be out for five to seven
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he knew what might have caused the accident, Mathers
said, ``Yeah, I think it was rain. I think you can't turn left in
the pouring rain. It just started to rain and they were in the
qualifying session. Of course, they all wanted to get the fast lap
in case they don't get to qualify again (in Saturday's final
Superbike session).
</P>
<P>
   ``What we always tell the riders is that they're the first ones
to know when they get rain on their goggles,'' Mathers added. ``We
always tell them if it rains to come in. But riders are riders.''
</P>
<P>
   Duhamel had posted the second-fastest lap of the one-hour
qualifying session with a tour of 1 minute 14.482 seconds, .10
seconds off the pace set by Suzuki rider Mathew Mladin (1:14.472).
At the time of Duhamel's accident, a cloudburst erupted over the
south end of the track near the first turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``He probably thought he could do just one more fast lap,''
Mathers said. ``Apparently, it was only raining hard down in that
corner there. It moved in from that corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other riders sustained serious injuries. Superbike rider
Thomas Wilson of Oregon, Ohio, suffered fractures to both legs and
his pelvis region when he crashed his Harley-Davidson in Turn 1
during Fridaythe morning practice session. Wilson was taken to
Concord Hospital and transferred to Dartmouth Hitchcock Medical
Center in Lebanon for further treatment of his pelvic injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Metzger of Newington, Conn., crashed exiting Turn 12 and
sustained a possible head injury while practicing on his Suzuki. He
was also transported to Concord Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Miguel crashed at Daytona (and finished 58th), it just
about took us clear out of the championship,'' Mathers said.
``After Daytona, our second race, we had a meeting and said, `Look,
it's mathematically possible to get back into it.' We did our part
when Miguel won four races. Coming into this race was the first
time we were back in the points. So we came all the way back from
nothing to get back into the hunt, but now we're out of it again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
