<HEADER>
A7939 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-MULAN-BOS &LR;      06-19 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-MULAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MULAN' A WINNER, IF NOT IN THE DISNEY MOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
MULAN 
Directed by: Barry Cook, Tony Bancroft 
Screenplay by: Rita Hsiao, Christopher Sanders, Philip Lazebnik,
Raymond Singer, Eugenia Bostwick-Singer 
With the voices of: Ming-Na Wen (sung by Lea Salonga), B.D. Wong
(sung by Donny Osmond), Eddie Murphy, Harvey Fierstein, Miguel
Ferrer, Jerry S. Tondo, Gedde Watanabe (sung by Matthew Wilder),
Soon-Tek Oh, Freda Foh Shen, Pat Morita, June Foray (sung by Marni
Nixon) 
Running time: 87 minutes 
Rated: G 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Female empowerment isn't exactly new to Disney, given ``Beauty
and the Beast,'' ``The Little Mermaid,'' ``Snow White and the Seven
Dwarfs,'' and a few other titles. But ``Mulan,'' Disney's new
animation about a young woman in old China who disguises herself as
a man to take her ailing father's place as a soldier and saves the
country, moves the theme and the Disney formula a big step forward.
After a few recent sub-par efforts, ``Mulan'' bracingly and
captivatingly reinvigorates the Disney animation line. Sporting the
look and feel of an instant classic, it's the studio's strongest,
freshest entry since ``The Lion King.''
</P>
<P>
   With Chinese art influencing the look of ``Mulan,'' it's not
only stylistically innovative, but the first full-length feature
out of Disney's Orlando facility. Given the chance to show what it
could do, the Orlando team vaults past its more established Burbank
colleagues to emerge as Disney's new animation pace-setters.
Luckily, the project kicked around long enough to have been rescued
from its original incarnation as a short, titled _ with consummate
political incorrectness and insensitivity _ ``China Doll.'' Far
from being a cute mannequin looking for the right prince, however,
``Mulan'' is Disney's most vital and complex animated heroine ever.
</P>
<P>
   Not until the very end does the possibility of love enter the
picture. Mulan, to whom the maidenly arts do not come naturally
anyway, has too much work to do. The antithesis of passivity, she's
tough, smart, opinionated, driven by honor and duty. Fearing her
father won't survive another army hitch, she chops off her hair,
dons his armor, and rides off to defend her country against the
fearsome chieftain of the Huns, Shan-Yu, who, as voiced by Mel
Ferrer, sounds as looming as he looks. Although she's accompanied
by the usual Disney comic sidekick, a shrimpy ancestral dragon who
looks like the perpetually disheveled cat from the old comic strip,
Bloom County, she never sits back waiting for supernatural
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   She's tough, passionate and smart _ a fact brought home in the
film's climax, when she outsmarts Shan-Yu and the Huns on a snowy
battlefield, even though they vastly outnumber the gallant little
Chinese army. Just as ``The Lion King'' suggested a familiarity
with ``Triumph of the Will'' and a few other film classics, this
one reinvents Eisenstein's famous battle on the ice from
``Alexander Nevsky'' (Kurosawa reinvented it, too, in ``Ran''). The
computer-generated parts of the scene never advertise themselves or
get in the way of the grandest, most sweeping tableaux since ``Lion
King.'' There's a lot more sophistication in ``Mulan'' than is
immediately apparent, including an air of cool independence.
</P>
<P>
   The artists also skillfully integrate the conventions of Chinese
art _ from the misty landscapes to Mulan's stylized horse _ into
the story, which, by the way, has the boldness to make the leading
male role, the brave but untried captain Shang, clearly subordinate
to Mulan. She even looks less like a young woman than any previous
Disney heroine. The scenes of her toughening herself up during
basic training could have come right out of ``G.I. Jane.'' She wins
over a rough trio of fellow recruits, who naturally become her best
buddies. Even at the end, when she's unmasked as a girl, and finds
herself in trouble from which only the emperor can extract her, she
compels the respect she earned from everybody, including Shang,
whose life she saved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mulan'' is a warrior all the way. Her zestfulness and
innovation incline you to overlook, or at least minimize, Disney's
clinging to formula in the framework surrounding her, by which I
include the music, which sounds machine-made, as almost all the
music in Disney animations does. It's wallpaper for the ears, but
does no serious harm to Ming-Na Wan's voicing (and Lea Salonga's
singing) of Mulan, B.D. Wong's (sung by Donny Osmond) physically
brave but emotionally timid Shang, Murphy's scene-stealing dragon
named Mushu, and the others, ranging from Harvey Fierstein's army
buddy to Pat Morita's emperor. (Anticipating ethnic sensitivities,
Disney has prominently, and with a prudent eye to political
correctness, cast Asian actors in the speaking and singing roles;
Mulan's untraditional expression of indiviaulity and emotion will
strike a repsonsive chord among emerging Asian women of today.)
</P>
<P>
   Some Hollywood observers predict ``Mulan'' will face an uphill
battle because it's different. In my view, this is its strength.
``Mulan'' is not even that different, but it's different enough,
even though it has been calculated to present audiences with enough
reassuringly familiar Disney animation trademarks to hedge its
bets. Hollywood studio execs usually assume people want the same
old thing until they're surprised by how people react to newness
and departure from familiarity. ``The Truman Show'' is proving
that. ``Mulan'' will continue to prove it. Although it's Chinese
culture Disneyfied, it pulls far enough away from the Disney
formula to make you wish it had shown more of Mulan's independence
and moved even farther. ``Mulan'' is a winner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 1911EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
