<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-LYRES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LYRES: STILL `ON FYRE' AFTER 22 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jeff Conolly, singer-organist of the Lyres, works in used record
stores by day and proudly plies the trade of garage rock by night.
Here's what he says about his chosen field of music: ``Garage rock
goes up and down (in popularity), but the people are always the
same: At the lower spectrum of the food chain of rock 'n' roll.
We're at the bottom, essentially, where there's a lot more
infighting and backbiting.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet ...
</P>
<P>
   When the Boston-based Lyres are on _ Conolly playing his Vox
Continental one-handed, shaking a tambourine with the other, and
scream-singing, with his three mates pumping away _ life does not
get much better. At least in that moment. The sentiments in the
songs are pretty simple _ ``I wanna help you Ann!,'' ``Don't give
it up now!,'' ``Trying just to please you!'' _ but the music is
swirling, the power and passion undeniable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really very good with lyrics and stuff,'' Conolly
says, ``so I try to make up for it with rhythms.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lyres have been with us, off and on, for 22 years. They were
formed out of the ashes of the band DMZ, which had a brief unhappy
life on Sire in the 1970s. Signed to Rick Harte's Ace of Hearts
label, the Lyres hit a peak in the mid-1980s _ there was a
four-year period Conolly says when the band was his only means of
support _ and disintegrated in 1988. Conolly split Boston for what
he believed to be the garage-rock mecca of San Diego, and formed a
Lyres with a different lineup. The band lasted a few months and
made no records. ``It was a cultural wasteland out there,'' says
Conolly, ``all yard sales and flea markets. I went because I
thought if I pulled the plug I could reinvent myself out there.''
In 1990, Conolly returned to Boston and the Lyres were reborn
again.
</P>
<P>
   A number of players have passed through the portals, but Conolly
is proud to state the current version is the longest-lasting to
date, more than four years. It includes cofounders, drummer Paul
Murphy and bassist Rick Coraccio, and guitarist Steve Aquino. Why
so many lineup changes?
</P>
<P>
   ``People say, `Jeff Conolly is cantankerous, volatile, and hard
to work with,''' says Conolly, and indeed people have said those
words. ``I've always had to take the rap, but it's garage rock
itself that's the fall guy. There's no money in garage rock, no
garage rock band ever has ever lasted more than a few years.''
Intact, at least. The Fleshtones and ? and Mysterians play on, and
the Lyres joined both bands for a glorious night of rocking a few
months back at the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   The Lyres are celebrating a remastered four-CD re-release of the
discs ``Lyres,'' ``Lyres Lyres,'' ``On Fyre,'' and ``A Promise Is a
Promise'' on Matador. ``I'm a little bit proud of myself,'' Conolly
admits. ``It was a six-year project and was very slow going, but we
got to Matador right when we were ready for them to take care of
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Conolly says the remastering process was done at Sterling
studios in New York by the same people involved with the Jimi
Hendrix and Led Zeppelin remasters. He calls the sound ``10 times
hotter'' than the original Lyres albums, adding, ``It's not phony,
no remixing or any of that junk.''
</P>
<P>
   If you only want to buy one, Conolly says, ``the smart money is
on `On Fyre.' That's what the project began with and the one I
cared about most.'' Agreed. The Lyres do beautiful justice to two
Kinks songs, ``Tired of Waiting'' and ``Love Me Till the Sun
Shines,'' and it features their best work including, ``She Pays the
Rent,'' ``Help You Ann,'' and ``Don't Give It Up Now.''
</P>
<P>
   Conolly, nicknamed Monoman for his love of monoaural sound, has
come to terms with his status in the pop world. ``We used to be
successful in the '80s because back then WBCN would play our
records,'' he says, ``which they don't do anymore. ... I'm starting
to become more content with my lot in the whole scheme of things.
I'm not as frustrated as I used to be. I'm not as upset. I don't
get messed up, either. I don't really need that right now. The
music does it for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lyres go into the studio Sunday to work on a new song, ``(We
Ain't Got) Nothing Apart,'' and Conolly promises, ``I'm gonna have
a full-length record out, and a good one, before the millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   As to the garage rock genre _ experiencing a mini-rebirth at
present _ Conolly says, ``it keeps getting reinvented. There's a
continued interest in it, because over time, people realize the
stupider you get in rock _ well, it's a natural thing, to be stupid
and dumb. The more scholarly you get, the shorter the lifespan. It
will always be there, but it's always taken for granted, too. Once
in a while, you feel like giving up, but there's something that
makes you wanna keep doing it. It gets me out of the house.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 1912EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
