<DOCNO> NYT19980619.0295 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7946 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-LOWE-BOS &LR;      06-19 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-LOWE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOWE GEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nick Lowe was once called ``the Jesus of cool'' by an English
rock magazine. He promptly selected that over-the-top praise as the
tongue-in-cheek title of his solo debut album. (In America, it was
changed to ``Pure Pop for Now People.'')
</P>
<P>
   If, Lowe is asked, 20 years ago he was the Jesus of Cool, what
might he be now?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I feel, ummm, I suppose I feel a bit of a grand old man
of Rockdom,'' says the long-graying 49-year-old Lowe. Indeed, he is
profiled in, of all places, the July Esquire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been at it a long time,'' says Lowe, ``but I don't feel
very retro. I think I'm starting to get the hang of it. I think
when you're just doing what you did when you were a kid _ well,
it's so unseemly when you see the old geezers doing that. It just
looks awful.''
</P>
<P>
   Singer-bassist Lowe was one of the bright stars of
late-'70s-early '80s British new wave, as an artist and a producer,
the latter most notably for Elvis Costello. He was hardly a rookie,
having served nobly in the pub-rock group Brinsley Schwartz. He
cofounded Stiff Records, the label that helped give new wave its
early irreverence.
</P>
<P>
   His own pop gems included ``I Love My Label,'' ``(I Love the
Sound of) Breaking Glass,'' ``Heart of the City,'' ``So It Goes,''
``Marie Provost,'' ``Cruel to be Kind,'' ``(What's So Funny 'Bout)
Peace, Love and Understanding.'' He was Paul McCartney with a nod
and a wink. Melody: cheerful. Lyric: semisubversive.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe, who recently released the CD ``Dig My Mood,'' is very much
an artist who's turned a corner, made a transition. To be truthful,
Lowe's been in turnaround mode for some years, ever since leaving
Rockpile, the band he formed with pal Dave Edmunds, in the
mid-'80s. ``The Impossible Bird'' made it clear in 1995, and ``Dig
My Mood'' takes Lowe's remaking a step farther. Where ``The
Impossible Bird'' seemed to rock gently, ``Dig My Mood'' barely
rocks, but draws you in for other reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Even if wit and irony, once primary tools of his trade, are on
holiday. Even if Lowe is not shouting his head off _ he's
caressing, massaging the lyrics. Even if there's no big walloping
backbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've sort of done enough of that,'' Lowe explains prior to a
US tour. ``I can't imagine where I'd ever do that again. ... Europe
seems to be perceiving what I do now more favorably, but I've
noticed over here there's been a number of people who are genuinely
kind of aggrieved _ `Where's the rock?' _ and I don't like to see
people disappointed at my shows. But if they are, they're happy to
drop by the wayside and find someone else for them to relive their
youth through.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dig My Mood'' is an often somber, melancholic, bittersweet
effort. There's plenty of nuance and atmosphere. There's a country
tinge. It's got the intimate feel of a rainy, late night session.
It features Lowe singing, ``The friends I've had are so-called
now/They slipped away somehow,'' and commiserating about being
``lost in lonesome reverie,'' about feeling ``so tired,'' in need
of a holiday. It's not the blues, but feels like the blues.
</P>
<P>
   Has Nick Lowe become a sad sack?
</P>
<P>
   Not at all. ``I certainly don't try and put my diary to music,''
says Lowe. ``It is not an autobiographical thing. That is of no
interest to me. I like pop which is `made up,' but having said
that, I love singing and writing songs that have got some bottom _
I don't mean bass, I mean substance, and in order to do that you've
got to know what it feels like to be blue. If you are blue, you
can't write any songs let alone go into the recording studio and do
them. But you've got to get in a sort of mood. My stick is that I
think depression is an illness, but being blue is a rite of
passage, and it's, in some way, kind of a glorious feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe notes that although he plays a chunk of the new CD in
concert, he dips into his catalog for songs that still make sense.
``Marie Provost'' doesn't make the cut _ ``a gruesome story with a
cheerful melody, it was fun but I can't put that across anymore,
it's too arch.'' ``Cruel to Be Kind'' makes it _ ``my bonafide Top
20 hit!, a very slight thing, but it turns people on.'' He still
knows the bride and the old hippie in him is still asking what's
funny 'bout peace, love, and understanding.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Lowe doesn't earn the bulk of his living from record
sales or concert tickets, but from other people covering his songs.
Huey Lewis and the News made Lowe a pile of money when they did ``I
Knew the Bride,'' and Curtis Stigers made Lowe a cool million when
his rendition of ``(What's So Funny 'Bout) Peace, Love and
Understanding'' graced the mega-platinum soundtrack to ``The
Bodyguard.''
</P>
<P>
   Stigers, Lowe says, has a lifetime offer of four-star restaurant
dining whenever he comes to London and visits. ``Mind you,'' Lowe
cautions, the money ``is all gone, as I plowed it back into the
family firm. It enabled me to do `The Impossible Bird' and gave me
a degree of comfort. I could pay my guys (band) right. I bought a
couple of shirts, took a couple of people out to dinner, and that
has taken care of it. Everything's back to normal now.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe the songwriter describes himself as a canny fisherman,
dangling his hook-packed songs off a line. ``A passing artist tends
to be swimming past,'' says Lowe, ``and they might hear my song and
go `That's a good song, I could do it better than that guy.' Then,
the rod bends, the line goes taut, and you're reeling 'em in, and
you've got a cover and that's really how I earn my living.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
