<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-B52s-PRETENDERS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
  
 B-52s AND PRETENDERS: DIFFERENT STYLES, BUT BOTH IN TOP FORM  
 (bl)  
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In their 1980s heyday the B-52s and the Pretenders were both
considered new- wave rock, which shows how vague a category can be.
</P>
<P>
   The two bands, which began a summer tour together Thursday night
at the PNCBank Arts Center in Holmdel, N.J., shared an era but not
a sensibility. The B-52s turned a few campy jokes into a
fountainhead of giddy, joyful party songs; the Pretenders chronicle
Chrissie Hynde's shifting attitudes, from tough-talking rocker to
affectionate wife and mother.
</P>
<P>
   In Holmdel, both bands were in top form. The B-52s socked out
their garage-rock grooves as Fred Schneider, Kate Pierson and Cindy
Wilson performed every conceivable synchronized arm and wrist
maneuver except the macarena.
</P>
<P>
   And Ms. Hynde _ leading a band that includes drummer Martin
Chambers, the only other surviving member of the original
Pretenders _ brought out all of the swagger and underlying
tenderness in her songs. The tour comes to Radio City Music Hall in
New York City on June 24.
</P>
<P>
   Both bands wrote decidedly unconventional tunes when they
started. The combination of Schneider's nasal talk-singing and the
untutored, fervent belting of Ms. Pierson and Ms. Wilson is
downright peculiar, though satisfying. And through ignorance or
willfulness, their songs use melodies that stop and start and jump
around; ``Mesopotamia'' piles up short, asymmetrical motifs like
pick-up sticks.
</P>
<P>
   Chrissie Hynde's early songs for the Pretenders are dialogues
between her rhythm guitar and voice, with vocal lines tucked
between the chords; later, her voice seized the foreground.
</P>
<P>
   When the B-52s got together in the late 1970s, they resurrected
outre pop artifacts, like the twang of a surf guitar and the hoot
of cheap keyboards; their lyrics were about 1950s-style leisure,
complete with patio parties, and about the future as learned from
space-age cartoons. Lately, bands from the Beastie Boys to the
Propellerheads have rediscovered lounge music and half-forgotten
dance grooves, making the B-52s prescient.
</P>
<P>
   On stage, the B-52s romped through their catalog. With a
miniature disco ball hanging from Schneider's microphone, guitarist
Keith Strickland wearing a cowboy hat, Ms. Wilson in a green
feather boa and Ms. Pierson in a sequined dress that made her look
like a Las Vegas Valkyrie, the band still has an eye for retro
frivolity. Amid songs about a dog dyed green, alien abductions,
strobe lights and the ``Love Shack,''
</P>
<P>
   Schneider delivered the least necessary introduction of all
time: ``This is a dance tune,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hynde, who taught a generation of rock women some ways to be
feisty, simply played a supercharged set. With a voice that shifted
from offhanded sultriness to a thoughtful vibrato, and a band that
adds a little rockabilly twang to the old Pretenders sound, she
moved from elegies to defiance to guarded love songs to vows of
loyalty. A new song, a ballad in Spanish, ponders sadness and hope.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hynde wrested back ``My City Was Gone'' from Rush Limbaugh's
radio show, which used its opening riff, by rearranging the song
without the riff. And in ``Brass in Pocket,'' she enlisted women
from the audience to sing what she had helped teach them: ``I'm
special.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
