A7951 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOB-GAP-COX &UR;  &UR; REPORTCI     06-19 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOB-GAP-COX </SLUG>
     REPORT CITES LOW-SKILL `JOB GAP' IN AUSTIN
 &HT;     Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;     By SAMAR ABULHASSAN 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Austin's employers are not creating enough jobs for
workers with low skills, according to a national report released
Friday, but local officials said they had high hopes of overcoming
the job gap.
</P>
<P>
   Only 12,180 low-skill jobs will become available by 2003 for the
14,229 current welfare recipients expected to enter the local job
market, according to a ``State of the Cities'' report issued by the
U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development (HUD) at a U.S.
Conference of Mayors meeting in Reno, Nev.
</P>
<P>
   The report includes data from a Conference of Mayors survey
predicting that in 74 metropolitan counties, the number of welfare
recipients seeking jobs by 2003 would exceed the available
low-skill jobs by about 350,000. Low-skill jobs include machine
operators, unskilled laborers and those in the food and service
industry, which often require little or no high school education.
</P>
<P>
   As federal welfare reform efforts try to move all able-bodied
recipients into the workplace, ``the challenge is for the nation to
produce jobs on the scale needed to accommodate all of the
households making the transition,'' said J. Thomas Cochran,
executive director of the Conference of Mayors.
</P>
<P>
   But Austin officials say that their city's projected job deficit
_ which projects 1.2 people vying for each low-paying job _ is
relatively small compared to other cities' and is easily
surmountable.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that we have a tight low-skill market,''
said Mayor Kirk Watson. ``But as that period of time goes by, if
we're providing jobs, training and work force skills, those numbers
could change.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a real opportunity by being in a situation where you
have as low as a deficit as this one,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Austin currently has several efforts in place to ease the
transition from public assistance to self-sufficiency, including
the Welfare to Work Coalition, a four-month-old program attempting
to ``bring all the stakeholders together,'' including social
service agencies, to address the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Butler, executive director of the Community Action Network,
which directs the coalition, said, ``the most critical issue is to
get a real understanding of what makes up the population we're
dealing with,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The major factors in moving people off public assistance, Butler
said, is providing job training services, child care and
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is, how do we tie it all together and provide
support services to allow them to move out of self-sufficiency?''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Travis County, there were 3,346 adults on Temporary
Assistance for Needy Families as of this month, or 8,397 people
when children are included, Butler said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the HUD report, the national economy has produced
more than 16 million new jobs in the past five years, with
unemployment at a 28-year low. But the report found that cities are
still suffering from concentrations of poverty, shrinking
populations and inadequate housing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not talking about something insurmountable,'' William
Apgar, a senior HUD official, said in a conference call with
reporters on Friday. ``These problems are well within our reach.''
</P>
<P>
   To combat this problem, the administration wants Congress to
expand or create a number of programs in fiscal 1999, which starts
Oct. 1, including a new $400 million fund to create and retain an
estimated 280,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's ``urban agenda is helping cities continue to
recover from years of decline and making them better places to live
and work,'' HUD Secretary Andrew Cuomo said in a statement. ``This
is a midterm report card with an A grade for cities, but there is
still work to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
