<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-OPPOSITE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICCI'S WICKED WAYS MAKE `OPPOSITE' ATTRACTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
THE OPPOSITE OF SEX 
Directed and written by: Don Roos 
Starring: Christina Ricci, Martin Donovan, Lisa Kudrow, Lyle
Lovett, Johnny Galecki, Ivan Sergei, William Scott Lee 
Running time: 100 minutes 
Rated: R (strong language and sex-related dialogue and sexuality) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Opposite of Sex'' reminds us that a little family
dysfunction goes a long way. There's more dysfunction than the film
can frankly sustain. Still, even though it capsizes, it sports a
tangy performance from Christina Ricci as a would-be sex bomb
armoring herself from her own youth and inexperience with an
icepick tongue. Flawed though the film may be, it's an impressive
move by Ricci beyond juvenile roles into acerbic teen assignments,
keeping the promise of her precocious malcontent in ``The Ice
Storm.''
</P>
<P>
   Although his inventiveness flags, writer-director Don Roos, in
his debut film, certainly keeps Ricci's Dedee supplied with
scorchers that begin flying from her mouth before she's even left
home in Louisiana and keep going in voice-overs when she's not in
scenes. After verbally skewering her mother and a teen lover of the
moment, she complicates the life of her gay half brother, Bill, who
until her arrival had been leading a stable existence as an English
teacher in a small Indiana town, in, you might say, ``In &AMP; Out''
territory.
</P>
<P>
   As Bill, Martin Donovan does a lot to make passivity droll. Lisa
Kudrow's Lucia, the virginal sister of Bill's dead lover, makes her
maladroit ways seem simultaneously funny and sad. Their patience is
soon enough put to the test by Dedee, who loses little time
seducing Bill's hunky new lover, Ivan Sergei's Matt. Getting
pregnant, she takes off with him and a chunk of Bill's money.
Before it's over, Bill must chase them down to Arizona, then clear
himself of a false accusation of seducing the jilted lover of the
guy who now has jilted Bill.
</P>
<P>
   There's compassion at the core of ``The Opposite of Sex,'' and a
rueful understanding of the permutations and combinations of
loneliness-driven relationships and the ways people stay lonely by
defending themselves too well. But the dysfunctional canterings
soon seem to be unfolding by rote, especially given Roos's
inability to make the actors do little beyond zombie-ing through
them in the apparent hope that their affectlessness will pass for
cool. There are glints of originality in ``The Opposite of Sex,'' a
talent for an arresting turn of phrase, and an impressive balance
between vulnerability and wildness in Ricci's Dedee. But the film
can't avoid seeming to take place in a vacuum long before it's
over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 1914EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
