<HEADER>
A7956 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-XFILES-BOS &LR;      06-19 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-XFILES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
X-FILES: THE TRUTH IS STILL OUT THERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
THE X-FILES: FIGHT THE FUTURE 
Directed by: Rob Bowman 
Screenplay by: Chris Carter 
Starring: David Duchovny, Gillian Anderson, Martin Landau, William
B. Davis, Armin Mueller-Stahl, John Neville 
Running time: 121 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (some violence, a dash of adult language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In transporting ``The X-Files'' from small screen to big, Chris
Carter, the television series' creator, presented himself with a
rather daunting challenge: how to make a film satisfying to both
newcomers and the program's rabid devotees.
</P>
<P>
   For five years, the popular Fox series has been a frustratingly
slow but deliciously seductive tease, revealing bits and pieces of
an expansive government conspiracy involving extraterrestrial life.
At the heart of it are FBI special agents Fox Mulder (David
Duchovny) and Dana Scully (Gillian Anderson), the two-person team
investigating the so-called X-Files within which may lie the fate
of humankind. All this has spawned thousands of Websites and
newsgroups and created one of the great water cooler shows of all
time. Hence, ``X-Files'' philes will enter their local cineplex
looking to be rewarded with deserved answers to lots of questions.
</P>
<P>
   But what about all those people who've never watched the series,
and wouldn't know the Cigarette-Smoking Man from the Marlboro Man?
If the movie were too inside baseball, many moviegoers would be
left dazed and confused, if they bother to go at all. Not exactly
what Carter wanted for his $65 million movie.
</P>
<P>
   So, it speaks volumes about the talents of Carter, as well as
the work of Duchovny and Anderson, that he almost pulls this movie
off. That's almost. ``The X-Files'' is an intense, entertaining
movie, more likely to appease nonfans more than those who schedule
their lives the show's broadcast each week. Which isn't to say
Carter and director Rob Bowman, who has helmed more than two dozen
of the show's episodes, don't give aficionados a few answers to
long-pondered questions. They just don't offer enough.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the truth; the tease is out there.
</P>
<P>
   The movie begins with a flashback, and what a flashback _ all
the way back to 35,000 B.C., with two fur-clad cavemen making their
way across the snowy tundra. Within a cave, they they encounter
what fans will immediately recognize as the nefarious black oil
(later revealed as something far, far nastier). Fast forwards to
the present day, where that once snowbound site now a dust-choked
North Texas field. Once a group of boys out for a day of adventure
stumble into the same oil-oozing cave, the conspiracy is up and out
of the blocks.
</P>
<P>
   When the show ended its fifth season last month, the X-Files had
been torched. Mulder and Scully have been reassigned to an
anti-terrorist unit, and wouldn't you know it, they're looking for
a possible bomb in a government building in Texas. The bomb
explodes, takes out an FBI bomb expert, and leaves a bite in the
edifice which looks eerily like the Alfred P. Murrah Federal
Building in Oklahoma City after Timothy McVeigh paid his deadly
visit in April 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake, it's not a coincidence, and it's quite
unsettling. Nothing from the fevered mind of Carter is ever a
coincidence. One of the program's staples is seasoning its shows
with just enough history and reality _ say, the public's continuing
disbelief concerning the official report on the assassination of
John F. Kennedy, or the Buffalo Bills' inability to win the Super
Bowl _ to make viewers wonder about their own government officials,
and all the deep, dark secrets they may be keeping from us.
</P>
<P>
   Mulder is approached by Dr. Alvin Kurtzweil (Martin Landau), a
gynecologist so stoked by his own alien conspiracy theories, even
Mulder finds him paranoid. But he eventually convinces Mulder that
the bombing was part of an elaborate cover-up designed conceal
something hidden within the building.
</P>
<P>
   Suspected government coverups are to ``The X-Files'' what
state-of-the-art sports cars are to James Bond. Each has to be more
elaborate and lethally loaded than the one before. This one is a
beaut, which racks up frequent flyer miles from Texas to Washington
D.C. to London to Antartica.
</P>
<P>
   And here's where the film gets a little slippery. The first half
of the film, for the most part, is what fans have been waiting for.
But since Carter can't reveal his entire hand _ novices won't get
it, and he still has at least two more TV seasons to fill _ the
second half pretty much becomes standard action fare, albeit one
which isn't afraid to have a brain and snappy dialogue. There are
chases, explosions, and plug-ugly, bloodthirsty creatures, but real
fans may feel disappointed that wherever the truth is, it isn't
necessarily in this movie.
</P>
<P>
   Also, some characters prominent in the television show are all
but relegated to wallpaper such as Mitch Pileggi, who plays
Assistant FBI Director Walter Skinner, Mulder and Scully's
supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Duchovny and Anderson are just as electric and
entertaining to watch in the theater as on TV. With the whip-smart
banter of Tracy and Hepurn, the relationship between Mulder and
Scully has always been one of the program's hallmarks. Even if the
actors aren't that fond of each other in real life, there is an
undeniable chemistry between the two, and Carter has wicked fun
with the sexual tension within their platonic, but charged
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   William B. Davis as Cigarette-Smoking Man is also there,
scheming and doing his part for the tobacco states, but his
resonance is lessened. Thinking about those mainstream audiences,
Carter likely had no choice. Making a far greater impact is John
Neville as Well-Manicured Man, who has some surprises under his
perfectly-tailored sleeve. With his haunted eyes and serial
killer-grin, Landau brings such a tangible paranoia to Krutzweil,
it's a wonder he hasn't been on the TV show before.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, ``The X-Files'' is far more enjoyable than most of
the nonsense taking up screen space this summer. But the quality of
the TV show has raised expectations impossibly high for this film.
At its best, the program is a wonderful, at times brilliant
60-minute film every week. Virtually, the same can be said of this
two-hour ``X-Files'' movie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 1916EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980619.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7958 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POPE-AUSTRIA-NYT &LR;      06-19 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-AUSTRIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE IN AUSTRIA, WHERE CHURCH IS BESET BY DIVISION AND APATHY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALZBURG, Austria _ Pope John Paul II arrived in Austria on
Friday on a mission to grapple with two of the most troubling
problems of his pontificate in the Western world _ bitter divisions
inside church ranks, and the alienation and indifference of the
prosperous society around it.
</P>
<P>
   Even more than in the United States and Western Europe, the
Roman Catholic Church in Austria is in crisis, as many people
abandon it and reformers challenge its leadership on such
contentious issues as celibacy, women's ordination, and the role of
the laity.
</P>
<P>
   Those issues were compounded by a recent sex scandal that forced
the resignation of the archbishop of Vienna, the leader of the
church in Austria.
</P>
<P>
   In a homily in a Salzburg cathedral, the pope urged, ``Don't
leave the church!'' He warned that many Europeans are more
attracted to ``the feast of well-being and consumerism'' than the
feast of the Eucharist.
</P>
<P>
   And while lauding the efforts of lay believers, he also reminded
his Austrian audience that the church expects its followers to
respect the rules. ``In the flock of the Good Pastor, the equality
of dignity does not mean equality of office and activity,'' John
Paul said in German, reading from a text. ``The particular duties
of priests cannot be simply passed to the laity.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the pope's third trip to Austria, and in the 10 years
since his last visit, the world and the Catholic church has changed
dramatically. Then, the church was one of the driving forces behind
the burgeoning revolt against communism in Eastern Europe. Now that
battle is over, and other more internal conflicts dominate the
Catholic agenda. Some 77 percent of Austrians are Catholic, but a
recent poll indicated that less than 20 percent attend church
regularly.
</P>
<P>
   The ideological rift within the Austrian church, moreover, was
deepened by a scandal that bred rebellion and mass defections.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal Hans Hermann Groer, a conservative who was appointed by
Pope John Paul II in 1986, was forced to resign in 1995 amid
allegations that he molested seminarians 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh charges of sexual abuse surfaced in January. When a
leading conservative bishop dismissed the priest who made them
public, it intensified the rift.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to smooth the path for the pope's visit, Groer's
replacement, Cardinal Cristoph Shonborn, took the extraordinary
step last April of declaring that the charges were true and
apologizing publicly for his predecessor's actions. The church then
let it be known that the disgraced cardinal would be sent to a
monastery outside Austria for the duration of the pope's visit.
</P>
<P>
   Before the pope's mass, Shonborn told reporters that the crisis
in the Austrian church was real, but could be overcome. ``We need
to regain mutual trust, and the only way is through discussion and
dialogue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The 53-year-old cardinal is conservative in doctrinal matters,
but diplomatic and open in manner, and is often described as
``papabile,'' someone who could someday be elected pope. But the
impasse within his church is unlikely to be quickly resolved even
by a papal visit.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Last November, the bishop of Innsbruck, Reinhold Stecher, sent a
letter to the Vatican criticizing its unyielding position on such
issues as celibacy for priests and lay workers delivering mass.
``Rome has lost the image of mercy and assumed the image of harsh
authority,'' he complained.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the cathedral and outside on the square, followers
greeted the pope with cheers, applause and emotional tears. But on
the same square, many young people expressed the alienation that
brought the 78-year-old pope back to Austria for a third pastoral
visit, which ends Sunday, when he leaves Vienna for Rome.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the church were more open to young people, I would be more
interested, said Anne Pichler, 21, a psychology student in Salzburg
who walked past the cathedral square with a friend, and declined to
linger for a glimpse of the pope. ``The pope is the head of the
church but he is an old man and I can't identify with him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
