<HEADLINE>
RANDY TRAVIS: NO LONGER `ALONE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Singer Randy Travis isn't joking when he says, ``Any
entertainment business is a strange business.'' That surely
describes today's country music, where flavor-of-the-month
newcomers are often given preferential treatment over artists of
his stature. By that, we mean artists who have been around long
enough to realize that Merle Haggard, Tammy Wynette, and George
Jones mean more to the music's legacy than the dime-a-dozen,
faux-cowboy hat acts romping through Nashville's MTV-style videos.
</P>
<P>
   Chalk one up for the good guys, however, because Travis is
getting a second commercial life.
</P>
<P>
   After selling 20 million records, scoring 15 Top10 hits, and
launching the New Traditionalist movement with its return to
fiddles and steel guitars, Travis fell into a mid-'90s limbo that
is finally lifting. He recently notched a No.1 hit, ``Out of My
Bones,'' followed by a new single, ``The Hole,'' which is racing up
the charts with its apt verse about digging oneself out of a hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know all about that,'' says Travis. ``It does seem like
radio has welcomed me back,'' Travis says during a break from this
week's Fan Fair in Nashville. ``I hadn't recorded in over a year.
And you're not sure if radio is going to play you or not. Sometimes
they forget you and want nothing else to do with you. But that
hasn't been the case.''
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't been the case because the stubborn Travis, now 39,
wouldn't let it be. As the son of a North Carolina construction
worker, he knows about toughing it out. After releasing 12 albums
with Warner Bros., he made a career-saving move to DreamWorks, the
well-endowed label owned by entertainment moguls Steven Spielberg,
David Geffen, and Jeffrey Katzenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Travis's engaging new album, ``You and You Alone'' thus became
the first on the new DreamWorks Records Nashville label.
</P>
<P>
   ``DreamWorks has been behind me 110 percent,'' says Travis, who
had feuded with the CEO of Warner Bros. and the head of its country
promotion.
</P>
<P>
   He feels doubly vindicated with the success of the singles
because he says Warners made some wrong decisions when promoting
singles, but that DreamWorks has given him more leeway and support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought one of my strong points was choosing good
material,'' says Travis. ``And I think we're proving that can still
be the case. The fact that I signed with DreamWorks and the first
single went to No.1 proves that I am not wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Travis, known as a song interpreter rather than a writer, also
did his part by knuckling down and choosing some terrific songs for
the new disc. They range from the Western swing of ``Stranger in
the Mirror'' to the country-rock of ``I'm Still Here, You're Still
Gone'' (with the Grammy-winning Alison Krauss singing backup), to
the mature title track (with Vince Gill and Melba Montgomery on
backup) and the thoughtful ``Spirit of a Boy, Wisdom of a Man,''
about teenage pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to look and look and look to find good songs,'' says
Travis. ``We went through over 1,000 songs. There were four of us
looking for five months to find songs. They're harder to find,
simply because there are so many artists looking. And regardless of
how good a writer is, if he writes 20 songs, there might only be
one in there worth recording. And I would say that's true of most
writers.''
</P>
<P>
   Travis was no stranger to hits in the '80s and early '90s _ such
radio classics as ``On the Other Hand,'' ``Forever and Ever,
Amen,'' and ``Look Heart, No Hands.'' But that was before country
became diluted by so many here-today, gone-tomorrow acts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have very strong opinions about what's happening in country
music,'' says Travis. ``I think (the labels) oversign acts, and
when that happens, you have more records than radio can possibly
play. And often you don't find out who is recording a certain song.
They may become hits, but you don't know who does them.''
</P>
<P>
   Travis still loves country legends like Haggard and Jones
(``he's still one of the best singers in any genre''), but as for
new male acts, he likes Trace Adkins, Darryl Singletary, and Tim
McGraw. As for females, he loves Patty Loveless, Faith Hill, and
Trisha Yearwood.
</P>
<P>
   He also has some strong feelings about all the ``crossover''
attempts of country acts to capture pop listeners. ``We've drifted
too far to the pop format,'' he says. ``Variety is great, but this
is country music, after all. We should stick closer to the roots.''
</P>
<P>
   Travis's down-home voice is not only easily recognizable, but
so, these days, is his well-chiseled face, since he has a dual
career as a movie star. He has 25 film and TV credits to his
resume, including films such as ``The Rainmaker,'' ``Maverick,''
and this spring's ``Black Dog,'' his first starring vehicle, in
which he shared the limelight with Patrick Swayze. ``I played a bit
of a redneck in it,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Next up is ``The White River Kid'' with Ellen Barkin and Antonio
Banderas. ``I play a sheriff who's kind of nuts,'' Travis says with
a laugh. ``I guess you'd call it a dark comedy. My character is way
out there. He's running for election and if he sees his opponent's
picture on a telephone pole, he shoots at it.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Travis says he didn't join DreamWorks _ despite the
presence of Spielberg _ in order to further his movie career. ``We
wanted to keep that separate,'' he says of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   For now, he's just glad to be touring again. He's glad to be
coming back to New England, where previously he has played the
Worcester Centrum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I've been up in that part of the country, the
audience has responded wonderfully,'' Travis says. ``I couldn't ask
for a better response.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
