<SLUG> BC-FUNDS-WATCH-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUND WATCH: WHERE YOU CAN TURN IF THE BOTTOM DROPS OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 21)  
 (bl)  
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUIZ: If the Dow Jones industrial average drops 1,500 points,
American workers invested in defined contribution plans will:
</P>
<P>
   (a) panic
</P>
<P>
   (b) ignore the selloff
</P>
<P>
   (c) receive calm and measured advice from their 401(k) plan
sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   If you're counting on (c), think again.
</P>
<P>
   According to a survey by William M. Mercer Inc., a human
resources consulting firm, more than half the 209 employers
surveyed _ 52 percent _ have no plans to communicate with their
employees in the event of a major market selloff. Nor have they
looked into whether their plan vendor is prepared, willing or able
to provide the employees with information or service in a crash.
</P>
<P>
   The great majority of the remaining 48 percent have only
informal plans to communicate with their employees or simply expect
their plan vendor to handle the job for them, according to the
survey. (There was no word as to whether such vendors would,
indeed, provide such hand-holding.)
</P>
<P>
   Only a piddling 3 percent of the employers surveyed had formal
plans in place to counsel their employees in a major stock market
downdraft. Such a plan might include making sure that managers and
supervisors are prepared to counsel employees against making
drastic moves.
</P>
<P>
   The long-running bull market has, of course, rewarded Americans
who invest regularly in their company's 401(k) retirement plans.
But a market downturn could obliterate employees' confidence _ and
leave companies scrambling to deal with the employees' problems.
Employees typically have at least two-thirds of their 401(k)'s
invested in stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't been through a really large or extended correction
during the 10 years in which 401(k) plans have become so popular,''
said Brian Ternoey, a principal with Mercer. ``How companies help
employees through a downturn will affect their attitude toward
investing for many years.''
</P>
<P>
   Mutual fund companies learned their lesson the hard way in 1987,
when frantic investors couldn't get through to telephone
representatives to sell their shares. Fund companies have since
geared up for similar disasters, and in fact weathered the 1990
downturn very easily.
</P>
<P>
   Companies, for their part, overwhelmingly believe that the
vendors who run their 401(k)'s will be able to handle a selloff.
Among other things, the survey found that the companies believe
vendors will communicate with their employees and manage to handle
phone calls and high trading volume. But Ternoey said the staff at
401(k) vendors has not necessarily received training to help
investors handle a market crash.
</P>
<P>
   How companies deal with the issue of employee hand-holding may
well have an impact on their own stock. Of the respondents, 32
percent said they included company stock as an investment option
within their 401(k)'s. Of those, 22 percent said that more than 50
percent of the plan's assets was invested in company stock.
</P>
<P>
   Putnam's Analyst Fund
</P>
<P>
   Putnam Investments introduced a new fund to the public that
tests the stock-picking prowess of its well-respected research
department without the help of a dedicated, professional manager.
The lead manager of the fund, Putnam Research, is Thomas Bogan,
Putnam's associate director of global equity research. He heads a
team of 43 analysts that picks 70 to 90 mostly midsize-to-large
U.S. companies for the fund's portfolio. The analysts use a blend
of value and growth investing styles and closely hew to the sector
weightings of the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index.
</P>
<P>
   The fund has been open without a load to Putnam employees and
trustees living in Massachusetts since October 1995. Since
inception, the fund has returned an annual average of 32.8 percent
through March 31, 1998, Putnam said.
</P>
<P>
   For the public, the fund, which holds $14.6 million in assets,
levies a maximum initial sales charge of 5.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Putnam's new fund arrives as a couple of other analyst-based
offerings have been started. Massachusetts Financial Services,
which began the analyst-only MFS Research fund in 1991, opened an
international version of that fund in January to outside investors,
after running it with seed money for one year. The State Street
Research Galileo fund, another analyst-run offering, was also
opened this year.
</P>
<P>
   Third Avenue Value Shut
</P>
<P>
   Value manager Martin Whitman will close his flagship fund, Third
Avenue Value, to new investors effective July 15. Whitman's chief
concern is the fund's huge cash position, which accounts for about
30 percent of the fund's $1.82 billion in assets, a company
spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Whitman announced plans to open a real estate
value fund this fall; it will invest in real estate and related
companies. Whitman and a real estate analyst at his firm will be
co-managers.
</P>
<P>
   It's an asset class with which Whitman has some familiarity.
About 15 percent of Third Avenue Value's assets is invested in real
estate, as is 25 percent of the Third Avenue Small-Cap Value fund.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
