<HEADLINE>
FOR ALLMANS, ALL ROADS LEAD TO BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Allman Brothers Band is the quintessential Southern rock
act, yet it has enjoyed a longstanding love affair with New
England. The group is playing three area dates this summer _ up
from two last year _ and all are at the 19,900-capacity Great Woods
Center for the Performing Arts &UR;  &LR; in Mansfield, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``We start the tour in Boston, end it in Boston, and also start
the second leg of the tour in Boston,'' Allmans drummer Butch
Trucks said of the additional July 31 and Sept. 19 shows. ``The
demand seems to be there. I don't know if it's a tribute to Boston
that we're playing all these shows, but we sure do appreciate it.
If every city treated us as well, we'd make a good living.''
</P>
<P>
   That last remark is an attempt at humor, because the Allmans, as
most anyone knows, have made a tremendous living in recent years.
Not only have they been playing well, but their fan base has
increased because of the number of Deadheads who have come aboard
since Jerry Garcia died.
</P>
<P>
   The Allmans had a few moments of tension last year while
integrating new members Oteil Burbridge (bass) and Jack Pearson
(guitar). But Trucks said the tension is now gone. ``We're starting
to lock in with Oteil and Jack. We're doing a lot of jamming and
are taking more chances. Everyone has just gotten used to each
other. The more you do that, the deeper the musical conversation.
We're able to get out on the edge a little more.''
</P>
<P>
   The Allmans also are getting looser about their song lists. Last
year, they alternated two separate shows. This year, they've raised
that to three different set lists, but they're changing those
around as well. They're also digging out some songs, such as
``Don't Keep Me Wondering,'' ``Nobody Knows,'' ``High Falls,'' and
``Ain't Wastin' Time No More.''
</P>
<P>
   The Allmans are so confident that they're only doing one
rehearsal before tonight's show. Trucks feels they will still be in
a groove based on the 15 nights they did at New York's Beacon
Theatre in March. ``Those Beacon shows were so much fun,'' he said.
``And at times, we played as well as we've ever played.''
</P>
<P>
   The band members also have kept up their chops through side
projects this year. Gregg Allman made a solo album and toured
behind it. And Trucks and Burbridge were part of Frogwings, a
jazz-rock act that likewise toured. (Look for a record from them
next year on Trucks's label, Flying Frog Records.)
</P>
<P>
   But for the last 2 1/2 months, the Allmans have been off the
road. ``We're ready to go to work again,'' said Trucks. ``And we're
looking forward to Boston again.''
</P>
<P>
   The Allmans also have a new album, ``Mycology, an Anthology''
(mycology is the study of mushrooms) on Sony's 550 label. It
contains tracks from their last five discs on Epic Records, as well
as an acoustic ``Midnight River'' and some live material from the
Atlanta Pop Festival in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A bewitching Sinead: Sinead O'Connor was stiff and somewhat
out-of-sync during her show with the Chieftains at Harborlights in
Boston Wednesday, but she was infinitely better when she swung over
to sing later that night at McGann's Pub near North Station at 1
a.m. She joined the Donal Lunny Band (from Dublin) and flashed more
smiles in her short set than she did in her entire show at
Harborlights. She might not like to hear this, but she also seemed
more comfortable with Lunny's Band than with her own. At the
jampacked McGann's, which was experiencing its greatest moment
since opening a few years ago, O'Connor even climaxed with ``Danny
Boy,'' investing it with such dignity that you could have heard a
pin drop in the room. And she humorously introduced it by saying,
``This is going to be very sad, so shut up!'' She also did one of
her own songs (``I Stretched Across Your Grave'') and added a
transporting version of ``Dawning of the Day.'' It was a charming
set, backed by the sure hand of guitarist Lunny (known for his
association with Planxty and Moving Hearts) and an all-star cast
that featured fiddler Molly Casey and squeezebox virtuoso Sharon
Shannon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Renaming Great Woods?: Promoter Don Law confirmed this week that
discussions have been held to rename Great Woods with a corporate
imprint. One of the possibilities is Fleet Bank (yikes, Fleet
Woods?), but Law said that no deal has yet been done. And the talks
started taking place well before Law's Blackstone Entertainment
company was sold to SFX. ``The sale had nothing to do with it,'' he
said, rebutting a newspaper report last week that said it did.
</P>
<P>
   One direct result of the SFX purchase, however, is to soon
implement SFX's push for a second stage for all Great Woods
concerts, not just for the major touring festivals. The second
stage would feature local bands. The reasons? ``To expose new
talent, to get people out of the parking lots, and obviously to get
people to use the venue earlier,'' said Law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
