A7968 &Cx1f; paxxx
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-watch-PA     06-19 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-watch-PA </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  pennsylvania votechart
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON WATCH VOTE CHART Questions regarding this
transmission should be directed to 202-628-3100, ext. 216.
WASHINGTON, June 19 -- The following chart shows how senators and
house representatives voted on key bills and amendments this week.
A ``Y'' means the member voted for the measure; an ``N'' means the
member voted against the measure; a ``?'' means the member did not
vote; and a ``P'' means the member voted ``present.''
</P>
<P>
   SENATE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: TOBACCO
</P>
<P>
   The Senate voted Wednesday to kill the tobacco settlement bill
proposed by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz. The bill sought to cut
teenage smoking by giving the government authority to regulate
nicotine as a drug and by increasing the federal tax on tobacco by
$1.10 per pack of cigarettes, which would have raised more than
$500 billion. Although the procedural vote was 57 to 42 in favor of
bringing the bill to a vote, under Senate rules, 60 votes were
needed. Supporters said that opponents overloaded the bill with
extra programs to make it unpalatable. Opponents said that the bill
created too many new programs, unfairly focused a tax on low-income
Americans and included no limits on the liability of tobacco
comanies. A ``yes'' vote favored bringing the measure to a vote,
and a ``no'' vote effectively killed the bill.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   SANTORUM (R-PA) N
</P>
<P>
   SPECTER (R-PA) ?
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: TAXES
</P>
<P>
   The House voted Wednesday, 219-209, to overhaul the current tax
code by December 31, 2002. Supporters said the tax code needs to be
reformed because it is too complicated for the average American to
understand. Opponents said it would be risky to overhaul the tax
code without putting an alternative code in place. A ``yes'' vote
favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: SCHOOLS
</P>
<P>
   The House approved Thursday, 225-197, a tax cut to offset
elementary and secondary education expenses, including for private
and religious school tuition. The bill would allow parents to save
as much as $2,000 a year for school expenses for each child without
paying taxes on the interest. Supporters said public schools are
failing America's children, and parents should have the opportunity
to try alternatives. Opponents said the bill would only help
wealthy families who already send their children to private
schools. A ``yes'' vote favors the tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   3) BILL NUMBER: CHINA
</P>
<P>
   The House voted Thursday, 409-10, to set up a special
nine-member committee to assess whether U.S. national security was
undermined by the President when he allowed the Chinese government
to launch U.S. satellites on Chinese rockets. Supporters said
allegations in the national media that the President's decision had
undermined U.S. national security were credible and deserved to be
investigated. Opponents of the measure made no statements on the
House floor statements. A ``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2 3
</P>
<P>
   --- --- ---
</P>
