<HEADER>
A7974 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-MEXICO-HNS &LR;      06-19 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-MEXICO-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN P. LOPEZ  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
BORDEAUX, France _ Mexico might not have the best soccer team at
this 1998 World Cup. Then again, who knows, considering how well
the Mexicans played in their Cup opener last week.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``We were like killers for a while in the second half,'' said
Mexico forward Luis Hernandez, who scored a pair of goals in the
3-1 victory over South Korea. ``It was like old times. How far that
one game will take us, who knows?''
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? But one thing is certain: The fans of the famed
tri-color have proved to be among the most loyal and conspicuous in
France over the past two weeks, their unconditional love for the
Mexican team making for one of the warmer stories of the Cup thus
far.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soccer is like that,'' Mexican forward Luis Garcia said. ``You
win, and you have a great party. You lose it's time to cry. We're
tired of seeing our people crying. They like to party. We're here
to play, and they're here to celebrate.''
</P>
<P>
   For the victory over South Korea in Lyon, an estimated 25,000
Mexican fans squeezed their way into 35,000-seat Stade Gerland,
ready to begin the celebration and put away horrible memories of a
team that looked disorganized even days before the start of the
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Three Mexico goals in the second half set off the party.
Afterward, Lyon's streets were flooded with jubilant but peaceful
Mexican revelers celebrating the return of the stylish, high-level
game Mexico had been accustomed to seeing.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing we did in that game was not think about the World
Cup, or playing in a different country, or anything but playing
Mexican soccer,'' defender Dauilio Davino said. ``We stopped
worrying about anything but playing like we do at home. It was a
lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the night, even the normally conservative waiters
at Lyon's upscale restaurants were bedecked in sombreros and
serapes, yelling for ``El Tri'' and singing the unofficial Mexican
soccer anthem, Cielito Lindo, which has been reverberating off
walls in Paris, Lyon and now here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beautiful little sky,'' the title translates. ``Sing, don't
cry,'' is part of the lyric.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's fans have had much to sing about in recent days after
the amazing transformation of this team, from tentative to
aggressive, from seemingly lost to focused.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Mexican faithful have descended on Bordeaux for today's
second round-robin game against Belgium, a strong team that many
experts placed ahead of the Mexicans as favorites to advance out of
Group E with the favored Dutch.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican fans are filling train stations and city buses. They are
partying at nearby beaches, plazas, vineyards and chateaus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans have more faith in us than before because we won a
game and played well,'' Mexico coach Manuel Lapuente said. ``It
makes us feel good that the fans believe in us again. We believe in
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The sheer number of Mexican fans who have made the long trip to
France is staggering, considering the cost, time commitment and
long hours spent looking for costly tickets. Some World Cup
organizers estimate that better than 40,000 Mexican fans are here,
the majority of whom seemed to be wandering through the Bordeaux
city center Friday, wearing the green Azteca shirts, tooting horns,
cheering wildly and singing Cielito Lindo.
</P>
<P>
   Sing, don't cry.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Mexico's improvement here has been attributed not just
to Lapuente's relaxing of what had been a defense-oriented style
implemented by former coach Bora Milutinovic. Players such as
Hernandez, Garcia and Alberto Garcia-Aspe also seem to have become
more daring with their attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've changed a lot; everybody's changed,'' Garcia said. ``A
week ago, no one gave us a chance, and I'm not sure we were
confident ourselves. But now we're expected to go on, and we expect
to go on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much of that is because of the confidence we have in how we
play. It also has to do with the fan support. If you're a good
team, you know that it's time to show up at the World Cup. Two
months ago, we left our homes, our families, with the idea of
winning the World Cup. That's why we're here. We will do what it
takes.''
</P>
<P>
   And they will have an army of fans behind them.
</P>
<P>
   Bordeaux city officials even announced Friday that an extra
outdoor viewing area with a large-screen television will be erected
for Mexican fans who can't get tickets for today's game.
</P>
<P>
   Lapuente began his daily news conference Friday by saying, ``I
have no more tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   Bus drivers are wearing small Mexican flags on their lapels.
</P>
<P>
   Even the weatherman seems to have jumped on the bandwagon. After
more than a week of cool, damp weather in France, Friday was hot
and humid, with temperatures in the low 90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, if the weather is like this, it will be an
advantage for us,'' Lapuente said. ``It's been more than a month
since we've been here, but yes, it will be an advantage. This is
Mexican weather.''
</P>
<P>
   Cielito Lindo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the motivation, the talent and the support,''
Hernandez said. ``We are going to win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
