<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7976 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIBERIANS-REUNITED-BO     06-19 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIBERIANS-REUNITED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIBERIAN FATHER GETS GIFT: MISSING SON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding; Molley is cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GLORIA NEGRI  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ Molley Jones got a Father's Day gift by airmail
special delivery Friday _ a shy boy, small for his age, with
soulful eyes, dressed in a beige African dashiki.
</P>
<P>
   After two years, the son the 39-year-old Jones thought forever
lost to him in Liberia's civil war was back in his arms for good.
</P>
<P>
   Brown eyes shining, a big smile on his face, Boimah Jones, 12 in
July, jumped into his father's arms as soon as he exited the United
Airlines gate at Logan International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The moment seemed to erase the trauma Boimah suffered after
seeing five people die on the crowded, leaky boat that, in 1996,
took him and other Liberian refugees away from their wartorn
country to a refugee camp in Ghana.
</P>
<P>
   Boimah spent a year in the camp before he went back to Liberia
to more civil strife and an uncertain future. Only his father's
unwavering determination to overcome bureaucratic red tape and the
help of the American Red Cross of Massachusetts Bay were able
finally to bring him here.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Red Cross is cool,'' Boimah said on the tarmac as he
hugged Regina Szwadzka, coordinator here of the Red Cross's
international services program.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Deyton, executive director of the chapter, put a white
Boston baseball cap on Boimah. His father dressed him in a Boston
T-shirt that went to his knees as the happy family stepped into a
silver limousine loaned for the occasion by businessman Russell
Robbat.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``They deserve a little first-class treatment,'' said Robbat,
who also paid Boimah's $1,300 airfare from Ghana.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; On hand to greet Boimah were his stepmother, Sara Jones, his
half sister, Massah Jones, 16, who emigrated from Liberia last
year, Red Cross officials, and Robbat.
</P>
<P>
   Jones had last seen his son in the Liberian capital of Monrovia
in 1996 during a lull in the fighting. He had begun planning to
bring him here, along with his two daughters, after the war broke
out in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' Jones said, ``for seven years I lost complete contact
with my children.''
</P>
<P>
   Boimah's mother, Emor, as well as the mother of Jones's two
daughters, remain in Liberia. Boimah's mother has been too
devastated by the war to care for him, Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones came to the Boston area from Liberia in 1986, got a
student visa ``so I could help my family back home,'' and graduated
from Lesley College with a degree in community development. Then he
earned a certificate in business software systems. Now he has two
jobs, with IDX Systems Corp. in Boston, and as a hotel concierge.
</P>
<P>
   Jones recalled that as he listened to reports of civil unrest in
Liberia, one question haunted him: ``Where is my son?''
</P>
<P>
   Boimah was only 5 months old when Jones left Liberia in 1986 and
3 years old when the war broke out. The next time Jones saw him,
during a visit to Liberia, he was 10.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after Jones returned to his residence in suburban Malden,
Boimah fled Liberia. To escape the shooting, disease, and hunger
that killed thousands each day, Boimah, his aunt, and others
crowded on a leaky boat, Jones said. Several countries turned the
boat away, but Ghana accepted the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Jones recalled that two weeks after the refugees arrived in
Ghana, he heard from his sister that she and Boimah were in the
camp. He immediately called the American Red Cross in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross said it would send Boimah his father's handwritten
message that he was looking for him, as required under the Red
Cross family reunification program. But with so much fighting in
the region, it took two months for the message to get through.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, meanwhile, took to the Internet, sent e-mail messages,
and spent hundreds of dollars on telephone calls to embassies and
agencies, trying to get permission to bring his son to Malden.
</P>
<P>
   His American wife, Sara, filed official papers for Boimah's
immigration, as she had to bring Jones's two daughters, Tina, 18,
and Massah, to the United States. But Boimah's immigration was
denied.
</P>
<P>
   One obstacle, Jones said, was that he had to prove Boimah was
really his son.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Boimah got back to Liberia from the camp, I contacted the
American Embassy there for his visa,'' Jones said. ``It was refused
because they did not believe he was my son. I got my mother in
Liberia to identify him. But all failed. I was told both Boimah and
I had to have our blood tested. I had Boimah send a sample of his
blood here. Then, I sent both samples to a lab in Maryland. When
the test came up positive, I got his visa.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Boimah has a much happier future. This weekend he will
luxuriate in his father's embrace.
</P>
<P>
   ``A boy should be in school,'' his father said, ``not in a
refugee camp.''
</P>
</TEXT>
