   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-US (Paris) _ Analysts doubt that America's effort to prop
up the wilting Japanese yen will prove effective for long. First,
intervention in money markets has not generally worked, and second,
Japan has repeatedly failed to live up to its promises to
straighten out its economic problems. By BERNARD D. KAPLAN.
(Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-JITTERS (Tokyo) _ President Clinton's decision not to stop
in Japan going to or coming from his trip to China has fed Japanese
fears that the United States may be ready to dilute its close
relationship with the richest and most developed nation in Asia in
favor of the strategic allure of the world's most populous country
and its vast economic potential. By CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA-BASEBALL (Guacara, Venezuela) _ If you grow up in the
ghetto playing stickball with bottlecaps on potholed streets, how
hard can it be to hit a perfectly stitched baseball? That is one
explanation Venezuelans offer when asked why their nation has
produced so many dominating ``beisbolistas.'' By JOHN OTIS.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-OVERLOAD (Undated) _ The federal justice system along the
U.S.-Mexico border is experiencing record criminal caseloads, with
drug and immigration offenders clogging courts and crowding
prisons. From San Diego, Calif., to Brownsville, Texas, the surging
caseloads are the result of tougher drug and immigration laws, more
agents enforcing them and perhaps more illegal activity. By
THADDEUS HERRICK.
</P>
<P>
   HABITAT-HOUSTON (Houston) _ An estimated 6,000 volunteers who
built 100 new homes for need people will celebrate their
achievement. President Jimmy Carter will dedicate the houses and
present Bibles to the families at one Habitat for Humanity
construction site. By MATT SCHWARTZ.
</P>
