<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-CAMPAIGN-850&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE MAJORITY, INCLUDING 65 REPUBLICANS, BACK CAMPAIGN FINANCE
REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ps) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A majority of the House, including 65 Republicans,
voted on Friday to protect a bipartisan campaign finance bill from
the first Republican leadership effort to water it down by
amendment.
</P>
<P>
   The vote of 254-155 put Reps. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., and
Martin T. Meehan, D-Mass., over only the first of many hurdles they
will have to cross as they try to prevail in a free-for-all debate
on campaign finance that is expected to last until August.
</P>
<P>
   It indicated that a larger than expected number of Republicans
are likely to break with Speaker Newt Gingrich and ultimately vote
for their bill to overhaul the law governing campaign contributions
and help shepherd it to passage.
</P>
<P>
   The Shays-Meehan measure _ and a companion bill in the Senate _
have been fiercely opposed by top Republicans, who see it as an
effort to cut into their party's traditional fund-raising
advantage. It would effectively ban the large unregulated
contributions to political parties that were at the heart of the
1996 campaign finance abuses and also curb independent advertising
by interest groups.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Gingrich went to great parliamentary lengths
to prevent the bill's ever coming up for a House vote. But his
tactic backfired and led to an incipient Republican revolt. He
headed it off by promising a full and fair debate on the campaign
finance law.
</P>
<P>
   Now it has become such a full debate that a dozen campaign
finance proposals and 258 amendments have been authorized for
consideration throughout the summer, a procedure virtually unheard
of in the usually tightly controlled House. Democrats have charged
that this is a ruse to subject the Shays-Meehan bill to ``death by
amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   But on Friday, Shays and Meehan managed to defeat the first
amendment, which Shays characterized as ``an attempt to gut the
bill.'' They also passed an amendment designed to bring them more
support.
</P>
<P>
   The most telling vote came on an amendment offered by Rep. Bill
Thomas, R-Calif., the chairman of the Committee on House Oversight,
which has jurisdiction over campaign finance legislation. His
amendment said that if any element of the Shays-Meehan bill was
held unconstitutional, the entire bill would be void. That would be
a departure from the usual practice in Congress, in which bills
state that the nullification of one provision does not effect the
rest of the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas argued that past court rulings on the subject of campaign
finance had left in place a flawed system that Congress had never
intended to devise. With many lawmakers believing that part of the
Shays-Meehan bill will not meet constitutional scrutiny, he said,
``I think the far-better choice is to say if a piece falls, it all
falls.''
</P>
<P>
   But his proposal was handily defeated 254-155, with 65
Republicans voting against the California Republican and only 6
Democrats supporting him. If that kind of vote total continues to
hold, it shows that there will be more than a majority of the House
voting for the bipartisan campaign finance legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Shays said he cannot predict whether all 65 Republicans would
stay with him. Some are also supporting a separate bipartisan
campaign finance measure drafted by House freshmen, but were
willing to cooperate to make sure both proposals get a clear shot
at a vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not be able to declare any victory,'' Shays said.
``There's no victory, but there's been some strong votes showing
that campaign reform has legs in the House.''
</P>
<P>
   Meehan said several weeks of House proceedings had persuaded him
that his coalition can prevail. ``The general feeling is we've got
the votes,'' he said. ``It's just a matter of surviving the
procedural land mines.'' He said he hoped that over time opponents
would recognize the strength behind overhaul and stop the blizzard
of amendments.
</P>
<P>
   The House also voted 325-78 on Friday to attach to the
Shays-Meehan bill a proposal to create an independent commission to
study other changes in the finance law. Shays and Meehan had agreed
to the amendment as a way of drawing support away from a rival
campaign finance proposal that would have created an independent
commission to study changes in the campaign finance law.
</P>
<P>
   Under the procedure created for the campaign finance debate,
whichever proposal gets the most votes above a majority becomes the
one then considered by the House for final passage.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition supporting the ban on soft-money had come to fear
that Republicans might throw their majority behind the commission
bill to trump Shays-Meehan. So they said they would add a
commission to their own legislation to study further changes in
law.
</P>
<P>
   The free-standing proposal for a commission went down to defeat,
201-156, on Wednesday night, with 68 lawmakers voting ``present''
even though they favored the idea.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The votes on Friday came after a long Thursday night of debate
that continued on Friday morning and saw some pointed exchanges on
the state of modern politics. At one point, lawmakers squabbled
over the question of just how much money is too much money in
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ron Kind, D-Wis., insisted ``the average person in western
Wisconsin believes that under the current finance system, even
though it is legal for a wealthy individual or group to contribute
a million dollars to either political party, that is too much
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, scoffed and said that in the
last campaign the spending on House races amounted to $218 million.
``That breaks down to about $3.80 per voter who voted in the
election,'' he said. ``That is less money than we spent on bubble
gum in this country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
