<HEADLINE>
ENOUGH HOTEL ROOMS AVAILABLE FOR DEMOCRATS, BOSTON SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY RAKOWSKY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Three days before an inspection of the city as a
possible host for the National Democratic Convention, city
officials announced that one of the obstacles to hosting the
extravaganza has been solved.
</P>
<P>
   Where once the city was thought to lack the necessary hotel
space, officials now say they have ``found'' the rooms.
</P>
<P>
   City officials, intent on bringing more than $100 million in
spending to the city, scrutinized the hotel space surrounding
downtown Boston and came up with additional rooms in inns that had
previously been overlooked _ closing the biggest hole in Boston's
bid for the convention in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   City officials Friday said they can offer 21,000 hotel rooms,
3,410 more than previously thought.
</P>
<P>
   The windfall of hotels, which were missed by the Greater Boston
Convention and Visitors Bureau because they are not bureau members,
comes as the city prepares for Monday's arrival of about 50 ranking
Democrats scouting Boston as a possible convention site, said
Howard Leibowitz, director of intergovernmental relations.
</P>
<P>
   In the home stretch to land what would be a tremendous prize _
Chicago derived $130 million in direct spending from the last
Democratic convention _ the Menino administration is scrambling to
spruce up the city and prepare a three-day tour for the party's
site selectors.
</P>
<P>
   Panel members will be inundated with classic Boston experiences
from an exclusive shopping spree at Filene's to a Pier Four
clambake, a night at Fenway Park, and lunch at Old City Hall with
Sen. Edward Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   The glitz and the grit of the visit are designed to quell three
concerns that the Democrats might have about Boston hosting the
convention: Hotels, transportation, and politics.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Thomas M. Menino had been leaning on executive housing in
area universities to make up for a paucity of downtown sleeping
quarters. But the mayor asserted that the fresh supply of rooms,
found by the Massachusetts Lodging Association means, ``Hotel rooms
are a non-issue.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials had hawked their accommodations as being located
within a 30-minute ride from the Fleet Center, but blocks of rooms
in Plymouth and Sturbridge ``strained that definition,'' Leibowitz
said.
</P>
<P>
   On other counts, the DNC panelists will have to squint and use
their imagination about where the Big Dig and other construction
projects will be in August 2000.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, they'll have to just imagine the Fleet Center
without cranes and backhoes surrounding it, ignore the hard hat
site near the airport and picture a finished 800-room Hilton
instead. And the Big Dig? Imagine if the work was all underground.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they see in two years will be much better,'' said Menino,
who will lead a 6 a.m. walk through the South End next Tuesday.
``They have to imagine that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A panel of the visiting Democrats will be briefed by Central
Artery officials on what state the Big Dig will be in during the
convention, complete with maps and other visual aids.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who spends a day and a half in Boston will see that
traffic moves, businesses are open; Boston is thriving,'' said
Andrew Paven, spokesman for the Big Dig.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the summer of 2000, you'll see far fewer construction
barricades on the surface streets and there'll be a lot more
activity underground where you can't see it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Democrats will hear that traffic in August is
17 percent lighter, due to vacations and the absence of college
students, than the June traffic they will see next week.
</P>
<P>
   As the Democrats pass the demolition site of the Boston Garden
and work being done on a bridge over the Charles and North Station
changes, they will hear that the convention ironically will come at
a great time.
</P>
<P>
   By August 2000, there will be a large clear space around the
Fleet Center that will be suitable for the semi-trailers of
television production crews, said Kelley Quinn, a key architect of
the city's convention bid. It ``will be a great time to be at the
FleetCenter,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Other computer models will depict how the FleetCenter would
accommodate journalists in the underground parking garage, said
Quinn. The garage is already air-conditioned and could easily be
outfitted with telecommunications equipment, she said, adding that
the FleetCenter also offers movable luxury boxes and a TV
production crew that has been hired to do major shows and
tournaments in other venues.
</P>
<P>
   But none of that matters if Democratic higher-ups decide they
would rather have the convention in a region that is less reliable
for party support or if Vice President Al Gore does not want to
come to the home state of putative primary opponent Senator John
Kerry.
</P>
<P>
   Leibowitz downplayed the significance of Boston being ruled out
as Kerry's home turf.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are over-estimating that part of the political
equation,'' said Leibowitz. ``In recent years, the nominee of the
party is chosen well before the convention.''
</P>
<P>
   As for whether Boston, nestled in a Democratic home court with
relatively low electoral vote totals, recommends itself to the
Democrat's politically is another matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Choosing the site,'' said Leibowitz, ``goes back to what is
the best backdrop for the nominee.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
