u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOCH-TRIAL-VERDICT-57     06-19 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOCH-TRIAL-VERDICT-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY RULES FOR DEFENSE IN FEUD BETWEEN RICH BROTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Fla., Mass.)  (mk) 
 By LESLIE WAYNE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOPEKA, Kan. _ One of the longest and nastiest family disputes
ended Friday, sort of, as a working-class jury blocked efforts by
William Koch, one of the nation's richest men, to get $2 billion
from two of his brothers who he said cheated in a business deal
more than a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   After 10 weeks of testimony and two days of deliberations, a
six-man, six-woman U.S. court jury said that Koch, who led the
legal charge on behalf of another brother and a group of relatives,
was owed nothing by his brothers Charles and David Koch, who almost
entirely own Koch Industries, a $35 billion oil conglomerate in
Wichita, Kan., that is the nation's second-largest private company
after Cargill Inc.
</P>
<P>
   No important legal issues were at stake. But the enormous sums
in dispute and the brother-to-brother hatreds that emerged made it
a soap opera of avarice and malice that far outdistanced other
celebrated courtroom brawls over rich people's money.
</P>
<P>
   Collectively, the Koch (pronounced ``coke'') family is worth
around $6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   After the verdict, William Koch said he would appeal, and he
continued to attack his brothers: ``These guys are crooks. In my
opinion, this is the 10th round of a 15-round championship fight.''
Koch also criticized Judge Sam Crow of U.S. District Court as a
``hometown judge'' who ``cut us way back'' in his rulings from the
bench.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers said it was premature to speculate on the basis of an
appeal or how long the legal process would drag on. ``I'm sure they
could find some errors to appeal,'' said Robert Howard, an attorney
for Koch Industries. ``I am confident the verdict will be upheld on
appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Webb Heckler, a law professor at the University of Kansas, said
of the verdict: ``This may be an example of the pig rule in law. If
you overreach egregiously, cosmic justice will have its way with
you.''
</P>
<P>
   The legal battle stemmed from a 1983 settlement between William
and the two brothers his group sued. That settlement gave William;
another brother, Frederick, and a number of Koch cousins $1.1
billion in return for their 5.5 million shares in Koch Industries,
which has larger revenues than such corporations as Microsoft, Walt
Disney or Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   William contended that the group was shortchanged in that 1983
deal and has been pressing the case through 25 federal and state
courts. He was seeking $339 million more for the group's holdings
in 1983 dollars. Court documents he filed estimate that interest
would bring this to more than $2 billion today.
</P>
<P>
   In issuing the verdict, the jury did find that Koch Industries
made ``misrepresentations and omissions'' in 1983 about the output
of an oil refinery, but concluded that these lapses were not
significant. The jury rejected William's allegations that Koch
Industries' accounting practices were misleading in financial
documents used in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   ``The jury did find that they lied,'' said William Koch, 57, an
oil businessman himself who is best known for spending $70 million
to win the America's Cup yacht race. ``To us, that's a significant
finding.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, Charles Koch, 62, chief executive of Koch
Industries, who was not present for the verdict, said: ``We are
glad that this long saga is behind us. This issue has been painful
for the entire Koch Industries family. For more than 13 years, we
have been forced to allocate substantial financial and legal
resources to defend our company.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The trial provided a two-month legal spectacle in which the
courtroom here was filled with squadrons of lawyers, more than 800
exhibits, 10,000 pages of documents and overhead projectors, flip
charts and television monitors. Local Topeka attorneys estimate
William's legal costs at around $200,000 a week or around $5,000 an
hour. By contrast, the jurors who decided against him were paid $50
a day.
</P>
<P>
   The trial of the lawsuit gave jurors a window on a rich,
dysfunctional family mixed with tales of boardroom backstabbing.
The 1983 buyout at the center of the litigation came two years
after William led a boardroom coup and tried to oust Charles as
chief executive. At that time, William and the other minority
shareholders complained that Charles had poured too much money back
into the company and did not give enough to shareholders, who were
receiving $20 million to $30 million a year in dividends.
</P>
<P>
   Painful family secrets were laid bare in testimony: A Christmas
dinner where William reduced his mother to tears; Christmas gifts
sent by William to Charles' children, returned unopened; a tearful
David breaking down on the witness stand over his failed
relationship with William, his twin.
</P>
<P>
   Today, William and Frederick, 64, are not on speaking terms with
Charles and David. Even in the court, they passed within feet of
each other, not talking. Charles lives in Wichita and heads the
company founded by their father, the late Fred Koch. David is a
Koch executive, living in New York and best known for buying
Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis' Fifth Avenue apartment. William lives
in Palm Beach, Fla., and Cape Cod, Mass., while Frederick, a
reclusive man who loves to restore castles, owns homes in London,
Monaco, Austria and New York.
</P>
<P>
   The wealth of the family made all four unsympathetic figures to
the jury, who, unlike the expensively dressed lawyers, came to
court in casual clothes, the men tieless.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the wealth did was eliminate sympathy for one side or
another,'' said Stanton Uffman, a farmer and truck driver who was
the jury foreman. ``A great percentage of this case was really a
family issue. We felt the deal was a fair price, but we wanted to
say also that neither side was blameless.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Smelser, a juror employed by Hallmark Cards, added:
``Their wealth had nothing to do with it. But it was personal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
