<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8017 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILWAUKEE-VOUCHER-BOS     06-19 1504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILWAUKEE-VOUCHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL VOUCHER EXPANSION STIRS MILWAUKEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ It's unusually noisy in this otherwise orderly city
on the shores of Lake Michigan, and not just because 50,000 bikers
vroomed in last weekend for the 95th anniversary of
Harley-Davidson, or because the oompah bands are practicing polkas
for this weekend's wildly popular Polish Fest.
</P>
<P>
   The real commotion is over last week's Wisconsin Supreme Court
ruling _ the first of its kind in the nation _ that will allow
low-income children in Milwaukee to attend religious schools with
public money. The city's seven-year-old Parental Choice program
will be expanded, making as many as 15,000 students eligible for
taxpayer-funded tuition this fall at some 80 parochial as well as
31 non-sectarian private schools.
</P>
<P>
   The civil-liberties leaders are in full throat, charging the
court with punching a hole in the constitutional wall that
separates church and state. The local NAACP and teachers' union
decry the decision as dooming the already troubled public schools,
while Republican officials and conservative activists declare
victory and praise private-school vouchers as a free-market cure
for what ails American education.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the loud, political rhetoric, however, there is a more
muted, but no less important, debate going on in and around the
city's religious community. It's about balancing churches'
obligations to serve needy families against the risks of a
state-run voucher program that could change the mission and
character of Milwaukee's parochial schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ruling for choice may look like a free windfall, an
exciting adventure, or a positive opportunity, but if I were
running a Catholic or a Lutheran school today, I'd be very
cautious,'' said Angeline Cepelka, an associate professor of
education at Marquette University here. ``There is always a price
when you get involved with the state, but the sticker isn't on top
of this package.''
</P>
<P>
   The price may be unknown, but the landscape isn't altogether
uncharted for nonpublic schools. Under Milwaukee's pioneering
voucher program, 23 private schools that enrolled 1,500 low-income
children last year received almost $7 million from the state with
virtually no strings attached and none of the rules and regulations
imposed on public schools. So far, Wisconsin officials have pledged
to keep it that way for religious schools.
</P>
<P>
   The infusion of funds _ as much as $4,000 per ``choice'' student
_ is alluring to parochial schools. Many have seen enrollments and
tuition decline sharply as descendants of the immigrant Poles,
Irish, Italians, and Germans who built the sturdy, steepled
Catholic and Lutheran churches and schools in Milwaukee moved to
newer homes in safer suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   The city, once sustained by a booming brewing industry, is now a
somewhat depressed and highly segregated place: North Milwaukee is
predominantly black, the south side is Hispanic, and the eastern
edge on Lake Michigan is white.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been struggling to serve our neighborhoods as parishes
have closed, merged, and restructured,'' said Jerry Topczewski,
spokesman for Milwaukee's Roman Catholic archdiocese. ``We expect
our enrollments to increase with school choice, and that is a
positive impact.''
</P>
<P>
   But questions abound. The telephone hasn't stopped ringing in
Brad Adams's office in the Wisconsin Department of Public
Instruction since the state Supreme Court ruling June 10. Parents
are desperate to know if they qualify for the school-choice program
and where they can place their children. Private schools, which up
to now have not been accredited by the state or required to hire
licensed teachers, want the ground rules before they sign up.
</P>
<P>
   Adams, an education consultant, predicts taxpayers won't
tolerate this ``tremendous lack of oversight'' for long, not when
they are paying a $70 million annual bill for 15,000 of Milwaukee's
104,000 students to attend private schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not today, but maybe five years from today, religious schools
may be very sorry they got into this,'' Adams said. ``The state
will demand accountability, and the result will be two public
school systems.''
</P>
<P>
   For parochial schools, there is also accountability to a higher
authority. Some school administrators say they will challenge a
state law that allows voucher students, at a parent's request, to
be excused from religious activities. Otherwise, administrators say
they can't participate in a program that would restrict religious
instruction and thwart their mission.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Schmeling, schools administrator for the Wisconsin
Evangelical Lutheran Synod, said theology is so incorporated in the
educational program _ for example, science is based on creationism,
and history evolves through God's hands _ that Lutheran schools
could not in good faith become ``choice'' schools if the state
opt-out law stands.
</P>
<P>
   Schmeling said the Lutheran schools he oversees also would
``have a real problem'' with a state policy that protects students
from discrimination based on sexual orientation. ``We believe
homosexuality is a sin, and that is what we would counsel a
child,'' Schmeling said. ``It would be a lie for us to sign off on
this to become a choice school.''
</P>
<P>
   A memo circulated by the Wisconsin Catholic Conference after the
state Supreme Court ruling says the religion opt-out provision
theoretically ``could create a challenge to Catholic identity.''
But John Huebscher, the conference's executive director, said urban
Catholic schools already are so multicultural that accepting more
non-Catholics via vouchers ``is something we will be able to live
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet some fear parochial schools will be caught in uncomfortable
compromises over practices and curricula once they begin to depend
on state funds. Cepelka of Marquette University said Catholic
administrators might give up mandatory communion services that
would exclude non-Catholic children or go along with a ``tyrannical
state'' that prescribes sex education including abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``By virtue of vouchers, there may be entanglements that
directly or indirectly force parochial schools to minimize their
mission as institutions of strong and proclaimed values,'' Cepelka
said.
</P>
<P>
   That is the last thing Valerie Johnson wants. She has refused to
send her five children to Milwaukee's tough public schools,
scrimping and finding scholarships to keep them in parochial
schools, where she said not only academic achievement, but also
virtues like self-discipline, respect, love, and forgiveness are
stressed. A non-Catholic, Johnson is on the school board at the
Resurrection Catholic Academy in north Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I afraid of the religion they teach here? No _ that's why I
like it,'' said Johnson, who belongs to a dynamic group of black
women who launched the city's grass-roots school-choice movement
seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``In public schools you get busing, metal detectors, garbage in
the halls, and classes that are out of control,'' Johnson said.
``Here you get small classes, school uniforms, caring teachers, and
parents who are involved.''
</P>
<P>
   For all those reasons, and others _ including a dropout rate of
50 percent in Milwaukee's public high schools _ the number of
low-income parents expected to make the parochial-school choice
this fall will far exceed the number of spaces available. The
influx will test not only the attitudes of tuition-paying parents,
but also the commitment of private schools to randomly select its
student body.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Rauh, director of the one-year-old Marva Collins
Preparatory School in north Milwaukee, said the biggest myth in the
school-choice debate is that private schools like his will ``skim''
the cream of the academic crop and cast off youngsters with the
severest disabilities and antisocial behavior to public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the opposite. Kids who are doing well stay where
they're at. The children who are struggling are leaving the public
schools,'' Rauh said. He said his facility, which once housed St.
Anne's Catholic School, can handle children with learning
disabilities, but not serious physical handicaps.
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks west, past the Love Child Liquor store and Flo's
Gospel Connection, principal Spencer Korte runs Hi-Mount Community
School, reputedly one of the best public elementary schools in
Milwaukee. Korte doesn't believe that private or parochial school
will accept troublesome students. But he dares them to try. Last
semester, he had to tackle and pin down a parent trying to beat up
a third grader.
</P>
<P>
   ``If, as a political reality or moral imperative, parochial
schools do select `choice' students at random, they will be
surprised at how challenging it is to work with the most badly
damaged families and children,'' Korte said. ``What may surprise
them more is how easy it is in those circumstances to lose your
identity and the identity of who you want to serve.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
