<HEADLINE>
LARGEST HMO WON'T PAY FOR VIAGRA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kaiser Permanente, the nation's largest health maintenance
organization, said Friday it will not pay for Viagra, the
controversial new drug that treats male impotence.
</P>
<P>
   The decision is likely to influence how HMOs across the country
deal with the thorny issue of whether to provide coverge for
Viagra, a problem that some HMO executives are calling
``Viagravation.''
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Massachusetts said Friday it will
pay for only four Viagra pills a month for each patient diagnosed
with impotence, down from 12.
</P>
<P>
   The decision follows a similar move last week by Harvard Pilgrim
Health Care, the largest health maintenance organization in New
England, to cut its coverage from eight pills a month to four.
Aetna U.S. Healthcare, one of the nation's largest HMOs, on Monday
told the New York state regulators that it will not cover Viagra,
at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is cost. At $7 to $10 a pill, Viagra is a potential
budget-buster that threatens to plunge health maintenance
organizations nationwide deep into the red.
</P>
<P>
   Health insurance companies are trying to deal with that threat
by making a distinction between ``life-saving'' and
``life-enhancing'' drugs. In refusing to cover prescriptions for
Viagra, Aetna cited the ``primarily recreational/lifestyle use and
abuse of this drug.''
</P>
<P>
   Under this emerging standard, insurers are saying no to drugs
that may be medically useful but whose main benefit is to make
people's lives more enjoyable.
</P>
<P>
   The distinction is not trivial, health experts say. As medical
miracles continue to roll out of medical laboratories and on to
pharmacy shelves, insurers are sure to adopt tougher standards for
determining whether new drugs are medically necessary. While
impotence is considered a disease, insurers nevertheless that in
many cases Viagra is being used by men to enhance their sex lives
and not to treat a medical problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of a question of where you draw the line,'' said
Susan Pisano, a spokeswoman for the Americal Association of Health
Plans, an industry group in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to make the distinction between something that was
cosmetic versus something that was medically necessary. Viagra is
new. Now there's a new distinction. Are patients using Viagra
because they have an underlying medical problem, or are they using
it for life enhancement?''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Joseph Gerstein, medical director for Tufts Health Plan in
Waltham, Mass., said the same question also could be raised with
anti-depressants such as Prozac or Zoloft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it okay to use it for people with mild depression? Or for
someone who's feeling blue, or fatigued or unhappy?'' Gerstein
said. ``We're not dealing with absolutes. In every case, we're
making a value judgment on how much to spend for certain benefits.
We sit in judgment almost every week about how to distribute other
people's money.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, when Blue Cross was deciding whether to cut back its
coverage for Viagra, officials at the health insurance said that
maintaining coverage at the 12-pill-a-month level would affect its
ability to pay for treatments of other illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned that this is a very expensive product, and we're
going to spend far more on Viagra than on childhood depression this
year,'' said Kathleen J. Goonan, medical director for Blue Cross.
She was unavailable for comment Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser also cited cost as the main reason it had decided to end
coverage for Viagra. ``This has been a particularly difficult
decision for us,'' said Dr. Francis J. Crosson of Kaiser, which has
9.1 million members in 19 states. ``We could, of course, build the
cost of Viagra into everyone's premium, but is that the right thing
to do?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
