u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DORM-TRASH-BOS &LR;      06-19 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DORM-TRASH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTERSN TO COKES: IT'S ALL JUST LAST YEAR'S COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DANIEL A. GRECH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ Laptop computers. Futons, passports, leather wallets.
Laser printers, rugs, watches, mountain bikes. TVs, VCRs,
microwaves, halogen lamps, refrigerators, floral couches.
</P>
<P>
   Wire hangars, plastic hangars, metal hangars.
</P>
<P>
   Enough books to fill a library.
</P>
<P>
   Call them the traces of postmodern university life.
</P>
<P>
   Every June, Boston area college students stage a mass exodus,
stuffing suitcases and station wagons with the collected
remembrances of college life. But it doesn't all fit, or the trip
is too long, or the postage costs too much, or the owner is too
lazy.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Dorm Crew, over 400 Harvard University students who sweep,
scrub, mop, and polish undergraduate dorms in time for summer
school. When they stumble upon items of value, such as the $800
Nieman Marcus evening gown found this year, they collect them for
return to the owner or, if unclaimed, for donation to charity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seniors are by far the worst offenders,'' says Zack Gingo, 22,
a Dorm Crew student supervisor from Bennington, Vt. ``Seniors don't
bother with the heavy furniture, the fridges. It takes us twice as
long to clean out a senior dorm as any other.''
</P>
<P>
   But refrigerators are only the most common booty discovered in
the ghost towns that are college campuses after graduation.
</P>
<P>
   There was an 800-pound, fully assembled V8 engine left in the
fireplace of a room in Adams House several years ago; a
professional moving crew had to be called in to disassemble the
engine and move it out piece by piece.
</P>
<P>
   This year, there was a broken-down old-time Coke machine selling
bottles for 15 cents found in Claverly Hall. And a small cooler
filled with a orange juice and vodka along with a note: ``Dorm
Crew, don't screw around too much.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there are the things students forgot.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Neiman Marcus evening gown, its $800 price tag still
hanging from a sleeve; its owner claimed it within a week. Or the
wardrobe of men's suits, worth close to $2,000, left unclaimed for
over three months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not so much that there is an amazing amount of stuff,
but it is hard to believe that people could leave behind a printer,
a CD player,'' says Gingo, who has been working with Dorm Crew
since his freshman year. ``Students are in a rush, and so they
forget things. Some objects are so much a part of daily life they
become part of the furniture. And some students really don't care
that people have to clean up after them.''
</P>
<P>
   Some students don't even care whether they recover their
valuables. They live across the country _ or the globe _ making it
prohibitively expensive to ship their larger belongings. Others are
too wealthy to care or too distracted during graduation to notice,
Gingo says.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Wolfreys, supervisor of custodial services at Harvard,
says Dorm Crew distributes leftover items in different ways.
Cleaning supplies, which are considered hazardous chemicals, are
handed over to Harvard's waste disposal unit. Expensive items such
as printers and stereos are stored until they are claimed.
</P>
<P>
   Pens, staples, and office supplies are used in the Dorm Crew
office. One drawer alone has a dozen scissors. Books, sports
equipment, and other less valuable items are lotteried off to Dorm
Crew workers.
</P>
<P>
   In a program Wolfreys started last year, stackable crates, trash
cans, mirrors, bulletin boards and message boards are donated to
Habitat for Humanity, which resells them to students in the fall.
Last fall $1,400 was raised, and this year, Wolfreys says, there is
even more to sell.
</P>
<P>
   Other area universities are also involved in recycling student
trash for charitable causes. Boston College has a service project
called Clean Sweep, which recruits 40 alumni volunteers to collect
items students leave behind. This year alone, 17,000 items were
donated to local social service agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were given enough furniture and housing supplies to fully
furnish 25 apartments for battered women,'' says BC spokesman Mike
Seele.
</P>
<P>
   MIT runs a furniture exchange, selling furniture back to
students and donates proceeds into a scholarship fund. Three
hundred students from one dormitory collected 70 trash bags of
clothing which were donated to the Salvation Army and the Pine
Street Inn.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Boston University students have gone through dorms
collecting pennies to donate to local charities, says university
spokesman Joan Schwartz.
</P>
<P>
   But Harvard's Dorm Crew, whose job is to clean as much as to
pillage, emphasizes that their job is not just for amateur
archeologists. They find more junk than jewels. Like the hallway in
Mather Hall so filled with furniture that workers had to climb to
get around. Or the dorm room with 50 wads of gum glued to the
floor.
</P>
<P>
   Or the pair of handcuffs on a bedpost.
</P>
<P>
   Hazards Gingo, ``The owner must have lost the keys.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
