<SLUG> BC-MOB-HEARING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1983 MOB SURVEILLANCE OF CRIME PROBER DETAILED AT HEARING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA NEALON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As the FBI and federal prosecutors prepared to indict
the hierachy of the local Mafia in 1983, the bureau relied on one
of its top informants, reputed gangster Stephen Flemmi, to alert
agents to fallout from the impending roundup of the mob's leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi did just that, former FBI supervisor James A. Ring
testified Friday, even tipping the bureau to an ominous bit of
counter-intelligence: reputed mobsters Donato ``Danny'' Angiulo and
Ilario Zannino were keeping close tabs on the lead prosecutor in
the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were tracking Jerry O'Sullivan (the head of the organized
crime strike force) from the courthouse to North Station,'' Ring
testified. ``They knew his schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   But Flemmi knew what they were up to and told the FBI. ``Flemmi
was on top of the situation,'' said Ring, who headed the organized
crime squad in the Boston office of the FBI from 1983 to 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The tip is just the latest example of the kind of help that the
co-leader of the Irish mob gave the FBI during 30 years of sporadic
informing on his criminal rivals in the Italian Mafia.
</P>
<P>
   Documents released during the first phase of hearings in January
show that Flemmi told the FBI that the local Mafia was ``seriously
considering'' murdering a district attorney and a judge in the
1960s. He was also credited with providing the FBI with information
on a Mafia plot to assassinate a US attorney in the late 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   But now, some 30 years later, attorneys for Flemmi and three of
his codefendants, including reputed New England Mafia boss Francis
P. ``Cadillac Frank'' Salemme, are arguing that extortion and
racketeering charges brought against them should be dropped because
Flemmi infiltrated the Mafia and committed crimes with the
authorization of the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   They are asking US District Judge Mark L. Wolf to dismiss the
landmark 1995 indictment that charges the leaders of the Irish and
Italian mobs with running the region's rackets in tandem for
decades. Wolf is also considering whether a series of wiretaps,
including the bugging of a Mafia induction ceremony in Medford in
1989, was legal.
</P>
<P>
   Under cross-examination Friday by Assistant US Attorney James D.
Herbert, Ring denied that he or anyone in the FBI had ever given
Flemmi or his criminal partner and fellow informant James
``Whitey'' Bulger immunity from prosecution or authorization to
commit crimes.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Ring insisted that Bulger and Flemmi had been warned
that if they were commiting crimes ``you're on your own,'' though
there are no FBI documents to back up his claim that he met with
them at least once a year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a formal bureau procedure that allowed supervisors and
their superiors to authorize crimes, Ring said he did not agree
with the process. ``We should not be in the business of authorizing
criminal activity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   During nearly three months of hearings, no FBI employee, past or
present, has said that Flemmi and Bulger were given permission to
commit crimes, though there has been abundant evidence that the FBI
was aware that they were involved in loansharking, gambling, and
extortion of drug dealers, and were suspects in several murders.
Neither was indicted, however, until January 1995, four years after
they were closed as FBI informants.
</P>
<P>
   Bulger fled before he was indicted _ tipped off, Flemmi claims,
by the FBI _ and remains a fugitive. Ring said he never tipped off
anyone to an upcoming indictment and knew of no one in the FBI who
had done so.
</P>
<P>
   Questioned by Wolf, Ring said he was never told by FBI agent
John Connolly that Connolly had received phone calls from Angelo
``Sonny'' Mercurio while Mercurio was a fugitive. Mercurio was a
key informant, the person who told Ring exactly where and when the
Mafia induction would take place.
</P>
<P>
   Ring insisted that Mercurio had never told Connolly, his
handler, about the planned assassination of Salemme in June 1989,
even after Salemme's attorney, Anthony M. Cardinale, showed him a
report by Connolly 11 days before the botched hit in which Mercurio
told him that the Boston Mafia would ``like to clip Frankie
Salemme.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of talk about killing in that particular
(report),'' said Ring. ``But it doesn't direct us to a particular
event.''
</P>
</TEXT>
