<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8035 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEARNINGSMITH-BOS &LR;      06-19 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEARNINGSMITH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEARNINGSMITH TO DOUBLE NUMBER OF STORES BY 2000 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After struggling earlier in the decade, Learningsmith Inc. says
it will nearly double its number of educational toy-and-games
stores by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now is the time to rapidly expand,'' said Janet Emerson,
president and chief executive of the Bur-lington company.
</P>
<P>
   Paragon Capital, a Needham, Mass. lender that specializes in
helping retailers, said it will provide Learn-ingsmith with a $30
million ``emerging growth facility'' that will help Emerson add 60
new stores to a chain that today has 67.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, Learningsmith had ``significant financial
problems,'' said Paragon president Andrew Moser, but since hiring
Emerson in 1995, Learningsmith has been on a rebound.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's made an incredible difference,'' Moser said Friday.
``She's adopted a new marketing and merchandising strategy that has
turned the company around.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately owned Leaningsmith does not disclose sales or
earnings. Founded in 1991 by local entrepreneur Marshall Smith,
Learningsmith thought it had a winning retail formula that could
quickly be expanded nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   WGBH, Boston's public television station, was an early investor
in the chain, which was once known as WGBH Learningsmith.
</P>
<P>
   But when early sales didn't meet expectations, expansion plans
were put on hold and new managers hired. By her count, Emerson is
the fourth person to hold the company's top job.
</P>
<P>
   Because toys make up a fraction of sales, Emerson takes issue
with descriptions of Learningsmith as an educational toy store.
</P>
<P>
   When he came up with the idea, Smith wanted to create something
unique, a store that sold educational books, puzzles, toys, games,
and videos to both children and adults. About a third of sales are
for products used by adults, Emerson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have only one doll,'' she said. ``There is very little
overlap between what's in a Learningsmith and what's in a Toys
``R'' Us.''
</P>
<P>
   In seeking to become ``a learning store for all ages'' and ``a
general store for the curious mind,'' Learn-ingsmith needed much
trial and error to get its store format and merchandise mix where
it is today.
</P>
<P>
   Some early Learningsmiths too closely resembled a ``serious
bookstore,'' said Emerson, who added, ``When I came in, we said,
`Let's make the store fun again.' It had become too severe.''
</P>
<P>
   About a year ago, the chain hit upon a prototype Emerson thinks
can provide the chain with a robust growth vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Using that model, a roughly 4,300-square-foot store is divided
into ``right-brain and left-brain sections.'' The right-brain
section includes scientific products and a software area called the
Information Highway. The left-brain section is devoted to crafts
and ``humanities,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Given its eclectic merchandise, there are no direct rivals,
though several chains such as the Nature Co. look to nibble at
small pieces of Learningsmith's business, Emerson said.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, many fun-and-games retailers are exploring
alternate sales channels, such as catalogs and the Internet, to
augment sometimes slumping store sales.
</P>
<P>
   Learningsmith isn't ready to dabble in e-commerce just yet.
</P>
<P>
   It plans to continue to focus on opening most stores in malls
that draw affluent, well-educated consumers and attempting to
provide them with an entertaining and informative shopping
experience that allows them to see and touch the merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Said Emerson, Learningsmith seeks to offer ``a fun
environment,'' one with a lot of motion and color and lots of
computers and interactive exhibits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
