r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-US-LADN     06-19 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-US-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S., IRANIAN PLAYERS KNOW IT'S MORE THAN A GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ As much as the participants in the ``mother of all
soccer games'' would like to convince the world otherwise --- as
much as they would like to believe it is not true --- they
recognize that when the United States and Iran share the field
Sunday at the Stade Gerland in Lyon, it will be much more than just
a game.
</P>
<P>
   That's not what they say, of course. For the record, this is
``just an opportunity to get three points,'' ``another game'' or,
more pointedly, ``a game we have to win.''
</P>
<P>
   It is, obviously, far more than that, but if the history that
divides the two nations makes this the most politically charged
clash that will take place in France this summer, those taking part
would rather not deal with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the political stuff and history between the two countries
really has nothing to do with us,'' declares U.S. defender Alexi
Lalas. ``If you really want to look at it that way, (then) look at
Germany. We've got a history with them, too, right? Or Yugoslavia.
They aren't wonderful. We could be pissed off at everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The politics of the situation,'' says Steve Sampson, the
Americans' coach, ``we could care less about.''
</P>
<P>
   It's all rhetoric, although there's a scrap of truth to the
protestations. If Iran coach Jalel Talebi, as he asserts, is ``not
a politician (but) a sportsman,'' he --- and his American rivals
--- understands there is more at stake than a potential berth in
the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Sunday's match is a sizable stride on the road to
normalization between the nations, a process set in motion when
reformist president Mohammad Khatami took power in Iran last
August. He softened his country's official anti-Western stance and
called for improved relations with the United States, the ``Great
Satan'' that had become enemy No. 1 in the wake of the Islamic
revolution of 1979.
</P>
<P>
   American officials followed suit this week. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright on Wednesday unveiled an offer to begin
repairing the relationship with Iran. ``The gap between us remains
wide,'' she said. But it is time to test the possibility for
bridging this gap.''
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the announcement could hardly have been by chance.
Iran, which is competing in the World Cup for the first time since
1978, sees the tournament as a passageway back into the world, and
players on both teams realize that their actions in Stade Gerland
will be rife with symbolism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all of us understand the implications of this game,
and we're all excited about it,'' says U.S. forward Eric Wynalda.
``It's an opportunity for soccer to bring two nations together ---
that's the beauty of the World Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Says U.S. captain Thomas Dooley:``We are athletes and are
playing soccer against athletes. I look forward to meeting these
people. ... We have to live peacefully with these people --- we
live only one time, and if we can do something where the two
nations can come together peacefully, that's good.''
</P>
<P>
   The build-up to the match has been anything but peaceful.
Hardliners within Iran's government called for their players to be
barred from shaking hands with the Americans --- an instruction
Talebi, whose family has lived in the Bay Area since leaving Iran
in 1980, refused to consider.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Monday night, a French television station aired the 1991
film ``Not Without My Daughter,'' starring Sally Field and based on
a true story of an American woman who accompanies her Iranian
husband to his homeland and discovers she can't leave. The Iranian
camp erupted in protest, calling the decision to screen the movie
an intentional ``insult'' that weakened team morale.
</P>
<P>
   There were reports, quickly denied, that the Iranian team might
withdraw from the World Cup in protest, but some saw the furor as
just plain silly. ``If they've been insulted by a movie that's
being shown, they've got bigger problems,'' Lalas said. ``It means
nothing to us --- it's their problem. It's just a movie, man.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, security around the U.S. camp has been tightened,
World Cup officials are bracing for a threatened disruption of the
game by Iranian exile groups, and FIFA even selected the game's
referee --- Urs Meier of Switzerland --- because his ``is the only
country that has excellent diplomatic relations with both
countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone involved is approaching the match in a benign
fashion. Iranian star Khodadad Azizi calls the game ``the most
important of my life'' and admits he's looking for blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``The USA mistreated our country,'' he charges. ``In the
(1980-88) war, they supported our enemies Iraq. ... We will not
lose this game. Many families of martyrs are expecting us to win.
We will win for their sake.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the Americans carry such hard feelings, but few of them
--- aside from the coaching staff, which is three-quarters
foreign-born --- remember much about the hostage crisis, in which
militants seized the U.S. embassy in Tehran and held 52 Americans
for 444 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lived it every night (on TV),'' Sampson says. ``I relate to
it more than the players. ... At some point, you have to put that
aside.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Lalas, who was 9 at the time: ``I certainly was too young
to understand what was happening. It was just, `U.S.: Good. Iran:
Bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Midfielder Frankie Hejduk, who was 5, was asked about ``The
Great Satan.'' His reply: ``I don't really know what you're talking
about.''
</P>
<P>
   His mind, during the crisis, was ``on recess,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's game, even those who see it as merely a game agree, is
part of a process meant to get past the troubles between the
nations the past 19 years. The Iranians plan ``something special''
for the Yanks before the game; they presented roses to Yugoslavia,
their first World Cup foe. Talebi says he has ``a surprise'' in
store for the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides believe they will be building bridges, even if that
is secondary to gaining a needed victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports from the beginning is about getting people together,''
says Talebi. ``It's like those circles in the Olympics that link
together. It is, I believe, what we feel, and I hope it stays that
way.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. forward Ernie Stewart is looking forward to the tradition
jersey exchange at the end of the match. ``Before the game,'' he
says, ``we are going to shake hands, and at the end I would like to
trade jerseys with an Iranian player. That would be a symbol to
both nations of how things can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, no one wants to lose sight of what's truly important.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please don't make (the outside issues) too big for us,''
Talebi pleaded with reporters earlier this week. ``This is a game.
A game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
