<HEADLINE>
APOLLO MANAGEMENT TO BUY TRANSPORTATION EQUIPMENT COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHANA R. SCHOENBERGER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Xtra Corp., a Boston &UR;  &LR; company that leases transportation
equipment, Friday said it agreed to be acquired for $1.9 billion in
stock and debt by Interpool Inc. and financier Leon Black's Apollo
Management IV LP.
</P>
<P>
   The deal values Xtra at $65 a share, or $976 million, a premium
of 41 percent over its closing price Thursday of 41 1/16. The
transaction will be structured as a recapitalization of Xtra, and
the new company, Wheels MergerCo., will assume nearly $1 billion of
Xtra's debt.
</P>
<P>
   Xtra currently has about 900 employees, including 40 in
Massachusetts. Robert Blakely, vice president and controller, said
the company could not comment on whether those workers would remain
on the new firm's payroll or whether Wheels would stay in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Xtra stock soared on the news, closing at 61, up 14 15/16.
Interpool, a transportation leasing firm based in Princeton, N.J.,
gained 1 1/16 to 15 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   Interpool will pump $73.1 million of equity into the new
company, giving it a 22.5 percent stake, while Apollo will invest
$219.4 million for a stake of 67.5 percent. The remaining 10
percent held by existing shareholders will likely trade on the open
market, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   The sale joins two of the top companies in the container-leasing
industry. About half of the world's 12 million shipping containers
are owned by leasing companies like Xtra and Interpool; shipping
companies own the rest, according to Burton M. Strauss, an analyst
with Dominick &AMP; Dominick Inc..
</P>
<P>
   Xtra's business includes marine and railroad containers, highway
trailers, and chassis for moving containers. Interpool also has a
significant chassis business, but is mainly involved with
international containers, said Thano Hasiotis, an analyst with
Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   A strong US economy has driven up the demand for freight and
shipping containers. In Asia, where countries are trying to boost
exports to revive their flagging economies, a shortage of
containers is beginning to develop.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said consolidation is critical for the industry's
smaller companies, particularly in the marine-container market, so
they can expand their capacity and boost efficiency. They said
Interpool was likely to eventually combine its operations with
Xtra's.
</P>
<P>
   Xtra's principal investors, namely Franklin Mutual Advisors and
Tiger Management LLC, were eager to sell the company, according to
Strauss. Xtra said investors holding 44 percent of the stock had
agreed to support the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Apollo would not comment on additional details of the sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's a franchise business with dominant market share
in the business they compete in,'' said Apollo partner Michael
Gross. ``It's been well run for a number of years with a strong
management team.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Material from Bloomberg News was used in this story.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
