<SLUG> BC-SPEND-TICKET-SWITCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'BYE, MOM; HELLO, HIGHER AIR TRAVEL COSTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 21)  
 (bl)  
 By NOELLE KNOX   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every summer, thousands of young children fly across the country
to visit grandparents or, for the growing number of divorced
families, to spend time with a parent. This season, however, if a
youngster is flying alone, it may cost more.
</P>
<P>
   On June 1, Northwest Airlines and Delta Air Lines doubled their
escort fees _ a charge on top of the air fare for unaccompanied
children of varying ages _ to $60 one way if the child has a
connecting flight. (The fee for children flying direct or nonstop
is still $30 one way.) If history is any guide, their competitors
will soon do the same.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines say that higher fees are needed to cover the costs
of the service, but some parents are outraged. One mother in
Detroit, where Northwest has a hub, was so upset she wrote a letter
to Sen. Spencer Abraham, R-Mich., calling the fees ``anti-family
and anti-children.'' She also posted a copy of the letter on the
Internet news group alt.kids-talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid other airlines will feel compelled to hop on the
bandwagon to stay competitive on revenue,'' the parent wrote,
adding that if they do, ``it'll cost more for parents who live
apart from their kids to see their kids.''
</P>
<P>
   The increase has made a stir on Capitol Hill, not just because
it affects children but because it is the latest in a string of
creeping fees. In the last year, carriers have bumped up charges
for everything from changing the dates for nonrefundable tickets to
picking up prepaid tickets at the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Like banks and many other consumer service companies, the
airlines see fees as an important avenue for bolstering revenue.
With air-passenger traffic at record levels and ticket prices up an
average of 8 percent for leisure and 11 percent for business fares,
operating profits for the six largest airlines are expected to top
$7.5 billion this year.
</P>
<P>
   Fees account for a small but growing percentage of that total.
Thomas Schreier, an analyst for Credit Suisse First Boston, said,
``They tend to be areas where it is fairly easy to increase
revenue, since they end up getting matched.''
</P>
<P>
   Many major carriers have raised the fees for customers who pay
for tickets in advance and pick them up at the airport. Many now
charge $75, up from $40 a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers also pay more now to change itineraries on
nonrefundable tickets. In November, Continental Airlines and Delta
raised the fee for reissuing a ticket to $75 from $50. Competitors
followed suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1992, the fee was $25. Today it's $75,'' groused Tom
Parsons, editor of Best Fares Online (www.bestfares.com). ``The
friendly skies are becoming very unfriendly.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is the rise in the child-escort fee that has finally
garnered some political notice. Thursday, in response to the
distressed parent, Abraham asked the Senate Commerce subcommittee
on aviation to ``investigate the issue of excessive airline fees on
minors traveling alone.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue is also getting attention in the House. The higher fee
``seems to be way out of line,'' said Rep. James Oberstar, D-Minn.
``I don't think the workload is twice as difficult as it was; I
don't think the service is twice as valuable as it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Oberstar, the ranking Democrat on the aviation subcommittee of
the House Transportation Committee, raised the issue at a hearing
on June 11 and said he would ask the Transportation Department for
a ``comprehensive review'' of the airlines' programs for
unaccompanied children.
</P>
<P>
   In the age of deregulation, however, government intervention is
unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement is effectively an agreement between the airline
and a parent. Children who fly solo are usually escorted to and
from the plane by a gate agent. The flight attendants look after
the children, often introducing them to the captain and giving them
airplane pins or other souvenirs. If a child must connect to
another flight, some airports have special waiting areas where he
can play until a member of the ground crew takes him to the next
plane.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines do not offer the service for infants or toddlers,
and the age of eligibility varies with each carrier. For Alaska
Airlines, Trans World Airlines and Northwest, children must be at
least 5 years old to travel without a parent. For the other major
airlines, including Delta, the minimum age is 8. Some carriers,
including Southwest Airlines, do not offer escort services.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest expects its service to accommodate 150,000
unaccompanied children this year, a 36 percent increase over 1995.
Delta estimates that it will fly 10,000 solo youngsters this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the summertime, we're dealing with situations where so many
children who are traveling back and forth to spend time with one
parent or another you can have as many as a dozen on the
airplane,'' said Patricia Friend, international president of the
Association of Flight Attendants union. ``The staffing does not
increase, and there is a limited amount of time we can spend with
the child; the best thing we can do is make sure they're OK at all
times.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Peach, a spokeswoman for Northwest, said the company
had to hire more people, build in a child-tracking system and
expand waiting areas in Minneapolis, Detroit and Memphis to
accommodate the junior soloists. She estimated that the company had
spent $400,000 to upgrade the operations, which include
large-screen televisions, video games and art supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The company should be able to recoup its investment quickly.
While Northwest does not break out the number of children who make
connecting flights, the carrier could collect fees in excess of
$4.5 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the child is just going from point A to point B, I don't
know what they're getting for it,'' said Ms. Friend, who has been a
flight attendant for 32 years. ``But if there is a connecting
flight, the airline is accepting responsibility for the well-being
of the child in transferring him or her.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, most parents paid without complaint, said Leslie
Tillem, president of Eltee Travel in Manhattan. ``Anything to do
with children, people will pay.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
