<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-FRENCH-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIGERIA IS LATEST BORA TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ It was vintage Bora.
</P>
<P>
   There he was, addressing a mob of media from within the bowels
of Parc des Princes speaking much but saying little, bouncing from
English to French to Spanish, confounding his translators all the
while a huge smile plastered across his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very happy,'' he repeated again and again, and with good
reason. Nigeria, the fourth team Bora Milutinovic has taken to the
World Cup, had just claimed its place in the second round with an
at-times impressive 1-0 victory over Bulgaria. The score was quite
deceptive, and while the Super Eagles had not soared as they can,
he knew they were celebrating in Lagos.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, what change a couple weeks can bring. When Bora arrived in
France two weeks ago, his tenure with Africa's finest side appeared
nearing an end. A horrible run-up to the Cup with one-sided losses
to Yugoslavia, Swiss club Grasshoppers, and the Netherlands had
turned Nigeria from favorites to laughingstocks, and the Nigeria
Football Association had had enough.
</P>
<P>
   Jo Bonfrere, who guided the Eagles to Olympic gold in 1996,
checked into the team hotel, and the men who make such decisions
determined that Bora no longer was fit to be coach.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing in Nigeria is so simple. Before Bora's ouster could be
finalized, approval was needed, from none other than Sani Abacha,
the nation's military ruler. Instead, news of a different sort
arrived: Abacha was dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am Bora,'' Milutinovic would say later. ``I am a lucky
man.''
</P>
<P>
   And Nigeria, while in deepest mourning over the loss of its
leader, can count itself fortunate that Bora is still around. He's
a master tactician, a ``miracle worker'' whose feats with lesser
squads --- among them the United States in the 1994 World Cup ---
finally earned him the chance to guide a team as talented as he is
brilliant.
</P>
<P>
   It was almost over as soon as it started.
</P>
<P>
   Those losses, and Nigeria's lackluster play in them, impressed
nobody, least of all the bureaucrats who run soccer in Africa's
largest nation. Abacha's death might have gained Bora some time,
but unless the Super Eagles pulled off a stunner in their Cup
opener, a week ago in Nantes, he was on his way out.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria 3, Spain 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Spain had beaten us,'' he said afterward, ``I'm sure I
would be at home with my family. That's life. ... Whatever happens,
I'm very fortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Six days later, and he's on top of the World Cup, champions of
the Group of Death with one match remaining, a second-round matchup
with Denmark or South Africa --- neither much of a threat ---
looming just ahead.
</P>
<P>
   It's not quite what it was in '94, he admits, even though he has
a team this time that could --- but won't --- win it all. The
Nigerians lack discipline, and their attack-at-all-costs mentality
does cost it at times, and it will once they come up against a
truly outstanding team, like Brazil in the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Bora was happy just to get to the second round
with the Americans, who had no business getting there. That was a
labor of love, and this is a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``In U.S., the team was like my boys,'' he said Friday. ``Here
is different. I'm a professional.''
</P>
<P>
   In America, there wasn't much pressure. He could lose and lose
and lose leading to the World Cup as long as his team didn't
embarrass itself when the games counted. This time was different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friendly matches don't count,'' he said after the 5-1 loss to
the Dutch. ``The World Cup is all that's important.''
</P>
<P>
   His players, who acknowledge they have trouble getting motivated
for friendlies, agree. The only thing that matters is the World
Cup, and Bora --- again --- is proving his worth when it counts.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Friendly games) don't really matter that's not where the
action is,'' said forward Daniel Amokachi, echoing his coach. ``The
World Cup is the World Cup, and a friendly game is a friendly game.
Now we're doing the job, and everybody is happy. The government is
happy, the fans are happy, everybody is happy.''
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, Bora is happy, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
