<SLUG> BC-MANZANAR-NATIONAL-SITE-ART-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL HISTORIC SITE REMEMBERS WORLD WAR II JAPANESE INTERNEES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ps) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONE PINE, Calif. _ The stone sentry posts stand empty and
silent now at Manzanar, their graceful pagoda shapes a haunting
reminder in the desolate high desert here on the eastern slope of
the Sierra Nevada. In World War II, this lonely stretch of scrub
off Highway 395 was the largest outpost between Los Angeles and
Reno.
</P>
<P>
   It had a Bank of America branch and a hospital of 250 beds, plus
an orphanage, a hog farm and chicken ranch. It had a Boy Scout
troop, baseball teams, a 9-hole golf course with oiled-sand greens
and a swing band called the Jive Bombers, who played all the
wartime hits, even Cole Porter's jaunty cowboy ballad, ``Don't
Fence Me In.''
</P>
<P>
   But Manzanar was no ordinary town. Behind its armed guards and
barbed wire fences, in tar paper barracks that baked in the summer
heat and shook in the winter winds, it housed 10,000
Japanese-Americans, most of them U.S. citizens, who were brought
here from their homes and businesses along the West Coast against
their will in the mass hysteria that followed Pearl Harbor. In all,
10 ``relocation centers'' held about 120,000 internees imprisoned
between 1942 and 1945 as a result of the infamous Executive Order
9066.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after years of halting steps, the National Park Service is
just beginning to develop the abandoned remains of Manzanar as a
National Historic Site, to tell the story of all the camps to new
generations. Congress conferred the designation in 1992 after a
long campaign by survivors, but provided no initial appropriation
to run the park. Last year, the Park Service finally got title to
813 acres in a land swap with the Los Angeles Department of Water
and Power, which had owned the parcel for decades. This summer, the
staff of one full-time superintendent is about to double with the
addition of a ranger from nearby Death Valley National Monument.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, this is going to be a grabber,'' said Ross R. Hopkins, the
park superintendent, his voice alive with enthusiasm for a master
plan that calls for reconstructing parts of the camp's grounds and
buildings, adding a shuttle bus with interpretative tours and
putting up weatherproof metal signs scattered around the ruins and
restoring the camp's one surviving building, the auditorium, as a
visitor's center and museum. It is a big change from the last four
years, when Hopkins, 61, has been what he wryly calls ``sole owner
and operator'' of the site.
</P>
<P>
   There are many reasons for what Hopkins diplomatically calls the
``lack of leadership'' that has delayed development of Manzanar,
chief among them the Park Service's recent years of budget-cutting
in which ``we're competing with Yellowstone and Yosemite and other
heavily used parks with tremendous environmental problems,''
Hopkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Even with no formal program, park officials here estimate that
Manzanar, about 212 miles north of Los Angeles on the road between
Death Valley and Yosemite National Park, already draws 18,000 to
25,000 visitors a year. They drive around its rutted roads, dotted
with the ghostly remnants of rock gardens and ornamental ponds
built by the internees. Virtually all the barracks were torn down
at the end of the war, and their lumber was sold to returning
veterans at discount prices to build homes.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the only organized tours are conducted by Richard
Stewart, a 54-year-old elementary school art teacher in nearby
Bishop, who will begin on Saturday his second summer of twice-daily
walking tours of an hour and 45 minutes. His tours are financed
with a $3,500 grant from the Eastern California Museum in
Independence, five miles up the road from the camp site and now
home to a heartbreaking collection of artifacts from Manzanar _
carved wooden pins, mess kits, a fragment of barbed wire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody said that if the Park Service tells this story right,
we'll have everybody mad at us,'' said Hopkins, who keeps an
unlisted home phone number because of harassment from some local
residents who oppose developing the park and have threatened to
burn down the auditorium, which was preserved in the first place
only because it served as a garage for the Inyo County Department
of Public Works.
</P>
<P>
   ``My objection is it's not being recognized truthfully,'' said
W.W. Hastings, 73, a retired banker and World War II Marine veteran
in nearby Bishop who has conducted a letter-writing campaign in the
local newspaper objecting to the Park Service's plans. ``The
Japanese were free to come and go. All it was was an assembly
center,'' he said. ``They were escorted there not to keep them
under control but just to protect them. It did have a loose
barbed-wire fence, but I saw them sneaking out all the time to go
fishing.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Those kinds of comments, according to Sue Kunitomi Embrey, help
explain why even now, many elderly survivors are deeply ashamed and
reluctant to talk about their camp experiences, and why it has
taken so long to get the park up and running.
</P>
<P>
   ``They focus on, `Oh, it was a not a concentration camp,''' said
Ms. Embrey, a 75-year-old retired teacher in Los Angeles who was 18
when she was taken to Manzanar with her family and now heads the
Manzanar Committee, the survivor group that pressed for creation of
the park. ``They don't focus on how it could have happened in a
democracy. I think it's very important that Americans remember what
happened. Everyone talks about the Holocaust Museum in Washington
being so popular, but that happened across the ocean.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who has heard the firsthand stories of dozens of
survivors who come to Manzanar on pilgrimages, says the most
painful irony of the camp remains the apple-pie Americanism of the
very people who were interned as threats to America. When some
internees threatened to tear down the camp's American flag in
protest over their treatment, the camp Boy Scout troop got wind of
the plan and formed a protective cordon around the flagpole,
Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as Stewart leads visitors around the groves of trees and
the remnants of gardens, his eyes are eagle-sharp. Not long ago, in
the ruins of the garden of Block 6, he saw a slender green shoot of
bamboo sprung to life again from the hard, rocky soil.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got to be more than 50 years old,'' he said in quiet
wonder. ``They say it grows in 20 year cycles, so it's coming up
again, just in time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
