<SLUG> BC-WOODWARD-INTERVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AU PAIR'S MOTHER DENIES BEING PAID FOR INTERVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Budgeted as Woodward-Elton; a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JORDANA HART   AND JOHN ELLEMENT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELTON, England _ In a rare impromptu interview, Louise
Woodward's mother adamantly denied that a London newspaper paid
them for an interview last fall, after Woodward had been convicted
of murder for the death of baby Matthew Eappen.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many times do we have to say it?,'' Susan Woodward told
reporters stationed outside her home, most from Boston. ``We've not
been paid. We don't want to be paid.''
</P>
<P>
   But the London Daily Mail issued a statement Friday
contradicting her. The paper said Susan Woodward and her husband,
Gary, were paid for an interview last November, shortly after a
Middlesex County, Mass. jury had convicted their daughter of
second-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, the Woodward family was invovled in a fight to
clear their daughter's name,'' according to the statement. ``They
considered it necessary to receive payment in order to help fund
their legal battle.''
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, Harvey Silverglate, a member of Louise Woodward's
defense team, said he spoke with his client Friday and she told him
she has never accepted payment for an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only speak for Louise,'' he said. During a conversation with
her Friday evening, he said, Woodward ``confirms ... that she has
received no money. She has entered into no deal'' and has not
received any payments through her parents.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Frederic L. Ellis, the Boston attorney suing Woodward
and her parents on behalf of Sunil and Deborah Eappen, said the
Woodwards' denials made him ``sick.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe this is the tip of the iceberg,'' Ellis said. ``We
believe there were other payments made to her and her family and we
believe that she has continued to negotiate other deals despite her
denials.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court upheld
Woodward's manslaughter conviction in Matthew Eappen's death but
declined to order a new sentence, effectively freeing her.
</P>
<P>
   Within 68 minutes, the Eappens filed a wrongful-death suit
against Woodward in federal court, and later won a 12-day
injunction which blocks her and her parents from spending any
profits in a media deal.
</P>
<P>
   Since she was released in November, Woodward, her attorneys and
her parents have denied reports the family will profit from her
plight. The Daily Mail statement seems to contradict them.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of Woodward's conviction, the newspaper said, public
opinion in Britain strongly backed her, and many believed the
teenage au pair had been railroaded.
</P>
<P>
   That feeling ``was vindicated within days of us publishing the
interview with the Woodwards when Judge (Hiller B.) Zobel quashed
the murder conviction,'' the paper said.
</P>
<P>
   Silverglate said that in November 1997, once the Woodward case
made international headlines, dozens of offers for paid interviews
flowed in _ including $100,000 from the National Enquirer and
$250,000 from News of the World.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Silverglate said, Louise Woodward reiterated
instructions she gave the defense team before trial: Reject all
offers for paid interviews.
</P>
<P>
   That position, Silverglate said, has ``just been consistent from
the day the case began to take on a high profile, which was long
before last November.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ellis said he strongly believes that secret deals are being
made for the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``This really makes me sick _ the thought of her making money
from the death of this child, while telling supporters of hers ...
to contribute to a defense fund,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Elton Friday, Susan Woodward spent about 20 minutes talking
to journalists, and insisted she had not been paid. She spoke
briefly about her daughter, whom she said was striving to ``to get
her life back'' under difficult circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matthew's death has been difficult for her and she had not
been able to deal with it properly,'' Susan Woodward said.
</P>
<P>
   She also scolded the reporters who are still camped in town, and
vowed to protect her daughter from any intrusions on her privacy.
``She is not Princess Di and she won't be hounded to her death,''
Susan Woodward said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
