<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8060 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLUECROSS-COX     06-19 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLUECROSS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ga. Blue Cross could seek partnership
 &HT;    By Andy Miller
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- As the health care industry rumbles through
consolidation, Georgia's biggest insurer, too, might be looking for
a partner.
</P>
<P>
   Past merger speculation has paired Blue Cross and Blue Shield of
Georgia with Blue plans based in Alabama, Virginia and Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   The newest possible match, however, could be a huge
California-based insurer, WellPoint Health Networks, which has Blue
Cross roots as well. WellPoint has the money and the track record
to pull off such an acquisition, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Neither WellPoint nor Blue Cross of Georgia would comment Friday
on the possibility of talks between them. Blue Cross issued a
statement that said company policy is to comment only when a
decision has been reached to proceed with a new initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   For-profit WellPoint is acquisition-minded, having recently
picked up the health care business of John Hancock and
Massachusetts Mutual.
</P>
<P>
   Its managed-care business in California is operated as Blue
Cross of California. WellPoint's health plans in Georgia are
offered under the UniCare label. Overall, the company has 6.7
million managed-care members.
</P>
<P>
   WellPoint is among the best-run U.S. health insurers, said
analyst Todd Richter of Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``They are a
prudent buyer; they buy things that are a good strategic and
cultural fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent megamergers in health insurance have included Aetna and
U.S. Healthcare, and a pending $6.3 billion agreement between
United HealthCare and Humana. Consolidation provides market clout
and cost efficiencies as insurers battle ferociously for managed
care business. A WellPoint acquisition likely would provide a
handsome payoff for the investors in Blue Cross' 1996 conversion
from a nonprofit to a for-profit company. It might also lead to a
multimillion-dollar settlement on a lawsuit by consumer groups.
They are seeking to recover hundreds of millions of dollars the
plaintiffs say were illegally transferred to Blue Cross when it
converted.
</P>
<P>
   That conversion gave about 70,000 policyholders five shares of
stock each in Cerulean, the new parent company. A group of wealthy
investors who put about $50 million into the plan received about 20
percent of Cerulean.
</P>
<P>
   If Blue Cross is acquired, ``the investors' return becomes a lot
higher than their investment risk,'' said Richard Winston, an
Atlanta financial analyst who opposed the conversion.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could cash out at about 15 percent to 20 percent return,
or they could convert their shares into common shares, if the
acquisition offer is high enough,'' Winston said. ``And that return
could exceed 20 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   But before a possible Blue Cross deal goes through, the consumer
groups' lawsuit likely would be settled first, Winston said. ``It
would behoove them to clear any potential big liability,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That could mean millions for charitable health care
organizations in the state. Neither Blue Cross executive Charlie
Harman nor an attorney for the consumer groups would comment on
possible negotiations in the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Such conversions of Blue Cross plans have run into strong
opposition nationwide from consumer groups, who say the insurers
have accumulated years of tax breaks as nonprofits.
</P>
<P>
   In many states, legislative and regulatory actions have caused
billions to be set aside or designated for charity. For example,
all assets of Blue Cross of California, about $3.2 billion, have
been transferred to two health care foundations.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, that California conversion involved WellPoint,
formed in 1992 to operate Blue Cross of California's managed-care
business.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, WellPoint and Blue Cross of California merged into a
stockholder-owned company. As a result, the foundations were
created.
</P>
<P>
   State Insurance Commissioner John Oxendine, who approved Georgia
Blue's conversion, recently dismissed a petition by the consumer
groups to re-examine the deal. Oxendine would have to approve any
acquisition of Georgia Blue.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
