<HEADER>
A8061 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GM-DEALER-COX     06-19 0414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-DEALER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GM dealers displaying showroom confidence
 &HT;    By Kristi E. Swartz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- While General Motors' pipeline of vehicles has been
nearly shut off at the source, metro area dealers remain confident
that their showroom inventory won't trickle out soon.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 23 assembly plants, including Doraville, have been
closed and nearly 110,000 workers idled because of strikes at two
Flint, Mich., parts plants.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, President Clinton urged the union and automaker to
settle their disputes. GM Chairman and Chief Executive John F.
Smith Jr. said the company wants a quick resolution but said it has
to be one that makes GM more competitive. So far, neither side
seems willing to compromise as GM pushes to cut costs and the union
digs in to save jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Metro area dealers say the affects of the strike will be felt in
the showrooms in 60 to 90 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now the inventory is good, but if they're not building
anything, we'll see the affect down the road,'' said Daniel
Rothermel, general sales manager for Bob Davis Pontiac Oldsmobile
GMC Isuzu in Roswell.
</P>
<P>
   Most dealers have a six- to eight-week lag time between ordering
vehicles and receiving them, Rothermel said. He's more concerned
with the orders he's filing now for vehicles that won't be built
until negotiations between GM and the United Auto Workers are
settled and production resumes.
</P>
<P>
   Some models aren't affected. Chevrolet's Corvette plant in
Bowling Green, Ky., and the Saturn plant in Spring Hill, Tenn.,
remain open.
</P>
<P>
   Sales representative Jim Snyder at Moore Pontiac Quick GMC in
Canton said he's using the strike as a chance sell vehicles to
indecisive customers. ``It's made a lot of them make their move,''
he said. ``They know that this is as low as the price is going to
get.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ron Hood, general manager of Balmy-Strickland Chevrolet
Oldsmobile Pontiac in McDonough, said customers are used to hearing
the word ``strike'' and aren't paying attention to it anymore.
``Even if the workers come back tomorrow or next week, new
inventory won't show up for a few weeks or a month down the road,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This costs everyone: the union members who aren't getting pay,
the businesses around Doraville and average dealership stock will
go down every day,'' said Gregory Barranco, president of Barranco
Pontiac GMC in Lilburn.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
