<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHERS-FLUNK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE-THIRD OF TEACHER CANDIDATES FAIL READING, WRITING TEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH DALEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ At least a third of the 1,800 candidates who took
Massachusetts' first teacher certification test are not qualified
because they can't read or write well enough, state Commissioner of
Education Frank Haydu III said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The number of candidates who failed the test may increase on
Monday, when the state Board of Education votes on what constitutes
a passing score. While at least a third failed the literacy
portion, as many as 59 percent failed overall, based on a standard
recommended by a panel of 300 educators.
</P>
<P>
   Haydu has recommended a standard under which 44 percent will
have failed the test overall.
</P>
<P>
   The two-part, eight-hour test was given as part of Education
Reform efforts to raise standards for both teachers and students.
Those taking the test included seniors or recent graduates of such
teaching colleges as Wheelock and Simmons; the Harvard School of
Education, and the Lesley College School of Education.
</P>
<P>
   In the literacy portion, which ``a strong student in tenth-grade
should be able to pass,'' said Haydu, the college graduates did so
dismally on spelling, grammar and writing, they showed an
``inability'' to construct proper sentences. Candidates did better
on the section that tested knowledge of their subject area.
</P>
<P>
   The large number of failures is not expected to affect the
hiring of an estimated 3,000 teachers by schools across the state
next year, because there are enough certified teachers to fill the
need.
</P>
<P>
   But a continued high failure rate by college graduates could
have profound ramifications over the next decade, as the state
retires almost 40 percent of its teaching force. Public schools
rarely hire teachers who are not certified.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a wake-up call to all of us,'' said William Dandridge,
dean of the Lesley College School of Education. He said the problem
is not limited to students of education, but is a result of a
dumbing down of learning standards for all students, beginning in
elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   ``How would this play out if you would require all college
graduates to take the same test?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But state Board of Education chairman John Silber said, ``Let's
blame the colleges,'' who ``pass students who haven't demonstrated
competency in subject matter.'' Silber wants the board to approve a
higher passing score than what Haydu has recommended.
</P>
<P>
   Students can retake the test this summer, or as many times as
they like until they pass it, Haydu stressed Friday. He and other
educators declined to estimate how many teachers now in classrooms
would fail the test if they had to take it. Before this year,
Massachusetts was one of only seven states that did not test
teachers for certification.
</P>
<P>
   The tests were criticized in April after college students found
out the scores would count toward certification only a week before
the test.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the actual student answers shown to reporters Friday
illustrated a strikingly poor grasp of English grammar. Some
sentences were missing verbs; in others, common words were
misspelled or incorrectly defined.
</P>
<P>
   Haydu said that because the test is new and more challenging
than other states' teacher tests, he is recommending a lower
passing score than the educator panel has recommended. He said he
could have gone even lower, as other states have done. He also
recommended the lower passing score to protect the department from
possible lawsuits from those taking the test, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though students will not receive their score for several
weeks, there was plenty of protest against the test Friday.
Education professors said it did not test teaching skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teachers are going to be taken to task for a test that does
not test what we teach,'' said Frinde Maher, an education professor
at Wheaton College in Norton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Kellie Jones, a 29-year-old graduate education student at
Simmons College in English as a Second Language, said parts of the
test would have been difficult for anyone. In one dictation
section, it ``was difficult to ascertain through the narration when
the sentence began. There wasn't appropriate inflection or tone.''
She said ``there was a lot of anxiety for students'' because many
were unaware the test would ``count'' until only days before it was
taken.
</P>
<P>
   Haydu said that despite the disappointing resuts, the test could
serve as proof that the teaching of writing and grammar must
improve at all grade levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the beginning of a public policy debate,'' Haydu said.
``We all have to look at the issue of literacy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
