<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pepsico pours it on in war of words
 &HT;    By Mickey H. Gramig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Pepsico Inc. on Friday fired the latest salvo in
what, for now, is a war of words with the world's largest
soft-drink company.
</P>
<P>
   In a 21-page legal brief, Pepsico urged the U.S. District Court
in New York not to side with the Coca-Cola Co., which last month
submitted a 26-page memorandum asking the court to throw out
Pepsico's antitrust lawsuit against the Atlanta-based beverage
giant.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed May 7, accuses Coca-Cola of using illegal
tactics to dominate the $54 billion fountain soft-drink business
Coca-Cola has a 65 percent market share to Pepsico's 24 percent.
Pepsico says Coca-Cola has a monopolistic lock on fountain
business, and that it has threatened to cut off the supply of Coke
products to independent food service distributors who also deliver
the Pepsi line to restaurants, movie theaters, s
</P>
</TEXT>
