<DOCNO> NYT19980619.0344 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8073 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BC-CLINTON-CHINA-0620     06-19 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-CLINTON-CHINA-0620-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON TO SEEK NUCLEAR MISSILE DE-TARGETING AGREEMENT FROM
CHINA
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service (at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton said Friday that China and the
United States should stop targeting each other with nuclear weapons
and that he would seek an agreement to accomplish that when he
meets with Chinese President Jiang Zemin next Saturday in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   The move could increase the security of both nations, help build
confidence between the two Pacific giants and strengthen global
efforts to contain the threat of nuclear war, Clinton said in an
Oval Office interview.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it'd be a good thing if we could get it,'' said
Clinton. ''I'd like to see it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also said China's bloody 1989 crackdown on democracy
advocates near Tiananmen Square would weigh on his mind as Jiang
welcomes him in front of the Great Hall of the People, along the
western edge of the 98-acre square.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously I want to see Tiananmen Square, and I will think
about what happened there nine years ago,'' Clinton said. ''But I
also will be thinking about the last, turbulent century in China's
history and the fact that that whole setting there has been the
center of China's political life . . . There will be a lot to think
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton leaves Wednesday, June 24 for China. He will be the
first sitting American president to visit the communist country
since the Tiananmen massacre, which left hundreds of unnarmed
Chinese dead.
</P>
<P>
   Critics on Capitol Hill and elsewhere have said Clinton would
dishonor those killed in 1989 if he visits Tiananmen Square. The
president has rejected that argument, however, saying the Chinese
traditionally fete visiting heads of state at the Great Hall.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton has said Beijing must apologize for the 1989
crackdown ''sooner or later.''
</P>
<P>
   White House and Pentagon officials acknowledged last week that
the administration is working toward a nuclear de-targeting
agreement with China, though Clinton conceded Friday that
outstanding issues remain. Part of the problem is that China wants
the United States to pledge that it would not launch a nuclear
attack on China unless the Chinese launched such an attack first.
The United States refuses to renounce such so-called
''first-strike'' options.
</P>
<P>
   While neither country publicly discusses its nuclear targeting
regime, analysts generally believe both countries have
intercontinental ballistic missiles with nuclear warheads on them
aimed at each other. That creates a dangerous hair-trigger
situation that poses grave risks of a miscalculation by one side or
the other.
</P>
<P>
   De-targeting such weapons would not mean they couldn't be used
against each other. They can be re-targeted within 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But, said Clinton, de-targeting would sharply reduce the risk of
an accidental attack by one side or the other and could allow
critical time for leaders to defuse an emergency situation.
</P>
<P>
   ''Twenty minutes, in a world of instantaneous communications, is
an eternity,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   A de-targeting agreement, Clinton said, would also buttress
China's position as a force for stability in a potentially volatile
region, where recent nuclear tests by India and Pakistan have
heightened fears of a nuclear exchange.
</P>
<P>
   He made his comments in an interview with Cox Newspapers,
McClatchey Newspapers and the CBS television network.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a dark suit, white shirt and brightly patterned tie,
Clinton answered questions centered on his China trip during the
half-hour interview, as his puppy, Buddy, wandered about
punctuating the president's comments with sporadic barking. Clinton
said that a busy week battling Congress over tobacco legislation,
monitoring events in the former Yugoslav republic of Kosovo and
working to buttress the sagging Japanese currency had left him with
less time than he would like to focus on his upcoming China trip --
and a softness beneath his eyes hinted at a week of less than
optimal rest.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, however, the president appeared fit, healthy and
tightly focused on interviewers' questions.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the session he remarked that he was happy his daughter,
Chelsea, was returning to Washington from Stanford University on
Saturday night, in time to be with him for Father's Day on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT(at)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
