<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYPRUS-CONFLICT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREECE AND TURKEY REVIVE DISPUTE OVER CYPRUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
(lb) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ Greece and Turkey are at odds again over the
divided island of Cyprus, with Greek planes landing on the island
and Turkish planes screeching overhead in retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   The latest quarrel reflected the fact that although the Cypriot
dispute is ostensibly between the Republic of Cyprus and the
ethnically Turkish enclave in the north, the greater conflict is
between their patron states, Greece and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   This week's tension began rising on Tuesday when four Greek F-16
fighter jets accompanied by two military cargo planes landed at a
Cypriot airfield. Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz of Turkey asserted
that by sending the aircraft to Cyprus, Greece had ``shown its
offensive intentions directed against Turkey.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, six Turkish F-16s flew across the island on
Thursday. They made several low-level passes over Greek areas.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Greek-populated Cypriot republic, Christos
Stylianides, said that Turkey was creating ``artificial tension,''
but that he did not expect the confrontation to lead to any ``hot
incidents.''
</P>
<P>
   Turkish officials said they were preparing an appeal to Britain
for help in calming tension on the island. Under terms of the
treaty that gave Cyprus independence in 1960, Britain is a
``guarantor power,'' along with Greece and Turkey, and thus has a
legal right to intervene in order to enforce terms of the treaty. A
government spokesman in London said that Britain would welcome an
appeal from either side.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Holbrooke, the newly designated U.S. delegate to the
United Nations, who is also a special U.S. envoy assigned to deal
with problems on Cyprus, is due in Athens, Greece, on Monday.
Holbrooke's last visit there, in May, produced no substantial
results.
</P>
<P>
   Cyprus has been formally divided since Turkish troops landed on
the island in 1974, saying they had been called to protect the
rights of ethnic Turks. In 1983 Turkish Cypriots proclaimed their
one-third of the island a separate republic, but it is recognized
only by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Greece and Turkey are historic rivals, and tensions between them
have risen in recent months. Turkey is worried that new Russian
missiles that are to be stationed in Greek Cyprus will upset the
military balance, and that they could be used to attack its planes.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Ismail Cem of Turkey argued this week that the
missiles would ``not serve defensive purposes, but are an important
part of a Greek plan for possible aggression against Turkey.'' The
United States has urged Greek Cypriot leaders not to deploy the
missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Greece was a key force in the European Union's decision last
December not to consider Turkey's application for membership.
Greece has also blocked the release of funds for Turkey. At a
European Union leaders' meeting last weekend in Cardiff, Wales,
Prime Minister Costas Simitis of Greece vetoed plans by Britain and
other countries to make a new overture to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Simitis said President Clinton had telephoned him in Cardiff and
urged him to soften Greek stances toward Turkey because they
``might lead to tension in the area.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I told President Clinton that this was not possible,'' he
said. ``My response was that Turkey, and not Greece, would be
responsible for any tension in the area.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
