<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8079 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SCULPTURE-COLUMN-N     06-19 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCULPTURE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: OPEN-AIR SCULPTURE WITH A ZIP CODE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The postman never rings twice when he gets to Ezra
Shales' house on a half-empty strip of Beach 43rd Street in
Edgemere, Queens. A double take is more likely. There is no bell;
nor, for that matter, any doors, walls or people. Just a bright
yellow mailbox set into the sandy dirt by the cracked sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   Shales has a house in name only, and even that detail won't be
decided until later Saturday during a housewarming party on the
block. For weeks, Shales has culled dozens of postcards that have
arrived at his lonely mailbox with suggested names for his
``Nominal Home,'' a sculpture set in a weed-covered lot near the
Far Rockaway boardwalk.
</P>
<P>
   The home consists of bales of hay scattered on the narrow lot.
Each bale was slathered with plaster and labeled BED, DOOR, TABLE
and even DOG, all built to crumble through rain, heat and time.
Shales wants people to reconsider their ideas about the changing
faces and fortunes of the city. Although the postman has got used
to it, most people who walk down this deserted street just off the
concrete arches of the A train think the home is a work in
progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``You put a mailbox up on a street with no house, and you get
mail there,'' Shales said with wry satisfaction. ``Still, I like it
when people ask me what it's going to be. There's a refusal to
believe what you see. It tells you what people think about work,
art and land. And vacant lots.''
</P>
<P>
   There are lots of lots on this stretch of the Rockaway
Peninsula, thanks to ideas the city had in the 1960s about urban
renewal. Once home to bungalows and beachgoers, Edgemere and nearby
Arverne became desolate after blocks were razed for homes that were
never built. Recently, modest plans emerged to build affordable
housing and shops and reclaim some of the hundreds of empty acres.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of my awareness of the city comes from having read about
archeology and reading things like Alfred Kazin's `A Walker in the
City,''' said Shales, a museum educator. ``In the city you think
about how it flows, how things are built and fall apart.''
</P>
<P>
   He plopped his sculpture on a lot that a friend of a friend had
purchased years ago at a city auction. ``They were lifelong New
Yorkers who had always hoped it would come back,'' he said.
``Beautiful beachfront property, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   He cleared away some of the land, purchased some hay from a man
who also supplies the race tracks, and printed 10,000 picture
postcards of the sculpture, which he gave to friends, teachers and
anybody else he could find. In fact, he considers the postcards and
their suggested names as artistically important as the sculpture
itself. Among the recommendations are: Housilly, Baleful and No Mo
Ho.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm making something here that people might not come all the
way out here to see,'' he said. ``You go to flea markets, though,
and you see people buying and selling old postcards. It's a funny
memento of a place they aren't even sure exists anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Shales knows that some people deride conceptual art as being
understood only by the black turtleneck crowd. Others look at
public art, if at all, as high-priced corporate street furniture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having this outside here, it's not about degrees, paper
degrees or provenance,'' he said. ``No pretensions. It just has a
kind of street value. That's what people talk about when they talk
about something having value. In economic terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why many people who pass by his house always ask if
he is going to put a fence around it. For protection, you know.
Like John Fillyaw, who stopped on the street a few days ago on the
way to visit his girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is that?'' Fillyaw asked. ``What is it going to be?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It already is,'' Shales replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like that?'' Fillyaw said. ``You're putting up no fence?
Nothing?''
</P>
<P>
   Fillyaw tilted his head back as he beheld the lot. He liked it.
He liked the idea of things changing. Of course, he has long heard
talk about all kinds of changes promised for this neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think years ago they were talking about bringing casinos out
here,'' he said. ``That would have been good for New York. Now
Jersey's got it all.''
</P>
<P>
   As an electrician, he savored the thought of all the work that
would have brought his way. All that money. But, ever the optimist,
he ventured a suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need lights out here,'' he said to Shales. ``I can put up
some garden lights. All low voltage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
