s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-IPO-ART-$ADV21     06-19 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-IPO-ART-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW STOCK IS FUELED BY NESTING BOOMERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Attn: Calif., N.Y., Conn., Texas)   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 21)  
 (af)  
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One part Pottery Barn, one part J. Peterman catalogue,
Restoration Hardware is the latest home store trying to capitalize
on the nesting urges of baby boomers to come to market.
</P>
<P>
   Investors' urges sent the stock ballooning up to $26.25 a share,
or 38 percent above the offering price of $19 on Friday, the first
day of trading.
</P>
<P>
   The chain's name is a bit deceiving. It does sell hardware, but
none of it is really meant for restoring anything. The company's 47
stores are actually emporiums of big leather chairs, fancy dog
biscuit mix and the odd Russian flashlight or wind-proof lighter,
as well as doorknobs and lamps and the like.
</P>
<P>
   The company was founded by Stephen Gordon in Eureka, Calif., in
1980 and has spread to malls in 22 states with an off-beat product
mix that has some retail consultants calling it ``Pottery Barn for
boys.''
</P>
<P>
   Its oddball assortment of hard-to-find items like the Russian
flashlight (which runs without a battery), old-fashioned wrenches,
Patio Daddy-O grill cookbooks and various gadgets do indeed have
the male appeal to distinguish Restoration Hardware from the mass
of mall stores aiming to attract female shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   But the retailer's bread and butter _ 42 percent of its sales _
is furniture and lighting, most of it with an Americana aesthetic,
and the key buyers of those products remain women. (Face it, it is
a special kind of fellow who willingly sets out on a Saturday to
survey some ``rollerball'' shower curtain rings.)
</P>
<P>
   Expectations for the initial public offering were high, and
Restoration Hardware did not disappoint. Exciting retail IPOs have
been scarce in the last six months, and Restoration Hardware's road
shows packed in all the major institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was exceptionally impressed,'' said Bruce Bartlett, who
manages Oppenheimer's Total Return Fund. ``I try to invest in
concepts that are leveraging the baby boom, and this concept hits
it on the nose. It appeals to both genders and people in the upper
income bracket.''
</P>
<P>
   What is more, retail stocks have been hot this year. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's retail index is up 32 percent so far this year,
compared with a 13 percent rise in the S&AMP;P 500. The home
furnishings segment has traditionally been fragmented, and players
like Crate and Barrel have shown how to grab market share.
</P>
<P>
   But make no mistake: Restoration Hardware is expensive. At
Friday's closing price, the company is already trading at roughly
45 times forward earnings, compared with a 17 multiple for Pier One
or 31 for Williams-Sonoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously this company has created an aura around selling
chairs and tables and knobs,'' said Linda Killian, a portfolio
manager at Renaissance Capital Corp. in Greenwich, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Restoration Hardware is just at the beginning of its
run. The company plans to open 25 more stores this year, and
roughly the same number in 1999. A catalogue to be introduced in
September will raise the profile of the store's name. New shoppers
will more than likely be tickled by the whole notion of romancing
the Bosco sauce.
</P>
<P>
   But like its shares, Restoration Hardware's goods are not cheap.
That club chair, for instance, costs $850, and much of the store's
furniture is priced much higher than Crate and Barrel or Pottery
Barn offerings. From an investor's perspective, it may have more in
common with a luxury retailer than, say, Home Depot.
</P>
<P>
   If the economy or the American shopper's disposable income
should dip, gourmet dog biscuit mix and expensive leather chairs
are likely to be the first things consumers abandon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that the company itself has outstanding merchandising
and good management,'' said Tara Schuchmann, a managing partner of
Tara Capital Partners, a Dallas hedge fund with a retail focus.
``The biggest question for us is how long can people afford their
mortgage and still buy that cherry slate bed.''
</P>
<P>
   The company also likes to keep a lot of inventory in its stores,
which crowds out selling space, Ms. Killian noted. It could find
itself with bloated shelves at the end of a quarter.
</P>
<P>
   According to the prospectus, Restoration Hardware loses money
almost every quarter but the fourth of each year. Most retailers
depend heavily on the fourth quarter, but a furnishings store
shouldn't be as seasonal as, say, a toy store.
</P>
<P>
   Another nit: Gordon and other officers redeemed 1.3 million
common shares of common stock in May of 1997. But management still
owns 30 percent of the stock after the offering.
</P>
<P>
   If Restoration Hardware meets its goals of roughly 8 percent
annual same-store sales growth and fat 68-percent earnings
increases, investors who choose to hold the stock as long as they
would a couch from the company's stores could find themselves happy
indeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should have confidence that they can do what they want
to do,'' Ms. Killian said. ``In which case it will be an enduring,
unique concept.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
