<SLUG> BC-INVEST-SELL-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SETTING AN ALARM TO TELL YOU WHEN TO SELL A STOCK  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 21)
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: Calif., N.Y.)  (af) 
By ANNE TERGESEN  
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a world where bull markets rage, interest rates sink and the
endlessly repeated apple-pie advice is to buy and hold, more than a
few investors have trepidations about selling. It can always seem
to be too soon: The winners may have further to climb, the losers
may be just about to redeem themselves, and patience may prevent a
mistake, or having to admit one.
</P>
<P>
   But sooner or later, everybody has to, or ought to, sell. And
the way the market has been behaving lately, with the Dow diving
400 points in five days, then rebounding a bit, then dropping
another 100.14 points on Friday, the mood of many investors may be
headed for the sooner end of the spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   Is now a good time to sell? There is no certain way to tell.
Even professionals armed with sophisticated computer programs and
years of experience say that selling is more art than science.
</P>
<P>
   Still, without a disciplined approach to selling, investors risk
making the common mistake of basing decisions on emotions like
fear, pride, or greed rather than on a company's fundamentals, a
practice that can be costly.
</P>
<P>
   ``All good money managers have sell strategies,'' said Stephen
Janachowski, a founder of Brouwer &AMP; Janachowski, investment
advisers in Tiburon, Calif. ``Individual investors, if they are
going to buy and sell stocks, should, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Some money managers cut their losses when a stock falls by a
certain amount. Others single out high price-to-earnings ratios or
earnings disappointments as reasons to say goodbye. But nearly all
adopt selling criteria that force them to stick to their investment
themes.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Bruce Hutson, manager of the Marshall Equity Income
Fund, always sells a stock when its yield dips 20 percent below the
average yield for the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index _ no ifs,
ands or buts.
</P>
<P>
   With dividend-to-stock-price ratios at historic lows, parting
has become commonplace for Hutson's fund, which specializes in
undervalued large companies and aims to beat the S&AMP;P 500's yield by
at least a percentage point.
</P>
<P>
   General Electric, Maytag, and H.F. Ahmanson are a few of the
stocks he recently excised from the portfolio because of low
yields. Hutson also sets a ``fully valued'' target price for each
stock he holds, and usually sells when a stock reaches its target.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Hutson's criteria have him selling more often than he
would like _ his fund's turnover is 60 percent _ but the results
are hard to argue with. The fund is up 17.7 percent in the last 12
months and is yielding 2.89 percent, well ahead of the S&AMP;P 500's
1.3-percent average, with less risk.
</P>
<P>
   Other money managers leave themselves some leeway to make
exceptions to selling rules. At the UAM FMA Small Company
Portfolio, for example, warning bells sound when a stock approaches
what the managers consider its full value, typically 20 percent or
more above the purchase price, said Kathryn Vorisek, vice president
of UAM.
</P>
<P>
   But if Ms. Vorisek and her colleagues decide the company's
outlook has improved since the target was set, they can be
persuaded to hold on.
</P>
<P>
   The fund did just that with Flowers Industries, a baking
company, and it was not sorry. Ms. Vorisek said a turnaround at the
company's Mrs. Smith's division, a recent cost-cutting plan, and
Flowers' growing stake in a revitalized Keebler justified
successively higher target stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   The fund finally sold in March, after Flowers' market
capitalization surpassed $1 billion, the upper limit on the fund's
small-cap holdings.
</P>
<P>
   The fund also has a ``butcher rule'' that calls for dumping
anything that falls more than 25 percent after the fund buys it,
but that too is not automatic, said Ms. Vorisek.
</P>
<P>
   On rare occasions, managers decide it signals a buying
opportunity. This flexible approach has helped the fund beat the
Russell 2000 index of small-cap stocks by eight percentage points
over the past 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Money managers say stop-loss limits like the butcher rule are
particularly useful with volatile or thinly traded stocks. Dan
Sullivan, who edits two newsletters and manages $175 million for
himself and clients that include his 93-year-old mother, is quick
to cut losses, sometimes selling one of the handful of fast-rising
momentum stocks he owns on a dip as small as 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing you want is to be in them at the wrong time,''
said Sullivan, who has made his mother a millionaire even though
her portfolio's return has lagged slightly behind the S&AMP;P 500 over
16 years.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Vorisek said a butcher rule has another advantage. It
prevents managers from getting too attached to their favorite
holdings. ``It takes all the emotion out of a sale. You admit you
probably made a mistake, sell the stock, and move on,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   An important corollary is what might be called the Satchel Paige
rule: Don't look back. Even if a selling strategy produces one or
two spectacular blunders, it is worth keeping if it has generated
good returns over the long run, professional money managers say.
</P>
<P>
   As president of the Brandywine Fund, Foster Friess focuses on
small-cap and mid-cap stocks that sell for an average of 18 times
1999 earnings, while delivering fast earnings growth of 20 percent
or more. When the fund buys a hot prospect, it generally makes room
by selling a slower grower, a strategy Friess calls ``pigs in the
trough'' because of the way hungry pigs displace satisfied ones.
</P>
<P>
   In early January, Friess' pessimism about future earnings
prospects convinced him that stocks in general were a bad bet, and
he moved three-quarters of the fund's assets into cash. His timing
was terrible, and he missed several months of double-digit gains in
the market.
</P>
<P>
   Brandywine got back into stocks in March, when 1999 earnings
estimates made them seem a better bargain, but the damage was done,
and the fund's 12-month return slumped to 2.77 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Even after an experience like that, though, Friess is unwilling
to second-guess the sell discipline that served him well for so
long.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always regret not participating in the things that are
going up, but at the same time, if you know a strategy has worked
for 30 years, you don't want to abandon it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Money managers caution against trying to trim a selling strategy
based on short-term results, and point out that transaction costs
and capital-gains taxes ought to figure in every selling decision.
Keeping a well-balanced and diversified portfolio can sometimes
mean pruning part of an overgrown holding, even if the fundamentals
do not call for a sale.
</P>
<P>
   And trying to outguess day-to-day price gyrations or bolts from
the blue like big mergers is generally just as futile when selling
as when buying.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to ask, `Does the combination of your buy and sell
strategies outperform the market?' '' said Richard Bernstein, chief
quantitative strategist at Merrill Lynch. ``Or should you just
invest in an index fund and play golf?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 2019EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980619.0353 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8093 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-SPOCK-DIET-HEALTH-2     06-19 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-SPOCK-DIET-HEALTH-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY EXPERTS QUESTION SPOCK'S DIET FOR CHILDREN
</HEADLINE>
  (Repeating for all needing.)  
(ja) 
 By JANE E. BRODY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The late Dr. Benjamin Spock, arguably the most influential
pediatrician of all time, has left children and their parents with
a surprising and rather demanding legacy: advice that they stick to
a vegetarian diet devoid of all dairy products after the age of 2.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh edition of his world-famous book, ``Baby and
Child Care,'' issued last month by Pocket Books just weeks after
his death at age 94, he recommends an approach to childhood
nutrition that many experts, including his co-author, Dr. Steven
Parker, consider too extreme and likely to result in nutritional
deficiencies unless it is very carefully planned and executed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now know that there are harmful effects of a meaty diet,''
the new book tells parents. ``Children can get plenty of protein
and iron from vegetables, beans and other plant foods that avoid
the fat and cholesterol that are in animal products.'' As for dairy
foods, Spock says, ``I no longer recommend dairy products after the
age of 2 years. Other calcium sources offer many advantages that
dairy products do not have.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the influence of the book, pediatricians and nutritionists
have reacted with concern to Spock's new recommendations to raise
children on an all-plant or vegan diet. Throughout its 52-year
history, ``Baby and Child'' Care has been the second-best selling
book next to the Bible. Overall, parents continue to rely heavily
on Spock as an authoritative guide to raising children.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. T. Berry Brazelton, pediatrician specializing in child
behavior at Boston City Hospital and a long-time admirer and friend
of Spock, called his new dietary recommendations ``absolutely
insane.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't agree with them at all,'' he said. ``A vegetarian diet
doesn't make any sense. Meat is an excellent source of the iron and
protein children need, and to take milk away from children _ I
think that's really dangerous. Milk is needed for calcium and
vitamin D.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts expressed concern about the ability of small children to
consume calories and fat to sustain normal growth on an all-plant
diet, as well as the diet's adequacy in supplying recommended
amounts of such essential nutrients as calcium, riboflavin, vitamin
D, iron and zinc and possibly even protein. They also said that
having to follow a vegetarian diet free of dairy products could
place undue social pressures on children, few of whom like to be
different from their friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raising children on an all-plant diet can be done, but it
would be like climbing Mount Everest,'' said Dr. Michael Georgiess,
professor of pediatrics and child development at the University of
Minnesota in Minneapolis. ``It would take an incredible amount of
planning and balancing of nutrients.'' Georgiess, who wrote the
chapter on vegetarian diets in the American Academy of Pediatrics
nutrition handbook, said that a strictly vegetarian diet ``involves
very significant risks. It would probably provide only about 60
percent of a small child's calorie needs and maybe the same
proportion of protein and would require supplementation with
vitamin D, calcium, iron and zinc.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Marc Jacobson, a specialist in adolescent medicine at
Schneider Children's Hospital in New Hyde Park, N.Y., said, ``If a
strict vegetarian diet is part of someone's long-term culture, the
kids grow fine, though not as big. But for those who became vegans
recently, I can't say it's dangerous but there are risks.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting with the first edition of his landmark book in 1946,
Spock always included meat and milk products as part of a child's
recommended diet. Spock's revisions of what had been his most
recent nutritional advice _ to include small amounts of lean animal
foods in children's diets _ stemmed from a switch he himself made
to an all-plant diet in 1991, following a series of illnesses that
left him weak and unable to walk unaided. His wife, Mary Morgan,
said his health rebounded after he made the dietary change. He lost
50 pounds, regained his ability to walk and became healthier
overall and more energetic, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It enabled him to revise his book before he died, which was
his most important goal,'' Ms. Morgan said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Neal Barnard, president of the Physicians for Responsible
Medicine, a Washington-based organization that advocates strict
vegetarian diets for everyone, said he had drafted the section on
nutrition in the new edition of Spock's book, but that Spock had
edited it to give it ``his personal touch.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Morgan said, ``Ben had a hand in every part of the book''
and that he was ``very committed'' to the diet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not difficult at all to get complete nutrition on a
vegan diet if it is supplemented with Vitamin D and B-12,'' Barnard
said in an interview. He said diet-related problems like obesity
and atherosclerosis begin in childhood and added, ``today's kids
are in worse health than ever before.''
</P>
<P>
   But Parker, the book's co-author and an expert in behavioral
pediatrics at Boston Medical Center, objected to the stringency of
the dietary advice and suggested that parents at least be offered
two alternatives. However, Spock rejected this idea, stating in a
letter to Parker that he wanted his book to be ``in the forefront''
of the growing awareness of the link between animal foods and
disease.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Parker said Spock felt his vegetarian diet ``improved his
quality of life and given him a new lease on life his last five
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He believed you should try to inculcate a taste for plant
foods early on and not acquire a taste for saturated fats, salt,
etc.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker said a vegetarian diet ``can be healthy for kids,'' if
parents make sure they obtain all the nutrients they need, but that
he did not believe people had to be vegetarian as children to adopt
the diet as adults.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said in an interview, ``I think the book is a terrific
book. There was no other area in which we had a disagreement.
</P>
<P>
   The book does makes some concessions to parents who do not go
the full vegetarian route. ``If you are including meats, poultry or
fish in your regular family routine, let me encourage you to
explore vegetarian meals and to serve as many meat-less meals as
possible,'' Spock advises parents.
</P>
<P>
   But the book says placing children on an all-plant diet will
their risk of developing such health problems as heart disease,
obesity, high blood pressure, diabetes and certain diet-related
cancers later in life. Several studies have shown that, in general,
vegetarians are leaner and at lower risk of such diseases. As for
dairy products, Spock wrote that some children are allergic to
cow's milk and others have trouble digesting it. He also noted that
milk protein may trigger insulin-dependent diabetes in susceptible
children.
</P>
<P>
   However, several experts questioned the need to be so extreme.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be sticking to dietary changes that have
demonstrable health benefits, like those outlined in the food
pyramid _ that's where the evidence is right now,'' said Dr.
Johanna Dwyer, nutrition expert at Tufts-New England Medical Center
in Boston who has studied the effects of vegetarian diets on growth
and development. The food pyramid, a dietary guide developed by the
U.S. Department of Agriculture, emphasizes grain-based foods,
fruits and vegetables but also includes meats, poultry, fish and
dairy products.
</P>
<P>
   Dwyer said it would be possible to provide growing children with
adequate nutrition by following Spock's recommendations, but added,
``most people would need a lot of help to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nutrition experts strongly disagreed with Spock's advice to
avoid dairy foods. The book states that ``most green leafy
vegetables and beans have a form of calcium that is absorbed as
well as or even a bit better than that in milk.'' But the experts
noted that calcium-rich vegetables contain substances like
oxalates, phytates and other fibers that interfere with calcium
absorption in the gut. (Spock also suggested calcium-fortified soy
milk and orange juice as sources of this mineral that is critical
to the proper development of bones.)
</P>
<P>
   As for diabetes, Dr. Susan S. Baker, a pediatric
gastroenterologist at the Medical University of South Carolina and
chairperson of the American Academy of Pediatrics Committee on
Nutrition, said the committee had examined the evidence for milk as
a factor in the disease and had found ``no real cause-and-effect
relationship between them'' that would justify eliminating dairy
products from children's diets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless there is a compelling reason to avoid dairy products,
they should not be deleted from a child's diet,'' Baker said. ``It
would be very difficult for a child to get adequate calcium from
vegetables in the quantities needed to support optimal bone growth.
Milk is the most concentrated source of bioavailable calcium.''
</P>
<P>
   Brazelton said the advice was ``neither parent-friendly nor
child-friendly.'' He pointed out that ``although vegetarian
families, if they are very careful and conscientious, can eat a
balanced diet, most children in their second and third year are in
such rebellion about food, it's hard to get them to eat any
vegetables. This recommendation puts pressure on parents who in
turn will put pressure on their kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Older children, too, would face added pressure, he and others
said, when forced to eat differently from their friends in social
situations. Susan Adams, a registered dietitian and nutrition
educator at the University of Washington in Seattle who has written
pamphlets with vegetarian meal plans, said, ``By restricting
children's diets so much, they can't interact normally in social
situations with other children. What's a birthday party without ice
cream? Having to be treated separately is hard on kids.''
</P>
<P>
   It can also be hard on parents, who might have to spend more
time preparing meals, including box lunches for their school-age
children. Ms. Adams said, ``Rice and pasta can be quick to fix, but
cooking beans and other vegetarian foods takes time. It's not the
way most people live today. Parents shouldn't be made to feel
guilty or that they are putting their children at risk
nutritionally because they make other choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Bonci, a dietitian in private practice in Pittsburgh,
said that parents who decide to raise their children on a
plant-based diet must make vegetarianism a family affair. Ms.
Bonci, who is herself a plant-only vegetarian, has two sons, ages 9
and 14, who are also vegetarians but who consume some dairy
products and eggs. She said, ``Children are so influenced by what
their parents are and are not eating, they will balk if their
parents don't eat what they do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
