<HEADLINE>
BC-HOUSTON CHRONICLE BUDGET 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  The Houston Chronicle is planning these stories for Saturday, June
20. For questions, contact Bill Wampler at (713) 220-6845 or 7674. 
NEW THIS CYCLE: BUSH-WILSON; PRISON-GANGS; JUVENILE-CRIME;
PHIL-COLLINS; SUNDAY ADVANCE LIST 
 
 
NATIONAL NEWS 
 
HABITAT-HOUSTON (Houston) _ Wrapup/dedication of the 1998 Jimmy
Carter Work Project. An estimated 6,000 volunteers who built 100
new homes will celebrate their achievement Friday evening at
Transco Tower's Wall of Water in Houston. Earlier in the day,
sponsors will conduct their own house dedications and presentations
with homeowners. President Carter will dedicate the houses and
present Bibles to the families at one construction site.
Developing. By MATT SCHWARTZ. 
With:  
HABITAT-FOUNDER (Houston) _ Interview with Millard Fuller, founder
of Habitat for Humanity about the future plans of the organization
after this historic project. By JOHN MAKEIG. 
 
BORDER-OVERLOAD (undated) _ The federal justice system along the
U.S.-Mexico border is experiencing record criminal caseloads, with
drug and immigration offenders clogging courts and crowding
prisons. From San Diego, Calif., to Brownsville, the surging
caseloads are the result of tougher drug and immigration laws, more
agents enforcing them and perhaps more illegal activity. The
government is also spending more money than ever to prosecute
offenders in federal court, a signal that drugs and immigration are
a nationwide priority. By THADDEUS HERRICK.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
JOBS-REPORT (Houston) _ The Houston/Harris County area is faring
slightly better than many other large urban areas in terms of
available jobs for low-skilled workers, according to a new report
from the Clinton Administration and the U.S. Conference of Mayors.
Widespread improvement apparently attributable to a general
economic rebound in the nation's cities _ however, officials warn
that challenges remain in areas of housing and education. By JULIE
MASON. &QL; 
 &QL; 
JUNETEENTH-TEXAS _ News-feature on Juneteenth, which commemorates
June 19, 1865, the Texas reading of the 1863 Emancipation
Proclamation which declared freedom for slaves. JO ANN ZUNIGA . &QL; 
 &QL; 
LATINO-EDUCATION _ Education Secretary Richard Riley kicks off the
15th annual NALEO conference with a keynote breakfast speech before
the largest national gathering of Latino politicians. After a
morning focused on the future of Latino education, the elected and
appointed officials turn to affirmative action. A keynote lunch
features state Rep. Irma Rangel, whose controversial bill allows
the top 10 percent of high school graduates automatic admission to
Texas universities, and an afternoon workshop examines lessons
learned from the November referendum that preserved the Houston's
still-threatened minority contracting goals and California's
flip-side Proposition 209. By LORI RODRIGUEZ &QL; 
 &QL; 
HOMELESS-HEAT (Houston) _ Homeless shelters do their largest
business in the winter, but these dog days of presummer have
prompted at least one shelter, the Salvation Army Harbor Light
Center in Houston, to offer refuge from the heat during the daytime
hours. By CARLOS BYARS. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
INTERNATIONAL NEWS &QL; 
 &QL; 
JAPAN-JITTERS (Tokyo) _ If Japanese leaders listen carefully, they
may hear the jets of Air Force One whisking President Clinton high
above their island nation, straight to his state visit to China.
Government and business leaders in Tokyo will wonder nervously, as
a senior Japanese diplomat put it: ``Has `Japan-bashing' turned
into 'Japan-passing?' `` Clinton's decision not to stop in Japan
going to or coming from his nine-day sojourn in China has fed
Japanese fears that the United States may be ready to dilute its
close, 50-year post-World War II relationship with the richest and
most developed nation in Asia in favor of the strategic allure of
the world's most populous country and its vast economic potential.
By CRAGG HINES.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
VENEZUELA -BASEBALL _ (GUACARA, Venezuela) _ If you grow up in the
ghetto playing stickball with bottlecaps on potholed streets, how
hard can it be to hit a pefectly stitched baseball? Or to turn a
doubleplay on a manicured Major League infield? That is one
explanation Venezuelans offer when asked why their nation has
produced so many dominating ``beisbolistas.'' Like the Dominican
Republic _ which has provided the largest number of Latin American
big leaguers _ Venezuela has become an El Dorado for pro clubs
seeking baseball prodigies. By JOHN OTIS.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
FEATURES &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
PHIL-COLLINS (Houston) _ Take a look at him now. Phil Collins, the
venerable 47-year-old pop icon, is trying to reinvent himself _ and
his music. And not everybody is happy. By ANDY SUMMA &QL; 
 &QL; 
WATER GARDENS (undated) _ Water. A welcomed, cooling thought these
hot, dry days. A water garden can lessen the wallop of three-digit
temperatures. The sight and sound of water magically calms and
cools the irritable and overheated. Egyptians and Persians got the
idea thousands of years ago, when they installed decorative pools
in their gardens. There is a water garden for every person, for
every budget. It doesn't have to be expensive, says Leo van Poppel,
Texas branch manager at Lilypons Water Gardens in Brookshire. Tips
on plants, placement and more. By KATHY HUBER. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SUNDAY ADVANCE
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NATIONAL &QL; 
 &QL; 
BUSH-WILSON (Los Angeles) _ When Ruben Barrales heard that Texas
Gov. George W. Bush was going to be in California this spring, he
hustled into action to wangle an endorsement in his race for state
controller. ``The image of George W. Bush is one of an aggressive
leader who embraces the Hispanic community and our relations with
Mexico,'' Barrales said. ``This has brought him notice and a
following in California. He is a breath of fresh air out here ...''
Left unspoken is that the Bush image contrasts sharply with
California Hispanics' view of their own governor, Pete Wilson. To
some Republicans nationally it has come down to shorthand: the
``California approach'' and the ``Texas approach.'' By CRAGG
HINES. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
PRISON-GANGS (undated) _ Two of the three men suspected of the
racially motivated slaying of James Byrd Jr. in Jasper were
believed to be affiliated with a white supremacist prison gang. In
fact, many who know suspects Bill King and Russell Brewer say they
exhibited no overt racial prejudices before they did hard time in
Texas prisons. After they got out, they were heavily tattooed and
spoke in a language sprinkled with racist epithets. The racist
gangs that thrive behind prison walls come from fear and a need for
belonging, according to prison experts. There are almost a dozen
such gangs in Texas prisons. By KATHY WALT. &QL; 
 &QL; 
JUVENILE-CRIME (Austin) _ Despite signs that a 1995 crackdown on
juvenile offenders is working, many Texans want even more stringent
sanctions for young criminals, including requirements that all
youthful offenders be sent to adult prisons when they turn 17 years
old and that all juvenile murderers be tried as adults, according
to the latest Texas Poll. By JOHN W. GONZALEZ. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MINOR-RIGHTS (undated) _ Erica was beaten constantly by her mother
as a child, and she always told herself she would be a different
mother and shower her children with love. She may never get a
chance to be a mother to her first child because of a judge's
decision last week. A family judge awarded primary custody of the
3-year-old to her grandfather and step-grandmother instead of
mother Erica. This is a feature story showing the pitfalls when
minors who sign joint custody agreements with their parents. By RON
NISSIMOV &QL; 
 &QL; 
INTERNATIONAL &QL; 
 &QL; 
FOREST-FIGHT (Eureka, Calif.) _ In the silence of the primeval
Headwaters Forest, which Houston businessman Charles Hurwitz
planned to cut, it's easy to believe the end of the clamorous
battle over this largest unprotected grove of ancient redwoods is
finally in sight. Beyond the virgin forest, however, the debate
hasn't grown much quieter in what may be its waning days. Lawmakers
are maneuvering. Press releases are flying. If the Headwaters fight
is drawing to a close, it's ending in much the same way it has
played out since 1986, when it became one of the most acrimonious
environmental issues of recent times. 3 TAKES. By BILL DAWSON &QL; 
 &QL; 
COLOMBIA-CAMPAIGN (La Dorado, Colombia) _ Although Horacio Serpa is
desperate for votes in Sunday's tight presidential runoff, he has
been operating a shoestring campaign. That's because both Serpa and
his opponent, Andres Pastrana, are haunted by the specter of the
campaign finance scandal that nearly toppled the government of
President Ernesto Samper. As a result, Serpa's rally here last week
seemed like a neighborhood pepfest with a stage that was full of
holes and a sound system that was underpowered. By JOHN OTIS.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
COLOMBIA-PRESIDENTS (Bogota, Colombia) _ When they leave the White
House, former U.S. presidents often disappear on the golf course,
make a few speeches, write memoirs. In Colombia, however,
ex-presidents often remain major powerbrokers. They have swayed
voters in this year's presidential elections by publicly endorsing
candidates and offering back-room advice. By JOHN OTIS. &QL; 
