<SLUG> BC-BIZWEEK-ART-2TAKES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WEEK IN BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 21)  
 (af)  
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARKETS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With Yen Supported, Stocks Recover &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A bystander could be forgiven for thinking the stock markets had
gone off their lithium. The Dow industrials skidded 207.01 points
on Monday, to 8,627.93, only to soar 164.17 points on Wednesday.
The blue-chip average ended the week at 8,712.87, down 122.07 from
last week. Behind the stock market's zig was the currency market's
zag. The fall reflected fears that Asia's economic crisis would
hurt profits of American companies. Then the United States and
Japan bought yen to bolster the sagging currency, and investors
stampeded back into the markets, only to have second thoughts about
the Asian situation on Friday. The yen, which had neared an
eight-year low on Monday at 146.15 yen to the dollar, recovered to
end the week at 136.10. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AUTOS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Strike Cripples GM &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   General Motors' North American operations were crippled, with
100,000 employees out of work, most of its assembly plants shut
down and nearly 100 parts factories idle. At issue in what began as
a U.A.W. strike at two key Michigan parts plants are not only
short-term job security and workplace safety disputes, but also a
larger struggle over how far G.M. will go in adopting at home the
manufacturing techniques it is introducing abroad. G.M.'s
operations in Brazil, where outside suppliers assemble many parts
for new cars before delivering them to the assembly plant, have
become the company's most profitable, efficient and flexible. The
United Automobile Workers see G.M.'s reliance on outside suppliers
as a threat. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sound, Fury and Then Silence &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After a month of contentious debate and too few votes for
passage, the Senate jettisoned a comprehensive tobacco bill meant
to discourage teen-agers from smoking. Although there appeared to
be almost no hope that it could be revived this year, leaders of
both parties vowed not to give up.
</P>
<P>
   Speaker Newt Gingrich said he would put forward a low-budget
alternative to the Senate bill, to discourage teen-agers from
smoking. President Clinton said: ``It's not dead over the long run
because the public health need is great. I've never quit on
anything this important in my life, and I don't intend to stop
now.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WALL STREET &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Goldman Goes Public &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clearly the tradition that Wall Street holds most dear is
profit. So little wonder that Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., the Street's
last big private investment bank and by many measures its most
successful, decided to end its 130-year partnership and go public.
</P>
<P>
   The move could make Goldman a prime player in the financial
industry's rush to consolidate and allow the partners to capitalize
on the long-running bull market. Right? No, contended Jon S.
Corzine and Henry M. Paulson Jr., co-chairmen and co-chief
executives of the big investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine said, ``This is not about money or cashing out.''
Paulson added, ``We don't think that being a financial conglomerate
is the way to go.'' They did say, however, that they intended to
make some acquisitions and to expand in Europe and Japan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   THE ECONOMY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reports Are Mixed &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The American economy has continued its excellent performance,
the Federal Reserve said in its ``beige book'' survey of regional
economic conditions, citing high employment levels and stable
prices. But the Consumer Price Index rose 0.3 percent in May,
seasonally adjusted, the Labor Department said, bringing inflation
for the first five months of the year to a 1.5 percent annual rate.
</P>
<P>
   The rise, although moderate, was the largest in 17 months. The
Commerce Department reported that the trade deficit for April
expanded to a new monthly high of $14.5 billion, well above the
$13.3 billion projected by many economists, in large part because
Asia's crisis has reduced demand for goods. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSPACE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Business Frontier &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   America Online, the nation's largest cyberspace company,
e-mailed employees to say that it had discussed being acquired by
AT&AMP;T but would remain independent. ... The Walt Disney Co.
announced a complex $900 million deal to buy 43 percent of
Infoseek, a service that helps guide users to what they want on the
World Wide Web.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PEOPLE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's Tough at the Top &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Richard Branson, the British entrepreneur whose diverse Virgin
Group holdings include airlines, high-speed trains, retail stores
and soft drinks, says he wants to start a low-cost airline
tentatively called Virgin America. So far he has been blocked by
federal restrictions that prevent foreigners from controlling
domestic airlines. ... Live by the chainsaw, die by the chainsaw.
</P>
<P>
   Albert J. Dunlap never winced at the moniker ``Chain Saw Al'';
rather, he frequently boasted of the thousands he had thrown out of
work to lift a company's stock price. Add one to the list of the
downsized. A board room revolt at Sunbeam led by some of his
hand-picked directors decided the ailing company needed a new boss.
... As Barney's emerges from bankruptcy, Bob and Gene Pressman, the
grandsons of the founder, are stepping down as co-chief
executives. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MANAGED CARE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A California Failure &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After two and a half years, three chief executives and $11
million in losses, California Advantage is filing for bankruptcy.
That's the managed care company that the California Medical
Association and 7,500 of its member physicians created to take on
the state's big health maintenance organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jack C. Lewin, a family practitioner and executive vice
president of the association, said that by offering subscribers
easy access to thousands of specialists, it tended to attract those
who were the sickest and costliest to treat. California Advantage,
which said it needed 40,000 subscribers to break even, is going out
of business with about 6,000. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TAXES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Washington's Silly Season &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What better way to win favor with voters than to oppose taxes?
The House, citing the complexities and inequities in the tax code,
voted 219 to 209 to require that Congress come up with a new tax
system by Independence Day 2002 and scrap the current code by the
end of that year.
</P>
<P>
   Clint Stretch, director of tax policy for Deloitte &AMP; Touche,
said wryly that it was easy to vote that way because the members of
Congress knew the president would veto any such law, rescuing them
from their folly. ``Sun-setting'' the tax code would make financial
planning impossible for both individuals and businesses, Stretch
said, citing dilemmas over issues like whether to rent or buy a
home, whether to put money into IRAs or other retirement plans and
whether to take capital gains on stocks. And businesses would not
know whether and how to invest in new plants and equipment. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA'S FINANCIAL DISCIPLINE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Traders Work While Central Bank Supports Currency &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chinese traders worked at their computer terminals at the
Shanghai Stock Exchange on Tuesday, even as the People's Bank of
China intervened to support the yuan, which is also called the
renminbi. The finance minister warned that the Asian crisis could
destabilize China's currency, a warning that some analysts suggest
influenced a decision by Japan and America to support the yen. A
Chinese devaluation could have kicked off a new wave of Asian
devaluations, leaving the region's economies in an even more
precarious state. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
