u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOMELESS-HEAT-HNS &LR;      06-19 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMELESS-HEAT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOMELESS SEEKING RELIEF FROM TEXAS HEAT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CARLOS BYARS 
1998c. Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (HOUSTON) _ Homeless people are seeking relief from record-high
temperatures by spending the daytime hours in air-conditioned
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   In a trend that normally occurs on cold winter days, the
homeless are spending time in shelters. The Star of Hope men's
shelter at 407 LaBranch on Friday reported an increase in the
number of men visiting during the day.
</P>
<P>
   Also, in a break from normal practice, the Salvation Army Harbor
Light Center, 2407 N. Main, will be open Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The city is experiencing not only record and near-record highs
during the day but abnormally high temperatures at night. The
overnight low of 79 degrees reached early Friday morning tied the
record minimum set in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Daytime temperatures are averaging 6.4 degrees above normal in
Houston, the National Weather Service said. And the prediction is
that if current trends continue, Houston may set several records.
</P>
<P>
   The weather service said the daily average high of 94.7 degrees
makes this the third warmest June of all time. The highest average
maximum temperature is 96.3 degrees in 1980 and the previous second
warmest average daily high was 96.2 in 1902.
</P>
<P>
   The extended forecast offers little hope for relief, the NWS
said. National computer models indicate only a slight weakening of
the upper level high pressure ridge that presently dominates Gulf
Coast weather.
</P>
<P>
   So for relief, the homeless are headed for shelters.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Arthur, spokesman for Star of Hope, said the agency's
walk-in center has about 600 men each week for showers and lunch,
which is an increase of 50 percent over the those served earlier
this spring.
</P>
<P>
   The shelter is closed during the day on Sunday, but Arthur said
it could be opened if the need becomes critical.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur said that in anticipation of the additional summer load,
the center spent $5,000 upgrading the air conditioning system.
</P>
<P>
   Rolan Chambless, spokesman for Harbor Light Center, said since
there is limited day labor available on weekends and most
social-service agencies are closed, the center will open at 10:30
a.m. on Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The center will provide lunch, dinner, an outdoor physical
activity area and an indoor area to read or watch TV, he said.
Information and referrals also will be available.
</P>
<P>
   Chambless said the center usually is open during the day only to
men in its drug- and alcohol-recovery programs. This gives these
men time to do the necessary cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   The center houses about 300 men each night, he said. Over the
weekend, another 100 to 150 men are expected to use the center
during the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to see everybody take advantage of it, but we
have the guys who are going to go out to drink no matter what we
do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street from the Star of Hope, a small group of men
and a woman made the most of a patch of shade as they waited for
the center to open.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the heat, a couple slept, a man read while he kept an
eye on his drying clothes hanging on a nearby fence and the woman
shared a late lunch with pigeons.
</P>
<P>
   Willie and another man who asked not to be identifiedagreed that
their situation is not too bad. There's only a problem on Sunday,
when the Star of Hope does not open until 3 p.m. and there is no
nearby place to get water.
</P>
<P>
   Harbor Light is a mile away, they said. They can't walk that
far, Willy explained, and if they did, they would just have to walk
back because ``this is where we live.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Open Door Mission, 5803 Harrisburg, there is no special
program. ``We don't asks guests to leave the property; we don't put
them out on the street,'' a spokesman said. ``We are open 24 hours
a day.''
</P>
<P>
   And at the Caring Heart Outreach Shelter, 6205 Jensen Dr.,
director Nora Seymore said officials are prepared to give people
relief from the heat but have had few, if any, takers.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet Home for the Homeless, 4440 Bennington, also is open from
7 a.m. until 8 p.m. seven days a week, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Another traditional, if less known, resting place is the public
library. Spokesman Sheryl Berger said the downtown branch at 500
McKinney ``has four or five regular visitors, although I'm not sure
of their status. They seem to enjoy what we have to offer. They
seem to be avid readers for the most part.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
