<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8102 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-EDGAR-ART-$ADV     06-19 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-EDGAR-ART-$ADV21-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINING EDGAR, THE ONLINE GUIDE THAT CHARTS SEC FILINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (For release Sunday, June 21)  
 (bl)  
 By RICHARD KORMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you are after the important dope on a public company, set
aside the glossy annual report and the spin-doctored announcements.
The really telling stuff is often in the filings to the Securities
and Exchange Commission, where the company has to come clean or
risk a securities fraud suit, or worse.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, getting at those filings has become much easier for
investors, thanks to the SEC's Electronic Data Gathering, Analysis
and Retrieval system, known as EDGAR, which is available on the
Internet at www.sec.gov.
</P>
<P>
   But just as public education has not wiped out illiteracy, easy
access to dense, dry SEC documents does not make them easy to
decipher. To the uninitiated, EDGAR can seem an immense haystack of
boilerplate, arcana and gobbledygook, in which the valuable needles
of telling information can be especially hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ellen Bates, who teaches corporate employees to find
competitor information in SEC filings, calls annual 10K's
``quintessential overload documents.'' ``It's all there, but it's
buried,'' she said. ``It's almost too rich.'' Less well-known forms
can be even more forbidding.
</P>
<P>
   Once an investor learns how to hack through the semantic
camouflage, though, the payoff can be great. A savvy EDGAR reader
might spot questionable policies, hidden vulnerabilities and
ticking time bombs before they make news and bite unsuspecting
stockholders.
</P>
<P>
   It takes practice to become proficient at mining EDGAR. But even
the casual investor can save a great deal of time by recognizing
details, phrases and sections where the most interesting tidbits
are likely to lurk.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, it is impractical to read the filings of hundreds of
companies when first scanning for interesting businesses. Most
experts suggest developing a short list of target companies and
then reading the EDGAR filings on the list.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC filings are becoming less off-putting as the commission
gradually forces companies to write their reports in plain English.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in October, companies must submit easy-reading cover
pages, business summaries and risk factors. The greater challenge
lies in ``getting people to the document,'' says Nancy M. Smith of
the SEC
</P>
<P>
   Here are some examples of places to look in SEC filings for
signals of potential trouble or strength.
</P>
<P>
   MISMATCHED NUMBERS _ Even a cursory glance at income statements
and balance sheets in a company's 10K report can turn up curious
figures. On March 31, a report for the 1997 fiscal year by FPA
Medical Management, a medical-practice manager in San Diego, showed
accounts receivable doubling from the year before and positive
operating income in a year when cash flow was negative, signs that
something _ the accounting or the business _ may be amiss.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers in the 10K were published in time for investors to
bolt before the stock tumbled to $2 from $14. ``If you are looking
for warning signs, look for confusing, contradictory numbers and
ignore the spin from management,'' said John Ransom, an analyst for
Raymond James.
</P>
<P>
   A BULL IN THE CORNER OFFICE _ Tultex Corp., a maker of cotton
sportswear, is losing money, and its stock is way off its 52-week
high. But SEC filings show that one investor apparently hasn't
given up hope _ the company's chief executive, Charles W. Davies
Jr.
</P>
<P>
   During Tultex's decline, he has been buying blocks of the
company's stock on the open market, paying $4.50 to $5.50 a share.
Each time he did, the assistant corporate secretary filed a Form 4
that shows up in EDGAR.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT'S THAT DOING HERE? _ Companies don't always report the most
telling information in the places you would expect. The part of a
typical 10K marked ``Liquidity and Capital Resources'' is usually a
bland section demonstrating that the company has enough money to
continue operating. But in SMC Corp.'s 1996 report, something very
unusual turned up there: Capital expenditures of $11.1 million,
including a $3.8 million corporate jet _ a lot of money for a
luxury motor coach maker whose entire operating cash flow that year
was only $4.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   PAST EMPLOYMENT _ Proxy statements filed in EDGAR include
biographies of people who are up for election as directors. Judging
by Amcor Capital's proxy, Dale Paisley probably can't get a letter
of recommendation from Travelmax International, where he was chief
financial officer for 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Amcor, a real estate and agricultural company in Coachella,
Calif., discloses in its proxy that Travelmax is suing Paisley and
others for ``fraud, misappropriation of funds, breach of fiduciary
duty and unjustified enrichment.'' It goes on to say that Paisley,
a former partner at Coopers &AMP; Lybrand, denies Amcor's accusations,
which involve an alleged attempt to illegally acquire large blocks
of Amcor stock very cheaply, and believes he has been released from
liability for his conduct.
</P>
<P>
   CONFLICTS OF INTEREST _ Go straight to the phrase ``related
party transactions'' for a quick read on a company's determination
to stay free of suspicious entanglements with shareholders and
directors.
</P>
<P>
   In the 10K for 1997 filed by Sulcus Hospitality Technologies, a
software maker in Greensburg, Pa., the company notes that it leases
its main office from a trust established by Jeffrey S. Ratner, a
principal shareholder and former director. When the company says
``these leases were not the result of arms length negotiations,''
it means no disinterested party has checked to see whether the
terms are fair to both sides.
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY TIES _ In publicly traded companies where a single family
controls much of the stock, the line between shareholder and family
interest can be hard to draw.
</P>
<P>
   Zapata Corp. in Houston has been controlled by its chairman,
Malcolm Glazer, in recent years. While analysts have wondered
whether the company's strategy hangs together _ it diversified from
marine products and food service into Internet magazines and plans
to change its name to Zap _ the company's 10K filings leave no
doubt that the Glazer family does. Malcolm's sons Avram, Bryan and
Edward are directors, and Avram is chief executive; Malcolm's
daughter Darcie is employed by Zapata as an investment analyst.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OVERDUE NOTICES PILING UP _ Late filings appear with the letters
NT before the form name and can sometimes presage accounting
trouble. ThinkNew Ideas, an Internet advertising company, filed
notice of a late quarterly report May 15. When the NT-10Q appeared
May 21, it came with upward restatements of expenses for the
quarter ended March 31, 1997. Then, on May 27, the company reported
that it had dismissed its outside auditor in February.
</P>
<P>
   COURT TANGLES _ The ``Legal Proceedings'' section in SEC
documents will note problems that could drain money and distract
managers' attention, says John Bajkowski, a financial analyst with
the American Association of Individual Investors.
</P>
<P>
   Neuromedical Systems, which uses computerized scans to improve
cervical cancer tests, faces the formidable task of convincing
doctors, technicians and insurers to accept its methods.
</P>
<P>
   But lately, the Suffern, N.Y., company has been waging an
increasingly costly multifront war in the courts against two
rivals, Neopath and Cytyc. The patent infringement, business
interference and unfair competition suits probably won't have a
material financial effect, the company says in its 10K, but, as
they drag on, the company says costs during 1998 ``could be
significant.''
</P>
<P>
   CHUTZPAH _ Personality can seep through the boilerplate format
of SEC filings, and smaller companies sometimes reveal themselves
in unusual ways. Paradise Inc. in Plant City, Fla., strikes a note
of self-congratulation in its annual 10K.
</P>
<P>
   The company writes that it ``knows of no other manufacturer in
the Western Hemisphere'' that claims as big a share of the candied
fruit business.
</P>
<P>
   But self-confidence only goes so far. The report also says that
as of March, Paradise has failed to comply with new minimum
requirements for listing on Nasdaq's market for small-cap stocks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
