<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-DUNLAP-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NET JOB? DUNLAP HAS CHAIN SAW, WILL TRAVEL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 21) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass.)   (af)  
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On page 127 of the paperback version of his autobiographical
management manual, ``Mean Business,'' Albert J. Dunlap writes,
``People perform in the future the way they did in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   That is exactly why Dunlap, dismissed last week as the Sunbeam
Corp.'s chairman and chief executive, will almost certainly be
scratched off the A-list when top-tier companies seek new bosses,
recruiters and management experts say.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a decade, the former paratrooper got a lot of
mileage out of his patented modus operandi. He would parachute into
companies like Lily-Tulip or Scott Paper, cut thousands of jobs,
shut down factories and walk away, pronouncing his war on the
bloated balance sheet a success.
</P>
<P>
   But at Sunbeam, he was ignominiously tossed out after less than
two years by a board that said it had unanimously ``lost confidence
in Dunlap's leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap and his lawyer did not return calls seeking comment. But
the recruiter who placed him at Scott Paper in 1994 said the heyday
of ``Chain Saw Al'' ended with his abrupt departure from Sunbeam.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traditional board is going to be less welcoming to him,''
said the recruiter, Thomas J. Neff, the president of Spencer
Stuart, an executive search firm. ``Only in a situation that is
viewed as a mission impossible, where other candidates may not have
the stomach to take them on, will perhaps the board and Mr. Dunlap
find a match.''
</P>
<P>
   So what is Dunlap's next move likely to be? Given Sunbeam's
well-publicized financial woes _ the company has posted two
quarters of unexpected bad results and said it would miss its
numbers for the current period and full year _ the experts say his
prospects are limited, at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   If Dunlap wants to run another corporation, they say, he will
likely have to go to a smaller, low-profile public company (think
John Sculley, the one-time Apple Computer chairman and his brief
foray at Spectrum Information Technologies) or a struggling private
firm. He might be welcome overseas or could become a consultant,
advising companies on how best to trim fat. That career track,
though, would be heavy with irony: a chapter in Dunlap's book is
entitled ``Fire All the Consultants.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever he chooses to do, ``he has become a victim of the trend
he was part of leading,'' said Rakesh Khurana, an assistant
professor of human resources and strategy at the Sloan School of
Management at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, fallen executives regularly rebound. But for the
best-paid, highest-profile bosses, the expectations are that much
greater and the impatience of corporate boards that much shorter.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, John R. Walter resigned as AT&AMP;T's president last
July under pressure from the board after only nine months. Gilbert
F. Amelio lasted less than a year and a half as chief executive at
Apple Computer.
</P>
<P>
   As for Dunlap, he will be busy for some time wrangling with
Sunbeam's board over his severance. That distraction, as well as
his age _ he is 60 _ are likely to make him a harder sell,
recruiters say.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is his notoriety, cultivated with coast-to-coast book
tours, biting one-liners hurled at the business press and speeches
peppered with flattering assessments of his own talent. ``Because
some executives can't make decisions or constantly make the wrong
ones,'' he has said, ``their incompetence virtually screams out for
an Al Dunlap.''
</P>
<P>
   It was such boldness, of course, that made his downfall national
news. And now he will reap what he sowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The notoriety that he has now gotten as a result of this will
in some ways cast some kind of cloud, whether good or bad, on
whomever he goes to work for in the future,'' said John F. Johnson,
chairman of Lamalie Amrop International, an executive search firm.
``Now they've got to go in and say, `Well, we hired Al Dunlap, and
even though he didn't do well in his last role, we have confidence
he'll do well in this one.' I don't know that the Street will buy
that.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't look for Dunlap to retire to the golf course yet.
Andrew Ward, an assistant professor of management at Emory
University, who has studied the downfalls of chief executives,
said, ``I don't expect this is the last we've heard from Al
Dunlap.''
</P>
</TEXT>
