<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-U.S.-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH PREMIER, IN U.S., SPEAKS OUT ON KOSOVO CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin said Friday
that the West faced a serious quandary in the southern Serb
province of Kosovo by trying to stop the violence there without
appearing to side with the ethnic Albanians who are fighting for
independence.
</P>
<P>
   While France insists that any NATO action in or over Kosovo be
authorized by the United Nations Security Council _ an
authorization that Russia threatens to veto _ the world cannot
ignore turmoil in Kosovo that threatens a regional explosion,
Jospin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want a possible veto in the United Nations to be an
excuse to do nothing in the face of massacres,'' Jospin told
reporters Friday during his first visit to the United States as
prime minister. ``But the Russians face a dilemma, too,'' he added,
which he said he discussed with President Clinton in their Oval
Office meeting Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, it's difficult for Russia to use its veto,''
Jospin said, because the Kremlin would have to choose between the
good relations it needs with the West for its financial stability
and its older, more rhetorical solidarity with its fellow Slavs in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there is a lot of convincing we have to do,'' he said,
urging Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, ``to come to his
senses'' and stop building support for the rebels of the Kosovo
Liberation Army through his attacks on innocent civilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic's attitude is irrational,'' Jospin said. ``The
international community accepts Kosovo as part of the Yugoslav
federation, so the solution is autonomy. There is a crazy evolution
of events, and I hope Milosevic will come to his senses.''
Milosevic withdrew autonomy from the province in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Jospin, a Socialist, was elected a year ago in a major defeat
for conservative French President Jacques Chirac, who had called
early elections. But Jospin is a pragmatic sort of socialist,
arguing that socialism means social justice and not national
ownership of the means of production.
</P>
<P>
   The benefits of economic prosperity must be shared, he said
Friday, as must the pain of economic adjustment, like the
transition France is undergoing in its effort to adapt its
state-dominated economy to the demands of global competition.
</P>
<P>
   Although Chirac is ultimately responsible for France's foreign
policy, there is a sharing of power between the president and prime
minister, and Jospin has received the full treatment from the
Clinton administration. In addition to meeting with Clinton, he has
also met with Vice President Al Gore and the secretaries of state,
defense and treasury.
</P>
<P>
   Jospin, whose approval rating in France has never fallen below
50 percent, is a likely presidential candidate in 2002, and the
Clinton administration wants to get to know him better, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Jospin and Clinton together attended the opening of a new
French-U.S. business council intended to promote trade and
investment.
</P>
<P>
   In return, Jospin has been preaching a new period of global
partnership with the United States and an end to the backbiting
that marked the end of Clinton's first term. The French foreign
minister at that time, Herve de Charette, and Secretary of State
Warren Christopher rubbed each other the wrong way over issues
ranging from Africa to the Middle East.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While their successors, Hubert Vedrine and Madeleine Albright,
have had their differences _ over U.S. sanctions on Iran, for
instance, and the Iraqi crisis _ both have worked hard to emphasize
common goals. Albright goes out of her way to speak the French she
learned in a Swiss school, and Vedrine praises her at every
occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Jospin, for his part, insisted on speaking a vigorous, clear
English, and his various toasts and speeches have praised the
longstanding alliance between France and the United States and the
increasing understanding in America of European integration and
transformation.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing a clearer idea of France to the United States was one
of his prime goals, he said Friday. ``Do not be misled by
caricatures that would have you believe France to be so burdened by
its singularities and faults as to be incapable of adjusting to the
world now emerging,'' he said at the National Press Club. ``France
is in reality far removed from the gloomy picture some people
paint.''
</P>
</TEXT>
