<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW DROPS 100 TO END VOLATILE WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices fell again Friday as Wall Street closed
out a volatile week just the way it began: with waves of
large-scale selling. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shares tumbled across the board, hitting blue-chip issues the
hardest, in an extremely heavy trading session that saw the Dow
Jones industrial average drop 100.14 points, or 1.14 percent, to
close at 8,712.87. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts said Friday's selloff was a result of
trading related to ``triple witching,'' the day when options on
stocks, stock indexes and futures expire, which often creates
market havoc.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But in a week filled with more serious concerns about economic
distress in Japan _ and the possibility that such distress might
set off a deeper economic slump in Asia _ it was no surprise that
share prices slumped. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While prices were weak through much of the day, shares slid even
more on news service reports that Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin
had suggested that despite the U.S. intervention in buying the
Japanese yen earlier this week, Japan's economic recovery might be
long and difficult. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those remarks helped lift bond prices Friday, sending the yield
on the benchmark 30-year Treasury issue, which moves in the
opposite direction of the price, down to 5.66 percent from 5.70
percent a day earlier. The dollar also rallied against the yen as
optimism about Japan's recovery soured.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a tough week,'' said Alfred Goldman, a market
strategist with A.G. Edwards Inc. in St. Louis. ``The big question
is: How bad is the economic malaise in Asia?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The last few weeks have not inspired optimism. Japan confirmed a
week ago that it had fallen into a recession. And on Monday, the
the yen fell to an eight-year low against the dollar, heightening
fears that the weakening yen could undermine other Asian
currencies. That day, the Dow plummeted 207 points, or 2.3 percent,
in one of the sharpest selloffs of the year. But on Wednesday ,
when the United States joined Japan in buying yen, the Dow
rebounded 164.17 points, or 1.89 percent.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As part of the coordinated effort, the Japanese government
agreed to resolve its banking crisis, and take steps to right its
economy. But if it cannot, investors are worried that American
corporate profits could be weakened. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, U.S. markets continue to be volatile. The Dow,
which reached a record 9,211.84 in mid-April, slid as low at
8,627.93 on Monday, a drop of 7 percent from its peak.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Blue chips, however, have fared much better than smaller company
issues, which are generally flat, according to the Russell 2000
index of small company stocks, which is up just 0.3 percent.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even with the turbulence, though, both the Dow and the Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500-stock index are up more than 10 percent this year, and
so is the Nasdaq composite index, where some big technology stocks
trade. Indeed, Friday the Nasdaq stock market gained nearly 0.5
percent in one of the few signs of strength in the market. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What Wall Street is worried about is a sharp slowdown in profit
growth in the first quarter, and signs of more trouble ahead.
Asia-related earnings warnings have already come from IBM,
Hewlett-Packard, Boeing and Minnesota Mining and Manufacturing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Abby Joseph Cohen, the widely followed investment strategist at
Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., however, remains as bullish as ever,
contending that the ``supertanker'' U.S. economy is strong enough
to withstand the effects of turbulence in Asia. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone conference this week, she told investors that
``even if Asia stays extremely weak,'' the economy and the market
will remain strong, and she said the Dow could easily reach 9,300
by year's end. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
