<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA ISN'T LIKELY TO RECEIVE MORE FUNDS NOW, IMF SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The International Monetary Fund warned Russia on Friday
that it does not plan to provide the $10 billion to $15 billion in
additional assistance that the Kremlin is seeking.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Fischer, the fund's second-ranking official, said the
request, announced Thursday, was for ``a lot of money, more than
the IMF can give to one economy.'' Fischer spoke at a news
conference in Sao Paulo, where he is attending a seminar on
Brazil's economy.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer is to arrive in Moscow for new talks early next week.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials say they need the extra money to reassure
investors, prevent the devaluation of the ruble and stabilize the
financial markets. Many Western investors also agree the money is
needed, but the IMF has been more skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer's comments do not necessarily mean that other sources of
help will not be found, but no nations have announced any intention
to provide extra help. They might do so, however, if the IMF agreed
to provide more assistance and Russia's economy continued to
deteriorate.
</P>
<P>
   In South Korea, the IMF provided $21 billion in aid; other
international groups and nations provided the rest of a $57 billion
package.
</P>
<P>
   Government released data Friday that indicated 1998 is likely to
be a year of economic stagnation for Russia, or even gradual
decline: The gross domestic product dropped two-tenths of 1 percent
in the first six months of the year, from the corresponding period
last year, the State Committee on Statistics reported.
</P>
<P>
   Russia suffers two ills: high interest rates and low prices for
its oil.
</P>
<P>
   The government has been forced to ratchet up the interest it
pays on treasury bills to attract nervous foreign investors. But
that has also vastly raised the cost of borrowing and choked off
investment and economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   The worldwide decline in oil prices has hurt the profitability
of the producing companies and made them even more reluctant to pay
taxes.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Despite Fischer's comments, Russia is pinning much of its hopes
on securing billions more from the IMF. Before Russia can do so,
however, it has to remove some of the roadblocks that held up the
disbursement of an earlier $10 billion loan.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF has deferred the latest $670 disbursement from this
loan, saying the government has not met all the conditions. Russian
officials said Friday that there are two main problems:
</P>
<P>
   _ A demand that Russia deny access to its oil pipelines to
companies that have not paid their taxes. The government has been
working out a plan that calls on Russia's 13 oil companies to pay
their taxes for June and then pay their arrears over the next three
months.
</P>
<P>
   _ The government's pledge that it will clamp down on the 20
biggest tax delinquents and speedily collect about $808 million in
back taxes. A Kremlin aide said that it would be difficult to meet
this goal and that the government hopes a compromise can be struck
with the IMF
</P>
<P>
   Friday, President Boris Yeltsin struggled to reassure the public
that the country would find a way out of its financial jam,
including the worsening problem of unpaid wages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are hanging on'' he said during a visit to Kostroma, 200
miles northeast of Moscow. ``But you know, we lack rubles, and
that's where the delays come from.''
</P>
</TEXT>
