<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOBS-REPORT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTLOOK FOR LOW-SKILLED JOB SEEKERS IN TEXAS IS GOOD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JULIE MASON 
1998c. Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (HOUSTON) _ The outlook for low-skilled job seekers in Houston
is good compared with many other urban areas, and typifies an
economic rebound among the nation's cities.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 38,691 Houston job-seekers with limited skills will
compete over the next few years for 33,030 jobs _ a gap of 5,661 or
about 1.2 potential applicants for each job, according to a report
released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A survey by the U.S. Conference of Mayors measured the number of
low-skilled workers in 74 cities against the projected job growth
in related occupations through 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Although the report did not rank the 74 cities, Houston compares
favorably with other large urban centers and the national average.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, for example, the gap for low-skilled job seekers is
projected to be 6.4 for every job available over the next five
years. In Detroit, an estimated 23 workers will compete for each
job requiring limited skills.
</P>
<P>
   The results for Texas cities were varied, with Dallas projected
to have 1.7 low-skilled job seekers for every job, while Fort Worth
is projected to have more jobs than workers to fill them on the low
end of the employment scale.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the forecast indicates there could be 1.9
low-skilled workers for every one job available to them through
2003.
</P>
<P>
   Low-skill workers are defined as those having less than a high
school education, and are employed in areas such as food service
and manual labor.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Craig, professor of economics at the University of
Houston, said three specific employment categories help Houston's
overall rating.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of manufacturing here, and while you might
think of that as high-skilled labor, the bottom rung in
manufacturing really isn't,'' Craig said. ``Clearly, we also have a
lot of construction going on, and third, like all large cities, we
have a big service economy.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Craig noted, the lack of stringent business
regulation in Houston also favors low-skill workers _ in areas such
as daycare, for example.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our service sector of the economy is relatively unregulated.
We assume people know how to take care of themselves,'' Craig said.
``That creates a lot of employment opportunities that some other
cities regulate out of existence.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Conference of Mayor's survey coincided with a State of
the Cities report issued by the Department of Housing and Urban
Development, where officials also took note of the generally
positive employment outlook in the nation's cities.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, entry level job creation grew by 34
percent in cities nationwide during the past year. In last year's
State of the Cities report, cities captured just 13 percent of
entry-level job growth.
</P>
<P>
   Officials attributed the increase to favorable employment trends
and a rebound in traditional urban economies creating jobs for
people coming off welfare and others with limited professional
skills.
</P>
<P>
   But Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo and others cautioned that
challenges remain for cities in the areas of housing and education.
</P>
<P>
   On providing enough jobs for low-skilled workers, a senior
housing official in Washington said despite the gains of cities
such as Houston, the national forecast of two workers vying for one
job remains ``a serious issue.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
