<SLUG> BC-MARKET-WATCH-ART-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEWARE OF JAPANESE BEARING GIFTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 21)  
 (af)  
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Like a bungee jumper who finally reached the end of
his rope, the Japanese yen made a mighty bounce last week. The yen
ended the week 7 percent above the eight-year low against the
dollar it hit just days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The bounce came courtesy of the United States Treasury, which
bought billions of dollars worth of yen in currency markets on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   What did Uncle Sam get for his big investment? Promises by Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto and Finance Minister Hikaru Matsunaga to
address their nation's economic problems. Something called ``the
Total Plan'' is supposed to allow Japan's banks to escape their
problem loans without causing a nationwide depression.
</P>
<P>
   This is supposed to impress. In fact, it sounds like little more
than hot air _ about which the Japanese know plenty.
</P>
<P>
   It was Japan, after all, whose Nikkei 225 stock index rang in
1980 at 6,556 and exited the decade at 38,916, a rise of nearly
sixfold. Yet even when the market was at its dizziest, high-level
officials at Japanese banks angrily denied that the Nikkei might be
a hot-air balloon. Punctured, the Nikkei now stands at 15,268, down
61 percent from its 1989 peak.
</P>
<P>
   Robert E. Rubin, the United States Treasury secretary, may
believe that the Japanese promises are substantive enough to
deserve a big-buck intervention. He may also think that the
measures needed to revive the country's comatose economy will be
taken. But others say the intervention was folly and that the yen
will once again descend.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to prop up the yen was a tactical error on the Treasury's
part, argues Andrew Smithers, president of the economic consulting
firm Smithers &AMP; Co. in London, because Japan's bureaucracy has
historically been antimarket.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Japanese believe markets are there not to tell you bad
news, but to be manipulated so that you can alter the real world,''
Smithers said. By intervening, he contends, the Treasury has given
financial support to the antimarket elements within Japan's
bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, while dealing with bad bank loans is laudable, that
alone is not enough. Japan needs to raise its falling exports, a
strategy of which Japanese officials make no mention. In real, not
nominal terms, Japan's current account surplus fell from 3.76
percent of gross domestic product last December to 3.27 percent in
the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Because 45 percent of Japan's exports last year went to
now-decimated Asian countries, Tokyo must look elsewhere to sell
its goods. To compete in key markets like the United States and
Germany, however, the yen will have to fall, not rise, against the
dollar and the mark. Bolstering the yen just makes Japan's exports
more difficult to push.
</P>
<P>
   While world markets react warmly to Japanese promises, it's
worth remembering that these folks have been known to pledge one
thing and deliver another. Just last November, rumors swirled that
Yamaichi International, Japan's fourth-largest brokerage firm, was
near bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the firm's top-ranking executives came from Japan to meet
with officials at the Federal Reserve Bank of New York and the New
York Stock Exchange. The executives assured the regulators that
Yamaichi, which had an American subsidiary, was solvent, and they
reiterated their commitment to the American markets.
</P>
<P>
   Not 10 days later, the firm petitioned Japan's Ministry of
Finance for permission to cease operations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 2031EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
