A8122 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEME-PARKS-RIDES-ART     06-19 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEME-PARKS-RIDES-ART-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
5 ATTRACTIONS FOR SUMMER JOY RIDING  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 21) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa., Calif., Mo., Fla., N.J.)   (af)  
  
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Summertime blockbusters are not confined to movie theaters. To
entice repeat visits, amusement parks spend millions of dollars on
new thrill rides.
</P>
<P>
   This year, according to Amusement Business, which tracks the $8
billion industry, is a record one for roller coaster construction,
with nearly 80 being built worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The construction, said Tim O'Brien, an editor at the magazine
who focuses on theme parks, ``connotes a very positive attitude.
These parks are going forward knowing that the business is going to
be there.'' O'Brien cited five of the hottest new rides and
attractions. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE GREAT BEAR
</P>
<P>
   In Hershey, Pa., the state's first steel inverted roller coaster
is causing a frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   ``People tend to scream as soon as they sit down. We don't even
have them buckled in yet,'' said Becca Combs, a ride operator at
the Great Bear, Hersheypark's newest attraction. The wait averages
an hour or more for a ride that lasts 175 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Suspended from the track in overgrown car seats with their feet
dangling, riders are propelled into space at 58 miles an hour, as
if on a ski-lift gone berserk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enjoy your 124-foot drop,'' a recording intones. There's also
a 100-foot loop and a few barrel rolls.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, the effect is smooth, with no abrupt jolts or head
bumps. Many emerge weak-kneed, though, and with a new-found sense
of religion. ``I think I'm going to faint,'' said Lorie Sands, 41,
of Bloomsburg, Pa., who took her 15-year-old daughter on the ride. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Megan O'Matz &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RIDDLER'S REVENGE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To ride the loops and spirals of the Riddler's Revenge coaster
at Six Flags Magic Mountain, in Valencia, Calif., 40 miles north of
downtown Los Angeles, is to appreciate more sedate modes of
transportation _ like Southern California freeways.
</P>
<P>
   Tailgaters and kamikaze drivers seem harmless after you've been
tossed side to side and floated weightless during plunges on what
is billed as the world's tallest and fastest stand-up roller
coaster.
</P>
<P>
   The thrill ride begins with a 16-story incline, with spectacular
views of farmland. By the time the cars reach the crest, thoughts
shift to self-preservation: riders grip handholds, press against
backrests and plant feet to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The next two-and-a-half minutes are spent alternately lurching
along precipitous straightaways at 65 miles an hour, spinning in
corkscrews and gazing at the ground from the top of two loops.
</P>
<P>
   If a coaster is judged by headaches, lightheadedness and nausea,
then Riddler is a success. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Verne G. Kopytoff &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MAMBA
</P>
<P>
   Cori Longfellow and Jenny Miller tried the Mamba roller coaster
at the Worlds of Fun park in Kansas City, Mo., ``so we could say we
did it.'' But the nearly three-minute, 75-mile-an-hour ride has
made them fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great,'' said Ms. Longfellow, 27, a teacher from Fort
Riley, Kan. ``It takes so long to go up the first hill and then you
go down so fast you can't even scream.''
</P>
<P>
   For almost a minute, the coaster's car travels up, giving riders
the time to close their eyes, lift their arms and question their
sanity. After an agonizing pause, it plummets 205 feet before
climbing a second 184-foot hill.
</P>
<P>
   The second drop is followed by a 580-degree rotation _ more than
1{ full spins _ at 60 miles an hour, then five ``camel-back bumps''
to give riders ``air time,'' a sensation of negative gravity force.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a rush,'' Missie Brittain, 18, of Kansas City, said.
``You even forget to breathe.''
</P>
<P>
   Jilian Mincer &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JOURNEY TO ATLANTIS
</P>
<P>
   At Sea World in Orlando, Fla., a combined roller coaster and
water ride called Journey to Atlantis is an effort to recast the
park as something more than dolphin shows.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantis is a pink palace 10 stories tall. As visitors await
their turn _ a 35-minute wait on a recent weekend _ they learn from
mock TV broadcasts that Atlantis has risen in the harbor of a Greek
fishing village. And the lost city is not only beautiful but also
inhabited by Allura, an evil spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Eight at a time, riders hop into roller cars done up as fishing
boats. The experience starts as a serene ride on a river past
scenes of village life, then shifts tempo as Allura takes control.
The plot line, however, is superfluous. What counts is the sheer
thrill of the attraction's final two minutes, when the real roller
coaster and water ride begins.
</P>
<P>
   The first 60-foot drop into the outside world is anticipated but
delightfully stomach-wrenching and soaking. It is followed by a
steep climb back into a candlelit cave.
</P>
<P>
   A second 60-foot plunge comes as a surprise, as the ``boat''
begins to fall in the dark. The ride ends with a flourish of fast
curves and splashes. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BATMAN &AMP; ROBIN: THE CHILLER
</P>
<P>
   From a distance, Batman &AMP; Robin: The Chiller, at Six Flags Great
Adventure in Jackson, N.J., doesn't look like a big deal. Though 20
stories tall, The Chiller is dwarfed by The Great American Scream
Machine, whose white scaffolding dominates the park's skyline, and
lacks the ominous bulk of Batman: The Ride.
</P>
<P>
   Be prepared. The Chiller catapults riders to 70 miles an hour in
less than four seconds before shooting them 200 feet in the air
through a set of rolls and turns. The seven-ton trains are then
rocketed back to the gate in reverse, propelled by an
electromagnetic field.
</P>
<P>
   The Chiller is actually two rides. The icy blue Batman track
features four inversions; the Robin track, bright red, has six
rolls, to reflect the sidekick's youthful vigor. Each ride is 45
seconds long. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kirsty Sucato
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 2032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
