<SLUG> BC-JUNETEETH-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXANS COMMEMORATE JUNETEENTH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JO ANN ZUNIGA 
1998c. Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texans commemorated Juneteenth on Friday, marking the end of
slavery in the state with celebrations and educating children on
``healing spirits.''
</P>
<P>
   The largest event in Houston remained the Juneteenth Freedom
Festival at Miller Outdoor Theater where a choir, bands and
barbecue attracted thousands despite high temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   John Gorey, Miller's general manager, said the annual event
draws about 20,000. For the 25th year in a row, the National
Emancipation Association sponsored the event to commemorate June
19, 1865, when Union Gen. Gordon Granger read the Emancipation
Proclamation in Galveston.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time blacks in Texas officially learned they
were citizens and not slaves, although President Lincoln signed the
Emancipation Proclamation on Jan. 1, 1863.
</P>
<P>
   News that the nation's slaves had been freed had reached the
Gulf Coast before 1865, but it was not until Granger's arrival that
Union soldiers were there to enforce it, according to Patricia
Prather, a local historian.
</P>
<P>
   ``General Sam Houston read an account of the proclamation in a
newspaper in 1862 even before President Lincoln signed it and
announced it to his slaves, freeing them,'' Prather said.
</P>
<P>
   Prather, who co-authored ``From Slave to Statesman: Legacy of
Joshua Houston, servant to Sam Houston,'' wrote an account of
Houston, in his Sunday best, making the announcement as both sides
broke down in tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they could not leave until the Union soldiers or the
Freedmen's Bureau came or they (freed slaves) would have been shot
down like dogs (by Confederacy supporters),'' Prather said.
</P>
<P>
   With the recent event of the Jasper killing of a black man by
three white men linked to white supremacy groups, Prather said
further education is still needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much has been suppressed about man's inhumanity to man. But if
we don't tell our children the truth, it's a disservice,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Julia C. Hester House in the Fifth Ward held a Juneteenth
celebration that included ``honoring of ancestors and elders and
healing spirits,'' an African tradition.
</P>
<P>
   The community center's senior citizens and and children from its
daycare and surrounding neighbors joined in the commemoration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are recognizing the need for healing spirits as we recall
freedom from slavery and knowing what people went through before
us,'' said Sherri Clausell, the center's job developer.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony opened with a drum call and a senior adult and a
young child led the readings.
</P>
<P>
   ``A big part of the celebration is education. It did not take
Texas two years to find out about the proclamation,'' Clausell
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds dramatic. But the real deal was that it couldn't
happen until the Union came down with its troops to provide
protection.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 2034EDT &QL; 
