<HEADER>
A8135 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Fire-CRACKER-COX     06-19 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Fire-CRACKER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fireworks sale lights Florida officials fire
 &HT;    By Mary Lou Pickel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. -- With the county as dry as a tinder box
and north Florida up in smoke, Palm Beach County fire officials are
warily eyeing the start of the state's 16-day roadside fireworks
sale season, which starts today.
</P>
<P>
   Residents should realize that setting off fireworks is illegal
and could start a blaze, Palm Beach County Fire Marshall Jim Sweat
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just a spark away from being another Flagler County,''
Sweat said, referring to the wildfires that have ravaged northern
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach County firefighters have fought 52 brush fires in the
last two weeks, up from last year's average of 31, fire officials
said. Sweat has banned open burns in the county during the past two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   And Jacksonville's mayor has banned all fireworks, saying the
risk is too great.
</P>
<P>
   Places such as The Acreage, the Palm Beach Ranchettes and other
areas close to undeveloped lands worry Sweat most because they
could burn if a forest fire heads east.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from caution and common sense, a new county rule seeks to
increase safety by clamping down on who buys and sells fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new rules:
</P>
<P>
   __ Customers must fill out a notarized affidavit swearing the
fireworks are for legal reasons, which include: quarrying, military
uses, shooting cap guns at sporting events, scaring birds from a
farm or fish hatchery and making signals at a railroad crossing.
</P>
<P>
   __ Vendors must post a $5,000 bond per site, up to a maximum of
$20,000 total, to cover any fines and costs of prosecution. The
county will return the money after the season ends on July 5 if the
vendor has obeyed the law.
</P>
<P>
   __ Vendors also must get a permit that shows they've been
inspected by the fire marshal, are registered with the state and
only sell permitted goods.
</P>
<P>
   Penalities for customers and vendors who break the rules are a
$500 fine and 60 days in jail or both.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff's deputies will patrol the 40-odd tents and two
wholesale fireworks stores in the county, looking for lawbreakers,
sheriff's Capt. Ed Bieluch said. It's illegal for most people to
buy firecrackers, county attorneys said, but that hasn't stopped
vendors from selling them.
</P>
<P>
   Tent vendors never have been allowed to sell fireworks _ things
that explode in the air such as Roman candles, torpedoes or bottle
rockets _ county attorneys said. Tents are only supposed to sell
sparklers.
</P>
<P>
   Stores can sell firecrackers because they have better fire
safety equipment and climate control, Chief Assistant County
Attorney Andrew McMahon said.
</P>
<P>
   Sweat expects some problems with the rules because only a
handful of vendors have applied for permits so far.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, officials didn't expect that 84 stores such as Wal-Mart
and Sam's Club also would have to fill out permits. Sweat's office
sent packages to those stores last week. ``I haven't been off the
phone since then,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sweat says he may have to give a little leeway to those who are
trying to comply because the rules are so new. But he plans to
pursue those who make no effort.
</P>
<P>
   Fireworks vendor John Hunnewell, president of Loxahatchee-based
Paradise Farms, said he doesn't plan to follow the rules and has
sued the county, instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pathetic, every year you gotta file a new lawsuit because
they can't interpret a state statute correctly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hunnewell said he plans to open three fireworks tents this year.
The average tent owner makes about $4,000 the week before the
Fourth of July, he said, but sales can reach as much as $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Phantom Fireworks manager Ira Schwartz said he has done
everything to comply with the law, including hiring notaries public
to notarize the affidavits that customers must sign, and adding a
copying machine to keep the records, as the rules require.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're running a safe place and we're going to follow this law
and we feel everyone else should too,'' Schwartz said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
