</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No green light: Talks between GM and UAW at a stand still
 &HT;    By Mike Wagner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio -- General Motors Corp. and the United Auto Workers
headed into the weekend with no signs of resolving two parts-plant
strikes that have wiped out 90 percent of the automaker's
production and idled one-third of GM's Miami Valley work force.
</P>
<P>
   The strikes that began June 5 and 11 in Flint, Mich., have shut
down 23 of GM's 30 North American assembly plants and idled about
6,200 workers in the Dayton area at five local plants. Parts
shortages from the strikes have led to the layoff of about 110,000
workers, or about one third of GM's North American work force. More
GM suppliers also furloughed employees and closed factories Friday.
</P>
<P>
   As the impact widened, President Clinton urged the union and the
world's largest automaker to settle their disputes. GM Chief
Executive John F. Smith Jr. said the company wants a quick
resolution but it has to keep GM competitive. So far, neither side
seems willing to compromise as GM pushes to cut costs and the union
digs in to save jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're having some dialogue but we're hearing the same
rhetoric,'' said Duane Zuckschwerdt, president of UAW Local 659,
which represents 5,800 workers on strike at a Flint metal-stamping
plant.
</P>
<P>
   With GM headed for a regular two-week shutdown on June 29, the
strike probably will last into at least mid-July, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, the strikes caused about 1,400 more GM workers to be
laid off on Friday, including 1,200 more GM's Kettering suspension
parts plant.
</P>
<P>
   So far, more than 6,000 Dayton-area GM workers have been idled
by the Flint walkouts. Those layoffs include 3,900 at the Moraine
truck assembly plant; 1,250 at the Kettering plant; 526 at two
Dayton brake plants; 247 at GM's Vandalia air bag plant; and 115 at
the Delphi Chassis plant on Home Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The walkouts at GM's Flint Metal Center and an instrument panel
and engine-parts plant are costing the company an estimated $60
million a day in pretax profits. The halt to GM's production has
trimmed 0.3 percentage points off the U.S. economy's second-quarter
growth rate, according to First Chicago NBD economist Diane Swonk.
</P>
<P>
   GM shares fell 2 1/16 to 67 1/2. The stock has slipped 11
percent from the day before the first strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are getting increasingly nervous about the ultimate
impact of the strikes,'' said James Drury, fixed income analyst at
Bear Stearns.
</P>
<P>
   GM's 8,000 U.S. dealers, meanwhile, are bracing for vehicle
shortages that may last through the summer.
</P>
<P>
   GM's virtual halt to the production of light trucks, among its
most profitable vehicles, poses an especially big problem as it
comes in the middle of the peak selling season, according to
several GM dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said in a commencement address at Flint's Kettering
University, the former General Motors Institute, that GM is
``committed to reaching a settlement as quickly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added that the company must have an agreement that allows
it to meeting the demands ``of this changing marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the Friday, the only major GM assembly plants
operating were the Saturn car factory in Spring Hill, Tennessee, a
small-car plant in Ramos Arizpe, Mexico, and sports car factory in
Ste. Therese, Quebec.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg Business News contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The DAYTON NEWSPAPERS INC., DAYTON, OHIO
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-06-19-98 1905E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
