<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8140 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-JITTERS-HNS &LR;      06-19 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-JITTERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN QUIETLY NERVOUS AT CLINTON PASS-BY DURING CHINA TRIP 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
1998c. Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ If Japanese leaders listen carefully Thursday afternoon,
they may hear the jets of Air Force One whisking President Clinton
high above their island nation, straight to his state visit in
China.
</P>
<P>
   Government and business leaders in Tokyo will wonder nervously,
as a senior Japanese diplomat put it: ``Has `Japan-bashing' turned
into 'Japan-passing?' ``
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's decision not to stop here going to or coming from his
nine-day sojourn in China has fed fears that the United States may
be ready to dilute its close, 50-year post-World War II
relationship with the richest and most developed nation in Asia in
favor of the strategic allure of the world's most populous country
and its vast economic potential.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration brushes aside any Japanese concern,
pointing to the plan to send Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
to Tokyo from China for consultations and the state visit of
Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto to Washington next month.
</P>
<P>
   A Western diplomat, however, called the Hashimoto trip a
``consolation prize'' arranged after it became evident that the
Japanese government privately was irked at Clinton stiffing Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Japan has lodged no official complaint, but as another Western
diplomat explained: ``There's nothing they can do about Clinton's
schedule, and they do not want to lose face by complaining
publicly.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the days of President Nixon's dramatic overture to China
in the early 1970s, which the Japanese did not learn about until
moments before the public announcement, there has been concern that
Tokyo might again be left in the dark on U.S.-China relations.
</P>
<P>
   Now, some top Japanese foreign policy analysts believe the
Clinton administration has decided that China, more than Japan, is
the key to preserving both economic and political stability in the
Far East.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of thinking certainly exists in the U.S. government
and with a good deal of influence,'' said Takashi Inoguchi, an
Asian affairs specialist at Tokyo University. He said, however, he
was not convinced it was the governing thought at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's man in Tokyo, Ambassador Tom Foley, the former House
speaker, has spoken out strongly against the view.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not true. Not true,'' said Foley when questioned at a public
speech in Tokyo last month. ``Let me make the statement again as
strongly as I can.
</P>
<P>
   Japan in the 21st century will remain our close partner and ally
above all other countries in the region, and not China or any other
country.''
</P>
<P>
   On the record, Japan is taking the Clinton visit to China
stoically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Improvement of U.S.-China relations would be helpful and
beneficial to peace and stability of the whole world, as well as
the Asian-Pacific region,'' said Shigekazu Sato, director of China
and Mongolian affairs at the Japanese Ministry of Foreign Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   But privately, it's another matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nine days!'' exclaimed a Japanese government official. ``How
can he afford to spend so much time? It's like a vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   That view does not surprise some experienced Asia analysts in
the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Japanese like to be victims,'' said Bruce Stokes,
Washington-based senior fellow with the Council on Foreign
Relations. ``They can say, (the United States and China) are
ganging up on us; this is our worst fear.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has visited Japan twice during his five-plus years in
office, and a White House official contended that the president's
trip to China was of historic significance because it will be the
first by a U.S. head of state to China since the pro-democracy
demonstrators were killed by Chinese army troops in Tiananmen
Square nine years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of a Clinton visit was complicated by former President
Carter, who during a visit to Tokyo in March said he expected
Clinton to stop in the Japanese capital on the way home from China.
A U.S. diplomatic source contended Carter voiced an assumption
without having spoken to the administration about the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese leaders are further galled that Clinton's ``no side
trips'' itinerary seems to have been dictated by the Chinese
government.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese officials had expressed a desire that Clinton's visit be
seen as precisely equal to their president's trip to the United
States last year, on which Jiang Zemin did not visit another
country. But China is also never sorry to see a little friction
between Washington and Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   A Japanese diplomat said that not only do Beijing and Tokyo have
ongoing differences _ including broad nuclear nonproliferation
questions as well as territorial disputes about islands in the East
China Sea _ but that the relationship remains ``under a shadow''
since Japan's occupation of much of China in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Also in dispute is Japan's request for a permanent seat on the
U.N. Security Council, a body on which China _ one of the five
full-time, veto-wielding members _ is not anxous to see another
Asian nation.
</P>
<P>
   Stokes noted that Clinton's bypassing Japan on the upcoming
Asian trip is part of a ``convoluted'' situation, especially in
light of the current Asian economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton were to stop, it would be incumbent on him to
publicly urge Hashimoto's government to take additional steps to
reinvigorate Japan's economy _ now judged by most international
analysts to be in recession for the first time in almost 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's gross domestic product, which accounts for more than
half of Asia's GDP, shrank at an annual rate of 5.3 percent in the
quarter ending in March _ the second consecutive quarter of
contraction.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and Japanese central bankers took the unusual step of
intervening in the currency exchange markets last week to bolster
the sliding yen.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese will be watching closely for any attempt by the
Chinese to rope Clinton into badmouthing Tokyo's recent economic
efforts, either in a joint statement or by a Chinese leader making
a public comment that it might be difficult for Clinton to
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Such an occurrence would be ``perceived as a poke in the eye to
Tokyo,'' Stokes said.
</P>
<P>
   Inoguchi said there ``some concern that Clinton might be drawn
into the Chinese stragem,'' and that ``if the two countries start
singing a song that is anti-Japan, it will not be welcome.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
