<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8149 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-WILSON-2TAKES-$A     06-19 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-WILSON-2TAKES-$ADV21-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 21) 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
1998c. Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When Ruben Barrales heard that Texas Gov. George
W. Bush was going to be in California this spring, he hustled into
action to wangle an endorsement in his race for state controller.
</P>
<P>
   ``The image of George W. Bush is one of an aggressive leader who
embraces the Hispanic community and our relations with Mexico,''
Barrales said. ``This has brought him notice and a following in
California. He is a breath of fresh air out here . . .''
</P>
<P>
   What about the Golden State's own Republican governor, Pete
Wilson? The usually talkative Barrales, a San Mateo County
supervisor, demurred.
</P>
<P>
   His silence points to a growing view that in all things
Hispanic, Bush has become a touchstone for Republicans while Wilson
has become anathema. To some Republicans nationally it has come
down to shorthand: the ``California approach'' and the ``Texas
approach.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear there are people eagerly pushing that,'' said
Wilson, who has chafed quietly at the comparisons with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The Wilson camp believes the criticism in Republican circles is
being fueled by Bush supporters and driven by competition for the
party's presidential nomination in 2000 _ which both Wilson and
Bush may seek.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are actively promulgating the thesis that George Bush is
good for the Republican Party because he will attract Hispanics and
Pete Wilson is bad because he is anti-immigrant,'' said a senior
figure in the Wilson organization.
</P>
<P>
   The divergent opinions were accentuated in a recent poll by
Univision, a major Spanish-language television channel. Hispanic
residents in Texas gave Bush an 81 percent favorable rating;
Hispanic residents in California gave Wilson a 26 percent favorable
rating.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking two different points on the spectrum'' said
Harry Pachon, a political scientist at Claremont Graduate
University and president of the Toms Rivera Policy Institute.
``Wilson is seen as the Antichrist.''
</P>
<P>
   That view is due in large part to the passage, with Wilson's
leadership or support, over the last four years of three
voter-initiated measures in California that many Hispanics see as
anti-immigrant, although Wilson strongly denies such an intent.
Bush has criticized all three measures.
</P>
<P>
   The first, and for Hispanics most searing, was Proposition 187
in 1994, which sought to deny almost all state services, including
education and all but emergency medical treatment, to illegal
immigrants. The measure passed overwhelmingly, but a U.S. district
judge has ruled it unconstitutional, a finding which is being
appealed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, voters approved Proposition 209, which dismantled the
state's affirmative action program. And on June 2, voters supported
Proposition 227, a measure all but abolishing the state's bilingual
education program.
</P>
<P>
   By this spring, Wilson had become such a politically polarizing
figure that the main sponsor of Prop. 227 disavowed the governor's
support of the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson is most closely identified with Prop. 187, which
coincided with his re-election campaign _ a stunning
come-from-behind victory that focused on his efforts to stem
illegal immigration. The campaign's keystone television commercial
featured grainy footage of illegals scurrying between cars at the
border as an announcer boomed: ``They keep coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some Wilson aides now see that line as failing to draw
enough distinction between legal and illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put the bullet in the opposition's gun,'' said one Wilson
adviser. ``We were outfoxed, out-PR'ed, outspun by a minority of
loud voices.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush has spoken out against illegal immigration and the
financial burden it places on states such as Texas and California,
his rhetoric has been less sharp-edged than Wilson's. The Texas
governor described Propositions 187 and 209 as ``divisive.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texan has also criticized various ``English only'' proposals
as an affront to Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``To stand up and say `English only' basically says to a lot of
Hispanic people: `You don't count.' I think they do count,'' Bush
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Wilson each said in interviews that they had never
talked to one another about their differing approaches. Both said
they believed it stemmed from historic and cultural differences in
California and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexican-Americans have been an integral part of the economy
and the social fabric of our state since 1846,'' Bush said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 2048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980619.0385 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8151 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-WILSON-2NDTAKE$A     06-19 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-WILSON-2NDTAKE$ADV21-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(BUSH-WILSON-2NDTAKE-$ADV21) 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  .... the social fabric of our state since 1846,'' Bush said. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although there are many old ``Californios,'' families who have
been on the West Coast since the days of the Mexican empire, many
more in Texas ``have been there for generations,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's tack has drawn support from some Hispanic leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously it's a superior approach,'' said Henry Cisneros, the
former San Antonio mayor who was housing secretary in the Clinton
administration before becoming president of Los Angeles-based
Univision.
</P>
<P>
   ``California Republicans have gone out of their way to alienate
the Latino community over the years,'' Cisneros said. ``And I think
it's in part a Pete Wilson legacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as Wilson was winning re-election two years ago, he
suffered a Latino backlash. Where he had gotten more than 40
percent of the Hispanic vote in 1990, it dropped to about 25
percent in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson aides point out that is the same approximate quarter of
the Hispanic vote that ``the sainted Bush,'' as one referred to the
Texas governor, got in defeating Democratic incumbent Ann Richards
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polling indicates that Bush could get as much as 50
percent of the Hispanic vote in the fall election, although
Republican share of Latino vote is sometimes smaller on Election
Day than in polls during the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In California, the virus spread from Wilson to the Republican
Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, they tried to demonize me, and then to engage in a sort
of guilt by association against Republicans,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   An analysis for Republicans in the California Assembly showed
that in the 1996 election cycle, the GOP suffered its ``worst
registration performance in six decades.''
</P>
<P>
   Without commenting directly on Wilson, Barrales, son of
immigrants who came to the United States from Mexico in the 1950s,
said: ``There is a lot of room for growth. The Republican Party has
lost a lot of good will _ unnecessarily.''
</P>
<P>
   In an open letter last fall to California Republicans, Stuart K.
Spencer, a veteran party strategist, compared turning off Hispanics
to the GOP failure to win votes of Irish and Italian immigrants
earlier in this century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our party has a sad and politically self-defeating history of
alienating immigrant groups and new voters,'' Spencer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are dramatically losing market share of the fastest-growing
segment of the electorate,'' he said. ``These voters should be with
us on the issues of jobs, taxes, government regulation, public
safety and the importance of family.''
</P>
<P>
   Without action, he said, California Republicans could doom
themselves ``to permanent minority status.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the political fallout in two states, there is a sense
that the ``Wilson effect'' has soured California's relationship
with Mexico _ at a time that Bush is eagerly courting Mexican
government and business leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, since his days as a mayor and assemblyman from San
Diego, has watched what he called ``this unfortunate love-hate
relationship'' between the United States and Mexico, including the
problems of illegal immigration and drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson points out that California exports to Mexico more than
doubled in his eight years in office and have increased since
passage of Prop. 187.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business relations have never been better,'' said Jesus
Arredondo, California's assistant secretary for trade.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Wilson source said that Bush advocates are selling the
line that ``the Mexicans are so charmed by George W. and put off by
Pete Wilson that all the trade is going to Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   A Wilson confidante pointed to a quote from Texas Secretary of
State Alberto Gonzalez to the San Francisco Chronicle in April:
``If you're a Mexican businessman and you can make an equally
profitable deal with California and Texas, you're much more likely
to do it where you're more comfortable _ here,'' in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, without invoking Bush's name, believes his own approach,
which doesn't shy from expressing differences with Mexico, is more
based on reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``To make nice and ignore it, I think, is utter folly,'' Wilson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's administration was dumbfounded when Bush urged the
Clinton administration and Congress to again certify that Mexico
was cooperating in the anti-drug fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is an act of total denial,'' said a senior figure in the
Wilson organization.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson and even some of his critics point to demographic
differences in the Hispanic populations of the two states,
including California's larger number of illegal immigrants and the
more established Hispanic community in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Census figures suggest that California has almost three
times as many illegal immigrants as Texas _ in 1997 an estimated 2
million vs. 700,000. That means illegals make up 6.3 percent of
California's population to 3.8 percent in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty percent of Hispanics in Texas are U.S. citizens, while in
California half of Latinos are not, said political scientist
Pachon.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Texas there has been an accommodation, even though it was
sometimes ugly'' in ethnic terms, Pachon said. ``In California,
even though there has been a culturally more open environment, with
the influx of Latinos (in the 1970s and 1980s) there has been
enormous scapegoating. This has especially been true since the
economic hardships of the early 1990s. And people took advantage of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
