<DOCNO> NYT19980619.0388 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8154 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORLDCOM-MCI-1STLD-WR     06-19 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLDCOM-MCI-1STLD-WRITETHRU-345&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEAN OFFICIALS MOVE TO APPROVE WORLDCOM-MCI DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (changes `Holland' to `the Netherlands')   (bl)  
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ After more than a month of negotiations,
European antitrust regulators Friday tentatively approved Worldcom
Inc.'s $37 billion takeover of MCI Communications Corp. after the
two companies agreed to concessions in the sale of MCI's Internet
holdings, industry executives involved in the negotiations said.
</P>
<P>
   Though a few details still need to be clarified, the executives
said, Friday's agreement removes the biggest remaining uncertainty
about the ability of the two telecommunication companies to
complete their deal.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, MCI will sell its main Internet businesses
and will promise not to actively recruit its old corporate
customers. Under an agreement announced last month, MCI agreed to
sell its wholesale Internet business to the British telephone
company Cable &AMP; Wireless PLC, for $625 million. But that deal would
have allowed Worldcom to pursue that business again after the sale
_ a provision that brought protests from Worldcom's competitors.
</P>
<P>
   While the European agreement will prevent that, WorldCom will be
allowed to retain its crown jewel, Uunet, the world's largest
operator of the Internet's high-speed main artery known as the
backbone.
</P>
<P>
   Worldcom's shares closed Friday at $47.0625, up $1.3125. MCI's
shares rose $1.8125, to close as $56.50.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, neither Worldcom executives nor European Commission
officials would comment on the plans Friday. But privately,
officials on both sides confirmed that they had reached a working
agreement and would try to resolve a few remaining issues within
the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Justice Department is examining the same issues as
European regulators, and is not expected to make its decisions for
several weeks. But Worldcom executives consider the European
objections to be their most serious problem. And the Federal
Communications Commission has allowed European regulators to take
the lead in determining how much of the combined company's Internet
backbone will have to be sold off before the deal can be given
approval.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A merger between MCI and Worldcom, which are now the second- and
fourth-largest long-distance telephone companies in the United
States, would create an entity with about $70 billion in sales and
a sprawling array of businesses in voice and data communications.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest part of that empire is in traditional long-distance
telephone service, but both companies provide high-speed data
communications, and Internet services are one of the
fastest-growing areas in both Europe and the United States. What is
more, the industry is quickly digitizing voice calls and moving
them to the Internet and other data lines as a cost-saving measure.
</P>
<P>
   Though MCI and Worldcom are both U.S. companies, European
regulators assert their right to review any merger in which the
companies have significant sales in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Karel van Miert, the European Commission's powerful competition
minister, objected several months ago that the combined companies
would have too much power in the area of Internet services.
</P>
<P>
   MCI agreed last month to sell Cable &AMP; Wireless its backbone
business, which serves local companies that provide Internet access
to businesses and individuals. But Van Miert pressed for more
divestiture, and MCI offered this week to sell off its retail
businesses that provide direct Internet access to corporate and
individual customers.
</P>
<P>
   When it became clear that MCI would have to sell more of its
Internet assets to satisfy European regulators, Cable &AMP; Wireless
sued MCI on June 10, demanding that it be given the right of first
refusal on any additional Internet assets MCI decided to unload. A
court rejected that claim last week.
</P>
<P>
   The European Commission must reach a final decision on the
merger by July 15, though officials want to deal with it at their
meeting July 8.
</P>
<P>
   Van Miert met Friday in Brussels with what is known as the
merger task-force, which consists of competition regulators from
each country in the European Union. That group must recommend
either approving or rejecting a proposed merger, relying largely on
the work done by Van Miert's Competition Ministry in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   Though the arguments over the Worldcom deal have been rather
arcane, the stakes are significant because of both the size of the
deal and its timing.
</P>
<P>
   The huge merger is part of a much broader race for position
between the world's giant telecommunications carriers, most of
which have formed global alliances. It also comes as the European
Union is forcing its own state-controlled telephone monopolies to
accept competition. That process began in earnest last January,
when most European countries simultaneously dropped rules that
prohibit competition in ordinary local and long-distance telephone
service.
</P>
<P>
   Though MCI has relatively little business within Europe,
Worldcom is an aggressive competitor here in several lucrative but
little-noticed niches of the telecommunications industry.
</P>
<P>
   Through MFS Communications, which it acquired nearly two years
ago, Worldcom owns high-speed fiber optic networks in seven major
European cities, including London, Frankfurt, Amsterdam and
Brussels. These networks serve big corporate customers, including
banks and financial institutions, and Worldcom is linking the local
fiber optic networks into a pan-European network that should be
completed next year.
</P>
<P>
   Through Uunet Technologies, Worldcom has become one of Europe's
biggest providers of Internet access services. In the last two
years, Uunet has bought up commercial Internet access companies in
Germany, Britain, France, the Netherlands and Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in the United States, where Worldcom has traditionally
been known as a cut-rate provider of long-distance service for
residential customers, the company's European focus has been much
more on big corporate customers.
</P>
<P>
   Now that European governments have lifted most of the
restrictions on competing with established telephone companies,
Worldcom executives are trying to broaden out and serve small and
medium-sized businesses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
