 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
SCRAMBLE IS ON FOR LAST-MINUTE VOTES IN COLOMBIA
<TEXT>
<P>
   (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 21) &QL; 
 &QL; 
By JOHN OTIS &QL; 
1998c. Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LA DORADA, Colombia _ The venue was a dusty soccer field in a
crime-infested slum. The stage was a collection of splintered
planks stretched across sawhorses. The sound system wasn't much
louder than a boombox.
</P>
<P>
   But Enrique Gaviria, an advance man for the ruling Liberal Party
presidential candidate, Horacio Serpa, refused to panic. Once a
roadie who toured with rock bands such as Lynyrd Skynyrd and Pink
Floyd, Gaviria has a show-must-go-on mind-set.
</P>
<P>
   To salvage one of Serpa's final campaign rallies in the stretch
before today's election showdown with Conservative Party candidate
Andres Pastrana, Gaviria pulled out his cell phone last week and
went to work.
</P>
<P>
   He called in carpenters to patch the stage and procured a bright
red carpet to hide the knotholes. He posted sharpshooters on the
rooftops. And he scoured the barrios for stereo gear to amp up the
sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always like this,'' said Aurelio Iragorri, tour manager
for the Serpa campaign. Local politicians ``tell you that
everything is ready, and nothing's ready,'' he said. ``It's a total
mess.''
</P>
<P>
   With polls indicating an extremely tight race, both presidential
candidates frantically barnstormed across rural Colombia to drum up
last-minute support.
</P>
<P>
   Serpa ventured into some of the most dangerous areas of this
war-racked nation. A Pastrana aide journeyed into the Andean
foothills last week to meet with top guerrilla commanders.
</P>
<P>
   In a three-way race on May 31, Serpa edged Pastrana by less than
34,000 votes out of the nearly 11 million cast. But he failed to
get more than 50 percent of the vote in that first-round election,
forcing today's runoff.
</P>
<P>
   As time ran out, so did the campaign money _ one reason for the
austere look of the Serpa road show last week. But Serpa's campaign
also took extreme measures to avoid any hint of impropriety.
</P>
<P>
   That's because President Ernesto Samper's 1994 election was
partly bankrolled by the Cali cocaine cartel, a scandal that nearly
toppled his government and brought international shame to Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   Serpa was one of Samper's top advisers during the 1994 campaign.
Although Serpa was cleared of any wrongdoing during that race, many
analysts insist that he had to have known about the influx of drug
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the narco-scandal, there's a lot of paranoia about
expenses,`` said Gaviria, who traveled to more than 300
municipalities during the past year in a second-hand bus decorated
with Serpa graffiti. ``Serpa is very scared about overspending and
being accused of illegal acts.''
</P>
<P>
   This time around, there was no evidence of drug money filtering
into either campaign. However, both Serpa and Pastrana were
expected to exceed the legal spending limit of $6.6 million. Rafael
Mateus, of the independent watchdog group Citizens' Oversight,
predicted their bills could top $9 million.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates differ both in style and substance.
</P>
<P>
   A former interior minister in the Samper government, Serpa, 55,
has a walrus mustache and a fiery speaking style. He was at his
best stumping in the countryside, where he promised to build more
schools and hospitals, reactivate the farm economy and help the
poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has to teach me what it's like to have no food in the
house or no family salary. I'm against poverty, because I have
suffered from it,'' Serpa declared last week from the stage in La
Dorada, a Liberal stronghold 60 miles northwest of Bogota.
</P>
<P>
   But due to Colombia's soaring fiscal deficit and economic
recession, analysts predict that the next government will lack the
money for populist programs and will be forced to follow a more
orthodox path.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana, 44, a former TV journalist and mayor of Bogota, lost a
close runoff election to Samper in 1994. During this race, he
pledged to usher in a new era of clean government and fiscal
responsibility and to improve relations with the U.S. government,
which yanked Samper's visa in 1996 due to the campaign finance
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   But as the son of a former president, Pastrana has had trouble
shaking his image as a moneyed technocrat out of touch with
Colombia's poor, who make up 53 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   For example, when asked about education initiatives during a TV
debate last week, Pastrana proposed tax breaks to students to buy
personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana put together an effective media campaign, but Serpa had
done more legwork.
</P>
<P>
   After his speech in La Dorada, Serpa went house to house,
shaking hands. Last month, when his helicopter was about to touch
down in the northern state of Bolivar, gunfire rang out. Yet Serpa
insisted on landing and greeting his supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Serpa also counted on his party's network of powerbrokers. The
Liberals have ruled Colombia for the past 12 years, and the party's
congressmen can deliver blocs of loyal voters.
</P>
<P>
   In La Dorada, Serpa's key contact was Sen. Victor Renan Barco, a
Liberal who has been in office for 30 years. Iragorri described him
as a regional godfather and ``the owner of all the votes.''
</P>
<P>
   The day before the Serpa rally, Iragorri and Gaviria met with
Barco for four hours. They drank beer, watched a World Cup soccer
match on TV and talked politics.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose was to flatter the senator and cajole him into
delivering votes. ``This is called `oiling the machinery,' ''
Iragorri said.
</P>
<P>
   During the meeting, Barco dispensed favors to needy constituents
lined up outside his office. When a crippled lottery salesman
entered the room, Barco pulled out a fat wad of pesos to pay for a
wheelchair. The man promised to vote for Serpa.
</P>
<P>
   The next day at the rally, Barco took the stage and demanded
that the town support Serpa.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians who deliver votes can expect more federal money for
their districts, Iragorri explained.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, campaign aides were angling for posts in an eventual
Serpa administration. Gaviria pestered Serpa for a diplomatic post
in Madrid, so he can spend more time with his Spanish girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Such cronyism and quid-pro-quo arrangements are the kinds of
practices that Pastrana campaigned against.
</P>
<P>
   His strategy for winning today's election was largely based on
attracting the support of the 2.8 million voters who cast their
first-round ballots for independent Noemi Sanin, who finished
third.
</P>
<P>
   Sanin, however, refused to endorse either candidate, which was a
major blow to Pastrana.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Pastrana may have received some help from the
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC, the nation's
largest guerrilla group.
</P>
<P>
   Ending Colombia's 34-year-old civil war is the No. 1 issue in
the campaign, and both Serpa and Pastrana portrayed themselves as
the ``peace candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a communique released last week, the FARC's high command
said that Serpa had done nothing to promote peace while serving in
high government positions over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
