u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLOMBIA-PRESIDENTS-$     06-19 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-PRESIDENTS-$ADV21-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-PRESIDENTS CAN GAIN CLOUT OUT OF OFFICE 
 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 21 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN OTIS 
1998c. Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia _ Unable to resolve pressing problems like drug
trafficking and civil war, recent Colombian presidents have fared
better after stepping down.
</P>
<P>
   Take former President Alfonso Lopez Michelsen. He's 84. He left
office more than two decades ago. Yet he has been one of the most
influential players in Colombia's current presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   For U.S. presidents, power often seems to evaporate the moment
they vacate the White House. Retirement often involves writing
memoirs, building presidential libraries, playing golf or inspiring
name changes for airport terminals.
</P>
<P>
   But in Colombia, former chief executives lead political parties.
They serve as ambassadors. They become trusted presidential
advisers.
</P>
<P>
   President Ernesto Samper once joked that his job's main perk is
that he gets to be an ex-president.
</P>
<P>
   Some former presidents move on to the international stage. After
his government dismantled the Medellin drug cartel and helped
modernize the economy, Cesar Gaviria _ president from 1990 to 1994
_ was elected secretary-general of the Organization of American
States.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez, who was president in the mid-1970s, made the cover of
Semana, Colombia's largest magazine, last month simply by endorsing
ruling Liberal Party candidate Horacio Serpa for today's
presidential runoff election.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lopez's administration was plagued by charges of
widespread corruption, he is a Liberal Party guru who can make or
break presidential hopefuls. His weekly newspaper column helps
shape the national debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are never judged by what happened during their
governments,'' said Jesus Ortiz Nieves, an editor at the weekly
magazine Cambio 16, who wrote a cover story about Lopez last
November. ``But if you look at the results, some of them should
have been brought to the public pillory.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, former presidents are considered political wisemen,
partly because Colombia's Liberal and Conservative parties are
based more on personalities than ideology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our parties are divided up, with two or three big figures in
each one,'' said Rodrigo Losada, a political science professor at
Javeriana University in Bogota. ``What they say or don't say
carries a lot of weight.''
</P>
<P>
   Colombia's Constitution allows presidents to serve for just one
four-year term. Since they can no longer vie for formal power,
ex-presidents become political referees _ kingmakers who are called
upon to settle internal party disputes.
</P>
<P>
   It seems unlikely, however, that politicians will seek President
Samper's counsel once he leaves office on Aug. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Samper was elected in 1994 with the help of $6.1 million from
the Cali drug cartel. The scandal nearly led to Samper's ouster and
blackened Colombia's reputation. Claiming that his life will be in
danger once he leaves the presidential palace, Samper plans to
relocate to Spain or Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to find it tough to become an elder statesman,''
said one foreign diplomat.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 2054EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980619.0391 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8159 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENEZUELA-WAYOUT-$ADV     06-19 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-WAYOUT-$ADV21-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
IN VENEZUELA, PLAYING BALL BECOMES A WAY OUT FOR POOR YOUTHS
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 21)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
By JOHN OTIS &QL; 
1998c. Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GUACARA, Venezuela _ If a young man grew up in a shanty playing
stickball with bottle caps on potholed streets, how hard can it be
for him to hit a perfectly stitched baseball? Or to turn a double
play on a manicured Major League infield?
</P>
<P>
   That, at least, is one explanation Venezuelans offer when asked
why their nation has produced so many dominating ``beisbolistas.''
Like the Dominican Republic _ which has provided the largest number
of Latin American big leaguers _ Venezuela has become an El Dorado
for pro clubs seeking baseball prodigies.
</P>
<P>
   The explosive growth in salaries in the United States has turned
the sport into something more than the national pastime here. Much
like basketball in the United States, baseball can be a way for
poor Venezuelan teen-agers to move up in the world.
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen Venezuelans are on Major League rosters this
season, including five-time Gold Glove winner Omar Vizquel of the
Cleveland Indians and Atlanta Braves slugger Andres Galarraga _
known as the South American Babe Ruth. Hundreds more have signed
minor-league contracts. And two dozen Major League teams now run
year-round baseball camps in Venezuela. The diamonds and sandlots
are also swarming with scouts from the professional leagues in
Korea, Taiwan and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every Little Leaguer in the country knows the story of
Jackson Mellion. A 16-year-old pitcher from the sleepy, seaside
town of Puerto de la Cruz, Mellion received a $1.6 million bonus
last year for signing a minor-league contract with the New York
Yankees. He had never even pitched in Venezuela's pro league.
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga recently signed a $24.75 million contract with the
Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because so many players, like Galarraga and Vizquel, have made
it big, kids are now driven to play baseball. It represents
economic power,'' said Baldemar Bottini, whose son, Baldemar Jr.,
plays shortstop for a Caracas city league team.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Asuncion, who teaches English to youths attending a
``baseball academy'' run by the Houston Astros here, agrees.
``Baseball is a way out,'' he said. ``It's like winning the
lottery.''
</P>
<P>
   The sport was introduced to Venezuela by American oilmen at the
turn of the century, and it quickly caught on. Boys often start out
playing stickball and can join join little leagues at the age of 4.
Venezuela's professional league attracts U.S. players looking to
hone their skills during the off-season. Pete Rose, Dave Parker,
Rod Carew and Greg Maddox have all played in Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   On TV, baseball fanatics can watch Major League games every day.
``The passion for the big leagues is so strong that the (Caracas)
stadium never fills up during the playoffs. People will stay home
to watch the World Series,'' Rueda said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Venezuelans focused on Omar Vizquel, who made it to
the World Series with the Indians. He is one of a series of great
Venezuelan shortstops including Hall-of-Famer Luis Aparicio and
Dave Concepcion of Cincinnati's dominating ``Big Red Machine'' of
the 1970s. As a result, shortstop is the preferred position for
youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ask 200 kids, 150 of them want to play shortstop,''
Asuncion said.
</P>
<P>
   The most promising teen-agers are invited to the baseball
academies, which are like maquiladoras for U.S. teams. Cheap to
operate, they mold raw Venezuelan players into valuable exports to
the United States. Each Major League club receives 28 visas to
allow such foreign-born players to join their stateside farm teams.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Guacara, a farming town 60 miles west of the capital
city, Caracas, the Houston Astros operate one such academy. At the
start of practice one recent morning, 45 players wearing blue
Astros caps jogged around the outfield, which was littered with
fallen mangoes from nearby trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, baseball has always been everything,'' said Pablo
Morales, a lanky, 15-year- old pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Added a catcher, Kleber Zerpa, also 15, ``Baseball is in my
blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Morales and Zerpa are confident that they will one day play
in the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   The prospects undergo hours of daily instruction and weight
training. They are also given a balanced diet.
</P>
<P>
   ``They run well and they may have good bat speed. But some
arrive here with nutrition problems and are really skinny,'' said
Pablo Torrealba, who runs the Astros academy in Guacara and used to
pitch for the Oakland Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   Besides fattening them up, trainers try to prepare the players
for life in the United States, since most will eventually sign
minor-league contracts with an average pay of $7,000 annually. Some
of the players come from broken homes and lack the discipline
required of professionals. In fact, poise, dedication and language
skills are almost as important as physical talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their performance can be affected if they don't understand
their coaches,'' Asuncion said after a recent English class held in
a church on the outskirts of Guacara. ``I also teach them to stay
out of trouble, to do their job and to save their money. What I
teach them here is for whatever career they end up having.''
</P>
<P>
   That's especially important because the average minor-league
career lasts about five years. What's more, fewer than 1 percent of
the players in the academies ever make it to the majors. To help
them cope with the pressure, the Astros team psychologist pays
frequent visits to Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their chances are very small,'' said Torrealba, who toiled for
nine years in the minors before being called up by Oakland.
``Everyone thinks they will get to the majors, but it's almost
impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   For many Venezuelan prospects, getting paid to travel around the
United States to play single-A baseball for a few, precious seasons
can be thrill enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if they drop-out, it's a great experience,'' Asuncion
said. ``They come home more mature and more realistic about life.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
