<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINOR-RIGHTS-$ADV </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINOR LOSES PARENTAL RIGHTS TO GRANDPARENTS 
 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 21) 

</HEADLINE>
 21-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RON NISSIMOV 
Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If some people find Erica Zeman an unappealing person because
she kept her baby after being raped at age 14 and got married to a
38-year-old man when she was 17, then so be it, she says defiantly.
</P>
<P>
   But in her mind, those are not good enough reasons to remove her
firstborn child from her household, which a judge did two weeks
ago. Since Erica never mistreated her 3-year-old daughter Bianca,
she can't fathom why the judge decided the girl should live with
Erica's father and step-mother.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the decision of state District Family Judge ``Cactus
Jack'' Kagle is changed, Erica will only see her daughter every
other weekend, during parts of summers and some holidays.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one deserves having a child taken away because society says
it's bad to have an age difference,'' said Erica, who married Mark
Zeman in December and recently had another child with him. ``All
the people who criticize me should have their child taken away when
their child is the center of their world.''
</P>
<P>
   The unusual custody battle arose out of a joint custody
agreement Erica signed in January 1996 with her father and
step-mother, Kevin and Melodie Avis. At the time, Erica and Bianca
were living with the Avises in west Houston, and the agreement was
ostensibly needed so Kevin Avis could provide medical insurance for
Bianca.
</P>
<P>
   All three said last week that the Avises convinced Erica to sign
the agreement by reassuring her Bianca would live with her when she
became a legal adult.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless Erica did something flighty,'' Melodie Avis added.
</P>
<P>
   Erica said she was told the only way the Avises would fight for
custody of Bianca was if Erica abused the child, which she was
never accused of doing.
</P>
<P>
   But when Erica left with Bianca last October to move in with
Zeman, Melodie Avis went on a mission to prove he was a child
abuser and to try to get Bianca back.
</P>
<P>
   State investigations have cleared Zeman of the allegations made
by Melodie Avis that he abused Bianca. Illinois investigators also
cleared him of accusations made there by his ex-wife that he had
neglected their children. Zeman's ex-wife lost a custody battle
over their son, but Melodie Avis said she has no reason to doubt
the veracity of her stories.
</P>
<P>
   Legally, only Kevin Avis has the right to determine where Bianca
lives. But Melodie Avis, who clearly has a role in the decision,
said she is far from ready to allow Erica to have Bianca.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, any 38-year-old man that gets involved with a
17-year-old child is a child molester anyway,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she would allow Erica to have Bianca if she left Zeman,
she said Erica is still too ``immature.''
</P>
<P>
   Melodie Avis, 32, said she understands the love Erica feels for
Bianca because she also had a child out of wedlock as a teen-ager.
She said she was glad her parents helped her raise the two children
she had before she married Kevin in 1995, and wondered why Erica
did not welcome similar aid from the Avises.
</P>
<P>
   The Avises, who had their own baby, are already raising six
children, but feel they also need to care for Bianca for her own
good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the evil step-mom wanting to take the child,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The case illustrates the potentially unforeseen consequences
when mothers who are minors sign joint custody agreements to help
provide financially for their infants, said a Houston family law
expert.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you enter into a joint custody arrangement, just because
you're the biological mother doesn't mean you will have more
rights,'' said Stewart Gagnon, a partner at Fulbright &AMP; Jaworski
who chaired a committee that played a major role in rewriting the
state's family law code in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   He said it is often likely that minors won't fully understand
the implications of signing the agreements and state laws have ``no
real obligations to make them understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Gagnon said he believes there should be mandatory education for
anyone who signs such an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   He added that if the mother is a minor, there is no reason a
court could not appoint an ad litem attorney to represent the
mother's interests, but it is unclear how often this is done. The
court did not appoint an ad litem attorney for Erica, but it
appointed one for Bianca.
</P>
<P>
   To Erica, the irony of all this is that she was a trusted mother
figure to her two younger sisters and younger brother for many
years because their real mother left home for months at a time and
frequently mistreated them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would cook my sisters' and brothers' meals, give them baths,
and change their diapers,'' Erica said. ``We were real close,
because we knew we were all we had.''
</P>
<P>
   Their mother _ who was shunned while growing up in Korea because
she was an ``Amerasian,'' half American, half Asian _ left home for
good five years ago when Erica was 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day she left us I made a vow I would never make my
children feel what I felt growing up,'' said Erica, who graduated
from high school this spring and hopes to become a nurse.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Avis, 40, said he could do little about how his wife
treated the children because he was frequently away on military
missions and he fought in Operation Desert Storm in 1991. Before he
left the military and moved to Houston in 1992 to work as a
surveyor, the family lived in many places, including Korea, Germany
and Ft. Hood.
</P>
<P>
   Erica became pregnant with Bianca by a 21-year-old man who was
convicted of aggravated sexual assault and waived his parental
rights.
</P>
<P>
   After signing the joint custody agreement, Erica and her
step-mother intermittently argued over how to raise Bianca. But the
arrangement did not truly sour, they said, until the Avises learned
last fall that she was engaged to Zeman and was pregnant with his
baby.
</P>
<P>
   The machinations to take Bianca away from Erica began the day
she left the Avises' home on Oct. 2. She first stayed with Zeman,
but then with other friends.
</P>
<P>
   That day, Zeman's ex-wife called Melodie Avis alleging he had
neglected his own children and that he was being investigated by
various law enforcement agencies.
</P>
<P>
   During the course of the next few days, Melodie Avis said she
repeatedly asked police to arrest Zeman at either his apartment or
workplace at a car dealership for outstanding traffic warrants. She
said police wanted ``to put him behind bars so they could
fingerprint him'' to possibly link him to other incidents.
</P>
<P>
   Zeman said he lost both his job and apartment because of the
police visits and Melodie Avis' false accusations. He landed a job
as a salesman at another car dealership.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 21, without Zeman or Erica's knowledge, Melodie Avis
obtained a temporary restraining order from a judge keeping Erica
away from Bianca because of Zeman's alleged history of child abuse.
Melodie Avis' affidavit also said, ``At this time Crime Stoppers
and the U.S. Marshal are working on a case against him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bianca was already with the Avises when the order was issued.
The Zemans say the Avises took her from a day care center without
permission, but the Avises say Erica left the child with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just cried,'' Erica said about her reaction to the TRO.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 18, Zeman showed a judge letters from various law
enforcement agencies explaining he was not being investigated for
anything. By this time, he had also been cleared of Melodie Avis'
allegations of child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   The judge returned Bianca to Erica, giving the Avises visitation
rights during Christmas vacation.
</P>
<P>
   But one month later, the Avises brought the judge documents
showing Zeman also was being investigated for child neglect in
Illinois. The Avises denied these charges were filed by Zeman's
ex-wife to help their case. The judge allowed Erica to keep Bianca,
but wanted to hold a hearing in Harris County after the Illinois
matter was scheduled to be heard on March 4.
</P>
<P>
   On March 3, however, a hearing was held in which the Avises were
granted extended weekend visitations every week from Wednesdays
through Sundays. The judgment was entered because neither the
Zemans nor their attorney, Jim Farmer, showed up.
</P>
<P>
   They said they were never notified. Farmer said the Avis'
attorney, Bruce Zivley, had no proof that he ever notified the
other side. Zivley said it was the court's duty to inform Farmer,
and a court clerk did so.
</P>
<P>
   Farmer said if he had been notified by the court he would have
come.
</P>
<P>
   Bitter and distrustful, Erica refused to take Bianca to the
Avises until late April, after a judge had already cited her for
contempt and had threatened to send her to jail.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Kagle denied the Zeman's request to have a jury trial to
hear the final disposition of the case.
</P>
<P>
   Zivley said the judge denied the motion because Zeman didn't pay
his jury fee. Zeman has a certified mail receipt showing he
notified Zivley on May 4 and a receipt from the county dated May 1
showing he paid his $30 jury fee.
</P>
<P>
   During an interview at the Avises' home, they showed a reporter
a videotape they made to ostensibly show how much Bianca fears
going to the Zemans' home.
</P>
<P>
   When it was time for Bianca to leave the Avis' house during a
recent visit, Melodie Avis clutched the girl and spoke in grave
tones about how Bianca needed to go back to her mother's.
</P>
<P>
   As Bianca became more and more agitated, one of Melodie Avis'
daughters from before her marriage to Kevin Avis tried to calm
Bianca down by saying, ``Nobody's going to hurt you, baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Melodie Avis interrupted her daughter, telling her, ``Don't say
that, you don't know that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm careful not to make promises to kids that I'm not sure
about,'' she explained to a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   The Zemans said they will try to appeal the ruling, but they
don't have much money for a protracted legal battle.
</P>
<P>
   The families, who belong to the same church, initially tried to
resolve their differences with the help of their pastors. In a
letter dated Nov. 20, Mark Zeman expressed this wish to Kevin Avis:
</P>
<P>
   ``As it says in 1 Corinthians 6:1-8, `we should not take our
disputes to worldly courts, but resolve them with the help of God
and our fellow believers.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
