u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JUVENILE-CRIME-$ADV21     06-19 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUVENILE-CRIME-$ADV21-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
MANY IN POLL WANT STIFFER LAWS ON JUVENILE CRIMINALS
<TEXT>
<P>
   (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 21) &QL; 
 &QL; 
By JOHN W. GONZALEZ &QL; 
1998c. Houston Chronicle &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Despite signs that a 1995 crackdown on juvenile
offenders is working, many Texans want even more stringent
sanctions for young criminals, including requirements that all
youthful offenders be sent to adult prisons when they turn 17 years
old and that all juvenile murderers be tried as adults, according
to the latest Texas Poll.
</P>
<P>
   But kids aren't the only targets of those wanting to reduce
juvenile crime.
</P>
<P>
   A significant number of those polled said parents should be held
legally accountable, through fines or imprisonment, for the
criminal acts of their children _ a notion that Texas lawmakers
rejected as unconstitutional when they rewrote the juvenile justice
code.
</P>
<P>
   The poll said that while Texans still overwhelmingly support the
death penalty for adults, most people oppose a proposal to allow
death sentences for offenders as young as 11. That proposal is
likely to be debated in the 1999 legislative session because of the
national rash of schoolhouse shootings by juveniles.
</P>
<P>
   Almost unanimously, Texans described juvenile crime as a
``serious problem'' and most of the respondents said parents are
the ``major cause'' of juvenile delinquency. A distant second on
the blame list was drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 adults were queried by the Scripps Howard Texas
Poll on juvenile crime issues earlier this month. The results,
calculated by the University of Texas Office of Survey Research,
carried a margin of error of plus or minus 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   On several issues, the results indicated widespread support for
harsher treatment of young offenders:
</P>
<P>
   1) Seventy-three percent of the respondents said juveniles in
the custody of the Texas Youth Commission automatically should be
sent to adult prisons when they turn 17 years old. Current law
gives juvenile court judges the option of transferring them to
adult prisons of the Texas Department of Criminal Justice.
</P>
<P>
   2) Fifty-five percent said juveniles, regardless of their age,
should be tried as adults if they're accused of murder. Existing
law specifies that murder suspects must have been at least 14 when
they committed the crime in order to face trial as an adult.
</P>
<P>
   3) Twenty-five percent favor a change in law so juries can
impose death sentences on juveniles as young as 11 years old, even
though the U.S. Supreme Court requires that the offender be at
least 17.
</P>
<P>
   Some 66 percent of the poll respondents rejected the proposal,
but its chief proponent said the findings are nonetheless
encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   ``I regard this as an awakening call to Austin that enough is
enough,'' said state Rep. Jim Pitts, R-Waxahachie, who plans to
submit the death penalty proposal in next year's session.
</P>
<P>
   Pitts is expected to encounter stiff opposition there. Gov.
George W. Bush has already stated he sees no reason to change
current law that sets 14 as the age at which a juvenile can be
certified to stand trial as an adult. State Rep. Toby Goodman,
R-Arlington, architect of the 1995 reform package and chairman of
the House Committee on Juvenile Justice and Family Issues, likewise
opposes Pitts' suggestion. It was first floated after the quintuple
homicide at a Jonesboro, Ark., school attributed to youths 13 and
11 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman described Pitts' proposal as unconstitutional and ``a
moot point,'' adding, ``I'd be opposed to it even if there weren't
a Supreme Court decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Analyzing other poll findings, Goodman tossed cold water on the
idea of punishing parents for their kids' crimes. Again, it's a
problem of unconstitutionality, he said, noting that lawmakers
carefully analyzed the parental responsibility issue in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The result, he said, was a decision to allow juvenile judges to
hold parents in contempt of court if they don't see to it that
their children make restitution and attend school and counseling
sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't sentence a parent to jail for something the child
did _ unless the parent participated in the act, and then they
would be a co-conspirator anyway,'' Goodman said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that public sentiments about the severity of the
juvenile crime problem belie statistics indicating that existing
reforms already have made a positive impact. The Texas Department
of Public Safety reported that the 181,625 juvenile arrests in 1997
represented a 2.4 percent decrease compared with 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's particularly important because the (number of) offenses
for which juveniles can be referred to the juvenile authorities has
increased significantly,'' Goodman said. ``All the statistics are
indicating that what we did worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than formulate a strict rule requiring all juveniles to
be tried as adults, lawmakers opted for flexibility with hopes that
confinement by the TYC would be effective, Goodman said. Even so,
the law leaves room for long-term incarceration for aggravated
cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can try a juvenile as an adult if the juvenile court
waives jurisdiction and if the offense was committed after the
juvenile's 14th birthday,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Further, ``if a 10- or an 11-year-old commits murder, they're
subject to a 40-year prison stay. They're subject to a 10-year
minimum before they're released and I don't think the public's
aware of that,'' Goodman said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Poll coordinator Ty Meighan said the results, when broken
down by region and age groups, yielded a few intriguing findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interestingly, younger Texans are least likely to support
fines or prison for parents of juvenile criminals,'' he said.
Thirty-seven percent of 18- to 29-year-olds said they would support
such a law, compared with 53 percent of respondents 60 and older.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 2059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
