<DOCNO> NYT19980619.0395 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8164 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREST-FIGHT-3TAKES-$     06-19 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREST-FIGHT-3TAKES-$ADV-21-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 21 
 
HEADWATERS FOREST FIGHT ENDING MUCH AS IT BEGAN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BILL DAWSON 
1998c. Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUREKA, Calif. _ In the silence of the primeval Headwaters
Forest, which Houston businessman Charles Hurwitz planned to cut,
it's easy to believe the end of the clamorous battle over this
largest unprotected grove of ancient redwoods is finally in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the virgin forest, however, the debate hasn't grown much
quieter in what may be its waning days.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers are maneuvering. Press releases are flying. And a
young woman named Butterfly is living in a tree she calls Luna,
declaring in as many interviews as her supporters can line up that
a pending deal to preserve Headwaters isn't good enough.
</P>
<P>
   If the Headwaters fight is drawing to a close, it's ending in
much the same way it has played out since 1986, when it became one
of the most acrimonious environmental issues of recent times.
</P>
<P>
   That was the year Hurwitz, Maxxam's chief executive, seized
control of Pacific Lumber Co. with high-interest junk bonds from
the later-jailed Michael Milken. The Houston businessman also
controls Kaiser Aluminum and Sam Houston Race Park.
</P>
<P>
   After a study showed Pacific Lumber had more standing timber
than was thought, Hurwitz doubled its logging rate and replaced
``selective'' harvesting with clearcutting, which removes all the
trees from an area.
</P>
<P>
   The redwoods in the 3,000-acre Headwaters grove, some worth tens
of thousands of dollars, tower more than 300 feet above fern-clad
slopes where they took root a millennium and more ago. In the dim
light, fading slashes of blue paint on huge trunks are the only
obvious signs that humans ever set foot here. They mark the trees
Hurwitz once planned to cut down.
</P>
<P>
   But if a sale negotiated with state and federal officials in
1996 can be finalized in the next few months, the Headwaters grove
will become the core of a government preserve of 7,500 acres. That
could also close the last major chapter in a much older
conservation issue.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy years after large-scale logging of old-growth redwoods
began, prominent Californians in 1918 founded the Save-the-Redwoods
League. Raising funds to buy groves, they expressed feelings of awe
and reverence for the ancient trees that echo in the later
Headwaters debate.
</P>
<P>
   Preservationists seeking to save Headwaters combined spiritual
and biological arguments for protecting the old-growth ecosystem
and its wildlife. In Hurwitz, they confronted a philosophy that
views redwoods as an agricultural commodity, like corn or wheat _
insensitive, some individuals who know him say, to aspects other
than economics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, it's a clash of values,'' said Rabbi Les
Scharnberg, an environmentalist from Arcata, Calif., near
Headwaters, who has talked with Hurwitz. In keeping with his usual
practice, Hurwitz declined to be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   The coast redwood, world's tallest tree and one of the oldest,
grows only in a thin band from mid-California to southern Oregon.
Of the original 2 million acres of old-growth redwoods _ trees
about 200 years and older _ only 5 percent remains, mostly in
parks. Pacific Lumber owns most major ancient groves in private
hands.
</P>
<P>
   Company and state officials would not release figures, but the
Save-the-Redwoods League estimates Pacific Lumber had cut half the
old-growth redwoods it had when Maxxam took over. Proposed
restrictions would let it cut about half of what is left.
</P>
<P>
   These land-use rules, which would govern the 202,000 acres PL
would keep after selling Headwaters, resulted from months of thorny
negotiations by company and government officials. A federal habitat
conservation plan would protect an array of wildlife species. A
complementary state forestry plan would guard watersheds and ensure
``maximum sustained production'' of timber.
</P>
<P>
   Crucially, the habitat plan would grant a much-desired permit
under the Endangered Species Act, authorizing otherwise illegal
actions _ ``incidental'' deaths of protected wildlife and
destruction of their habitat. In recent years, PL has had trouble
keeping an old-growth mill running at the same time it complied
with that law, federal officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The Headwaters sale is contingent on adoption of the two plans,
expected to be issued for 90 days of public comment this month
after weeks of delay as biologists and lawyers massaged fine
points. When an agreement on key principles was announced in
February, California's Republican Gov. Pete Wilson declared it
``puts an end to years of debate'' over Headwaters. That hasn't
come close to happening yet, however.
</P>
<P>
   The rules would allow logging on about 10,000 acres of
old-growth redwoods, 8,700 acres of old-growth Douglas fir and
176,000 acres of younger trees. The rules would prohibit logging
redwoods on nearly 8,000 acres, including 4,200 acres of old-growth
in all but one of PL's major remaining groves and in smaller,
scattered stands. This ban would last 50 years, but could end
earlier if numbers of the marbled murrelet, a rare seabird species
that nests in old-growth trees, increase enough.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   ...a rare seabird species that nests in old-growth trees,
increase enough.
</P>
<P>
   Separate rules to reduce erosion into streams were designed to
protect coho salmon. Scientists say logging and other practices
have decimated its populations in northern California and Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Wilson put the state's share of the $380 million
sale price negotiated for Headwaters in his proposed budget to
avoid possible voter rejection in a bond issue. Despite strong
support from his one-time electoral opponent, Democratic U.S. Sen.
Dianne Feinstein, the prospects for approval remain in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers allied with environmentalists and commercial salmon
fishermen have won committee approval for a measure to require
stronger conservation rules before state funds are provided.
</P>
<P>
   Maxxam spokesman Bob Irelan said, however, that the negotiated
rules are ``as far as the company can go.'' And Feinstein, who
brokered the Headwaters sale, has warned that state legislators
will kill the deal if they insist on tougher logging restrictions.
Without California's share, a federal appropriation of $250 million
expires in March.
</P>
<P>
   The very word ``Headwaters'' says a lot about the issue's
remarkable trajectory to national prominence since its earliest
days.
</P>
<P>
   A trespassing hiker from Earth First!, a small, structureless
group, coined the name in 1986 when he discovered the grove.
Although they objected to the name for years, Hurwitz and his
companies finally started using it themselves, despite Earth
First!'s role as their fierce and persistent critic.
</P>
<P>
   The group is responsible for an unremitting barrage of invective
aimed personally at Hurwitz. It also has staged a long series of
``nonviolent direct actions'' to slow logging, which Pacific Lumber
President John Campbell calls ``antics.'' (In the 1980s, the group
was accused of ``tree-spiking'' _ pounding large spikes into trees
_ which endangers loggers and mill workers.)
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Earth First! activists have locked themselves
to equipment and staged ``tree-sits'' in an old-growth area along a
stream outside Headwaters, where logging might be regulated more
strictly under the pending land-use rules.
</P>
<P>
   Earth First! has a ``no compromise'' philosophy, but after years
of failed political attempts at settlement _ including five federal
and three state legislative efforts and three state bond measures _
compromise is the essence of the deal now pending.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Wheeler, secretary of the California Resources Agency and
former national director of the Sierra Club, said it ``recognizes
both the need for the economic use of land zoned for that purpose
and identifies those parts of Pacific Lumber's holdings that hold
transcendent natural value and ought to be in the public domain.''
</P>
<P>
   As with most compromises, longtime combatants are uncomfortable
with this one. Although he signed the agreement, Campbell said he
``can't see the justice and the breadth of it.''
</P>
<P>
   After years of controversy and a changing regulatory situation,
however, company officials ``were after some sort of certainty,''
he said. ``We felt we needed to resolve the issue and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Cecilia Lanman, program director of the private Environmental
Protection Information Center in Garberville, Calif., is not that
reconciled.
</P>
<P>
   ``No deal's better than a bad deal _ that's just the way it
is,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   EPIC, oriented toward research and litigation, was founded in
the late 1970s to fight aerial herbicide spraying on private and
federal timber lands.
</P>
<P>
   It has played a key role in the Headwaters issue's history,
filing 16 lawsuits over PL's logging practices since the Maxxam
takeover. Perhaps most crucial was a landmark case that extended
the Endangered Species Act's protection of wildlife habitat to
logging on private lands.
</P>
<P>
   In that context, Lanman said the federal habitat plan's waiver,
allowing some wildlife deaths and habitat disruption, is ``a
license to kill,'' and would ``undermine the law and biology we
have worked on so many years.''
</P>
<P>
   A former organizer for the United Farm Workers Union, Lanman
learned about forest and watershed issues when she and her
then-husband moved to Humboldt County, where PL operates, to become
self-reliant homesteaders.
</P>
<P>
   They were part of a back-to-the-land migration to northern
California that was far more in tune with the countercultural ethos
of the 1960s than the freewheeling business climate of the Reagan
era, when Hurwitz gained fame with corporate takeovers.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the college town of Arcata boasts the nation's first city
council with a Green Party majority, and the area's most famous
cash crop may not be trees: ``If marijuana were ever legalized,
this place would be Kuwait,'' a local prosecutor joked.
</P>
<P>
   If Hurwitz ever doubted Humboldt critics' ability to magnify the
Headwaters cause beyond their small communities, as some California
observers believe, he was soon proved wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Local environmentalists complained that he was liquidating a
priceless forest to pay off junk bonds, and the national media
picked up the theme. In 1989, even the conservative Reader's Digest
blamed ``corporate greed'' for ``California's chainsaw massacre.''
</P>
<P>
   The company tried to fight back, assailing ``radical
environmentalists'' and their ``emotional'' motives for saving the
Headwaters grove when much larger areas of old-growth redwoods were
already in parks.
</P>
<P>
   Even some critics concede Hurwitz introduced ``industrial
forestry'' policies at PL that were already common at other
northwestern timber companies. But the symbolism of Headwaters as
the ``last stand'' took root, along with the ``greed'' charges
Maxxam still tries to combat. Recently, it has publicized a
revisionist study by two University of Southern California
economists, who say Hurwitz acted mainly to boost profits, not pay
off his debt.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, though, it was not the sparring in the news media
but the Endangered Species Act that pushed the Headwaters issue
into talks that produced the pending settlement _ particularly,
decisions by federal officials to grant its protection to the
marbeled murrelet in 1992 and the coho salmon in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Without environmentalists' legal challenges to PL's harvest
plans under the species law, ``the company would have just
bulldozed its way through,'' and ``would have cut all their
old-growth by now,'' said Jeff Barrett, who joined PL as fish and
wildlife director this spring.
</P>
<P>
   A company lawsuit against the U.S. government, alleging its use
of the species law confiscated property without compensation, also
moved the issue toward resolution. Sources say Clinton
administration officials wanted to avoid an expensive legal fight
over this ``takings'' issue while the law is vulnerable to attack
in the Republican Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists who negotiated the federal habitat plan, meanwhile,
say it goes as far as the limits of the species law allow,
restricting logging only insofar as it would ``jeopardize'' the
continued existence of the murrelet and coho.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett, who helped negotiate those rules as a consultant for
Pacific Lumber, said they will make it the industry leader in
protecting the environment. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``It's not an exaggeration to say this company is committed to
doing business totally differently than it has ever done business
before _ or any other timber company in the Northwest,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have targeted the plan's temporary salmon rules,
however, because they are not as strict as federal officials'
no-logging buffer zones along streams in national forests. Erosion
can kill salmon eggs, fill pools where the fish's tiny prey thrive
and harmfully raise water temperatures in wider, shallower
channels. After a three-year study, officials will tailor
site-specific restrictions for PL that will probably be more
permissive than the temporary rules in some cases and more
restrictive in others, said Jim Lecky of the National Marine
Fisheries Service.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco-based Sierra Club has pressed California
lawmakers to require changes in the salmon rules as a condition for
funding the Headwaters sale, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to give Charles Hurwitz another pot of money,
we'd like to know what we're getting in return,'' said Elyssa
Rosen, a regional representative for the group.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett said the rules, ensuring 75 percent to 95 percent of the
benefits of unlogged forests, will ``substantively restore coho
salmon on our land.'' Allowing some stream disturbance is
consistent with historical conditions in ancient groves, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A biological debate about the marbeled murrelet's needs was
central to the question of how many acres of PL's old-growth forest
would be off limits to logging in the rules. The company argued for
16 months that selling the Headwaters grove provided enough habitat
for the bird, said Phil Detrich, a U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service
official.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the company agreed to set aside ancient redwoods on
lands including all but one of six other large remaining groves _
its ``lesser cathedrals.'' This ban will last 50 years, but could
end earlier if the murrelet's status improves so much that
officials remove it from legal protection.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately, PL would get to log in its choice of one of two
``lesser cathedrals'' _ Owl Creek, at the heart of EPIC's landmark
lawsuit, or Grizzly Creek, which the Save-the-Redwoods League wants
to buy to add to a state park.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the Headwaters grove, environmentalists, elected
officials and others have called for Hurwitz to transfer extra land
to public ownership in a ``debt-for-nature'' swap to settle federal
banking charges against him.
</P>
<P>
   In a civil hearing that resumed last week in Houston, the Office
of Thrift Supervision alleges reckless banking practices by him and
others caused United Savings Association of Texas to fail in 1988,
costing taxpayers more than $1.6 billion. Hurwitz's attorneys say
the charges are politically motivated, and he was a victim, not
perpetrator, of the failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if there were a debt, we wouldn't swap it for trees,''
Maxxam's Irelan said.
</P>
<P>
   But company and government officials evidently have discussed
the idea. In April, the Press Democrat of Santa Rosa, Calif.,
quoted Feinstein saying a ``debt-for-nature'' swap was possible,
and another U.S. official confirming talks have occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding that report, Irelan said there is ``certainly not
anything ongoing'' in the way of discussions. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The best known advocate of ``debt-for-nature'' at the moment is
a woman from Arkansas, who came to Humboldt County last fall on a
``spiritual journey'' after recovering from severe injuries in a
traffic accident. She has lived since December atop one of Pacific
Lumber's ancient redwoods.
</P>
<P>
   PL had planned to cut this hilltop stand, next to an earlier
clearcut blamed by some residents for a 1997 landslide that
destroyed several homes in the tiny community of Stafford.
</P>
<P>
   On June 10, Julia Butterfly (originally Hill) completed six full
months on her 180-foot-high platform _ the longest by far of many
``tree-sits'' by Earth First! activists over the years. Her
endurance has reaped a bonanza of coverage by CNN, Time, People,
Newsweek, The New York Times and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds almost kind of hippie-ish and hokey, but to heal the
forest, we have to heal ourselves first,'' the 24-year-old woman
said in an interview by cellular telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to tell Mr. Hurwitz that I love him as a human
being but I'm very, very sad about what he's doing because he's not
just destroying the forest, but destroying people's lives,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's chanting the same mantra _ Charles Hurwitz,
debt-for-nature,'' said Campbell, PL's Australian-born president,
with weary annoyance about such activities on company land.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Headwaters is set aside,'' he said. ``We've set aside
additional old-growth. We're putting in a comprehensive landscape
scheme here. It's time for them, I think, to turn their energy to
something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists have used ``misinformation, certainly less
than factual statements'' during the long dispute, he said. ``They
have demonized Charles Hurwitz and they have demonized Pacific
Lumber when this is not true. I am affronted by that. It seems
almost un-American.''
</P>
<P>
   The dispute has been marked by angry confrontations over the
years between environmentalists and timber workers. Someone set a
fire at Campbell's house three years ago. In 1996, Hurwitz showed
up on a list of names found in later-convicted Unabomber Theodore
Kaczynski's Montana cabin, and last year a California protester hit
the businessman with a pie.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Darryl Cherney, prominent Earth First! activist and
publicist, is suing the FBI and Oakland police for allegedly
mishandling the investigation of an unsolved 1990 incident in which
a bomb exploded in a car, hurting him and severely injuring fellow
activist Judi Bari. Cherney and Bari, who died of cancer last year,
were arrested but released without charges.
</P>
<P>
   Cherney, a singer of his own biting topical songs and author of
other broadsides against Hurwitz, makes no apologies despite
Campbell's ``demonization'' charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see Charles Hurwitz as a human being, very sick with the
greed disease,'' he said in the tiny office of his Environmentally
Sound Promotions business in Redway, Calif., where a colleague
maintains the ``Jail Hurwitz'' site on the World Wide Web
(www.jailhurwitz.com), dealing with the banking allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Cherney predicted protests and lobbying against the Headwaters
agreement will accelerate as the congressional funding deadline
next March approaches. But he admitted that if the deal goes
through, ``a lot of wind could be taken out of the sails of the
Headwaters Forest cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Lanman said EPIC will probably sue again if the habitat plan is
adopted as proposed. And Campbell said the company will continue
acquiring new timber land if the deal is finalized, but probably
return to its ``takings'' suit if it falls through.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of yet more litigation doesn't seem to appeal to
anyone, however, least of all Mike Spear, regional director of the
U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``The marbeled murrelet,'' he said, ``has a very poor chance of
coming out ahead when you throw it into claims court.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   ...poor chance of coming out ahead when you throw it into claims
court.''
</P>
<P>
   A company lawsuit against the U.S. government, alleging its use
of the species law confiscated property without compensation, also
moved the issue toward resolution. Sources say Clinton
administration officials wanted to avoid an expensive legal fight
over this ``takings'' issue while the law is vulnerable to attack
in the Republican Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists who negotiated the federal habitat plan, meanwhile,
say it goes as far as the limits of the species law allow,
restricting logging only insofar as it would ``jeopardize'' the
continued existence of the murrelet and coho.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett, who helped negotiate those rules as a consultant for
Pacific Lumber, said they will make it the industry leader in
protecting the environment. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``It's not an exaggeration to say this company is committed to
doing business totally differently than it has ever done business
before _ or any other timber company in the Northwest,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have targeted the plan's temporary salmon rules,
however, because they are not as strict as federal officials'
