<SLUG> BC-NY-DEAF-MEXICANS-ART-950&AMP;ADDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
49 ABUSED DEAF MEXICANS TO BE ALLOWED TO STAY IN U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV.: a photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling 212
556-4204.) 
 (ps) 
 By MIRTA OJITO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The 49 deaf Mexican men and women whose ordeal as
virtual slaves in a quiet Queens County neighborhood shocked New
York and attracted national attention will be allowed to stay in
the United States, federal officials said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The illegal immigrants, who were forced to peddle trinkets in
the subway and turn over their earnings to ``bosses'' who sometimes
beat and abused them, will be permitted to remain because of their
help in convicting their tormentors, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The news came as the federal criminal case against the men and
women who victimized them ended on Friday with the sentencing of
the last of 18 bosses. The man, Agustin Rodriguez-Torres, was
sentenced to to the time he has already served, 10 months, for
crimes including conspiracy to commit slavery and harboring illegal
aliens.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Immigration and Naturalization Service said the
deaf Mexicans, who have been held under the agency's custody at a
motel in Queens for almost a year, would be released within 30
days. Then, city officials said, they will be allowed to stay in in
city-owned housing in Brooklyn for as long as they need to, and
will be free to go wherever they choose. The city has reserved $1
million for their care, said Gerome M. Hauer, the director of the
Mayor's Office of Emergency Management.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Wishnie, a lawyer with the American Civil Liberties Union
who represents the detainees, said he was relieved to hear that the
government did not intend to deport them. ``They are excited that
the case is over and the bosses who oppressed them are going to
jail,'' he said. ``At the same time, they are anxious to leave the
hotel and begin new lives in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear how the Mexicans might make a living, but Wishnie
and city officials said several nonprofit organizations were
willing to pay for whatever training and schooling they will need
to be self-sufficient. In the meantime, other organizations are
prepared to help them to apply for whatever federal welfare
benefits and health care they may be eligible to receive.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will be clothed, fed, their children will go to school.
They'll get everything they need,'' Hauer said. ``The mayor has
repeatedly said he is committed to help them and we will.''
</P>
<P>
   An INS spokesman, Russell A. Bergeron Jr., said the workers
would be allowed to apply for a special visa granted to people who
contribute significantly to a criminal investigation. Although the
workers do not have the visas yet, ``it is highly unlikely any of
them will be denied,'' Bergeron said. Those who want to return to
Mexico will be free to do so as soon as travel can be arranged, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Wishnie said that 10 to 15 of the workers want to go home,
including a woman who has not seen her two sons for years. However,
he said, many are worried about going back to Mexico because they
fear retaliation from the families of the men and women they helped
to convict.
</P>
<P>
   The end of the criminal case came exactly 11 months from the day
when four deaf Mexican immigrants walked into a police station in
Queens and handed an officer a note asking for help. An
investigation revealed that the immigrants were part of a larger
group of indentured laborers who had been smuggled in the country
and forced to work up to 20 hours a day selling $1 trinkets in the
city's subways. They were living in two cramped apartments in
Queens and sleeping on the floor. If they did not earn enough money
for their bosses, they were beaten and starved.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty people were indicted; two remain in a Mexican jail
awaiting trial and 18 pleaded guilty in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Rodriguez-Torres, who was sentenced on Friday,
was an enforcer who beat the workers and held them down while the
ringleaders shocked them with stun guns. His sentence was lenient,
though, because Rodriguez-Torres never initiated the violence
himself, prosecutors said, and because he cooperated with the
government from the start. He indicated in court yesterday that he
was sorry for what he had done and that he wanted to go home.
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke, about 45 of his victims watched from three benches
at the front of Judge Nina Gershon's courtroom. They looked serious
and transfixed, with their eyes moving from the judge to the sign
language interpreter translating the proceedings. Only after the
session was over did they begin to smile; several also wept
quietly.
</P>
<P>
   The other 17 bosses had been sentenced earlier this year to jail
terms that ranged from 14 years for Adriana Paoletti, the woman
considered to be the ringleader, to 5 years of probation for Frank
Coenen, who was charged with conspiracy to commit slavery but
cooperated with the authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're satisfied with the job we did, that the sentences were
fair and that justice was served,'' said Sandy Cohen, a prosecutor
in the case. Cohen said his office was seeking to extradite the two
bosses who remain in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Days after the workers were found in the houses in Queens,
similar cases of abuse against deaf Mexicans were discovered in
North Carolina and in Chicago. Bergeron said the workers in North
Carolina had all opted to return home, but he did not know the
status of those in Chicago.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While the New York case wended its way through the courts, the
workers and their 11 children, including one born last week, the
fourth to be born in custody, were held at Westway Motor Inn, a
motel in Queens because they were important witnesses for the
prosecution of their ``bosses'' and because they entered the
country illegally. They filled their hours making arts and crafts,
watching Spanish language soap operas and playing board games.
Their view from their rooms was an expressway that leads to La
Guardia Airport. Beyond that, a cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Because they were detainees of INS, they were not allowed to go
outside without and escort and still are not. INS officers continue
to guard the doors to the motel.
</P>
<P>
   Wishnie said that for a long time the government did not raise
the possibility that his clients would be allowed to stay, refusing
to discuss the options until every single one of the men and women
convicted had pleaded guilty. It was only in February of this year,
he said, when the federal prosecutors in charge of the case began
exploring the possibilities of offering a legal status, he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The visas they could soon receive, known as S-visas, are offered
to cooperating witnesses who can provide information for the
prosecution of cases in the United States, or those who, having
provided the information, fear for their lives once they return
home. They are difficult to obtain because INS grants only up to
250 a year for the entire country. To apply for one, the petitioner
has to have a law enforcement agency as a sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the Mexicans have three sponsors: the INS, the
U.S. attorney and the Civil Rights Division of the Justice
Department. All agreed that visas were justified because of the
workers' ``significant contributions to the arrest, indictment and
conviction of the principals in this important case.'' The fact
that INS itself is sponsoring them makes them likely to receive the
visas, because the final decision is made by the attorney general
and INS.
</P>
<P>
   Once they have the S-visas, they can apply for legal residency
in three years, and for citizenship in five more years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
