<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News service for Saturday, June 20. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   STADIUM (Phoenix) _ The Arizona Cardinals and a group of backers
unveiled the largest redevelopment project in Arizona history
Friday, a $1.5 billion master-planned community on the Tempe-Mesa
border that would include a massive convention center and domed
stadium for the NFL team. The Cardinals said they would kick in as
much as $200 million to the 900-acre project, including$75 million
up-front. They claim that is the largest contribution a team has
ever made to a stadium project. The public would be asked to pay
$320 million through a voter-approved quarter cent sales tax that
would run for 20 years. Backers envision 12,000 people living
within Rio Salado Crossing and 10,000 people workingin a huge
office complex. By LISA GONDERINGER. Story will move in the ``A''
category.
</P>
<P>
   CARDS20 (Phoenix) _ Although Michael Bidwill says the Cardinals
are ``committed to Arizona,'' he and the team say they are not
focusing on anything beyond the November stadium vote. BY KENT
SOMMERS. Story will move in the ``A'' category.
</P>
<P>
   SKYHARBOR (Phoenix) _ The name Sky Harbor International Airport
lives, at least for the summer. After days of angry phone calls
from the public _ and waning support from some council members _
Mayor Skip Rimsza agreed Friday to reconsider a decision torename
it Goldwater Sky Harbor Airport. by CHRIS FISCUS. Story will move
in the ``A'' category.
</P>
