<SLUG> BC-CHINA-DISSIDENTS-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGED TO MEET TOP CHINA DISSIDENT
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ A group of 55 democracy advocates from around China
has called on President Clinton to meet with a prominent Beijing
dissident during his visit to China next week as a visible symbol
of America's commitment to human rights. In a letter to President
Clinton faxed to foreign news agencies and to the U.S. embassy, the
group said the planned official welcome for Clinton ``on the bloody
red carpet on Tiananmen Square,'' where the military crushed
student-led demonstrations on June 3 and 4, 1989, was ``a source of
great grief.''
</P>
<P>
   After meeting President Jiang Zemin, the letter said, Clinton
should meet with Xu Wenli, a 54-year-old veteran of democracy
activities from the late 1970s who spent 12 years in prison. Xu has
recently re-emerged as one of the most active remaining dissidents
inside the country, making public demands that the Communist
government allow free labor unions, multiple political parties and
an independent human rights monitor. In the last few months he has
been briefly arrested several times and warned to curtail his
activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hold that meeting with Mr. Xu Wenli, or at least strongly
demanding to meet with Mr. Xu Wenli, is a way to indicate that you
are genuinely concerned about the cause of democracy and human
rights,'' the letter said. If Clinton does not make the effort, it
said, ``we will not be able to believe that your trip to Beijing
will have any significance other than helping the Chinese
government to cast off the diplomatic shadows of June 4 in exchange
for your own political interests.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the U.S. embassy said the letter had been
forwarded to Washington. However, diplomats here said it was
extremely unlikely that Clinton would want to provoke the outrage
of the Chinese government by seeking a meeting with such an
outspoken critic.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has said he will firmly press the cause of human rights
during his visit, from June 25 to July 3. But overall, the trip has
been carefully scripted to cast light on China's growing diversity
and progress, in keeping with the desire of both governments to
cement smoother ties.
</P>
<P>
   Since Jiang's state visit to the United States last year, China
has sent from prison into exile its two most famous dissidents, Wei
Jingsheng, a contemporary of Xu's, and Wang Dan, a student leader
of 1989. But rights monitors abroad say that thousands of people
remain in jail or labor camps for publicly advocating democratic
change.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's letter was written by Wang Zechen, a lawyer in Liaoning
province. Most of the remaining signers are, like him, little known
either inside China or abroad but are part of a network of people
who, in the face of steady police harassment, are communicating by
e-mail and fax to call for major political change.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Xu, together with the best known among the
signers of the new letter, Qin Yongmin of Wuhan, started faxing out
regular reports on arrests of dissidents and other rights
developments. But the reports recently ceased after both men were
detained overnight and their fax machines, computers and other
materials confiscated.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials are hoping that China will offer at least one nod
to human rights concerns during Clinton's visit, by announcing a
firm date for signing the International Covenant on Civil and
Political Rights.
</P>
<P>
   When China said last winter that it planned to sign the
document, which involves commitments to free speech and assembly,
the U.S. government said it would stop pursuing resolutions
critical of China's human rights policies in an annual U.N.
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   China did not say when it would sign or how soon after signing
that it might ratify the convention, nor did it say what
reservations it would make that would exempt it from selected
obligations.
</P>
<P>
   When China does join the convention, U.S. officials argue, it
will be subject to inspections and probing reports, a useful way to
nudge legal improvements here. But in the years before that occurs,
both countries will avoid confrontations over rights in the U.N.
forum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
