<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-DROP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS DISNEY'S MAGIC GONE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
LOS ANGELES _ Shares of The Walt Disney Co. have lost more than 15
percent of their value since reaching an all-time high seven weeks
ago, as Wall Street has become concerned that the entertainment
giant won't meet growth targets.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Disney declined 4 7/16 (seven-sixteenths) to 107 9/16
(nine-sixteenths) Friday and traded as low as 106 7/8
(seven-eights) as a trio of leading media trackers reducing
earnings estimates, following a loss of 2 5/16 (five-sixteenths) on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The analysts cited a quartet of factors for the cuts:
</P>
<P>
   _ Nonblockbuster performances of ``The Horse Whisperer'' and
``Six Days, Seven Nights,'' along with long-term concerns over
Disney's reduced spending on live-action films and increased
competition in animation.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Cannibalization'' of attendance at its older Florida theme
parks due to Disney's Animal Kingdom, which opened in April, and
next year's opening of Universal Studios' Islands of Adventure.
</P>
<P>
   _ Disappointing ratings at Disney's ABC television network and
increased costs of telecasting pro football at ABC and ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   _ Soft sales of consumer products due to weaker economies in
Asia and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Jessica Reif Cohen of Merrill Lynch and Richard Simon of Goldman
Sachs both sliced a dime from their forecasts for the fiscal year
ending Sept. 30, to $3. Ed Hatch of UBS Securities lowered his 1998
projection by 19 cents to $2.96 and cut 42 cents from his 1999
forecast to $3.25.
</P>
<P>
   Disney earned $1.89 billion, or $2.75 a share, on sales of
$22.47 billion in fiscal 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch, who has a ``hold'' rating on the stock, expects Disney's
shares to fall to 100 eventually. That would represent a 21 percent
decline from the all-time of 127 1/8 (one-eights) reached on May 4
amid optimism over prospects for Animal Kingdom, 1998 films and new
ventures such as Disney's cruise line.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
