<HEADLINE>
COMPANY NEWS
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Ford Motor Co. took a big step Friday into the car
dealership business, announcing that it would set up a joint
venture with Republic Industries Inc. and Ford dealers in
Rochester, N.Y., that would own all of the Ford dealerships in the
city. Republic has become the nation's largest retailer of cars by
buying nearly 300 dealerships over the last year and a half. The
transaction calls for the creation of a new company that would own
all eight Ford dealerships in Rochester plus one of the city's
three Lincoln-Mercury dealerships. The new company would be owned
by the dealerships' current owners plus Ford and Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Mercantile Bancorp, St. Louis, agreed to acquire Bruno Stolze &AMP;
Co., St. Louis, a discount brokerage firm, expanding into the
retail securities market. The terms were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   International Multifoods Corp., Wayzata, Minn., the largest U.S.
supplier of food for vending machines, took a first-quarter charge
of $27.1 million to close factories and warehouses and dismiss an
undisclosed number of workers.
</P>
<P>
   Lear Corp., Southfield, Mich., a maker of automobile seats and
interiors, delayed completing its purchase of the Delphi Automotive
Systems' unit of General Motors Corp., Detroit, because of the
strikes at GM plants in Flint, Mich.
</P>
</TEXT>
