<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-KUCHAR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KUCHAR HOLDING HIS OWN AGAINST THE PROS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ On his Georgia Tech golf team, Matt Kuchar plays
second fiddle to Bryce Molder, the 1998 collegiate player of the
year. In the Atlantic Coast Conference tournament, he finished
fifth.
</P>
<P>
   But surround him with a bunch of professionals at a major
championship and the perpetually perky Kuchar kicks it into a
higher gear.
</P>
<P>
   During yesterday's second round at the U.S. Open, for instance,
Kuchar kicked around British Open champ Justin Leonard and U.S.
Open champ Ernie Els for a second consecutive day.
</P>
<P>
   Kuchar, 19, carved out a 69 at the Olympic Club to move to 1
under par through 36 holes for a two-day total of 139, while his
more-celebrated playing partners struggled. Els, who shot a 70,
stands at 5 over. Leonard, who soared to 75, is 6 over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been beaten by an amateur in a long time,'' Els
said. ``At one point, I told him, `After this week, you might as
well turn pro. You'll have a 10-year exemption.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the PGA Tour rolled back the exemption limit for
major-championship winners to five years earlier this season. But
Els' point is well-taken. Kuchar, the toothy, upbeat media darling
who finished 21st at the Masters Tournament, has a legitimate
chance to become the first amateur since 1933 to win the Open.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't try to convince Kuchar, who stands at two strokes off
the lead, of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so,'' Kuchar said, when asked if he felt like an
Open contender. ``I'm just having a great time, trying to play one
shot at a time, and I'll add it up at the end. I had no
expectations coming in here. But, who knows? Maybe I will win.''
</P>
<P>
   As he did at the Masters, the reigning U.S. Amateur champ has
become a gallery favorite at the Open with his engaging smile and
wide-open playing style. After hooking a drive into the left rough
at No. 9, Kuchar tried to play a 4-wood out of the tall grass to
reach the green in regulation. Instead, the ball went dead right
and he took bogey.
</P>
<P>
   After making double-bogey at No. 14, Kuchar attacked the pin at
the 15th hole and wound up in the tall rough on the short side of
the green _ a definite no-no, according to the textbook on Open
course management. Yet Kuchar pulled out a sand wedge and chipped
in for birdie from 30 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like the wheels were coming off after I missed the
green on 15. Then the chip went in, and all of a sudden, all the
momentum came right back,'' said Kuchar, who will be a junior if he
opts to return to Georgia Tech in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   As his son climbed the leader board, Peter Kuchar, who serves as
Matt's caddie, repeatedly pumped his fist or gestured gleefully
after good shots. At one point, Leonard asked Peter Kuchar to step
back so he could hit. On the 17th tee box, Els had to wait to hit
while Peter Kuchar walked in the rough more than 100 yards down the
fairway.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Kuchar's father had been a distraction during the
round, a visibly distressed Leonard said: ``Next question. It does
me no good to answer that question.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuchar, who spent last week taking four final exams at Georgia
Tech, said his father exhibits ``very good golf etiquette'' on the
course and did not understand why he would be a distraction to
other players.
</P>
<P>
   The looming distraction for Kuchar, at this point, is a decision
on whether to return to college.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the Masters, it was too bad to see that $40,000 go to
waste,'' Kuchar said of the paycheck he bypassed by competing as an
amateur. ``I'd love to turn pro. The money looks real good. But I
have no idea when it will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The last amateur to dust the reigning champs from the British
and U.S. Opens through 36 holes was Leonard, who got the best of
Nick Faldo and Tom Kite in 1993 at Baltusrol Country Club. He opted
to finish college before joining the PGA Tour in June 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he would advise Kuchar to do, Leonard didn't waver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stay in school,'' Leonard said. ``He's playing great ... but I
think it's too important to finish school. Once you leave, you're
never going back. No one should kid themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuchar, at this point, figures people are kidding themselves if
they expect him to become the first amateur to win the Open since
Johnny Goodman in 1933.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember in junior tournaments, I would be playing in the
last group and thinking, `What am I going to say when I get the
trophy?' I never won a single junior event,'' Kuchar said. ``So, I
have kind of learned to not think about that. Right now, I'm just
having a great time and I'm pretty close to contention.''
</P>
<P>
   At the least, the teen-ager has humbled two of golf's four
reigning major champions in a head-to-head setting over 36 holes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
