<SLUG> BC-nigeria-bulgaria-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Milutinovic works his magic
<TEXT>
<P>
   Well-traveled coach guides Nigeria past Bulgaria, into second
round
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PARIS _ Before Friday's pivotal match against Bulgaria, Nigerian
coach Bora Milutinovic was asked about the rampant rumors
circulating that he actually had been fired three weeks ago but got
an 11th-hour reprieve.
</P>
<P>
   How lucky do you feel now, Bora, since you're leading maybe the
most surprising team of the World Cup into the second round?
</P>
<P>
   ``I am Bora Milutinovic,'' he said. ``I always feel lucky. I'm
just that way _ a good soccer coach and a lucky man.''
</P>
<P>
   How else could the magnificent World Cup run the Nigerians are
making be explained?
</P>
<P>
   The Africans have hitched their hopes to a coach with a golden
World Cup touch, and it is paying off big, much like things did
when Milutinovic coached Mexico (1986), Costa Rica (1990) and the
United States (1994).
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria again put on a terrific show Friday, much to the delight
of its enthusiastic fans, in a 1-0 victory over 1994 Cup
semifinalist Bulgaria at Stade Parc des Princes.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Nigerians opened the '98 Cup with an impressive
3-2 upset of Spain, which was considered the favorite to win Group
D _ the so-called ``Group of Death.'' Now, with two victories and
six points, Nigeria has already guaranteed itself first place in
the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great compliment to African football that we have
qualified for the second round,'' Milutinovic said. ``This team
earned its place. It was a nervous team before we played Spain, but
now it is a confident team. Winning resolves everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Long considered a talented team but one prone to fall short of
expectations, the Nigerians have played wonderfully.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's game against Bulgaria, Victor Ikpeba kicked in the
eventual game-winner in the 27th minute after a big run sparked by
Jay-Jay Okocha, with Daniel Amokachi getting a nice assist to a
sliding Ikpeba, who pushed it past the goalie.
</P>
<P>
   It was an athletic, well-designed play that the Nigerians would
repeat often during the day, although only the one goal hit the
net. Nigeria outshot Bulgaria 21-13 and had seven shots on goal to
Bulgaria's three.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing a very disciplined game but keeping the pressure
on the goal,'' Ikpeba said. ``We're making plays that are difficult
to make, but they seem easy.''
</P>
<P>
   For Milutinovic, it is an all too familiar World Cup team.
</P>
<P>
   He now has coached four nations past the first round of the Cup.
In 1986, he helped Mexico to the quarterfinals. In 1990, Costa Rica
became the first Central American team ever to make it past the
first round.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Milutinovic survived his own firing.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the Nigerian soccer federation tired of the sluggish
efforts put forth by the Nigerians in Cup-preparation matches and
told Milutinovic he would be replaced. But Nigerian president Sani
Abacha stepped in and told officials to keep Milutinovic.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, Abacha died of a heart attack, but the
federation officials kept to his order.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could thank (Abacha),'' Milutinovic said. ``He would
enjoy this game that we are playing now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
