<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Intergraph Punched By Intel   By Dan Fost  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Intel struck back at its rival Intergraph Corp. this week, asking
an Alabama judge to throw out the central portion of Intergraph's
lawsuit against Intel.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Santa Clara chipmaker also is seeking unspecified damages
from Intergraph, an Alabama maker of large corporate computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're conducting a vigorous defense,'' Intel spokesman Chuck
Mulloy said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Intergraph's lawsuit forms part of the basis of the antitrust
action that the Federal Trade Commission launched against Intel
earlier this month. In addition, Intergraph already has won a
preliminary injunction, under which Intel now must share key
information with Intergraph, and rebuffed Intel's efforts to move
the case from Alabama to California.
</P>
<P>
   Intel, which recorded more than $25 billion in sales last year,
controls more than 90 percent of the market for microprocessors,
the chips that run personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   Intergraph sued Intel in November, charging that the giant chip
company used its market clout to bully it in a patent dispute. With
a filing late Wednesday, Intel said it had the right to use its
intellectual property to defend itself, making a legal formality of
claims that it had already asserted in public statements.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, U.S. District Court Judge Edwin Nelson set a trial
date of Feb. 14, 2000. Nelson also indicated that he will hear
arguments on Intel's motion for summary judgment around October,
Mulloy said.
</P>
<P>
   Before this dispute, Intel and Intergraph enjoyed a cooperative
relationship. Intel supplied Pentium chips for Intergraph's
workstations &UR; .  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   As part of that relationship, Intel also supplied advanced
information about the next chips it would release, enabling
Intergraph to speed up the designs of its machines.
</P>
<P>
   Intergraph says the relationship soured when Intel sought patent
rights to Intergraph's Clipper chip. Intel says it has the rights
to the Clipper chip, thanks to a quirk of law.
</P>
<P>
   The Clipper chip was owned by Fairchild Semiconductor. When
National Semiconductor acquired Fairchild, it also took ownership
of the rights to the Clipper chip, but it quickly sold those rights
to Intergraph.
</P>
<P>
   Intel, however, says because it has a broad cross-licensing
agreement with National, it now has the rights to the Clipper chip.
When Intergraph denied those rights to Intel, Intel responded by
withholding the advanced information about its Pentium chips, an
action that Intergraph says hurt its business.
</P>
<P>
   Under the preliminary injunction that Judge Nelson granted in
April, Intel has been supplying Intergraph with the advanced
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intergraph's case isn't just about patent infringement,''
Intergraph chief executive Jim Meadlock said in a statement
yesterday. ``It's about Intel's willful and unconscionable
anti-competitive behavior that threatened to put Intergraph out of
business.''
</P>
<P>
   On June 8, the FTC, citing similarities between Intergraph's
case and prior disputes that Intel had with Compaq Computer Corp.
and Digital Equipment Corp., filed suit charging the company with
abusing its monopoly in microprocessors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 2121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
