<HEADER>
A8184 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THERAPEUTIC-RIDING-AR     06-19 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THERAPEUTIC-RIDING-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISABLED JOIN THE MANY WHO RIDE FOR THERAPY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Wyo., N.J., Md., Conn.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(mk) 
 By BARBARA STEWART   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Guiding a chestnut gelding as it stepped carefully over
obstacles in a ring in Huntington, N.Y., Tricia Schrader could have
been any novice rider preparing for her first competition. She sat
erect. She seemed confident, in control. Not until she spoke did
her disabilities become apparent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ... feel,'' she said, very slowly, in a barely audible
whisper, pausing during a practice one Saturday last month, ``I ...
feel ... I'm ... the ... master ... of ... the ... horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, doctors told Ms. Schrader she would never again
master walking, let alone riding. She was 17, a week from her
senior prom, when a truck rammed into the side of her car. After
eight months in a coma, she awoke with head injuries that
immobilized her legs and skewed her balance and muscular control.
She has thrown herself into all kinds of therapies. But riding, she
said, actually lets her feel normal for a while _ and it is the
only therapy that is not a chore.
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of physical and occupational therapists are
using horses in treatment, contending that the physical rigors of
riding strengthen the limbs and muscles of people with cerebral
palsy, multiple sclerosis, paraplegia and other disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   And some proponents of therapeutic riding go even further,
asserting that the emotional bonding and mental discipline involved
can help children with autism and patients with addictions and a
range of emotional and behavioral problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an extremely powerful tool,'' said Barbara Glasow, a
founder of the 500-member American Hippotherapy Association, whose
name refers to the medical use of a horse. ``You can achieve
posture and balance control in half the time,'' compared with
therapeutic devices and machines, she said. ``It improves mobility,
flexibility, fine motor control.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more compelling, she said, are the emotional benefits.
``Autistic kids learn to talk about horses,'' she said. ``Using
horses to open a person's diaphragm and get them breathing better _
that's physical therapy. But horses that give a child the desire to
talk _ that's magic.''
</P>
<P>
   While the concept of riding as therapy is not new, the notion of
horses as healers who can touch troubled souls is attracting a wave
of attention in popular culture. Films and best-selling books
portray horses as full-fledged characters, with their own
personalities, emotions and wounded psyches.
</P>
<P>
   In the film version of the novel ``The Horse Whisperer,'' Robert
Redford plays a laconic Montana trainer who does crisis counseling
for Pilgrim, a traumatized horse _ and through that, connects with
its owner, a chilly New York mother, and her injured daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Buck Brannaman, a horse trainer from Sheridan, Wyo., who was one
of the models for the Redford character, speaks almost mystically
of the powers of horses. ``Horses,'' he said, ``are incredibly
forgiving. They fill in places we're not capable of filling
ourselves. They've given people a new hope, a new lease on life. A
horse really wants to please you, to get along.''
</P>
<P>
   Metaphysical musings aside, riding therapy is not for everyone.
The majority of disabled riders are children, but some young
patients are terrified and want nothing to do with the horses. And
while many disabled people who use horse therapy get discounts,
stables that offer the therapy are few and far between, mostly
because they are expensive to run.
</P>
<P>
   And while the practice has been recognized by the associations
of physical and occupational therapists, it is not approved by the
American Medical Association _ or covered by the vast majority of
insurers.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is that there are only a few scattered studies on the
subject. More research may emerge, though, now that some colleges
are adding horse therapy to existing equine studies programs, said
Octavia Brown, director of equine studies at Centenary College in
Hackettstown, N.J., where students can major in therapeutic riding.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Zaro, executive director of the Autism Society of America
in Bethesda, Md., said she had little information about the
effectiveness of riding in treating autism. But, like others who
work with handicapped people, she said an activity like riding
could probably do no harm, and might well help by improving
confidence and coordination.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Kampmann of Riverside, Conn., whose 7-year-old autistic
daughter rides, said the greatest benefit was an intangible one.
``Mostly, it's a normal thing she can do,'' Ms. Kampmann said.
``Anything a typical child could do, that your child can do, you
jump on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Many adult riders with disabilities, like Christina Nazzaro, 38,
of Bethpage, N.Y., also find the experience liberating. ``I love, I
love,'' Ms. Nazzaro, who is deaf and developmentally disabled,
said, signing the words enthusiastically.
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of therapeutic riding has grown steadily since
the North American Riding for the Handicapped Association in Denver
was founded in 1969. More than 500 centers around the country,
including 39 in New York, New Jersey and Connecticut, are
affiliated with the group, which certifies instructors and offers
insurance. About 60 new centers join each year while about 40 drop
out, mostly for financial reasons, said Bill Scebbi, executive
director of the riding group.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of psychologists are even using horses in treating a
variety of mental and emotional problems, from troubled teen-agers
and young sex offenders to the sexually abused and people with
anorexia. These psychologists say riding gives troubled people
feelings of being in control and teaches power through gentle
behavior. Antisocial teen-agers must curb aggressive behavior to
win a horse's cooperation. Victims of abuse can develop trust in a
horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Horses are kind and gentle, but large enough to protect
themselves,'' said Philip Tedeschi, a social worker at the Resource
Center for High-Risk Youth in Denver. ``Holding the reins,
controlling a large animal _ it's tremendously uplifting to kids
who've been downtrodden and out of control. It really works with
notoriously difficult juvenile offenders.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Physically disabled people, like those with cerebral palsy or
multiple sclerosis, benefit by moving with the horse, exercising
their unused muscles and relaxing their rigid ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gait of a horse is an exaggerated form of the gait of a
person,'' said Jay Colan, executive director of Pegasus Therapeutic
Riding in Darien, Conn. ``Forward and back, side to side, up and
down. For someone who doesn't have the experience of walking, being
on a horse trains muscle groups.''
</P>
<P>
   Most instructors are people who have ridden since childhood and
learned therapy techniques at the riding centers, in college
courses or through training offered by the Riding for the
Handicapped group. Both instructors and volunteers are schooled in
safety measures. Horses, too, are trained to be steady and to
ignore distractions like a child's pummeling. The trick is to get
riders off spooked horses uninjured, Colan said. ``We train people
to catch them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Scebbi said he knew of no serious injuries among riders at
member centers.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the insurance necessary to run a therapeutic
riding stable, combined with the cost of buying and caring for
horses, can make it a struggle to keep a riding center going.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Gatti, a special education teacher, founded Pal-O-Mine
Equestrian Inc. on Long Island, which is where Ms. Schrader rides.
After five years, Ms. Gatti is still depending on her parents for
support. Officially she charges $50 an hour for lessons, but many
of her 150 clients cannot afford that and end up paying less.
</P>
<P>
   Pegasus, with 200 clients and 10 centers, has an annual budget
of $500,000. It has received some relatively large donations,
including $5,000 recently from the Christopher Reeve Foundation.
But most of its budget comes from events like fairs and raffles,
and it depends on hundreds of volunteers who work as riding aides
or who raise money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do it because, when the alarm goes off, we can't wait to go
to work,'' Ms. Gatti said.
</P>
<P>
   Most disabled children who have tried the therapy cannot wait,
either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents say, `My kid talks about horses, he draws horses,'''
Colan said. ``This is about socializing, too. This may be their
only outdoor recreation.''
</P>
<P>
   Monty Roberts, author of ``The Man Who Listens to Horses,'' said
children find horses compelling: ``It's a huge animal. It's
athletically superior, and it wants to be your friend.''
</P>
<P>
   When Michelle Teichmann _ a 12-year-old with severe cerebral
palsy _ began riding five years ago, she flopped over the horse's
neck like a rag doll. Now, with an aide behind, holding her hips,
she sits, swaying forward. Walking along each side is another aide.
</P>
<P>
   The bouncing motions strengthen her trunk and force her to
straighten her back, said her mother, Camille Teichmann. In a year
or two, perhaps, she may be able to sit up without support. At
Pal-O-Mine, Michelle was squirming with excitement when she was
placed on a horse.
</P>
<P>
   Bobbing, she grinned, as she did since being wheeled out of the
car for her lesson. Not much else makes her grin this much, her
mother said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trying to get somebody in a clinic to do those movements on a
machine is boring,'' said Jane Fitzpatrick, a physical therapist at
Pegasus. ``Kids on horses will do this for 40-minute sessions and
have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Schrader, riding is not just a pleasure but a chance to
excel. At a disabled-riding competition last month in California,
she placed first in two events. It was the first time she had
competed since high school, where she was on the swimming, bowling
and soccer teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year I am trotting,'' she said, as Pat, her mother,
interpreted. ``Next year I will be cantering. The year after, maybe
I will be jumping.''
</P>
<P>
   Riding and winning, she added, ``was a high for me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It made me feel like myself again. I haven't felt like that in
10 years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
