<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Software Group Seeks Probe Of Microsoft   By Julia Angwin  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Netscape, Justice Department, Ralph Nader: Meet Microsoft's latest
critic _ the Software Publishers Association.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although the Washington, D.C., trade group counts Microsoft as
one of its biggest members, it asked the Justice Department
yesterday to investigate Microsoft's practices in the corporate
software server market.
</P>
<P>
   In a 40-page report, the group accused Microsoft of using
monopolistic practices in promoting Windows NT _ which is a
corporate operating system.
</P>
<P>
   ``This paper goes to the heart of the question: Is there
opportunity in the software industry?'' said Ken Wasch, president
of the association, which represents 1,200 firms.
</P>
<P>
   But some say the question should be: Why is the trade
association biting the hand that feeds it?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really stupid,'' said Rob Enderle, analyst at Giga
Information Group in Santa Clara. ``This is not what you do as a
trade organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft agrees. In a sharply worded letter, Microsoft Chief
Operating Officer Bob Herbold accused the trade group of caving in
to pressures from a few members that are Microsoft competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This new `white paper' seems to be the latest iteration of
some sort of anti-Microsoft campaign by a few SPA members and some
of your staff,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, this is not the group's first &LR;   &LR; anti-Microsoft action.
In February, the SPA released a thinly veiled attack against the
software giant as part of a set of ``competition principles'' for
the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, SPA President Wasch has been increasingly outspoken
about his concern that Microsoft's monopoly needs to be restrained.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's action, however, was the group's most direct attack
yet. The report, titled, ``Competition in the Network Market: The
Microsoft Challenge,'' states that Microsoft is unfairly leveraging
its dominance of PC desktops into a new market _ networked
computing.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the report alleges that Microsoft:
</P>
<P>
   _Requires third-party software developers to make programs run
on Windows NT in order to be labeled compliant with Windows 95 or
Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   _Bundles other software applications, such as Internet programs,
with Windows NT.
</P>
<P>
   _Charges customers less for other Microsoft products if they
purchase Windows NT.
</P>
<P>
   _Discourages competitors by announcing new features of Windows
NT months before they are available.
</P>
<P>
   ``The charges mirror almost exactly the accusations leveled
against Microsoft related to Windows 98,'' said Mike Elgan, editor
of Windows Magazine in Jericho, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Despite the SPA's stance, a Microsoft spokesman said the firm
has no plans to quit the trade group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 2122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
