<HEADER>
A8188 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     06-19 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: KUCHAR CAN'T WIN OPEN. OR CAN HE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It can't happen. The 98th U.S. Open here at
Olympic can't be won by an amateur golfer, if only because an
amateur golfer hasn't won the Open since 1933. But if Matt Kuchar
is still under par after the final round Sunday, his 20th birthday,
well, maybe, just maybe, an amateur could win.
</P>
<P>
   You remember Matt Kuchar, the big kid with the big smile that
lighted up the Masters two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   He'll be a junior at Georgia Tech, but he's not even considered
the best golfer on the team there. He didn't win the recent
national collegiate championship. He didn't even win the Atlantic
Coast Conference tournament title.
</P>
<P>
   But as the reigning U.S. Amateur champion, he was an automatic
entrant in both the Masters and the Open.
</P>
<P>
   At Augusta National he tied for 21st at even-par 288. And as the
Amateur champion, he teed off here in a threesome with Ernie Els,
the defending Open champion, and Justin Leonard, the British Open
champion, during the first two rounds.
</P>
<P>
   With a one-under-par 69 yesterday for 139 after 36 holes, the
6-foot-3-inch teen-ager from Lake Mary, Fla., was six shots better
than Els, seven better than Leonard.
</P>
<P>
   If the kid were to shoot another 139 over Saturday and Sunday,
well, maybe, just maybe, he would be the first amateur to win the
Open since Johnny Goodman in 1933 at North Shore in Glenview, Ill.
Goodman's 287 edged two of that era's best pros, Ralph Guldahl and
Craig Wood.
</P>
<P>
   But win or not, Kuchar's boyish smile is lighting up Olympic
just as it lighted up the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun when you are in the fairway and on the green,'' he
said in the interview tent. ``In the rough it is definitely no fun.
But it's a grind too, much more of a grind than Augusta was. You
have to concentrate just every shot, every hole. If you let down an
inch, this course will grab you.''
</P>
<P>
   When his tee shot on the 157-yard 15th hole hopped into the
rough, it appeared that Olympic had grabbed him. During a double
bogey on the previous hole, he had left what he called an ``easy
bunker shot'' in the rough.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like the wheels were coming off when I missed the
green on 15, and then the chip went in,'' he said. ``All of a
sudden all the momentum came right back and I parred out. I made a
good up-and-down on 16 and on 17 a par is almost like a birdie. I
played pretty solid once I chipped in.''
</P>
<P>
   A teen-age amateur isn't supposed to do this at the Open. Then
again, he did it at the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Augusta really requires precise iron shots,'' he said. ``But
here you have to be precise with the driver, with the 3-wood, with
the 3-iron, with all the irons. But I'm only halfway there. We'll
see what happens in the next two days.''
</P>
<P>
   At Georgia Tech, however, Kuchar is No. 2 on the golf team
behind Bryce Molder, the college golfer of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a terrific player, I guess the best player in college
golf,'' Kuchar said. ``We compete a lot, just matching scores. When
we do get a chance to play together, it's a great time.''
</P>
<P>
   Molder and Kuchar have been selected for the U.S. team of
college golfers that will go against British college golfers for
the Palmer Cup at St. Andrews, Scotland, this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully we will be partners,'' Kuchar said, referring to
Molder, ``and really have a good time cleaning up.''
</P>
<P>
   College golfers carry their own golf bag but here, as in the
Masters, Kuchar's father, Peter, has been his caddie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if my dad would be good for other guys, but he's
great for me,'' he said. ``He really keeps me calm. And seeing him
get excited is just a lot of fun for both of us.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Leonard was asked about Peter Kuchar's outbursts, he
replied, ``Next question.'' After a pause, Leonard added: ``It does
me no good to answer that question. Do you understand?''
</P>
<P>
   Up to now, Matt Kuchar has talked about getting his
business-management degree at Georgia Tech before turning pro.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I really don't know,'' he said. ``I really haven't thought
about it. Dad and I really haven't thought about it. It's all up in
the air. I'm just kind of rolling with everything right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Rolling along on the Open leader boards. But nobody asked him if
he thought he could win the Open. After all, an amateur can't
possibly win the Open.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
