<SLUG> BC-BISHOPS-SEX-VIOLENCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BISHOPS DECRY SEX, VIOLENCE AS ENTERTAINMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The nation's Roman Catholic bishops issued an appeal Friday to
the entertainment industry and the government to reduce the public
portrayal of sex and excessive violence.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that pornography and images of violence ``gravely harm
the moral and psychological health'' of society, the bishops
offered a mixture of criticism and encouragement, specifically
warning about the use of the Internet to distribute obscenity and
prejudice, while also declaring that parents have more influence
over their children than they may realize.
</P>
<P>
   The statement, titled, ``Renewing the Mind of the Media: A
Statement on Overcoming the Exploitations of Sex and Violence in
Communications,'' was adopted by a vote of 207-11 at the bishops'
annual spring meeting which is being held through Saturday in
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Monsignor Francis Maniscalco, a spokesman for the National
Conference of Catholic Bishops, said the statement arose in part
out of concerns expressed by Cardinal William Keeler, archbishop of
Baltimore, who has been active in interfaith efforts against
pornography.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Maniscalco said, ``It's a reaction to the outcries
we have heard from people who say, `I can't watch television with
my kids.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the statement, the bishops voice concerns about a wide range
of media _ faulting talk radio for angry remarks, the music
industry for songs with obscene lyrics, video games that rely on
violent images and the advertising industry for using sex to sell
products, sometimes with models who could be mistaken for minors.
</P>
<P>
   But the statement did not solely fault the producers of what the
bishops referred to as indecent and obscene material. ``Those who
freely choose to support the industries which purvey pornography
and graphic violence have a responsibility not only for themselves,
but for those who will be trapped in what the Catechism of the
Catholic Church calls `the illusion of a fantasy world' filled with
sex and violence,'' the bishops said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the bishops said the government needed to use its
existing regulatory powers over broadcasting, they also said that
they did not favor censorship. Instead, they called on leaders in
entertainment companies to be self-regulating.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking to parents, the bishops said that parents share a
bond with their children ``that nothing else can replace no matter
how much, at any given moment, children seem to look elsewhere for
example and guidance.''
</P>
<P>
   Maniscalco said that in recent years, Keeler has been meeting
privately with top officials at Hollywood studios and television
networks to discuss some of these issues. ``We're in dialogue with
so many groups in society,'' he said, ``we thought we ought to be
in contact with these people who run these culture-forming
industries.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
