<SLUG> BC-WHITTAKER-HUGHES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUGHES ELECTRONICS PLANS TO DIVEST WHITTAKER SHARES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY ENRIQUE RIVERO  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIMI VALLEY, Calif. _ Hughes Electronics Corp. is selling the
107,841 shares of Whittaker Corp. stock it acquired in May,
according to Securities and Exchange Commission documents filed by
Whittaker.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes, based in El Segundo southwest of Los Angeles, received
the stock as royalty payments on sales that Whittaker was required
to pay as part of its purchase two years ago of the Hughes LAN
System division, which was renamed Whittaker Communications Inc.
and has since been discontinued, according to Whittaker officials
and the documents filed Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes' shares represent less than 1 percent of Whittaker shares
outstanding, which closed Friday at 13 3/64 (three-sixty-fourths),
up 3/64 (three-sixty-fourths). Whittaker, based in Simi Valley
northwest of Los Angeles, makes fluid control and fire safety
systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sale of the stock was part of a continuing re-evaluation
of the company's business plan,'' Hughes spokeswoman Marcy Garber
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Lexington, Mass.-based electronics giant Raytheon Co. sold its
entire 1.97 million shares of Whittaker stock on June 12 to Beverly
Hills-based investment group Canpartners Investments IV LLC for
$11.95 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Whittaker chairman and chief executive officer Joseph Alibrandi
said Whittaker Communications was shut down in early 1997. The
technical know-how that was left was sold along with Xyplex earlier
this year to Los Angeles-based MRV Communications Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes' sale of the stock is unlikely to have a negative effect
on Whittaker, Alibrandi said. Hughes has been talking to an
investment group that is interested in purchasing the stock, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's been done, but I'm pretty confident it
will be done,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He did not know the name of the group, and Garber refused to
identify the company.
</P>
</TEXT>
