<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YAC-BERMUDA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AND THEY'RE OFF FROM NEWPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT R.I. _ In picture-perfect weather across Rhode Island
Sound Friday, the largest fleet of boats in 16 years took off for
Bermuda in the biennial showcase of blue-water racing on the East
Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Led by four Maxis, which are concluding their world
championships, most of the 163-boat fleet enjoyed steady southwest
breezes that made the start a brisk and well-sailed spectacle.
However, the last two classes started in the teeth of an
approaching thunderstorm that deadened the wind.
</P>
<P>
   One of the four Maxis _ Sayonara, Morning Glory, Boomerang, and
Alexia _ is expected to take line honors, reaching St. David Light
on the tip of Bermuda 635 miles away tomorrow night. Boomerang
holds the record with a time of 57 hours 20 minutes. Two new Bruce
Farr 60s, Deep Powder and Rima, are also expected to make quick
time across a route that intersects the tricky Gulf Stream on its
eastward passage.
</P>
<P>
   The largest fleet ever was in 1982, when 178 boats entered, and
numbers dropped off dramatically through the '80s. But the fleet is
building up again.
</P>
<P>
   The Cruising Club of America and Royal Bermuda Yacht Squadron
host the historic race. In every off year, Beverly Yacht Club in
Marion hosts a detuned version of the race, sailed mainly by
amateur cruisers. Newport-Bermuda allows all means of high-tech
equipment and professional sailors and manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Two entries this year, Fei Hu III and Mackintosh, are Canadian
boats that sailed to the start from Toronto. According to George
Bauer, a race spokesman, these two sailed the most arduous route to
get to Friday's start _ through canals, lakes, the Hudson River,
and Long Island Sound.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the race will be monitored by the 117-foot
communications vessel Rainbow, which will release up-to-the-minute
standings over the World Wide Web at www.rbyc.bm/newportfinlog.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
