<SLUG> BC-SHORT-SALES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG BOARD POSTS 2.3 PERCENT RISE IN UNCOVERED SHORT SALES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Open positions of short sales on the New York Stock
Exchange increased 2.3 percent in the last month, to 4.02 billion
shares as of June 15, up from 3.93 billion a month earlier, the
exchange reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The new figure equaled 1.8 percent of all shares listed on the
Big Board.
</P>
<P>
   On the smaller American Stock Exchange, short interest rose 3.7
percent, to 196.5 million shares as of June 15 from 189.5 million
shares, the exchange reported.
</P>
<P>
   A short position is created when an investor sells shares that
have been borrowed. If the share price falls, the investor can
profit by buying shares at a lower price to replace the borrowed
ones.
</P>
<P>
   While an increase in short positions may indicate a rise in
bearish attitudes toward stock prices, the volume of short
positions can also be affected by complex trading strategies.
</P>
<P>
   The largest Big Board short position _ 78.6 million shares _ was
in Compaq Computer Corp. U S West Media Group showed the largest
decrease, to 3.8 million shares from 32.1 million in mid-May.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
