<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRS-OVERHAUL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS NARROWS DIFFERENCES IN IRS OVERHAUL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress moved closer Friday to final passage of
legislation that would overhaul the Internal Revenue Service, as
House and Senate negotiators resolved many of the differences in
the details of their bills.
</P>
<P>
   Several contentious issues remain unaddressed, including how to
pay for what would be the most sweeping changes to the agency in
decades.
</P>
<P>
   But members of both parties, eager in a congressional election
year to rein in what is perhaps the most unpopular of government
agencies, said they were optimistic that they could reach agreement
in time for the House to vote on final passage next week and for
the Senate to act right after the Fourth of July recess.
</P>
<P>
   The House passed its version of the legislation late last year,
and the Senate passed a broader and more expensive bill last month.
In negotiations this week that involved lawmakers of both parties
and the Clinton administration, all sides agreed to scale back some
of the Senate bill's provisions, people involved in the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would create an independent board to oversee the
agency, provide more legal protections for taxpayers engaged in
disputes with it and spur an internal reorganization to make it
more efficient and more responsive to taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin and Charles Rossotti, the
commissioner of internal revenue, issued a statement calling the
progress on the legislation ``a major step forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the changes to which negotiators agreed were a narrowing
of some of the protections the Senate bill would have granted to
taxpayers fighting collection actions and to so-called ``innocent
spouses'': taxpayers who maintain they were unaware of tax
avoidance or fraud by their husbands or wives.
</P>
<P>
   Those changes should save several billion dollars of the
estimated $18 billion cost of the Senate bill over 10 years, moving
the final legislation closer to the House version, whose estimated
10-year cost is $6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiators also agreed to adopt the Senate version's
approach to shifting the burden of proof in some tax-court cases
from the taxpayer to the IRS. The Senate version would impose a
less rigorous definition of the cooperation with the revenue
service that taxpayers would need to show in order to force the
agency to prove them liable. Under current law, the burden in such
cases rests on taxpayers, to prove that they are not liable.
</P>
<P>
   People involved in the negotiations said it remained unclear how
Congress would pay for the legislation's costs, which stem
overwhelmingly from revenue loss that would result from restricting
the IRS' power to pursue taxpayers with whom it is having disputes.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill would pay for many of its provisions by changing
the rules under which elderly people can shift money from one type
of individual retirement account to another. The change would
generate additional tax revenue over the next 10 years but would
cost the government billions after that, and Democrats have
criticized it as a substantial tax break for the wealthy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 2127EDT &QL; 
