<SLUG> BC-ASTRA-MERCK-NYT </SLUG>
  
 ASTRA TO BUY OUT MERCK IN VENTURE  (ja) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Astra A.B., the Swedish pharmaceuticals giant, announced Friday
that it would buy Merck &AMP; Co.'s half of their American joint
venture.
</P>
<P>
   The parting of the two companies, which will take at least 10
years, helps both companies. Hakan Mogren, Astra's chief executive,
announced in March that he would like to seek a merger, but Astra's
venture with Merck was a major hindrance.
</P>
<P>
   Merck, however, charged a high price. It will immediately stop
paying its share of expenses, but continue to pocket revenue from
the sale of Astra's existing products and those in the pipeline.
Astra can end Merck's revenue sharing by paying the company at
least $4.4 billion in either 2008, 2012 or 2016.
</P>
<P>
   The deal also gives Merck a revenue stake in the popular
Prilosec ulcer drug until 2017, provided sales of the drug remain
at a certain level.
</P>
<P>
   Merck will also pocket additional money if Astra should merge or
be acquired. If a deal occurs, Astra must pay Merck $675 million to
$1.5 billion. And as a sweetener to the deal, Astra agreed to lend
Merck $1.4 billion over 40 years at 6 percent interest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
