<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLD-KELLER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KELLER PROVES HE'S A KEEPER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; SAINT-JEAN d'ARDIERES, France _ In 1990, he was a tourist in
Tuscany, a college kid along for the ride with a passport and a
team bag. Four years ago, Kasey Keller watched the World Cup on
television, the third keeper on a roster that carried two.
</P>
<P>
   This time he's the iron man, all but certain to be occupying the
goal for every minute of every match. And on a team that has
struggled to score all year, Keller may well be the difference
between the US soccer team making it to the second round again or
packing for home next Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited to be given the opportunity,'' says Keller, who
probably will need to blank Iran tomorrow night in Lyon to keep the
Yanks alive. Keller thought he would get that chance in 1994 after
earning a rep as a zero-based guardian with Millwall in the English
First Division.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody thought Keller belonged on the roster except coach
Bora Milutinovic, the Spanish-speaking Serb mystic who went with
Tony Meola and Brad Friedel instead. For nearly three years while
he was piling up shutouts in southeast London, Keller didn't pull
on a US jersey.
</P>
<P>
   But as soon as Milutinovic was let go in 1995, Keller's phone
rang. Timo Liekoski wanted him as one of the overage players for
the Olympic team. And Steve Sampson wanted him for the national
squad. ``Both of them told me the same thing,'' Keller says. ``That
it was out of their hands in 1994 but that they thought I should
have been there.'''
</P>
<P>
   Keller, who grew up on an egg farm in Lacey, Wash., had been on
the radar screen since 1988, when he led the University of Portland
to the NCAA Division 1 Final Four as a freshman. He was 20, still
an undergraduate, when he made the 1990 Cup team and watched the
Yanks' three-and-out from the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd never played a pro game in my life,'' Keller says. ``But
it would have been OK if I'd played because I didn't know that I
shouldn't have been there.''
</P>
<P>
   Keller went straight from college to Millwall's crucible,
playing in the raucous ``Den'' on Cold Blow Lane before thousands
of profane fans penned into terraces behind him. Nobody quite knew
why the club had hired a Yank (``At the very beginning, it was,
`why?''' Keller says), but after he started 51 straight matches in
1992-93 and posted 16 shutouts, nobody in the Den was asking
questions. Instead, they chanted, ``U-S-A, U-S-A,'' whenever Keller
clamped his mitts around a ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you start to play, it doesn't matter if you're a
Martian,'' Keller realized. ``If you do a good job, you're
accepted.''
</P>
<P>
   When Keller played more than 100 matches the next two seasons
and hung up another 35 shutouts, he became part of the London
wallpaper. ``It's like it would be if I were in Seattle playing for
the Sonics,'' says Keller, who now plays for Leicester City in the
Premier League. ``You walk around town and everybody knows you. You
walk around another town and everyone knows you there, too. Rugby
has its niche and cricket has its niche, but in England, everything
is basically football. That's all you read in the papers, see on
TV, hear on the radio.''
</P>
<P>
   Keller and a lot of other folks figured he'd be a cinch to make
the US team for the 1994 Cup. But Milutinovic thought otherwise.
``Managerial decisions come and go,'' says Keller. ``There've been
a lot of players who play for one coach and not another. The only
one who knew was Bora, and I don't think you'd get it out of him.
Everyone else speculated.''
</P>
<P>
   Keller took his omission philosophically. ``It was win-win for
me, actually,'' he says. ``Most everyone thought I should be
playing and I didn't have to prove it. I was 24 years old. It
wasn't a big deal. I knew if I kept playing, I'd be given another
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Once Liekoski and Sampson rang him up, Keller was reborn. He
captained the Olympic team and played every minute. The Yanks were
5-1-3 (with six shutouts and 562 consecutive scoreless minutes) in
Cup qualifiers in which he kept goal.
</P>
<P>
   Keller blanked Mexico and Argentina in 1995. And he made five
saves on the legendary Romario in this year's historic 1-0 decision
over Brazil. ``That was the greatest performance I've ever seen by
a goalkeeper,'' Romario said. ``It was an honor to be on the field
with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Romario isn't here this time. He was sent home injured and
weeping days before the opener. Keller, who watched Romario on the
tube four years ago, is center stage now. He is no longer the
Tuscan tourist, no longer the third man out. This time Kasey Keller
has a passport, a team bag, and a full-time job.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
