<HEADLINE>
THE DREAM IS ENOUGH FOR LIU'S NEW COACH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Ind., Ohio, N.C.)   (bl)  
 By RON DICKER    c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Ray Martin received the telephone call informing him that
he would be Long Island University's new basketball coach, he
screamed. But during Friday's news conference at LIU, Martin was a
man of muted expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Martin said his goal was to win Northeast Conference
championships, a far cry from the Final Four aspirations voiced by
his predecessor, Ray Haskins, who resigned when his ambition grew
too big for the university.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's enough right now,'' the 43-year-old Martin said
of his objective. Martin signed a one-year contract, just like all
LIU faculty members, and will earn between $70,000 and $80,000.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, a native of Long Island City, Queens, starred at Mater
Christi High School in Astoria, Queens, before playing for Notre
Dame. His 18-year career as an assistant coach includes eight years
at North Carolina State and, most recently, two years at Miami of
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Martin has never been a head coach except for three games last
season when he took over for Miami Coach Charlie Coles, who became
ill. But John Suarez, LIU's athletic director, said Martin's
experience in the Atlantic Coast Conference and his familiarity
with New York clinched the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been through the wars,'' Suarez said. ``He won't get
frustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   LIU expects a difficult season after two years of more than 20
victories and two post-season appearances. The Blackbirds are
losing Charles Jones, the nation's leading scorer, and Mike
Campbell, the team's second-leading scorer. And one of the top
recruits, guard Devon Fowler of Philadelphia, has yet to meet
academic requirements.
</P>
<P>
   It was Haskins' gym-first approach that first created a conflict
with the administration. Asked whether she laid out academic
guidelines for the new coach, Gale Stevens Haynes, LIU's provost,
said: `'I didn't have to. He gave me a piece of who he is, not a
piece of what Gale wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin said he would first mine New York for recruits and slow
down Haskins' run-and-shoot scheme while still keeping an up-tempo
style.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we win, I don't mind,'' said guard Issiah Francis,
one of a handful of players who showed up to meet their new mentor.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, his wife, Valerie, and their four children, ages 6 to
16, have yet to begin house-hunting. Martin might hold off because
the July 8 start-date for writing letters to high school seniors is
approaching. But Martin, a career underling who will finally be the
boss, can wait for the house part. He is home. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `'It's a dream come true,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
