<HEADLINE>
PRESBYTERIANS ASK MEMBERS TO REMOVE HANDGUNS FROM HOMES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for minor rewrite of lede graf; changes vote tally from `4-1'
to `more than 3-1' in 2nd graf; minor rephrasing in several
places)  
 (ATTN: N.C., Kan., Ohio, Va., Calif.)   (mk) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a strikingly strong statement on individual responsibility
and guns, the top policy-making body of the Presbyterian Church
(U.S.A.) has passed a resolution calling on the denomination's 2.6
million members to begin removing handguns and assault weapons from
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution, passed by more than 3-1 at the church's annual
General Assembly late Thursday afternoon, follows a three-decade
stream of declarations by several major Protestant, Roman Catholic
and Jewish organizations favoring restrictions on handguns and
assault weapons.
</P>
<P>
   But Presbyterian officials and other church leaders said the
assembly's resolution took a different tack in asking for
individual action by church members, rather than seeking a purely
legislative remedy.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution, which comes after recent shootings at schools
around the country, says the General Assembly should ``call upon
all Presbyterians to intentionally work toward removing handguns
and assault weapons from our homes and communities,'' adding that
church members should ``develop community strategies and create
sanctuaries of safety for our children.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Its new ground is in speaking directly to Presbyterians to do
something,'' said the Rev. Kathy Lancaster, a Presbyterian official
who specializes in criminal justice issues.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Joan Brown Campbell, general secretary of the National
Council of Churches, said, ``It's taking this very serious issue
and bringing it home.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that some of the boys and youths accused in the recent
school shootings had been involved in local churches, Dr. Campbell
said, ``Maybe we're not doing all we could as church people to
teach people a lifestyle of living nonviolently.''
</P>
<P>
   The Presbyterians' resolution is strictly advisory, rather than
binding. Nonetheless, it stirred up about 40 minutes of debate in
the General Assembly, an annual eight-day gathering that is winding
down at the Charlotte, N.C., Convention Center. The resolution was
favored by 393 commissioners, or delegates, while 120 voted against
it.
</P>
<P>
   An amendment that would have modified the resolution's language
by removing the reference to handguns was defeated 361 to 144.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Ward, a commissioner from Wichita, Kan., who spoke in favor
of the amendment, said in an interview after the vote that ``our
church is treading on something that's legal and trying to say to
all of us who use shooting as a sport'' that that sport is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution does not mention rifles, shotguns or hunting. In
1990, the assembly adopted a resolution calling for handgun control
but said the statement was not intended to ``disparage the
legitimate ownership and use of firearms'' for hunting, collecting
and recreational sports. Others at the assembly who opposed the
amendment described it as a ``feel-good'' measure that would have
little practical effect.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Harley, a lawyer from Springfield, Ohio, said, ``If you
look into history, you'll see the first thing totalitarian
dictatorships have done is disarm its citizenry.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ann Holt, a retired teacher from Raleigh, N.C, who voted for
the amendment, said it was ``the church's responsibility to make a
response'' to gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner who made the motion proposing the resolution
could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Asked for her response to the resolution, Tanya Metaksa, chief
lobbyist for the National Rifle Association, said that the NRA was
sorry that the Presbyterian assembly ``would suggest to their
parishioners that self-defense is no longer an option.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Metaksa said that 2.5 million times a year, a firearm is
used for self-defense, ``and 95 percent of those times no shot is
ever fired, but people's lives are saved.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although critics have accused the church's leadership of being
liberal-leaning, Presbyterians are an ideologically diverse group.
Lately they have waged a fierce internal fight over whether to
allow the ordination of homosexuals as ministers, elders and
deacons. In 1997 the church amended its constitution to bar such
ordinations by declaring that those who are ordained must be either
monogamous within marriage or celibate as unmarried people. An
effort to soften the amendment's language failed earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess is we're a slice of middle America,'' said the Rev.
Douglas Oldenburg, a seminary president who was elected last
Saturday as the denomination's moderator, one of its top officials.
``I have no idea what percentage of us have handguns _ probably
more than I'd wish.''
</P>
<P>
   The church has long been among the religious groups that favor
restricting access to handguns and, most recently, assault weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these declarations date to 1968, when the Rev. Dr.
Martin Luther King Jr. and Sen. Robert Kennedy were assassinated.
But some were issued in 1975, after two attempted assassinations
against President Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Others have come more recently, with the rise in urban violence
and drug abuse in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, a committee of Catholic bishops in the United States
called for ``effective and courageous action to control handguns,
leading to their eventual elimination from our society.'' The
bishops reaffirmed that statement in 1992 in a pastoral message on
substance abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Also in 1975, the Union of American Hebrew Congregations, which
represents about 800 Reform synagogues, called for eliminating the
manufacture, sale and possession of handguns except for use by
police, the military and licensed gun clubs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the United Church of Christ's General Synod asked for
legislation requiring safety devices on guns.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago the United Methodist Church, building on earlier
statements, recommended that the denomination's churches be
designated as ``no gun zones,'' prohibiting all firearms. The 1990
Presbyterian statement, which focused on handguns and assault
weapons, criticized the entertainment industry for the
``glorification of violence.''
</P>
<P>
   In interviews Friday, Presbyterians at the assembly expressed
differing opinions about the resolution. The Rev. Thomas Nance Jr.,
a Richmond, Va., minister who described himself as being ``on the
right wing of things,'' said he voted for the resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just too much violence and we have to do some things
to insure the safety of people in this country,'' Nance said.
</P>
<P>
   But Arlynn Barner, a Los Angeles real estate salesman who voted
against the resolution, said, ``I would feel uncomfortable without
a handgun in my home for protection.''
</P>
<P>
   Oldenburg, the moderator, said he voted for the resolution.
``Will it make a difference? Who knows?'' he asked. But he added,
``Now it's up to individual Presbyterian families to follow the
counsel, the advice, of this assembly or not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
