<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8205 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-HUNDLEY-290&AMP;     06-19 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-HUNDLEY-290&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNDLEY GETS NO-TRADE DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the last month, Todd Hundley has lost his catching
job to Mike Piazza, been asked to learn a new position, nearly
completed his rehabilitation from elbow surgery and read that some
in New York Mets management are concerned about his work and
drinking habits.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Mets did what they could to temper the tumult
surrounding Hundley's season. At his request, the Mets agreed to
include a no-trade provision in Hundley's contract for the rest of
the 1998 season. This clause, according to general manager Steve
Phillips, grants Hundley ``peace of mind.''
</P>
<P>
   But the agreement also represents a compromise. Hundley feared
being traded to a team with a losing record, but the Mets did not
want to give him a no-trade clause for the entire length of his
contract, which runs through the 2000 season. The Mets wanted a way
out should Hundley's attempt to remake himself into an outfielder
fail.
</P>
<P>
   So, during the remaining two years of Hundley's contract _ and
during the 2001 season should the Mets pick up the option year of
the contract _ the Mets granted Hundley a limited no-trade clause.
In essence, Hundley and the Mets said Friday, Hundley can veto a
trade to only about half of the teams in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I am traded,'' Hundley said in a conference call Friday.
``I have the option to make sure it's to a contender.''
</P>
<P>
   Seth Levinson, Hundley's agent, said that while the list of
teams Hundley could agree to be traded to would change at various
times during the years covering the new agreement, the list would
be generally defined by the teams' winning percentages.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fairly simple,'' Levinson said. ``You can look at the
standings and figure it out.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the meantime, Hundley continues to work on his skills in the
outfield, where Phillips said Hundley would play when he returns to
the Mets lineup probably sometime following the All-Star Game
break, July 6-8. Hundley is taking daily batting practice, throwing
to restore strength to his rebuilt right elbow and shagging fly
balls in both left and right field at the Mets complex in Port St.
Lucie, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun,'' Hundley said. ``It's challenging and not as easy
as I thought it would be. But I know I'm a good enough athlete to
make the switch.''
</P>
<P>
   While Hundley may be a defensive risk in the outfield, he can
only help the team's offensive production there. None of the
regular Mets outfielders has more than nine home runs, and entering
Friday night's game with the Florida Marlins, Bernard Gilkey had
the highest batting average at .251.
</P>
<P>
   And Gilkey was out of the lineup, recovering from an injury
suffered when he was hit by a pitch above his left eye a week ago.
Another outfielder, Butch Huskey, is also sidelined with soreness
in his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you move away from home plate, the transition usually gets
easier,'' manager Bobby Valentine said, assessing Hundley's chances
of succeeding in the outfield. ``It would be impossible for someone
to learn to be a catcher at this stage, and the next toughest thing
is coming from the outfield to the infield. I think Todd can do it.
He's a good athlete, and I hear he's working hard on the switch.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Hundley's no-trade clause, Phillips said it was one step in a
long-term effort to make sure Hundley remains a Met and is
comfortable taking his place in the same lineup as Piazza, the
All-Star catcher the Mets obtained four weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the right thing to do,'' Phillips said. ``And it gives
Todd some control over his destiny beyond this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, however, was emphatic that there would be no
competition between Piazza and Hundley for the catcher's job _ even
if Piazza signs a contract to return to the Mets next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's unrealistic,'' Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza said he was happy for Hundley.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can only help us,'' he said. ``And if that's what Todd
wants, I'm glad for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley, asked whether Friday's no-trade agreement assuaged any
of the bitterness he felt last month when the team's management
leaked its concern about how much he was drinking, said the
no-trade provision was not a response to that episode.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about me feeling I've been wronged,'' Hundley
said. ``I might quite possibly not fit in on this team next year,
and this is a way for me to control my options.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
