r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JUNTEENTH-COLONY-TEX     06-19 0503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUNTEENTH-COLONY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMANDONED TEXAS COMMUNITY BEGUN BY FORMER SLAVES WILL AGAIN COME TO
LIFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARY SALTARELLI 
c.1997 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRANBURY, Texas _ A Hood County community settled more than a
century ago by former slaves will celebrate Juneteenth on Saturday
for the first time in more than 60 years.
</P>
<P>
   The last resident moved away in the late 1930s, and all that
remains of The Colony, nine miles southwest of Granbury, is an old
cemetery with 75 to 100 graves, many of them unmarked. It had been
unkept for several years until about 100 volunteers began restoring
it in March of last year.
</P>
<P>
   But some still recall the Juneteenth celebrations _
commemorating the day that Texas received word of the signing of
the Emancipation Proclamation _ that were held when the community
was thriving.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used to spend the night before barbecuing,'' recalled
Marvin Allen, 71, of nearby Fort Worth, whose father was pastor of
the community's Methodist church.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next day they would have ballgames. It was a good
celebration. Folks would come from Cleburne, Stephenville,
Granbury, anywhere from probably 100 miles. There were at least 200
folks there in its heyday.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's celebration will be from 9 a.m. to 6 p.m., with a
barbecue lunch from 1 to 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Perkins, president of The Colony Cemetery Committee, which
is hosting the celebration, encouraged those who have recollections
of the historic community to attend and share their memories.
</P>
<P>
   Allen, whose father is buried at the cemetery, said he plans to
attend and hopes to see other descendants of former residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will serve a two-fold purpose,'' Allen said of the
celebration. ``It's kind of like a family reunion and it's a
community get-together, getting out and getting to meet folks.''
</P>
<P>
   The cemetery was neglected for several years after its
caretaker, R.D. Edwards, was killed in a car accident in 1991. He
had been the last resident to move away from The Colony in the
1930s, but periodically returned to clean the cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   The cemetery committee hopes to obtain Texas Historical Markers
for the cemetery and for the original settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins said The Colony _ not related to the modern-day Denton
County city of the same name _ was forgotten for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knew anything about it,'' he said. ``All of the sudden,
it's come to life again.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Goin, vice president of the cemetery committee, said
residents of The Colony helped build Granbury's old limestone
structures and were instrumental in rebuilding the nearby town of
Tolar after a devastating fire in the early 1900s.
</P>
<P>
   Allen said he is pleased that Granbury residents are working to
preserve the old cemetery and the traditions of the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it hadn't been for them, it would have gone on and nobody
would be left to tell the tale,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 2135EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980619.0427 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8208 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BERKSHIRE-GENERAL-ART     06-19 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERKSHIRE-GENERAL-ART-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUFFETT TAKES GENERAL RE INTO HIS FOLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.)  
(lb) 
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Warren Buffett added to his vast financial empire Friday, buying
the largest U.S. reinsurance company for $21.7 billion in stock.
Reinsurance companies specialize in covering the risks of other
insurers.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of General Re Corp. by Buffett's investment
company, Berkshire Hathaway Inc., sharply expands his presence in
insurance. General Re, based in Stamford, Conn., would join a
stable of insurers that includes Geico, National Indemnity and
stakes in several other companies.
</P>
<P>
   For Berkshire, a phenomenally successful investment vehicle,
General Re offers an additional $24 billion in stock and bond
investments held by the insurer. And while General Re is already
the world's third-largest reinsurer (after Munich Re and Swiss Re,
both European companies), a combination with Berkshire Hathaway
would give it more capital so that it could provide greater
coverage and expand its operations around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are creating a Fort Knox here,'' Buffett said Friday at a
New York news conference. ``Previously, General Re has been limited
in how much business they have been willing to take on. Now they
will be a position to do anything they want.''
</P>
<P>
   Buffett is known for not overpaying for companies, and analysts
said he paid in the low range of what other recently acquired
reinsurance companies have fetched.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say it was a bargain,'' said James English, the
senior property and casualty analyst with J.P. Morgan Securities,
``but I think what he paid was reasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   Reinsurance can be an extremely profitable business. Reinsurers
promise, in effect, to cover much of the claims of their clients _
other insurance companies _ for a relatively small portion of the
premiums collected from corporations and individuals. And they
agree to pay if the insurance companies suffer huge losses. But
huge losses are rare, and often the reinsurers have little to pay
out.
</P>
<P>
   General Re's revenue of $8.25 billion last year was down
slightly from $8.30 billion in 1996, and Ronald Ferguson, the
chairman and chief executive, said in May that revenue was not
expected to grow this year. But analysts said this reflected a
trend toward lower prices for corporate insurance and did not
suggest a company in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``General Re is certainly an exceptional franchise,'' said Alan
Murray, a senior analyst with Moody's Investors Service, the
credit-rating agency.
</P>
<P>
   The merger was announced after the close of the market Friday.
But in after-hours trading, the Class A shares of Berkshire
Hathaway, the highest-priced stock on the New York Stock Exchange,
rose $1,900 to $80,900. General Re shares jumped $51.50 to $275.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal, General Re shareholders will
receive the equivalent of $276.50 in Berkshire Hathaway stock for
each of their shares.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations for the deal were conducted chiefly between
Buffett and Ferguson, who have known each other for 10 years, with
little help from bankers and lawyers outside their organizations.
They started talking about a year ago, Buffett said. The talks
broke off, and resumed about a month ago.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In addition to insurance, Berkshire Hathaway's holdings range
from H.H. Brown Shoe Co., the leading North American shoemaker, to
interests in jewelry and furniture stores, substantial stakes in
Coca-Cola Co., and Gillette.
</P>
<P>
   Among its insurance holdings, National Indemnity is heavily
involved in providing coverage to other insurers against
catastrophes like hurricanes and earthquakes. Buffett said National
Indemnity would complement General Re, which also takes on high
risk but provides a great deal of coverage to back up claims made
by large and medium-size corporations, a business without great
volatility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm almost certain the two companies will write significantly
more business together than they would if they operated
separately,'' Buffett said.
</P>
<P>
   Buffett said he did not have ``lots of great ideas or even lots
of good ideas'' on how to invest the new money that would be
available through General Re.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he said, ``there will be a time when we do have a good
idea, and when we do, we will deploy all the money we can get our
hands on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
