<HEADER>
A8212 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-U.S.-HEJDUK-NYT &LR;      06-19 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-U.S.-HEJDUK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEJDUK AND U.S. SOCCER TEAM HAVE GOALS IN COMMON
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This story, which was sent and held Thursday, is now
restored.)  
(ja) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAINT-JEAN D'ARDIERES, France _ He wears his hair to his
shoulders. He proposed to his wife in the Pacific Ocean surf,
holding her with one hand and his surfboard with the other. Even
into last year, Frankie Hejduk struggled to determine whether his
profession would be surfing or soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen months ago, this free spirit was kicked off the U.S.
soccer team for missing a team flight to China. But his searing
speed, boldness in attack and renewed dedication have won him a
place on the World Cup squad. He provided the only scoring chance
in Monday's humbling 2-0 loss to Germany, and is expected to start
Sunday's crucial match against Iran in Lyons.
</P>
<P>
   When given the nod at halftime on Monday, with the U.S.
trailing, 1-0, Hejduk (pronounced HAY-duck) searched for something
to wrest his team from its timid start. Baseball players break out
the rally caps, but soccer players don't wear hats, so Hejduk went
to his rally shorts, turning his game pants around, number facing
the back.
</P>
<P>
   The night before, he had practiced his trademark reggae dance in
his hotel room, just in case he scored a goal. And nine minutes
into the second half he launched a diving header that appeared to
be a certain score, only to be thwarted by a desperate reach from
the German goalkeeper, Andreas Kopke.
</P>
<P>
   Against Iran, the Americans will again need his assertive
efforts to get behind what is considered a penetrable defense. Goal
scoring figures prominently in the tie-breaker system used at the
World Cup. The Americans feel they must win by at least two goals
on Sunday and win or draw against Yugoslavia next Thursday to have
any chance of advancing to the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Hejduk is expected to replace Mike Burns at right wing in
midfield, and Coach Steve Sampson is considering whether to play
with two forwards instead of one. The idea is that the Americans
must be aggressive from the beginning and not lie back as they did
against Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Politics continue to swirl around this game. But politics don't
seem to resonate in the slightest with the 23-year-old Hejduk. He
was only 5 in 1979 when the Americans were taken hostage at the
U.S. embassy in Tehran.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he knew about the Great Satan appellation given to the
United States by Iran's conservative clerics, Hejduk said blankly,
``What's that?''
</P>
<P>
   He had much the same incredulous reaction in January 1997, when
he did not hear his watch alarm, and he missed a team flight to
China. Infuriated, Sampson dismissed Hejduk from the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was finished,'' Sampson said.
</P>
<P>
   Hejduk said that, at the time, he wasn't sure whether he
preferred soccer over surfing. A native of Cardiff, Calif., he had
been a state surfing champion in high school. But his parents
convinced him that a soccer scholarship to UCLA was not an
opportunity to be wasted. Nor, he later realized, was a chance to
play in the 1998 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know whether I wanted to do this for a living or not,
but it kind of woke me up,'' Hejduk said of the China trip.
</P>
<P>
   Several months later, Hejduk and Sampson met to clear the air.
</P>
<P>
   Marriage and the birth of a young son have brought maturity and
discipline to Hejduk, according to Sampson, who granted him a
second chance. And Hejduk says he now sets six alarm clocks instead
of one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not just doing it for me anymore,'' Hejduk said of his
family. ``Now I have someone to support and be a role model for.''
</P>
<P>
   His biography was not included in the 1998 soccer team media
guide. But Hejduk intrigued Sampson with his tireless running in a
1-0 victory over Brazil in February and scored in a 3-0 exhibition
victory over Austria in April. Then he missed the final four World
Cup tuneups with a hamstring injury and was nearly cut from the
team.
</P>
<P>
   Healthy again, he remains one of the few real American threats
with his ability to sprint ceaselessly down the wing. Except,
perhaps for Cobi Jones, no one on the team can match Hejduk's
enduring speed. And few demonstrated the absolute fearlessness that
he showed against Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a lack of concern about who's on the other side,''
Sampson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 2145EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980619.0430 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8213 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HABITAT-HOUSTON-HNS &LR;      06-19 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HABITAT-HOUSTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEARS OF JOY FLOW FREELY AT COMPLETION OF 100 HABITAT HOMES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JAMIE STOCKWELL 
and SHANNON WRIGHT 
1998c. Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sha Lyn Lewis said she would try not to cry. But the tears
flowed anyway at the dedication Friday of her new home, one of 100
built by Habitat for Humanity for the 1998 Jimmy Carter Work
Project.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a lot of emotions right now,'' said Lewis, who, with a
friend, will move into the new house in near northeast Houston next
week. ``I'm excited. I'm really thankful. I serve a good God.''
</P>
<P>
   She was hardly alone in her excitement as dozens of sweaty,
paint-speckled volunteers gathered at the front of the house to
joke about the hard work and heat and congratulate each other on a
job well done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw people I see every day at work, and this week I saw a
different side of you,'' said volunteer Steve Furbacher, a senior
vice president of the energy company that sponsored Lewis' house.
``We didn't come with experience, but we came with will. And I know
lots of us have things on our desks back at work, and the piles
have gotten a little deeper this week, but, if you're like me, the
work seems a little easier. We built a house. Now it's going to
become a home.''
</P>
<P>
   Billed as the largest Habitat for Humanity project, the Jimmy
Carter Work Project brought together nearly 6,000 volunteers, about
1,500 of them from across the country, to spend a week under the
blazing sun building affordable homes in Second and Fifth Ward area
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers, under the guidance of professional craftsmen and
Habitat staff, labored on every aspect of the houses, from framing
and siding to wiring and painting. Initially slowed a bit by the
sweltering heat and humidity, volunteers worked overtime to
complete the homes in time for the presentation to their new owners
Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Over on Sakowitz Street in east Houston, volunteers gathered on
freshly cemented driveways and held hands. Some sang ``Amazing
Grace'' and ``America the Beautiful.'' Others laughed and teased
each other as the last coats of paint were applied and grass and
trees were planted.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is really no other feeling that can match that of
handing the keys to the house to the new owner and seeing their
faces light up,'' said Mary Lou Bowman, a volunteer from Ft.
Lauderdale. ``To know in your heart that you've made a difference
is incomparable.''
</P>
<P>
   Former President Carter, who with wife Rosalynn worked alongside
the volunteers throughout the week, walked from door to door in the
newly refurbished east Houston neighborhood Friday, presenting each
new homeowner with a Bible and encouraging words.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives me great honor to present these houses to the new
homeowners. God bless you for your efforts,'' he said, shaking the
hands of Shaline and Wade Gibson as they stood on the sidewalk in
front of their new single-story, yellow house on Sakowitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are so proud,'' Wade Gibson said. ``Much love to everyone
who put their heart into this.''
</P>
<P>
   Each of the new owners was required to put his or her own back
into the construction for 300 hours of ``sweat equity'' in order to
qualify for the small three- and four-bedroom homes. The new owners
buy the houses from Habitat for Humanity with no-interest mortgages
of up to $46,000.
</P>
<P>
   The 100 new houses almost doubles the number of Habitat for
Humanity homes built in Houston since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Though the project officially ended Friday, some work remained,
including finishing the interiors, landscaping and inspecting the
100 new homes on Houston's east and near-northeast sides.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Saturday, volunteers and Habitat staff will inspect
the houses to ensure they are ready for move-in day, June 27.
</P>
<P>
   New homeowner, Tamara Franshaw, 36, said she was blessed to have
worked all week with many caring individuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just wonderful when you have people working together like
this, people you go to church with and work with,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Franshaw said she could hardly wait for her three daughters to
step inside their new home next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of love and heart was put into this,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And a lot of sweat. But volunteers said the sunburns and sore
muscles they endured could not compare to the deep gratification
they felt from doing something for someone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next to giving birth and getting married, it's the next most
emotional experience of my life,'' said volunteer Kimmy Hallman.
``I have caught the mission of Habitat and what it stands for and
the impact it has left on me will stay with me forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, volunteers and new homeowners convened again to
attend an ecumenical service at First Baptist Church of Houston and
a volunteer celebration at the Transco Tower's Wall of Water.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
