<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HABITAT-FOUNDER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HABITAT FOUNDER HAS TAKEN ON `GOD'S WORK' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN MAKEIG 
1998c. Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a near-divorce that inadvertently propelled Alabama
attorney and businessman Millard Fuller into a Christian ministry
that since the 1960s has erected thousands of homes for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Linda, had left him, gone to New York. He traveled
there for a reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   When that succeeded, the Fullers sold their direct-mail company
and he quit practicing law in Montgomery, Ala. They simply gave
away their $1 million proceeds to Christian ministries and small
colleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went looking for what would be God's work,'' he explained
Friday as his latest project _ the Habitat for Humanity effort to
build 100 homes in a week in Houston with 6,000 volunteers sweating
out 100-degree days _ was approaching an end.
</P>
<P>
   His debut at building homes for the impoverished came in 1969 in
southwest Georgia. He helped a man and his family replace their
shack.
</P>
<P>
   The recipient signed his new mortgage with an ``X.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that man's daughter is an attorney in Washington, D.C., and
Fuller considers that small beginning a sort of lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``A house is a foundation on which a family can grow,'' said
Fuller, 63, a tall, thin grandfather of four.
</P>
<P>
   The experience started what since has grown into a veritable
unending crusade to put up simple houses.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 60,000 have gone up worldwide in numerous places. And
with Fuller as president of Habitat for Humanity International
based in Americus, Ga., and employing more than 400, thousands more
houses are coming.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of them are similar to the 1,100-square-foot,
three-bedroom houses being finished in Houston this week. The many
erected in African countries are much more humble _ a couple of
rooms, no indoor toilets or kitchens, total cost $2,000 or less.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, at least, Fuller and his workers have been
unmolested by the government. In Uganda, the military confiscated
their trucks to haul corpses away from battlefields _ a problem
Fuller's best known volunteer, former President Jimmy Carter, was
able to solve with one telephone call.
</P>
<P>
   Fuller considers the Houston project a success, despite some
personnel not arriving on time, minor thefts from three work sites
and numerous volunteers ailing from the relentless heat.
</P>
<P>
   Friday evening's end of the marathon project did not mean Fuller
can take a break to rest up. He leaves Saturday for Boston, makes
other stops for speeches and fund-raisers, and by July 10 will be
off for Asia for more work on homes in Sri Lanka, South Korea and
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   By next March he will be in the Philippines where 250 more homes
will go up.
</P>
<P>
   And the list continues, edging toward his goal of simply
eliminating poverty housing entirely.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
