<DOCNO> NYT19980619.0436 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8220 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CONSTRUCTION-LICEN     06-19 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CONSTRUCTION-LICENSING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI SEEKS STRICTER LICENSING FOR CONSTRUCTION COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SELWYN RAAB   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Having declared victory in campaigns against
corruption at garbage-carting companies and in the Fulton Fish
Market, the Giuliani administration now has its sights on another
target: New York City's giant $24 billion construction industry.
</P>
<P>
   In a proposal to be submitted Monday to the City Council, Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani will ask for the power to determine through
licensing regulations which companies are fit to work on public or
private construction projects in the city. Contractors could be
denied licenses if they were found to ``lack good character,
honesty and integrity'' _ a broad standard that includes
criminality, ties to organized crime, tax delinquency and a record
of poor workmanship.
</P>
<P>
   If enacted, the legislation is expected to have far-reaching
effects on a huge industry with more than 9,000 companies and
90,000 workers who are responsible for projects ranging from the
erection of skyscrapers to modest renovations in apartment
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said Friday they were proposing the
licensing procedure because they believe that persistent corruption
within the industry has elevated the cost of construction in the
city. Industry officials said they had not seen the mayor's plan
and declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the proposal is a five-member New York City
Construction Commission, appointed by the mayor, with broad
regulatory and investigative powers. Several large cities and
scores of states, including New Jersey and Connecticut, have
limited forms of regulation, but none as extensive as the
administration proposes for New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Under current laws, the city has virtually no licensing controls
over companies that do private construction work. A contractor is
required only to obtain a permit from the Buildings Department
certifying that its plans comply with the city's zoning and
building codes.
</P>
<P>
   The city, however, can bar a construction company from obtaining
municipal contracts on grounds that the company is considered
professionally unqualified or that its officials lack integrity _
for example, if they have financial ties to organized-crime
figures.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials say that abuses are still rife in the
industry despite numerous law enforcement crackdowns over the last
20 years against mobsters, dishonest contractors, corrupt union
officials and city inspectors who took bribes to overlook
violations. According to the officials, the costs of construction
in the city are 35 percent above the national average and they
attribute most of the inflated prices to bid-rigging and other
corrupt practices.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also takes aim at contractors with poor safety records.
Officials cited the deaths of two pedestrians this year who were
struck by falling bricks, and the extensive problems caused last
year by crumbling walls in a midtown office building, as evidence
of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill is about accountability,'' Randy Mastro, the deputy
mayor for operations, said in an interview Friday. ``It is also
about higher standards and personal and professional integrity in
an industry that has been plagued by corruption and safety problems
in the recent past and over many decades.''
</P>
<P>
   Mastro said he felt the city's proposal is on firm legal footing
since similar mechanisms for regulating the waste-carting industry
and the Fulton Fish Market have survived legal challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has credited the tough licensing policies for
eliminating Mafia influence in the businesses, for increasing
competition and for sharply lowering private garbage-removal costs
and the wholesale prices of seafood.
</P>
<P>
   The past initiatives of the mayor, a Republican, were swiftly
approved with strong support from City Council Speaker Peter
Vallone, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani and Vallone are now locked in an acrimonious budget
dispute and Vallone's support for the construction-industry bill
was not evident Friday. In a terse statement, he said that the
mayor's office had not consulted him about the bill and that he was
unaware of its contents.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, what we want is a bill that goes after corrupt
businesses and does not hurt honest business people,'' Vallone
said.
</P>
<P>
   By seeking to regulate construction companies, the
administration will be tackling a politically more powerful and
affluent industry than trash haulers and fish merchants, who
opposed the attempts to monitor their businesses and investigate
their backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   The heads of construction-industry trade associations said they
knew that a bill was being prepared but they declined to comment
until they could study its actual language.
</P>
<P>
   But some industry leaders, speaking on the condition of
anonymity, said the proposal would likely be seen by some in the
business as costly intrusions in enterprises that are vital to the
city's economic health.
</P>
<P>
   The trade association officials said corruption and the
influence of organized crime was not pervasive and that
construction prices in the city were elevated by labor costs and by
congestion that delays deliveries of equipment and supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Under the mayor's proposal, the licensing commission would have
the following powers:
</P>
<P>
   _ To conduct background investigations and the fingerprinting of
the principal officers and investors of companies applying for
licenses.
</P>
<P>
   _ To examine the financial and tax records of company officials
and investors.
</P>
<P>
   _ To deny licenses to companies affiliated with organized-crime
figures or who employ subcontracting companies that the commission
finds unfit for licenses.
</P>
<P>
   _ To demand as a condition of licensing that a company hire an
independent auditor and monitor approved by the commission to
oversee the company and to guarantee its integrity and fitness to
operate in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials who violate commission regulations would be
subject to misdemeanor charges and fines of up to $10,000 and six
months in jail.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal mandates that the commission phase in the licensing
by beginning with the 400 to 500 major contractors that have
obtained at least $3 million in contracts in the city in the last
year.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1980s, Giuliani, as the U.S. attorney for the
Southern District, and Mastro, as one of his top prosecutors, were
involved in the conviction of more than 30 Mafia leaders and
associates on racketeering charges involving multimillion-dollar
construction contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prosecutions alone have not solved the problem,'' Mastro said.
``As part of a long-term strategy, comprehensive regulatory reform
is needed to end the hidden `mob taxes,' and the end results will
benefit the public and businesses through lower building costs and
rents in the city.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
