<DOCNO> NYT19980619.0438 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8223 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TELE-COMMUNICATIONS-A     06-19 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELE-COMMUNICATIONS-ART-3TAKES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENIGMATIC ARCHITECT OF A CABLE RESURGENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Wash., Mass., Va.)   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.
Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 21)  
 (af)  
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What makes Leo run?
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 16 months, Leo J. Hindery Jr. has been the good
cop to John C. Malone's bad cop at Tele-Communications Inc., the
nation's second-largest cable operator.
</P>
<P>
   Since joining TCI in March of last year, Hindery has improved
the company's image on Wall Street by selling cable systems to
reduce its staggering debt. Delighted investors have shown their
approval by sending TCI's long-depressed stock up 149 percent since
the February 1997 announcement of his coming arrival.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, his assiduous schmoozing has won over even the
most vociferous critics of Malone's often arrogant style. ``I think
in a very short period of time, Leo has tried to deliver a
different kind of message about the company,'' said Andrew J.
Schwartzman, president of the Media Access Project, a public
interest law firm.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Hindery has accumulated a personal fortune of at
least $70 million, much of it from a huge TCI stock-option grant.
</P>
<P>
   But there is more to Hindery than the stick-figure portrayal of
a rich, hard-working president. Realistic as he has been in
tackling TCI's problems, when it comes to his own life he has the
puzzling habit of relating stories about the difficulties of his
childhood that are at odds with the accounts of his family members.
</P>
<P>
   At a 7 A.M. breakfast interview recently at the Waldorf-Astoria
Hotel in Manhattan, during one of his frequent business trips to
New York, the 50-year-old executive recounted how he had left home
at the age of 13 to fend for himself.
</P>
<P>
   His parents didn't bother looking for him, he said, because
``they didn't care if I left.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was cheaper having me out of the house,'' Hindery
continued. He said he lost touch with his family _ was ``living
with people,'' that ``the Jesuits got me through'' and that he
joined the merchant marine at age 16.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of his family, however, doesn't remember it that way.
In separate telephone interviews, Hindery's widowed mother, sister
and brother all said that Hindery lived at home until he graduated
from high school. His younger brother, Michael, a dean at Stanford
Medical School, remembers that when Leo Hindery was in his early
20s, he got his kid brother a job at the mining company where he
then worked, Utah International, based in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the Rev. William F. LeRoux, assistant dean for
university relations and Hindery's former professor at Seattle
University, Hindery's alma mater, said that in his recollection,
Hindery had remained close to his father throughout his college
years. Father LeRoux, Michael Hindery and his mother, Marie, could
not recall a stint by Leo Hindery in the merchant marine.
</P>
<P>
   Confronted with these discrepancies late last week, Hindery said
that his recollections of events that took place decades ago were
less benign than those of others, and he stood by his accounts of a
difficult childhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never exaggerate about that,'' he said. And he insisted that
he had spent several summers working on a ship called the U.S.S.
Avila off the Northwest coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The past hurts, and I don't like it,'' Hindery said.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham Zaleznik, Konosuke Matsushita professor of leadership
emeritus at the Harvard Business School, said storytelling is a
pattern among some American business leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Dramatized accounts of childhood might well reflect ``the need
to create a mythology about himself that may protect him from more
painful memories,'' Zaleznik said. Business luminaries including
Andrew Carnegie and Henry Ford, he said, have portrayed themselves
as ``the lonely figure who was hurt and injured and travels through
life, overcoming all travails to become a success.''
</P>
<P>
   That an executive might exaggerate his past could send up red
flags for an investor _ or spur confidence that his drive to
succeed could work for the benefit of his employer.
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, Hindery's energy seems well harnessed at
TCI, which among cable operators is eclipsed in size only by Time
Warner. His success in part may come from his skill in telling
people what they want to hear while maintaining his positions. And
he may have the ideal partner in Malone, TCI's chairman, who seems
to care little about what people think of his company.
</P>
<P>
   During Hindery's tenure, TCI has transformed itself from a
company that customers, investors and regulators loved to hate into
one of the more solid and image-conscious performers in the cable
industry.
</P>
<P>
   An incident at a cable-industry conference in Atlanta last month
illustrated the soothing effect the president has had in his role
as diplomatic counter to his blunt boss. Malone had just upset
congressional leaders and broadcasting executives by threatening to
drop all-news cable services if the federal government forced TCI
to carry high-definition television signals.
</P>
<P>
   But before another Malone-induced media imbroglio could move
into high gear, Hindery rushed out a conciliatory statement that
``no cable customer will be disenfranchised from receiving an HDTV
broadcast signal.''
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake: TCI was not suddenly caving in to public
pressure. But the company, which had rarely taken account of public
opinion until Hindery came on board, was finally showing some savvy
in playing industry politics. Hindery at least indicated that TCI
would continue a dialogue with the government about cable's role in
the HDTV business.
</P>
<P>
   Revamping TCI's image has been a gargantuan task. Malone, long
considered a brilliant strategist and technical expert, built TCI
into the nation's dominant cable operator by gobbling up cable
systems but investing less than many other operators in customer
services. Malone had no problem playing the corporate heavy, once
even declaring that Reed E. Hundt, then the chairman of the Federal
Communications Commission, should be shot.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
