<HEADER>
A8224 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN     06-19 0451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGENT: VAN EXEL EXPECTS TO GO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ A labor standoff and imminent lockout of players has
put a chill in the usually heated offseason swap meet of NBA
talents. But amid that uncertainty the Lakers are certain about
this much: They will attempt to trade point guard Nick Van Exel by
the time training camps open this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Executive vice president Jerry West made that much clear to Van
Exel's agent the day after the Lakers were eliminated from the
playoffs. All that remains is finding the right return package.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right after the playoffs, they said he was gone.... We've been
operating on that assumption since,'' said agent James Bryant of
Pro Serv.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers, as per usual policy, won't confirm West made the
statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry West had a conversation with James Bryant.... We're not
going to comment on what was said in those private conversations,''
Lakers spokesman John Black said.
</P>
<P>
   Talk of a Van Exel trade is as much a June tradition as Michael
Jordan chomping championship cigars, and yet Van Exel has weathered
several offseasons of such chatter.
</P>
<P>
   This time it sounds like more than just idle speculation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to happen,'' Bryant said. ``Who knows
where.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Where'' might be the sticking point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nick's not going to go to just any situation,'' according to
Bryant, and his objections to certain teams could potentially
scuttle a deal. Though the NBA does not allow no-trade clauses in
player contracts, a handful of coveted players _ notably Kenny
Anderson and Rony Seikaly _ worked trades in their favor this
season by refusing to report.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant didn't indicate Van Exel would follow that route, but
said any deal ``needs to be a mutually worked through situation,''
with input from Van Exel's camp. Bryant said he's not insisting on
a trade to a contender. He also figured a trade to the Eastern
Conference was likely _ ``I suspect Jerry West doesn't want him
somewhere where (Van Exel) can hurt (the Lakers).''
</P>
<P>
   Van Exel, 26, has one year remaining on a five-year, $10.5
million contract and poses both a bargain and a gamble to any
suitors. He's coming off his first All-Star campaign and led the
league in assist-to-turnover ratio, but finished the season with
just a 13.8-points-per-game average _ lowest since his rookie
season _ after undergoing right knee surgery in late February.
</P>
<P>
   Van Exel also has a chronically sore left knee and although he
never cited injuries as a factor, Van Exel struggled in the
playoffs, shooting 23.8 percent in the conference finals loss to
Utah.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 2156EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980619.0440 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8225 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TELE-COMMUNICATIONS-A     06-19 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELE-COMMUNICATIONS-ART-2NDTAKE-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: be shot.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``John is a kind of John Wayne,'' observed Hundt, who left the
commission last fall. ``He didn't see a lot of reason for the
government to be in his business.'' Malone declined to be
interviewed for this article.
</P>
<P>
   Hindery's more measured approach to both the government and the
balance sheet appears to be paying off. To consolidate operations,
he began to negotiate joint ventures with companies that had cable
systems adjacent to TCI's. The ventures offered their owners
economies of scale and let TCI focus more intently on its remaining
cable systems.
</P>
<P>
   Those deals, when completed, will let TCI reduce the debt on its
own balance sheet by $4.7 billion, or 32 percent, to $9.6 billion,
while still retaining a minority stake in the new companies.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the crucial ratio of debt to cash flow available to
make interest and debt payments is expected to fall to about 4.5 by
the end of the third quarter of 1998 from 6.1 at the end of 1996,
improving TCI's credit rating and making its borrowings less
costly.
</P>
<P>
   True, the creation of these joint ventures will also reduce the
number of TCI subscribers by 30 percent, to about 10 million. But
it will streamline operations, since TCI will have 60 percent of
its customers in 10 states, rather than sprawled across 24 states.
</P>
<P>
   Hindery boasts that he is a master of reading people. ``I know
people. I know them better than anyone knows them. I don't talk
about it much, but I never make mistakes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he isn't always so good at getting along with them. Before
going to TCI, Hindery founded various limited partnerships,
collectively known as Intermedia Partners, to invest in cable
systems. All three of his general partners left after disputes with
him, according to several people formerly associated with the
group.
</P>
<P>
   Hindery upset at least one of those partners by pressuring him
to reduce his stake in the partnerships, one insider said.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the former partners, Ed Allen and Ted Liebst, declined to
comment, and the third, David Rozzelle, did not return phone calls.
Hindery said simply that ``they left.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, though, Hindery has apparently established good rapport
with his underlings at TCI. A hard driver who puts in 15-hour days,
he has replaced 25 managers, mostly from within. To give employees
a stake in TCI's growth, he has nearly tripled the number of
nonofficers and nondirectors in the stock-option program to 440
people, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there were about three people in the option program
before,'' he said at the recent breakfast meeting _ the first of
three he held that morning.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps most important, Hindery throws himself into the task
of marketing TCI with unrestrained gusto. He can be as obsessive
about promoting the company as he is about selling himself.
</P>
<P>
   When an analyst at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter put out a lukewarm
report on the company, for example, TCI angrily responded by taking
away its investment banking business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Malone was never that sensitive, but Leo takes what an analyst
thinks of the stock as a personal thing,'' said one person close to
the situation. Hindery countered that Primestar Partners, a
satellite-TV consortium in which TCI is a member, has done business
with Morgan Stanley since the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his efforts have helped polish the cable industry's
image. Many people say the arrogance of the cable executives was at
least partly responsible for the Cable Act of 1992, which
reregulated the industry.
</P>
<P>
   By 1993, when Hundt took office at the FCC, 128 members of
Congress and a third of the Senate told him that the the first
round of cable price cuts were not adequate because the industry
had effectively lobbied for regulation with huge loopholes.
</P>
<P>
   Burdened by debt and government regulation, TCI's stock declined
from the end of 1993 to the start of 1997. Finally last year, as
the stock languished and pressure mounted on the company, Malone
himself brought Hindery aboard.
</P>
<P>
   He has proven a respectful subordinate. ``John has a great sense
of the industry and he sees things,'' Hindery said. ``He is
brilliant. I am clever. I am not as smart as John.''
</P>
<P>
   Diplomatic, yes; modest, no. ``I think we all have our strengths
and weaknesses,'' Hindery said. ``John can be anything he wants to
be, but it is better for us if I go run the company, and he figures
out where we are going to take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Malone, who avoided industry association roles, Hindery
has just been named head of the National Cable Television
Association. And he is far more willing than Malone to work with
Washington and community franchise boards.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Hundt recalled that last summer, during a weeklong
outing for media moguls organized by Allen &AMP; Co., the investment
banking firm, Hindery laid out to him TCI's plan for selling cable
systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked whether the FCC could work with it,'' Hundt said.
``He smoothed the way.''
</P>
<P>
   TCI, of course, has not entirely changed its spots. Hindery and
Malone are currently arguing with broadcasters on how much
bandwidth the broadcasters are entitled to for HDTV signals.
</P>
<P>
   But Wall Street clearly likes the new team. True, its stock's
149 percent surge since the announcement that Hindery was coming on
board has fallen short of the rival Cablevision Systems' 257.2
percent leap in that time, though it exceeds Comcast's doubling and
has kept pace with the overall market.
</P>
<P>
   More important, TCI has regained Wall Street's confidence. In an
event almost unimaginable five years ago, the Association for
Investment Management and Research in Charlottesville, Va., awarded
TCI a prize for the most improved investor-relations program in the
media industry last year. And there is an obvious effort to make an
immensely complex annual report clearer.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 2156EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980619.0441 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8226 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TELE-COMMUNICATIONS-A     06-19 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELE-COMMUNICATIONS-ART-3RDTAKE-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: report clearer.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hindery is in the office or on the phone by 5 a.m. and says he
doesn't need more than four or five hours' sleep a night. He
attributes that drive to his ``weird'' childhood in Tacoma, Wash.,
where, he said, ``I started paying for everything in my life when I
was 9 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to work in the fields, and I would give the money to my
family, partly because that was how my family worked and partly
because I was so mad at them,'' he continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a such a crummy childhood. You just can't know how cruel
my parents were. Nobody beat me, but there was just a total absence
of affection. I got a Christmas gift once. It was a belt, a size 38
belt. I weighed about 125 pounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Family members confirm that Hindery had a job picking berries at
the age of 9. But they describe his childhood as reasonably
structured, saying he held down such prosaic jobs as packing
grocery bags at a Safeway supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leo lived at home with us through high school and had the same
treatment and gifts,'' said Michael Hindery, who insisted that he
remained attached to his older brother for years after.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Hindery acknowledges that she has had her share of
emotional problems. In telephone interviews, she said she suffered
from the eating disorders of anorexia and bulimia, had low
self-esteem and was estranged from all three of her children.
</P>
<P>
   And both Hindery brothers agree that their parents, who had not
gone to college, insisted on hard work. ``I worked in shipyards
full time to put myself through school,'' Leo Hindery said. ``I
went to sea and I drove trucks, and I picked crops. I did every
crummy job.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Seattle University, he said, he attended
Stanford's business school, subsequently going to work for Utah
International, a mining company. After General Electric acquired
the company in 1976 (it has since sold it), he moved to Wall
Street, where he served as managing director and chief financial
officer of A.G. Becker Paribas, the investment banking firm.
</P>
<P>
   He entered the media world when he was hired by the Chronicle
Publishing Company in San Francisco, where he was chief financial
officer.
</P>
<P>
   Like many executives at the notably fractious Chronicle, his
performance at the media company got mixed reviews. Some members of
the Theriot family, which owns the company, felt he was too
ambitious, while others applauded him for helping to bring deal
making to the stodgy concern.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, he decided to go out on his own, and raised $200
million to buy cable systems through a series of partnerships,
creating Intermedia.
</P>
<P>
   Then, last year, Malone offered Hindery the chance to run TCI.
Hindery says he accepted because of his affection for Malone, whom
he knew through industry circles, and because he welcomed the
chance to straighten out the nation's second-largest cable
operator.
</P>
<P>
   Money wasn't a consideration, he says. Even so, there was
certainly a lot of it. First, Hindery sold his stake in
Intermedia's cable systems to TCI for $55 million in stock and
cash. Hindery left $20 million of that in the company, though with
strings attached to encourage employees and advisers to stay on and
run it.
</P>
<P>
   And at TCI, Hindery got himself a lucrative options grant. By
the company's own reckoning, his 4.425 million options were worth
$27.7 million when they were granted. Adding in two other grants
that were not valued, the executive-compensation expert Graef
Crystal estimates the total value at more than $35 million, making
Hindery the recipient of one of 1997's largest option packages.
</P>
<P>
   ``It couldn't have been more well deserved,'' Hindery said.
</P>
<P>
   If the stock has gone up since his arrival, it is in part
because Hindery works like a maniac, a style even his family can
find taxing. Hindery described himself as somewhat of an absentee
father to his teen-age daughter, and his wife said that living with
her husband was rather like having an eccentric uncle in the attic.
``You get used to it after a while,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Eccentricity might well be Hindery's defining characteristic,
driving both his need to perhaps embellish his life story and his
need to succeed. Indirectly, then, his very eccentricity seems to
have brought some management sanity to Tele-Communications. Whether
it will always play such a positive role is a harder call.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
