<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8227 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMITH-GLOBE-PROFILE-5     06-19 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMITH-GLOBE-PROFILE-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LACK OF TRUTH BRINGS A BOUNTY OF CONSEQUENCES
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In December, Patricia Smith was on top of this town,
her center-parted braids and half-smile dominating the cover of
Boston magazine's issue on the city's most intriguing women.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, Ms. Smith was winning ovations from hundreds of
adoring literati at the Taos Poetry Circus with her fiery
declamation of a poem about an 11-year-old gang member about to
die.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Ms. Smith was in disgrace, her brilliant journalism
career mourned by colleagues and admirers, her downfall gloated
over by enemies, after she was caught fabricating quotes and
characters in her Boston Globe columns.
</P>
<P>
   But the focus of scrutiny also moved Friday to Mike Barnicle,
The Globe's superstar columnist, whose tough-guy style and devoted
following recall the famed New York columnist Jimmy Breslin.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Dershowitz of the Harvard Law School said Friday in a open
letter to The Globe that were also serious questions about
Barnicle's credibility and that the newspaper's decision to demand
the resignation of Ms. Smith, who is black, and not Barnicle, who
is white, ``raises serious questions of a double standard, possibly
based on race, gender and ethnicity.''
</P>
<P>
   Dershowitz has accused Barnicle of falsely attributing a racist
and sexist remark to him in 1990. He said The Globe, which is owned
by The New York Times Company, did not dismiss Barnicle ``because
he's too valuable and he appeals much more to the core constituency
of The Globe than she does.''
</P>
<P>
   In light of Dershowitz's comments and the case of Ms. Smith, The
Globe has initiated a full review of columns by Ms. Smith and
Barnicle since January 1996, when the newspaper began a system
under which editors occasionally double check metropolitan
columnists' sources, a spokesman for The Globe, Richard Gulla, said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle failed to return telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith, 42, was also unavailable for comment Friday, said
Michael Brown, her husband and a fellow poet. It was not clear what
she would do next, he said. Asked in a brief telephone interview if
she would concentrate on a work-in-progress, a novel in poem form
about a young gang member, he said, ``It would be wrong to make
that inference at this stage.''
</P>
<P>
   What was clear, at this stage, is that her words will be deeply
missed by an array of colleagues and readers who valued her columns
championing blacks, Hispanic residents, the poor, women, gay men
and lesbians, AIDS patients and others.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith was the only black female columnist at a major Boston
newspaper, and colleagues say that though she often drew criticism
for writing too often or too outspokenly about race, she wrote with
widely acclaimed linguistic talent and drew attention to people
whose views are often ignored or discounted. She was a Pulitzer
Prize finalist this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find her enormously talented, and I believe that she had an
important voice in this market, in Boston,'' said Scott Powers,
arts editor at The Globe, who has known Ms. Smith for almost 15
years. ``There are a number of people here, including me, who
looked up to her tremendously _ as a creative person, as a
journalist, as an important voice and just somebody you felt you
could rally around.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Zachary Dowdy, president of the Boston Association of Black
Journalists, said, ``I think people feel as if they had lost a
friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Or an enemy. On WRKO radio, the conservative Boston Herald
columnist Howie Carr suggested Ms. Smith be called ``Patricia
Pinocchio Smith'' and said the departure of the ``preachy, pompous,
man-hating'' columnist made him so happy that he needed no Father's
Day present.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith reached her lofty columnist status from relatively
humble beginnings. She grew up lower-middle-class in Chicago,
daughter of a newspaper-loving father who was murdered when she was
20. At 21 she had a son by a man who later left her.
</P>
<P>
   She broke into journalism as a typist at The Chicago Daily News,
and her self-fueled career start, she wrote in her farewell column
Friday, could have contributed to the overdrive that led her to cut
corners: ``To make up for the fact that I didn't get that `correct'
start in journalism, I set out to be 10 times as good by doing 10
times as much,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But from the beginning, it seems, Ms. Smith also took some
poetic license with the truth. She told a jobs fair for minority
journalists this winter that she gained her first writing job on
the Chicago Daily News, reviewing music performances, by lying to
an editor and saying she had heard black people discussing a
boycott of the newspaper because it reviewed so few performances by
blacks, The Providence Journal-Bulletin reported earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, a review of an Elton John concert that she wrote for
The Chicago Sun-Times contained such inaccuracies _ including which
songs were performed _ that questions arose as to whether she had
attended at all. Powers, who was her superior at the time, said she
attributed the mistakes to inattention and other circumstances, and
he kept Ms. Smith, who was then only an editorial assistant and
aspiring reporter, from writing for a couple of months.
</P>
<P>
   But when, eight years later, Ms. Smith was being considered as a
columnist at The Globe, he did not bring that old gaffe up: ``I
don't believe it would have been fair to her or the paper to raise
the issue,'' he said. ``I regarded it as a lesson learned.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith's columns on Mondays and Fridays turned into some of
the most controversial and discomfiting writing in the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial of the British au pair Louise Woodward, for
example, she wrote that ``If Louise Woodward had been a black woman
accused of killing a white child, the public would have called for
the electric chair to be wheeled directly into the courtroom.'' And
concerning a dispute over development in Cambridge's Central
Square, she castigated ``slimy and greedy bottom-line visionaries
summarily raising their grubby middle fingers toward a community
they've vowed to destroy.''
</P>
<P>
   She also delved into accusations of racial discrimination in
Boston's public transit system, and offered slices of life from the
street that often reflected the opposite side of Boston from the
more white, Irish-American areas where Barnicle seems most
comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Even as she wrote two columns a week, Ms. Smith also gained
renown as a poet, publishing volumes of poetry and organizing
public readings at a Cambridge lounge.
</P>
<P>
   Her poetic habits of mind may have contributed to Ms. Smith's
willingness to blur the lines of truth, said Jeff Johnson, a copy
editor and friend of Ms. Smith at The Sun-Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a very creative person,'' Johnson said, ``and she
probably didn't consider that all the rules of journalism applied
to her.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
