<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKS END VOLATILE WEEK LOWER IN WAVES OF SELLING
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices fell again Friday as Wall Street ended a wild week
just the way it began: with waves of large-scale selling. Blue-chip
issues were hit the hardest and pulled down the Dow Jones
industrial average by 100.14 points, or 1.14 percent, to close at
8,712.87. Broader stock indexes also dropped.
</P>
<P>
   The declines partly reflected selling related to expiring stock
index and futures contracts. But traders said shares also weakened
for the same reasons that undermined stocks all week: economic
distress in Japan and the possibility of a deeper slump in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Open positions of short sales on the New York Stock Exchange,
which some traders view as a measure of bearish sentiment,
increased 2.3 percent in the last month.
</P>
<P>
   IMF WARNS RUSSIA ON AID
</P>
<P>
   The IMF has warned Russia that it does not plan to provide the
$10 billion to $15 billion in additional assistance that the
Kremlin is seeking. Russian officials say they need the extra money
to reassure investors, prevent the devaluation of the ruble and
stabilize the financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   ASTRA AND MERCK TO PART WAYS
</P>
<P>
   Astra, a leading Swedish pharmaceuticals company, will buy
Merck's half of their joint venture in a deal that could be worth
as much as $10 billion. Both companies stand to benefit from the
breakup of the alliance, which will take at least 10 years to
complete.
</P>
<P>
   JAPANESE BANKS DENY MERGER PLAN
</P>
<P>
   News reports in Japan said the government might merge two weak
banks, Long-Term Credit and Nippon Credit. The banks denied the
reports, but their shares jumped and led investors to believe such
mergers are planned as a way to strengthen the debt-troubled
Japanese financial system.
</P>
<P>
   CAMCO IN $3.1 BILLION DEAL
</P>
<P>
   Schlumberger agreed to buy a smaller rival, Camco International,
in a $3.1 billion stock swap. Camco, based in Houston, will operate
as a division of the leading oil-services company. Its stock rose
20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   GM CHAIRMAN SEEKS END TO STRIKE
</P>
<P>
   John F. Smith, the chairman of General Motors, called for a
speedy resolution of the two-week strike that has shut down
virtually all of the carmaker's North American assembly plants and
has idled more than 100,000 workers. But even as Smith sought labor
peace, the impact of the strike spread further, idling two more
plants and 5,000 additional workers. Analysts said a settlement and
resumption of production is unlikely before GM's annual two-week
shutdown, starting June 29.
</P>
<P>
   FIGHT LOOMS ON BRAZIL PHONE SALE
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilian government plans to proceed late next month with
the breakup and sale of Telebras, the giant telephone holding
company, in an $11.7 billion sale that would constitute the largest
privatization in Latin America to date. Opposition politicians are
not so enthusiastic, however, and are threatening legal action to
block or revoke the sale.
</P>
<P>
   INSURERS SAYING NO TO VIAGRA
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser Permanente, the United States' top nonprofit
health-maintenance organization, became the latest big health
insurer to decide that it will not cover Viagra, the
impotence-treatment drug, except as an extra benefit at additional
cost. Health insurers have said that providing the recommended six
to 12 pills a month would be too expensive, adding hundreds of
millions of dollars to annual costs.
</P>
<P>
   SWISS BANKS' OFFER REJECTED
</P>
<P>
   Switzerland's three biggest commercial banks offered $600
million to settle claims from Holocaust victims who have contended
that their families' assets were stolen. Jewish leaders immediately
rejected the offer as ``humiliating,'' and said negotiations had
broken down.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
