<SLUG> BC-NY-TAXIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC TAXI BOARD LIKELY VIOLATED OPEN MEETINGS LAW, JUDGE SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A state Supreme Court judge in Manhattan said Friday
that the Taxi and Limousine Commission apparently violated the
state's open meetings law when it met in private May 28 shortly
before approving most of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's strict package of
taxi safety rules, according to lawyers for both the city and an
industry group suing to overturn the rules.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers said Judge Franklin Weissberg said he would decide
by July 2 whether to throw out the commission's votes. If he did,
the commission would have to start the approval process over again
if it wanted to pass the rules. The judge also said that at least
one of the rules _ he did not say which _ seemed improperly vague,
lawyers on both sides said.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's 17 rules have been attacked by drivers and owners
since they were proposed in April. On May 28, after seven hours of
public testimony on the rules, the commissioners disappeared for an
hour. When they reconvened, they immediately voted to approve 15 of
the rules, including measures to increase sharply the amount of
insurance taxis and car services must carry and to suspend or
revoke cabbies' licenses much more quickly for violations.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the rules were modified during the recess. Votes on
two others, one requiring cab owners to post a $100,000 insurance
bond and the other cracking down on drivers, were postponed.
</P>
<P>
   Two industry groups representing fleet owners and taxi managers
said in a lawsuit that the votes were improper because the meeting
just before the vote, and several others, were in violation of the
open meetings law.
</P>
<P>
   The law, which requires nearly all meetings of public bodies to
take place in the open to insure that agencies stay accountable to
the public, gives judges wide discretion on whether to overturn
actions that may have been influenced by improper meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The city argued in court papers filed Friday that the
commissioners did gather in private several times during breaks on
the day of the vote but that the meetings addressed legal issues.
The open meetings law makes an exception for meetings protected by
attorney-client privilege. Three commissioners appointed by the
mayor filed affidavits in support of the city's side in which they
described the meetings.
</P>
<P>
   But according to both sides in the suit, Weissberg said that
nothing in those affidavits refuted an affidavit filed by another
commissioner earlier this month in support of the industry's suit.
</P>
<P>
   In that affidavit, Commissioner Alberto Torres swore that at
three different closed-door meetings in the course of the day, the
commissioners debated among themselves the merits of the rules and
discussed which rules they were ready to vote for and which should
be modified.
</P>
<P>
   Torres, who was appointed by Bronx City Council members, is one
of the five members on the eight-member commission who were not
appointed by Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   According to Merril Mironer, a lawyer for an industry group in
the suit, the Metropolitan Taxicab Board of Trade, which represents
15 fleet owners, Justice Weissberg said the meetings seemed likely
to violate the open meeting law and that the main question was
``what he should do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge, Mironer said, also asked what harm would be done if
the votes were set aside and the measures considered anew.
</P>
<P>
   The city's lawyer, Hillary Weisman, called Mironer's account
accurate. Weissberg left town after Friday's hearing and could not
be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Weisman said that the city did not know yet what it would do
if the judge overturned the vote, but she said she did not think he
should.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not concede that there was a violation of the open
meetings law,'' she said. ``But even if there was, most courts do
not invalidate activity even if they find the open meetings law was
violated.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Freeman, the executive director of the state's Committee
on Open government, which advises governments on proper conduct,
said recently that courts had ruled variously in cases like this.
</P>
<P>
   But he added: ``I would hope that in view of the intent of the
open meetings law that if a court found that the deliberative
process occurred in private, and that a consensus was essentially
reached behind closed doors, that was merely rubber-stamped at an
open meeting, a court would find that the action was taken in
private and that it could be invalidated.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
