<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-PAROLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FISHER WANTS TO TAKE BACK GUILTY PLEA IN BUTTAFUOCO SHOOTING
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By JOHN T. McQUISTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINEOLA, N.Y. _ When Amy Fisher agreed to plead guilty to the
1992 shooting of Mary Jo Buttafuoco she said she believed she had a
promise from the Nassau County district attorney to help her win
early parole and entry into a work-release program. Now she says
the district attorney, Denis Dillon, has broken that promise and
she wants to vacate her guilty plea and proceed to a trial, even
though she has spent more than 5 1/2 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   But in papers filed in State Supreme Court here Friday morning,
the sixth anniversary of the shooting, Dillon said that no such
promise was ever made by him or the chief prosecutor in the case,
Fred Klein.
</P>
<P>
   In opposing Ms. Fisher's request, Dillon said that Ms. Fisher's
lawyer at the time, Eric Naiburg, had vigorously pursued the
possibility of a plea bargain and that it was eventually agreed
that if Ms. Fisher pleaded guilty, she would be sentenced to 5 to
15 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``At no time did I ever promise or in any other way represent or
suggest to Mr. Naiburg, defendant, or anyone else, that, in return
for defendant's plea of guilty, I would recommend that she be
released on parole,'' Dillon said. ``Nor did I ever promise or
represent that this office would not oppose defendant's parole.''
</P>
<P>
   Should the case go to trial, Ms. Fisher, if convicted, could
face a sentence of 12{ to 25 years for attempted murder.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fisher contends that Naiburg, of Hauppauge, N.Y., assured
her that such an agreement was ``guaranteed'' and ``written in
stone.'' Now 23, Ms. Fisher is in the Albion Correctional Facility
in upstate New York. She was denied parole in June 1997, after
Dillon recommended against her release.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the prospect of such a long term of imprisonment did not
appeal to me, I opted to plead guilty based solely on the
understanding that I would be released from prison after serving
the minimum portion of my sentence,'' Ms. Fisher said in a sworn
statement in late April, submitted along with her request to have
her guilty plea set aside in preparation for a trial.
</P>
<P>
   Naiburg, in a statement filed with the court, said that in
return for Ms. Fisher's cooperation, Klein promised that the
district attorney's office would make a recommendation for work
release for Ms. Fisher when she became eligible after serving three
years of her sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Naiburg acknowledged that the agreement was not made part of the
plea or sentencing record. He said that it was contingent on Ms.
Fisher's continuing cooperation in the investigation of Ms.
Fisher's lover, Joey Buttafuoco, which was going on then.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fisher, who was 17 at the time, contended that Buttafuoco,
now 41, had been actively engaged in the planning of the assault
against his wife and that Buttafuoco had engaged in sexual
intercourse with her when she was 16 years old, making him
responsible for the crime of rape in the third degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ms. Fisher fully fulfilled her obligations,'' Naiburg said,
noting that her cooperation led to Buttafuoco's plea of guilty to
the rape charge for which he served six months in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Naiburg, after reading the statements filed Friday by the
district attorney's office, said, ``Unfortunately, this was a
matter that will now have to be fought out in court.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fisher has since engaged a new lawyer, Bruce Barket, of
Garden City, N.Y., who said Friday that he would soon file a
response to the statements filed Friday with Judge Donald DeRiggi.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing is certain,'' Barket said. ``Amy Fisher believed she
had a deal. She was deceived and treated unfairly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
