<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8231 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLOBE-COLUMNISTS-BOS &LR;      06-19 1535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBE-COLUMNISTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLOBE ACTION UNFAIR, SAYS DERSHOWITZ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Outspoken defense attorney Alan Dershowitz Friday
accused The Boston Globe of employing a double standard ``based on
race, gender and ethnicity'' for asking columnist Patricia Smith to
resign after she admitted fabricating characters and quotations.
</P>
<P>
   Resurrecting an eight-year-old feud, the noted Harvard Law
School professor said the paper should also have asked for the
resignation of columnist Mike Barnicle after he allegedly
fabricated a quotation in which Dershowitz made a boorish, racist
slur.
</P>
<P>
   Although the 1990 quotation in dispute was never verified or
disproven, Dershowitz said Barnicle admitted fabricating it in
private conversations with him and with mutual friends. He said
Barnicle also extended an apology _ but not an admission _ on the
David Brudnoy radio show in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle, who is on vacation in Europe, said Friday that ``the
only thing I regretted on the Brudnoy show was that I had not been
able to reach Dershowitz despite trying three times.''
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper had begun a review of Barnicle's columns from
January 1996 to the present before Dershowitz went on television
and faxed a letter to the Globe, with copies to the major Boston
media outlets, accusing the newspaper of racism and sexism.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Globe's check of a number of columns during that period
has so far turned up no fabrications, and about the Dershowitz
column, there remain only allegations and continued dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Said Barnicle Friday: ``Every time I have gone into the Globe
and sat down and written my column for the last 25 years, I have
never violated the trust my publisher has placed in me, nor have I
violated the trust, faith, and confidence I hope my readers have
placed in me. This is a sad time for the paper and for Patricia
Smith. It is particularly despicable that a pack of parasites has
been participating in a feeding frenzy over the misfortune of
others. As for Alan Dershowitz, he's simply running true to form.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Globe spokesman Richard P. Gulla stressed that
Barnicle had never admitted to or been found to have fabricated
quotes. In response to the allegation of a double standard, Gulla
said, ``The Globe believes that the past two days have vividly and
painfully demonstrated that the Globe will apply vigorous standards
to its employees, and no one will be exempt from those standards.''
</P>
<P>
   The Globe Friday also reviewed the five columns for which Smith
won this year's American Society of Newspaper Editors Distinguished
Commentary Prize, and the additional five for which she was named a
finalist for the 1998 Pulitzer Prize. Of those 10 columns, six were
about public issues or events, two were personal reflections _ on
the death of Chicago columnist Mike Royko and a friend's brother _
and the two remaining contained people whose identities the
newspaper identified through various databases.
</P>
<P>
   The Dershowitz letter inflamed a controversy that began with the
paper's announcement Thursday that it had asked for and received
Smith's resignation after she admitted that she had invented
quotations and characters, who in two cases were the foundation for
entire columns. Smith, 42, had written a twice-weekly column since
1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem for me is this: I have compassion for Ms. Smith,''
said Dershowitz, the defender of such high profile clients as O.J.
Simpson and Claus Von Bulow, in a telephone interview. ``She sees
Barnicle being criticized for fabricating and nothing happens.
Then, for her to get this termination when Barnicle didn't even get
a rebuke. ... I think Barnicle is such a popular writer _ he's on
television, too _ that he gets special treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, Globe editor Matthew V. Storin said Friday, ``We
are aware of allegations of a double standard. We believe our
actions in Patricia's case were fully considered and fair. We would
respond in the same way in any other instance involving the same
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Storin also said, ``During the time I have been editor of the
paper, I have had no reason to doubt the authenticity of Mike
Barnicle's columns.'' Storin became editor in March 1993.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990 column, which was about Dershowitz's
publicity-seeking and entitled ``Open Mouth, Get In Paper,''
Barnicle closed with a scene in which he described the only meeting
between the two men, at Out of Town News in Harvard Square,
Cambridge. The conversation had taken place eight years previously,
and Barnicle wrote that during it, Dershowitz said, ``I love Asian
women, don't you? They're ... they're so submissive.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the Globe and in subsequent columns in the Boston
Herald in 1990 and 1992, Dershowitz said the two men exchanged only
brief greetings, and there was no mention of Asian women. His son,
he said, witnessed the conversation and backed him. Barnicle said
there were two witnesses, one of whom had died in the intervening
years; he would not name the other. Sheldon Cohen, the newsstand's
owner, who introduced the two men that day, said he could not
recall the conversation or any witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   A few months later, the newspaper's ombudsman wrote that he
could not determine who was telling the truth, but was skeptical of
Barnicle's ability to remember the quotation. ``The real issue is
credibility,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Dershowitz Friday said Barnicle admitted twice to fabricating
the quote. In the first instance Dershowitz cited _ from his
transcript of the show _ Barnicle replied to a caller to the
Brudnoy show who asked about the quotation in the Dershowitz
column, ``I gotta tell you about Alan Dershowitz ... he's got a
legitimate beef with me. ... I apologize to Alan Dershowitz.''
According to the Dershowitz transcript, Barnicle said he had
written an upcoming column about the incident.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; WBZ-radio discards tapes after five years, Brudnoy said. But
Brudnoy _ and Dershowitz himself _ conceded Friday that Barnicle's
olive branch did not include an admission of fabrication.
</P>
<P>
   Dershowitz said the second admission from Barnicle came in a
phone call from the columnist, and in a message the columnist asked
mutual friends, Richard and Doris Kearns Goodwin, to relay to
Dershowitz. The Goodwins, close friends of Barnicle, strongly
denied that Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason we would have been involved,'' Kearns
Goodwin said Friday. ``Absolutely not. I'm sure we never talked to
Dershowitz about this. We cannot be part of this corroboration.''
</P>
<P>
   Dershowitz said Barnicle told him he had ``gotten carried
away,'' because the lawyer attacked then-Senate President William
Bulger, a frequent Dershowitz target.
</P>
<P>
   Dershowitz Friday issued a challenge to the newspaper and to
Barnicle to publish the column Barnicle mentioned on the Brudnoy
show, which never appeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let him produce that column so the public can see his
statement in 1992 and what it is now. If he is saying he didn't
make up the quote, then he's repeating that I said that racist
remark. If he dares to repeat the fact that I said that, there'll
be an opportunity for me to cross examine him, and I would love to
cross-examine him.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been other allegations about Barnicle fabrications
over the years, none substantiated. In 1973, a Blue Hill Avenue gas
station owner denied having made a a racial slur, and sued
Barnicle. The case was finally settled in 1982, with the judge
saying portions of the disputed quotations appeared in Barnicle's
notebook, but that he could not verify the entire statement. He
ordered damages of $25,000, plus about $15,000 in interest dating
back to 1974.
</P>
<P>
   A Boston Magazine story in 1991 about Barnicle _ and a
subsequent short-lived running feature entitled ``Barnicle Watch''
_ raised questions of his veracity, but never established that he
had fabricated any sources or quotations.
</P>
<P>
   Based on questions about both Smith and Barnicle, the newspaper
in January 1996 began requiring its three metro columnists _ who
have some of the most prominent platforms in the paper _ to supply
editors identifying details for anyone quoted in their columns.
</P>
<P>
   Over time the system lapsed into occasional inquiries, the
editors acknowledged. Yet in recent months, when there were
concerns that quotations in Smith's columns were, as her editor
said, ``too perfect,'' the paper began checking her columns again.
</P>
<P>
   Managing Editor Gregory L. Moore, who edited Smith's columns
beginning in early 1996, confronted her with six names and asked
her to verify them. Over the course of a two-hour conversation
Wednesday, she admitted that four of the people did not exist. The
fabrications ranged from a one-paragraph character and quotation in
an otherwise factual column about alleged kidnapper Stephen Fagan,
to entire columns about fictitious people.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper's statement Friday said it would review all Smith
and Barnicle columns dating back to January 1996, when the new
editing procedure was formally established by editor Storin.
</P>
<P>
   ``When that review is completed, it will be shared with Globe
readers,'' Gulla said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
