<HEADLINE>
CAMPBELL IN LINE FOR A TOP NHL JOB
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four months after being dismissed as coach of the Rangers, Colin
Campbell is a top candidate for one of the most difficult jobs in
the National Hockey League _ senior vice president and director of
hockey operations.
</P>
<P>
   The post has been held for the last five seasons by Brian Burke,
who has said he is ready for a new challenge, possibly as an NHL
general manager. The most public and controversial duty of Burke's
job is ruling on suspensions and fines of players who foul each
other during games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in hockey for 25 years,'' said Campbell, who
confirmed Friday that he had been interviewing with Commissioner
Gary Bettman. ``I've been in a lot of aspects of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   No announcement for a new appointment has been scheduled,
according to Frank Brown, a league spokesman. The decision is
Bettman's alone and would not need to be ratified by the Board of
Governors, which meets next Thursday in Toronto to vote on rules
changes and other league matters.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell also could be considered as a coaching candidate by
several teams. Anaheim, Chicago and Florida are without coaches.
There is speculation in Toronto and Vancouver that Mike Murphy of
the Maple Leafs and Mike Keenan of the Canucks also could be
replaced. Burke, a former assistant general manager with the
Canucks, is said to be a candidate for the vacant general manager's
job in Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   The candidacy of Campbell, who is well connected at many levels
of the sport, has much to offer for an expanding business that has
suffered some growing pains over the past year. Campbell is a
native of southern Ontario, in Canada, a nation in which some say
they feel increasingly estranged during the Bettman era, which
began in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   A Campbell appointment could send a signal and rebuild a bridge
to a constituency that supplies more than 60 percent of the players
as well as most of the coaches, general managers and referees.
Politically astute, Campbell networks well with many people on many
levels, particularly those with whom he shares a common culture. In
player relations, his difficulties tended to be with some, not all,
Europeans and French Canadians.
</P>
<P>
   Around news media and team personnel behind the scenes, Campbell
is approachable and glib, an important quality in a job that
demands constant explanations of suspensions, rules changes,
scheduling and building operations. Around the Rangers, Campbell
consistently displayed a willingness to work long hours, to answer
even the most difficult questions with candor and to confront
problems in a straightforward manner.
</P>
<P>
   He occasionally showed flashes of temper in verbal
confrontations with other coaches and opposing players and would
call up reporters to complain when he did not like what was written
about himself or his team. An NHL defenseman for 11 seasons,
Campbell was never a star player. But he learned survival skills
and frequently expresses gratitude and appreciation for what is
positive about the hockey life.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers General Manager Neil Smith, Campbell's boss in New York,
said ``I've talked with him a lot'' about his possibilities in an
executive role, and about ``where I thought he'd be successful and
where he'd have difficulty.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
