<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GOOD CATCHER BLOCKS OUT THE BAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Jorge Posada lamented his three at-bats without a
hit to a teammate Thursday night, after the Yankees' 5-2 victory
over the Cleveland Indians. Joe Girardi, the team's other catcher,
assured Posada that, in fact, he was essentially responsible for
the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Posada repeatedly and expertly knocked down breaking balls and
changeups that bounced in the dirt, several times with a runner at
third base, and had 12 blocks in all, according to Gary Tuck, who
coaches the Yankee catchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had some tough ones to block,'' Tuck said. ``But he had a
great game.''
</P>
<P>
   Blocking balls in the dirt is imperative when catching Orlando
Hernandez, the starter Thursday. Hernandez throws curveballs and
changeups when he is ahead in the count, which has been often in
his three games as a Yankee. Rather than aim the pitches at the
edges of the strike zone, Hernandez intentionally bounces them, to
insure that the batter can do nothing more than flail
unsuccessfully.
</P>
<P>
   To do this, however, Hernandez must have confidence that his
catcher has the ability to block the ball, and before the catcher
calls for either a breaking ball or a changeup, he has got to
believe that he can knock down the ball. Against the Indians on
Thursday, Hernandez aimed at the dirt and Posada kept everything in
front of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did a great job,'' Hernandez said through an interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   Posada and Girardi practice blocking balls before every game in
the Yankee bullpen. Tuck will stand 20 feet in front of them and
fire balls into the ground, and Girardi and Posada try to control
the bounce, like hockey goalies trying to contain rebounds. The
goal of the catchers is to keep the ball in front of them, rather
than allowing it to bounce to either side or get by them.
</P>
<P>
   Girardi and Posada will use their shoulders like flippers in a
pinball game, twisting their torsos to redirect a bouncing pitch
back to the plate. Tuck rests an undersized glove on the plate, and
as soon as one of the catchers can make a ball roll into the mitt,
the drill is complete.
</P>
<P>
   Posada is a converted infielder who, as a catcher, used to reach
for pitches instead of moving his body to block them. But he has
improved greatly, Tuck said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you want to do is get in the habit of blocking
everything,'' said Tuck, noting that the Yankee catchers try to
block balls in the dirt even when the pitcher is warming up between
innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good thing about these two guys is that they're not
satisfied where they're at,'' Tuck said. ``They're always trying to
get better with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Posada said: ``It's a part of the game that's taken for granted.
But it can make a big difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter Bounces Back
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter rejoined the Yankees on Friday night after playing
one exhibition game with Class AAA Columbus. He was activated from
the 15-day disabled list and was in the starting lineup at
shortstop against the Indians, having recovered from a strained
abdominal muscle.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter reported that turbulence bounced his commuter plane all
over the sky. ``I almost pulled a rib cage on the flight,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Sojo played well in Jeter's absence, but the return of
Jeter should help the leadoff hitter, Chuck Knoblauch, get better
pitches to hit. Knoblauch scored in only 3 of the 13 games that
Jeter missed.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees returned Shane Spencer to the minor leagues to make
room for Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
