<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLISH SCULPTOR WORKS AT CONCILIATION
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The last time Pope John Paul II visited the New York
area, in October 1995, he stayed less than a week and drew 125,000
people to an open-air Mass in Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the pontiff returned _ in representative form, that
is _ as a larger-than-life bronze statue, his robes flowing and his
right hand outstretched in blessing, a figure that will adorn the
grounds of a Roman Catholic shrine off Route 31 in Washington,
N.J., for the next six months. The shrine is about an hour and a
half from Manhattan by car.
</P>
<P>
   The statue is one of four large works by a Polish sculptor,
Maksymilian Biskupski, which officially go on display on July 11 at
the 100-acre pilgrimage shrine operated by the Blue Army of Our
Lady of Fatima, an organization that commemorates an apparition of
the Virgin Mary in Portugal in 1917.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview this week in Manhattan, Biskupski, 39, who works
in both abstract and realistic styles, said reconciliation, between
nations and religious groups, was a central theme of his work. But
he is concerned, too, with preserving the memory of people who have
suffered under dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, he presided as a memorial he created to Poles
killed under Communist rule was unveiled in Warsaw, in a ceremony
attended by Lech Walesa, Poland's president at that time. The
sculpture, titled ``To the Fallen and the Murdered in the East,''
consists of the bed of a railway car stacked mainly with rough-hewn
crosses.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, he opened a portfolio of plans for future
projects to show one intended for the memory of Jews murdered by
the Nazis, in which twin pillars of outstretched hands support a
semi-circular stone carved with a Star of David.
</P>
<P>
   Biskupski and Mary Ann Sullivan, the Blue Army's spokeswoman,
spread out photographs showing the statue of John Paul II arriving
at the shrine on a flatbed truck and being lowered to the ground by
a crane.
</P>
<P>
   The other works by Biskupski that are to be displayed at the
shrine are a statue of a crucified Christ that rises from a tree
stump and wears of a crown of nails; a medieval Polish monk, St.
John of Dukla, whose arms are open as if to embrace, and a towering
``cross of reconciliation,'' whose horizontal beam consists of
outstretched arms and whose base is covered with reaching hands.
</P>
<P>
   Those sculptures, along with the statue of the pope, will be
placed so visitors can approach closely, Ms. Sullivan said.
Biskupski ``wants people to touch them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He feels that when a person comes into the world, they first
know the world through touch.'' Ms. Sullivan said. ``So touching is
very important.''
</P>
<P>
   High season at the shrine began a month ago, on May 13, the
anniversary of the date in 1917 when, according to the church, Mary
appeared to three children near the Portuguese village of Fatima.
The children returned to the site of the vision each succeeding
month until Oct. 13 of that year, saying that the Virgin reappeared
to them each time. In 1930, church authorities declared that the
apparition was valid, a recognition that has since turned Fatima
into a major pilgrimage destination.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey shrine draws widely, too, attracting about 33,000
visitors annually. Most come from May 13 to Oct. 13, the
anniversary dates of the apparition, Ms. Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   Biskupski, to judge by the news clippings he carried with him,
had received some attention in Germany, where he has lived since
1986, and in his native Poland. In the United States, he said, he
hopes to find sponsors for a large memorial he would like to
construct for people who died under Communist rule worldwide. He
would call it the Chapel of Reconciliation, he said, displaying
photographs of a model that included a structure surmounted by one
of his ``reconciliation crosses,'' with exterior walls adorned with
statues of bound and chained people. It would be surrounded by
concentric circles of gravestones.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his own religious beliefs, Biskupski sought to place
himself in a broad context.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm Christian,'' he said, but added that he found space for
reflection in many places.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter if it's a Catholic church or a Protestant
church or a Russian Orthodox church, the most important thing is to
pray,'' he said. ``It doesn't matter if I'm Catholic, or
Protestant, or Jewish, or Muslim, or Buddhist. We must make a
reconciliation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
