u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCCER-FEMINISTS-500&AMP;     06-19 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCCER-FEMINISTS-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AD CAMPAIGN FOR SOCCER ANGERS SOME FEMINISTS
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Soccer is usually the great unifier, the one hallowed
passion that brings warring Italians together. When the first
matches of the World Cup began last week, even the irreconcilable
Italian Parliament agreed to hold sessions in the morning, which by
odd coincidence leaves their afternoons free to watch the matches.
</P>
<P>
   But this year the World Cup, usually the apotheosis of social
harmony, has opened a huge rift in Italian society. It is not the
customary war between the sexes, because Italian men are cloistered
all month in front of their television sets. Instead, the World Cup
has set off a bitter debate between Italian feminists and those who
call themselves post-feminists over how women should be portrayed
in the news media.
</P>
<P>
   The opening salvo was a series of three spots for the World Cup
coverage on the Italian state network RAI-TV; they also appear in
newspapers and magazines. One shows frontal and profile mug shots
of an Italian woman, a parody of a ``wanted'' poster. On the side a
box lists her traits. ``Sex: female. Profession: girlfriend.
Behavior: relentless. Distinguishing characteristic: tireless.
Common expressions: Let's go out, Let's go out, Let's go out.'' At
the bottom, the warning: ``Avoid Her.''
</P>
<P>
   The advertisement, produced by the Italian branch of the
advertising company McCann-Erickson, was an attempt at levity about
a national obsession that is perhaps the only topic Italians treat
with high seriousness. But it drew no smiles from Italian
feminists, who denounced it as perpetuating a crude stereotype.
</P>
<P>
   Silvia Costa, president of the government Commission on Equal
Opportunity, fired off an angry letter to RAI directors demanding
that the network pull the ad.
</P>
<P>
   RAI declined. ``I didn't consider it for a second,'' said
Giuliana Del Bufalo, 50, the network's public affairs director.
``Frankly I was a little surprised at the reaction. There is plenty
to complain about in the way women are portrayed in Italian
advertising _ either housewives or beautiful bimbos _ but this is
not degrading to women. If anything, it's embarrassing for men.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she added, she had braced herself for complaints that
the ads mocked Italy's two sacred icons, soccer and mothers.
</P>
<P>
   One spot features a smothering Italian ``Mamma'' (her most
common expression: ``Did you eat?''). ``That's an old, tired
stereotype, but it's also true,'' Mrs. Del Bufalo said sheepishly.
``The first thing I ask my 15-year-old son when I get home is `Did
you eat?'''
</P>
<P>
   One oddity is that the ad campaign was produced by women, most
of whom said they considered themselves post-feminists and who
argue that even though Italian society is still lagging in the
battle for equal rights, women have made sufficient strides to
allow a bit of self-mockery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at all the barricades for women's rights in the '70s,''
said Anna Innamorati, director of McCann-Erickson Rome, one of the
very few women to run a company in Italy. ``But I see no reason why
we Italians cannot laugh at ourselves.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The condition of women in Italy, however, is no more a laughing
matter than it is in the United States. Despite notable
improvements over the last two decades, there are still gaps in the
fight for equality. Italian women on average earn 30 percent less
than men in the same field. Women are poorly represented in
politics, making up only 9 percent of the members of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   And efforts to alter the way women are portrayed in the news
media are mixed. The notorious quiz show ``Colpo Grosso,'' in which
housewives who failed to answer questions correctly stripped to
their underclothes, is no longer on the air. But female nudity is
still a mainstay of Italian journalism and advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The news magazine Panorama, the equivalent of Time or Newsweek,
won points with women's groups in 1996 by declaring that it would
no longer put naked women on the cover. But last week, with a new
editor, Panorama's cover was embellished by the model Naomi
Campbell lying naked, with stones artfully covering her private
parts, to illustrate a story on summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nudity doesn't sell magazines,'' said an editor who did not
wish to be identified. Asked why, then, the magazine featured a
naked woman on the cover, he replied, ``We want to sell
magazines.''
</P>
<P>
   Revenge, even by feminists, is Italian style. This week Noi
Donne, Italy's best-selling feminist magazine, published a survey
of 800 women that suggested that 26 percent were planning to cheat
on their boyfriends and husbands during the World Cup. The poll
sample was too small to be entirely credible, but that is not why
some Italians expressed doubts about the findings.
</P>
<P>
   Daniela Gambino, who is writing a daily column about the World
Cup for her newspaper Ultime Notizie, wondered, ``Where are they
going to find lovers, now that there is an obvious scarcity?''
</P>
<P>
   Some Italian wives say they actually welcome the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should I be angry if my husband wants to watch the soccer
matches?'' asked Silvana Pennisi, 40, a corrections officer. ``The
difference from my mother's day is that our husbands no longer
forbid their wives from going out without them.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Pennisi organized a women's night out _ pizza and a
nightclub _ timed to Italy's victorious match against Cameroon on
Wednesday night. ``As long as I can get out, he's welcome to stay
home,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, many Italian women are also watching the matches.
Renato Mannheimer, a sociologist, just published his own study of
soccer and discovered that 48 percent of women consider themselves
fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ads are a little out of date,'' he said, referring to the
RAI spots. He pointed out that the Italian passion for soccer among
both men and women had grown sharply in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It spans both genders and all social classes,'' he said.
``Politics is over, even the debate about entering Europe is
finished. There is nothing left to care about except soccer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
