<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8236 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-GOLDCUP-NYT &LR;      06-19 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-GOLDCUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILVER CHARM JOINS FRAY FOR GOLD CUP SHOWDOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The long-awaited confrontation between two heralded horses
became a reality Friday when Hollywood Park got word that Bob
Baffert was sending Silver Charm, winner of the Kentucky Derby and
the Preakness last year, to face Skip Away in the $1 million
Hollywood Gold Cup next Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be there, barring anything unforeseen,'' said Bob Lewis,
a California beer distributor who owns Silver Charm. ``All plans
are to run in the Gold Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Gentlemen, who won the Gold Cup last year, is entered again in
the race.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert, who also won the Derby and the Preakness this year with
Real Quiet, said from Churchill Downs that ``the plan is to run
Silver Charm in the Gold Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert added: ``He works Tuesday. I'm confident he'll work well
and, if he does, the Gold Cup is a go.''
</P>
<P>
   The race had been billed as a showdown between Gentlemen, who
has won 9 of his last 12 starts, and Skip Away, who has won his
last six races and was voted champion older horse of 1997. But it
suddenly became a three-way battle with the addition of Silver
Charm, who won the $4 million Dubai World Cup in March and ran
second in the $750,000 Stephen Foster Handicap at Churchill Downs
last week.
</P>
<P>
   It will feature the three best older horses in the country:
Silver Charm at 4, Skip Away at 5 and Gentlemen at 6.
</P>
<P>
   A war of words broke out recently between Baffert and Sonny
Hine, the trainer of Skip Away, over which horse was ducking the
other. It had appeared very likely that their two horses would not
meet until the $1 million Pacific Classic in August, or possibly
not until the $4 million Breeders' Cup Classic in November. But it
was believed that Lewis intervened to bring Silver Charm home right
now.
</P>
<P>
   Silver Charm, who has won 8 times and finished second 6 times in
14 starts to earn $4.8 million, will leave Louisville with Baffert
on Sunday and fly to his California base at Santa Anita.
</P>
<P>
   The horse ran second in the Foster Handicap, and Baffert said
Friday, ``That race didn't take anything out of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Hine welcomed the news that his longtime rival would make the
scene next week, saying, ``I hope he's there.''
</P>
<P>
   Skip Away has won 15 of his 33 starts and earned $8.3 million,
second to Cigar's record total of $9.9 million. He has been
training at Belmont Park, where he was involved in an incident
during a morning gallop Friday when another horse, Pacificbounty,
slipped in the mud and fell in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   Skip Away ducked to avoid the fallen horse and unseated his
exercise rider, Jose Sanchez, who was not hurt.
</P>
<P>
   But Skip Away got loose for a while and joined other horses
along the track until taken in tow by an outrider and delivered to
Hine, who said later: ``I've been all over him, and nothing seems
wrong. We're not leaving for California until Thursday, and the
only way we wouldn't go is if something came up where we couldn't
work him.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 2202EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980619.0452 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8237 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-OPERA-NYT &LR;      06-19 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-OPERA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: IN SHANGHAI, FINE POINTS ARE CRUCIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When New York's Lincoln Center Festival announced that it was
presenting a production of the classic Chinese opera ``The Peony
Pavilion'' as its centerpiece next month, many wondered whether so
arcane an offering could capture the attention of even a few
hundred theatergoers in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the sets, props and costumes remain tied up in Shanghai,
the production is the center of an international incident involving
diplomats from at least three countries.
</P>
<P>
   It may be hard for Americans to understand why. Why would the
Municipal Cultural Bureau of Shanghai, which detained the cargo at
the Shanghai airport Thursday, take such drastic action over
seemingly minor artistic issues?
</P>
<P>
   But for the bureau, nothing involving Kunqu, the most refined
and venerated of the many forms of Chinese opera, is minor, and
``The Peony Pavilion,'' written by Tang Xianzu in 1598, is
considered the Kunqu masterpiece. The bureau claims a proprietary
interest in the way Kunqu is presented, because the genre was born
in Kunshan and grew up in Suzhou, both close to Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
   Chen Shi-Zheng, who is directing the Lincoln Center production
for the Shanghai Kunqu Opera Company, has his own ideas about how
Kunqu should be presented. Chen, an American who was born and
reared in China, feels that current performance conventions have
little to do with the way Kunqu was performed in the 17th century
and just as little to do with conveying human actions and emotions.
</P>
<P>
   He is presenting the work at its full 20-hour length, perhaps
for the first time anywhere in the modern era, and he recently
staged a preview in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who came to see it criticized it for having too
much life,'' he said by telephone from Shanghai on Thursday. ``It
was too relaxed, not rigid enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the distinctions at work are subtle. In particular, it
should not be thought that the production's eroticism, which is at
the center of the dispute, bears any relationship to the explicit
eroticism Westerners know so well.
</P>
<P>
   Kunqu (pronounced kun-SHU), even more than other forms of
Chinese opera, relies on stylization of gesture. Fluidity is
everything, as typified by the ``water sleeves'' of costumes,
which, unraveled, may extend to the floor. Movement is not angular
and direct but sweeping and curved.
</P>
<P>
   All of this was magnificently illuminated recently by Ben Wang,
a Kunqu authority in New York, in a series of lectures at the China
Society, presented in conjunction with the Lincoln Center
production. Gestures and movements around the stage, Wang
explained, tend to be circular, because the Chinese believe that
the circle represents the perfect union of opposites, the yin and
the yang. Within this fluid universe, each poetic word is acted out
in elegant fashion.
</P>
<P>
   As may well be imagined, there is little room within such
conventions for anything approaching overt eroticism. In recent
rehearsals, for example, Chen was grappling with the decision as to
whether the young heroine, Du Liniang, should sit on the lap of her
male counterpart, Liu Mengmei: everyone, of course, being fully and
beautifully clothed.
</P>
<P>
   The eroticism, in fact, originates in the text. ``The Peony
Pavilion'' is a fantastical love story in which ``Beautiful Du,''
as she is called, pines to her death for want of a lover, leaving
behind a self-portrait. When Liu discovers the painting and is
smitten, Du is restored to life through the power of love. The
eroticism is refined, just as it is in works of Tang's contemporary
Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   The amorous scene especially in question is one of the opera's
most famous, ``The Dream Interrupted,'' in which a handsome young
scholar _ Liu, though Du doesn't know him yet _ appears to Du in a
dream, and they make love.
</P>
<P>
   In Chen's production, the lovemaking is to occur only by
suggestion and behind a screen. But unquestionably, to judge from
recent rehearsals, Chen tries to humanize the young characters,
dispensing with much of the stiffness of current convention.
</P>
<P>
   More than that, he applies touches both older and newer than
current convention. On one hand, he tries, in the manner of the
Western early-music movement, to reimagine how the work might have
been performed in the 17th century; on the other, he injects such
modernisms as break dancing in the acrobatic scenes indigenous to
Chinese opera. He also harks back to Chinese folk traditions, with,
for example, a funeral procession for Du that trails out of the
theater and culminates in a burning of effigies.
</P>
<P>
   Such are the issues in the current negotiations. In the Shanghai
preview, the comic character Sister Stone (named for her
impregnable maidenhood and played by a man) added improvisation,
which Chen has agreed to remove, as not intrinsic to the
production. But other objections go to its very heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to show only the `best' of China,'' Chen said
Thursday. The statement was an ironic echo of what Chen had said
shortly before in Shanghai, after proudly showing off the sets,
props and costumes for the production, which he had had made in
traditional modes by the most skilled craftsmen and seamstresses
available: ``I want to show the best of China.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, matters remain at a stalemate despite the
intervention of high-level diplomats from the United States and
France (where the production is scheduled to go next).
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a problem,'' an official of the central office of the
Shanghai municipal government confirmed Friday.
</P>
<P>
   If the cargo is not shipped Sunday, as Lincoln Center hopes, the
next opportunity will occur only on Thursday, and problems may
arise with the opening of the production and the festival,
scheduled for July 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hopeful,'' Nigel Redden, the festival's director, said
Friday. ``If it's Sunday, we're in fine shape. If it's Thursday,
we're cutting it extremely tight. But we will do absolutely
everything we can not to miss the first performance, even if it
means working around the clock.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
