<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8246 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-OPEN-KUCHAR-HNS &LR;      06-19 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-KUCHAR-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Young Kuchar just soaking it all in
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JAYNE CUSTRED &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SAN FRANCISCO _ Pardon Matt Kuchar for the good time he has been
having at the Olympic Club.
</P>
<P>
   He's young, and apparently someone forgot to tell him the U.S.
Open is supposed to be a serious grind, not a fun break from
classes and exams. And he certainly wasn't supposed to contend for
America's national golf championship.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there was Kuchar after a 1-under-par 69 Friday, grinning
from ear to ear and sitting only two strokes off the second-round
lead, very much in the hunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am just having a great time,'' Kuchar said. ``I am taking it
one hole at a time, and I am at 1-under (139) and pretty close to
contention. It is exciting. It is exciting when you get that twinge
in your stomach. That is really what golf is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuchar, who just finished his sophomore year at Georgia Tech,
went from relative obscurity to stardom this year at the Masters,
when his quick smile and obvious enthusiasm won over even the most
hardened of golf fans. His golf game wasn't too bad, either.
</P>
<P>
   Kuchar, who got into the Masters by winning the U.S. Amateur
Championship, finished as low amateur at Augusta National and
earned a return trip to the Masters by tying for 21st.
</P>
<P>
   But that was the Masters, and this is the U.S. Open. Golf's
toughest test. Golf's most demanding moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the rough, it is definitely no fun,'' Kuchar said. ``And it
is a lot of a grind, much more of a grind than Augusta was. You
have to stay focused. You have to concentrate on every shot, every
hole. If you let down an inch, this course will grab you.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it is fun when you are in the fairway and on the green.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is where Kuchar was for most of Friday. He made nice
birdie putts on Nos. 7 and 8, rolled in a 20-footer for birdie on
No. 12 and then chipped in from 10 yards on No. 15 for his fourth
birdie of the day. The blemishes on his card came on No. 9, where
he missed the fairway left, had to knock the ball back out and made
bogey, and on No. 14, where his bunker shot landed in the left
rough and he ended up with double bogey.
</P>
<P>
   But Kuchar recovered on the par-3 15th hole, despite missing the
green.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the heavy rough, into the grain a little bit,''
Kuchar said. ``It wasn't a very good lie. I knew I really had to
hit it pretty hard to get it to the hole. I ended up getting
through it nicely and trickling into the hole. That was a great
momentum saver.''
</P>
<P>
   That left Kuchar in remarkably good shape heading into the
weekend, although history shows he has little chance of being in
the winner's circle Sunday. The U.S. Open has been won by an
amateur only eight times, and four of those victories belong to
Bobby Jones. The last amateur to win it was John Goodman in 1933.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the U.S. Open trophy has always gone to the
professional golfers. In fact, no amateur has even threatened to
win the tournament in the last 26 years, but that doesn't mean
Kuchar is going to have any less fun trying.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a continuation of a dream, just like Augusta was,''
Kuchar said. ``I know I could wake up tomorrow, and it could be
over. It is quite a test of golf, and to be in the position I am in
now after two days is fantastic. But I am only halfway there. There
is still two more days of golf left. We will see what happens in
the next two days.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
