A8249 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  AM-BRAZIL-PHONES-600&AMP;ADD     06-19 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICS OVERSHADOWING AUCTION OF BRAZILIAN PHONE GIANT 
</HEADLINE>
 AM-BRAZIL-PHONES-600&AMP;ADD-NYT  (nk) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO 
  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ Amid fierce election-year politics, the
Brazilian government has announced plans to go ahead late next
month with the breakup and sale of Telebras, the giant Brazilian
telephone holding company.
</P>
<P>
   The government has placed a minimum $11.7 billion price tag on
its controlling share of the 12 Telebras-affiliated companies
scheduled to be auctioned off on July 29. The sale would constitute
the largest privatization in Latin America to date.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real opportunity and one of the few that exist right
now,'' said John Mein, president of the American Chamber of
Commerce in Sao Paulo.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition politicians are not so enthusiastic, however, and are
threatening legal action to block or revoke the sale.
</P>
<P>
   In preparing for the auction of Telebras, the government broke
the holding company into three fixed phone systems, eight cellular
concessions and one long-distance company, and created an
independent regulatory agency, Anatel, that will monitor the
telecommunications industry.
</P>
<P>
   The Telebras sale is expected to be followed by a second auction
of so-called mirror licenses for competing companies, thus ending
the Telebras monopoly on fixed telephone lines. In 2002, the
industry is to open to even broader competition.
</P>
<P>
   Luiz Carlos Mendonca de Barros, Brazil's Communications
Minister, has been gauging investor interest in New York and
Europe. So far, he told reporters traveling with him, Telefonica de
Espana and France Telecom have shown a keen interest in the sale.
Among United States companies, Sprint, MCI, BellSouth and Airtouch
are expected to submit bids.
</P>
<P>
   The minimum price the government has set for the sale is well
below the $25 billion to $35 billion that Sergio Motta, Mendonca de
Barros' predecessor, who died two months ago, had repeatedly said
the privatization would fetch. Mendonca de Barros said the price
had dropped largely because the government opted to end the
Telebras monopoly and sell licenses to create unlimited
competition. The subsequent sale of those licenses could bring in
an additional $8.7 billion by 2001, government officials say.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the economic turbulence in Asia has made investors
somewhat more skittish about emerging markets generally.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago, the whole sentiment toward Brazil and emerging
markets was much more positive than today,'' said Rodrigo Fiais, an
investment adviser at Banco Itacu here. ``We're in a much more
volatile period of investment decision making.''
</P>
<P>
   Direct investment in Brazil, however, has remained strong, Fiaas
said. Though the Brazilian stock market has dropped steeply in the
last eight months, economists predict that the country will draw an
average of $2 billion a month in direct foreign investment this
year.
</P>
<P>
   And interest in the telecommunications sector has been steadily
building. With just 10 percent of the country's 160 million people
owning telephones, Brazil is considered to be fairly bursting with
pent-up demand for phone service.
</P>
<P>
   Purificacion Carpinteyro, senior counsel and director for
international regulatory affairs at MCI, said the company was
specifically interested in Brazil's long-distance service. ``MCI is
not a short-term investor,'' she said in a telephone interview from
Washington. ``Brazil has a good future and a stable economy.''
</P>
<P>
   The sale is scheduled to take place three months before the
first round of presidential elections in October. And the
unexpectedly low floor price has turned the auction into a volatile
election issue.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The American depository receipts of Telebras, which are traded
on the New York Stock Exchange, are a convenient vehicle for
investors to bet on the Brazilian economy, and their price has
fallen sharply in recent months over uncertainty about emerging
markets in general and about the Brazilian elections. Telebras
ADR's closed Friday at $107.9375, down about 36 percent from their
high of $169.25 last July.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Friday, Telefonica de Espana and a Brazilian media group
agreed to pay 1.18 billion reais, or $1.02 billion, to increase
their stake in Companhia Riograndense de Telecomunicacoes, known as
CRT, one of four Brazilian telecommunications companies that do not
belong to the state-owned Telebras system. The price was higher
than analysts had expected.
</P>
<P>
   In Brazil, the opposition candidate, Luiz Inacio ``Lula'' da
Silva of the left-of-center Workers' Party, has called for an audit
of the process by which the Telebras minimum price was set, and has
vowed to scrutinize any contracts the government awards. da Silva's
vice-presidential running mate, Lionel Brizola, has vowed to revoke
any privatization of the phone companies.
</P>
<P>
   Da Silva is arguing that the sale should be put off until market
conditions improve, and he has accused the government of going
ahead with the sale ``possibly to create a slush fund for the
election campaign.'' President Fernando Henrique Cardoso, in
response, threatened to sue his rival for slander, while his
Communications Minister likened the criticism of privatization to
Nazi propaganda.
</P>
<P>
   Though the remarks against privatization might ordinarily be
dismissed as mere election-year grandstanding, polls show da Silva
running in a dead heat against Cardoso, who is the first Brazilian
president ever to run for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Economists and executives said the threat of legal challenges to
the privatization could deter investors and drive down bids.
``It'll scare them away,'' said Alexandre Barros, an economic
consultant based in Brasilia. ``Except for one wise contrarian
who'll clean up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
