<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8254 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRILL-ARTICLE-ART-2TA     06-19 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRILL-ARTICLE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW MAGAZINE STRIKES A NERVE IN THE MEDIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-1243 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Steven Brill had simply written an opinion column for his new
magazine, condemning the news media for their conduct in the
coverage of the Monica Lewinsky investigation, Washington might
have been able to ignore it. If all he had done was to get Kenneth
Starr, the independent counsel, to admit leaking information to
reporters, the storm might have passed after a brief downpour of
headlines.
</P>
<P>
   But what Brill did this week in the inaugural issue of his media
review, Brill's Content, was far more brazen and ultimately
subversive of the insular culture of the nation's big newspapers
and networks. His immensely long and detailed examination of the
first three weeks of Lewinsky coverage _ identifying anonymous
sources and calling prominent reporters ``lap dogs'' _ jackhammered
directly into the basement of the nation's media establishment,
which is unaccustomed to such visible light.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine had rather loudly announced its arrival in a
suspicious neighborhood, and the reaction was commensurate: Within
hours of its publication, reporters and editors in New York and
Washington were demanding retractions, accusing Brill of dishonesty
and questioning his motives.
</P>
<P>
   The clamor called to mind Murray Kempton's line that reporters
are not thin-skinned; they have no skins. Michael Isikoff of
Newsweek called the article ``utterly garbage.'' The Wall Street
Journal, in an editorial, called it ``rank sensationalism.''
Michael Kelly, a syndicated columnist and senior editor of The
National Journal, said the basic theme of the article was
``flat-out wrong.'' Brill, summoned to talk shows and telephone
interviews to explain himself, found his subjects giving him a
publicity bonanza beyond his wildest business plan.
</P>
<P>
   Many journalists said that any attempt to look into their
sources and dissect a humanly flawed process made them profoundly
uncomfortable; others said Brill's research was simply shoddy. In
interviews this week, many of the same reporters who complained of
being misquoted in the article said their problems with it went
beyond inaccuracy _ they were troubled by its very nature, its
assumption that sources were a legitimate area of inquiry, its
undermining of the way journalists do their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing good about that piece _ it was not in any
way a service,'' said Susan Schmidt, a Washington Post reporter who
has been covering the Lewinsky story and has unsuccessfully sought
a correction from Brill about a quotation she says she never
uttered. ``It's misleading, it's a gross distortion. This is very
bad journalism, and nobody should be subjected to this sort of
thing.'' Ms. Schmidt was accused in the article of doing
``stenography'' for Starr's office.
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Judd, an ABC News reporter who was skewered by Brill for
what he said were flimsily sourced reports that President Clinton
and Ms. Lewinsky had been caught together, said that while Brill
had a right to ask who her sources were, she was appalled that he
would do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found it extraordinarily peculiar and inappropriate for one
journalist to be asking another who their sources are,'' she said.
``It's off limits; we don't do it. And then when I wouldn't say, he
speculated in print about who my sources were.''
</P>
<P>
   None of those in the proud profession conceded that any of their
habits might change as a result of the magazine's sudden presence
over their shoulder. Brill, the founder of The American Lawyer
magazine and the Court TV cable channel, said he never expected
they would. But he admitted to being amazed by the ferocity of the
reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't start this magazine counting on the press to be the
way to get readers to want to read us,'' he said. ``The onslaught
from everybody was surprising even to me.'' He recalled a similarly
stormy reaction from the legal community to the birth of The
American Lawyer in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the reaction was clearly due to the towering pile of
journalistic errors Brill cataloged in his 25,000 words and 29
pages. Many of the incidents and mistakes had been recounted
before, but their presentation in one place seemed overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   ``The outlines of the media screwups on this story were pretty
well known,'' said Howard Kurtz, the media reporter for The
Washington Post, who was quoted in the article, has written about
the article and also wrote a freelance piece for the magazine's
first issue. ``But Brill has added some important new details and
gotten acknowledgments from the likes of Tom Brokaw that
journalists had their foot on the gas pedal, and at times seemed to
be careening out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   A more typical reaction was that of Evan Thomas, an assistant
managing editor of Newsweek, who said that while the idea for the
article was a good one, the article itself was flawed. ``Nowhere in
the story does it indicate the care and deliberateness of our
approach to the story, which is a really important thing for us,''
he said. ``But it's probably pointless to whine about it.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the few things that most reporters regard as sacred is
the protection of their sources, whom they rely on in order to get
closer to the truth behind the official version of events.
Reporters know this relationship is subject to manipulation. But
many said they were surprised to see Brill try to puzzle out the
sources for various stories about the Lewinsky investigation, and
expressed concern that his article could make it harder for them to
get sources to talk.
</P>
<P>
   Brill, who said he believes the press has relied too heavily on
leaks handed out by Starr's office, is cheerfully unconcerned with
the effect of his inquiries into sourcing, which he likened to a
Pentagon reporter's sometimes justified attempts to learn military
secrets. If the process shows reporters to be sloppy, to be easily
misled, to curry favor in exchange for leaks, then so be it, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't blame anyone for not telling me their sources, but
they shouldn't blame me for asking,'' he said. ``Reporters are in
the business every day of asking people to tell them things that
they may have promised to keep secret. That's what I'm doing when
I'm asking a reporter who a source is.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Brill said that in at least one case the reaction to his article
has been unprofessional, and in doing so he perhaps unintentionally
demonstrated that there is plenty of thin skin to go around. He was
extremely angry Friday that The Washington Post said he had
retracted part of his article dealing with The Wall Street
Journal's role in the Lewinsky saga.
</P>
<P>
   The Post ran a short item about the first substantive correction
Brill has issued of his article. On Thursday, he said in a
statement that he was wrong in describing a sequence of events by
which The Journal had erroneously reported that a White House
steward had testified to seeing the president alone with Ms.
Lewinsky near the Oval Office. (Brill had written that The Journal
had published the article on its Internet site before being told
that the White House wanted a half-hour to prepare a comment.
Friday he conceded that the paper had known, but chose not to wait
the half-hour.)
</P>
<P>
   Brill said he hadn't ``retracted'' a section of his article; he
had simply admitted to having erred on a minor point that amounted
to one phrase in a sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``After seeing that story today, I really think that some
parties, including The Washington Post, are showing their thin skin
in a very unprofessional way,'' he said, adding that he thought The
Post was retaliating against him out of anger at being criticized
in his magazine. ``When I started the magazine, I said the only
people more sensitive to criticism than lawyers are journalists;
the only difference is they have a way to respond.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if The Post had published the item to get back at Brill,
Robert Kaiser, the newspaper's managing editor, responded, rather
wearily, ``No.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
