u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HIV-REPORT-NYT     06-19 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIV-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIDS GROUPS STUNNED BY NEW YORK'S PASSAGE OF PARTNER NOTIFICATION
MEASURE 
 
</HEADLINE>
 (ja) 
 By LYNDA RICHARDSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Advocates for HIV-positive people in New York Friday
heard with disbelief the news that the state Legislature had passed
a bill requiring that the names of infected people be reported to
the state and mandating that government workers contact the sexual
partners of those people.
</P>
<P>
   The state Assembly's approval of the HIV tracking measure, in
the waning hours of the session, could help change the nation's
system of monitoring the epidemic. As the state with the nation's
highest rate of AIDS cases, New York could be influential in
prompting other states to adopt such reporting.
</P>
<P>
   But many advocates for people with HIV, and even some supporters
of reporting the names of those people, called the requirement that
state health workers notify partners intrusive and coercive. These
advocates said the new mandate would only reinforce some people's
reluctance to be tested for HIV.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the worst piece of legislation on AIDS ever to pass the
state Legislature,'' said Jeffrey Reynolds, the director of policy
and public relations at the Long Island Association for AIDS Care.
``We have enacted a law that will drive people from testing because
of the fear of being identified in their community and the fear of
having the Health Department at your front door.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, sponsored in the Assembly by a Queens Democrat,
Nettie Mayersohn, was approved on the last day of the session to
the surprise of advocates who had believed that the bill had no
chance of passage in this session. For years, AIDS advocacy groups
had resisted such a measure, and members of the state AIDS Advisory
Council, which advises the Legislature and the governor, were
unable to agree on how to put such a reporting program into effect.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Sheldon Silver, the Assembly speaker, had kept
notification bills from coming to a vote for years. But on Thursday
night, he relented in the face of pressure from other Democrats to
allow the measure to be considered, and the legislation was
approved 112 to 34. The Senate had earlier approved the bill, and
aides to Gov. George Pataki said he intended to sign it into law.
</P>
<P>
   Under the legislation, the names of people infected with the
AIDS virus would be reported to the state Health Department, which
would keep a central registry of the names of infected people.
Local health agencies would interview all people reported as
testing positive, ask them to name their sexual partners, and then
warn those partners that they had been exposed to the virus. The
legislation also appears to allow government health workers to
contact spouses and known sexual partners without the consent of
the infected person.
</P>
<P>
   The law, however, would not penalize those who refused to
divulge the names of their sexual partners. And the legislation
would preserve some sites where people could be tested anonymously.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-eight states, including New Jersey, already require the
reporting of the names of people with HIV, but those states account
for only a third of all AIDS cases. And many of those states do not
require the tracing of contacts.
</P>
<P>
   The president of Planned Parenthood of New York City, Alexander
Sanger, called the legislation misguided. ``The way to stop this
epidemic is to make testing easier, more available and affordable,
not by Draconian legislation that threatens punishment and the fear
of repercussion from health authorities disclosing, without your
consent, private health information,'' Sanger said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 2233EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980619.0463 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8260 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-OPEN-BOS &LR;      06-19 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEWART HANGS ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When Payne Stewart birdied his first three
holes, opening a five-stroke lead in the 98th US Open, novices and
rookies and newcomers to Open golf murmured, ``It's over ...
Stewart is running away with it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the wind was swirling, the rough was snarly, and the Open
has long had a tradition of sticking its tentacles into golfers who
dare have red numbers like ``5'' and ``6'' and ``7'' on the
leaderboard beside their names in the second round. The sun is less
likely to sink in the evening sky than a Friday Open leader with a
sub-par score of 6 or 7 under is sure to sink in the Open.
</P>
<P>
   And so it was Friday that Stewart, his score by then a mere 4
under, looked over an 8-foot birdie putt on that damnable 18th
green, tapped his ball, and watched as it rolled ... and rolled ...
and rolled .... before ending ``20 or 25 feet from the hole,'' he
said. Birdie? The Open sent Stewart home with a bogey 5.
</P>
<P>
   While Stewart (71_137) may lead the Open after two rounds by one
stroke over Jeff Maggert (69) and Bob Tway (70) and two over Lee
Janzen (66) and amateur Matt Kuchar (66), he looks decidedly
unsteady. He made the turn at The Olympic Club 6 under but was
fortunate to come home 3 over as he struggled and struggled just to
save pars.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's late collapse, which included bogeys on the 17th and
18th, enabled a slew of golfers such as Jack Nicklaus, Paul
Azinger, and Fred Couples _ all at 147 _ to breathe easier as they
made the cut since they are within 10 strokes of the leader. They
might have made the cut, anyway, since the top 60 and ties play
onward, but they would have had to wait until the last golfer
finished his round as darkness fell over the Pacific to know for
sure.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart left the course muttering at that vicious 18th green,
the hardest of the day for the Open golfers to read as they
averaged 2.01 putts on it. So quick was that green that Kirk
Triplett incurred a penalty stroke when his putt approached the
pin, only to begin rolling down the hill away from it, and he
placed his putter atop the rolling ball about 4 feet from the cup.
</P>
<P>
   That green, said Stewart, ``is bordering on the ridiculous. When
you have putts roll up to the pin, stop, and begin rolling back,
that's bordering on the ridiculous. I don't think I was the only
one who talked to a USGA official about the pin placement on the
hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Casey Martin _ who won a court victory allowing him
to ride a cart because a debilitating circulatory condition makes
walking difficult _ made the cut with a solid 71_145. Tiger Woods
recovered in the late afternoon from near extinction for a 72_144.
</P>
<P>
   On the sixth hole, it seemed that the Tigermania of the last 15
months was officially done as Woods circumnavigated the green,
needing four putts to get down from 25 feet. That double bogey left
Woods 8 over at the time, and it seemed his stay at the Open would
be brief, like those of Ben Crenshaw (160), Nick Faldo (149), and
Davis Love III (153).
</P>
<P>
   But Woods birdied the seventh and eighth, came home in 33, and
spared himself the ignominy of missing the cut at the Open, which a
few observers picked him to win. Meanwhile, Brad Faxon of
Barrington, R.I., who has always struggled at the Open because of
his wayward driver, was tied for eighth with a 68_141.
</P>
<P>
   Janzen briefly tied Stewart as he played in late evening and
drew even with a birdie on the 609-yard 16th. But he immediately
gave two strokes back on the par-4 17th when he found the right
rough, found the high rough on the edge of the green, put the ball
in a bunker, and did not rest until he wrote a ``6'' on his
scorecard.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Kuchar, the Georgia Tech student and US Amateur champ,
provided a highlight amid the travails. ``I'm just having a great
time,'' said Kuchar, whose 20th birthday is tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   He was one of the few _ the very few _ golfers who could use
such words on this day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
