<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- June 19, 1998 -- COMPUTER-BOOKS-B&AMP;W, 6-19 --
One way to select your summer reading material is to browse in a
bookstore. The new way is to get some help from an on-line data
base. (Jack Manning/1979 New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) DENVER -- June 19, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 21 --
TELE-COMMUNICATIONS, 6-19 -- Leo Hindery, president of the Denver
cable giant, Tele-Communications Inc., in his office overlooking
the Rocky Mountains. Since joining TCI in March of last year,
Hindery has improved the company's image on Wall Street by selling
cable systems to reduce its staggering debt. (Kevin Moloney/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- June 19, 1998 -- BRILL-ARTICLE, 6-19 --
Steven Brill, publisher of Brill's Content, at his office in New
York. Brill's immensely long and detailed examination of the first
three weeks of Monica Lewinsky coverage Q identifying anonymous
sources and calling prominent reporters ``lap dogs'' Q jackhammered
directly into the basement of the nation's media establishment,
which is unaccustomed to such visible light. (Librado Romero/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) LONE PINE, Calif. -- June 19, 1998 --
MANZANAR-NATIONAL-SITE, 6-19 -- About 120,000 people of Japanese
descent were interned in World War II at camps throughout the
United States. Ross Hopkins runs the national memorial at Manzanar,
which housed 10,000 of them, mostly U.S. citizens, who were brought
here from their homes and businesses along the West Coast against
their will in the mass hysteria that followed Pearl Harbor. (Ed
Carreon/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- June 19, 1998 -- NY-DEAF-MEXICANS, 6-19 --
The 49 deaf Mexican men and women whose ordeal as virtual slaves in
a quiet Queens neighborhood shocked New York and attracted national
attention last year will be allowed to stay in the United States,
federal officials say Friday. The illegal immigrants Q shown
standing behind a guard at the entrance to the Westway Motor Inn in
Queens Q will be permitted to remain because of their help in
convicting their tormentors. (Barbara Alper/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) HUNTINGTON, N.Y. -- June 19, 1998 -- THERAPEUTIC-RIDING,
6-19 -- Michelle Teichmann, who has cerebral palsy, speaks with
Denise Avolio, her instructor at Pal-O-Mine Equestrian in
Huntington. A growing number of physical and occupational
therapists are using horses in treatment, contending that the
physical rigors of riding strengthen the limbs and muscles of
people with cerebral palsy, multiple sclerosis, paraplegia and
other disabilities. (Richard Harbus/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- June 19, 1998 -- MCDONALDS-OVERHAUL, 6-19 --
McDonald's admits it has a taste problem and says a solution is in
the works. The only question is whether people will notice it. At a
McDonald's restaurant in Manhattan recently, they apparently did
not Q and that means the fast-food giant also has a marketing
problem on its hands. Asked if they thought the fare had improved
of late, several customers put on puzzled looks. (Nancy Siesel/New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) UNDATED -- June 19, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 21 --
