<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8279 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-TURCOTTE-TEX     06-19 0370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-TURCOTTE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURCOTTE PRAISES JOCKEY COMPETITION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By DAVE IVEY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND PRAIRIE, Texas _ While touring the country this year to
commemorate the 25th anniversary of Secretariat's storied 1973
Triple Crown triumph, retired jockey Ron Turcotte is often asked by
young riders for advice.
</P>
<P>
   Turcotte, who will be 57 next month, has a stock response.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always tell them to keep their ears and eyes open and keep
their mouths shut,'' he said last night at Lone Star Park at Grand
Prairie. ``I also remind them to put everything they make away,
because you never know when a rainy day is coming.''
</P>
<P>
   For Turcotte, that rainy day came July 13, 1978. A spill at
Belmont Park left him paralyzed from the waist down.
</P>
<P>
   Turcotte was in town for the NTRA All-Star Jockey Championship.
He lauded the four-race event for putting the spotlight on the
jockeys instead of the horses. He also had another reason to praise
the competition.
</P>
<P>
   One percent of the total nationwide betting on the jockey
championship will be donated to the disabled riders fund
administered by the Jockeys Guild. The inaugural event last year
helped raise about $60,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't dwell on what happened to me, but accidents can and do
happen. It is good to be prepared,'' Turcotte said. ``It is
comforting for the jockeys to know that someone is looking out for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Turcotte and Secretariat owner Penny Chenery were honored
Thursday during the live race card and at a banquet yesterday.
Turcotte also spent several hours signing autographs and chatting
with fans.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the distinguished jockeys attending the weekend
festivities, perhaps none made as long a journey as Turcotte.
Together with his wife, Gae, he drove 2,500 miles from his home in
the eastern Canadian province of New Brunswick, averaging about 500
miles a day in his specially equipped van.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always just preferred taking the van over flying,'' he
said. ``Gives us a chance to see new places and meet new people.''
</P>
<P>
   It also keeps Turcotte where he made so many memories _ memories
like riding to a 31-length victory in the 1973 Belmont Stakes _ in
the driver's seat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
