<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 6/19/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- June 19, 1998 -- COMPUTER-BOOKS-B&AMP;W, 6-19 --
One way to select your summer reading material is to browse in a
bookstore. The new way is to get some help from an on-line data
base. (Jack Manning/1979 New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) DENVER -- June 19, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 21 --
TELE-COMMUNICATIONS, 6-19 -- Leo Hindery, president of the Denver
cable giant, Tele-Communications Inc., in his office overlooking
the Rocky Mountains. Since joining TCI in March of last year,
Hindery has improved the company's image on Wall Street by selling
cable systems to reduce its staggering debt. (Kevin Moloney/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- June 19, 1998 -- BRILL-ARTICLE, 6-19 --
Steven Brill, publisher of Brill's Content, at his office in New
York. Brill's immensely long and detailed examination of the first
three weeks of Monica Lewinsky coverage Q identifying anonymous
sources and calling prominent reporters ``lap dogs'' Q jackhammered
directly into the basement of the nation's media establishment,
which is unaccustomed to such visible light. (Librado Romero/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) LONE PINE, Calif. -- June 19, 1998 --
MANZANAR-NATIONAL-SITE, 6-19 -- About 120,000 people of Japanese
descent were interned in World War II at camps throughout the
United States. Ross Hopkins runs the national memorial at Manzanar,
which housed 10,000 of them, mostly U.S. citizens, who were brought
here from their homes and businesses along the West Coast against
their will in the mass hysteria that followed Pearl Harbor. (Ed
Carreon/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- June 19, 1998 -- NY-DEAF-MEXICANS, 6-19 --
The 49 deaf Mexican men and women whose ordeal as virtual slaves in
a quiet Queens neighborhood shocked New York and attracted national
attention last year will be allowed to stay in the United States,
federal officials say Friday. The illegal immigrants Q shown
standing behind a guard at the entrance to the Westway Motor Inn in
Queens Q will be permitted to remain because of their help in
convicting their tormentors. (Barbara Alper/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) HUNTINGTON, N.Y. -- June 19, 1998 -- THERAPEUTIC-RIDING,
6-19 -- Michelle Teichmann, who has cerebral palsy, speaks with
Denise Avolio, her instructor at Pal-O-Mine Equestrian in
Huntington. A growing number of physical and occupational
therapists are using horses in treatment, contending that the
physical rigors of riding strengthen the limbs and muscles of
people with cerebral palsy, multiple sclerosis, paraplegia and
other disabilities. (Richard Harbus/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- June 19, 1998 -- MCDONALDS-OVERHAUL, 6-19 --
McDonald's admits it has a taste problem and says a solution is in
the works. The only question is whether people will notice it. At a
McDonald's restaurant in Manhattan recently, they apparently did
not Q and that means the fast-food giant also has a marketing
problem on its hands. Asked if they thought the fare had improved
of late, several customers put on puzzled looks. (Nancy Siesel/New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) UNDATED -- June 19, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 21 --
CAR-SMART-CONVERTIBLE, 6-19 -- The C70 convertible has a sturdy,
fully automatic top. Having developed some eye-catching curves,
Volvo is going topless. The convertible goes on sale early next
month, at a starting price estimated at $44,000. (New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) UNDATED -- June 19, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 21 --
ABOUT-CARS-VOLVO, 6-19 -- Volvo hopes the C70 coupe will embellish
its safe, staid image. While the C70 is eye-catching and elegant
and its turbo-charged engine serves up some serious fun, it is not
particularly enjoyable to drive. It lacks the sharp reflexes of a
BMW 328is, the rock-of-ages rigidity of a Mercedes CLK320 or the
fist-in-a-velvet-glove control of the Lexus SC 300. (New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) SAN JOSE, Calif. -- June 19, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE
21 -- MUTFUND-TECH-VALUE, 6-19 -- Kendrick Kam, left, and Kevin
Landis, co-managers of First Technology Value, say they do well
investing in high-technology stocks because of their work
experience in the sector and good contacts. ``We had the good sense
to stay invested, and actually we capitalized some more and bought
more stock,'' says Landis, 37. (Jenny Thomas/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) PORTLAND, Ore. -- June 19, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE
21 -- INVEST-IPO, 6-19 -- A restoration Hardware store in Portland.
The company's stock began trading on the Nasdaq stock market
Friday. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) LARGO, Md. -- June 19, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 21 --
PREMIER-PARKS, 6-19 -- Kieran Burke, the chairman and chief
executive of Premier Parks, has engineered a wave of acquisitions
and says more purchases may be in the offing. From nowhere, his
company has become the world's No. 2 operator of theme parks. ``We
never viewed our long-term goals or performance as competition with
Disney,'' says Burke, a Harvard-trained lawyer. (Scott Robinson/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- June 19, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE
21 -- THEME-PARKS-RIDES-2, 6-19 -- The Mamba roller coaster at
Worlds of Fun in Kansas City rotates 580 degrees at 60 miles an
hour. To entice repeat visits, amusement parks spend millions of
dollars on new thrill rides. This year, according to Amusement
Business, which tracks the $8 billion industry, is a record one for
roller coaster construction, with nearly 80 being built worldwide.
(New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) VALENCIA, Calif. -- June 19, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE
21 -- THEME-PARKS-RIDES-1, 6-19 -- Riddler's Revenge Roller Coaster
at Six Flags Magic Mountain in Valencia. Tailgaters and kamikaze
drivers seem harmless after you've been tossed side to side and
floated weightless during steep plunges on what is billed as the
world's tallest and fastest stand-up roller coaster. This year,
according to Amusement Business, which tracks the $8 billion
industry, is a record one for roller coaster construction, with
nearly 80 being built worldwide. (New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) BEDFORD, N.Y. -- June 19, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 21
-- STONE-WALLS, 6-19 -- This 1/4 mile long fence is six-feet high
and made of linerar field stone. It took three months to make and
cost about $500,000. Stone walls are the latest indispensable
accessory in New York's northern commuter-rail belt. (Norman Y.
Lono/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- June 19, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 21 --
MOGULS-SONS-3, 6-19 -- At top are the generations at Hartz Mountain
Industries; from left, Emanuel, Edward, Leonard and Andrea Stern.
Belows is Howard Rubenstein, center, with his sons Steven, left,
and Richard. ``If I didn't think they could make it, I would pull
them out,'' the seniorStern, chairman of Hartz Mountain Industries,
the pet-food conglomerate that also owns more than 175 buildings.
(Angel Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- June 19, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 21 --
MOGULS-SONS-2, 6-19 -- Earl Graves, right, is grooming his three
sons to take over his multimillion-dollar publishing and soft-drink
business. They are, from left, Michael, John and Earl Graves Jr.
Graves is the multimillionaire publisher of Black Enterprise
Magazine and the chief executive of the nation's largest
minority-controlled Pepsi-Cola franchise. (Angel Franco/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- June 19, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 21 --
MOGULS-SONS-1, 6-19 -- Jeff Wilpon, right, stands with his father,
Fred, in the stands at Shea Staduim, home of the New York Mets.
Jeff might have played baseball professionally, but he joined his
father in helping to run the team. ``I always knew I wanted to do
what my dad did,'' he says. (Angel Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) LOS ANGELES, Calif. -- June 19, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
JUNE 21 -- STARS-SOMMELIER, 6-19 -- Christian Navarro at Wally's
Wine Shop in Los Angeles. ``Christian has built the most
significant Hollywood base for wine and spirits in the industry,''
says James Orr, the screenwriter of ``Three Men and a Baby.''
``He's a wine therapist.'' (Marissa Roth/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- June 19, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 21 --
MEN'S-SHIRTS, 6-19 -- This checked shirt at Paul Smith, right, is
available for $155 to $195. It also come in cheerful colors. For a
sexier look, left, this sheer short-sleeved shirt is $305 at
Costume National. Once d class , the short-sleeved dress shirt has
achieved the status of anti-fashion icon. (Carrie Boretz/New York
Times Photos) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) ANNETTE ISLAND, Alaska -- June 19, 1998 --
MILITARY-WASTE-COX, 6-19 -- Military crews prepare a landing site
for boats bringing supplies to a base camp on remote Annette Island
off the southeast coast of Alaska. The armed services are spending
five years constructing a 14-mile, $20 million road, connecting the
town of Metlakatla to a future ferry landing. (Courtesy of Alaskan
Command Public Affairs, Department of Defense/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) WASHINGTON -- June 19, 1998 -- SMALL-BIZ-COX, 6-19 --
Cleta Mitchell, director of policy initiatives at the National
Federation of Independent Business, collects some of the one
million signatures the NFIB is gathering for its petition to
abolish the IRS code. The NFIB has some 600,000 dues-paying firms,
900 employees and an $85 million annual budget. It was ranked this
year as the nation's most powerful business lobby in a survey of
Washington insiders by Fortune magazine. (Photo by George
Bridges/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) HONG KONG -- June 19, 1998 -- ADV. FOR. SUN., JUNE 21 --
CHINA-POWER-2-COX, 6-19 -- F.D. ``Rick'' Kuester, the top executive
in the Southern Co.'s Hong Kong-based Asian subsidiary Consolidated
Electric Power Asia in his office. ``China obviously needs power -
a lot of it,'' says Kuester, who was sent to Asia from Mississippi
Power. (Marcia Kunstel/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) SHAJIAO, China -- June 19, 1998 -- ADV. FOR. SUN., JUNE
21 -- CHINA-POWER-1-COX, 6-19 -- Workers head to their jobs at the
Southern Co.'s giant Shajiao C power plant located in China's
booming southern industrial strip. ``If you look at the per-capita
consumption of electricity compared to anywhere else in the
world,'' says F.D. ``Rick'' Kuester, a top executive in Southern's
Hong Kong-based Asian subsidiary, ``you can see tremendous
opportunities for growth.'' (Vincent Yu/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
