<HEADER>
A8284 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-astros-elarton-HNS &LR;      06-19 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-astros-elarton-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Elarton gets chance 
he's been waiting for
<TEXT>
<P>
   Astro takes mound today in big-league debut
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By NEAL FARMER &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
One of the last times Scott Elarton and Astros general manager
Gerry Hunsicker talked, Elarton left angry.
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker left impressed.
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker had told Elarton after spring training that the
pitcher would start the season not in the big leagues but at Class
AAA New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `I'm not happy about it,''' Elarton said. ``I
wasn't sure how he would take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Hunsicker: ``I would have been disappointed if he hadn't
been angry.''
</P>
<P>
   Elarton has a chance to impress the general manager again but
with more on the line. The righthander will make his major-league
debut when he starts today's 12:15 p.m. game against the Cincinnati
Reds at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   Elarton was called up Friday to start in place of Mike Hampton,
who is on the 15-day disabled list with a strained left groin.
Elarton thought he had a chance to step in and be a starter earlier
this year when three spots were up for grabs in spring training.
But Hunsicker said no.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty conservative when it comes to young pitchers,''
Hunsicker said. ``I told the (coaching) staff before spring
training this year, `I don't care what kind of spring training this
guy has. He needs to start this year in Triple-A.'''
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker calls Elarton (6-7, 240 pounds) one of the top
pitching prospects the Astros have. But the GM didn't want to rush
him into anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there are right or wrong answers when it comes
to deciding whether a kid is ready or not for the big leagues,''
Hunsicker said. ``It is a feel thing. But based on what he had done
in his career and experience he had _ he had just had a month to
six weeks in Triple-A at the end of last year _ I just wasn't
comfortable starting the season in the big leagues with him. It's
much like we did with Billy Wagner a couple of years ago. We
started him in the minors, he got on a roll down there, we brought
him up, and he's never gone back. Hopefully, that will be the same
thing with Scott.''
</P>
<P>
   In 14 starts at New Orleans this season, Elarton was 9-4 with a
4.01 ERA and 100 strikeouts in 92 innings. He has a fastball, a
curve and a changeup and is working on a cutter, said Astros
manager Larry Dierker.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not an extremely hard thrower for a guy that size, but he
is only 22,'' Dierker said. ``I think he is going to throw a little
harder in the coming years.''
</P>
<P>
   When Hunsicker became the Astros' general manager in 1996, he
questioned how Elarton _ the Astros' first-round draft pick in 1994
and 26th pick overall _ could be pitching with less velocity in the
minors than he did in high school at Lamar, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a No. 1 pick with a high profile and a lot of hype,''
Hunsicker said. ``Then, the guy is throwing 88-89 mph, which to me
is a little suspect.''
</P>
<P>
   Elarton now throws his fastball in the 90-91 range.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's thrown a little harder every year since I have been
here,'' Hunsicker said, ``and I wouldn't be surprised where he got
to a point where he was pitching 93-95.''
</P>
<P>
   Elarton said his fastball slowed down because he was learning
how to pitch instead of just throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't throwing as hard my first couple of years in pro ball
as I did in high school,'' he said. ``Then suddenly, one day my
velocity jumped up, and I'm hitting around the 90s now.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he has a chance to impress. But even if he does, he could
end up back in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plan right now is that he'll take Hampton's spot for two
starts, and when Hampton comes back, Scott will go back,''
Hunsicker said. ``But the door is always open, and obviously,
performance is what the major leagues is all about. If he is doing
a good job, we will have to reassess things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
