<HEADLINE>
CASEY MARTIN MAKES THE CUT AT U.S. OPEN
</HEADLINE>
  (See GLF-U.S.-OPEN)  
(ja) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Casey Martin felt that making the cut at the
U.S. Open made a strong statement about his golf game.
</P>
<P>
   As the first player to compete at the Open using a golf cart,
Martin has drawn attention ever since he arrived at The Olympic
Club this week. Martin, who suffers from a rare circulatory disease
in his right leg, successfully sued the PGA Tour for the right to
use a cart earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday, Martin made news on the golf course, shooting an
impressive 1-over-par 71, leaving him 5-over at 145 for the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have proved something about myself, because I know I am not
playing as well as I am capable of, yet I made the cut at the U.S.
Open,'' said Martin, who is playing on the Nike Tour this year.
``That gives me confidence, knowing I am supposed to be here. If I
just keep playing well and improving, I can be out here and really
be a steady fixture.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to describe his first two days, Martin said, ``The crowd
support, just playing in the U.S. Open period, it's a blast.''
</P>
</TEXT>
