A8289 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FUEL-FRAUD-NYT &LR;      06-19 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUEL-FRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUR EXECUTIVES CONVICTED FOR EVADING FUEL TAXES
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ Four fuel company executives were convicted
Friday for their roles in a scheme that cheated the federal and
state governments out of more than $140 million in fuel taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The case centered on a fuel company based in Brooklyn that
prosecutors said was owned by Russian organized crime figures, and
it revealed the growing reach of the Russian mob throughout the
metropolitan region.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law-enforcement officials praised the verdict by a jury
in U.S. District Court in Camden, N.J., and called the fraud case
the largest involving oil taxes. Federal prosecutors are committed
to ``bringing to justice those who rip off state and federal taxing
authorities,'' said Robert Cleary, the first assistant U.S.
attorney for the district of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The conspiracy hinged on a tax code provision under which oil is
sold tax free as home heating oil but is taxed when sold as diesel
fuel for other uses. According to the evidence presented by the
prosecutors, the Brooklyn company, Kings Motor Oils Inc., purchased
666 million gallons of home heating oil tax free, and the oil was
later resold as diesel fuel. Customers buying the diesel fuel were
charged the heavy taxes, the prosecutors said, and the conspirators
pocketed the money instead of turning it over to the state and
federal governments.
</P>
<P>
   The fuel was passed through a series of middle companies,
creating a trail of invoices and other paperwork that falsely
indicated that the taxes had been properly paid, the prosecutors
said. Ultimately, the oil was sold to Petroplus Petroleum a
family-owned business in Deptford, N.J., which reaped huge profits
both by keeping part of the diverted tax money and reselling the
oil to customers at reduced prices.
</P>
<P>
   The president of Petroplus, Daniel Enright of Mullica Hill,
N.J., was one of the four executives convicted Friday after a
nine-month trial before Judge Joseph Irenas. Enright was convicted
of 38 charges, including tax evasion, money laundering, wire fraud
and conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Stahl, a special assistant U.S. attorney who prosecuted
the case, said that Enright and his company had received more than
$50 million in the scheme, the largest single share of the diverted
taxes. Enright, like the other suspects, was indicted in 1995 after
a long undercover investigation by the Federal Bureau of
Investigation and the Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enright was one of the largest people in this bootleg fuel
business,'' Stahl said. Petroplus reduced its prices so much that
it was able to woo customers from the major oil companies and
attract buyers up and down the East Coast, Stahl said.
</P>
<P>
   The owners of Kings Motor Oils, Igor Erlikh of Brooklyn and
Aaron Misulovin of East Hills, N.Y., both Russian immigrants, are
fugitives. The federal authorities are seeking them, but believe
they have fled the country. One of their partners, Demetrios
Karamanos, a Greek citizen who lived in Norwood, N.J., was
convicted Friday on tax evasion, fraud, laundering and conspiracy
charges. Investigators said Karamanos was an expert on the fuel
industry who helped mastermind the scheme.
</P>
<P>
   The jury also convicted Mary Ingram of Woodbridge, N.J., the
president of American Minority Petroleum, a wholesale oil
distributor in Woodbridge, of tax evasion, wire fraud, laundering
and conspiracy charges. Richard Pedroni of Clermont, N.J., who was
president of Pedroni Fuel Company in Vineland, N.J., was convicted
of conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   The various charges carry potential maximum sentences ranging
from five to 10 years and fines of as much as $250,000 on each
count. The federal government is also seeking $2.6 million from the
executives based on the money-laundering and tax evasion charges.
</P>
<P>
   The jury acquitted John Ruocco of Jackson, N.J., who was an
employee of American Minority, and Michael Lipkin of Manhattan, who
had worked for Kings Motor Oils.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
