<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8292 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LEGISLATURE-600&AMP;AD     06-19 1223
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LEGISLATURE-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGISLATURE OK`S BILL TO OVERHAUL SCHOOL BOARD ELECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ In its rush to adjourn for the year, the state
Legislature passed a bill that would overhaul school board
elections in New York City, replacing paper ballots with voting
machines and simplifying a system of weighted voting.
</P>
<P>
   Both steps would speed up the notoriously slow process of
tallying results in school elections. But the Legislature did not
follow a recommendation from government-reform groups to switch
school board elections from May to November to coincide with the
general election.
</P>
<P>
   While the groups said such a move would improve voter turnout
for school elections, which are nonpartisan, many Republican
legislators worried that a higher turnout would work against their
party in the partisan races because New York City has far more
registered Democrats than Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Under the old system, the Board of Elections spent weeks
counting paper ballots, keeping the results a mystery for as long
as a month after an election. To give candidates with small
constituencies a better chance to win seats, the votes were tallied
under a complicated system of proportional representation. During
the tally, as one candidate reached the minimum number of votes to
win, his surplus votes were transferred to the second-choice
candidate on the ballot, and so on down the line until nine winners
were picked.
</P>
<P>
   That system will be replaced by one in which each voter will
simply vote for four candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people didn't understand how the system worked, and that
undermined confidence in the system,'' said Assemblyman Steven
Sanders, D-Manhattan, who sponsored the legislation, which was
passed late Wednesday. ``Hopefully, this will end single-digit
turnouts.''
</P>
<P>
   As the legislative session staggered to a close Friday, the
Republican-controlled Senate and the Democratic-led Assembly also
adopted measures that would require trucks to be inspected for
excessive emissions and speed the creation of a riverside park on
Manhattan's West Side.
</P>
<P>
   In other last-minute action, the lawmakers set aside $87 million
to help Yonkers meet a federal court order to desegregate its
schools and agreed to set a stricter cap on property tax increases
for New York City homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   And they passed a bill aimed at funneling $100 million more
toward New York City's public hospitals to help pay for the rapidly
growing number of uninsured people. The bill lifted a cap
legislators had imposed on the city's Health and Hospitals Corp.,
which prevented it from applying for its full share of federal
Medicaid money for hospitals that treat very sick and uninsured
people. The bill could translate into $50 million more from
Washington, to be matched by $50 million already pledged by the
Giuliani administration.
</P>
<P>
   But lawmakers went home Friday with no agreement on several
pieces of legislation that Gov. George Pataki had considered
crucial, including a bill that would end discretionary parole for
violent felons.
</P>
<P>
   After the Senate last month passed the bill, known as ``Jenna's
Law,'' the Assembly introduced its own version. But the Assembly
bill included provisions that Pataki opposed, like one that would
allow low-level offenders to attend drug treatment programs instead
of being sent to prison.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly speaker, Sheldon Silver, a Democrat from Manhattan,
declined to drop the drug treatment provision despite intense
pressure in recent days from the parents of Jenna Grieshaber, the
women for whom the proposal was named. Ms. Grieshaber was killed in
Albany last year by a felon who was on parole, police say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly should have passed Jenna's Law,'' Pataki said at
an afternoon news conference. ``It's just tragic that there will be
literally thousands of crimes that will be committed by people who
otherwise would not have been out on the streets.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Senate and the Assembly also failed to agree on legislation
that would have streamlined the state's multilayered court system.
And despite a well-financed lobbying effort, the Assembly rejected
a bill that would have allowed mutual insurance companies, which
are owned by policy-holders, to sell $40 billion in stock while
turning over a relatively small amount of money to policy-holders.
</P>
<P>
   Still, legislative leaders said they deserved credit for
wrapping up business significantly earlier than last year, when a
battle over rent control and budget negotiations kept lawmakers in
Albany until August. Silver and the Senate president, Joseph Bruno,
a Republican from Rensselaer County, both said they were proud of
the new open budget process, in which rank-and-file lawmakers
helped hammer out a budget for the first time in decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we had a very productive year,'' Bruno said at a news
conference. ``We got an almost-on-time budget and we did it with
the involvement of almost every legislator in an open and public
forum. That is big.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmental advocates were divided over the legislation
creating Hudson River Park, which will stretch along the water from
the Battery to 59th Street. The measure designates most of the
waterfront as park land and creates an agency jointly run by the
city and the state to plan, build and operate the park. It also
requires the park to be paid for, in part, by revenue from existing
commercial development in the area, such as Chelsea Piers.
</P>
<P>
   But some environmentalists fear the legislation will not
adequately protect the park from commercial development. Gene
Russianoff, a lawyer for New York Public Interest Research Group,
said the park should be supervised not by a new public agency but
by existing state and city park agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very troubled about turning over a precious stretch of
the Hudson River to a public authority,'' Russianoff said. ``The
bill gives incentives to develop, because the premise of
legislation is that you need to raise money from commercial uses to
pay for the park.''
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the measure say Russianoff's fears are unfounded
because the legislation sets strict limits on commercial
development. The state expects to begin construction of the
Greenwich Village part of the park this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The measure creating the park and the measure requiring
emissions tests for trucks were the most significant pieces of
environmental legislation passed by the Legislature this year.
Under the new emissions law, diesel-powered trucks weighing more
than 8,500 pounds will have to pass an annual emissions test if
they are registered in New York City, on Long Island or in Rockland
or Westchester Counties.
</P>
<P>
   The trucking industry supported the New York measure, in part,
because New Jersey and Connecticut already have similar laws. The
state will increase truck registration fees by 2.6 percent to pay
for the new inspection program, which will take effect next June.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most trucks will meet the standard, but we've all seen a truck
belching black smoke and wondered why that's allowed to happen,''
said Richard Kassel, a senior lawyer for the National Resources
Defense Council. ``This program identifies the gross polluters and
requires their cleanup.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
