<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 23:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8377 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-OPEN-BLINEBURYCOL     06-19 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-BLINEBURYCOL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Martin starting 
to fit right in
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By FRAN BLINEBURY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SAN FRANCISCO _ It was Mark Twain who once described the game of
golf as a good walk spoiled.
</P>
<P>
   To hear Jack Nicklaus, Arnold Palmer, Tom Watson and some of the
other traditionalists, it is Casey Martin who is taking that
pleasant stroll further down the road to ruination with his
reliance on that contraption known as the golf cart.
</P>
<P>
   So you take yourself out onto the ticklish Lake Course at the
Olympic Club to get a look at the infernal devil machine, expecting
to see something that resembles the Batmobile or, at the very
least, a low-rider Chevy with twin exhaust pipes being driven by a
creature with a tail and a cackle as he cuts wide skid marks into
the manicured fairways.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, there is a polite, somewhat shy 26-year-old behind the
wheel of a forest-green E-Z-Cart with beige upholstery because he
has a congenital circulatory ailment in his right leg that is
extremely painful and causes him to walk with a pronounced limp.
</P>
<P>
   Martin drives the cart down the fairways and hobbles to each
shot. When he arrives at the green, a USGA marshal takes the cart
ahead to the next tee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Way to go, Casey!'' comes one shout from the gallery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep it up, Casey!'' shrieks a teen-age girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give 'em hell, kid!'' yells an old man.
</P>
<P>
   He never asked for this, to be the poster boy for every man,
woman or child with a handicap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't come here to make history,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   No, he came to make birdies, which he did three times, along
with four bogeys in Friday's second round to finish at 1 over par
on the day and stand 5-over halfway through the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Before the first tee shot was struck here, who would have taken
the bet that among Stanford graduates Martin not only would manage
to survive the cut but would have a one-shot lead on Tiger Woods?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was fortunate, because I got some good lies in the rough on
a couple of occasions, and I didn't hit very many fairways,''
Martin said. ``But I made some putts and I saved some pars. I think
the support I got from the gallery really helped.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a smaller crowd of both fans and media that followed him
than the throng that dogged his first round Thursday, which
finished up in the gloaming and the swirling fog that is San
Francisco's trademark.
</P>
<P>
   There was always a voice to congratulate him for a good shot or
to pick up Martin when things didn't go right. His playing partners
_ Larry Fryatt and David Eger _ never appeared bothered by the
added attention, and the one extra security guard who tailed their
threesome remained in the shadows and unobtrusive.
</P>
<P>
   It is precisely the way Martin always wanted to be until the
stiff collars on the PGA Tour forced him to take to court in order
to be permitted to ride his cart in professional tournaments.
Earlier in the week, USGA officials did relent on a plan to make
him use a smaller, less-mobile, one-rider electric cart.
</P>
<P>
   So Martin took to the undulating hills of the Olympic Club in
the traditional two-seater, and quite frankly it was difficult to
see the advantage he is supposed to have over his non-handicapped
competitors. See him struggle to get up out of a crouch after
lining up a putt. Watch him limp from a green to the next tee
before uncoiling another booming tee shot.
</P>
<P>
   If the staunch traditionalists had bothered to look, they would
have seen the course lined with dozens of handicapped fans in
wheelchairs and their own electric carts, pumping their fists and
shouting encouragement as he passed.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, his former college teammate, opened the door for
minorities to embrace the game. Would it be so horrible if Martin
did the same for people with handicaps? After all, it is called the
U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   Klippel-Trenaunay-Weber Syndrome is the name of the disorder
that prevents Martin from walking the course and may someday claim
his right leg. It is the thing that has made him a household name
in the way that none of us should envy or dare to suggest gives him
an easier way to play this game.
</P>
<P>
   Martin was like so many of the other golfers who teed it up
here, struggling to keep the ball in the fairway, wrestling to keep
control of his emotions and his sanity when he didn't. He hit only
six fairways on the day. But he kept himself alive by using only 29
putts to get through 18 holes.
</P>
<P>
   The leader board says that Payne Stewart is at the top, but it
would be wrong to put anyone's accomplishments ahead of Martin's at
this point. He is in front of names like Woods, Nicklaus, Watson,
Faldo, Irwin and others with cachet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in a way I have proved something to myself,'' he said.
``Because I know I'm not playing as well as I am capable, and yet I
made the cut at the U.S. Open. So that gives me confidence knowing
that I'm supposed to be here. And I think if I just keep playing
well and keep improving, I can be out here and really be a steady
fixture. It is a way off. But it is definitely realistic.''
</P>
<P>
   For Casey Martin, may the ride be long.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
