<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-U.S.-OPEN-375&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEWART HALFWAY, BUT PUTTS ARE CAUSING HIM GRIEF
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Payne Stewart escaped the U.S. Open Friday still
in the lead, but he did not escape the Olympic Club's wrath.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart may have nightmares Friday night about the putt he
missed for birdie on No. 18, a putt that would have put him in the
clubhouse with a three-stroke lead. It was a 7-footer that broke to
the left, but the hole sat on a downhill slope that was ready to
kidnap any putt that strayed even inches left of the target.
Stewart's putt barely missed the hole, turning about 3 inches short
of the hole and almost coming to a complete stop.
</P>
<P>
   But then his ball caught the slope, and it rolled slowly, slowly
down the hill. The crowd groaned with every agonizing turn it took,
while Stewart became angrier as he watched. Instead of a tap-in for
par, Stewart faced a 20-foot uphill putt when the ball finally
stopped rolling. He missed it, finishing with a bogey on No. 18
that followed a bogey on No. 17.
</P>
<P>
   So, instead of starting the weekend at 5 under par, Stewart
stood at 3-under 137 through 36 holes after Friday's round of
1-over 71.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who had finished Thursday's round with three birdies
and started Friday's round with three more, led all day, though Lee
Janzen caught him at 3 under after birdies at the 15th and 16th
holes. But Janzen double-bogeyed No. 17 to fall back to one under,
where he finished the day after a 66. Until that misfortune, he had
seven birdies and just one bogey in his round.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Maggert, who shot a 69 Friday, and Bob Tway, who shot a 70,
were tied for second at 2-under-par 139.
</P>
<P>
   While Stewart used a masterful short game, a steady putter and
terrific recovery shots to avoid the double bogeys and triple
bogeys that plagued so many others, he was upset leaving the 18th
green. The U.S. Golf Association has achieved its wish, setting up
the Olympic Club as a severe test of golf. But Stewart felt the pin
placement at 18 was uncalled for.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really feel that pin's unfair,'' he said. ``That green's
bordering on ridiculous, where they have that pin. I wasn't really
pleased with that. I didn't expect to walk away from that green
with a five.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't had four good rounds of putting, but I've had two
good rounds so far. If I can have two more good rounds of putting,
maybe I'll hold that trophy again.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It is difficult to lead the U.S. Open from start to finish, but
Stewart is the last first-round leader to win, accomplishing it in
1991 at Hazeltine National Golf Club in Chaska, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   While Stewart held the lead throughout the day, there were many
other developments.
</P>
<P>
   _ Matt Kuchar, the 1997 U.S. amateur champion, was in contention
at 1 under par for the tournament after Friday's round of 69. And
three unheralded players, Chris DiMarco, Lee Porter and Mark
Carnevale, remained in contention. Porter was one under after a
round of 3-under 67, Carnevale was at even par despite a 73 Friday,
and DiMarco was 2 under after a 71.
</P>
<P>
   _ Casey Martin, the first player to compete in the U.S. Open
using a golf cart, made the cut after shooting a 71 Friday, leaving
him 5 over par for the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   _ Several prominent players were in danger of missing the cut
when the round was completed later Friday night, including the 1996
U.S. Open champion, Steve Jones (149), and the three-time Masters
winner Nick Faldo (149).
</P>
<P>
   _ Some of Thursday's contenders struggled Friday, including Tom
Lehman, whose 75 dropped him to 3 over par for the tournament, and
Jose Maria Olazabal, who shot a 75 Friday, also falling to 5 over
par for the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   But Stewart played efficiently in a round that included four
birdies and five bogeys. His course management has been superb.
When faced with trouble, he has often manufactured an escape. He
has taken advantage of several fortunate bounces.
</P>
<P>
   And though he stumbled on the back nine, Stewart started the day
with the three consecutive birdies, giving himself margin for error
when the inevitable bogeys came. His blistering beginning was
almost as shocking as his finish on Thursday. The string of six
consecutive birdies tied the U.S. Open record, set by George Burns
(1982) and equaled by Andy Dillard (1992), both at Pebble Beach. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After three holes, Stewart was at 7 under par for the
tournament, and he held a five-stroke lead. But comfort like that
does not last at the U.S. Open, especially on a course set up as
difficult as Olympic is.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tougher today than it was yesterday because there's more
wind out there, there's not as much fog, so the greens are
tougher,'' Stewart said. ``Everything about it is going to get
tougher each day.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart still had a four-stroke lead at 6 under par when he
reached the par-4 No. 14, but he bogeyed that hole, then made
another bogey at No. 17, drawing the rest of the field even closer.
Stewart's approach shot at No. 17 landed in deep rough left of the
green, and though he hit an excellent chip shot to within eight
feet of the hole, he missed the putt for par.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I can play under par on this golf course,'' Stewart
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that what it's going to take? I don't know. I can answer
that question Sunday night.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
