r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     06-19 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KUCHAR, 19, PLAYING LIKE A SEASONED PRO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Inertia blanketed the area around the 18th green
of the Olympic Club's Lake Course. The caffeine buzz that carried
the cafe latte crowd through the morning was gone. Sleepiness was
settling in.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve golfers staggered through Friday's second round of the
U.S. Open, bearing names like Clough and Morin and Mast and
boasting scores as high as +23. It was so quiet, you could hear a
pine needle drop.
</P>
<P>
   What the fans clearly needed was a sugar fix.
</P>
<P>
   As if on cue, Matt Kuchar's gangly form strolled into view. Out
in the fairway he was flashing a smile so dazzling, people in the
bleachers some 100 yards away couldn't stop blinking.
</P>
<P>
   Soon the fans ringing the green were sitting upright and alert,
their gazes trained on the 19-year-old Kuchar as he stood stooped
over a par putt. When it dropped to leave him at 1-under-par for
the day and the week, the crowd's roar was loud enough to wake the
dead.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Open had been revived.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard not to be captivated by Kuchar, who just completed his
sophomore year at Georgia Tech. If he were any sweeter, he'd give
you cavities; if he were any more gracious, Miss Manners would be
out of a job. And if he were any better around the tees and greens,
well, frankly, Ernie Els would rather not even contemplate that
one.
</P>
<P>
   Els, the reigning U.S. Open champion, was paired with Kuchar the
first two rounds. On Friday, he said he told Kuchar, ``You might as
well turn pro.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's hitting the shots. He's doing all the right things,''
explained Els, who finds himself five shots behind Kuchar after
following an opening 75 with an even-par 70.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been beaten by an amateur in a long time,'' Els
said, chuckling. ``All the credit to him.''
</P>
<P>
   To Kuchar's credit, he seems impervious to fame's and fortune's
joint advances, though he does admit to having given each a subtle
once-over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money looks real good,'' he said. ``But turning pro, I don't
know when that will happen. It'd be so easy to chuck school because
Georgia Tech is so hard. But I am really enjoying school. I don't
know if money can persuade me to leave or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuchar's record suggests he probably could foot the bill for
correspondence courses if the PGA Tour won out over college. He has
played in four Tour events this year and made the cut in three,
finishing in a tie for 21st at the Masters and in a tie for 36th at
the BellSouth Classic in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Kuchar sits tied for fourth with 36 holes to play here, but he
isn't getting ahead of himself. You won't find him invoking the
name of John Goodman, who was the last amateur to win the U.S.
Open, in 1933, at any time these next two days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember in the junior tournaments, I would be playing in
the last group on the last day and I'd think, `All right, what am I
going to say when I get the trophy?''' Kuchar said. ``And I never
won a single junior event.''
</P>
<P>
   He laughed heartily at his own expense, then added, ``So I have
kind of learned to just take one shot at a time and see what
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of good things happened in his first 12 holes Friday.
Kuchar opened with six straight pars (which are treasured
commodities on this course) and birdied Nos. 7 and 8 to go to
2-under par for the week.
</P>
<P>
   He bogeyed No. 9 after missing the fairway with his first shot,
but got the stroke back with a 20-foot birdie putt on the par-4
12th. It looked like his bullet train to the top of the leaderboard
was about to jump the tracks when he carded a double bogey on the
par-4 14th and missed the green with his tee shot on the par-3
15th.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like the wheels were coming off,'' agreed Kuchar,
who fixed everything in one swift and silken motion, holing his
30-foot chip shot to leave an incredulous Els laughing in the
background and Kuchar's father (and caddy) Peter prancing in the
foreground.
</P>
<P>
   Reigning British Open champion Justin Leonard, the third member
of the group, was having a humorless kind of day. In his agitated
state, Peter Kuchar's exuberance clearly struck Leonard as a little
over the top. That he answered Kuchar's chip-in with a 4-putt for a
double bogey merely magnified his pique.
</P>
<P>
   Asked after the round if Peter Kuchar's displays of emotion had
been a distraction, the normally gracious Leonard tersely said,
``Next question.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuchar looked stricken when it was suggested to him that not
everybody was charmed by his dad's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other players have time to calm down themselves and let
the crowd (noise) subside,'' Kuchar said. ``I think Dad (has) very
good golf etiquette.''
</P>
<P>
   Imbedded in the mini-controversy like a golf ball in the Lake
Course's rough was a cold, hard truth of the PGA Tour: When
mortgages and endorsement contracts and all manner of things come
into play, it's not all fun and gamesmanship.
</P>
<P>
   If college golf is a fraternity, professional golf is a
boardroom, replete with power plays and fragile egos and petty
jealousies. It's enough to wipe the smile right off a person's face
_ or has it escaped your notice how few golfers seem as happy to
ply their craft as Kuchar?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so many things pulling at you at the same time out
here, from autograph seekers to the media,'' Kuchar acknowledged.
``You could see how a guy could become angry at something
insignificant. It's a big juggling act.''
</P>
<P>
   The hope here is that Kuchar remembers that long after his last
putt this weekend has dropped. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
