<HEADLINE>
MARTIN ERRATIC, BUT MAKES CUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Despite hitting just four of 14 fairways,
disabled golfer Casey Martin scrambled to a second-round 71 and
survived the cut in his first U.S. Open appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, the first player in Open history to compete while using
a cart, stands at 5-over par through 36 holes after a three-birdie,
four-bogey second round that saw him find six greens in regulation
after drives into the rough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I've proved to anybody else, but I've proved
something to myself,'' said Martin, a Nike Tour competitor making
his debut in a PGA Tour event. ``I know I'm not playing as well as
I'm capable, but I made the cut at the U.S. Open. That shows me I
can be out there ... and be a fixture out there.''
Brooks in, Randolph out
Fort Worth resident Mark Brooks collected a birdie and six pars
over the final seven holes of his second round to survive the cut,
at 6-over. Brooks' second-round 71 (three birdies, four bogeys)
clinched his first weekend tee time at one of golf's major
championships since 1996, when he won the PGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Randolph, also a Fort Worth resident, was not as fortunate.
Although his three-birdie, three-bogey effort (70) marked a
10-stroke turnaround from an opening 80, Randolph missed the cut at
10-over.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly Graham Marsh, reigning U.S. Senior Open champ, hit Ben
Crenshaw's ball by mistake on the first hole yesterday and was
assessed a two-stroke penalty. The gaffe turned a birdie into a
bogey for Marsh, who missed the cut at 12-over.
</P>
<P>
   Two reigning major champions four-putted during the second
round: British Open champ Justin Leonard at No. 15 and Masters
champ Mark O'Meara at No. 7. Tiger Woods, 1997 Masters champ, had
his second four-putt of the tournament yesterday. Woods four-putted
the sixth green after four-putting at No. 9 in the opening round.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
