<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: RAY MARTIN COMES HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By WILLIAM RHODEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Long Island University became the final New York City
program to name a head basketball coach Friday. In the elegant
Great Hall of the former Paramount theater on the school's Brooklyn
campus, LIU introduced Ray Martin as the successor to Ray Haskins.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, a former Notre Dame player and a highly regarded career
assistant, stood before 75 people and spoke of aspirations,
philosophy and gratitude. The battle for the basketball soul of New
York has begun.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, St. John's ended a public, nationwide search when it
named the smooth and sophisticated Mike Jarvis as its coach. A
month earlier, Iona named the rugged Jeff Ruland. Seton Hall hired
the Duke-bred Tommy Amaker last season. In each instance, the new
coach vowed to go after the city's nationally renowned talent. The
43-year-old Martin repeated that theme Friday. ``There's a lot of
players in New York City,'' he said. ``They all can't go to one or
two particular schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin was raised in the Queensbridge Houses complex in Long
Island City. He played summers at the Rucker tournament in Harlem
and also in the Bronx and Brooklyn. His appointment at LIU was the
culmination of an arduous 18-year quest to secure a head coaching
job. He began at Harvard as the coach of the freshman team, then
made stops at North Carolina State, Southern Methodist, Tennessee,
Division II Shaw in North Carolina, Florida Atlantic and Miami of
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bounced around a little bit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin takes over a program that is at a philosophical
crossroads. Under Haskins, LIU experienced quick success. It won
the Northeast Conference regular-season championship the last two
seasons; both times it advanced to the postseason. Haskins abruptly
resigned two months ago amid conflicts arising _ on the surface _
from the university's refusal to offer him a long-term contract.
The school gives one-year contracts to its employees and refused to
make an exception for the basketball coach.
</P>
<P>
   There are subtle indications that LIU was not entirely
comfortable with its rapid basketball success as well as Haskins'
style, his Brooklyn-based following and his ambitions to take the
Blackbirds to an even higher level.
</P>
<P>
   Richie Parker, a skillful player who was given a second chance
by Haskins and LIU when so many other colleges turned their backs
on him in the aftermath of an assault charge, said Friday that he
would miss his former coach. ``Personally, I wish we still had him,
but I guess he had to move on,'' Parker said of Haskins. ``I just
hope that Ray Martin will come in, replace him and continue where
he left off.''
</P>
<P>
   The school's vision is still clouded with the residue of good
times from the last two seasons. John Suarez, the first-year
athletic director, wants to win but is realistic. LIU lost two
potential NBA players in Charles Jones and Mike Campbell. They also
lost Haskins.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a tough job,'' Suarez said, referring to
Martin. ``He took over for a guy who rebuilt this program:
back-to-back 21-win seasons, two postseason appearances.''
</P>
<P>
   Suarez wants to nurture local rivalries but also understands the
need to hit the road for revenue and national exposure. ``I want to
go out and I want to travel and I want these kids to experience
other parts of the country,'' he said, ``and obviously there is
some guaranteed money out there for us. So we have to play some
games to bring some money to the institution.''
</P>
<P>
   Next season, LIU will play at Florida, at Georgia and at South
Florida. Gale Stevens Haynes, the school's provost, said this
Blackbird road show began to trouble her as LIU went from the
doldrums to a program with national aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I say I had trouble this year, it is that we traveled
thousands and thousands of miles,'' she said. ``There were times
when I thought our kids should have been home with us in their
rooms studying and preparing for tests and instead they were on yet
another road trip.''
</P>
<P>
   The reality for LIU is that St. John's and Seton Hall are the
only schools in this area with the infrastructure to sustain a race
for the national championship. That leaves LIU, Iona and Fordham to
compete at their respective levels and occasionally come together
with the other schools to battle for local bragging rights.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, after 18 years as an assistant, is content to have the
opportunity to play the Paramount. He is older than Amaker and
Ruland, younger than Jarvis, but with considerably more mileage as
an assistant. With four children, ages 6 to 16, Martin is ready to
do battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key thing is that I'm back home,'' he said. ``I'm home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
