<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DECISION TIME COMING FOR MARTINEZ
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Ramon Martinez avoided surgery last year when he
suffered a partially torn right rotator cuff in his right shoulder
and returned to pitch again. This time might not be so simple.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez is expected to decide within the next 36 hours to have
surgery to repair another tear in the rotator cuff plus cartilage
damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a difficult decision and I have to give it a lot of
thought,'' Martinez said. ``They say the recovery time from surgery
is six to seven months. That is why I am giving myself some time.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers executive vice president Fred Claire, who told Martinez
to get as many opinions as necessary, has hinted that he thinks
surgery is the best option. There is a good chance Martinez would
not pitch again this season even without the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I've done is lay out the information and give him the time
to think about it,'' Claire said.
</P>
<P>
   There is a financial decision to consider as well. Martinez is
in the last year of his contract, but the club holds an option for
1999 at $5.6 million. If the Dodgers decline to pick up the option,
there is a $600,000 buyout. The Dodgers could then re-sign him for
a lower figure.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers physical therapist Pat Screnar said no timetable for
recovery can be determined until surgeons go into the shoulder.
Martinez has the same cartilage tear that has forced outfielder
Todd Hollandsworth to miss the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez also could opt for the same rehabilitation program that
last year put him back on the mound in two months. He returned and
went 2-0 with a 1.64 ERA in August, but faltered in September,
going 2-2 with a 5.14 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   This season, he was 7-3 with a 2.83 ERA in 15 starts before
breaking down last Sunday. He was placed on the 15-day disabled
list. Triple-A catcher Paul LoDuca joined the team to take
Martinez's spot on the roster and back up Tom Prince while starter
Charles Johnson spends time in Florida to attend his grandmother's
funeral. Johnson will be back Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   LoDuca arrives: The Dodgers needed a catcher for a couple of
days, but LoDuca will stick around for a while after Johnson
returns. LoDuca impressed Dodgers management during spring training
and continued to hit well at Albuquerque (.306, 4 HR, 25 RBI).
</P>
<P>
   The Dukes were in Calgary when LoDuca received the call. He
called his family in Arizona and the response was overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father couldn't stop crying,'' he said. ``My brother were
really pumped. Getting to the big leagues is everybody's dream. I
don't care how long you are here.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick hits: OF/1B Matt Luke, picked up by the Cleveland Indians
two weeks ago after being designated for assignment by the Dodgers,
will return to the Dodgers today.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians released Luke on Friday after he went 0 for 2 as a
pinch hitter.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers liked Luke but didn't see him getting playing time
after Jim Eisenreich was acquired May 15 from the Florida Marlins.
Luke batted .286 with seven doubles, three homers and 11 RBI before
being designated....
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers agreed to terms Friday with outfielder Bubba Crosby,
the club's first selection and 23rd overall pick in the June
free-agent draft. Crosby, who attended Rice University in Houston,
will report today to the Dodgers' Single-A affiliate in San
Bernardino.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
