<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8403 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-mickeyherskowitz-HNS &LR;      06-19 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-mickey </SLUG>
 herskowitz-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MickeyHerskowitz
</P>
<P>
   Commissioners list &QL; 
a mix for the ages
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
GEE, we thought we were being cute when we referred to Bud Selig as
baseball's Interim Commissioner for Life. Now, it turns out that we
may have been prophetic.
</P>
<P>
   It is a near certainty now that his fellow owners will elect
Selig within the next few weeks as their permanent boss and
servant, almost six years after he accepted the job on a part-time
basis. The idea, at the time, was to move with caution in filling
the emptiness left by the firing of Fay Vincent.
</P>
<P>
   So more than three-quarters of a century after the job was
created, the lords of the game are on the brink of defining what
they want in a fearless leader. In a nutshell, they want someone
like them. On the surface, it is a give-up decision. It tells us
the owners want calm. They've had excitement.
</P>
<P>
   Has anyone noticed what a hellish losing streak baseball has
endured in matters related to this office? The problems began about
the time they buried Judge Kenesaw Mountain Landis. Had to, you
know. He was dead.
</P>
<P>
   The owners replaced him in 1945 with a commissioner named Happy,
and then embarked on a lifelong search for Dopey, Sleepy, Grumpy,
Sneezy, Bashful and Arsenio.
</P>
<P>
   No disrespect is intended, you can be sure. We are simply trying
to point out the diverse range of intellects chosen to fill this
sacred position. The list of eight includes a jurist, a politician,
a former sportswriter, a retired general, an entrepreneur, two
lawyers and a scholar. Selig, owner of the Milwaukee Brewers, will
be the first to start out as a company man.
</P>
<P>
   Law-and-order leadoff man
</P>
<P>
   Landis, the game's original czar, was brought in to clean up the
stench left by the Black Sox scandal in 1919. A gambler named
Arnold Rothstein wished to make a wager on the World Series, and to
protect his investment he took out an insurance policy by
purchasing the services of several members of the Chicago White
Sox.
</P>
<P>
   So in a moment of desperation, baseball hired Landis to restore
law and order. He did it with unyielding discipline and the help of
a fellow named Babe Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   Happy Chandler, a former governor of Kentucky, accepted the job
under the impression that he had the power to actually make
decisions. As soon as he made a teeny-weeny one _ he approved the
breaking of the color line _ the owners sent him back to his old
Kentucky home.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Frick had moved into management after a career as a
sportswriter, raising the office to intellectual heights never to
be seen again. Frick survived in the job by discovering a magic
phrase. When any problem arose, he announced that it was ``a league
matter.''
</P>
<P>
   After his retirement, the owners turned to the military, hoping
to be prepared in case war broke out. Gen. William D. ``Spike''
Eckert was quickly dubbed ``The Unknown Soldier.'' He stood off to
one side and didn't make waves, unless you count the time he shook
hands with Roger Maris and congratulated him on winning 20 games.
</P>
<P>
   And Bud would make nine
</P>
<P>
   Next up was Bowie Kuhn, who had been the National League lawyer
during a period of labor unrest. His other qualification was his
youthful stint as a batboy for the Washington Senators. Those were
fun years in the Cuckoo's Nest. Oakland owner Charles O. Finley had
to issue a public apology after he called the commissioner ``a
village idiot.'' Humbly, Finley declared, ``I apologize to all the
villages of America. He's the nation's idiot.''
</P>
<P>
   After 14 years, the owners pried Kuhn's cold fingers from the
legs of his desk and moved in the dynamic Peter Ueberroth, the man
who had organized the 1984 Olympics and turned a profit. Gads, the
owners were dazzled by that credential.
</P>
<P>
   Criticism didn't faze Ubie. ``I've been vilified in 20
languages,'' he said, adding that he understood the mixed reaction
of the media. ``They've just gotten to where they can spell
Yastrzemski,'' he said, ``and now I come along.'' Peter was, in
fact, a fine choice, an activist, but he was too smart for the job.
He tried to put a lid on skyrocketing salaries. Instead, the owners
had to pay megamillions in antitrust damages. After five years,
they wished Ueberroth well in his next endeavor.
</P>
<P>
   His successor seemed the perfect candidate. A. Bartlett Giamatti
had been the president of Yale, a passionate baseball fan and a
poet. But Giamatti, who had a several-packs-a-day cigarette habit,
died of a heart attack one year after he was sworn in.
</P>
<P>
   It was hardly surprising to students of the pastime that after
experimenting with people named Happy, Ford, Spike, Bowie and Bart,
the owners would hire a guy named Fay.
</P>
<P>
   Given this history, Selig makes sense. A benign and decent man,
he knows the hardships of a small market. The owners are aware that
he balanced a difficult act as well as anyone could. Clearly, this
Bud's for them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
