</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-INDIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETER RETURNS BUT YANKEES LOSE TO INDIANS, 7-4 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Derek Jeter rejoined the Yankees' lineup Friday,
after 15 days on the disabled list with a strained abdominal
muscle, and in the fine tradition of baseball, he received nothing
but grief from his teammates, who jeered and teased him. Underneath
the verbal jabbing, they were thrilled to have him back, of course.
</P>
<P>
   He will probably get some more ribbing Saturday, for the Yankees
lost to Cleveland, 7-4, in Jeter's first game back, and David Cone
lost for the first time since April 4.
</P>
<P>
   Throwing erratically, Cone (9-2) allowed eight hits, three
walks, three wild pitches and five runs in five and one-third
innings, and his nine-game winning streak came to an end.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter played for Class AAA Columbus on Thursday night, hitting a
couple of doubles, running and throwing and showing once and for
all that he is ready to play once more, information that Stump
Merrill, the Clippers' manager, dutifully reported to Joe Torre,
the Yankee manager.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter awoke early Friday morning in Durham, N.C., and boarded a
commuter flight for Cleveland. By Jeter's rough count, the plane
had about 20 passengers and almost as many propellers, offering
scant resistance to turbulence as it leap-frogged a line of storms.
``I almost pulled a rib cage on the flight,'' Jeter said.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of one free fall, Jeter remembered his insistence
that he play Friday. Why didn't I wait till Sunday, he thought,
sincerely wondering whether he would land safely.
</P>
<P>
   With great enthusiasm, then, Jeter strolled into the Yankees'
clubhouse about four hours before Friday night's game, carrying a
bag of equipment and a smile the size of Lake Erie.
</P>
<P>
   A rectangular white box had been left in front of his locker,
the inscription on the box: WELCOME BACK WIMP. Cookies inside, all
kinds.
</P>
<P>
   Tino Martinez, Tim Raines and others, lounging in the clubhouse
and watching television, all called greetings to him, Jeter
answering with a sheepish grin. ``It's been a long time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were 9-3 in his absence, but he was missed, his
production, his speed, his enthusiasm, according to Luis Sojo, the
veteran who filled in capably at shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need that guy if we're going to win a championship,'' Sojo
said.
</P>
<P>
   Having seen nothing but batting-practice fastballs, and a lot of
breaking balls in his one minor league appearance Thursday, Jeter
naturally appeared to be out of sync early in Friday night's game,
grounding into a double play in his first at-bat, grounding out
again in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Cone had pitched exceptionally in his two starts before Friday
night, benefiting from seven days of rest before the first and six
before the second. He made the start with his usual four days of
rest; whether this contributed to his performance or not, Cone
struggled, particularly with command of his breaking pitches. When
Cone is at his best, he dominates with his slider and his
curveball, and he did not really have control of either against the
Indians.
</P>
<P>
   He lasted five and one-third innings, but only because of
Cleveland's inefficiency. The first six Indians to bat in the
fourth inning reached base _ and generated just one run. A
base-running mistake by Jim Thome cost them an out and with two out
and the bases loaded, Cone had a chance to get out of the inning
trailing only 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   But Cone appeared to constantly overthrow his slider, the ball
bending into the dirt in the left-handed batter's box, and
Cleveland scored its third run when Cone unleashed the second of
his three wild pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Thome more than atoned for his mistake, hammering two home runs,
one off Cone and the other off Graeme Lloyd, his 18th and 19th of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Down by 3-1, the Yankees charged back to take the lead in the
fifth against Jaret Wright (6-4). Chad Curtis singled and Ricky
Ledee lined a double down the left field line, Curtis stopping at
second. Then Scott Brosius, who had homered for the Yankees' first
run, lined a single through the middle to score both runners.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius eventually scored the run that gave the Yankees' a 4-3
lead in the inning, on a fielder's choice grounder by Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   But Cone could not contain the Indians. David Bell singled to
start the bottom of the fifth, and Kenny Lofton turned on a low
slider and launched it into the right field stands. Indians 5,
Yankees 4.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had runners at first and second and two out in the
seventh, but could not score. Cleveland finished off the Yankees in
the bottom of that inning: David Justice reached when Chuck
Knoblauch fumbled his ground ball to second, and Thome blasted his
second home run of the game, the first runs allowed by Lloyd since
April 18. (Incredibly, it was the first time since April 28 that an
unearned run scored against a Yankee reliever).
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, the Cleveland Indians are honoring the 1948
Indians, who won the World Series from the Boston Braves 50 years
ago. The former Indians outfielder Larry Doby was among the players
from that team honored on the field before Friday night's game.
Doby will be inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame July 26. Bob
Lemon, one of the pitchers on the Indians staff that season and
later a pennant-winning Yankee manager, will have his number 21
retired by Cleveland on Saturday ... To make room for Derek Jeter
on the 25-man roster, the Yankees sent the outfielder Shane Spencer
to Class AAA Columbus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
