<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-MAIN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Millwood stumbles as Braves fall 14-1
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Good thing they removed the Olympic Stadium roof last
month. Otherwise, the Expos would've blown the Kevlar roof _ all 65
tons of it _ off the Big O Friday night and injured the crowd. All
10,364 of them.
</P>
<P>
   There was one casualty: Kevin Millwood, whose briefest
big-league outing lasted just 1 1/3 innings and became an unsightly
14-1 loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was ugly,'' Bobby Cox said of Atlanta's worst defeat of the
season. It was punctuated by four Montreal homers (two by Chris
Widger), seven strong innings by Expos journeyman Shawn Boskie
(just called up from Class AAA), two Atlanta errors and the most
runs the Braves have allowed since Sept. 12, 1996, a 16-8 defeat at
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   At least that could be blamed on Coors Field's thin air. This
one? Millwood's fat fastballs, just five days after he'd stifled
Montreal with a four-hit complete game. ``Nothing worked,'' said
Millwood, 9-3 after allowing seven earned runs on seven hits and
raising his ERA to 4.43. ``I'd throw a bad pitch, tried something
new, couldn't get any strikes there.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 12 batters Millwood faced, nine reached base. Shane
Andrews followed Widger's second-inning solo homer with one of his
own in the Expos' six-run second. ``My location was bad,'' said
Millwood. ``All the pitches I threw were bad. It was just a bad
day.''
</P>
<P>
   And seemingly no way to start tuning up for the Yankees. And yet
...
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, I'd rather get beat that way and get the bullpen
some work than lose a tough one,'' Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty much one of those games that's over early,'' Walt Weiss
said of a night in which Atlanta trailed 8-1 after two innings,
11-1 after four. ``Not that you don't go out there and play nine
innings. But when they jump on you like that... On the other hand,
those games are sometimes easier to bounce back from than a tough
loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Millwood hopes so.
</P>
<P>
   This was the fourth time this year he's made consecutive starts
against the same club. The first back-to-backer was beneficial. He
beat Pittsburgh April 9 for his first win, then one-hit the Pirates
five days later. But in subsequent encores after beating Colorado,
Chicago and Montreal, he's lost all three while allowing 20 earned
runs in seven total innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to go out and change anything,'' Millwood said.
``I just want to get them out again. If they're making adjustments,
I have to make adjustments. Just seems every time I face 'em again,
the stuff isn't there. Maybe I'm trying too hard.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
