A8411 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-OPEN-COX     06-19 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-OPEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stewart clings to lead
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO -- Payne Stewart's lead in the U.S. Open nearly
rolled away on the 18th green Friday at the Olympic Club.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the 10-footer for birdie that turned into a
25-footer for par _ courtesy of a sadistic USGA pin placement and
hardening greens _ did not completely self-destruct the man in the
plaid knickers.
</P>
<P>
   After Stewart's birdie try slid two inches below the hole and
then caught the slope, the ball kept rolling and rolling, finally
stopping far from its original spot. Stewart two-putted from there
for bogey to complete a 71 for a 36-hole total of 3-under-par 137.
</P>
<P>
   With players still out on the course, Stewart, 41, held a
one-shot lead over Jeff Maggert (69-69) and Bob Tway (68-70) and
two shots over Georgia Tech's amazing 19-year-old U.S. Amateur
champion, Matt Kuchar (70-69), and PGA Tour qualifying school
graduate Lee Porter (72-67) of Greensboro, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually thought it (the ball) would finish about 3 or 4
feet below the hole and all of a sudden it's 20,'' said Stewart.
``I told the official walking with us that that green is unfair.
That green's bordering on ridiculous where they have that pin.''
</P>
<P>
   After birdieing the last three holes yesterday to cap a 66 and
opening with three straight birdies Friday, Stewart bogeyed three
of his last five. The slide only pushed Kuchar closer to the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just having a great time,'' said Kuchar, who will turn 20
Sunday on Father's Day, with his father, Peter, on his bag. ``It's
exciting when you get that twinge in your stomach. That's really
what golf is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Casey Martin, the first player to use a golf cart in the U.S.
Open, apparently made the cut with a second-round 71, standing at
5-over 145 for the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Tway made five bogeys and five birdies. His round ended with
wedge to within a foot of the hole at the 18th.
</P>
<P>
   Maggert, who finished fourth at last year's U.S. Open when his
putting game collapsed down the stretch, shot a second straight 69
to join Tway at 138. A year ago he double-bogeyed the last two
holes, using seven putts, but has kept the ordeal in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have time to reflect on everything, there's a lot
worse things that can happen to you in life than having a chance to
win the Open and blowing it. There are millions of people that have
dreamed about being in that position, and I'm not going to hold my
head down because I failed.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Open rookie Joe Durant and Mark Carnevale, who surprised
people by their first-day presence on the leaderboard, are still
hanging around after 3-over 73s. Carnevale is at even-par 140,
Durant a stroke higher, tied with Zimbabwe's Nick Price (68).
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion Ernie Els rebounded with a 70 Friday to make
the cut at 145, extending his weekend through a back nine 32 that
started with an eagle at the 10th. He holed out an 8-iron of about
160 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Nicklaus, playing in his 42nd Open, birdied the 18th to
apparently make the cut.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
