<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wilkens is second double honoree
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- One spot in the Hall of Fame isn't enough for Lenny
Wilkens.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkens, coach of the Atlanta Hawks, will become the Naismith
Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame's second double honoree on
Tuesday, when he is selected as a coach.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkens was inducted into the Hall of Fame in 1989 for his
performance as a college and NBA player. He joins former UCLA coach
John Wooden as the only other double honoree.
</P>
<P>
   The winningest coach in NBA history, Wilkens' second selection
will be announced at a press conference at the Omni Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkens has a record of 1,120-908 as coach in Seattle, Portland,
Cleveland and Atlanta. He not only coached the four franchises, he
also played for three of them.
</P>
<P>
   Although Wilkens surpassed the Boston Celtics' Red Auerbach in
victories with his No. 939 on Jan. 6, 1995, he had to wait until he
had completed 25 years of coaching before becoming eligible for
election. He is 201-159 in five seasons as coach of the Hawks. His
contract has been extended four years.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkens played at Providence College before signing with the St.
Louis Hawks. He averaged 20.5 points during 13 seasons with the
Hawks, Sonics and Cavaliers. He was player-coach in Seattle for
three years.
</P>
<P>
   Wooden was a three-time All-American as a guard at Purdue before
going onto an illustrious coaching career. He won nine national
championships at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
