<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wohlers' search for strike zone begins
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ The resurrection of Mark Wohlers begins in earnest.
The deposed closer requested an optional minor-league assignment
and will start working out today at the Braves' spring training
complex in Disney World.
</P>
<P>
   The assignment, which will last a minimum of 10 days, will begin
with Wohlers throwing several simulated games in Orlando. Because
he had more than two years of minor-league service, Wohlers can't
pitch in any Gulf Coast Rookie League games. He'll then be optioned
to Richmond and the Braves hope he'll return to the club in two to
three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll dictate the timetable,'' said assistant general manager
Dean Taylor, here for a weekend series with the Expos. ``When he's
ready to move out and pitch in game situations, we anticipate him
going to Richmond. Our anticipation is that within a two to three
week period, this thing will be resolved. It's our hope that at
that point, he'd be ready to pitch in the major leagues again.''
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers' 25-man roster spot goes to John Smoltz, who'll be
activated from the disabled list today and start tonight. Wohlers
could be called back up after 10 days if a Brave were injured. For
now, he's trying to rediscover the strike zone in a manner he
requested after Thursday's game.
</P>
<P>
   He's ba-a-a-a-ck ... again
</P>
<P>
   After his second stint on the DL and subsequent rehab
assignment, Smoltz will test his pitching elbow tonight. He'll be
on a 90-pitch limit in his first Braves' start since lasting two
innings against Chicago May 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may struggle. I may not,'' Smoltz said. ``My intentions are
to ... pitch a damn good ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   The reason I'm pitching is because physically, I know I can.
Now, it's a matter of getting back in a groove.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz (4-1) won his first four decisions but pitched in pain
his last two starts.
</P>
<P>
   Back to Earth
</P>
<P>
   Since homering in consecutive at-bats last Saturday (each time
following a Javy Lopez two-run job), Andruw Jones has gone into a
slump. Again. After each of his five two-homer games in his career,
he has skidded badly.
</P>
<P>
   After last Saturday (his third two-homer game of the season),
Jones went 1-for-13 the rest of the homestand to lower his average
to .262. He was 0-for-15 after hitting two on April 20 and 3-for-20
after two more on May 11. After his two July 22 last year, Jones
went 1-for-22. And after his two on Aug. 22, 1996, he went
9-for-50.
</P>
<P>
   Total two-homer futility: 14-for-120, .116.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why I go like that,'' said Jones, who ended that
skid Friday with a second-inning, RBI single.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
