<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons' signing adds experience at DE
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Servic
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Antonio Edwards, a five-year veteran from Moultrie,
signed a one-year contract with the Atlanta Falcons on Friday, as
the team tried to address its shortage of experienced defensive
ends.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, 6-feet-3, 271 pounds, was drafted in the eighth round
by Seattle in 1993 after playing at Valdosta State. The 28-year-old
played in 50 games for the Seahawks before being waived after one
game last season. Then he played in three games for the New York
Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards has played right and left end, with 24 starts in 53
games. He has 87 tackles, 14 sacks and two safeties. His best year
was in 1995 when he had 6.5 sacks.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards logged a few snaps with the first team on Friday because
starting right end Chuck Smith was not present. The team has worked
six days of a 10-day voluntary passing camp.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons had just three veteran defensive ends under
contract: Starters Smith and Lester Archambeau and backup John
Burrough. Anthony Pleasant played in 11 games last year as a
reserve but was waived after the season.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie free agent defensive ends on the roster include Shawn
Swayda (Arizona State), Barry Mitchell (Idaho) and Richard Freeman
(Valdosta State), but Freeman has been working at linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need a little depth at the end spot,'' said Edwards, who
played for coach Jim Hughes at Colquitt County High. ``It's great.
I used to come home twice a year, but now my brother (Howard, a
running back on Georgia Tech's 1990 national championship team) is
a little more than an hour away (in Macon), and my family is just
three hours away.''
</P>
<P>
   Celebrity basketball
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Terance Mathis is staging a celebrity basketball
game today at Morris Brown to raise money for the Terance Loves
Children Foundation (TLC). Tickets for the 4 p.m. game are $10.
Proceeds benefit TLC, which works to heighten awareness of how
drugs can ruin young lives. ... Backup quarterback Mark Rypien,
signed to a two-year deal earlier this spring, was a no-show again
as he continues to deal with personal issues. It is unclear if he
will be in Suwanee next week, when passing camp ends. Rypien
commuted for six weeks this spring from his Idaho home to begin
learning the Falcons' playbook. ... Rookie free-agent linebacker
Jody Littleton had to go home to Brighton, Colo., because his
brother was involved in a motorcycle accident. ... Coach Dan Reeves
was in a golf tournament, and assistant head coach/defensive
coordinator Rich Brooks ran the 80-minute practice. Cornerback
Randy Fuller (groin), receiver Keith Crawford (high calf strain)
and right guard Gene Williams (throat infection) missed practice.
Several players had excused absences, including Smith and receivers
Todd Kinchen and Tony Martin, cornerback Ray Buchanan. . . .
Running back Jamal Anderson took all rookies to nearby Jeffrey's
sports bar on Friday afternoon for dinner and beverages.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
