<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Steele picking up where he left off
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   POCONO, Pa. _ Three-time ARCA champion Tim Steele makes his
return today in the ARCA Mountain Dew 400, after injuries suffered
at Atlanta Motor Speedway in November.
</P>
<P>
   Steele qualified second-fastest, 162.655 mph, at Pocono Raceway
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel great, like I haven't missed a lick,'' Steele said.
``You don't know how good it feels to be back. It's like going
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Steele, a five-time ARCA winner at Pocono, suffered head
injuries when he lost control and slammed into the wall between
turns one and two at AMS. He's the all-time ARCA superspeedway
winner with 17 victories.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Ciochetti starts on the pole with a track-record 163.845
mph. Bobby Hamilton Jr. makes his debut, qualifying third-fastest.
</P>
<P>
   Buckshot too slow
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's Buckshot Jones made his debut at Pocono Raceway Friday
and was a bit awed. ``We tested her in early June and felt
comfortable. But I have never competed on anything like this
track,'' he said of the 2.5-mile track with its two long straights
and short chute.
</P>
<P>
   Jones qualified with a speed of 163.651 mph, but it wasn't good
enough to make the top 25. ``We have enough to make the field. We
just need to make some adjustments and get it up to speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Fined
</P>
<P>
   Dale Earnhardt Jr. was fined $5,000, his crew chief Tony Eury
Sr. $2,500 and Bryant Frazier, crew chief for Tony Stewart, $1,000
after last Saturday's Busch Grand National event at Pikes Peak.
Earnhardt's fine resulted from fighting Stewart. The two crew
chiefs were cited for actions detrimental to auto racing. None of
the parties would comment, but the incidents started on the track
with a bumping duel and ended in the garage with a shoving match
between the two crew chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   Robby's return
</P>
<P>
   Robby Gordon is expected to be car-owner Buz McCall's designated
driver of the week in next week's Savemart/Kragen 350 at Sears
Point. McCall released David Green two weeks ago and put Kevin
Lepage in the car for the Pontiac Excitement 400 at Richmond and
picked Hut Stricklin for Michigan and this week's Pocono 500.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
