<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gordon hits wall, still wins pole
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   POCONO, Pa. _ Even when Jeff Gordon bounces off walls, things
seem to go his way. They did Friday, and he won the pole with a
speed of 168.042 mph for Sunday's Pocono 500.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's flirtation with disaster came as he entered the third
turn, drifted up the track and smacked the wall with his right-rear
quarter panel. Then without another bobble, he had his Monte Carlo
on a straight line to his fourth pole in the last six races.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went out there and made a real hard, aggressive lap and
hoped that it would stick,'' Gordon said. ``It stuck pretty much
all the way until I came off the last turn and brushed that wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Crew chief) Ray (Evernham) is always telling me that to get
the car right, it needs to be a little loose coming off that last
turn. Well, it sure was after we got through with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Wallace was second-fastest without the drama of Gordon's
run. Wallace put his Taurus on a rail-like lap, hitting the
checkered flag with a speed of 167.436 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy with that lap, I just hope we can do something like
it Sunday,'' Wallace said. ``I know one thing, I'd rather be
starting on the inside (where Gordon is) than the outside, but we
got what we got.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Mayfield, Wallace's teammate, ran third-fastest and will
line up behind Gordon in the second row with Ken Schrader.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's surprise came from the No. 3 Monte Carlo of Dale
Earnhardt, who qualified 11th, his best non-restrictor-plate effort
of the year. His previous best was 25th, last week at Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're learning a little different and seeing some different
things with the crew-chief switch,'' Earnhardt said. ``It's a plus
as far as everybody taking a look at everything. These cars are
going to keep getting better and better.''
</P>
<P>
   Darrell Waltrip, who had to accept provisionals in three of the
last four races, qualified 18th.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
