<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stewart challenges Open's jinx on its first-round leaders
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO -- Like the old saying, ``You can't tell a book by
its cover,'' you can't judge a U.S. Open by who leads the first
round, usually. Beware that guy out of the minitours in Florida,
with the tattered old bag, ``Bullfrog Acres GC'' lettered on the
side, and the cap that says, ``Sam's Pawn Shop.'' He's the guy you
better watch out for for the first 18 holes, until he comes to his
senses. Top of the leaderboard Thursday, riding economy class out
of town Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   It happens. A guy named Lee Mackey, who was out of work, shot a
64 and set the Open record at Merion in 1950. The next day, he shot
81. First-round leaders have had names like Labron Harris Jr., Pat
Fitzsimons, Bob Brue, Bob Gadja and one like a school principal,
Clarence Clark. It's not that Nicklaus and Palmer and Hogan haven't
led the first round, but first-round leaders usually disappear like
a morning fog.
</P>
<P>
   Since the American championship was started in 1896, only 12
times has the champion led or tied for the lead after the first
round. Only four times has the champion had the lead to himself
wire to wire, Walter Hagen in 1914, Jim Barnes in 1921, Ben Hogan
in 1953 and the last foreign winner, Tony Jacklin, in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   There have been some who led after four rounds that were pretty
much a shock. Andy North, not once but twice. He won only one other
tournament in his career. Lou Graham, Steve Jones and Scott Simpson
came to mind here. Lee Trevino, too, at Rochester in 1968, before
any of us suspected what a diet of tortillas and beans could do for
one's game.
</P>
<P>
   When all the scores were in and Payne Stewart's name was at top
of the board at The Olympic Club Thursday, the subject reared its
shaggy head again. Master Stewart is known more for his clubby
garments, his knee pants, his exposed stockings and his flat caps,
than for his game. It is easily forgotten that he has won two
majors, a PGA Championship and the U.S. Open of 1991, with which we
deal here.
</P>
<P>
   That was the last Open in which the champion led from the first
round to the last, after which he still had to win a playoff from
Scott Simpson. That was at Hazeltine, the course outside
Minneapolis, where in 1970 Jacklin had been the last winner to go
the distance on the lead. Also where lightning had struck and
killed a spectator Stewart's year, setting off a wave of
weather-consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a more mature player than I was in 1991,'' Stewart said,
when somebody asked him. ``I feel I'm a more complete player, you
know, older and wiser.''
</P>
<P>
   The way he had finished Thursday would indicate his luck has
improved as well, a wedge to the pin on the 609-yard 16th, a
45-foot putt on the 17th and a downhill sidewise putt that dropped
on the treacherous 18th green, all for birdies, would seem to bear
that out. Those are the three toughest birdies at Olympic.
</P>
<P>
   Back out in plaid knickers, white hose that look like the
sanitary stockings baseball players wear, and a flaming red cap
Friday, he backed those up, ran his streak of birdies to six
through the first three holes. This was no fly-by-night first-round
leader. He was as serious about winning a matching bookend Open as
he is about his self-imposed wardrobe. He would bogey the 6th, get
the stroke back on the 7th and rock along until he came to the
16th, where his streak began Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Numbers on the leaderboard were shrinking and the gap between
him and his pursuers was widening. He flirted with trouble on the
15th, but saved par with a twisting 7-foot putt. He now was three
strokes up on Jeff Maggert and Bob Tway, and the one-round leader
was now about to stretch it to two.
</P>
<P>
   He was way ahead of his score at Olympic 11 years ago. He wasn't
coasting along, but he was having his way with it. The ``more
mature, older, wiser'' Stewart was beginning to show through. But,
in the words of that youthful philosopher, Matt Kuchar, ``This is
only the first two days.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
