<SLUG> BC-US-OPEN-NOTEBOOK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Martin's confidence bolstered by 71
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   San Francisco -- Casey Martin has come a long way this week
since his now-abandoned, one-seater cart was doing wheelies on the
Olympic Club's slopes Monday. When the U.S. Golf Association
finally settled on a practical mode of transportation for Martin _
the conventional golf cart he first rode on the Nike Tour _ the
26-year-old with the circulatory disease in his right leg could
concentrate on his golf game.
</P>
<P>
   It was a fairly smooth transition. Overwhelmed by the gallery
support, Martin shot a second-round 71 Friday for a total of
5-over-par 145 to make the cut. Not bad for his first event with
the PGA Tour players. Not bad for his first major. Very good for
all the hoopla that accompanied it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in a way I have proved something to myself,'' Martin
said, ``because I know I'm not playing as well as I'm capable of
and yet I made the cut at the U.S. Open. So that gives me
confidence knowing that I'm supposed to be here. I think if I just
keep playing well and keep improving, I can be out here and really
be a steady fixture.''
</P>
<P>
   His finish on both days would suggest a reasonable amount of
fatigue. The cart notwithstanding, Martin still must walk a
significant amount and deal with Olympic's ever-present slopes. On
both days he has bogeyed the final two holes.
</P>
<P>
   Admitting to a higher goal than making the cut but not revealing
what it is, Martin said, ``I'd love to be known more as a golfer
than a person with a disability. But, at the same time, I know that
I am probably not going to lose that label.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking it out on someone
</P>
<P>
   Tom Lehman, who has either shared or held the 54-hole lead of
the U.S. Open the last three years _ for two thirds and a second _
lost some ground Friday with a 75 and is at 3-over 143. Long before
leader Payne Stewart helplessly watched his ball trickle down the
slope from the green's upper level, Lehman found similar
frustration. Fuming as he entered the locker room after a
double-bogey at the 18th _ he four-putted from 50 feet _ Lehman
slammed the door and said, ``Whoever set up this course is full of
(expletive). That 18th green is as hard as a rock.'' ... Sick of
watching his ball rolling away, Kirk Triplett stopped it with the
head of his putter, absorbing a two-shot penalty, and then putted
again. He was about to miss the cut, anyway, but ended with
73-79-152. ... Sea Island's Davis Love III also watched his ball
roll away, along with his week. With his back hurting, Love shot
78-75 for 13-over par 153.
</P>
<P>
   Nobilo scorches front nine
</P>
<P>
   New Zealand's Frank Nobilo, the two-time Sarazen World Open
champion, shot a 5-under-par 30 on Olympic's front nine Friday on
the way to a 67, rebounding from an opening 76.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
