<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USOPEN-BAR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kuchar's 'A' game keeps him in hunt
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO -- The chants came from around the 18th green,
echoing through the elegant eucalyptus trees of the Olympic Club.
Not for Ernie Els, the U.S Open champion. Not for Justin Leonard,
the British Open champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kooch! ... Kooch!''
</P>
<P>
   Who does Matt Kuchar think he is, Bobby Jones? What's going on
here? Does a kid from Georgia Tech one day from turning 20 _ even
if he is the U.S. Amateur champion _ actually think he can win the
U.S. Open?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so,'' Kuchar said. ``I'm just going to take it
one shot at a time. But who knows? Maybe I will be in contention.''
</P>
<P>
   He already is. Kuchar fashioned a 1-under-par 69 Friday in the
second round of the U.S. Open, while some of the game's biggest
stars were being swallowed up by nasty rough and tricky greens. He
positioned himself at 1-under 139 for the tournament (two shots off
the lead), easily qualified for weekend play in his second straight
major championship and assumed an illogical spot on the leader
board.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the magic of Augusta has carried over to the
West Coast. Kuchar hasn't received the results of his sophomore
exams yet, but his grades at the U.S. Open are perfect. While some
fellow players and caddies think Kuchar's father, Peter, gets
carried away to the point of distraction as his bag toter, the
son's emotions are as steady as the Pacific Ocean breeze.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had my 'A' game there (at the Masters), and I think I
brought my 'A' game here as well,'' said the son, who tied for 21st
in Augusta in April. ``It's very cool stuff. It's way cool to be
inside the ropes and play well.''
</P>
<P>
   Els, the defending champion, would agree. Except he's been
watching Kuchar do it while struggling with his own game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been beaten by an amateur in a long time,'' said
Els, who needed a 70 Friday to stay within six shots of Kuchar,
``but the tournament isn't over yet.''
</P>
<P>
   For the second, Kuchar held together when he easily could have
come unglued. He double-bogeyed the 14th, misclubbing his approach
to the bunker and then coming up short of the green. Reversing the
trend, Kuchar chipped in from 30 feet for birdie at the 15th,
sending a roar across the back nine.
</P>
<P>
   Kuchar made a par save at the 16th, sinking a 10-footer after a
slick pitch from the rough; nearly birdied the rugged 17th after a
radar-like approach; and then came up short with a birdie putt at
the 18th.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a lot more of a grind than Augusta was,'' Kuchar said.
``You have to concentrate on every show, every hole. If you let
down an inch, this course will grab you.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuchar is being asked daily about the chances he will remain in
school for four years. While conceding that ``it was tough to see
that $40,000 go to waste'' at the Masters, Kuchar seems content.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money looks real good, but I am really enjoying school,''
he said. ``I had a great year this year at Georgia Tech. It was a
lot of fun. We have a great team, a great coach. ... I doubt myself
turning professional before school ends.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
