</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-JAVITS-CENTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: EXPAND THE JAVITS CENTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in editorial on Saturday, June 20:
</P>
<P>
   New York City's attraction as a site for trade shows and
conventions has been one of the key elements in its economic
growth. That makes it hard to understand why Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
seems so indifferent to the fact that the Jacob Javits Convention
Center is too small to accommodate the nation's largest trade
shows, and growing less competitive every year.
</P>
<P>
   New York has long since fallen out of the top 10 when it comes
to available exhibition space. It will drop further as other cities
expand their facilities.
</P>
<P>
   New York state, which runs the Javits Center, has been promoting
a plan that would double its 760,000 square feet of exhibition
space by creating a vast complex stretching all the way to 42nd
Street from the center's present site on the western end of 38th
Street. Tying the center to 42nd Street would pull the booming
development of the Times Square area all the way to the Hudson
River, while connecting the convention business to the city's
entertainment hub.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Silverstein, a developer who owns part of the property the
state would need, was apparently willing to swap the land for the
right to build a hotel or apartment tower over the Javits
expansion. But Silverstein recently said he was tired of waiting
for the city to commit, and was going ahead with other plans for
the property.
</P>
<P>
   It would be amazing if Giuliani swallowed the state proposal
whole. It would cost an estimated $700 million, and the state wants
the city to pick up part of the tab. But rather than demanding
changes or proposing alternatives, the city seems simply to be
turning away _ as if the convention center were a state project for
Syracuse rather than Manhattan. There have been no public comments,
no objections and apparently no private negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's critics contend that the mayor does not want any
other West Side program to compete with possible plans for a new
Yankee Stadium, although the two structures would be on different
sites. If so, Giuliani's strategy is all wrong. New York City must
both keep the Yankees and pursue the economic development projects
it needs to keep the economy growing. To suggest that both things
are not possible would hurt, rather than help, the mayor's cause.
</P>
<P>
   Building a world-class convention center would create jobs and
assure the city's ability to attract major trade shows and
exhibitions into the next century. The mayor must cooperate with
the state in reaching that goal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 2331EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980619.0498 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8427 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-JAPAN-NYT &LR;      06-19 0401
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-JAPAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: TIME FOR ACTION IN JAPAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, June 20:
</P>
<P>
   International financial officials are meeting in Tokyo with a
sense of urgency that has been lacking for most of this decade as
Japan refused to deal with its banking crisis. Now Japan has
promised prompt action, and has earmarked money to do the job. What
is unclear is whether the Japanese authorities are able to act
decisively.
</P>
<P>
   Action is essential because Japan is in the midst of a severe
credit crunch as shaky banks try to avoid new losses by avoiding
almost all loans. That has put a stranglehold on the economy,
deepening Japan's recession and making the bad-loan problem even
more severe.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to imagine a worse time for Japan to be in recession.
The problems of developing countries in Asia remain severe, and are
hurting others. Asian countries, unable to afford things, have
slashed their imports, and U.S. exports are falling. The developing
countries, confronted with their own weak banks and debt-ridden
companies, will have a hard enough time recovering even if Japan
does get moving and resume buying their products. Without a
Japanese recovery, it is easy to understand why World Bank
officials are now talking of an Asian depression.
</P>
<P>
   Intervention by Tokyo and Washington to support the yen set off
rallies in financial markets around the world this week, but they
quickly faded as investors looked for action, not words. Japan
needs to determine which banks are insolvent and close them, while
protecting depositors. At the same time, it needs to bail out the
remaining institutions that can make it with help. Then those banks
can start lending again and, with the help of an aggressive package
of government spending and tax cuts, Japan's economy can recover.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, work on sorting out which banks should be saved
seems to have not yet begun. It is up to the foreign officials
gathered in Tokyo to persuade Japanese officials to live up to
their pledge, and to offer them all the assistance they need. There
is no guarantee that the rest of Asia will recover soon even if
Japan starts growing again and keeps its currency from collapsing.
</P>
<P>
   But the chances of that happening will be far greater if Japan
deals with its problems decisively and quickly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 2332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980619.0499 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 23:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8430 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-NY-LEGIS-NYT &LR;      06-19 0465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-LEGIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE UNDERACHIEVING LEGISLATURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, June 20:
</P>
<P>
   New York's state Legislature has done an excellent job of
reducing expectations. When the lawmakers closed up shop and went
home Friday, relief that they had done so few things that were
terrible overcame some of the disappointment over their failure to
do much that was good.
</P>
<P>
   It was good news that the Legislature failed to pass a parole
bill that was more election-year pandering than serious reform of
the state's sometimes irrational sentencing system. In another
accomplishment of sorts, the Assembly killed a boondoggle for
mutual insurance companies sought by Gov. George Pataki and the
Republican Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Any time the Legislature resists the temptation to meddle with
city interests on behalf of its special constituencies is cause for
some rejoicing, so the state Senate deserves commendation for
killing a bill that would give the final say on city police union
contract disputes to a state arbitration board.
</P>
<P>
   But the Legislature passed another bill that meddled with the
New York City Police Department's ability to decide its own
promotion policies, and blithely approved new retirement benefits
for city workers that will cost $154 million a year, without
volunteering to pay for them.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the energy of the Legislature's last days was devoted to
passage of a bill requiring the state to track people infected with
the AIDS virus by name and to notify their sexual partners. The
Assembly leadership's concerns over privacy issues was
understandable, but the experience of other states with similar
programs suggests it was exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   The legislators passed some other good bills on health care for
poor children and consumer rights for health-care insurance policy
holders. The ridiculous system for New York City school board
elections got some improvements. The lawmakers also set up a
state-city structure to run the proposed Hudson River Park in
Manhattan below 59th Street, bringing the park's creation closer to
reality.
</P>
<P>
   But they ducked their responsibility to take a serious stand on
other important issues. Campaign finance reform was ignored, as
were the pleas from New York City's schools chancellor to end state
requirements that all public-school principals be given tenure. The
state Senate killed bills on gun control and gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most disappointing was the Legislature's failure to
approve a court reorganization bill proposed by Chief Judge Judith
Kaye. Assembly Democrats appear to prefer the present inefficient
and hopelessly complicated court system to the potential loss of
patronage that reform would entail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-98 2333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980619.0500 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-19 23:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8432 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-MARLINS-NYT &LR;      06-19 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-MARLINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR REED AND METS, GREAT START, BAD FINISH 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the second time in 12 days, Rick Reed, a
replacement player during the labor unrest of 1995 who is now
auditioning for a spot on the 1998 National League all-star team,
seemed on the verge of accomplishing what no other pitcher has been
able to do in the 37 seasons of Mets baseball: pitch a no-hit game,
perhaps even a perfect one.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night against the Florida Marlins at Shea Stadium, Reed
took a perfect game into the seventh inning, a circumstance eerily
familiar to his performance at Shea on June 8, when he retired the
first 20 batters in a game against the Tampa Bay Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay's Wade Boggs broke up that perfect-game bid with a
two-out seventh-inning double. Friday night, it was Florida's Edgar
Renteria who singled with one out in the seventh inning against
Reed.
</P>
<P>
   But in the next few minutes, what had been Reed's perfect game
became something else familiar this month: a Mets loss, their third
in a row, and their fifth in the last week to the Marlins and
Montreal Expos, two doormat teams in the National League. Reed
would not even finish the game.
</P>
<P>
   Following his single, Renteria was caught stealing, but two
Marlins hits ensued. Then, Florida's Cliff Floyd hit Reed's first
pitch for a towering three-run home run to right field that gave
the Marlins a 3-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   No perfect game for Reed (8-4), and perhaps a setback on his
road to an all-star game appearance _ although Florida manager Jim
Leyland, who will manage the NL squad and choose the pitching
staff, said before the game that he had Reed highly rated in a
statistical chart he keeps on all league pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' hitters, meanwhile, could not rescue Reed from his
meltdown. They scratched out two early runs off Marlins starter
Brian Meadows, but wilted thereafter. In the eighth inning, with
Carlos Baerga at third base with one out, neither Brian McRae nor
the Mets' pinch-hitter Luis Lopez got the ball out of the infield,
stranding Baerga at third.
</P>
<P>
   In the ninth inning, the rookie Benny Agbayani and Matt Franco
each drew one-out walks. Mike Piazza hit a ground ball that forced
Franco at second base and put runners on first and third. The
Florida reliever Matt Mantei struck out John Olerud for his first
save of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Reed, who pitched for the Mets' top minor league team in 1996
and was a surprising success with a 13-9 record last season,
breezed through the Marlins' lineup for six innings. He retired
Todd Dunwoody, Florida's leadoff hitter, at the start of the
seventh inning on a ground ball to Olerud at first base.
</P>
<P>
   But on a 3-1 pitch, Renteria _ the only .300 hitter in the
Marlins' starting lineup _ slapped a sharply hit ground ball
between Baerga and second base for a crisp single.
</P>
<P>
   Most in the crowd of 32,738 rose to their feet in an ovation for
Reed.
</P>
<P>
   Renteria was thrown out attempting to steal second base, but
Florida's Mark Kotsay followed with an infield single. Todd Zeile
laced a single to left field, and Floyd hit Reed's first pitch deep
into the right-field seats.
</P>
<P>
   Reed, who minutes ago was eight outs from a historic pitching
performance, stood in front of the mound with his hands on his
knees, staring at the grass beside his feet.
</P>
<P>
   He would leave the game after two Marlins hits and two outs in
the ninth inning, yielding six hits with no walks and eight
strikeouts. John Franco came on in relief of Reed, making his 402nd
appearance as a Met, a team record previously held by Tom Seaver.
</P>
<P>
   While Reed was masterful throughout the early parts of the game,
the Marlins nearly reached base several times. After Reed struck
out Dunwoody and Renteria to start the game, Kotsay lined a pitch
that Olerud snagged with a leaping grab.
</P>
<P>
   Meadows also slapped a pitch up the middle in the third inning
that Reed deftly fielded and threw to first for the out.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth inning, Mets shortstop Rey Ordonez made a
difficult play look easy, charging a high-bouncing ground ball off
the bat of Renteria, catching it between bounces and then hastily
firing to first base to retire Renteria by two steps. And in the
fifth, the right-handed-hitting Zeile pulled a Reed delivery
sharply toward third base. Mets third baseman Edgardo Alfonzo
stretched to his left for the catch.
</P>
<P>
   Florida's Craig Counsell was a few feet from ending the perfect
game and the shutout with one out in the sixth inning. Counsell
sent a 2-2 Reed pitch deep down the right-field line. The ball
curved just foul. Three pitches later, Counsell popped out meekly
to Ordonez.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets scored quickly against Meadows (5-6), who came into the
game 0-2 against the Mets. In his third game as a Met, Agbayani
singled up the middle to open the Mets' first inning. It was
Agbayani's first major league hit. A walk to Matt Franco, a ground
ball by Piazza and Olerud's sacrifice fly produced a run.
</P>
<P>
   Baerga led off the fourth inning with a double into the
right-field corner, which Alfonzo followed with a ground ball
single to left field. With runners on first and third base, Meadows
balked, allowing Baerga to score the Mets' second run. But it
wasn't enough on a night when Reed saw perfection turn into
frustration in a manner of minutes.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   An American League executive said the Mets had talked to the
Anaheim Angels about acquiring standout outfielder Jim Edmonds for
Mets pitchers Bobby Jones and Bill Pulsipher. Asked whether the
Mets had expressed interest in Edmonds, general manager Steve
Phillips said he would not comment on what players he was
interested in nor reveal what teams he had talked to ... Outfielder
Bernard Gilkey, who has not played since he was hit by a pitch
above his left eye last Friday, was examined by team doctors and
will not play until he is re-examined ... Butch Huskey sat out
Friday night's game following a magnetic resonance imaging test on
his right knee. ``They drained it and gave me some cortisone,''
Huskey said. ``It's nothing major, but after the season, I'll have
to have surgery.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets and the Chase Manhattan Bank announced that they had
donated 70,000 tickets to area children, 10,000 of whom are in
foster care. Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani, accepting the gift at a
ceremony at Shea Stadium, said many youngsters ``will get a chance
to see their major league heroes for the first time.'' The tickets
have been distributed to schools in low-income communities and to
youth groups in the metropolitan area, said the office of the
mayor. After announcing the program, ``Baseball Is for Kids,''
manager Bobby Valentine and pitchers John Franco and Al Leiter held
a baseball clinic for 70 children. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
