<SLUG> BC-RUN-SHOT-PUT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACHING GODINA STILL EXPECTS OOMPH IN HIS THROW 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By FRANK LITSKY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Just think how far John Godina would propel the
shot and the discus if he were healthy.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, the 26-year-old UCLA graduate is a two-time world
champion in the shot-put and the world leader this year in the shot
and the discus throw. In the U.S. outdoor track and field
championships he took aim at both titles _ the men's discus throw
(he was the defending champion) Friday night and the shot-put
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   And never mind the torn cartilage in his right shoulder. He says
he does not even think about it, except that he is more tired than
a 6-foot-4-inch, 285-pound muscleman figures to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been throwing with a lot of fatigue from lifting
weights,'' he said. ``I took time off for this meet. I haven't
competed in the shot for three weeks and the discus for two.''
</P>
<P>
   Godina has also cut back on his lifts. He would like to do the
standard two-part lift, which consists of cleaning the weight
(lifting it to the chest) and then jerking it overhead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do just cleans,'' he said, ``almost 400 pounds. But I can't
do overhead lifts because of the torn cartilage in my shoulder.
I've had it two years, but I don't want surgery on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Why lift so much with an aching shoulder?
</P>
<P>
   ``It keeps my mind from wandering,'' Godina said. ``My goal this
year was to get the shot-put record indoors and outdoors, but I
didn't get the indoor record and the outdoor record is way out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   The world outdoor records are 75 feet 10\ inches in 1990 by
Randy Barnes, an American shot-putter, and 243-0 in 1986 by Jurgen
Schult, an East German discus thrower. Godina entered this meet
with the year's best shot-put (71-5{) and discus throw (229-4). It
was on May 19 that he reached 71-5{ and then added a 218-1,
history's second-best shot-discus one-day double behind Ben
Plucknett's 67-6 3/4 and then-world-record 233-7 in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Godina's climb to glory has not been easy. In the 1996 Atlanta
Olympics, he struggled early in the shot-put, then took the lead on
the fifth of his six attempts with 68-2{. Just as it seemed Godina
would win the gold medal, Barnes, on his last attempt, sent the
shot flying 70-11\, and Godina's gold medal turned to silver.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes jabbed both arms over his head in triumph. Godina just
stared in disbelief and disappointment. Three days later, there was
more disappointment for Godina when he fell 13 inches short of
reaching the discus final.
</P>
<P>
   Things are better now. In paying tribute to Godina's
athleticism, Art Venegas, who coached him in college and still
coaches him, calls him ``the most explosive guy I've ever been
around.'' And Godina sees no reason why he should not keep
improving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'm as close to being as good as I can get,'' he
said. ``If I thought I couldn't get better, it would be boring. If
I can throw 250 and 78 feet, that sounds great. It depends how
everything happens, if my progression continues. I'm not going to
put my limits at 74 and 245. There's no reason to do that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
