<HEADER>
A8445 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CT-BOY-SUFFERING-NYT &LR;      06-19 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-BOY-SUFFERING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT DRAWS HARROWING PICTURE OF BOY'S LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ An 11-year-old boy who died at a psychiatric
hospital while being restrained had suffered his entire life, both
because of a mother who verbally and physically abused him and
because of a state agency that did not take him away soon enough,
according to a report issued Friday by a state oversight panel.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew McClain, whose death in March from suffocation is still
under criminal investigation, visited a hospital many times because
of injuries his family could not adequately explain, including a
series of eye injuries that made him blind in his left eye by age
3, according to Friday's report from the Child Fatality Review
Panel. The report also said that hospital workers witnessed him
being whipped with a belt by his mother and that she and his
grandmother were seen eating his food while he was staying in the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Yet workers for the state Department of Children and Families
did not take steps to remove Andrew from his home, despite urgent
pleas by doctors at the hospital where he was being treated, the
report said. One agency worker said then that the department was
``not in the business of breaking up families,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Linda Pearce Prestley, the state's child advocate and
leader of the Child Fatality Review Panel, said the case should be
studied by caseworkers, lawyers and judges on how not to treat a
child.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andrew M. suffered more in his brief eleven years of life than
most people suffer in a lifetime,'' Ms. Prestley said. ``There is
no question that numerous opportunities to protect Andrew in his
early years were missed.''
</P>
<P>
   Once in foster care, Andrew spent a year in a home not
appropriate for him, and his mental health worsened, the report
said. When he died, the state was still working toward placing
Andrew back with his mother _ an ``unrealistic and dangerous
plan,'' the report reads.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's criticism comes three years after Gov. John Rowland
promised to clean up the state's child welfare system in part by
focusing on child safety. That move was made after three children
died from abuse while under state care in one month in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The review panel said that Andrew's early encounters with the
system came before new policies were instituted following the 1995
deaths, but that even afterward, some of those policies _ including
that child protection be the primary goal of the agency _ were
ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Kristine Ragaglia, commissioner of the Department of Children
and Families, said Friday that the agency in the 1980s took what
was then considered appropriate action in keeping Andrew with his
mother. And she said the state is beginning intense reviews of all
its child welfare cases every six months to make sure a child is
getting the best care he can.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew died March 22 after two mental health workers at the
Elmcrest Psychiatric Hospital in Portland suffocated him while
physically restraining him by holding him to the ground while one
worker lay on him _ a method the child review panel later said did
not follow standards. The state found one of the mental health
workers to be abusive, and two other hospital workers to be
negligent. The hospital agreed to pay $100,000 in lieu of fines.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's 45-page report drew a harrowing picture of the boy's
life. Born to a 13-year-old mother, he had, by the age of 3, been
treated in the emergency room for a perforated ear drum, a small
burn on his shoulder, a cut on his finger that later became
infected because his mother did not take him for treatment, and
three eye injuries.
</P>
<P>
   In his 11 years, he attended six schools, stayed in four foster
homes, had two lawyers, was treated by four social workers, and had
six in-patient stays at mental-health facilities.
</P>
<P>
   As Andrew, who was described as mildly retarded, grew older, his
behavioral problems escalated. It is no surprise, Ms. Prestley said
Friday, that he ended up in a psychiatric hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew stayed with his mother or grandmother until January 1996,
when his mother was arrested for allegedly selling drugs in her
home when her children were present.
</P>
<P>
   Janette Getz, a lawyer for Lucinda McClain, said that the
mother's alleged abuse is not relevant to the suit she plans on
filing against the state and Elmcrest Hospital. ``Her child was not
killed while he was in her custody,'' Ms. Getz said. ``He was
placed in a system that was designed to safeguard this child. And
it is that system that ultimately failed.''
</P>
<P>
   The report makes a number of wide-ranging recommendations,
including that any case with more than three neglect or abuse
referrals in a year be reviewed by a multidisciplinary team; that
the state increase the number of foster homes and
residential-treatment facilities it has available; and that the
state's Judicial Department develop mandatory classes for lawyers
who want to represent children and a system to monitor their
performance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
